<SLUG> BC-SEINFELD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Seinfeld tells his classic jokes for the `last time'
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If only he'd ended his sitcom just like this.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Seinfeld closed out his old stand-up act Sunday night on
HBO in a live performance on Broadway that was practically
everything last season's gone-for-good Seinfeld finale wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   In his ``Jerry Seinfeld: I'm Telling You for the Last Time _
Live on Broadway,'' the comic was funny, breezy, light on his toes
and heavy on familiar but still-leave-'em-wanting punchlines.
</P>
<P>
   Like Seinfeld's classic Tide joke. ``If you've got a T-shirt
with blood stains all over it, maybe laundry isn't your biggest
problem right now.''
</P>
<P>
   You get it. Heard it all before. Enjoyed it all again.
</P>
<P>
   The jokes kept rolling for just over an hour. Maybe Chris Rock's
terrific, obscenity-filled ``tired, tired, tired'' tirade on his
own HBO special ``Bring the Pain'' does make him the late '90s
comic of the moment. But Seinfeld's infectious humor, as nearly
squeaky clean as Superman, makes him a comic for the ages.
</P>
<P>
   For the Seinfeld savvy who lack HBO, here's a sampling of what
you missed:
</P>
<P>
   _ Inside the yellow car: ``I don't even know what it takes to
get a cab driver's license. I think all you need is a face. This
seems to be their big qualification. No blank heads are allowed
driving cabs in this town. Also helps to have a name with like
eight consonants in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   _ In Florida, they're everywhere: ``What is that age that old
people reach when they decide when they back out of the driveway,
they are not looking anymore? ... They just go and then, `well, I'm
old and I'm coming back. I survived. Let's see if you can.' ''
</P>
<P>
   _ Only the cows know: ``Ever had milk the day after the
(expiration) date? Scares the hell out of you, doesn't it? ... I
smelled it, you smelled it. What's it supposed to smell like? It
smells like milk! I don't know how they're so definite, though.
Maybe the cows tip 'em off when they're milking them.'' (He leans
forward like a cow, turns his head and says, ``July 3.'')
</P>
<P>
   _ Can you spell pain relief? ``Nobody wants anything less than
extra strength. ... Give me the maximum allowable human dosage.
Figure out what will kill me and then back it off a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Olympic dream: ``You win the gold, you feel good. You win
the bronze, you think, `well, at least I got something.' You win
the silver _ that's like you almost won. Of all the losers, you
came in first of that group. You are the No. 1 loser. No one lost
ahead of you.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
