<HEADLINE>
`PRIVATE RYAN' MARCHING ON AT BOX OFFICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Steven Spielberg's ``Saving Private Ryan''
narrowly won a third straight box-office battle with an estimated
$17.6 million at 2,592 theaters nationwide during the Friday-Sunday
period, studio sources said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The performance, which gave the D-Day epic an impressive $104
million in its first 17 days, highlighted a strong weekend for
moviegoing overall, with the top dozen films taking in $106.7
million, up 30 percent from the same weekend last year. Analyst
Arthur Rockwell of Drake &AMP; Co. said studios have done a decent job
of scheduling a diverse slate of attractive films this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an incredible amount of product that's pretty strong
across the board,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan,'' a DreamWorks SKG release that is
already a leading Academy Awards contender, saw its Friday-Sunday
take fall by a mere 26 percent from its second weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``The movie continues to play very well to all demographics,''
said distribution chief James Tharp. ``And we are starting to see
substantial repeat business.''
</P>
<P>
   Rockwell said, `` `Saving Private Ryan' should have a terrific
run for the rest of the summer.'' Industry tracker Robert Bucksbaum
of Reel Source projected final domestic box office for ``Saving
Private Ryan'' should top $160 million by the end of the year.
``There's really no direct competition,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan'' became the only movie besides
``Titanic'' to top the weekend box office three times this year. It
also became the 174th film to top the $100million mark in U.S.
grosses and the eighth 1998 title to hit the milestone, joining
``Deep Impact,'' ``Godzilla,'' ``The Truman Show,'' ``Mulan,''
``Dr. Dolittle,'' ``Armageddon'' and ``Lethal Weapon 4.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan'' edged a pair of respectable openings _
Paramount's Nicolas Cage action-thriller ``Snake Eyes'' with $16.5
million at 2,713 theaters and Miramax's horror sequel ``Halloween:
H20'' with $16 million at 2,607 sites. The latter, which cost a
lowly $17 million to produce and featured Jamie Lee Curtis
reprising her role from the 1978 original, has taken in $24.6
million since its roll-out Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bucksbaum projected that ``Snake Eyes'' could reach $75 million
while ``Halloween: H20'' will hit $70 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miramax has obviously succeeded very well at tapping the youth
market for horror films,'' Rockwell said. The same studio had
back-to-back $100 million-plus domestic performances from the two
``Scream'' films.
</P>
<P>
   Also performing impressively was 20th Century Fox's fourth
weekend of ``There's Something About Mary,'' with $9.7 million at
2,111 screens as it went past the $76 million mark and lost just 11
percent from the prior weekend. With a budget of only $25 million,
it is likely to be among the most profitable movies in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary'' was followed by a trio of entries with solid returns in
their second weekends _ Disney's ``The Parent Trap,'' with $8.2
million at 2,402 sites, Fox's ``Ever After,'' with $7.2 million at
2,067 locations and Warner Bros.' ``The Negotiator,'' with $6.3
million at 2,436 theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Sony's fourth weekend of ``The Mask of Zorro'' came in eighth
with $5.7 million at 2,515 sites, followed by Disney's sixth
weekend of ``Armageddon,'' with $5.2 million at 2,123 theaters, and
Warner's fifth weekend of ``Lethal Weapon 4,'' with $5 million at
2,329 locations _ an astounding total for a film in 10th place,
where the usual figure tends to be under $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Armageddon'' has reached $172.7 million in 40 days and ranks
40th on the all-time domestic list, behind ``Rain Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox's seventh weekend of ``Dr. Dolittle'' finished 11th with
$2.6 million at 1,826 theaters to top $131 million overall.
</P>
<P>
   The only significant disappointment was Universal's second
weekend of ``BASEketball,'' with a meager $975,000 at 1,910
screens, giving the raunchy comedy only $5.7 million overall _ well
short of its $25 million production cost.
</P>
<P>
   Year-to-date business has topped $4 billion and is 8 percent
ahead of the same period last year. Paramount's ``Titanic,'' a
major factor in that increase, drew $935,000 at 681 theaters in its
34th weekend to push its overall domestic total to $597.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan'' will face competition next weekend from
two new entries _ Warner's action-drama ``The Avengers,'' starring
Sean Connery and Uma Thurman, and Fox's romance ``How Stella Got
Her Groove Back.'' Miramax will open ``Air Bud: Golden Receiver''
for the tough-to-crack family market.
</P>
</TEXT>
