<HEADLINE>
OSUNA ADJUSTS TO SETUP ROLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Dodgers' acquisition of closer Jeff Shaw a
month ago was accompanied by a quick tailspin by sometime-closer
Antonio Osuna. But difficulties adjusting now seem to be well
behind the 25-year-old right-hander.
</P>
<P>
   With two innings of scoreless relief Saturday, Osuna extended
his career-best winning streak to seven _ the second longest active
streak in the National League. He's pitched 82/3 scoreless innings
over his last eight appearances to lower his ERA from 3.21 to 2.72.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's throwing the ball like he was before,'' manager
Glenn Hoffman said. ``He seems to be pumped up.''
</P>
<P>
   The July 4 acquisition of Shaw from the Cincinnati Reds sent
Osuna into a temporary funk as he readjusted to the setup role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe all that stuff (the Shaw trade) did affect him a little
bit, but he's on track now,'' Hoffman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he just got more aggressive with his fastball, putting
it in the right spot. The last couple days here, he's played a big
part (22/3 innings in two wins over the Pirates).''
</P>
<P>
   Osuna has stranded 10 of the last 11 runners he's inherited and
ranks third in the NL in percentage of inherited runners allowed to
score.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrin honored: The Dodgers held a tribute to longtime
Spanish-radio broadcaster Jaime Jarrin before Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrin, who calls Dodgers games for KWKW-AM (1330), was inducted
into the Hall of Fame earlier this year, his 40th year covering the
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jaime, if you had a uniform number, we would retire it
today,'' Peter O'Malley, Dodgers chairman of the board, said.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow Hall of Fame broadcaster Vin Scully saluted Jarrin as a
respected colleague ``and a dear friend for the last 40 years'' and
likened the Ecuadorean immigrant to a protagonist in a Horatio
Alger rags-to-riches story.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has done his job with dignity and good taste for 40
years,'' Scully said.
</P>
<P>
   Former Dodgers manager and current interim general manager Tom
Lasorda called Jarrin ``the Vin Scully of the Latin broadcasters in
this world.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrin will get a star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Catch: Pirates left fielder Al Martin won rave reviews
Saturday for his eighth-inning circus catch in the seats near the
foul pole.
</P>
<P>
   With two outs and runners at second and third base, Gary
Sheffield hit a 320-foot foul ball, and Martin made a backward
flying leap into the first row to make the catch and end a
potential Dodgers rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``As good as it's going to get,'' said Pirates manager Gene
Lamont. ``With the tying run on third, that was a huge catch.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Martin: ``I knew I was close to the rail, but I didn't know
exactly where I was. I didn't have time to think about it. I just
went for it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a blow to the Dodgers, who thought their last chance
might have been snuffed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like, it's gonna be a rough night,'' said Eric Young.
Instead, Young drove home the game-winning run in the bottom of the
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Rebounding: Young's game-winning, one-out single completed the
Dodgers' 29th comeback victory of the season and the 15th in their
last at-bat.
</P>
</TEXT>
