<HEADLINE>
WELCOME PGA, TO BIG TREES AND STRIP MALLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ Welcome, PGA Championship golfers, to the Royal
&AMP; Ancient Links of Redmond, where civilized history stretches all
the way back to the time of colorful legends, such as Clan
Partridge.
</P>
<P>
   Before man walked on the moon, before Saturday night became
fevered, before every American knew the intimate details of the
impeachment process (Nixon's, not Clinton's), there was, barely,
Sahalee (Native American term for ``no parking''), rising from the
primordial mists of lot lines on subdivision plats.
</P>
<P>
   Just as golf's history predates Columbus's request for the boat
keys from Queen Isabella, the richness of the suburban tradition of
Sahalee goes back several years.
</P>
<P>
   Host city Redmond (Native American for ``strip malls unto the
horizon''), once home to primitives such as cows, horses and
bicycles, now looms as the Instant Three-Story Office Building
Capital of America. Merely toss a building permit to the ground,
add a water hookup and _ presto! _ Scottsdale Without Stucco.
</P>
<P>
   But please don't confuse it with those soulless, vacuous sprawls
of the American Southwest, or everywhere in California.
</P>
<P>
   The most important thing for golf visitors to know about Redmond
is that within its city limits (indistinguishable though they are)
is more money than any place the golfers will play. Even more than
Palm Springs, Palm Beach, Palm(er) Arnold, or wherever it was they
thought was filthy with wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond is Microsoft, source of the American gross national
product, which also has a shop in which it produces business
monopolies and a little computer software. Everyone there is richer
than Greg Norman, the PGA career money leader who decided to fake a
shoulder injury and avoid this tournament so his economic punyness
would not be a source of humiliation.
</P>
<P>
   Where 30 years ago the only fences kept cows from the sheep, now
there are enough walls, gates, turrets and drawbridges surrounding
some Redmond residences to make Scotland's Edinburgh Castle look as
vulnerable as a downtown mini-mart at 3 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these homes will be visible from the course, a prospect
that tends to be looked upon with disdain by the touring golfers
more used to country clubs devoid of the entrails of
upper-middle-class existence.
</P>
<P>
   But Sahalee is not the usual golf course housing where there is
more taste than restrictive housing covenants. Among the Redmond
requirements are the banning of sidewalks, street addresses more
confusing than Shawn Kemp's gift list on Mother's Day, and
driveways that include a well-scrubbed sport-utility vehicle 24
hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, trees. Big trees, not the scrawny East Coast
sissy trees, but cedar, hemlock, spruce, Douglas fir.
Northwesterners must have big trees like the English must have weak
teas. Particularly on the course, where by Sunday golfers new to
this thicket will be so sick of trees they will be carrying
kerosone and matches in their bags.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of this tourney will be the first golfer to fire his
caddy and hire gnomes and fairies to show him the way through the
forest.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the only downside to the week will be the weather, so
let me be the first to apologize for it. Whoever the dimwit was who
scheduled this event for the middle of August needs to move on to
another job, like Woody Woodward's bodyguard.
</P>
<P>
   This time of year is so unrepresentative of Puget Sound weather
as to be shameful. It is unlikely this week that visitors will see
so much as a cloud, much less rain. For weeks now, moss is dead,
lawns are brown and algae is gray. Not a slug can be found.
</P>
<P>
   It's just so ... phony. The touring pros will spend the entire
week here without once having a shoe sucked off by mud. The greens
will have no standing water, so there will be no putting around the
geese. Nor will there be need for 30-inch tees that can be pushed
down to hardpan.
</P>
<P>
   This is Puget Sound golf? Bah. This is like climbing
Disneyland's Matterhorn instead of the real one. Schedule this
tourney for November, and we'll see who's got game.
</P>
<P>
   The PGA in November would also allow the tourney more marquee
time, because this week it is only the second-biggest event in
Seattle. Sunday's Blue Angels air show drew to the shores of Lake
Washington either 50,000 or 500,000, depending on whether your
crowd-estimating police officer is on the mark, or on the take from
Seafair.
</P>
<P>
   As for Sunday's annoying boats on the water ... well, we've
tried for years to explain it, but we can't.
</P>
<P>
   Best to think of it as an odd little local custom, perhaps along
the lines of inviting your crazy Uncle Torvald down from the attic
every Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the world's TV cameras here for the tournament were
not turned on yet to catch our dark little secret, so King County's
bond rating remains secure.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many surprises remain to be revealed this week on the
Eastside, where the lush Royal &AMP; Ancient Links of Redmond and its
storied tradition will unveil the vertical lumberyard, property
taxes soaring overhead, to astonished visitors.
</P>
<P>
   If the golf visitor gets lost or confused, simply remember what
Sahalee means: No parking.
</P>
<P>
   Don't stop until you find a mall.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
