<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-COLTS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KITNA POISED TO MAKE IMPACT FOR SEAHAWKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Just when Jon Kitna was getting comfortable with being
compared to Dave Krieg, another large log has been tossed on the
fire of excitement and anticipation blazing around the Seahawks'
young quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Mike Pritchard did it after Kitna completed 9 of
13 passes while directing two scoring drives in his first preseason
start Saturday night in a 24-21 victory over the Indianapolis Colts
at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   Pritchard compared Kitna to, of all people, Green Bay's Pro Bowl
quarterback, Brett Favre.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jon is a student of the game and he wants to get better. And
that's what you want in a young quarterback, somebody who wants to
be the best,'' Pritchard said.
</P>
<P>
   Pritchard then shared a conversation he had with Favre in 1991
while both were in Atlanta. Favre was a rookie quarterback, a trade
to the Green Bay Packers and five seasons removed from becoming a
two-time league MVP.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brett was always saying: `You know what? I'm going to be the
best quarterback in this league. You just watch, Pritch,' ''
Pritchard said. ``That's Kitna. He wants to be better, and he's
passing the test. That's who I compare Jon to right now _ that
young Brett Favre who was going to be the best and not let anyone
or anything stop him.''
</P>
<P>
   If Saturday night's game was a test, and it definitely was,
Kitna aced it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We keep giving him tests and he just keeps passing them,''
vice president of football operations Randy Mueller said about the
undrafted, second-year player from Central Washington. ``There were
things we wanted to see Jon do in this game, and we saw him do all
of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The significance of Kitna's leaps-and-bounds development has
intensified because starter Warren Moon's holdout is entering its
fourth week and John Friesz did not play well after replacing Kitna
against the Colts.
</P>
<P>
   Talks about restructuring Moon's contract are back to being
one-sided, because the club says it does not have the $4.5 million
Moon is seeking this season. The team is holding firm on its offer
of a one-year, $2 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Warren doesn't come back,'' Kitna said, bluntly, ``I'd be
more than happy to step in and take the job.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why Kitna started against the Colts. Everyone _ from
owner Paul Allen, to the coaches, to his teammates, to Kitna _
needed to see if he could do the things he has been doing on the
practice field in a game against another team's No. 1 defense.
</P>
<P>
   They saw Kitna make the throws, improvise and move the offense.
</P>
<P>
   His completion percentage would have been even higher if tight
end Christian Fauria had not slipped at the goal line to cause one
incompletion and wide receiver Joey Galloway had not let another
pass go off his hands.
</P>
<P>
   Showing a knack for making something from nothing, Kitna
scrambled 15 yards on the drive that ended with his TD pass to
Pritchard and later changed a play at the line of scrimmage and
completed a pass for a first down.
</P>
<P>
   Kitna produced 171 of the team's 371 yards in 31 plays _
compared to 200 yards in 53 plays after he left. Kitna was 3 of 4
for 47 yards on third-down passes, including his 25-yard TD toss to
Pritchard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about it, he gets those chains moving,'' coach
Dennis Erickson said Sunday after reviewing video tape of the game.
``He makes things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kitna's most impressive attribute was his poise. After
getting his frayed nerves under control, he seemed totally
unaffected by everything that was happening around him _ the
pre-game anticipation, the Colts' pass rush, the post-game crush of
reporters around his locker.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you stand in that huddle and you see (Howard) House
Ballard, Brian Habib, Kevin Glover, Pete Kendall and Walter Jones,
there's a sense of calmness that comes about,'' Kitna said about
his offensive linemen. ``They didn't get all excited for me being
in there. Joey and Pritchard gave me a little bit of a hard time,
but it was all in fun and I had a good time out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitna went to Central Washington with plans to be a high school
math teacher, not an NFL quarterback. Asked to grade his
performance against the Colts, he offered: ``I'd say B-plus. I
thought I played pretty well. That's grading on the curve, of
course.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitna was not perfect, and Erickson has yet to say who will
start this week's game against the San Francisco 49ers in
Vancouver, B.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to continue to get better,'' Erickson said. ``There
were a couple of times he probably should have thrown it someplace
else. But those are things he will continue to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Forget the closeness of the final score. The Seahawks were
handling the Colts in all three phases of the game before backup
quarterback Kelly Holcomb rallied Indianapolis to a third-quarter
TD and third-string defensive end Kendel Shello returned an Ahman
Green fumble for a score in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks looked good, but are they good enough without Moon?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very good football team,'' said Colts offensive line
coach Howard Mudd, who coached the same position the previous five
seasons with the Seahawks. ``They're the real deal.''
</P>
<P>
   And Kitna continues to look too good to be real.
</P>
<P>
   As the last players were filing out of the locker room, he sat
in front of his cubicle playing with his young son, Jordan, who was
dressed in overalls that had a Seahawks logo on the bib.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to hope it's the start of something that could last a
long time,'' he said of his first preseason start. ``It was
exciting to come out and play in front of the home fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been nice to have the offense get introduced
(before the game),'' he added with a laugh. ``But it was exciting.
It definitely was.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
