<HEADLINE>
MARINERS COMPLETE SWEEP OF TIGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ There is a new Tiger Stadium on the way, but Mariner
shortstop Alex Rodriguez has a special place in his heart for the
old one.
</P>
<P>
   The hits keep coming for him in this outdated ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   The 23-year-old shortstop hit a three-run home run in the
seventh inning on Sunday, lifting the Mariners to a 6-3 victory
over the Detroit Tigers and a sweep of their four-game series.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez went 9-for-15 during the series, scoring seven runs,
hitting two home runs and driving in six runs. He now is hitting
.374 (52-for-139) lifetime against Tiger pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea why I've had so much success here,'' Rodriguez
said. ``Maybe it goes back to when I was 18 years old, had some
good games here and that put some confidence in me.''
</P>
<P>
   With Rodriguez hitting, center fielder Ken Griffey Jr. making an
astounding catch and relievers Bob Wells, Heathcliff Slocumb and
Mike Timlin finishing what Bill Swift started, Seattle got its
first-ever four-game sweep against Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were four good games of baseball here,'' Mariner manager
Lou Piniella said. ``We played well in all phases, specifically our
pitching and just great timely hitting.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey Jr. robbed Luis Gonzalez of a two-run homer in the third
inning, reaching over the fence to catch the ball, but the big blow
came off Rodriguez's sizzling bat.
</P>
<P>
   With Shane Monahan and Joey Cora on base, Rodgriguez sent a Matt
Anderson slider over the left field fence, barely over Gonzalez's
glove, for his 35th homer of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a terrible pitch,'' Detroit manager Buddy Bell said.
``For Rodriguez to hit that pitch, he has to be seeing the ball
pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more surprising than Rodriguez's uncanny hitting against
Tiger pitching is that Seattle swept the series without getting a
homer from Griffey, who has 41 on the year but now has gone 42
at-bats without clearing a fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Griffey's obviously struggling at the plate right now,'' Bell
said, ``but that tells you something about his game. He played as
good a center field as you can play in this four-game series. He's
an extremely talented guy, and he couldn't have made that catch
unless he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella planned to use Griffey as the designated hitter Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has played every day in a demanding position,'' Piniella
said. ``Plus, he is constantly getting bombarded by the media about
the home run record. I think he's tired physically and mentally.''
</P>
<P>
   On cue, Griffey was asked about the homer drought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who knows me understands that Roger Maris' record means
nothing to me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   No one is talking about Rodriguez challenging Maris'
single-season home run record of 61, but he moved closer to
becoming only the third player in major league history to hit at
least 40 homers and steal 40 bases in the same season.
</P>
<P>
   Besides hitting his 35th homer Sunday, Rodriguez stole his 33rd
base.
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Martinez, contributed his 22nd homer, which gave the
Mariners a 1-0 lead in the second inning, and two singles. Monahan
singled twice and scored a run. And Raul Ibanez, inserted at first
base when Griffey went to center field, slugged an opposite-field
homer to left field in fifth, giving the M's a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Swift checked the Tigers on one run through four innings, but
Detroit scored twice in the bottom of the fifth to grab a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   After Martinez delivered a game-tying single to center in the
top of the sixth, Wells survived a leadoff double in the bottom
half of the inning, setting the tone for another solid relief
effort from Seattle's bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are really pitching well,'' Piniella said of his
once-suspect relievers.
</P>
<P>
   Slocumb ended a Tiger threat in the seventh inning by striking
out pinch-hitting Geronimo Berroa with runners on second and third.
Timlin secured his team-leading ninth save despite Rodriguez's
error on Gonzalez's grounder leading off the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Timlin struck out Damion Easley and Bobby Higginson before
getting match point on a grounder to Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners are off Monday and continue the nine-game road trip
Tuesday night in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez continued his hot hitting despite having the middle
finger on his right hand bruised by a pitch Saturday night. The
finger will be examined today in Toronto, where he has a .375
career average and went 6-for-10 at SkyDome earlier this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
