<HEADLINE>
SAHALEE GREETS EARLY ARRIVALS FOR PGA CHAMPIONSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ South African Ernie Els, one of the PGA Tour's
tallest players at 6-foot-3, took one look around the fairways of
Sahalee Country Club, site of this week's PGA Championship, and
felt a bit dwarfed by the scenery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen trees this tall on a golf course,'' the
two-time U.S. Open champion said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Sahalee's tall firs and cedars caught the attention of the early
arrivals in a field that includes the world's top 150 golfers vying
for the last major championship of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Among those on the course Sunday for a practice round were last
year's PGA runner-up Justin Leonard, 1989 PGA champion Payne
Stewart, 1992 PGA runner-up Nick Faldo and U.S. Open champion Lee
Janzen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like heavily tree-lined courses, and being very narrow
doesn't bother me any,'' said Janzen, who tamed another tight
course at the Open, San Francisco's Olympic Club. ``You just have
to start the ball straight.''
</P>
<P>
   Janzen traveled eight hours Saturday from his home in Orlando,
Fla., to get ready for a run at his second major title of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just good to get here early and then be rested for
Tuesday and Wednesday to get some real good work in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if it was important for him to get an early look at the
Redmond course because of his loss last year to defending champion
Davis Love III, Leonard replied: ``Not just because of that, but
because this is a major championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those competing for $2.6 million in prize money will be 13
past PGA Champions, including Love, who will be trying to become
the first repeat title holder in 61 years.
</P>
<P>
   While the players trickled in Sunday, tournament volunteers,
Sahalee staff and PGA officials were adding the final trimmings for
the Northwest's first major golf championship since 1946, when Ben
Hogan won the event at the Portland Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been very exciting and very educational,'' said Sahalee
member George Smith, who has helped run the annual Northwest
Players Championship at the course, but never managed an event of
the magnitude of the PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of pride here right now,'' added Jim Pike,
Sahalee's head pro. ``Pride among the membership in that they
actually realize now that the tournament is here and that they see
the world is ready to showcase their golf course. And they are
elated that it's in such good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Only about a dozen spectators gathered around the practice green
and driving range Sunday, taking in the last day of peace and
serenity before the crowds of up to 30,000 begin to show up.
Practice rounds will be conducted Monday through Wednesday before
the tournament begins on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   One of the onlookers was Frank Carter of Yakima, who will work
for the rest of the week as one of the tournament's volunteer
security officers while his wife, Bonnie, works in the merchandise
tent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't miss this for the world,'' he said. ``As soon as
the call went out for volunteers, we put our hats in.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the players who arrived Sunday had never seen the course
before and were favorably impressed by the beauty of the layout and
the ideal summer weather.
</P>
<P>
   Faldo, an Englishman who also makes his home in Orlando, Fla.,
found the conditions pleasant compared to the sticky humidity of
last year's PGA Championship at Winged Foot in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played in Portland and Vancouver (B.C.) before, but not
here. This is lovely indeed,'' Faldo said.
</P>
<P>
   For Faldo, getting to the course early was important just to get
a feel for the conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The atmosphere is great and it looks really nice,'' he said of
the course.
</P>
<P>
   Els agreed. ``I've heard some really good things about the
course, and it just looks beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Also playing a practice round was Scott Williams, a teaching pro
at Bellevue's Glendale Country Club who qualified for this event by
finishing ninth during the PGA Club Pro Championship in June.
Williams lives barely a mile from Sahalee and has played the course
at least a dozen times since qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   ``The course is firming up a little bit more, and it appears
that the greens are a hair quicker this week'' because of the warm
weather, Williams said. ``They are going to get a lot faster, but
the course is in very good shape. It's getting tougher.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams noted that the rough, now 4-6 inches deep, is as tough
as he's ever seen it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't hit many shots out of it, not that I haven't hit
many into it,'' Williams said. ``Right now, I don't want to hurt
myself, literally, by hitting out of the stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Els has played only once before in the Seattle area, during the
Fred Couples Invitational three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite important to get out early for a course you have
never seen before to get a look at it when there are not many
players out here,'' he said. ``You want to start getting a picture
of what you have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason he was able to get to Seattle early was because he
has taken three weeks off from other PGA events to rest his back,
which had been giving him trouble since before the U.S. Open in
July.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see how it goes, but I think my back should be OK,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pike praised the members for their work in getting the course
ready and noted that the PGA now takes over most of the work
surrounding the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have my staff handling the range and the carts, and Thursday
through Sunday I'll either be starting on the first hole or
announcing on nine or 18,'' Pike said. ``I feel like I'm the
luckiest guy in the world. The only thing that would have been
better is to be playing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-98 0049EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
