<HEADER>
A5509 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO--WORLDS-HNS &LR;      08-10 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO--WORLDS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
U.S. whips Greece, takes third place
<TEXT>
<P>
   By EDDIE SEFKO &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   ATHENS, Greece _ Two teams were above them on the risers during
the medal ceremony for the 13th FIBA World Championship of
Basketball.
</P>
<P>
   But nobody stood taller than these Americans as they accepted
their bronze medals and floral bouquets Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   They've been called misfits, castoffs, unknowns, and the
basketball equivalent of riffraff. But the 12 players, led by coach
Rudy Tomjanovich, who cruised to third place with an 84-61 bashing
of the host team from Greece, knew as they draped their rewards
around their necks that they had done more than anybody at home in
the United States could have expected.
</P>
<P>
   They represented their country with class and won their spot on
the medal stand with heart and sweat.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always want to set your goals for the gold,'' David Wood
said. ``But I can't think of anything I'm more proud of than this
medal. It's probably the greatest accomplishment of my basketball
career.''
</P>
<P>
   Eleven teammates felt the same way, although their
disappointment at not getting to play for the gold medal was
obvious. And understandable. They had lost a heartbreaking 66-64
game to Russia a night earlier, dooming them to play the Greeks for
the bronze.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some disappointment,'' Tomjanovich said. ``Our goal
was the gold. We were two points away from having that opportunity.
Then to have this challenge against a very, very good Greek team on
their court and to come up with a big win _ I couldn't be more
proud of this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Barely a month in the making, the Americans didn't leave with
the gold. But they were better than 13 countries that have had
their national teams together much longer. And they were far better
than the Greeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``That Greek reporter that said we were the lint after the wash
might want to retract that statement,'' Wood said. ``I guess we
stick in there, don't we?''
</P>
<P>
   As Ashraf Amaya added: ``It wasn't the gold, but we didn't go
home empty-handed. It's not the one we wanted, but we have to be
thankful. It could have been a lot worse. There were a lot of
people who didn't think we'd even be playing for a medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like we represented the country very well. We kept our
character. We kept our poise. I don't think any team we played
against could say that we did anything like trash-talking or cheap
shots.''
</P>
<P>
   With 15,000 Greeks cheering on the home team Sunday, the U.S.
team was faced with the task of having to play Greece for the
bronze medal. It was the equivalent of an ant having the home-hill
advantage against the elephant. The Americans squashed them.
</P>
<P>
   The American replacement players for the Dream Team were on
equal footing with Russia, Yugoslavia, Italy and others in the
tournament, but they showed the Greeks how much distance the
blossoming basketball country has to cover before it can stand
toe-to-toe with even America's non-NBA talent.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia eked out a 64-62 victory over Russia in the
gold-medal game; the Americans felt almost as if they had
accomplished more than the Dream Team did in sweeping to the gold
medal in the past two Olympics or the '94 World Championship.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans jumped on Greece early, scoring 15 consecutive
points to go ahead 19-6 as Jimmy Oliver and Jason Sasser each
scored five points in the run.
</P>
<P>
   After that, it was all for show. The lead grew to 38-18 before
halftime, then hit 80-50 late in the game before the Greeks trimmed
the margin in the final three minutes. Sasser led the Americans
with 23 points. But as always, they were balanced, with every
player scoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expected a much tougher game,'' Tomjanovich said. ``They
have never won a medal before. But our guys wanted a medal very
badly, too. They (the Greeks) were a little bit down, but I give
credit to my team.''
</P>
<P>
   For the players, the joy outweighed the frustration of playing
for third place instead of first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal was to get the gold medal,'' Oliver said.
``Unfortunately, we lost and weren't able to do that. So we wanted
to finish as good as we could.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always are going to say something. People are never
going to be happy with anything less than the gold medal. And even
if we had won the gold medal, they would have said, `Yeah, but they
aren't the Dream Team.' I just think we played hard and did our
best. Getting the bronze makes the trip more enjoyable than losing
and getting nothing. To have something concrete to hold on to is
important. Not getting anything would have been terrible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't out to prove people wrong or compete against (the
legacy) of the Dream Team. We just were trying to be the best that
this team could be.''
</P>
<P>
   That best turned out to be bronze. In hindsight, the reason the
Americans didn't get a chance to play Yugoslavia for the gold was
their shooting in the semifinal game.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that we had throughout the tournament was making the
3-point shot,'' said Del Harris, an assistant to Tomjanovich. ``In
this game, we make it. Last night (against Russia), if we just make
one more, it's a different story. One little thing here or there
can be a big difference. Against Russia we were 4-for-22, and
tonight we were better (7-for-18).''
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich had nothing but fond memories of the tournament and
said it was hard to believe the entire thing was over in just more
than a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``A month ago, when we were putting this team together, nobody
gave us much of a chance at any kind of success,'' he said. ``We
didn't know what would happen. But these were a bunch of
hard-working players who came together very quickly. I couldn't be
prouder.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
