<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG TRADE IS GOLDEN... BUT IS IT FOOL'S GOLD?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The luster from The Big Trade, suffice to
say, no longer dazzles the crowd at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the Texas Rangers are better. I think. Maybe. Kinda.
</P>
<P>
   And I say that unequivocably. Sort of. Perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   But after Sunday night's 14-8 loss to Boston, reality is
starting to bite at the Rangers' new wings. The new pitcher pitches
like the old pitcher. The new third baseman, alas, is no longer
batting .800.
</P>
<P>
   What could have been a playoff-preview series with the Red Sox
over the weekend ended up unearthing more question marks than it
answered. Like, just how silly/intriguing would Mo Vaughn look next
year in red shoes? And who exactly is the No. 1 starter in this
fickle Rangers rotation?
</P>
<P>
   Add to the intrigue the strained ribcage of Lee Stevens and the
stiff neck of Juan Gonzalez, and you get an idea of the extra
baggage that the Rangers will tote on the road with them this week.
</P>
<P>
   Eight days in American League shark tanks like Jacobs Field,
Yankee Stadium and Fenway Park could sink the Rangers' playoff
optimism, or send it bobbing merrily to the surface. In either
case, what happened Saturday and Sunday at The Ballpark didn't
qualify as a champagne sendoff.
</P>
<P>
   The combined line for Rangers starting pitchers Aaron Sele and
Todd Stottlemyre looked like such:
</P>
<P>
   A total of 8 innings, 14 hits, 13 runs, 7 walks, 3 home runs, 2
losses.
</P>
<P>
   What new guy Stottlemyre showed in grit in his first outing
dissolved into murky disarray Sunday night against the Red Sox. He
was all over the place. That elusive AL strike zone?
</P>
<P>
   Even at his worst, Stottlemyre looks more capable and more
confident than the departed Darren Oliver ever showed this season.
But not getting through the fifth inning was what soured the
Rangers on Oliver in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Of the four new acquisitions, Stottlemyre has been the most
disappointing and _ for the Rangers _ the most potentially
devastating. When your purported No. 1 guy in the rotation can't do
it consistently, you're on a treadmill, not a race to a pennant.
</P>
<P>
   The visiting Red Sox were deemed a good measuring stick. They
are the best of the AL's non-division leaders, eternally doomed to
be graded on the pinstriped curve. If the Red Sox' 68-47 record
were in the AL West, on a 97-degree night like Sunday, the Rangers
wouldn't have been hearing cheers, but crickets.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers promptly won the first two games of the series, and
The Big Trade was looking downright invigorating. But then came
Sele's and Stottlemyre's outings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very proud of the way the team responded,'' first baseman
Vaughn said, after Boston had leveled the series and he,
personally, had left craters on the center-field hill. ``It was
great to get the last two to wrap up a very successful road trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, of course, is the loudest, largest, impending free-agent
first baseman that will be on the market this winter. The Rangers
have one, too. In fact, Rangers first baseman Will Clark had more
runs batted in than Vaughn going into Sunday night's contest.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of Vaughn, wearing Rangers red, taking aim at The
Ballpark's right-field porch should drive some fans giddy. He does,
remember, figure to cost about twice on the open market what Clark
will.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, there's this pitching itch that won't go away.
Inconsistency haunts the Rangers starters.
</P>
<P>
   They got eight runs ... against Boston ... and lost?
</P>
<P>
   After the game, manager Johnny Oates offered the opinion, ``I
think we have a much better team right now than we did at the start
of the homestand.''
</P>
<P>
   That was one Stottlemyre, a Todd Zeile and one Royce Clayton
ago. And Oates is right, if for no reason than Clayton alone. The
new shortstop's play in the eighth inning Sunday night _ going into
left field, spinning, and doubling off Orlando Merced at first base
was a season highlight.
</P>
<P>
   But after his steamy start, Zeile is starting to return to room
temperature. Stottlemyre, again, was expected to pitch better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think just winning some ballgames gives a team confidence,''
left fielder Rusty Greer said. ``If we can play consistently, put
some more wins together, we'll be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, in other words, the simplest tasks, put simply,
present the most taxing challenges.
</P>
<P>
   A huge road test against Jim Thome-less Cleveland, mighty New
York and Vaughn-fueled Boston awaits.
</P>
<P>
   For the Rangers, the Big Trade doesn't shine like gold anymore.
</P>
<P>
   But they're better. Sort of. Kinda. As we'll soon see.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
