<SLUG> BC-RANGERS-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOTTLEMYRE TAKES BLAME FOR BAD OUTING
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The first person who locates right-hander
Todd Stottlemyre within shouting distance of an excuse deserves an
exorbitant finder's fee.
</P>
<P>
   No one should expect to become rich.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre, who sustained an injury to his rib cage before the
Texas Rangers acquired the 33-year-old pitcher July 31 from the
Cardinals, refused to alibi for his problems in a 14-8 loss to the
Red Sox on Sunday night at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre _ who manager Johnny Oates removed before the fifth
inning _ could not prevent the Rangers from incurring their second
consecutive loss, which allowed the Angels to move to two games
behind the American League West front-runners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to use that as an excuse,'' Stottlemyre said.
``One thing I won't do is make excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates also dismissed any concerns regarding Stottlemyre's
health.
</P>
<P>
   ``I created my own jams by walking people,'' Stottlemyre said.
``You walk four guys against a team like that and ...''
</P>
<P>
   Well, a pitcher pays for it.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the evening became worse after Stottlemyre (1-1) departed
with the Rangers trailing, 6-2. Left-hander Eric Gunderson promptly
surrendered seven runs in his 1 2/3 innings, which effectively
negated the Rangers' six-run fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Red Sox's seemingly endless third inning
proved ghastly and exhausting.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre, who issued walks to four of the 10 Red Sox batters,
required 57 pitches to complete the lengthy inning. Catcher Scott
Hatteberg greeted Stottlemyre with a leadoff single and advanced to
third on the ensuing walks to second baseman Donnie Sadler _ the
Red Sox's No. 9 hitter _ and center fielder Darren Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw the ball in the right areas, but I kept missing by
three-to-six inches,'' said Stottlemyre, who allowed four walks in
5 2/3 innings in his start Tuesday against the Blue Jays. ``They
had a pretty good game plan coming in. They were aggressive early
and were able to take a lot of close pitches. It was a bit
uncharacteristic for me, but it's not like I was wild.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatteberg and Sadler scored on a line drive that John Valentin
whacked into right field, and the Red Sox loaded the bases again
when first baseman Mo Vaughn drew the third walk of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Todd Zeile, who the Rangers acquired from the
Marlins on the same afternoon they obtained Stottlemyre, prolonged
the inning with his second error in three games on a potential
double-play ground ball off the bat of shortstop Nomar Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis scored the Red Sox's third run on the play, and designated
hitter Orlando Merced later drew a run-scoring walk to culminate
the four-run inning. Stottlemyre retired Hatteberg on strikes _ his
third strikeout of the inning _ before returning to the dugout with
81 pitches through four innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``That might be an all-timer for me,'' Stottlemyre said of the
57-pitch inning. ``I gave up four runs, but I could have given up
10 that inning.''
</P>
<P>
   It served as a distinct contrast from the second inning, in
which he retired the side in order on strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early in the game, Todd was making all the pitches he had
to,'' Oates said. ``Then, he started missing by two or three inches
and just couldn't make the correction.''
</P>
<P>
   The appearance represented the third consecutive start for
Stottlemyre where he didn't reach six innings. He had done that in
21 of his first 22 starts.
</P>
<P>
   The rib cage might be bothering Stottlemyre, but the world will
never know if it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not to make any excuses for it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So we understand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
