<P>
   NATIONAL _ GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   NAPALM-DISPOSAL (Deer Park, Texas) _ Four months ago, after
local residents and politicians screamed bloody murder, a train
carrying 22,000 gallons of napalm en route to an Indiana disposal
facility was abruptly halted and turned back to California, where
it had been moldering since the end of the Vietnam War. In July,
another toxic waste company inherited the napalm disposal contract.
But this time the company, GNI Group, is situated along Houston's
heavily industrialized Ship Channel, one of the globe's largest and
densest concentrations of petro-chemical facilities. The result was
that very same shipment of napalm eased its way into Texas three
weeks ago with only the briefest flurry of complaint.
</P>
<P>
   HATTERAS-LIGHTHOUSE (Cape Hatteras, N.C.) _ The U.S. Park
Service wants to move the Hatteras Light, the candy-striped tower
that is the most recognizable lighthouse in America, to save it
from the ever-advancing sea. But residents and business owners in
this part of the Outer Banks say that moving the lighthouse will
destroy its character, and hurt tourism. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   CLIMATE-DISEASE (Undated) _ Scientists have long theorized that
climatic changes related to global warming could unleash outbreaks
of diseases like malaria, dengue fever, cholera and heat stroke.
But with the modest amount of warming experienced so far, they have
been unable to produce much hard evidence. Now the experts have a
research gift from an unlikely benefactor: El Nino. Combined with
an underlying global warming trend, say scientists who track such
things, El Nino will probably make 1998 the warmest year in several
centuries. By William K. Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-WATERMELONS (Moscow) _ Nature has much to do with
Russia's watermelon glut. A heat wave in southern Russia, Ukraine,
Moldova and Azerbaijan helped produce a particularly rich harvest
early this summer. But Moscow's crowded watermelon market also owes
something to the kind of hit-or-miss farm-to-market trading that
makes capitalism, Russian-style, a unique experience. By Celestine
Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-EMBASSY (Nairobi, Kenya) _ By design, terrorist attacks
are ruthlessly indiscriminate. The blast that tore through the
embassy here was no exception, taking and sparing lives at will as
it shattered the belief that any U.S. outpost could be a
low-security risk. By Raymond Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS DAY
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `f' category)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-SMALLSTOCKS (Undated) _ While the stocks of large
companies like Coca-Cola and Philip Morris have been battered for
much of the last month, the stocks of smaller companies have
suffered much more, prompting some Wall Street analysts to talk
about a darker side of the bull market and even to suggest that a
bear market is in the offing. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDEN-BOOKS-MEDIA (Undated) _ Before Richard Snyder's
unceremonious ouster in 1994, he was noted at Simon and Schuster
for publishing prestigious authors and reigning with a certain
imperiousness. The last two years, however, have found him
struggling to make a career comeback in a part of the book world
better known for $1.99 classics like ``The Poky Little Puppy.'' By
Geraldine Fabrikant and Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   PRICELINE-INTERNET (Undated) _ Priceline, a small start-up
company in Connecticut, has devised a new way of selling on the
Internet. By Peter H. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   CELLPHONE-CHIPS (Santa Clara, Calif.) _ New technology is being
used for the chips installed in cellular telephones. By John
Markoff.
