<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS HITTERS DON'T HELP PARK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Chan Ho Park set out to make history Sunday, but
all the Dodgers right-hander got for his effort was an embarrassing
baserunning error and a broken winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   Park carried an 11-game string of wins at Dodger Stadium into
his start against the Pittsburgh Pirates, and a 12th would have
tied Orel Hershiser's club record for consecutive home victories.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Park's seven strong innings went to waste in the wake
of another Dodgers hitting drought and an eventual 2-1 loss to the
Pirates before 43,227. And he had to endure the additional insult
of being thrown out at first base after hitting safely in the sixth
inning when he accidentally turned toward second base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not disappointed,'' Park (10-6) said of the missed record,
``because I have more (opportunities) in the future. Maybe next
time.''
</P>
<P>
   He meant, of course, the next time he holds an 11-game winning
streak at home, a rarity but not an impossibility for the promising
25-year-old in his third full year in the majors. Hershiser set the
mark at a young age himself (27), winning a dozen from September
1984 to October 1985.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just started,'' noted Park, 16-6 with a 2.56 ERA for his
career at Dodger Stadium. ``I feel more comfortable, confident; I
feel at home here.''
</P>
<P>
   Pirates starter Chris Peters (6-8) looked equally comfortable,
shutting down the Dodgers on four hits over seven innings. His lone
mistake was a seventh-inning solo home run by Bobby Bonilla.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the Dodgers offense was silent. Though they took two
of three games from the Pirates, the Dodgers managed just six runs
in the series, despite having the heart of the order back intact
for the last two games. The Dodgers have scored 11 runs in their
last six games, stranding 40 runners over that span.
</P>
<P>
   Three through five hitters Raul Mondesi, Gary Sheffield and Eric
Karros went hitless in 11 at-bats Sunday. Mondesi struck out three
times in four at-bats for the second game in a row since returning
from a back injury.
</P>
<P>
   The back, while sore, is not to blame, Mondesi said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sore, just a little bit. I'm not making excuses,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He did, however, cite the afternoon sun in the rare 5 p.m. start
as a problem. ``In the first through fourth innings, I couldn't see
the ball real good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the layoff from the sore lower back, which knocked him out
of two games and parts of two others, probably affected Mondesi's
timing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't take batting practice for a week,'' he said. ``I know
I'll get it back. I don't worry about it too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Bonilla's homer _ his first since May 16, a span of
136 at-bats _ the Dodgers got as far as second base only twice.
Mark Grudzielanek's sixth-inning double was their only other
extra-base hit. But it might have gone a long way if not for Park's
baserunning gaffe.
</P>
<P>
   Park led off the sixth with a hard-hit single to right field. As
Pirates right fielder Jose Guillen scooped it up, Park passed first
base and turned just slightly toward second, though he didn't take
a step and thought he was safe. Instead, Guillen threw to catcher
Jason Kendall, who fired back to first baseman Kevin Young, who
applied the tag while Park was jogging back toward the bag.
</P>
<P>
   First-base umpire Rich Rieker called Park out, and arguments
from Park and manager Glenn Hoffman proved futile.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Rieker) said (Park) made an attempt to second base, which is
correct. He didn't have to go over the foul line,'' Hoffman said.
``That's what he saw and that's what he had to call.''
</P>
<P>
   Park admitted he was unclear on the rule, believing he was safe
as long as he didn't cross the foul line.
</P>
<P>
   The loss prevented the Dodgers from making up another game on
the Chicago Cubs in the wild-card race. L.A. remains four games
behind Chicago, with the New York Mets and San Francisco Giants
ahead of them in the chase.
</P>
<P>
   But taking two of three from the Pirates reopened the door that
nearly slammed shut with last week's trio of losses at Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a good series, two out of three,'' Mondesi said. ``If
you do that every series, you make the playoffs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
