<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-RANGERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN LEAVES HIS MARK ON TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ With Mo Vaughn leaving some historic
footprints, the Red Sox Sunday night stomped out the notion they're
not big enough for Texas, running up double figures in runs for the
second straight game.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn hit home runs in consecutive innings, driving in four
runs, and just missed a third home run in a 14-8 Red Sox win over
the Rangers before a crowd of 31,127 at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Hatteberg and rookie Donnie Sadler also homered as the Red
Sox escaped here with a split of their four-game series with the
American League West leaders, scoring 25 runs and collecting 30
hits after losing the first two.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a key part of the season, a key moment after two
losses,'' said Vaughn, who now has 31 home runs, six of which came
on this trip, to become just the third player in Red Sox history to
hit at least 30 in four consecutive seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to get even one here. A lot of crazy things happen
to the Boston Red Sox when they come to Texas. I'm very proud of
the way the team responded.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox return home with an 8-4 record on their longest trip
of the season _ a 14-day tour of the AL West.
</P>
<P>
   When they left on July 27, the Red Sox held a 4 1/2-game lead in
the wild-card race. They return home 7 1/2 games ahead of Anaheim,
8 1/2 ahead of Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to stick with the right attitude,'' said Vaughn.
``We're all tired. We all feel like we left a month ago, but we
survived it. There's no time now for a letdown. No time not to be
focused.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimmie Foxx hit 30 or more home runs in five consecutive seasons
(1936-40) for the Red Sox. Ted Williams, in a streak that was
interrupted by three years of military service, did it in four
straight seasons (1941-42, 1946-47). They're both in the Hall of
Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's pretty good company to be in,'' Vaughn said. ``Every
season you have expectations of doing things, but once you get to
30, you want to try and really explode and get on top of your game
as much as possible. There are still a lot of runs to drive in, a
lot of games to play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox took advantage of a wild Todd Stottlemyre, who
walked five in the first four innings, and former Sox reliever Eric
Gunderson, who gave up seven runs in 1 2/3 innings in the worst
outing of his career.
</P>
<P>
   John Valentin's two-run single was one of only two hits the Sox
had in their four-run third, in which Stottlemyre threw 57 pitches,
walked four, and was further undone when third baseman Todd Zeile
booted Nomar Garciaparra's double-play grounder with the bases
loaded.
</P>
<P>
   One out after Sadler tripled to open the fourth and scored on
Darren Lewis's sacrifice fly, Vaughn hit his first home run of the
night off Stottlemyre, a 429-foot drive to the deepest part of the
stadium that landed halfway up the lawn beyond the center-field
fence.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn didn't hit his 30th home run last season until Aug. 31,
in the team's 137th game of the season. This one came six weeks
earlier, in game No. 115.
</P>
<P>
   No. 30 made it 6-2, Sox. An inning later, after a double by Troy
O'Leary and walk to Darren Bragg, Hatteberg unloaded off Gunderson
for a three-run home run, his 10th homer of the season and second
on the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Gunderson then proceeded to give up a single to Lewis and a walk
to Valentin, setting the stage for Vaughn's first three-run home
run of the season, a 399-foot drive into the bleachers in
left-center.
</P>
<P>
   It was Vaughn's second two-homer game of the series, fourth this
season, and 22d multi-home run game of his career, including the
two occasions when he hit three in a game. In the seventh, Vaughn
drove right fielder Mike Simms back to the warning track for his
flyout, and in his final at-bat he lined deep to left.
</P>
<P>
   But what should have been an easy win for Sox starter John
Wasdin unraveled in the fifth, when Wasdin couldn't stand the
prosperity of a 10-run lead. Wasdin retired 11 in a row, but in the
fifth the Rangers put together five straight hits and four runs,
forcing manager Jimy Williams to go to Derek Lowe.
</P>
<P>
   That quickly, Wasdin blew a chance at his sixth win and an
opportunity to solidify his hold on a spot in the starting
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe walked the first batter he faced and gave up a two-run
double to Will Clark before order was restored. Jim Corsi pitched a
1-2-3 sixth and received credit for his first win since June 1.
Corsi and three relievers _ Dennis Eckersley, Greg Swindell, and
Tom Gordon _ combined to hold the Rangers to one hit in the last
four innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big thing is the way we're playing,'' Williams said. ``The
intensity we're playing with. A lot of people are contributing, up
and down the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's been a tough trip, but it's behind us. We played
good, we pitched good, and we ended on a strong note.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
