<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-VIKINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS OFFENSIVE AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Ernie Zampese's offense has picked up where
it left off in Dallas. And that isn't good news for the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   After New England's first-team offense stumbled in a 14-13 loss
to the 49ers last week at 3Com Park, the performance didn't improve
significantly in the second exhibition game Sunday night against
the Minnesota Vikings, who took a 28-0 win before a quiet 54,111 at
Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Zampese, New England's new offensive coordinator, guided Dallas
last season, and the Cowboys offense ranked 24th in the league.
After two subpar showings, the Patriots are 0-2 and off to their
worst exhibition start since 1993 (Bill Parcells's first year).
They left the field at the half to a chorus of boos. By the end of
the game, there weren't enough fans left to voice much displeasure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week we wanted to do some things. This week they wanted
to work on the timing so we didn't have a game plan like we would
in the regular season,'' said Patriots captain Bruce Armstrong.
``In the preseason games, when they go good they go good and when
they go bad they go bad. It did not look good tonight, but you take
it for what it's worth and you go back to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Drew Bledsoe went 7 for 15 for 74 yards, but of more importance,
was sacked three times by the pumped-up Vikings front line, which
had its way with the Patriots' offensive line. Not only did the
line not pass block well, it didn't run block well either as
neither Sedrick Shaw (eight carries, 13 yards)nor Harold Shaw
(13-22) was able to bust loose. The Patriots ran for just 66 yards
on 24 carries. Derrick Cullors, who rushed only twice, led them
with 24 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure you guys just look at the score but we actually made
some progress,'' said wide receiver Shawn Jefferson. ``We were able
to forward some of the things on our offense and we still have a
lot of time to get things straightened out. There are some timing
things where we have to get open quicker as receivers and I think
that's coming. I know that sounds strange when it's 28-0, but
that's how we feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe, who took part in 30 plays and sustained a couple of
cuts on his chin, also seemed upbeat, saying progress was made with
Zampese's new quick-striking offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first time I actually felt like I was in a game,''
Bledsoe said. ``I was sacked a few times and I had to rush some
throws. But I think it was good to experience that. I think it's
going to take some time, but our offense will get there.''
</P>
<P>
   But coach Pete Carroll wasn't so pleased. It may be a tough week
of practice at Bryant College before the team sets out for Mexico
City for an exhibition against Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't getting much done,'' said Carroll. ``Obviously, camp
isn't paying off yet. It seems like we make progress in drills but
then when the lights go on, we can't seem to forward that.'' Of the
running game, Carroll said, ``There's not much to assess. We
averaged 2 yards per carry,'' actually 2.8, the same as last week.
</P>
<P>
   A good indicator of the ineffective performance of the line came
midway through the second quarter. On fourth and 1 at the Vikings
38-yard line, Bledsoe handed off to Harold Shaw, who was stuffed
for a 2-yard loss. There was absolutely no push by the line.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll had said during the week that the first team would stay
in the game as long as it took to get something accomplished.
Evidently, Carroll grew impatient as he brought Scott Zolak into
the game with 7:33 left in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings drew first blood with 13:01 left in the second
quarter on linebacker Dwayne Rudd's 34-yard return of an
interception that wasn't Bledsoe's fault. Bledsoe threw a perfect
pass to Terry Glenn about 9 yards downfield, but Glenn, who still
hasn't caught a pass this preseason, was rattled by cornerback
Corey Fuller, bobbling the ball into Rudd's hands.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings scored again on their first possession of the third
quarter, culminating with rookie Randy Moss's 44-yard touchdown
reception over Mark Tate. The pass, delivered by veteran
quarterback Randall Cunningham, was caught by Moss at the 4.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' second defense, which had played well against the
49ers, looked as if it hadn't even practiced all week. On the
Vikings' second possession of the third quarter, rookie Greg Spires
sacked Cunningham for a 2-yard loss, but the defense couldn't ride
that momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots rookie cornerback Tebucky Jones interfered with Moss on
a sideline pattern for a 14-yard penalty to the 35, and the Vikings
were off and running again. Cunningham connected with running back
Scottie Graham on a swing pass that went for 17 yards when a few
defenders missed tackles.
</P>
<P>
   The drive came to fruition when Cunningham threaded the needle
to tight end Andrew Glover for an 18-yard toss that was caught in
front of strong safety Larry Whigham, making it 21-0.
</P>
<P>
   Zolak, who had a decent game against the 49ers, fell back, going
3 of 10 for 36 yards. Northeastern's Jim Murphy got the call in the
fourth quarter, his first action of the preseason, but he didn't do
much either.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings scored their fourth touchdown in the fourth quarter
when third-stringer Todd Bouman connected with running back Mo
Williams on a 13-yard pass with 9:55 left.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
