<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 01:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5527 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SHAUGHNESSYCOLUMN     08-10 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S TILL PRESEASON 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Where have you gone, Marion Butts? Patriot
Nation turns its lonely eyes to you.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots played a home game Sunday night, an exhibition to
be sure, but still their first Foxboro Stadium appearance since
they made the Dolphins cry here last Dec. 28.
</P>
<P>
   New England was trounced by the Minnesota Vikings, 28-0. Let the
speed-dialing begin as the bloodthirsty shut-ins of talk radio take
the long knives to coach Pete Carroll, offensive coordinator Ernie
Zampese, quarterback Drew Bledsoe, and running backs Sedrick and
Harold Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing dramatic happened in Foxborough Sunday night. There was
no ceremonial pregame coin flip featuring Massachusetts House
Speaker Thomas Finneran. There was no pregame traffic jam. There
was no booth selling tickets for The Lilith Fair. There was no
rookie Robert Edwards (groin pull) in the Patriot backfield. There
was no relief from the heat and the bad moon risin' over the ugly
stadium. And naturally, there was no preseason break from the $15
parking fee.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and there was no pulse from the Patriots' first-team
offense. Again. No catches by Terry Glenn. No touchdown drives by
Bledsoe. And no emergence of a go-to running back.
</P>
<P>
   This is where we are supposed to remind you not to worry. Sunday
night's game was only an exhibition and there are three more to be
played before anything counts. The Patriots are instituting
Zampese's new offense and it takes time to get the timing down.
</P>
<P>
   But Carroll admitted, ``It's quite clear we haven't gotten much
done here. Group-wise, we're not moving along here. To be executing
that poorly at this time is unacceptable. Fortunately we have some
preseason games left.''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody got that? Don't worry about the fact that the Patriots
were hitless wonders at the end of last season and have thus far
played as if they don't want to stain their trousers for fear the
pants will be sent to the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe was on the field for only five series of downs. His
first three non-drives resulted in punts. Then came an
interception, which was converted into a 34-yard Vikings touchdown
return. In fairness, the pick wasn't Bledsoe's fault _ Glenn had a
chance to make his first catch of the preseason, but boxed the
ball. Minnesota linebacker Dwayne Rudd picked the pass from the air
and ran home.
</P>
<P>
   In the final Drew drive, the Patriots faced a fourth-and-1 on
the Minnesota 38-yard line and managed to lose 2 yards on a Harold
Shaw run. There were mock cheers when backup Scott Zolak took the
field with 7:22 left in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to look at it positively, but I think we made some
strides offensively,'' said Bledsoe. ``We're trying to work on our
stuff. Basically, things have to happen faster. It's an offense
that requires a great deal of decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Zolak didn't have much to work with, either. The running game
just wasn't there. The Shaw Twins carried the ball 15 times in the
first half for a combined total of 26 yards. Yeesh. When they were
living, George Bernard Shaw and Clay Shaw could have gained 26
yards on 15 carries. And this comes on the heels of the Candlestick
debacle when the Patriots ran 32 times for 88 yards. Sunday night,
the Patriots ran 24 times for 66 yards and one first down. Good
thing New England's running game is not being held down by that
no-good Curtis Martin anymore.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Patriot fans were patient with the local 11.
Despite the oppresive heat, and inconsiderate (Sunday night!)
timing, Billy Sullivan's Stadium was packed (a live gate of 54,111
with only 6,181 wise no-shows) and most of the loyalists stuck
around after halftime, eager no doubt to see Jim Murphy take a few
snaps. Murph got into the game at the end of the third quarter. The
New England diehards also got to see Minnesota backup wide
receiver, Yo Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, what the fans saw was positively dreadful, but that
is the nature of preseason football. Buyer beware. The NFL
exhibition season is fraudulent by definition. It is intramural
intensity at big league prices.
</P>
<P>
   It'll be interesting to see how long the local patience lasts
while Carroll and Zampese implore the masses to give them a little
more time to get things together.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' next preseason game is in Mexico City. It's always
a good idea to leave the country after a performance like Sunday
night's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to move on from here,'' said Carroll. ``We will. We
have three more weeks to work. We're extremely disappointed with
where we are now. We'll take a look at everything we're doing and
assess why we're not moving along.''
</P>
<P>
   But remember ... it's only preseason. Check out the Red Sox and
come back in four weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-98 0150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
