<HEADER>
A5528 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-WAGNER-HNS &LR;      08-10 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-WAGNER-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Wagner back on mound throwing heat
<TEXT>
<P>
   By ALAN TRUEX &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   With the ninth inning approaching _ his inning _ Billy Wagner
strolled to the bullpen Sunday to warm up. He didn't need much
warming, after the reception the Astrodome crowd gave him.
</P>
<P>
   Astros manager Larry Dierker had found the soft spot he sought _
an 11-2 lead _ to have his game-closing pitcher return from a
near-death experience that was quickly followed by the birth of his
first child.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker wanted the right time to plunge Wagner back into the
surreality of major-league baseball, where a 145-mph comet could
hit him in the head. And did.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a month ago that Wagner's left ear was struck by a
line drive off the bat of little-known Kelly Stinnett. He wasn't
seriously harmed, but it was a matter of inches _ like, 1{.
</P>
<P>
   It was such a dramatic, shocking scene _ Wagner dropping as if
shot in the temple, writhing on the ground _ the networks couldn't
show it enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I woke up in the hospital, that was the first thing I
saw. It didn't bother me to see a ball go off my head. It's just
something that happened. It's rare, but it happened. I'm not going
to make more out of it than it really is.''
</P>
<P>
   Far more important to him was the birth of William James Wagner,
which came as he was about to begin a short rehabilitation
assignment in Jackson, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I hadn't got hit in the head I wouldn't have seen my baby's
birth announced on ESPN. Sarah did a lot of things with him that I
wanted to do, like hold him. Since I got back, I haven't done
nothing but hold him.''
</P>
<P>
   So after he had a torn ear, a hospital stay, a birthday (July
25, his 27th), a son born and three shutout innings in Jackson,
Wagner finally would pitch again, against a major-league team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throwing in the bullpen, it was a little hard at times because
of the cheering. I was all over the place with my pitches. And then
I said to myself, `Who cares? Just throw it down the middle.'''
</P>
<P>
   With his sense of perspective intact, he sprinted to the
pitcher's mound in the middle of the stadium, buoyed by a standing
ovation from the 28,000-plus in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to do the same routine I always do. When I got out on
the mound I said the same prayer I always do. I thanked the Lord
for letting me have the opportunity to play in the game. A lot of
people were worried about me. I know the front office was a little
insecure about putting me in a situation where I had to get a
save.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take Wagner long to reassure everyone. The first of
the Philadelphia Phillies to face him was a muscular young catcher,
Bobby Estalella, who the night before had pumped Jose Lima and Doug
Henry fastballs into the outfield stands.
</P>
<P>
   Estalella went down swinging at Wagner's fifth straight
fastball. Jon Zuber doubled to left field on a pitch reported at 98
mph on the Dome scoreboard. Wagner recovered to retire pinch hitter
Ruben Amaro on a medium-deep fly ball to center field.
</P>
<P>
   When the heat reached 100 on a pitch to Doug Glanville, another
round of cheers swept through the Dome from the standing-again
crowd. Glanville flied out to right on a 1-2 pitch, game over.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Wagner tried to minimize his significance:
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a letter from a Little League pitcher who was hit by a
line drive and went into a coma. He wrote me and said he would be
back playing again in two weeks. As adults, we worry about
everything, and with something like that, we tend to get panicky.
But when I read that letter, it got a load off my shoulders. I
realized my accident wasn't nearly as serious as his. Now it's back
to business. I'm back throwing, doing what I'm supposed to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
