<HEADER>
A5530 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-JONES-BO     08-10 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-JONES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POSITIVE NEWS ON PATRIOTS ROOKIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ On a night when debates were raging whether
these Patriots looked more like a Rod Rust team or a Dick
MacPherson team _ no running, no blocking, no passing, no points,
and many a missed tackle by the second- and third-team defenses _
the only happy news for Patriots fans came in the locker room a
half hour after Sunday's game had mercifully ended.
</P>
<P>
   Tebucky Jones was smiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it happened, I thought it was my knee,'' said the rookie
defensive back, who went down 1:58 into the fourth quarter of a
28-0 exhibition loss to the Vikings with what appeared to be a
possibly serious leg injury. ``That's why I flipped sideways when I
was in the air, and when I landed I thought I might be hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Words failed Jones when he tried to describe that split second
when he was in the air and he felt pain in his left leg and then
his left foot. ``I don't know what I was thinking,'' he said. ``I
just laid down.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, the second of the Patriots' two first-round picks in the
draft, was on the punt coverage team when he collided with a
Vikings blocker and went flying through the air. After coming to
rest on the turf, he sat there for several minutes, being tended by
team doctors, until finally he was able to walk to the sideline,
albeit gingerly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to walk off on my own,'' said Jones, ``and when I came
to the sideline, sat down, and calmed down a bit, I tried to start
walking again on my own. And when I walked on my own, it seemed to
go away a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   The injury was termed a strained left foot, and the rookie said
there also was some pain in his ankle. ``I think it'll be OK,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones had been brought gradually into the game, playing only in
dime and nickel packages in the first quarter, but more and more as
the game wore on, often finding himself opposite the Vikings'
prized rookie receiver, Randy Moss. Jones was called for
interference on Moss on one play but did not allow Moss to catch
any balls on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I hear that hype (about Moss's skills), it only makes me
want to go out there and play more,'' said Jones. ``He put a couple
of shakes on me, but I was on him, though.'' Moss may be quick,
said Jones, ``but I'm quick, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Moss didn't do much talking to Jones ``and I didn't do talkin'
to him,'' said Jones. ``I just go out there and play. I don't need
to talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he would have liked to have had a chance to go
against Minnesota's top receiver and one of the NFL's best, Cris
Carter. ``But Carter was on the other side from me,'' said Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, said Jones after his second NFL experience, ``I feel
I'm getting better and better. I'm feeling more comfortable (at
cornerback), but there's a lot of running to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lopsided score, the Patriots' starting defense
played well. (With this offense, it may have to play more than
well.) But the defenders were disturbed by the team's overall
performance. Safety Lawyer Milloy said, ``We got our butts
whipped.'' Added defensive back Larry Whigham, ``No concern now,
because it's early, but if we're like this in a week or two, then
it's a whole lot of concern.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a sliver or two of bright light _ beyond Jones not
being seriously hurt. Tackle Bruce Armstrong said ``it felt good,''
after playing with a brace on his injured left leg, and rookie
defensive lineman Greg Spires had two sacks, including one on which
he chased down Minnesota backup quarterback Randall Cunningham from
clear across the field before bringing him down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a tough week at practice, so it felt good to feel my
legs back under me a bit again,'' said Spires, who showed off his
speed in his pass rush. On the chase down of Cunningham, he said,
``I saw it was a play-action and all of a sudden I was around the
tackle and when I looked up, Cunningham was about 10 yards from me.
So I went running and I kept running and we must have had good
coverage downfield for me to get a sack like that.''
</P>
<P>
   That play, said Spires, epitomizes his motto for playing
football: ``Just keep the motor running. I kept the motor running
and I was able to get Cunningham. Good things happen when I keep
running and hustle around. The play's not over till it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Two sacks or no two sacks, Spires said he would grade himself at
``B-minus'' for the game. ``I'm just trying to get comfortable
around here and play as hard as I can,'' said Spires, ``but it's
like starting all over again. But I'd give all the sacks back,
because I wish we had won the game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-98 0154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
