<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 01:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5531 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS     08-10 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS HAVEN'T HIT GROUND RUNNING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ When it comes to preseason, all opinions
are subject to change without notice, but in case you didn't notice
Sunday night the Patriots looked like a team that couldn't run to
the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Martin is long gone but not yet forgotten because in two
games the Patriots have run the ball like a team whose shoes were
designed by Al Capone. Cement brogans with laces seem in vogue
these days and people are beginning to notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy they have to worry about (replacing) isn't Jimmy
Hitchcock,'' said Jimmy Hitchcock, the former Patriot cornerback
who was traded to Minnesota last spring. ``I'm a passerby. It's
Curtis Martin. He's the one they have to worry about and it's
showing already. They got the draft picks for him but, hey, what
have they done yet?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, the first of them, No. 1 pick Robert Edwards carried six
times for 20 yards a week ago and no times for no yards Sunday
night because his oft-injured body was a no go because of a sore
groin. This is not necessarily a problem because this is the season
of sore groins and pulled hamstrings with training camp's drudgery
only about half finished. But when you have had a broken foot,
ankle problems, and a knee injury in college, you give people cause
to wonder about your fragility when you come into the NFL and are
limping less than a month into your rookie year.
</P>
<P>
   And so Sunday night you wondered.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Sedrick Shaw, The First Annual Bill Parcells
Replacement Pick of two years ago who was taken on the third round
out of Iowa. Sunday night he ran for an average of 1.6 yards a
carry. What that means is if there were seven downs instead of four
and the Patriots gave the ball to Sedrick Shaw on six plays, they
still would have had to punt on the seventh play.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Shaw didn't handle the ball until Martin was put in
traction as the playoffs approached. He then carried 10 times for
22 yards in the postseason, but those numbers have been hyped to
the point where one might conclude it was 122 yards on 10 carries.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean Shaw won't one day be the back who rushed for
4,156 yards at Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday night you wondered.
</P>
<P>
   This is not an attempt to be harsh. After all, it is still
early. But how could the Minnesota Vikings be playing their first
exhibition game of the summer and look four touchdowns better than
a team that was not only playing its second exhibition game of the
summer but had also promised to keep its offense out there ``until
they accomplished something''?
</P>
<P>
   Had head coach Pete Carroll stuck to his guns on that, the
offense would be playing as you're reading this but the Vikings
declined to stay around until Monday night. That being the case,
let's move along to this year's sixth-round choice, one Harold
Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   Missives from Smithfield have contended all summer that Shaw is
a little bit like Earl Campbell. Straight-ahead runner, they said.
Power personified, they said. Out of the Jerome Bettis mold, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   Well, who stole the kid's uniform Sunday night and wore it
against the Vikings?
</P>
<P>
   Harold Shaw averaged 1.7 yards per battering Sunday night while
he was out there, which admittedly was better than Sedrick but it
reminded no one of Earl Campbell. Not unless we're talking about
Earl's present condition, which people in Texas tell me would be
considered round now that he's a decade into retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Again, in the interest of fairness, let me point out that it is
still August and not football weather and the offense is still
adjusting and yada yada yada ... but let's get serious for a minute
if you can stand it. What you saw Sunday night when the Patriots
tried to run the ball was obvious. It was pathetic.
</P>
<P>
   You saw a line get no push and runners make no one miss. You saw
a running game that would have been overrated if it was called a
walking game. This is not good, even in mid-August, as people like
Hitchcock know all too well.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1996, the year we went to the Super Bowl, we went down and
beat Dallas, 31-7, (in preseason),'' Hitchcock recalled. ``We were
coming off the field and (Bill) Parcells turned to an assistant
coach and said, `That team's in trouble.'
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a parallel here. Maybe there's a touchdown difference
but I'm saying the Patriots are in the same situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Patriots fans were assured all spring and summer not to worry
about the absent Martin because computer experts in the employ of
Robert Kraft had done voluminous studies and system analysis on the
running back position and it was concluded your Aunt Minnie could
play it at least as well as Curtis Martin.
</P>
<P>
   One day he was one of the five best backs in football. Next day
_ which just happened to be the day after he signed with the hated
Jets _ he was as easy to replace as a bathroom plunger.
</P>
<P>
   You can always find a back, Kraft was told.
</P>
<P>
   It's the easiest position to fill, Kraft was told.
</P>
<P>
   Anybody with two legs can come in and play running back, Kraft
was told.
</P>
<P>
   Well, if that's the case why did it take the Patriots 30 years
to find a replacement for Jim Nance?
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night you wondered about that, too.
</P>
<P>
   Now this may all be just a midsummer night's panic. Robert
Edwards may get healthy by fall and run like the best back in
Georgia since Herschel Walker left. Or the Runners Shaw may soon
stop looking like George Bernard Shaw with a football and begin to
resemble ... well I can't think of a guy named Shaw who was a great
running back but maybe one of them will become the first.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there are still three exhibition games and a month of
practices left before the real McCoy against the Denver Broncos.
That's plenty of time to get running, isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   After all, you can always find a running back.
</P>
<P>
   It's the easiest position to fill.
</P>
<P>
   Anybody with two legs can do it.
</P>
<P>
   Can't they?
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, you began to wonder about that, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
