</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAVIA ON TOP OF WORLDS 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS _ Sitting atop the shoulders of a flag-draped supporter,
Yugoslavian guard Aleksandr Djordjevic kissed his jersey and waved
to his supporters, two of whom were holding aloft flares in the
delirious Yugoslavian cheering section.
</P>
<P>
   Earth has a new official men's basketball world champion, and it
is Yugoslavia, 64-62 conquerors of Russia in a game that gave new
meaning to the word ``passionate''.
</P>
<P>
   Take Duke-North Carolina, add centuries-old nationalistic
fervor, put great athletes on the floor, and you had the
championship game.
</P>
<P>
   Americans have no idea _ none _ about the nature of these
competitions. Five minutes after the game was over, the losing fans
were still singing their songs and cheering their side. It was an
extension of something that had begun 25 minutes before the game
even started, and which continued unabated throughout the tense
contest. Oh, and mix in the Greek fans, denied even a bronze, but
still the hosts, singing and chanting their stuff, and you had a
sensational climax to a tournament which, by the time of its
conclusion, had forgotten that the NBA even exists.
</P>
<P>
   So was the 1998 championship a success? If you're a Yugoslavian,
of course, you think it was a success. You did very well. If you're
the Greek organizers, you're extremely grateful your home team made
the medal round, thus ensuring enthusiastic capacity crowds for the
final three days of a tournament that was all-too-often
distinguished in the first week by the sorry sight of empty seats
for any game in which Greece was not a participant. In the end, the
absence of the NBA stars didn't affect the attendance as much as it
could have had the Greeks not remained in contention for a medal.
</P>
<P>
   The most unhappy man concerning the lack of American stars is,
as always, Borislav Stankovic, the Secretary General of FIBA, the
international basketball governing body. He was more responsible
for the formation of the original Dream Team than anybody, because
he believed the only way for the rest of the world to catch up to
the US in his beloved sport (he actually participated in the first
Worlds 48 years ago in Buenos Aires) was for them to breathe the
monster's fire, and he had the clout to get it done, in part due to
his relationship with key Americans such as David Stern and Dave
Gavitt.
</P>
<P>
   So while Yugoslavia can exult about being the current world
champions, Stankovic knows where the real power lies and he sees
his timetable being put on hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning, the US came to international competitions
with college and AAU players and they were able to win
everything,'' Stankovic said. ``Then, as time went on, they would
come with those players and they would lose, lose, lose. We brought
the NBA stars to Barcelona and they won by 40 points. But by
Atlanta there were more competitive games. I do not think the
difference will be so big in years to come. That's my opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   But the gap can only be closed by head-to-head competition.
Beating Rudy T's collection of CBA, European, and college players
was no big deal. The big story would have been if the US had
prevailed with such a team. And that brings FIBA folk to another
matter ...
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't understand why the quality of the tournament
should be judged just on one team,'' said Florian Wanninger, the
longtime head of FIBA press affairs. ``Everyone talked about the
absence of the NBA players, but no one questioned the absence of
Yugoslavian players. We felt a little unnerved.''
</P>
<P>
   It's true. Yugoslavia did well enough without Vlade Divac,
Predrag Danilovic, Zoran Savic, and Zarko Paspalj as it was. With
them, there would have been no question.
</P>
<P>
   Only someone more conversant with international basketball would
be able to critique adequately the quality of play as opposed to
other international tournaments, but let there be no question that
there are very good teams and players all over the globe. Even a
team such as South Korea, which went home winless, is an
entertaining, intelligent squad. Its center, Jang-Hoon Seo, is a
clever 6-foot-10-inch 24-year-old who must have had someone send
him some Kevin McHale tapes. He has a sneaky up-and-under move and
he handles himself very well around the basket in general. He would
enhance any number of Division 1 college teams.
</P>
<P>
   Senegal and Nigeria were loaded with American college players.
Lithuania, which peaked by beating the US, has a thoroughly likable
and skilled team. Spain, which has made little noise since picking
up the silver 14 years ago in Los Angeles, had a very competitive
team featuring forward Alberto Herreros.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina has a pair of quality big men in Marcelo Nicola and
the elegantly-named Fabricio Oberto, as well as a veteran guard
named Juan Espil, who attracted American attention as far back as
the 1992 Tournament of the Americas. The Argentines will not be
easy for any second-echelon American team to defeat when qualifying
time for Sydney rolls around in less than two years.
</P>
<P>
   There is much to be said for the actual game they play. Forty
minutes a game means that lengthy days of quadruple and sextuple
headers can roll by. But it's more than that. It's just basketball.
With the exception of Greece, a deliberate team, everyone else
looks to run. Fast breaks are a dying art in America, but they
weren't over here.
</P>
<P>
   There are fewer timeouts _ the final two minutes feel like two
minutes, not two months _ and there is no television intrusion. The
overall pace is better than ours. And in blessed contrast to the
wretched entertainment excess of the ever-bloated NBA, there are no
assaults on the senses. No dancing girls. No blaring music during
timeouts. No sound effects during the game. It's just basketball,
and that means basketball as it used to be and ought to be. The
only extras are spontaneous crowd noise. What a fascinating
concept, huh?
</P>
<P>
   What we definitely know is that only experienced American
professionals can win a tournament like this. You can't fully grasp
it until you see it, because seeing an isolated international in an
NBA uniform doesn't reveal what he's like on his national team,
with his friends, playing his rules for his purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``The international players perform so much better over here,''
maintains Lakers head coach and Team USA assistant Del Harris.
``They're playing their game in their surroundings. There's a
definite comfort level. Take a guy like (Australia's) Shane Heal.
He couldn't do anything when he played with the Timberwolves. But
in this game he's a great player.'' As proof, Heal lit up the US
for 31.
</P>
<P>
   And whatever the internationals are capable of, it will be on
full display here. ``You see a guy in his regular Spanish or
Italian League,'' says one American scout, ``and he might take a
night off. They don't take any nights off when they're playing for
their country.''
</P>
<P>
   The tournament is coming to Indianapolis in 2002, and this is
what you can expect: picture the NCAA tournament encapsulated into
nine days with international fans and flags and noisemakers. If
that sounds good, then perhaps you should check it out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
