<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-SPRINT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOMEZ BREAKS THROUGH 
</HEADLINE>
 PCS TOURNEY-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WELLESLEY, Mass. _ The first two sets of Sunday's Sprint PCS
final couldn't have been much closer, with only two service breaks
_ one each by Andres Gomez and Henri Leconte.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the first-to-10 tiebreaker to decide the championship,
that all changed. From the start, it seemed something was wrong
with Leconte, who has had three back operations. Gomez won the
first point when Leconte's forehand up the line went into the net.
Three Leconte double faults later, Gomez led, 5-1.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez won the longest match of the five-day event (2 hours 8
minutes), 7-5, 4-6, 10-3, and in so doing moved from sixth to
second on the Nuveen Tour, for players 35 and older. The win, worth
$40,000, was the 10th senior victory for Gomez, more than anyone
except Jimmy Connors, who defaulted in the semifinals with a foot
injury.
</P>
<P>
   Leconte, who defeated Gomez in four of five meetings on the
regular men's tour, earned $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez didn't know until the middle of the tiebreaker that there
was anything wrong with Leconte's back. ``I was just thinking about
my game,'' said Gomez, the 1990 French Open champion. ``I didn't
think about his game too much. It's more difficult to play someone
when you see he might not be moving that well. I didn't want to
push the ball whether he had a bad back, a good back, or any kind
of back.''
</P>
<P>
   Just after Gomez went in front, 6-1, when Leconte's backhand
crosscourt found the net, Leconte was on his back in the corner of
the court, trying to stretch out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have different exercises for my back and it worked, my back
popped back in,'' said Leconte. ``I have an old back. I'm 35 and my
back is 65. I just couldn't serve. On my toss ... well, I can't say
the word.''
</P>
<P>
   There were seven minibreaks in the tiebreaker, Gomez winning
five, the last when a Leconte forehand up the line went into the
net. That gave Gomez an 8-2 edge, but he was still worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like the 10-point tiebreaker, but the fans like it.
It's hard to enjoy,'' said Gomez. ``I've seen someone up, 9-2, and
he lost 10 straight points. It's a situation you're not used to. In
a seven-point tiebreak, you can be up, 5-1, and you pretty much
have the game in control, but here in a 10-point tiebreak, you're
up, 7-2, and you don't know what's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Gomez won the first set in the 12th game, getting to 30-40 on
Leconte's serve with a backhand crosser for the winner, followed by
a Leconte backhand mishit. In the first game of the second set, on
Gomez's serve, Leconte was up, 0-40, taking it on a backhand Gomez
popped into the net.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez has a history of playing well in Massachusetts. He won six
Longwood championships, three in singles and three in doubles. And
he won a senior singles title in 1995 at Mashpee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it here,'' Gomez said. ``I feel comfortable here and it
helps my game. Plus, you know your way around without asking for
directions.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting the winner's check makes you want to return.
</P>
<P>
   In the doubles final, John Fitzgerald and Shlomo Glickstein
defeated top seeds Hank Pfister and Tim Wilkison, 6-7 (4-7), 6-3,
11-9.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
