</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-KILROY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KILROY'S STORIES GO ON AND ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ It was a half-hour before Sunday night's
Patriots exhibition game and Bucko Kilroy, a consultant to the
Patriots and one of the most familiar faces at Foxboro Stadium,
already was in his seat. Ready for another season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bucko,'' Kilroy was asked, ``how many years in pro football
does this make for you?''
</P>
<P>
   Kilroy, 77, paused. Paused some more. And finally came back with
the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty-six years,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   Is there anyone still in pro football who has seen more seasons?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well ... I guess Wellington (Mara, the co-owner of the New
York Giants),'' replied Kilroy, the longtime Patriots executive.
``We came in the same year _ 1943.''
</P>
<P>
   And then came the stories, and then came the tales, and then
came the memories from a man who played both ways for the
Philadelphia Eagles (as did virtually all players) in the 1940s and
1950s, a man who coached, a man who was a general manager, a man
who has seen pro football grow from virtually nothing into
America's most dominant sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Otto Graham,'' Kilroy replied almost instantly, when asked who
was the best quarterback he had seen. ``He was the best but what
hurts Otto is that (Paul Brown, Graham's coach with the Cleveland
Browns) called all the plays for him, so that's always held against
Otto. But it shouldn't be because Otto was so good.''
</P>
<P>
   Which immediately led into another tale, Kilroy laughing his
familiar small laugh, saying, ``But I once picked off Otto twice in
one game, two interceptions. And you know why? Because I was the
guy calling the defensive signals _ none of that stuff about calls
coming from the coaches on the sidelines, I did the calls _ and I
put myself where I could pick off Otto's passes.''
</P>
<P>
   Which led into yet another tale because Kilroy's Philadelphia
Eagles were the best in the NFL in the late 1940s while Brown's
Cleveland Browns were kings of the All-American Football
Conference, and the teams met after the 1949 and 1950 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``They beat us (in 1950) in Cleveland but we didn't have our
best guy playing,'' recalled Kilroy. ``Steve Van Buren (the best
runner in the NFL in that era) was hurt and that really stopped
us.''
</P>
<P>
   In front of Kilroy as he talked was the program for Sunday
night's game between the Patriots and Vikings. On the cover were
pictures of this year's inductees into the Pro Football Hall of
Fame in Canton, Ohio, and Kilroy pointed to two of the pictures _
Tommy McDonald and Paul Krause _ and said, ``I drafted those guys,
both of them.''
</P>
<P>
   McDonald was a brilliant receiver for the Eagles whom Kilroy
drafted for Philadelphia in 1957, and Krause was a defensive back
for the Redskins from 1964 through 1967 _ when Kilroy called the
shots there _ and later moved on for 12 brilliant years with the
Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   Kilroy played on the offensive line for Philadelphia, and at
linebacker and on the line on defense, and, even to this day,
Kilroy's reputation as a dirty player is still alive. ``Aww,'' said
Kilroy, ``Ed Sprinkle (of the Chicago Bears) was the dirty guy. He
was really tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, of course, led into another tale when Look magazine
carried an article in the early 1950s, naming Kilroy as football's
dirtiest player, ``but I sued them and I won the case, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Kilroy looks at the pro football of the last generation, with
specialists upon specialists and mass substitutions by downs and
says, naturally, it was a far different sport when he played and
there were few substitutions. ``Players had to be tough, really
tough,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And the toughest of them all? His teammate with the Eagles,
linebacker Chuck Bednarik?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, Bednarik was tough, said Kilroy, ``but the really tough guy
was Hardy Brown of the 49ers. He was a small guy but he could just
explode off the line _ he was a defensive lineman _ and I remember
the way he would crouch down and just come up on people.''
</P>
<P>
   And tale after tale. Kilroy replied almost instantly when asked
who was the best passer he ever saw _ ``Sammy Baugh'' of the
Redskins of the early 1940s _ but he also threw in names such as
Sonny Jurgensen of the Redskins and Eagles in the 1950s and 1960s,
and Sid Luckman of the Bears of the '40s, and Norm Van Brocklin and
Bob Waterfield of the Rams of the 1940s and '50s.
</P>
<P>
   But the best quarterback? ``Otto Graham,'' he said again. ``The
guy still is probably one of the most productive passers in history
and what people forget is what such a great athlete he was. Otto
Graham could do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   And tales went on and on, Kilroy disputing the common belief
that Frankie Albert and the San Francisco 49ers of the 1940s were
the first to use the T-formation in pro football. ``You know who
was first? George Halas had it first with the Bears and we were
second with the `T' with the Eagles,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The tales went on and on. And Kilroy's words could not be taken
lightly. He has seen it all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-98 0206EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
