<DOCNO> NYT19980810.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5535 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS &LR;      08-10 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION DEFENSE HAS NO CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Revolution's mantra in recent weeks has been that
their situation could not get worse. But during a 6-1 defeat in
Columbus Saturday, they sank to another low.
</P>
<P>
   After 24 games, the Revolution have 19 points, their lowest
total in three seasons of Major League Soccer. With a quarter of
the regular season remaining, they are on a pace to earn 25 points,
which would be 8 less than in their inaugural season.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Revolution remain in playoff contention since all but
two teams in each conference qualify for postseason play. A
regulation-time victory at Tampa Friday would lift the Revolution
out of last place in the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   But the Revolution did not resemble a team with much winning
potential against Columbus. They seemed more like a team that is
fading fast, with few solutions to some serious problems,
especially on defense.
</P>
<P>
   They are hoping to make a trade and to add Jair (broken left
ankle) to the midfield by the Aug. 22 game against Los Angeles. It
might be too much to expect those moves to salvage a dismal season.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution's defense was especially ineffective against the
Crew, which were sparked by Andy Williams, a Jamaican midfielder
who studied business at the University of Rhode Island and hoped to
join the New England team. They now have surrendered 54 goals,
worst in the league and only two fewer than they gave up in '96.
</P>
<P>
   The Columbus game was the first this season in which the
Revolution completely collapsed. The Crew were playing well and had
the home-field advantage, but the Revolution simply lost their
poise. It was apparent early that New England was fighting an
uphill battle, but instead of being resourceful, the Revolution
self-destructed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were motivated, we knew it was an important game,''
midfielder/sweeper Edwin Gorter said. ``They scored a fantastic
goal, then two corners and it was 3-0 and the game was over. On
this field especially, Columbus is very good, and if they are ahead
by three goals it is hard for any team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were prepared for corners but these guys got some fantastic
headers. Those were strong goals, and after that the game was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a spanking, but maybe it was a spanking at the right
moment. Now we have to respond and we will do that Friday in Tampa
Bay. This was bad and we know it. Now we have two games left with
Tampa Bay and Miami and we have to win them. We are not happy about
this game. But it is better to lose once, 6-1, than to lose four
times, 2-0.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Revolution have now lost so many games in so many ways
that losing has become expected. This was a stigma that coach
Thomas Rongen had hoped to overcome, but his moves so far have
failed.
</P>
<P>
   With 89 points in 90 MLS matches, the Revolution have the worst
record among the league's original 10 teams. Rongen's position was
precarious before a 3-0 victory over San Jose Wednesday, but
general manager Brian O'Donovan remained encouraged by that win and
a second-half rally for a 3-1 win over Dallas July 18.
</P>
<P>
   But will O'Donovan be similarly discouraged by the Columbus
rout?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jamar Beasley is scheduled to join the Revolution after helping
the US defeat Trinidad and Tobago, 6-1,  &UR; yesterday &LR;  in
Port-of-Spain to qualify for the Under-20 World Cup, scheduled
April 3-24 in Nigeria.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
