   NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No 2470- August
10, 1998   We are offering the following articles for sale. Please
contact us for availability your country. Best regards, Karl
Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. DIGGING UP DIRT ON PRESIDENT CLINTON'S ENEMIES Terry Lenzner
once served a Watergate subpoena on Richard Nixon. Now, as head of
an elite group of private investigators, he is digging up dirt on
President Clinton's enemies - among them, Paula Jones. By David
Samuels. From The New York Times Magazine. 2,500 words. 2. RAYMOND
CARVER AND HIS (HYPERACTIVE) EDITOR Ten years after the death of
Raymond Carver, new disclosures about the influence of his editor,
Gordon Lish, are casting a strange light on some of the most
revered short stories in America's literary tradition. By D.T. Max.
From The New York Times Magazine. 3,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 3.
``DO THE NURSES DO THE SURGERY HERE?'' -- WOMEN IN
</P>
<P>
   THE OPERATING ROOM No area of medicine is as dominated by men as
surgery. Although half of medical students are now women, women
remain a rarity in operating rooms. Why are there so few women
surgeons? From Der Spiegel. 1,000 words. (English translation
available.)
_______________________________________________________________ 4.
'EVIDENCE' OF A PROMISING DIGITAL ARTIST In the web-based artwork
``Evidence : Meditations on Small Objects,'' Polish-born artist
Maya Drozdz is guilty - to great effect - of violating some of the
accepted precepts of how tales are told on the Internet. The
multimedia short story plays out in a pop-up window that covers
about a third of the monitor screen. Clicking on highlighted words
and images reveals additional information, and a narrative-like
chronology begins to take shape. ``Evidence'' departs in several
ways from the conventions of electronic storytelling on the Web. By
Matthew Mirapaul. From New York Times CyberTimes. 1,000 words. 5.
IT'S NO TIME TO FORSAKE DEMOCRACY IN AFRICA The ``new'' capitalist
and undemocratic regimes in Africa are not so new, not so stable.
Democracy and economic development must go hand in hand. By Joel D.
Barkan and David F. Gordon. From Foreign Affairs magazine. 1,500
words.
_______________________________________________________________
</P>
<P>
   6. WHAT'S DOING IN VIENNA Tips on events, sightseeing, hotels
and restaurants in Vienna. (The effects of the opening up of the
former Communist bloc can be subtly felt in the languages spoken in
the cafes and on the trams, and in glimpses of newly affluent
Russians who park money here.) By Jane Perlez. New York Times Way
To Go! 1,500 words + photos
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
RALPH REED IS HIS CROSS TO BEAR Randy Tate has been head of the
Christian Coalition in the United States for a year, but
conservatives still pine for his media-savvy predecessor, Ralph
Reed. Now Tate is finally getting attention for an issue Reed says
is a loser : homosexuality. By Melinda Henneberger. From The New
York Times Magazine. 2,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
FROM NATURE NEWS SERVICE (N/A France and Spain. Embargo 1800 GMT
Wednesday August 12)
</P>
<P>
   A. Satellite Climate Record In Error A record of cooling in the
lowest layer of the atmosphere seems to have more to do with
changes in the orbits of the satellites making the measurements,
than any real climatic effect. Once these changes are accounted
for, the trend turns from a cooling to a modest warming trend. This
conclusion is likely to be controversial. By Henry Gee. 1,200
words.
</P>
<P>
   B. Secret Life Of A Blood Clot Given that the majority of heart
attacks and strokes are triggered by platelet-dependent blood
clotting (thrombosis,) the discovery this week of a previously
unknown step in clot formation will be welcome news for researchers
and patients alike. By Helen Phillips. 800 words. 9. From THE NEW
YORK TIMES BOOK REVIEW A. The Enigma Of The Century : Whatever
anyone thinks about Hitler, someone else thinks a different thing.
Review of 'Explaining Hitler - The Search For The Origins Of His
Evil.' B. Get A Grip : Are hands the key to the evolution of human
intelligence? Review of 'The Hand - How Its Use Shapes The Brain,
Language, and Human Culture.'
</P>
