<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 09:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5765 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN12-CO     08-10 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Illogical air fares
 &HT;    (For release Aug. 12, 1998)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The absurdity of myriad airline fares cannot be more
graphic than in the rates at least one airline charges to fly to
Atlanta from two South Florida cities. Likely, similar situations
exist in other areas, on other airlines.
</P>
<P>
   A friend told me the other day that to fly round-trip from Miami
to Atlanta costs $600 more than it does to fly from Fort Lauderdale
to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Miami and Fort Lauderdale are about 25 miles apart.
</P>
<P>
   After telling the friend he must be smoking something funny, I
decided to call the airline, Delta _ just to be certain.
</P>
<P>
   To my great surprise, the friend was right.
</P>
<P>
   To fly from Miami to Atlanta on Oct. 1 and return on Oct. 3
would cost me $862.12, according to the reservations specialist at
Delta. But to fly from Fort Lauderdale to Atlanta on Oct. 1 and
return on Oct. 3 will cost only $246.82.
</P>
<P>
   The difference: $615.30, or enough to make a fall-season round
trip from the East Coast of the United States to many points in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why such a difference?'' I inquired of the Delta person.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because your trip from Miami didn't include a Saturday night
stay in Atlanta,'' she answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flight from Fort Lauderdale did not include Saturday
night, either,'' I responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's true,'' she said, ``but the Fort Lauderdale flight does
not require Saturday night; Miami does.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's see,'' I continued the exercise, ``Oct. 3 is a Saturday.
So if I stay over in an Atlanta hotel Saturday night and fly home
to Miami on Sunday, what's the fare?''
</P>
<P>
   ``$166.55.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Say that again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``$166.55.''
</P>
<P>
   The stay of one extra night in Atlanta would save me $695.57 in
air fare, she was telling me. I presume I could get a pretty good
room in Atlanta for that amount. And a pretty good dinner too. And
maybe a show. And some champagne. And a ticket to a Braves game.
</P>
<P>
   This was something I had to double-check, so I turned on my
computer and went to Delta Air Lines Skylinks Web Page. And there
it was: $862.12, round-trip, Miami to Atlanta, leaving 9:05 a.m.
Oct. 1, returning 9:40 a.m. Oct. 3.
</P>
<P>
   But the comparable flight from Fort Lauderdale was not $246.82,
as the phone representative told me. It was only $146.75. That made
it $715.37 less to hop up the road a bit and fly from Fort
Lauderdale!
</P>
<P>
   Some starched shirt at Delta, I am certain, would have an
explanation for this vast difference but it would be
incomprehensible to me, and to any other traveler.
</P>
<P>
   Presently, Atlanta is not on my destination list, but were it,
and I was living in Miami, as I do, I suppose I would either decide
to spend a Saturday night in Atlanta, even though I didn't have any
other reason to, or hire a stretch limousine, make certain it was
stocked with Diet Dr Pepper and Cheez Doodles and wend my way up
Interstate 95 the short distance to Fort Lauderdale International
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   And if I looked real hard, I'll bet I could find someone else,
coming down the road from Fort Lauderdale to Miami to board some
other flight that was equally unequally priced to a different
destination.
</P>
<P>
   The free market zips past in both directions.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
