<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Clinton's approval ratings rise
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Members of independent counsel Kenneth Starr's
grand jury now have heard sworn testimony from ``that woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Depending on how events unfold, Monica Lewinsky's grand jury
testimony could lead to President Clinton's removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   While it's Clinton who could be charged with various felonies,
Americans think Starr is a bum, Lewinsky is a hussy and Clinton
hung the moon.
</P>
<P>
   When the Lewinsky scandal broke in January with allegations that
Clinton committed criminal perjury, obstruction of justice,
subornation of witnesses and trashy behavior, his approval ratings
went up.
</P>
<P>
   When Lewinsky agreed to testify with a grant of immunity for any
crimes she may have committed with Clinton, the president's
approval ratings went up again.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the possibility that DNA evidence could show that
Clinton committed criminal perjury, an ABC News poll just before
Lewinsky's grand jury appearance showed Clinton's approval ratings
continue to rise.
</P>
<P>
   Americans in those polls must believe that Clinton is being
hounded for nothing more than his charming inability to say no to a
sweet young thing. Besides, what's wrong with a few lies about a
bit of hanky panky between consenting adults?
</P>
<P>
   That's the moral view of the Lewinsky sexcapade, which
unfortunately makes the French look like sexual prudes compared to
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   It has to be the sex that prevents Americans from seeing the
Lewinsky affair as a serious matter of law.
</P>
<P>
   America's revolution established a new nation based on the rule
of law with the explicit provision that no citizen is above the
law. All schoolchildren should know this basic American principle.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton especially should have no trouble understanding this
principle. After all, he's a lawyer and a former law professor who
placed his hand on the Bible and swore a solemn oath to preserve,
protect and defend the Constitution and to see that the laws are
``faithfully executed.''
</P>
<P>
   In sworn testimony in the the Paula Jones lawsuit, Clinton
admitted that he broke his wedding vows and lied to the American
people. The Starr grand jurors don't care about that.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jurors will care, however, if they believe Clinton
violated his solemn oath to faithfully execute the laws of the
United States by committing criminal perjury, encouraging others to
commit perjury or attempting to obstruct justice. All Americans
should care.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton supporters buy the White House spin that all the
president's troubles are the fault of an ``out-of-control''
independent prosecutor who hasn't produced diddly squat after
spending years and millions of dollars. They should recall that
Clinton called for the appointment of an independent counsel to
investigate Whitewater allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has attempted to block Starr's investigation every step
of the way. White House operatives have demonized Starr as though
the outcome of the investigation can be controlled by popularity
polls.
</P>
<P>
   If Starr were out of control, Attorney General Janet Reno could
fire him. That's the law. Under the independent counsel law, all
Reno needs to fire Starr is ``good cause.''
</P>
<P>
   The Whitewater investigation has been the opposite of ``out of
control.'' It has been painstaking, plodding and mind-numbing, but
not out of control.
</P>
<P>
   Whitewater also has not been a dry hole. Starr's probe has
produced 12 guilty pleas and three convictions in trials.
</P>
<P>
   If Starr's final report to Congress includes credible evidence
that Clinton willfully broke the law, surely Clinton's approval
ratings will drop. If not, America's rule of law is in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald. E-mail: RNeth(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
