<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Attacks on Reno are political strategy
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's one real issue and a lot of partisan fog in the reckless
decision of the House Government Reform and Oversight Committee to
cite Attorney General Janet Reno for contempt of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The real issue is whether Reno should appoint another special
counsel, a la Kenneth Starr, this time to investigate Democratic
and Clinton-campaign fund-raising in the last election. It was in
hopes of maneuvering the attorney general into a corner that the
committee ordered Reno to turn over memos from two key subordinates
arguing for such an appointment.
</P>
<P>
   The memos apparently do strengthen the case for an independent
counsel _ but strengthening is not the same as cinching and others
in the Justice Department argue the evidence doesn't, or doesn't
yet, animate the independent counsel law. Reno is right to withhold
the memos in any event.
</P>
<P>
   The authors themselves _FBI Director Louis Freeh and Charles
LaBella, who recently left Justice after heading its
campaign-finance task force _ urged the committee not to demand
their memos. The inevitable leaks _ and Chairman Dan Burton's
committee leaks like a geyser _ would compromise current Justice
Department investigations and vastly complicate the job of any
independent counsel, should Reno decide for one.
</P>
<P>
   Why would a committee that says it wants a stronger
investigation undermine the very investigation it says it wants?
Because the GOP majority is more interested in siccing another
go-for-broke prosecutor on the Clinton administration than in any
product a counsel might deliver.
</P>
<P>
   The committee vote was along party lines, and small wonder. The
committee's own investigation has been nakedly partisan, in the
manner of its chairman's manifest zealotry.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are beginning to fear their long war on President
Clinton just might force him out after all, putting Al Gore in
place to seek the presidency in 2000 as the incumbent. The public
would kick if a new independent counsel were set on Gore right
after he was sworn in, but if a counsel was already in place, Gore
could be molested through the election without public backlash.
</P>
<P>
   Even if that extruded scenario doesn't play out, the appointment
of an independent counsel would leave the Justice Department itself
investigating only GOP financial machinations, allowing Republicans
to charge partisanship and discount any findings as biased and
retaliatory.
</P>
<P>
   And at a minimum, the appointment would make potential
Democratic contributors even more skittish than they already have
been made by open-ended investigation. Despite Clinton's frequent
and sometimes unseemly fund-raising, Republicans at last count were
out-drawing Democrats $147 million to $84 million.
</P>
<P>
   The '96 elections resorted to funding extremes, some illegal and
more appallingly lawful. The larger fault rests with Democrats,
even though they were the lesser spenders, but the abuses were
bipartisan. This latest ploy by Burton's committee is one more step
in trivializing what ought to be a national scandal by reducing the
response to partisan gamesmanship.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
