(Repeating for all needing. Originally file on Saturday, August The Week in Review  
 (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Legislators Vote to Accuse Reno of Contempt
</P>
<P>
   No top government official has ever been prosecuted for contempt
of Congress. But that did not stop the House Committee on
Government Reform and Oversight from voting along party lines last
week to charge Attorney General Janet Reno with the crime. The
committee's complaint is that Reno refuses to turn over memorandums
from the Justice Department's top investigators, including FBI
Director Louis Freeh, holding that the law requires her to ask for
an independent counsel to investigate Democratic campaign finance
abuses in the last election.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Reno has adamantly refused to seek an outside
prosecutor. But even before the committee voted, there were
indications that she was reconsidering the question.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM
</P>
<P>
   The No. 1 Gun Dealer
</P>
<P>
   The United States has kept its title as the world's biggest arms
merchant, but Russia and France are poised to overtake it, the
Congressional Research Service reported.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has led the world arms trade for seven
straight years. It sold $15.2 billion worth of weapons to other
nations last year, a 44 percent share of the shrinking global arms
market. That shrinkage has a number of causes: the end of the Cold
War, the end of a splurge of weapons purchases after the 1991
Persian Gulf war, the economic crisis in Asia and the long slump in
crude oil prices, which has helped slow arms purchases by Saudi
Arabia and other Arab nations.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the world remains awash in arms. Developing nations
alone have bought $172 billion worth in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   _ By TIM WEINER
</P>
<P>
   Trauma at 2 Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   Past was all-too-palpable prologue in last week's turmoil at The
Boston Globe and The Miami Herald.
</P>
<P>
   At The Globe, where wounds caused by the revelation of
fabrication by a prized columnist were still healing, a second
prominent columnist found himself in the crosshairs. Mike Barnicle
came under fire after The Boston Herald documented that 10 items in
his column titled ``I was just thinking,'' paralleled jokes in
comedian George Carlin's book, ``Brain Droppings.''
</P>
<P>
   That led his editors to suspend him. But when Barnicle, who said
he had not read the book, turned up on a video clip recommending it
as summer reading, Globe editor Matthew Storin asked him to resign.
He declined. Friday, to resolve the impasse, Barnicle met with the
Globe's publisher, Benjamin Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, Miami Herald publisher David Lawrence told
an emotional crowd in the newspaper's cafeteria that he was
resigning. The announcement came after the staff had received memos
alluding to possible cutbacks. The Herald had a round of cuts three
years ago; some employees feared that the new publisher, Alberto
Ibarguen, whose experience was gained on the business side of
newspapers, would preside over more cuts.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Ibarguen spoke of ``streamlining,'' not
layoffs. The question, he said, was, ``How can we grow with this
community _ how do we take a mature and traditional institution and
fit an untraditional and evolving area?''
</P>
<P>
   _ By FELICITY BARRINGER
</P>
<P>
   Watching Kosovo Simmer
</P>
<P>
   Washington and NATO, embarrassed by a brutal Serb campaign
against ethnic Albanians in the southern Serbian province of
Kosovo, warned Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic yet again that
he risks military retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   The warning came in a message to Milosevic from Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright, who is seeking rapid negotiation between
the Serbs and Kosovar representatives.
</P>
<P>
   To make this latest threat more credible, NATO drafted
operational plans for limited air strikes against Serb forces that
could be more easily authorized by the alliance. And it announced
military exercises next week in Albania and next month in
Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials recognize Milosevic's right to put down a
rebellion, but say they are horrified by his tactics, which include
the razing of villages and the displacement of at least 10 percent
of the population.
</P>
<P>
   _ By STEVEN ERLANGER
</P>
<P>
   A Slap for Arafat
</P>
<P>
   Yasser Arafat turned 70 last week, but along with a celebration
the Palestinian leader received a rebuke to his governance.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat had been under pressure since last year from Palestinian
lawmakers to root out corruption and mismanagement from within his
Palestinian Authority. But the response that he finally unveiled
was so widely seen as inadequate that two ministers _ including
Hannan Ashrawi, an internationally prominent figure _ quit in
protest.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat's standing had already been diminished among Palestinians
by the lack of progress toward a broader peace with Israel. He has
always been able to rally support by blaming Israel for the
faltering peace, and he still commands great respect. But
increasingly now, Palestinians have felt freer to conclude that in
his aversion to addressing problems of efficient administration at
home, he is leaving himself no one to blame but Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DOUGLAS JEHL
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A Case of Switched Identity
</P>
<P>
   Paula Johnson of Ruckersville, Va., had been raising little
Callie Marie for three years when, in order to induce the presumed
father to pay child support, she had a paternity test done. The
test showed that Callie wasn't his child _ and another test showed
Ms. Johnson wasn't the mother.
</P>
<P>
   The little girl had been switched at birth, with another at the
University of Medical Center in Charlottesville. Callie was the
daughter of a couple in Buena Vista, Va., Kevin Chittum and Tamara
Whitney Rogers, and Rebecca, the child they were raising, had been
born to Ms. Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Monday it was discovered that Carrie's biological
parents had died in a Fourth of July car wreck. Ms. Johnson and the
Chittum and Rogers clans are now grappling with how the girls
should be raised. They are talking to lawyers, but none is named
Solomon.
</P>
<P>
   _ By PETER T. KILBORN
</P>
<P>
   A Swimmer Founders
</P>
<P>
   At the Summer Olympics in Atlanta two years ago, Michelle Smith
de Bruin of Ireland won three gold medals, a feat that surprised
many because her performance times had improved dramatically late
in her career.
</P>
<P>
   Now the International Swimming Federation has banned her from
competition for four years after finding that she tampered with a
drug test by spiking her urine sample with alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   The swimmer, now 28, denied wrongdoing, said she would appeal
the ban, and would sue the federation in a fight to clear her name.
She passed her drug tests in Atlanta; the test she was said to have
manipulated was conducted while out of competition this year.
</P>
<P>
   Doubt on Crime Statistics
</P>
<P>
   Crime has been dropping dramatically for the past six years, to
the lowest level since the 1960s, when the late-20th-century crime
wave exploded in the United States. But now charges are being
raised that police commanders in several cities have falsified
their crime statistics to keep up with the nationwide decline, and
this is raising concern that some crime data may be skewed.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few months, senior police officials have been
demoted or forced to resign because some crime statistics were
manipulated in New York, Philadelphia, Atlanta and Boca Raton, Fla.
Typically, felonies like burglary were downgraded to less serious
crimes like trespassing or vandalism.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these incidents, criminologists say the general downward
trend in crime is undoubtedly true, since it has shown up not only
in police reports but also in a Justice Department survey of
victims of crimes nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   _ By FOX BUTTERFIELD
</P>
<P>
   Indian Rights, Canadian Style &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 years after they made their first land claim, the
Nisga'a people of British Columbia signed a treaty that gives them
title to an area more than half the size of Rhode Island, along
with control over almost everything that happens there.
</P>
<P>
   But a treaty is only a first step to self-sufficiency, as
American Indian tribes who gathered in Washington last week for a
conference on development know.
</P>
<P>
   If the Nisga'a treaty is ratified by the provincial and federal
parliaments, traditional federal support will be cut. The 5,500
Nisga'a will then have to collect their own taxes and figure out
how to provide services and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   This is a problem that some American tribes have solved by
turning to gambling casinos. But Canada's Nisga'a say they have
other plans: to rely on traditional economic enterprises like
timber and fishing.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ANTHONY DePALMA
</P>
<P>
   Shhh. It Was a Secret. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The British government does not like it when its spies talk
about their jobs. In fact, under the Official Secrets Act, workers
at the security services are forbidden to disclose anything to
anyone about any aspect of their work.
</P>
<P>
   That was why it took 25 years for Sir John Masterman to get
permission in 1972 to publish ``The Double-Cross System,'' about
how Britain subverted Germany's World War II spies _ and then only
after Yale University Press in America forced the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Something even more peculiar happened in the ``Spycatcher'' case
in the 1980s, when a book disclosing British spy secrets was
published in the United States. That time, British newspapers were
forbidden to reveal what the book said, but Britons smuggled it in
and sold it by the side of the road.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, history seemed to repeat itself when David Shayler, a
former officer at the Libya desk of Britain's domestic security
service, was arrested after threatening to disclose embarrassing
agency secrets on the Internet. Newspapers that were poised to
publish his allegations found themselves slapped with far-reaching
injunctions in the name of national security.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on Thursday, the newspaper The Guardian reprinted an
article by The New York Times that described the British news
media's inability to cover Shayler's story. It included details of
Shayler's allegation that Britain's foreign intelligence service
botched an assassination attempt against Moammar Gadhafi in 1996 _
details subject to the injunction.
</P>
<P>
   The British government didn't prosecute The Guardian. But it
reissued its warnings to reporters not to repeat anything else
Shayler had told them.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SARAH LYALL
</P>
