<HEADLINE>
VANESSA WILLIAMS DANCES UP A STORM 
</HEADLINE>
  Includes a color slide of Vanessa Williams in a scene from ``Dance
With Me.'' 
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 &HT;     For release Aug. 10 and thereafter 
 &HT;     By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 &HT;    World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    The ground has always rumbled at a certain airplane hangar
outside of Los Angeles. But on the set of ``Dance With Me,'' the
place is set to rumba.
 &HT;    Vanessa Williams, her eyes wide, stands in the corner of what
has been transformed into a giant ballroom set. She gives the come
hither look to a hot Latin pop star who only goes by one name. He
is Chayanne, a man who is about to teach the former Miss America
that salsa is much more than a dip.
 &HT;    There will be a lot of dipping. And kissing. And hips that seem
to fit together like Leggos.
 &HT;    As sexy Spanish music plays, Chayanne approaches Williams and
begins his move. He doesn't move his mouth. Words are not
necessary. His look says it all.
 &HT;    His arm snakes around her waist. Hips swaying, her blue
high-slit dress gives the camera a leg shot. Williams doesn't
notice because her arms are around his neck. Feet pivot. Hips
grind. He grabs her shoulder. He drapes a hand around her front.
 &HT;    But the moment is short lived. Suddenly, he dips her. At almost
cement level, her head pops up and he kisses her on the lips.
 &HT;    The feeling here is hot. That's the point of ``Dance With Me,''
which opens Aug. 21. It's a love story between a competitive
ballroom dancer (Williams) and a Cuban emigre (Chayanne). It's
directed by Randa Haines, who directed ``Children of a Lesser God''
(1986) with William Hurt and Marlee Matlin.
 &HT;    Haines was introduced to the film's screenwriter and
choreographer Daryl Matthews almost a decade ago at a Cuban dance
club. ``I was determined to make a film that really showed people
how to dance,'' Haines says.
 &HT;    You won't hear Williams complaining about shaking her tail in
the movie. ``I've studied dance my entire life,'' Williams says.
``This movie was a dream come true for a little girl who used to
run around her room pretending that she was part of a chorus
line.''
 &HT;    Williams, 35, never experienced the thrill of Latin dancing. So,
before cameras rolled, Williams threw herself into classes to learn
the rumba, samba and cha-cha. ``I sound like I could open my own
Arthur Murrays,'' she groans. ``I also learned how to fox trot and
swing. On some nights, I would go home swearing I couldn't walk let
alone dance again.''
 &HT;    Then again, Williams started filming ``Dance With Me'' only a
few weeks after wrapping last fall's ``Soul Food.''
 &HT;    ``Please, on `Soul Food,' I was taking home huge peach pies with
me. I just want to say that me alone on location in a hotel room
with an entire pie is not a pretty thing.'' For her art, she had to
eat heaping platters of fried chicken, yams and collard greens, for
three months straight.
 &HT;    ``Frankly, I was delighted to get the part in `Dance With Me'
for a very selfish reason,'' Williams says. ``I gained a few pounds
on `Soul Food,' and I learned that Cuban dancing is better than
aerobics for burning calories.''
 &HT;    She didn't feel self-conscious in front of Chayanne, a man so
handsome he could lead the Hollywood Hunk parade. With over 4
million in Latin America record sales, ``Dance With Me'' marks the
singer-actor's American movie debut.
 &HT;    ``I was really nervous,'' he says, ``but Vanessa put me at ease
every single day. She was always there to answer my questions.''
 &HT;    These days it's Williams who is being questioned about the
dancing duo. Oprah asked her if working with Chayanne was like
getting a megadose of Viagra. ``He's so sexy,'' she says. ``I don't
think any Viagra is needed.''
 &HT;    No slouch herself in that department, Williams seems the most
secure she has ever been.
 &HT;    Williams is a pro at facing tough problems. As the first black
Miss America, she endured hate mail from white supremacists and
from blacks claiming that she was too white.
 &HT;    Williams will forever live in infamy as having been forced to
resign and turn in her crown in 1984. That happened after Penthouse
printed nude photos of her taken several years earlier.
 &HT;    ``I was 21 years old when I started seeing my face on the news
every night and these horrible stories printed about me,'' she
says. ``Now I look back, and I can't believe I got through what was
the worst time in my life. I think I was in shock and maybe that
helped. I just took it day-by-day.''
 &HT;    Williams could write a book about turning a scandal to your
advantage. Her first move was all but vanishing from the public
eye. She skipped apologies and dodged interview requests. Williams
wasn't hiding out. ``I went back to work. It was all that I could
do.''
 &HT;    During that period, she recorded her first solo album. ``The
Right Stuff,'' released in 1988, sold 500,000 copies. To critics
who cried fluke, she delivered a second hit. ``My mentality is that
I would show them,'' she says.
 &HT;    Showing them included a stint on Broadway where Williams
received rave reviews in ``Kiss of the Spider Woman'' (1995). She
followed that in the film ``The Pick-Up Artist'' (1987).
 &HT;    Later, she was hired by Disney to sing the Oscar winning song
``Colors of the Wind'' for its animated movie ``Pocohontas''
(1996). Williams portrayed a woman on the lam with Arnold
Schwarzenegger in ``Eraser'' (1996), a gangster moll in ``Hoodlum''
(1997) and starred in several TV mini series including ``The
Odyssey'' and ``Bye, Bye Birdie'' (both 1997).
 &HT;    ``As a kid, I always wanted to do it all,'' she says. ``I
thought the perfect job was something where I could sing and dance
and act.''
 &HT;    It isn't easy to have those ambitions when you are a young girl
growing up in Millwood, N.Y., a New York suburb. Williams
discovered the arts because her parents are accomplished music
teachers. ``I think in the back of my mind as a kid was the plan to
be a dancer in a big Broadway show.''
 &HT;    She didn't dream of her name in lights. ``I was never the
show-offy type of child who practiced an Oscar speech in front of a
mirror,'' Williams says. ``I was content to just be a tiny part of
the background if I got to sing and dance.''
 &HT;    Her career began quicker than expected. She won a theater
scholarship to Syracuse University, but on her first day there she
learned the money was gone. Not giving up, she looked for ways to
make money.
 &HT;    Although her heart wasn't in it, she decided that beauty
pageants might be a solution. ``I can't even tell you how surprised
I was when I kept winning. I never thought of myself as the type,''
Williams says.
 &HT;    A way to earn school money nearly wrecked her life, but Williams
thanks her mother for giving her a tough backbone. ``She drilled
something into me as a little girl. She would say, `Vanessa, as a
black woman, you will always have to do better than anyone else
just to be considered equal.'
 &HT;    ``I always knew that I would have to work and work harder than
anyone else to get a shot. That sort of philosophy really paid off
in Hollywood.''
 &HT;    There have been disappointments. Williams is divorced from her
husband of 10 years, Ramon Hervey, her mentor and manager after the
scandal. These days, she lives quietly.
 &HT;    ``I'm with someone special,'' she says, insisting that is all
she will say about her love life. She is more apt to gush about her
children, Melanie, 11, Jillian, 9 and Devin, 5. ``I look at them
and I see the future. Having children is the biggest accomplishment
of my life, and the best job is being a mother.''
 &HT;    Just because she's a mom doesn't mean she is home baking cookies
every night. While filming ``Dance With Me,'' she was shaking with
Chayanne.
 &HT;    ``It was a tough job, but someone had to do it,'' Williams says,
adding that when he would shimmy next to her, ``My pulse went up.
Way, way up.''
 &HT;    For his part, Chayanne insists, ``Vanessa makes me
hyperventilate.'' He rattles off a list of her attributes and ends
with past the highest compliment.
 &HT;    ``She even smells great sweating.''
 c.1998 Cindy Pearlman  
