<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALAN-ARKIN-IN-SLUMS-OF-BEVERLY-HILLS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALAN ARKIN'S A MAN FOR ALL SEASONS 
</HEADLINE>
  Includes a color slide of Alan Arkin in a scene from ``Slums of
Beverly Hills.'' 
 &HT;     For release Aug. 10 and thereafter 
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 &HT;     By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Alan Arkin was never one to be the Bruce Willis or Steve McQueen
of his day. Not that there's anything wrong with that.
 &HT;    In fact, the veteran actor is just fine with that. Versatility
and longevity are his forte.
 &HT;    ``What do I do for a living?'' asks Arkin, the noted stage and
screen actor, but also more than a dabbler in directing, singing,
playing guitar, and writing novels, stage pieces and children's
songs.
 &HT;    ``Ninety-five percent of my income comes from acting, so I'd
have to call myself an actor.''
 &HT;    Arkin, 64, perched comfortably on a couch at the Rihga Royal
Hotel in Manhattan, softens his well-tanned poker face with a
whimsical smile.
 &HT;    ``In a perfect world, 95 percent of my income would come from a
trust fund,'' he says. ``I don't know if I'd like to make the same
money doing one of the other things I do.
 &HT;    ``I like acting, but I also like that most of my life is a
surprise to me. I don't know from day to day if I'll be acting or
directing, or if an idea for writing something will come to me.
 &HT;    ``I love that I don't decide anything. The only thing I ever
decided to do was act _ when I was 5 _ and everything else just
happened.''
 &HT;    The latest things to just happen are the film ``Slums of Beverly
Hills'' and the off-Broadway play ``Power Plays.'' ``Slums'' begins
a slow roll-out into theaters Aug. 21, while ``Plays'' is currently
running.
 &HT;    A semi autobiographical comedy-drama written and directed by
first-timer Tamara Jenkins, ``Slums'' casts Arkin as Murray,
patriarch of the Abramowitz family.
 &HT;    A loving, if ever-bickering group, the Abramowitzes _ divorced,
financially struggling dad Murray, on-the-cusp-of-womanhood
daughter Vivian (Natasha Lyonne), sons Ben (David Krumholtz) and
Rickey (Eli Marienthal) and offbeat cousin Rita (Marisa Tomei) _
wander from low-rent hotel to hotel in 1970s Beverly Hills, hoping
for better days and clinging desperately to their dignity and zip
code.
 &HT;    ``I like Murray because he's a complicated man, a guy who's
trying to do good at great cost to himself,'' Arkin says. ``He's
one of these guys who tries to maintain a vision of himself as he'd
like to be.
 &HT;    ``He can't stop thinking of himself as a high-roller and a
businessman to be reckoned with, which he's not anymore and never
really was.
 &HT;    Tamara based Murray on her own father, but she was very flexible
and not overattached to the idea of making me make Murray her
father on screen.''
 &HT;    As the cast's most experienced actor, Arkin often found himself
surrounded by his co-stars. They sought advice, either about their
roles or acting in general, or wanted to pick Arkin's brain about
his experiences in Hollywood.
 &HT;    ``I guess I was the father figure on the set,'' he says,
laughing. ``But I didn't look at it that way.
 &HT;    ``To me, they were all my peers. Natasha is sensational, and
everyone else was there because Tamara believed in them and thought
they were right for their (respective) roles.
 &HT;    ``Everybody worked well together and got on very well. It was
magic when Carl Reiner and Rita Moreno (as Murray's rich brother
and his wife) came in, because all we did was crack up and tell
very old stories, and I think everyone enjoyed that ... except
Tamara, who couldn't get a word in edgewise.''
 &HT;    Reiner worked with Arkin on Arkin's Broadway and film debuts,
``Enter Laughing'' and ``The Russians Are Coming, The Russians Are
Coming'' (1966). Arkin and Moreno shared the screen in ``Popi''
(1969).
 &HT;    It was old times for Arkin on another level, too.
 &HT;    ``We shot a couple of scenes five blocks from where I grew up as
a kid, in Highland Park, Los Angeles,'' he says, relishing the
memory. ``Those were the formative days when I was desperate to act
and never dreamed anything would happen for me.
 &HT;    ``While we were shooting these scenes for `Slums,' I could
constantly look up at the hill where I lived and I could bridge my
life.
 &HT;    ``It was as if I were saying hello to somebody from 40 years
ago. If somebody told that kid that he'd turn into me now, I'd be
surprised and happy.
 &HT;    ``My life has taken a lot of turns I never expected,'' Arkin
says, ``but I guess that's true of everyone.''
 &HT;    Not everyone, though, pursued acting by age 12. Not everyone can
lay claim to serving as an original member of Chicago's famed
Second City theatrical revue.
 &HT;    Not everyone counts among their credits such films as ``Wait
Until Dark'' (1967), ``Little Murders'' (1971, which he directed),
``The In-laws'' (1979), ``Glengarry Glen Ross'' (1992), such TV
movies as ``The Defection of Simas Kudirka'' (1978) and
``Cooperstown'' (1993), and innumerable plays, many of which he
directed.
 &HT;    ``I'll give you that,'' Arkin says as modestly as possible. ``I
felt like I was born during my Second City days.
 &HT;    ``You get 50 years of training in a year, and in one night you
were forced to play 30 or 40 different characters. Audiences
recognized that you'd fail 40 percent of the time and didn't mind
because that was a part of the experience.
 &HT;    ``We've reached a dangerous state in the U.S. now and that's
that you're not allowed to fail,'' he says. ``At Second City, you
were not only allowed to fail, you expected to fail.
 &HT;    ``That gave everyone an enormous opportunity for
experimentation. We were our own writers and directors, and we did
workshops and performances, which meant we were working all the
time.''
 &HT;    Versatility became Arkin's calling card, and that remains the
case. Is he a dramatic actor adept at comedy? Or a comedian who can
handle drama?
 &HT;    ``I don't think in those terms,'' he says instantly. ``I try to
fulfill whatever the part is that I'm given.
 &HT;    ``If people think of me as a jack-of-all-trades, it means I get
to do a little of everything. Every actor should want that.
 &HT;    ``I'd be bored doing one kind of role all my life. These days,
I'm doing big films and little films, serious parts and lighter
parts, plays and whatever else I want.
 &HT;    ``I used to be obsessive about acting, to the point that it was
crucial that I work. These days, I actually enjoy it more than ever
because I'm not as concerned about there being as much at stake for
me.''
 &HT;    Arkin will next be seen opposite Robin Williams in ``Jacob the
Liar,'' a film set in a Jewish ghetto during the Holocaust, but he
plans to take a two-month rest once ``Power Plays'' ends this
summer.
 &HT;    The actor, separated from wife Barbara Dana, hopes to relax at
home in Connecticut, visit his three sons (Adam of ``Chicago
Hope,'' ``Power Plays'' co-star Anthony and Matthew), and indulge
in his passion for photography.
 &HT;    ``After that, my phone will hopefully ring with someone asking
me to be in something,'' Arkin says. ``If not, I'll create
something for myself.''
 &HT;    So what, then, if Arkin never emerged as the McQueen or Willis
of his day?
 &HT;    He's doing just fine, thank you very much.
 &HT;    ``I have no complaints. I don't think I could do what Willis
does or what McQueen did, and I'm not sure they could do what I
do,'' he says. ``To be honest, I don't know that I'd want to do
what they do and I'm really not so sure they'd want to do what I
do.''
 c.1998 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
