<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 10:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5910 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RETURN-OF-THE-RAT-PAC     08-10 1578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETURN-OF-THE-RAT-PACK-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOOK BACK AT THE RAT PACK IN AN HBO MOVIE 
</HEADLINE>
  Includes a color slide of the actors playing the Rat Pack in a
scene from ``The Rat Pack.'' 
 &HT;     For release Aug. 10 and thereafter 
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 &HT;     By JEAN OPPENHEIMER  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    They were the essence of cool, smoking, drinking martinis,
carousing, busting up clubs, sleeping with any women they wanted.
 &HT;    They were the Rat Pack _ Frank Sinatra, Dean Martin, Sammy Davis
Jr., Peter Lawford and Joey Bishop _ and they defined the term
``hip'' from the late 1950s to the early 1960s. ``They were the
rock stars of that time,'' says Don Cheadle, who portrays Davis in
``The Rat Pack.''
 &HT;    An original HBO Pictures drama premiering Aug. 22, ``The Rat
Pack'' explores the relationships between the men, the glamour and
glitz of their lives, and the sometimes dark reality behind the
facade.
 &HT;    ``It's not a tell-all or a nasty kind of thing,'' emphasizes Ray
Liotta, who plays Sinatra. ``Hopefully it's a fairly accurate
portrayal of these guys at a particular time in their lives.''
 &HT;    Sinatra is the central character, and Liotta (``Copland,'' 1997
and ``Goodfellas,'' 1990) admits it was an intimidating role.
 &HT;    ``I didn't want to just do the angry Frank, the Frank who beat
up photographers, the Frank who drank,'' he says. ``Sure, that was
part of it, as much as his generosity, as much as he fought against
racism, as much as the love of his friends. That's the Frank we
wanted to tell.''
 &HT;    A major focus is Sinatra's admiration for John F. Kennedy. An
early JFK supporter, Sinatra worked to get him elected. Sinatra
reconciled with Peter Lawford, then married to Pat Kennedy, to get
close to JFK. The actors hadn't spoken in eight years, since
Lawford had dinner with Ava Gardner after she divorced Sinatra.
 &HT;    Lawford claimed it was a ploy by studio publicists, but Sinatra
didn't believe him and cut him out of his life. Sinatra's desire to
get close to Kennedy was so strong that he engineered a
rapprochement.
 &HT;    As the film shows, Sinatra used his popularity and underworld
connections to help Kennedy get elected, only to be discarded when
he was no longer useful. Bobby Kennedy considered Sinatra a
liability, partially because of his relationship with alleged mafia
figures, but also because of his friendship with Davis, who was
engaged to marry Swedish actress May Britt.
 &HT;    ``This interracial marriage was a real problem for the Kennedy
campaign, which was in the middle of trying to win the South,''
remarks Rob Cohen, who directed ``The Rat Pack'' and previously did
``Dragon: the Bruce Lee Story'' (1993).
 &HT;    ``It became really contentious political fodder because Frank,
who was going to be best man at the wedding, is suddenly the most
visible member of the campaign.''
 &HT;    ``Lawford came to Frank with a message from Joe Kennedy: If
Sinatra shows up at the wedding, he is finished with the
Kennedys,'' Cohen says. ``Frank is really being twisted. And Sammy
is calling from Washington D.C., where he is playing a date and
being picketed by neo-Nazis, and Frank is telling him, `Forget that
stuff. I'm going to be there.' There is so much going on in this
movie that people don't know about.''
 &HT;    The movie also chronicles Sinatra's final split with Lawford.
After his election, Kennedy visited California. Sinatra expanded
his estate to make room for the Secret Service and a presidential
visit, but was told JFK would stay with Bing Crosby, a Republican
who did nothing to get Kennedy elected.
 &HT;    ``It hurt Frank so much, he just went beserk,'' Cohen says. ``He
turned on Lawford _ the messenger carrying the bad news _ and
bodily threw him down the stairs of his house.''
 &HT;    British actor Angus Macfadyen (``Braveheart,'' 1995), who plays
Lawford, recoils at the cruelty he sees in Sinatra's treatment of
Lawford. ``Ten years later Lawford went to Las Vegas with his new
wife to where Frank was singing and Frank refused to go on until
they were removed.''
 &HT;    Each actor has a different perspective on the Rat Pack.
 &HT;    Macfadyen deplores the monstrous egos he found. ``There always
seemed to be a shallow quality to their lives. It was all facade.
They were like children who never grew up.''
 &HT;    Liotta is more forgiving, lamenting that people too often focus
on Sinatra's negative side. The actor remembers an interview
Sinatra gave to Walter Cronkite on the singer's 50th birthday.
 &HT;    Most of the questions were about his relationships with the mob
or when he hit a journalist. ``The interview wasn't about his fund
raising or about the short film he produced about kids picking on
another kid,'' Liotta says. ``The movie won an Oscar.'' (Sinatra
also received an Academy Award as Best Supporting Actor in 1953's
``From Here To Eternity.'')
 &HT;    Cheadle (TV's ``Picket Fences'' and the film ``Out of Sight,''
1998) offers perhaps the most poignant view: ``I think these men
really dug each other. I think they really were close.''
 &HT;    Sinatra and Davis seemed to have a genuinely close relationship.
Sinatra first saw the younger entertainer perform as part of trio
with his father and uncle. Sinatra recognized Davis' talent and
started getting him into clubs. They became fast friends.
 &HT;    Cheadle, who learned to tap dance and play the drums for his
role, recites a quote he heard about the group: ```Sammy always
wanted to be Frank and Frank always wanted to be Dean and Dean
always just wanted to be left alone.' And that's really how you see
them in this movie. Sammy really looked up to Frank, Frank was
always trying to be as cool as Dean, and Dean was always `I don't
care about any of it.'''
 &HT;    Martin, portrayed by Joe Mantegna, is the group's mystery man.
``Like everything with Dean, he was in it but not of it,'' Cohen
says. ``He kept a kind of dispassionate distance.'' (Mantegna's
previous credits include ``Searching for Bobby Fischer,'' 1993 and
``The Godfather Part III,'' 1990).
 &HT;    Martin already enjoyed the outer trappings of success _ thanks
to the celebrity he achieved with Jerry Lewis _ and he wasn't
interested in it anymore.
 &HT;    ``Dean had had it all,'' Cohen says. ``That's why he seemed so
cool and easy. And the drunk thing was all a big act. He used to
drink apple juice on stage, not alcohol.''
 &HT;    Lauren Bacall is credited with giving the Rat Pack its nickname.
She and Humphrey Bogart were part of a group who played cards
together, although they were better known for carousing and
thumbing their noses at society.
 &HT;    Sinatra was a junior member. Legend has it that one night the
gang was drinking at Chasen's, a popular entertainment crowd
hangout, when Bacall looked around and remarked, ``You know, you
all look like a bunch of drowned rats.'' The name stuck.
 &HT;    When Bogart died, leadership fell to Sinatra. He and his cronies
became the second generation of Rat Packers.
 &HT;    Politically and historically, they lived through momentous
times. The Civil Rights movement was underway and the Rat Pack
helped break color lines, pushing the envelope with their
satirical, but always affectionate, racial humor. ``Dean and Frank
called each other `wop' and `dago,' Joey Bishop was `the skinny
Jew' and Sammy was `smokey' or 'the colored guy,''' Cheadle says.
 &HT;    ``Back then it was so taboo to say those words, but audiences
laughed, partially as a release of tension and partially because
they couldn't believe somebody was saying those things,'' he says.
``If there had been any real mean-spiritness or hatred, it wouldn't
have been funny.''
 &HT;    That kind of humor doesn't play as well today, and members of
the viewing audience may be offended. In fact, musicians hired to
appear in one of the scenes, were displeased.
 &HT;    ``You could hear them grousing and moaning at every line,''
Cheadle says. ``We had to tell them, `In 1958, people were cracking
up at these lines.'''
 &HT;    Cohen sees the story, particularly Sinatra's part, as a Greek
tragedy. ``He was an extremely sensitive man,'' notes the director.
 &HT;    ``He was easily hurt, easily angered, very generous, incredibly
passionate and, at times, extremely self-destructive.
 &HT;    ``He called himself `an 18-carat depressive.' When he was down,
he was in the depths. And when he was high, he was elated. He was a
man of enormous talents and enormous flaws and the interaction
between the two is what made him the icon we have come to love and
will never lose.''
 c.1998 Jean Oppenheimer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Jean Oppenheimer is a Los Angeles-based free-lance writer.) &LR;
</P>
