<HEADLINE>
BEAU BRIDGES GOES OVER THE TOP IN NEW SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
  Includes a color slide of Beau Bridges in a scene from ``Maximum
Bob.'' 
 &HT;     For release Aug. 10 and thereafter 
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 &HT;     By STEPHEN COLE  
 &HT;     (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Director Barry Sonnenfeld left marching orders for cast members
Beau Bridges and Liz Vassey on the first day of shooting for
``Maximum Bob,'' ABC's ambitious new one-hour comedy-drama series.
 &HT;    ``A lot of the stuff you'll be doing is pretty over-the-top and
crazy, but don't fool around or act like you get the joke, because
then the series just won't work,'' Sonnenfeld (``Men in Black,''
1997 and ``Get Shorty,'' 1995) told his cast.
 &HT;    Over-the-top is right. The Aug. 4 pilot opened with a mermaid
downing a banana in a vast, spectator-lined aquarium at the Weeki
Wachee Spring amusement park. Seconds later, an alligator attempts
to down her.
 &HT;    Then, before you can say Elmore Leonard, we're transported to a
backward Florida town populated by a gallery of funhouse mirror
grotesques, including a mambo-dancing sheriff and an environmental
extremist who ``kaboom!'' likes to blow up cars.
 &HT;    Bridges presides over the town as a sex-starved, right-wing
magistrate (called Maximum Bob because of his penchant for handing
out stiff sentences), who is running for office and away from his
wife ... who, by the way, is also the banana-gobbling mermaid.
 &HT;    Yes, Elmore Leonard has finally made it to TV. The series, which
is based on the author's 1991 best seller, is the loopiest venture
to hit prime time since Agent Cooper rode out of ``Twin Peaks'' in
the summer of 1991.
 &HT;    ``Yeah, we have some trepidations about whether the general
public will accept us,'' admits Vassey, who plays Maximum Bob's
nemesis, a public defender who is all that prevents Bob from maybe
taking over the world.
 &HT;    ``This is such a quirky show that there's a small fear people
won't get it. At the same time, everyone complains about TV being
too much of the same thing,'' she says. ``Well, `Maximum Bob' isn't
more of the same ... For an actor, this is a dream show: an
inventive, quality series that challenges and excites you every
morning you show up for work.''
 &HT;    Vassey should know about dream shows. The California actress,
who recently starred in ``Brotherly Love,'' has worked on some of
the biggest hits in TV history, including ``ER'' and ``All My
Children,'' for which she earned an Emmy nomination. She's also
guested on ``Cheers,'' ``Murphy Brown'' and ``Home Improvement.''
 &HT;    Still, nothing prepared her for the maximum pace of ``Maximum
Bob.'' ``Barry Sonnenfeld and the other directors and writers _
many of whom have come from ``The Larry Sanders Show'' by the way _
have really set out to make a feature-film caliber movie with every
episode,'' Vassey explains.
 &HT;    ``That means a lot of work. A lot of little touches. Each
episode is the result of eight straight 14-hour days ... It's
grueling because so little of what we shoot seems to be straight
forward dialogue.''
 &HT;    Vassey hasn't had to wrestle any alligators yet, but one episode
had her going a few rounds with a jumbo Rottweiler.
 &HT;    ``It was huge _ 120 pounds of solid muscle,'' she says. ``And
the only way you could get it to behave was to toss it a hot dog
before every shot.''
 &HT;    The actress makes it clear she prefers going one-on-one with
Bridges. ``I love the character of Maximum Bob. He's outrageous and
awful, but he's also disarming and fun,'' Vassey says. ``My
character's job is to disagree with him, to fight him, but at the
same time, I'm playing with him. I tell people it's kind of like
being on Howard Stern's show.''
 &HT;    The series is one of the few screen adaptations of Leonard's
works to capture the author's linguistic playfulness. There's a
great gag in the pilot where a good ol' boy struggles with a ransom
note, then finally breaks down and asks his kidnap victim how to
spell `orals.'
 &HT;    What do you mean? the victim asks. ``You know, `Do what I say,
orals I'm gonna put her in the wood shed,''' he responds. Vassey
allows that Leonard's peculiar world view and speech patterns
proved a unique acting challenge.
 &HT;    ``As Barry Sonnenfeld suggests, you have to underplay the crazy
scenes,'' she says. ``But at the same time, the dialogue carries
the story, and there's lots of it. When I first looked at how long
some of my speeches were, I said to myself, boy, I'm going to have
(to) play the dialogue very fast. I can't have viewers falling
asleep while I'm talking.''
 &HT;    Actors are notorious worriers. But Vassey has no reason to
concern herself with audience members nodding off during her most
recent work. For nobody is likely to fall asleep in the middle of
the outrageously funny, go-for-baroque world of ``Maximum Bob.''
 &HT;     c.1998 TV Guide (Canada)  
