<HEADLINE>
BACK-TO-SCHOOL BARGAINS 
</HEADLINE>
  Includes photo of Computer Renaissance used-computer store. 
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 By LEAH INGRAM 
 c.1998 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're like most parents, you'll spend an average of $408 per
child on back-to-school stuff this year _ so says an American
Express Retail Survey.
</P>
<P>
   Clothing alone comprises 58 percent of this budget. If you've
got more than one child to shop for, that dollar amount can really
add up. You'll also end up spending money on after-school
activities, lunches and other school-related purchases. But, with a
little creativity, you won't end up broke by Christmas.
 &UR; Clothing &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Instead of hitting the mall, organize a clothing exchange.
Usually held at community centers, churches or school gyms, parents
bring unwanted garments and, in return, they get gently used
clothing from other parents. No money exchanges hands, explains
Marjorie Norton, Ph.D., a professor of clothing and textiles at
Virginia Tech University.
</P>
<P>
   When money does exchange hands, it can benefit a good cause.
Cynthia Sutton's daughter, Cydney, now 12, used to attend a Dallas
public school that required uniforms. To help raise funds for the
PTA plus offset the cost of new uniforms, parents would set aside a
day to sell used uniforms. ``A jumper that sold new for $20 would
go for $5,'' recalls Sutton.
</P>
<P>
   Another way to stretch your clothing dollar further is to buy
from companies that stand behind their products. Catalogers Lands'
End (800-356-4444) and L.L. Bean (800-221-4221) offer 100 percent
satisfaction guaranteed policies. ``If at any time a customer is
not satisfied with a product, she can return it for a full refund
or an exchange,'' says Jolene McGowan, an L.L. Bean spokesperson.
</P>
<P>
   Backpack maker Jansport (800-346-8239) offers a full, lifetime
warranty, which Kathy Schriefer of Erie, Pa., took advantage of
last year after the zipper broke on daughter Jen's, 18, backpack.
``We sent it back and received a brand new backpack,'' Schriefer
recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Sears has a similar warranty through its Kidvantage program.
``If a kid splits, rips or wears out his clothing before he grows
out of it,'' says Kathleen Connolly, a Sears spokesperson, ``we'll
replace the same item in the same size.'' Sue McCloughan of
Plymouth, Minn., has been taking advantage of the Kidvantage
guarantee since 1994. ``I've received replacements about three
times,'' says McCloughan, mom to Kaitlin, 14 and Quinn, 12.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does Sears stand behind the clothing it sells, but it
rewards its customers, too. Parents who register with Kidvantage,
like McCloughan, get 15 percent off every time they spend $100 on
kid's clothing.
 &UR; After-School Activities &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Getting your kids involved in the extracurricular activities can
be an enriching, albeit expensive, endeavor. But they don't have to
put you in the poorhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of spending $1,000 on a new saxophone when son Sam, 12,
joined the junior high school band, Anne Tomlinson of Nukilteo,
Wash., bought a refurbished saxophone for $400 from Music Go Round
(800-645-7299), which sells first-quality, used musical
instruments.
</P>
<P>
   You can find savings on used sports equipment at stores like
Play It Again Sports (800-645-7299), which has 710 U.S. locations.
Instead of paying $99 for a pair of new ice hockey skates, you can
get a comparable secondhand pair for about $30, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be shy about asking relatives, coworkers and friends if
they have a flute stashed away in the attic or a baseball glove
they no longer need, suggests Mary Hunt, publisher of Cheapskate
Monthly ($18 for 12 issues, 800-550-3502). Or talk to your child's
coach or band leader about families he may know of who would be
willing to loan or sell you their used equipment.
</P>
<P>
   If you're not comfortable buying used sporting goods, try to
shop in a sporting superstore like Jumbo Sports (888-207-2965)
where they'll give you 5 percent off if you find cheaper prices
elsewhere.
 &UR; Grooming &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A back-to-school haircut can be had for a song, if you visit a
local beauty school. For example, cosmetology students at Pivot
Point in Chicago, under the supervision of their teachers, of
course, will cut hair for $5. Likewise, Empire Beauty Schools, with
20 locations in Pennsylvania, charge $7. (Regular salons charge
about $15 for a kid's cut.) Look in the Yellow Pages under beauty
schools.
</P>
<P>
   If you'd prefer to visit a bona fide salon, Vidal Sassoon salons
in nine U.S. cities give children under 12 a 30-percent discount.
In addition, one night a week, the salons will charge $15 for a
haircut if you're willing to let haircutters-in-training trim your
locks.
</P>
<P>
   Another option: invest in a pair of good scissors (about $8),
rent a video on haircutting from the library and learn to cut your
kid's hair, says Hunt, who trims her boys' locks herself. Or ask
your regular haircutter if she'll trim your kid's bangs for free or
a nominal fee (most charge $5), or let you barter services for a
free cut. ``You can sweep the salon or run errands while shes
cutting your kid's hair,'' suggests Hunt.
 &UR; Lunch &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kids can eat you out of house and home, but their school lunches
don't have to. See if your school district will let you buy hot
lunches in advance at a discount, like Judy Kessler of Van Nuys,
Calif., did for son Steven, 14. She spent $100 up front for 100
lunches and saved $75. Or, investigate whether or not your family
may be eligible for free or reduced-cost lunches; you don't have to
be poor to qualify. According to the U.S. Department of
Agriculture, which oversees the National School Lunch Program,
children from families of four earning up to $28,860 can buy lunch
for 40 cents each day.
</P>
<P>
   Another money-saver: don't use commercially prepared juice
boxes. Tracey McBride, author of Frugal Luxuries (Bantam, 1997),
estimates that every time you throw away a juice box, you're losing
20 cents. Instead, follow the lead of Denver mom Pam Lendi. She
invested in Rubbermaid juice boxes for about $1.30 each, refills
them each day and saves about $95 a year. Cheapskate extraordinaire
Hunt goes one step further by washing and reusing 20-ounce soda
bottles as drink containers.
</P>
<P>
   If you are truly brand conscious, call each company whose
product you use and ask for money-saving coupons. ``Almost every
brand lists a toll-free number on its label,'' says Hunt. ``I've
gotten 75-cent and $1-coupons, and the best part is, they have no
expiration date.''
 &UR; Computers &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are ways to save money on computer costs, if all your
child needs is a word processor. Stores like Kinko's (800-2-KINKOS)
rent computers by the hour _ an Ann Arbor, Mich., location lets you
use a PC or a Mac for $12 an hour. Or see if your local library has
computers for the public to use. ``It's not nearly as convenient as
having a computer at home,'' says Hunt, ``but it sure is cheaper.''
</P>
<P>
   If you decide to buy your child a computer this year, check out
used equipment at Computer Renaissance (800-645-7299) or mail-order
company Rumarson Technology (800-929-0029) in Kenilworth, N.J..
Recently, Rumarson was offering a Pentium chip computer, monitor
and printer for $1,000; it would cost $1,800 at retail. Both
companies offer warranties on all computers they sell.
</P>
<P>
   Make sure the computer you buy comes pre-loaded with software.
Rumarson's computers have about $200 worth of programs on them
already. However, if you must buy software yourself _ and you
already have Internet access _ check out shareware Web sites, from
which you can download software for a nominal fee (about $30)
instead of paying close to $100 at retail.
 &UR; Health Checkups &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If your kids are due for vaccinations, call the National
Immunization Information Hotline, operated by the American Social
Health Association under contract with the Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention, at 800-232-2522, to find local doctors and
clinics offering free or low-cost immunizations. If you haven't
been keeping up with your well-child visits and want your son or
daughter to have a back-to-school checkup, see if your local church
or synagogue participates in a program like the one Egleston's
Children's Health Care System offers with 45 houses of worship in
Atlanta, Ga. Together, they put parishioners in touch with low-cost
medical services available in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Your regular pediatrician may have hidden savings. Ask if you
can get a discount for paying in cash. It's one of Hunt's favorite
money saving tips. ``I've been able to get as much as 25 percent
off,'' she says. Another of her favorites: If you child needs
prescription medication, buy it through a mail-order pharmacy.
``You can save up to 50 percent over the pharmacy down the
street,'' she says
</P>
<P>
   In addition, ask family and friends if they know of any local
doctors who offer bargains or cash-saving incentives. Optometrist
Danna Haba gives free back-to-school vision screenings to
schoolchildren at her Utica, Mich., office _ a $60 savings off her
regular fee. Framingham, Mass., dentist Tom Orent rewards patients
with a $20 credit and a $20 gift certificate to a local restaurant
if they send their friends to his office. Their friends, in return,
get $50 off an initial exam.
</P>
<P>
   ---------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (LEAH INGRAM is a free-lance writer based in New Jersey.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
