<HEADLINE>
ONLINE MOMS PLUG INTO A COMMUNITY OF CHILDREARING EXPERTS
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 By ANNE GREGOR 
 c.1998 Child magazine 
 North American rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 (PLEASE NOTE: The word (TILDE) in the 5th paragraph stands for the
symbol often found in Internet addresses. The word has been used
instead of the symbol because it cannot be interpreted by many
newspaper computer systems.) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hospitalized for a week after going into premature labor, Mary
Searcy was sent home with strict orders from her doctor to remain
in bed.
</P>
<P>
   Her bed rest lasted for more than a month. Then, eight weeks
before her due date, she delivered her first child, David.
</P>
<P>
   Although Searcy, then 24, had been told to expect a premature
birth, no one counseled her about the special problems of caring
for a newborn preemie. When David came home after four weeks in the
hospital, he had difficulty swallowing and his heartbeat was
erratic. ``My husband and I were in a state of shock,'' Searcy
recalls. ``We were never told where to turn for support.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking for information, Searcy combed her local bookstores in
Wyoming, Mich., but had only limited success. In frustration, she
decided to try the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   She borrowed a modem for her computer, went online, and posted
requests for help on every baby and childbirth-related bulletin
board she could find. Eventually, she located a group of moms and
dads who had recently formed an online community, called Preemie-L
(home.vicnet.net.au/(TILDE)garyh/preemie.htm), for sharing their
feelings and experiences as parents of preemies via e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   It was ``like a family,'' Searcy says, ``a place where I met
others who knew what I was going through.'' From finding tiny
clothing that accommodated monitor leads to determining whether
David's speech delay was typical of preemies, Searcy got answers on
the Web. That was a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Preemie-L now features a discussion forum, the latest research
from neonatologists and psychologists, and an archive of resources
on bed rest and preemie care compiled by Searcy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Home on the Web &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Far from finding cyberspace cold and impersonal, Searcy
discovered a gathering place where she could get help and, later,
give something back to the community that had sustained her. And
the bonds grew over the years. At a conference held in Detroit this
summer, she met the Australian founder of Preemie-L for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   Searcy's experience is not unique. More and more women are going
online and discovering the value of Internet access. According to a
1997 survey by Nielsen Media Research/CommerceNet, women make up 42
percent of adult users of the Internet, up from 34 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Other studies indicate that anywhere from one-third to one-half
of Internet users live in households with children.
</P>
<P>
   Internet interconnections are myriad. Type the word parenting or
motherhood in any of numerous search engines (services such as
Yahoo! and Excite that sort Internet sites) and well over 10,000
hits, or entries, will appear.
</P>
<P>
   Moms turn to the Internet to stay in touch with family and
friends, to do research and browse for information, to tap into
special online forums of parents sharing similar interests, and to
shop.
</P>
<P>
   They compare notes on recognizing and treating childhood
diseases. One woman checks out the Northern California section of
``Moms Across America'' on the Moms On-Line Web site to see if
anyone has posted what children's software is on the shelves at the
local discount warehouse store. (That site is reachable via America
Online.) She also downloads coloring pages for her daughter and
sits with her son in her lap reading him a new Elmo story from the
PBS Web site. (www.pbs.org)
</P>
<P>
   One clear benefit of Internet connections, online moms say, is
that they help reduce the sense of social isolation that new
mothers can feel.
</P>
<P>
   When Nancy Brown, 37, of Martinez, Calif., was looking for a
play group, for her 1-year-old son, Evan, she started her search at
the computer, logging on to a mothers' forum on AOL. A woman living
nearby replied with details about a mothers club. Brown's query led
to some members forming a play group that has been meeting once a
week in local parks for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   In between their weekly encounters, the six moms in the play
group stay in touch via e-mail. ``We get a chance to finish up
those snatches of conversation that we had attempted at the park
while chasing after a little one,'' Brown comments.
</P>
<P>
   Going farther afield than area parks, a group of moms-to-be
spanned four continents to form close e-mail friendships when they
subscribed to an Internet mailing list for women with April 1996
due dates. Now, members of the April '96 Moms say their common
experiences run far beyond pregnancy. They've shared in everything
from the births of their children, their toddlers' first steps, and
the arrival of siblings to heated online debates over natural birth
and pacifiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I assumed the group would slowly dissolve, but our friendships
are stronger than ever,'' says Paige Schreiner, 31, of
Gaithersburg, Md., one of the club's 60-odd active members.
</P>
<P>
   Every month, new delivery-date groups are formed. Women
expecting babies in September can find a September 1998 Club by
checking out the news group misc.kids.pregnancy. (News groups are
forums on the Internet that are sorted by subject.)
</P>
<P>
   A world of cyber communities has formed around an almost
infinite number of topics from autism to childhood diabetes, from
home schooling to the Special Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   One e-mail group, CyberMommies, was created as a forum on
infertility and adoption. Karen Ledbetter, 42, of Mooresville,
N.C., tells of at least one fellow CyberMommy who adopted a baby as
the result of leads from the group. Ledbetter also cites coping
strategies the women share: ``We help each other deal with the rude
remarks people can sometimes make about adoption.''
</P>
<P>
   For many moms, the Internet has become as indispensable as the
phone. It's the Information Age's pen pal, armchair adviser, and
door-to-door salesman. As Searcy notes, her most important
discovery on the Web was that ``I wasn't alone.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Anne Gergor and her daughter Martha Rose write ``Bytes and
Bits'' for Girls' Life.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
