<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GET-MORE-DONE-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLOW DOWN AND GET MORE DONE
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 By RICHARD CARLSON 
 c. 1988 McCALL'S magazine 
 North American rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ever notice how the more you try to get done, the more you seem
to have in front of you? You try so hard to find ways to save
time-but where does it go?
</P>
<P>
   More likely than not, it gets packed with more things to do,
places to go, people to call, decisions to make. You pick up fast
food for the kids so you'll have a few minutes to yourself after
dinner. But instead of reading that new novel, you find yourself
trying to get a jump on tomorrow's work or getting sucked into
making some PTA telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Slow down! There's a way to get it all done without driving
yourself nuts. The truth is, all the timesaving tips and gadgets
can't help if you haven't learned to relax, to approach the world
and your life more peacefully.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is there is a way to not only feel better about
yourself but also to actually get everything done. The solution has
to do with changing your thoughts and feelings. A new attitude will
help you focus and prioritize. Because you'll be less distracted,
you'll conserve energy and minimize mistakes. Most important,
changing your mind-set will reduce any frenzied feelings you have,
because even though you'll have just as much to do, you'll feel
like you have plenty of time.
</P>
<P>
   First, a look at the ways your mind does and doesn't work.
</P>
<P>
   It's important to know you have two distinct modes of thought.
The first is analytical: your brain resembles a computer, storing
and processing, evaluating data and planning. The second is free
flow, when your mind operates like a river, always moving, bringing
you just the right ideas for the moment. Thoughts come to you
effortlessly, out of the blue. This mode kicks in when your mind is
relaxed instead of engaged.
</P>
<P>
   There's a time and a place for each way _ neither is better. The
analytical mode is suited for balancing your checkbook, calculating
time or planning a schedule. It's also useful when you're making a
list, figuring out the best way to get to an unfamiliar location or
doing something for the first time. You want to be in this mode
when you need to figure something out.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, most people spend too much time being
analytical. Trying to figure everything out is the biggest reason
you feel hurried and harried. Thinking leads to feelings. If you're
harboring angry thoughts, you're going to feel angry. Similarly,
cynicism breeds suspicion, and feeding yourself hurried messages
brings on the sense of being overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a really busy schedule, for example, thoughts like
``How am I ever going to get it all done'' or simply going over and
over your schedule, even talking about it with others, can stir up
anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   During these times, rather than being focused and calm, your
mind is all over the place, leaving you barely able to concentrate
on the one thing you're actually doing _ getting dressed, driving,
preparing a meal, cleaning a room or performing some other task.
</P>
<P>
   Give your head a break, and get your life back.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the best thing you can do when you're feeling rushed
is to clear your mind. You need to drop the racing thoughts, which
allows you to enter the free-flowing mode. When your brain is
clear, the door to inspiration and wisdom is opened. Because
there's less going on mentally, solutions that seemed impossible to
find will come to you as if out of left field.
</P>
<P>
   Ever have the experience of struggling to remember a name or a
fact, only to have it magically pop into your head only after you
gave up pushing for it? Ever wonder why your best ideas occur to
you not when you're straining for them but while you're taking a
shower or listening to some music ? That's the strength of the
free-flowing mode.
</P>
<P>
   This power means that whenever you stop analyzing and drop into
free flow thought, your inner wisdom surfaces to help you out of
whatever dilemma you face. Your mind isn't turned off. You're still
thinking but in a more passive way. Just as using the back burner
can be the best way to prepare a meal, the more passive mode is
often the best way to approach your hectic life.
</P>
<P>
   You can learn the easy device of switching between the two modes
by following these steps:
</P>
<P>
   Pay attention to your feelings.
</P>
<P>
   They are the key to knowing you're in the wrong mode. If you
feel stressed out, take a couple of slow, deep breaths and check in
with yourself. Is your internal voice yakking away about how things
are going or what you need to do for the rest of the day? By simply
acknowledging that your mind is too busy, you start slowing it
down.
</P>
<P>
   Admit to yourself you're caught up in your own thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Recognize that you need to become quieter within by saying
something gentle to yourself like ``Whoops, there I go again.''
This admission reinforces the fact that it's your own thinking, not
the outside world, that's making you feel frantic. Sometimes the
simple act of acknowledging you are off track is enough to bring
calm.
</P>
<P>
   Live in the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago I attended a lecture by a famous speaker who spoke
on the issue of being in a hurry. He was a very busy man but a
remarkably calm one. During the question-and-answer period, a
nervous-looking audience member asked, ``You've given lectures in
over 50 cities during the last two months _ and you have a family.
Aren't you exhausted? A schedule like that would make me crazy. How
do you do it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I simply do one thing at a time,'' the speaker responded in a
voice that calmed the entire audience. ``I remain present. Instead
of looking at my schedule and freaking out that I'll be in one city
today and another tomorrow, I do just what's before me _ one thing
after another.''
</P>
<P>
   Be patient.
</P>
<P>
   Slowing down your mind is simple, but it's not easy: You won't
learn to do it in a day. Plan to put the brakes on racing thoughts
as best you can, as often as you can. It's a practice that pays. If
you keep up your efforts, eventually you'll reap big serenity
rewards.
</P>
<P>
   Dare to be mellow.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so you know how to rein in your speedy mind and go into
free-flow mode. What about those all around you who are losing
their heads? Our culture gives us a lot of messages that it's a
good thing to hurry up _ and be completely stressed out. Many of us
brag about how busy, overwhelmed and sleep deprived we are.
</P>
<P>
   It's a badge of honor. It's true that most of us are over
committed. But we don't have to win first place in the
how-close-am-I-to-burnout sweepstakes. While everyone is rushing
around frantically, keep to your own more peaceful pace. It does
take courage. But it's the best thing for you. (Plus, you really do
get more done!)
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Carlson, a stress consultant, is the author of ``Don't
Sweat the Small Stuff With Your Family.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
