</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCHDEACON-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Voice from beyond greets Dickinson's survivors
 &HT;    By Tom Archdeacon
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ It was a voice she never dreamed she'd hear
again. It came to Judy Dickinson Thursday by overnight mail.
</P>
<P>
   The unexpected package had been sent to Dayton by a woman in
Macon, Ga. When the woman's husband had been dying of multiple
sclerosis and could no longer see, Judy's husband _ Gardner
Dickinson _ wanted to do something special. He and the guy had gone
to high school together in the early 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   And so, Gardner _ one of the pioneers of the PGA Tour and Senior
PGA Tour, as well as one of the best golf instructors the game has
ever known _ decided to read the golf book he had written, as well
as special notes and asides, into a tape recorder. He sent the
labor of love _10 cassettes in all _ to his dying friend.
</P>
<P>
   Now the guy's widow thought Judy might like to have the tapes
back. Gardner had died April 19th after years of heart problems. He
was 70.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the 48-year-old Judy _ who had taken golf lessons
from Gardner for years before marrying him in 1985 _ has struggled
not only with her grief, but with everyday life as she tried
competing on the LPGA Tour, while also raising the couple's
eight-year-old twin sons, Barron and Spencer.
</P>
<P>
   This season _ her 21st year on the women's pro circuit _ she has
tried to play in only nine of the first 25 tour stops. In four of
those outings, she has missed the cut. Her best finish is a tie for
24th and she's made just $14,156.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been hard, it still is,'' she said. ``People come up to
me along the way and tell me how they lost a husband or a wife.
Most everyone says it takes at least two years until you feel
you're not just going through the motions. You don't realize the
void that's there. I think of Gardner all the time. I can't tell
you how many times I go to call him and then it hits me. No one is
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Then last Friday morning, he was.
</P>
<P>
   As she and the boys were driving from the place where they're
staying near the Dayton Mall to the first round of the Star Bank
LPGA Classic at the Country Club of the North, Judy took out the
packet of tapes and shoved one in the tape deck.
</P>
<P>
   Instantly Gardner's voice filled the vehicle. He was telling a
story about Sam Snead. After that came a tale about Bobby Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boys were kind of shocked,'' she said. ``They hadn't heard
his voice in a long time. He had had his first triple by-pass a
year after they were born and the strokes and other problems never
let them really know their dad as he was. Toward the end, Gardner
hadn't been able to talk at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more they listened, the more it amazed them. They asked,
'Is that daddy? Is it really daddy?' I told them it sure was. For
me, it was great to hear his voice. I think it inspired me.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing her best golf of the past four seasons, Dickinson fired
a six-under-par 66 to finish the Star Bank's opening round tied for
third, four strokes off Dottie Pepper's lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all came together,'' Dickinson said. ``I think Gardner
helped me.''
</P>
<P>
   But then Gardner had always been able to coax the best golf out
of her. That goes back to the days when she was Judy Clark, a girl
raised in Akron and schooled at Glassboro State before becoming a
top New Jersey amateur.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner _ called the Slim Man because of his 5-foot-10,
130-pound build _ had always been bigger than life. After turning
pro in 1952, he was a sidekick of Ben Hogan and later influenced
golfers like Jack Nicklaus and JoAnne Carner.
</P>
<P>
   He was an opinionated guy who stuck to his guns. In describing
their differences, Judy once explained: ``I'm pretty much on the
left and he's on the right...of John Birch.'' Friday, she quietly
laughed at his ways:
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually that's part of what attracted me. He liked to have a
good time, but he let you know exactly where he stood. A lot of
people won't speak up. Instead they talk behind your back. He was
straight-forward.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years after they married they decided to have children.
``Truthfully, I was scared to death. I'd never baby sat much and I
didn't know how I'd be with children. Gardner (who had three
children by a previous marriage) said it's different when they're
your own kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``And my clock was ticking. I was 39 and he was getting older,
too. But it turned out it was the best thing that ever happened to
us.''
</P>
<P>
   As the LPGA president for three years, she made it better for
other touring mothers as well. She was instrumental in creating the
regular travelling day-care program on the tour. Now she's thinking
about getting a junior golf program for tour youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   Her kids have been travelling with her since June. ``The weeks I
didn't take them were the toughest,'' she said. ``Now we haven't
been back to our house (near West Palm Beach, Fla.) for a couple of
months. It's been good to get away from the memories, but Monday we
head back. Just as I'm playing better, it's time for the kids to go
back to school. I'll only play another tournament or two this year,
then it's back being a regular mom.''
</P>
<P>
   In practice and pro-am rounds last week, Barron did some
caddying for his mom and afterwards surmised that he wants to be a
player, not a caddy because he thinks the pros have the better end
of the deal. Although his mom did pay him, he returned the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loaned them $300 to buy a golden retriever, so he said,
'Here Mom, this is to start paying off Rosie.''' The rest of the
week, the boys have gone bowling, visited the Air Force Museum and
done some swimming.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're beginning to ask more and more about their dad,'' she
said. ``I just want them to know how much he loved them.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years after the boys were born, Gardner talked to a
USA Today reporter about having children late in his life. ``I
won't live to see them grown,'' he said. ``I guess that isn't fair
to them, but at least I'll leave part of me behind.''
</P>
<P>
   That he has.
</P>
<P>
   And this morning on the way to the golf course, Judy and the
boys plan to listen to him once again.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Archdeacon writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
