<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BROWN-TRADE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Now, trade looks good to Brown
 &HT;    By Dan Graziano
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Kevin Brown didn't like it at first. Not one bit.
</P>
<P>
   It was December 15, and the Florida Marlins had just traded
Brown to the San Diego Padres for three minor-league prospects. And
the prospect of moving almost a continent away from his Macon, Ga.,
home, his wife and two sons was pretty unappealing.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's eight months later, the Padres are sitting atop the
National League West, the Marlins are languishing in last, and
Brown himself his the proud owner of a 14-3 record and an 11-game
winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a lot better than I probably could have hoped for,''
Brown said Friday, before his new team took on his old team at
Qualcomm Stadium. ``I knew it was going to be difficult for the
family, that was the main thing. But when the team does this well,
it's easy to put the past in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   The past includes last year's 16-8 campaign, which of course
culminated in the Marlins' World Series championship. It also
includes the 17-11 season Brown had in 1996. Remember that one?
That was the year Brown had a major-league-best 1.89 ERA and walked
just 33 batters all season, yet couldn't seem to win because the
Marlins couldn't seem to score runs for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably threw the ball better that year,'' Brown said.
``But you can throw the ball well and not get the results. It's
definitely headed back in the other direction now. I could go for
about seven or eight years of it heading in the other direction.
That'd be nice.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Padres, who began Friday's game just two games behind
the Braves for the National League's best record, are thinking
about this year only. That's why they gave up well-regarded
prospects like Derrek Lee and Rafael Medina for Brown, even though
he can be a free agent at the end of this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great guy to have, because he's a horse, basically,''
Padres right fielder Tony Gwynn said. ``You can't have too many
guys like that. When he's on the mound, we feel like nobody can
beat us, and you can't put a price on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn also made the point that Brown's mere presence has helped
the rest of the pitching staff. Andy Ashby, who started Friday's
game, was 15-6 with a 2.55 ERA. A pair of aces like that makes
Sterling Hitchcock, Joey Hamilton and Mark Langston the No. 3, 4
and 5 starters, and that makes for a pretty good starting staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get a guy like Brownie, that takes a lot of pressure off
the staff,'' Marlins manager Jim Leyland said. ``It takes a lot of
pressure off the manager, too, because you know you're going to get
seven innings from a guy like that every time you run him out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``His attitude is just right,'' Padres manager Bruce Bochy said.
``He's out there, he won't accept losing. He has a hard time
accepting that he made one bad pitch. For other guys to see that,
it makes a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown is enjoying being back in a pennant race, but he's not
looking forward too much, mainly because he doesn't have much time
left this season to spend with his family. Candace, Ridge and
Grayson will be moving back to Georgia in the coming weeks, as
seven-year-old Ridge is getting ready to go back to school.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Ridge was in heaven. He was in the Padres' clubhouse,
wearing a jersey with his dad's name and number on the back, trying
to escape dental-floss-wielding Padres first baseman Wally Joyner,
who wanted to remove one of Ridge's very loose teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Ridge's glove, bought for him by his mother, had inscribed on it
the name of Chipper Jones, third baseman for hated rival Atlanta.
When this was pointed out to father and son, they both decided that
should change. They got a black magic marker and scribbled it out,
with Kevin promising to find some back shoe polish later with which
to finish the job.
</P>
<P>
   Winning ballgames, being in first place, goofing off with his
seven-year-old son. Yep, Kevin Brown was right. This has all worked
out pretty well.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Graziano writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
