</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGE-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No Marlins? No matter _ game still exciting
 &HT;    By Dave George
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   All right, so it's football season again and you're ready to
drop baseball like a bad habit.
</P>
<P>
   That's the problem with our remote-control generation, so eager
to surf from one hot topic to the next. Did the Marlins really win
the World Series, for instance, or was that all just a really slick
infomercial for some fast-acting antacid?
</P>
<P>
   Easy to get it all confused sometimes. Easy to forget that in
America, two things can and must endure : Elvis and baseball.
</P>
<P>
   I offer to frustrated South Florida fans a reminder that the
baseball season still runs through October. Playoffs included.
Marlins excluded. Like it or not. I offer, also, the suggestion
that there is a great deal to like about that, and a significant
amount to love.
</P>
<P>
   It begins with Mark McGwire, Sammy Sosa and Ken Griffey, Jr.,
each slowing in their chase for Roger Maris' epic single-season
record of 61 home runs. Which will burst from the pack this month
and make a true run at the thing is fascinating conjecture. My
opinion has shifted significantly of late, from a Big Mac certainty
to a Sammy surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa is the only one whose team still has a reason to play. That
will help keep his mind occupied with driving in run and winning
big games for Chicago. The home runs tend to come more naturally,
more easily, that way.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, should the Cubs continue their challenge for a
wild-card playoff spot, or even the NL Central title, Sosa's
home-run spectacle will be absorbed to some degree by the drama of
a haunted and beloved franchise inching once more toward the cruel
unknown. Not even the Bulls have ever gripped Chicago like a Cubs
World Series would.
</P>
<P>
   Here's another baseball question tough enough to chew upon until
September is spent. Which team is going to do what Florida did a
year ago, beating out Atlanta for the National League pennant?
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it may seem ridiculous to count out an Atlanta team whose
regal pitching staff leads the majors with 15 shutouts, including
consecutive three-hitters by Greg Maddux and Tom Glavine last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins eliminated the Braves in 1997 with a rotation that
lacked Alex Fernandez and featured Livan Hernandez, a rookie. San
Diego and Houston, leaders of their respective divisions, can do it
again, and not just because they inherited from Florida a pair of
noted Braves-killers (Kevin Brown with the Padres and Moises Alou
with the Astros).
</P>
<P>
   Both teams have solid lineups, in some ways more dangerous than
the Braves. Craig Biggio, the game's best leadoff man, always is on
base for the Astros. Greg Vaughn (39 homers) always is clearing the
bases for the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment I'm leaning toward the Padres as eventual NL
champions because they've got monster closers from either side _
right-hander Trevor Hoffman (37 saves) and lefty Randy Myers
(30-save seasons with five different teams). There is one enormous
reason to hold out for Houston, however, a 6-foot-10 equalizer
named Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   An Astros regular-season home record crowd of 52,071 watched the
Big Unit shut out the Phillies Friday. Most of those fans were in
the building in time to watch Johnson go through his pre-game wa-kp
in the bullpen. Baseball is booming in Houston, a city that doesn't
even have an NFL franchise and doesn't miss the one that got away.
</P>
<P>
   Whew, that's a lot of baseball talk without even mentioning the
Yankees, everybody's solid World Series favorite. Edge a little
closer to the television. Bore a little deeper into the box scores.
There is no need to retreat, no matter what course the Marlins
choose.
</P>
<P>
   As long as it's baseball, every citizen retains a legitimate
stake.
</P>
<P>
   Dave George wrotes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
