<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Golfer regains stride, plays for fun again
 &HT;    By Gary Nuhn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ She hit ``rock bottom,'' as she calls it, in
October of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Noble had lost her playing card after a promising start on
the LPGA Tour, was back at Qualifying School, it was Day One, and
she was in the process of shooting 81.
</P>
<P>
   On the back nine, tears came to her eyes and started tracing
down her cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Near a breakdown?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Totally,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Golf can do that to you; can grab you like a bouncer and start
tossing you around until you're bruised in both body and spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Noble was to that point and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   A three-time New Jersey State Women's amateur champion, she had
done well at Wake Forest, qualified in her first try for the LPGA
and finished 49th on the money list her rookie year. She tied for
second in her first LPGA Championship and was a star waiting to
happen.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime between the end of that magical 1992 season and the
start of 1993, Karen Noble lost her confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why, I don't know,'' she said. ``But I played awful. And then
I started trying to fix my swing. I should have taken time off to
work on my brain because out here you face failure every week. I
really did a lot of damage to myself.''
</P>
<P>
   The bad play fed on itself. It's a vicious circle: The worse you
play, the worse you feel, the worse you play. So 1993 bled into '94
. . . '95 . . . '96 and her game was in tatters and she finally
lost her card.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, everyone tried to help. Family, friends, fellow
players, the milkman. ``Everyone has solutions,'' she said.
``You're struggling. You're searching. You listen. You're
confused.''
</P>
<P>
   And finally, you lose your card, and you're at qualifying school
shooting 81 and you're crying and if someone came up and offered to
buy your clubs for $5 and a bus ticket to Memphis, you'd probably
take it.
</P>
<P>
   We were sitting upstairs in the clubhouse at Country Club of the
North last Friday, and Karen Noble wasn't crying anymore. She'd
just shot a 4-under-par 68 at the Star Bank LPGA Classic, finishing
before the blast furnace heat gripped the place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went back to just trying to have fun,'' she said. ``It
sounds silly, but I tried to just start enjoying myself again,''
she said. ``I try to avoid thinking of the outcome and think only
of the shot.''
</P>
<P>
   It sounds so simple, yet sometimes it's the only way out of
golf's cave. You go back to when you were a kid and dad dropped you
off at the course every morning and golf was fun and life was a
lark.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago at the Friendly's Classic in Massachusetts, Noble
tied for 11th. Hit 18 greens the final day, shot 2-under 70 and
made $10,340. It was her first five-figure check since her rookie
year. ``It looked like a million,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   More important, her confidence never waned. All day, shot after
shot, she held together as if made of steel.
</P>
<P>
   ``A huge step,'' she called it.
</P>
<P>
   She is blue eyed and blonde and has a Hollywood look _ like a
young Kelly McGillis.
</P>
<P>
   She'll turn 31 in 15 days. And she likes what she's doing again.
Loves coming to the course. Loves the whole scene.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time in the depths of her struggles when they called
her Karen CherNoble after the Russian nuclear plant. ``Terrible
temper, terrible attitude,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   What happened to that Karen?
</P>
<P>
   ``I killed her,'' Karen Noble said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week she went home to New Jersey and saw her Golden
Retriever, Baron, slept in her own bed, and came here refreshed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to enjoy myself,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Nuhn writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
