<HEADER>
A5969 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPORT-ENDORSEMENTS11-     08-10 1291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORT-ENDORSEMENTS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Superstar endorsers starting to fade
 &HT;    By Ethan J. Skolnick
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The idea of letting Mark McGwire walk
isn't a new one. McGwire was issued his first intentional pass of
1998 even before the baseball season began _ by Reebok. As you
might expect with a company that created a shoe called The Answer,
Reebok has one when it's asked the inevitable question:
</P>
<P>
   What were you thinking?
</P>
<P>
   ``He was looking for an ad about him,'' said Dave Fogelson,
Reebok spokesman, of the man chasing Roger Maris' home run record.
``We want to start talking about the product. For years, we have
had ads about the athlete, and by association, the brand. We can't
have that anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Why the shift in focus? Because the athletic-shoe business is
running in place, and many companies are starting to view superstar
endorsers _ with their super-expensive contracts _ as part of the
problem, not the solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a certain amount of burnout with the athlete
endorser concept,'' said John Horan, publisher of Sporting Goods
Intelligence, an industry newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Nike reported its first monthly loss in 13 years.
Reebok reported a 12.2 percent drop in shoe sales and a $3.4
million loss in the year's first quarter; Fila's parent company
reported an $8.7 million loss. Converse reported sales of its
basketball line fell 50 percent during that same period.
</P>
<P>
   Some of this decline is attributable to a change in public
taste. More young consumers are choosing street shoes, made by such
companies as Doc Maartens or Timberland, or ``extreme sports''
nontraditional footwear. Yet, it is notable that one of the few
growing companies in the industry is New Balance, which has long
abided by the slogan, ``Endorsed By No One.''
</P>
<P>
   So what becomes of the athletic someones? Many get cut.
</P>
<P>
   Converse has dumped controversial or high-priced NBA endorsers
such as Latrell Sprewell and Larry Johnson in favor of
lesser-known, lower-risk guys such as Bobby Jackson and Brevin
Knight. Pennsylvania-based athletic-shoe company And 1 ditched its
biggest-name endorser, Stephon Marbury. Fila parted ways with New
York Yankees shortstop Derek Jeter because the company, according
to director of advertising Mark Westerman, ``decided baseball was
not going to be a focus group for us.'' Not long ago, the shoe
company would have based its products on its athletes, not the
other way around.
</P>
<P>
   Reebok has made drastic cutbacks in its baseball and NFL ranks,
dropping such stars as Larry Walker and Emmitt Smith. It also has
sliced its NBA roster to about one-third of its high of 100-plus.
In June, it decided that Shaquille O'Neal was not worth his $3
million annual fee, and let him go.
</P>
<P>
   Think of O'Neal as the Dow Industrials Average, the most
high-profile signifier of a correction that had been taking place
in this market for some time. Now, says Westerman, ``it's a buyers'
market,'' in favor of the company buying the athletes' services.
</P>
<P>
   That's a major switch. Since the mid-1980s, shoe companies have
tried to replicate the success Nike had in promoting Michael Jordan
and his signature products. For Reebok, primarily a women's fitness
brand, and Fila, primarily a tennis brand, signing team-sport stars
was a way of creating a new image. Reebok, in particular, began
competing with Nike for baseball, NBA and NFL players.
</P>
<P>
   ``The focus was on which athlete was wearing what brand, as
opposed to what the product was really about,'' Fogelson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shoe companies went for the blanket effect, signing
endorsement deals with second- or third-tier players,'' said Sean
Brenner, editor of the Team Marketing Report, another industry
newsletter. ``It became difficult for consumers to differentiate.''
</P>
<P>
   Fogelson remembers watching an NBA game on TNT. Commercial
break. Jordan and Penny Hardaway endorsing Nike. Kobe Bryant,
adidas. Grant Hill, Fila. Allen Iverson, Reebok. ``This is nuts,''
he thought.
</P>
<P>
   Oversaturation hasn't been the only bugaboo. The more athletes
endorsing, the more risk for off-the-field travails and negative
associations. Now industry insiders believe that companies, if they
sign suspect individuals, will avoid long-term, guaranteed
contracts. Most new contracts give advertisers sole discretion to
terminate, if an athlete's actions disparage the company.
</P>
<P>
   Converse let Sprewell go after he choked his coach. Yet Reebok
has stood by Iverson, who has had various legal problems. The
company has even designed three Iverson shoes: The Question, The
Answer and The Answer II. The Answer wasn't quite as successful as
the Question, and Fogelson attributes that to design problems, not
image problems. ``The marketplace loves the authenticity Allen
represents,'' Fogelson argued.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, the marketplace likes a quality product.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a product is not good, I don't think any personality can
carry it,'' said Gregg Hartley, vice president of marketing for the
Sporting Goods Manufacturers Association.
</P>
<P>
   Proper marketing is a necessity, too, no matter how well known
the athlete-endorser is. Nike's Tiger Woods line of golf clothes
and shoes has fallen far short of expectations. Retailers have
complained that the products, especially the radical Air Zoom TW,
which retails for some $225, missed their market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tiger Woods marketing approach works real well for kids,
but kids can't afford pricing they are charging for them,'' Horan
said. ``Only so many kids can talk dads into buying those.''
</P>
<P>
   And only so many kids are playing golf. So the success of the
Woods products depended on an older, more conservative demographic.
Lee Weinstein, a Nike spokesman, says it was ``an OK launch. You
always learn a few lessons.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies have learned another lesson. ``Jordan was a
phenomenon,'' Hartley said. ``There are very few people who can
drive a product through in the market the way Jordan has.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Nike intends to keep trying. The company which now
provides McGwire's cleats isn't changing course. ``The very
foundation of Nike is built on working with athletes,'' Weinstein
says of a company that first worked with runner Steve Prefontaine
in 1972. ``Some of our competitors may be fickle, but we certainly
are not.''
</P>
<P>
   Reebok wanted to focus more on its DMX technology, and Fogelson
claims ``we are getting more feedback from that advertising than we
did from any other.'' Meanwhile, Nike is getting the fallout _ more
calls than ever from athletes' representatives, and less need to
bid the price up.
</P>
<P>
   Nike has the three players who are chasing the home run record,
which could help McGwire, Sammy Sosa or Ken Griffey Jr. transcend
his sport in a way Jordan, Woods, Greg Norman and very few baseball
players (maybe Cal Ripken Jr.) have. Weinstein said Nike has yet to
work up a ``home run'' ad, but may in the future.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, says Nova Lanktree of Sports Celebrity Network, could
be the perfect pitchman: ``Handsome, healthy, athletic, and about
to make history.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Fogelson says Reebok isn't regretful. He notes that when
Reebok-sponsored Northwestern won the Rose Bowl, ``a very
significant achievement, we celebrated with an ad. Did it help us
sell shoes? We're not sure.''
</P>
<P>
   He is among industry insiders who expect more athletes to
endorse because the shoe fits them, not because they fit the shoe
company. ``Where we get chosen, because they really like our
product,'' Fogelson said.
</P>
<P>
   A short time back, that seemed as unlikely as hitting 62 homers.
</P>
<P>
   Ethan J. Skolnick writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
