 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE TUESDAY COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Tuesday, August 11, 1998, are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ If Starr's final report to Congress includes
credible evidence that Clinton willfully broke the law, surely
Clinton's approval ratings will drop. If not, America's rule of law
is in jeopardy. (Nethaway, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Teachers don't ask for a
whole lot _ a little respect, some new textbooks from time to time,
and once in a while, a raise would be nice. Most of us aren't
militant and know little of the function of much maligned teacher's
unions. But you know what we'd like most of all? We'd like for
ambitious politicians to stop using teachers and education as
political footballs. (Schuett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GEEWAX-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ Eventually, the kids will move away,
the mortgage will get paid off and deceased parents will leave
behind an inheritance. That patrimony may be considerable:
Economists estimate $12 trillion is now in the hands of the fading
World War II generation whose heirs are the 76 million Americans
born between 1946 and 1964. (Geewax, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
MOVED. (f, k)
</P>
