<HEADER>
A5971 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEEWAX-COLUMN11-COX     08-10 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUSINESS COMMENTARY: A legacy besides rock 'n' roll?
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Many people are so busy paying the bills they scarcely
notice how much wealth they are building up. At the end of each
month, their house may seem more like a money pit than an
appreciating asset. But time will change that for most.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the kids will move away, the mortgage will get paid
off and deceased parents will leave behind an inheritance. That
patrimony may be considerable: Economists estimate $12 trillion is
now in the hands of the fading World War II generation whose heirs
are the 76 million Americans born between 1946 and 1964.
</P>
<P>
   When those boomers themselves start dying off in significant
numbers _ around 2020 _ their estates will be up for grabs. While
many of today's workers are not saving enough money to generate
adequate cash in retirement, most are investing in assets, such as
homes and furnishings, that will be worth a great deal after they
die.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, the baby boomers someday will have tens of
trillions of dollars to bequeath to others.
</P>
<P>
   What will happen with all that money? Will it get squandered by
spoiled heirs or put to good purposes? If it is spent well, the
aggregate wealth of the post-war generation could have a huge
impact on American life in the next century.
</P>
<P>
   But that's a big if.
</P>
<P>
   Unless more people start planning now, this immense fortune
could get wasted. Ron Chernow, author of ``Titan,'' a new biography
of John D. Rockefeller Sr., says dispensing money wisely is a
tougher job than most people realize.
</P>
<P>
   Rockefeller, the nation's richest man at the start of the
century, ``spent as much time giving away money as making it,''
Chernow said during a recent book tour in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The billionaire vastly improved life for millions by using his
money to spur the growth of libraries, universities and medical
institutions. Rockefeller's fortune had an enormous impact because
he spent decades teaching himself how to be an effective
benefactor.
</P>
<P>
   Many people assume that ``late in life, to atone for his sins,
Rockefeller suddenly turned to philanthropy,'' Chernow said. In
fact, he consistently gave money to his church starting from
childhood. His charitable work grew along with his wealth. By his
early 40s, he was no longer funding just Baptist activities but was
putting up the money for imaginative projects. For example, at age
43, he funded the creation of Atlanta's Spelman College so the
daughters of former slaves could be turned into schoolteachers.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Rockefeller retired, he was a world-class
philanthropist who knew that ``it takes work and it takes time to
give away money,'' Chernow said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, baby boomers are still focused on earning money and
aren't inclined to think about their own mortality. Drawing up a
will is no one's idea of fun. But time is passing. With the recent
deaths of so many boomer icons _ including ``Buffalo Bob'' and Roy
Rogers _ it's getting harder to pretend the post-war generation can
stay forever young. By getting involved with charities now, boomers
can begin learning how to leave some legacy besides rock 'n' roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are always gigantic needs to be filled,'' Chernow said.
``It's a matter of having the creativity to give away money'' in
ways that go to the roots of society's problems, as Rockefeller did
when he funded libraries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It always surprises me that no one has tried to open programs
to provide drug treatment'' to large numbers of poor people, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the generation that introduced widespread drug use to
American culture could use some of its assets to help undo that
great harm in the next century.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's commentary appears in the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
