<DOCNO> NYT19980810.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 11:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5972 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WALLSTREET-COLUMN11-C     08-10 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALLSTREET-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How to survive on volatile Wall Street
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Mutual fund executive James P. O'Shaughnessy asked a
client a few days back if he was ``nervous about the crash of
1987.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was 11 years ago. Why should I be nervous about it?'' the
puzzled client asked.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, was the point, O'Shaughnessy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eleven years from now, will you care about what happened in
August of 1998?'' he asked. ``Absolutely not.''
</P>
<P>
   The way for investors to get through the kind of stock market
we've had in the last month is to know why they're investing and to
have enough self-discipline to stay the course, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What usually happens is that the market goes down heavily and
then everyone bails out. To me, the greatest risk is that people
will focus on short-term volatility and take their eye off the
ball,'' said O'Shaughnessy, manager of the O'Shaughnessy Funds in
Greenwich, Conn., and author of ``What Works on Wall Street'' and
other investment books.
</P>
<P>
   Bailing out is especially tempting to relative newcomers to the
market, especially when stock averages fall as much as 3.4 percent
in one day, as the Dow Jones industrial average did Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the weekend arrived with some relief as investors followed
up the week's early declines by buying, helping the market recoup
some of its loss. Even so, the Dow lost 285.27 points for the five
days.
</P>
<P>
   It was a repeat, on a much smaller scale, of when the Dow
plunged 554 points last Oct. 27 _ its worst one-day point loss ever
_ only to rally by 30 percent over the next nine months to an
all-time high of 9,337.97 on July 17.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen if the market will take a similar course
over the next nine months.
</P>
<P>
   The October sell-off was triggered by the spread of Asia's
economic crisis, which threatened the profits of U.S. corporations.
Investors worred that Asia would curtail its buying of U.S. goods
and undercut American business by exporting cheaper products to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts believe the threat became a reality in the first
half of 1998 _ especially in the second quarter _ and the resulting
decline in profit growth precipitated the latest selling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recognition of earnings growth this year lower than 4 percent,
and continued downward earnings revisions for next year, are
finally spreading through the marketplace,'' said strategist Rao
Chalasani of Chicago-based Everen Securities.
</P>
<P>
   The bearish argument that stocks have further to fall is based
on the idea the prolonged bull market has pushed stock prices too
high for long-term profit growth to satisfy.
</P>
<P>
   The bullish perspective is based on the continued strength of
the economy, accompanied by benign inflation and falling interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve's forecast calls for gross domestic product
growth of 3.25 percent in 1998 and 2 percent to 2.5 percent in
1999; unemployment of 4.5 percent to 4.75 percent through next
year; and consumer inflation of only 1.75 percent to 2 percent in
1998 and 2 percent to 2.5 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
   There has never been a bear market _ generally defined as a drop
of at least 20 percent from a record level _ under those
conditions, according to the bulls.
</P>
<P>
   One of the factors that weighs on stock market analysis at this
stage of the game is that no other bull market has lasted this
long. That, plus the length of the economic expansion _
third-longest in U.S. history _ has prompted some to refer to this
as a ``new paradigm,'' in which the old rules are no longer in
play.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan has paid at least
guarded respect to this thesis by mentioning it several times in
public appearances.
</P>
<P>
   But he prefers to describe the current market condition as a
``virtuous cycle,'' the term he used in his recent Humphrey-Hawkins
congressional testimony.
</P>
<P>
   In this scenario, the economic conditions that produced the bull
market attract investors in large numbers, whose buying propels the
bull market still higher. The ``wealth effect'' created by the bull
market, meanwhile, encourages investors to spend, which fuels the
economy's growth.
</P>
<P>
   The downside of a virtuous cycle is a ``vicious cycle,'' in
which falling stock prices wipe out wealth, causing investors to
retrench and spend less, which in turn slows the economy, resulting
in a recession and bear market. The slide is exacerbated by the
presence of huge amounts of debt, much of it used to buy stocks,
under this scenario.
</P>
<P>
   So far the downside scenario is just a scenario, and there are
those who consider it unlikely to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Bullish analysts, such as Goldman Sachs strategist Abby Joseph
Cohen, deny that stocks are really as overpriced these days as the
bears contend. Low inflation supports higher valuations, she
argues.
</P>
<P>
   The bullish scenario is that economic strength, low inflation
and lots of baby boom investors will lengthen the bull market well
into the 21st century despite setbacks along the way.
</P>
<P>
   None of this debate may be of much consolation to a nervous
small investor, however, who probably wants most of all to know
what to do.
</P>
<P>
   David A. Lee, senior vice president and research coordinator at
Robinson-Humphrey in Atlanta, says ``three actions are necessary at
this juncture'' for investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``First is a quick check of your current financial objectives,
including an update on goals and risk-taking capacity,'' he said.
``We frequently find that as stock prices move higher, investors
start to increase the risk level in their portfolios.''
</P>
<P>
   They do so by buying riskier stocks and by borrowing to finance
the purchases.
</P>
<P>
   The second step is to begin even now to think about year-end tax
planning, which may guide investor decisions about which stocks or
funds to sell.
</P>
<P>
   The third step is to look for ways to ``protect profits.'' It
requires homework, such as looking for stocks that analysts expect
to perform well in the near future under current circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's periods like this that drive people to focus on the
day-to-day and make very bad choices,'' said O'Shaughnessy. ``We
try to get people to see movements like these as a fact of life.
They have happened many times before and will happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
