<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Borrowing from 401(k) takes careful evaluation
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Here's an alluring idea: The next time you need some
ready cash, borrow it from yourself. As you repay the loan, both
principal and interest will go to you, not to a lender.
</P>
<P>
   That may sound outlandish. But for many workers _ those who have
a 401(k) retirement plan with loan provisions _ it is an
increasingly attractive alternative.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, 28 percent of 401(k) participants had borrowed against
their retirement accounts, according to the Profit Sharing/401(k)
Council of America. Those loans averaged about $5,500.
</P>
<P>
   Other studies suggest the percentage of self-borrowers is slowly
growing, as more Americans accumulate more capital in 401(k) plans.
After all, it's your money. Maybe you really need it now, perhaps
for a down payment on a house.
</P>
<P>
   But is a retirement plan loan a good idea?
</P>
<P>
   Retirement analysts and advisers get edgy when presented with
that question.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not inherently bad,'' said analyst Paul Yakoboski of the
Employee Benefit Research Institute. ``It's an attractive feature
of these plans that gets people into them in the first place. But
you need to do a little calculating to find out what it's going to
cost you.''
</P>
<P>
   Most 401(k) plans have provisions for borrowing against your
balance. The limits and restrictions may vary, and there are some
fine points. In general, federal law allows you to borrow as much
as half of your account balance, to a maximum of $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Your employer's plan will usually list the permitted reasons for
borrowing, such as buying a house, medical emergencies or paying
for the kids' education. You must repay the loan within five years,
though you can take longer if you use the money for a house.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the numbers can get pretty depressing. Suppose you are 25
years old, and you borrow $5,000 and pay it back over five years,
the maximum allowed. If you pay 9.5 percent interest, or one point
above the prime rate, you'll shell out $1,301 in interest. That
goes back into your 401(k) and will continue earning for you.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose instead you left the money in your retirement account,
earning 11.1 percent _ the long-term average for large-company
stocks. In that alternative, all the money would have been working
for you throughout those five years.
</P>
<P>
   If you let those increased earnings compound for another three
decades or more, until you retire, you'll have tens of thousands
more dollars in your nest egg.
</P>
<P>
   There are other problem areas. The main one arises if you leave
your job, said Debra Zipp, a retirement planning specialist with
Waddell &AMP; Reed. Most plans require departing employees to repay an
outstanding balance within 30 to 90 days. If you can't do that, the
balance is considered to be in default. The company will usually
take the balance from your account, meaning you get back that much
less when you settle up.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Zipp said, you will owe income taxes on the unpaid
balance. Unless you are older than 59 1/2, you will owe a 10
percent early withdrawal penalty. Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   The same tax and penalty provisions apply if you stop making
your regular payments on the loan.
</P>
<P>
   Yakoboski worries about another possibility: Since people are
``paying themselves back,'' they will be tempted to reduce their
current contributions until the loan is repaid. The result will be
a considerably smaller retirement nest egg.
</P>
<P>
   There are advantages, of course. It's your own money you are
borrowing against, so you don't have to withstand a credit check.
In most plans, arranging the loan is not very complicated. Most
employers set up payroll deductions, so you can't let a payment
slide by unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   And it's a cheap loan, because the interest comes back to you,
not to a bank or credit card.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, a 401(k)-backed loan may make sense if the loan you
need is a short-term one, and if you can repay it quickly. It might
be a good idea if you use the money to pay off very high-interest
debt, like credit card bills.
</P>
<P>
   It's best to approach the subject with great caution. Remember
why you opened the account in the first place: It's a retirement
plan, not a piggy bank.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-08-07-98 2217E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
