<DOCNO> NYT19980810.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 11:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5977 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRASSROOTS-GAS11-COX     08-10 1926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRASSROOTS-GAS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Grass Roots fuels competition for gas customers
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Deregulation of Georgia's natural gas market doesn't
officially begin until Nov. 1. But don't tell that to Dave Rich,
who represents more than 7,000 Georgia consumers and is ready to
make a deal on their behalf for the best gas price once the market
is opened to competition.
</P>
<P>
   The Alpharetta, Ga. businessman saw an opportunity in late 1996,
when as a utility executive he was tracking the landmark
deregulation law as it moved through the Georgia General Assembly.
While large companies would certainly make out well in a
competitive market, he figured, ``no one really cared about the
small guy.''
</P>
<P>
   So a year ago, Rich left his job as a local wholesale
electricity and gas marketer for Missouri-based Utilicorp and
founded what is apparently a first-of-its-kind venture for the
energy industry: Grass Roots Energy.
</P>
<P>
   Grass Roots will act as a ``buyer's agent'' for thousands of
Georgians when competition in the natural gas industry begins this
fall. Seeing strength in numbers, it plans to negotiate lower rates
with the new marketing companies selling the gas.
</P>
<P>
   Rich plans to do the same for electricity when that industry is
decontrolled.
</P>
<P>
   Grass Roots won't take possession of the gas, bill customers or
read meters. But it will act as sort of a matchmaker between
consumer and marketing company.
</P>
<P>
   It's not actually selling anything, so it isn't bound by the law
requiring marketers to wait until Public Service Commission
certification Oct. 15 before they can start selling gas. Rich sees
room to negotiate ``the lowest rates available'' for his
subscribers and take a profit for him and his investors at the same
time.
</P>
<P>
   Buyer's agents for energy are nothing new. Pittsburgh-based
Strategic Energy Ltd., which represents large commercial and
industrial customers, has been retained by the Atlanta chapter of
the Building Owners and Managers Association to purchase gas for
members' office buildings in metro Atlanta, says Strategic Energy
spokesman Peter Tennis.
</P>
<P>
   But Grass Roots may be the first to enter mass markets for
residential and small-business customers using multilevel
marketing, which has been used to sell Amway products, Mary Kay
cosmetics and long-distance phone service.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is catching fire, at least with the ``independent
marketing representatives'' Rich is signing up. They show up twice
a week at meetings that are part pep rally, part ``Let's Make a
Deal,'' with a little Huey Long thrown in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way to be treated like a big guy is to become the
biggest guy. Come Nov. 1, we will command the lowest prices and
pass those on to the consumer,'' Rich told more than 200 people at
a recent ``opportunity meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   He's been holding the meetings at the Crowne Plaza Ravinia Hotel
at Perimeter Center since March and recently moved the sessions to
a ballroom to accommodate the growing crowds. He hosts smaller
groups at his office on Thursday mornings.
</P>
<P>
   Rich has signed up 1,300 marketing reps who have brought in more
than 7,500 signed contracts with consumers. They go door-to-door,
or work by phone.
</P>
<P>
   Grass Roots pays the marketing reps $10 for every signed
contract they bring in, plus additional commissions and bonuses of
up to $30 per contract.
</P>
<P>
   With funding from private investors, Rich's prepared to spend up
to $4 million to get started, then move into other states as
deregulation spreads.
</P>
<P>
   By signing the contract, consumers authorize Grass Roots to
negotiate on their behalf for ``lower rates for natural gas and/or
electricity than I am currently paying.'' The contract is for one
year and authorizes the company to obtain billing histories from
Atlanta Gas Light Co., which will ultimately exit the gas sales
business when the industry is fully deregulated. The contracts are
automatically renewed for one-year terms, unless terminated by
either party.
</P>
<P>
   Rich acknowledges the contract will be difficult, if not
impossible, to enforce if a consumer decides to seek gas service
elsewhere. He estimates an attrition rate of up to 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But he says he will have between 25,000 and 35,000 contracts in
hand by Nov. 1 and is shooting for 50,000 by the end of the year.
He says that would make Grass Roots customers collectively the
largest buyer of natural gas in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   One Grass Roots contract is with Kansas-based Applebee's
International and covers the restaurant chain's seven
corporate-owned Applebee's Neighborhood Grill &AMP; Bar and 10 Rio
Bravo restaurants in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Energy is a huge expense for us,'' says William Kampbell,
national energy buyer for Applebee's. Gas grills boost monthly gas
charges to $2,500 for each of the restaurants, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Rich is confident marketers will want to make a deal to, in
effect, ``rent'' his customer list.
</P>
<P>
   ``For someone who will be able to deliver 50,000 customers, they
(marketers) will bleed all over the floor,'' he says confidently
during an interview in his Duluth office.
</P>
<P>
   Rich says he's talked with most of the 28 companies that have
applied to market gas in the first phase of deregulation this fall
and has ``gotten indications of interest from a large number'' of
them.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Carter, director of sales and marketing at Utilicorp
Energy Solutions, which has applied for certification to sell gas
in Georgia, says the Kansas City, Mo., company is ``interested in
what they have to offer.'' Carter says his company ``definitely
could offer a better rate'' to Grass Roots, if Rich signs up enough
customers to make it worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   But other marketing companies say they're not interested.
</P>
<P>
   Some are leery of what one top executive called the
``looseness'' of Rich's sales force and prefer to sign up their own
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Others regard Rich as a competitor who is using a loophole in
the deregulation law to sign up customers before they can, then
charge too much for his customer list.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Dawson, vice president/general manager at Columbia Energy
Services Corp., recently told Rich his proposition would not work
for the marketing affiliate of Columbia Gas of Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't make it work so he would be able to make money and
we'd have enough to cover our expenses and go after the next round
of customers,'' Dawson says.
</P>
<P>
   Warren Darby, senior vice president of South Carolina-based
SCANA Energy who also has spoken with Rich, says SCANA would not
offer a ``special price'' to Grass Roots subscribers lower than
what it would offer to other customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've heard through the grapevine that a number of them
(marketers) do not want to see us in business,'' Rich says. ``We
have driven the cost down.''
</P>
<P>
   Rich, 43, says the main thing he has to offer companies is the
prospect of acquiring a huge bloc of customers without incurring
marketing expenses. He says $100 is a reasonable estimate of what
it would cost companies to acquire each new customer, given direct
mail, advertising and other expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Grass Roots is ``not looking for anywhere near that'' to sign
over a customer, Rich says. But he added he needs to charge at
least the $40 he ends up paying for each signed one-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   Clifton Payne, vice president of Atlanta Gas Light Services,
says the marketing affiliate of Atlanta Gas Light Co. ``will look
to acquire customers for substantially less'' than $100 each.
SCANA's Darby puts the cost at $50 per customer.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Gas Light Co. says average residential bills will run
$627 a year for consumers who stick with the utility during the
transition to deregulation. Rivals will already need to beat that
cost to be competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Latham, president of Optimum Energy Sources, says she
projects profits of $12 a year per customer and can't see where
there's room to pay a middleman like Rich.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe there's some magic formula we haven't figured out,''
says Latham, who has also talked to Rich.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Rich is paying out money, not collecting it.
</P>
<P>
   He writes checks to his marketing reps monthly, based on the
number of signed contracts they deliver. This Friday, he says he'll
pay out $150,000 for July's contracts. Including that amount, Rich
says he will have paid marketing reps $240,000 for signed contracts
and collected $60,000 for marketing materials he sells them at
cost.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of commissions are in the $100 range, says
Rich, who added he wrote one check for one month's work for $5,000
to one rep.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll put out a challenge,'' Rich told marketing reps at a
recent meeting. ``You folks make me run out of money.''
</P>
<P>
   In all, Rich says he's spent more than $400,000 to launch the
business and is deferring his own salary until gas sales begin. He
says the money is coming from seven outside investors whom he
declines to identify. But he says they are not ``hidden investors''
from the energy industry and more than happy to pay for more
subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   The 20-year utility and financial services industry veteran says
he had no prior experience with multilevel marketing. The sales
technique ``has a terrible connotation,'' he tells his marketing
reps. ``It has earned it and it deserves it.''
</P>
<P>
   He cautions the reps against ``slamming,'' or illegally
switching suppliers without consumers' permission and makes it
clear recent gas bills must accompany contracts to qualify for
payment.
</P>
<P>
   PSC spokesman Shawn Davis says brokers like Grass Roots ``can be
a healthy part of competition'' so long as ``consumers are not
misled, are not 'slammed' and are not locked into a contract that
denies them the benefits of competition.''
</P>
<P>
   But there have been some apparently minor lapses by Rich's sales
force:
</P>
<P>
   _ In June, the Office of Consumer Affairs told Grass Roots to
``cease and desist'' after a sales representative circulated a
flier falsely claiming the company ``has the approval'' of the PSC.
</P>
<P>
   _ In July, Rich terminated agreements with three sales reps
after they were accused by the commission of using ``scare
tactics'' in unauthorized fliers that claimed Atlanta Gas Light
would stop selling gas altogether on Nov. 1. In fact, the company
will continue selling gas during a transition period. Afterward, it
will become a distribution company only.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the marketing reps have prior experience with part-time
marketing ventures. Some are government employees or work in
doctors' offices. Others are raising money for schools or churches.
</P>
<P>
   Fred DeVaughn is a College Park bank auditor and president of
the Band Boosters Club at Tri-Cities High School in East Point.
He's gearing up as soon as school starts Aug. 24 to sign up parents
as Grass Roots subscribers as part of a drive to raise $130,000 to
send the school's band to perform in London on Jan. 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this is the wave of the future, I'm impressed,'' he said
after attending one of Rich's meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Juanita White, 53, a Georgia state employee, heard about Grass
Roots at a church dinner and is going door-to-door in her
neighborhood to raise money to help with expenses of a liver
transplant. She says she's made more than $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knock on the door and say, 'Do you know about natural gas
deregulation?''' White says. ``They look at you funny. Nobody knows
about it.'' But, she says, ``I sign up almost everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthew C. Quinn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
