</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSURANCE-PREMIUMS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A dent in insurance costs
 &HT;    (EDS: Runs with INSURANCE-SHOPPING11-COX.)
 &HT;    By Gene Tharpe
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ State Farm's announcement last month of a 2.6 percent
reduction in auto premiums for Georgia policyholders, totaling $21
million, was the 15th decrease by insurers this year in the state.
The other reductions totaled about $9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Not counting occasional payments of dividends to policyholders _
including $14.4 million in June _ State Farm's last rate decrease
in Georgia was 1991, which it attributed to the demise that year of
no-fault insurance.
</P>
<P>
   State Farm, Georgia's largest auto insurer, with 1.4 million
policyholders, joins a growing list of insurers nationwide that are
cutting premiums. As reasons, they cite competition, along with
better-built cars and older drivers who are driving more carefully,
resulting in lower claims and medical costs.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of what it costs to insure a car in Georgia, the
average annual expenditure for auto insurance was $627.47 in 1996,
latest data available, the 25th highest in the nation _ placing
Georgia right in the middle of the 50 states. New Jersey has the
highest average costs, $1,100. The cheapest is Iowa at $445.39
annually.
</P>
<P>
   And even lower premiums are expected, in Georgia and nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The $30 million premium decrease in Georgia so far this year is
less than 1 percent of the more than $3 billion in auto premiums
written annually in the state, but Georgia Insurance Commissioner
John Oxendine promises more is coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Auto insurance will be cheaper in Georgia next year than it is
this year,'' he said. The Insurance Information Institute, a
national group, has predicted the average cost of auto insurance
nationwide will decline about 1 percent this year, and hold steady
or decline slightly in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Hunter, director of insurance for the Consumer Federation
of America, thinks rate deceases should be considerably greater.
``Given the companies' profits, rates should fall 5 percent to 10
percent nationally,'' he said. ``I expect to see continued
reductions for at least the next two or three years.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, the last full year of no-fault here, the average
expenditure for auto insurance in Georgia was $544.96, or 20th
highest among the 50 U.S. states, according to the National
Association of Insurance Commissioners. The General Assembly voted
to dump no-fault in 1991 and to return to traditional auto
insurance, with prior approval by the insurance commissioner
required for rate increases. The vote also required insurers to
reduce the premium for bodily-injury liability insurance by 15
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Ryles, when running for Georgia insurance commissioner in
1990, promised to cut auto insurance bills ``no ifs, no ands, no
buts.'' He was elected, and during the next four years, denied 176
requests by insurers for premium increases _ every request
presented to him by auto insurers.
</P>
<P>
   By 1992, Ryles' second year in office, the average had fallen to
this decade's low point of $514.47, the 29th highest in the nation.
In addition to Ryles' freeze on premium increases, the decline was
also due in part to the demise of no-fault insurance, which was
more expensive than traditional coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Oxendine, when running against Ryles in 1994, said he would
study each rate boost request for auto insurance and say yes or no,
depending on the facts. Oxendine won _ and has approved 101
increases during his term to date, about two-thirds of the increase
requests presented to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``From talking with some insurers, I get the impression they
felt they had some `catching up' to do after four years of no
increases,'' said David Colmans, executive director of the Georgia
Insurance Information Service, a trade group.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Georgia's ranking nationwide in terms of average cost for
auto insurance is virtually unchanged. In 1991, Ryles' first year
in office, Georgia ranked 23rd. In 1996, the year for which latest
data are available and Oxendine's second year in office, Georgia
ranked 25th.
</P>
<P>
   For Oxendine, this year's premium decreases in Georgia come at a
fortunate time. He's running for re-election in November, and the
commissioner/
</P>
<P>
   candidate is happily announcing the rate cuts.
</P>
<P>
   If Oxendine, 35, is elected to a second term, he will be ruling
on auto rate requests for the next four years. He has raised more
than $1.1 million for the campaign, many times more than his
Democratic opposition, former state Rep. Henrietta Canty, 69.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the $1.1 million was contributed in $1,000 donations
from individuals employed in the industries Oxendine regulates, and
they are invited to attend quarterly round-table meetings _ usually
breakfasts _ at private clubs. In addition to insurance
commissioner, Oxendine is state fire marshal and regulates small
loan companies.
</P>
<P>
   Oxendine has said such contributions don't affect his rate
decisions, but Hunter _ a former Texas insurance commissioner _ is
quick to condemn the practice. ``It's not good at all, very bad in
my opinion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing illegal, however, about such fund-raising, and
previous Georgia insurance commissioners have funded their
re-election campaigns in such ways. Ryles raised more than $1
million in his 1994 campaign, much of it from industry employees,
despite his wholesale denial of auto rate increases.
</P>
<P>
   In June, the State Ethics Committee fined Oxendine $500 for
accepting one improper donation. But his supporters point out the
committee ruled in 1993 that Ryles also had accepted a prohibited
donation.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Tharpe writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
