</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSURANCE-SHOPPING11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Do some shopping around for insurance
 &HT;    (EDS: May run with INSURANCE-PREMIUMS11-COX.)
 &HT;    By Gene Tharpe
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia drivers paid an average of $627.47 for auto
insurance coverage in 1996, the latest data available _ an average
for all drivers, all cars, all locations. But many drivers paid far
more.
</P>
<P>
   That happened for several reasons, including one often
overlooked: They failed to shop around.
</P>
<P>
   Auto insurance companies are not all the same. Some concentrate
on drivers with safe records. Others concentrate on higher-risk
drivers. Some take on nearly all comers. And that means they don't
quote the same price for the same coverage. In fact, the price for
the same coverage for the same driver can vary dramatically from
firm to firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Insurers generally target specific categories of drivers and
price their policies competitively for them, while charging
less-than-competitive rates for others,'' said Tom Blum, manager of
Consumer Reports' auto insurance price service.
</P>
<P>
   Auto insurers, however, use much the same criteria in quoting
rates: The driver's age, sex, marital status and driving record;
the year, make and model of car insured; the car's annual mileage
and its use, such as commuting or personal use; the driver's
residence; theft rates in the area; and frequency and severity of
accidents and claims in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Some factors that affect price are beyond your control, at least
to a degree. For example, if you live in Atlanta, you will pay more
_ probably substantially more _ for the same coverage than if you
live in a town in South Georgia. Where you live is very important,
and sometimes even a small change will make a huge difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some years ago, I moved three miles from the border of an
urban territory into a suburban territory, and my auto insurance
rates fell 50 percent with no other change in my driver's
profile,'' said Blum.
</P>
<P>
   To get a full picture of your choices, contact several big
companies that sell through their own exclusive agents, several
insurance brokers who represent a mix of independent insurers that
don't have their own agents, and several ``direct writers'' _
insurers who sell policies directly to the public over the
telephone.
</P>
<P>
   If you call enough insurers, you will find great differences in
quotes. The Consumer Reports' price service checked insurers'
quotes for a ``typical'' married couple in their mid-40s, with a
17-year-old son, living in a suburban area of northwest Atlanta,
with three autos and clean driving records. The service found
annual quotes that ranged from $2,875 to $6,590, for a policy with
$100,000/$300,000 bodily injury liability, $50,000 property
liability, and collision and comprehensive coverage with $500
deductibles.
</P>
<P>
   Shop around and, unless you have a terrible driving record, you
should get at least two or three quotes from insurers that want
your business and will offer the coverage you want at competitive
prices. But in comparing two or more offers, be sure you are
comparing ``similar'' companies and the same type of coverage.
</P>
<P>
   CHART: HOW TO SAVE MONEY ON AUTO INSURANCE
</P>
<P>
   When shopping for auto insurance, these are some ways to keep
your costs down:
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't insure against every nick and scratch. Collision is
often the highest premium you pay, and the bigger the collision
deductible you are willing to accept, the cheaper your coverage
will be. The same is generally true of comprehensive coverage, but
don't scrimp on liability coverage, which protects you from
lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ask for discounts, which can amount to substantial savings.
But many times, if you don't ask, you don't get.
</P>
<P>
   _ Buy a car that costs less to insure. Expensive,
high-performance cars may be fun to drive, but they are expensive
to repair and therefore expensive to insure. Whatever the price of
the car, equip it with safety and anti-theft devices and you will
pay lower auto insurance.
</P>
<P>
   _ There are several things you or family members can do that
will result in lower premiums from some insurers. They include
passing a defensive-driving course, not smoking, being more than 50
years old, driving for three years without an accident and making
good grades in school.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Tharpe writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
