<HEADER>
A5983 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-REPORT11-COX     08-10 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-REPORT11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Portable sound systems gain respect
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Those of us who traipsed off to college those many
years ago toting a stereo-in-a-box remember the feeling:
inadequacy.
</P>
<P>
   Components spoke of seriousness about sound, of
blow-down-the-doors audio power and money. But portable stereos
that contained a tape deck, radio tuner and turntable that you
folded up and carried under an arm? That spoke of ... well, it
spoke of a limited budget.
</P>
<P>
   Oh sure, it was nice to have some kind of sound system, and it
did squeeze nicely into the back of the Chevy. But down the hall
was at least one dorm-mate whose stereo speakers had the heft of
the Chevy itself and whose amplifier was capable of lethal doses at
100 meters. Size might not be everything, but come on.
</P>
<P>
   Fold-'em-up stereos were always a discount alternative.
</P>
<P>
   And yet lately, the science of audio has nudged us closer to a
world in which convenient packaging can compete with components. We
have wireless phones that slip into your pocket, and we have
all-in-one stereo systems that claim to compete with the Big Sound.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most aggressive makers has been Bose Corp., whose
marketing is built around the notion potent and accurate sound can
come roaring out of small speakers. A decade ago, Bose pioneered
``The Wave,'' a portable system the company dared to match against
component systems.
</P>
<P>
   Now Marantz America offers its own entry. The package, brags
Marantz, ``makes no apologies to conventional expectations of what
a stereo system should look like.'' The MR2020 is scheduled to be
in the stores this month at a suggested retail price of $1,000.
This system, boasts Marantz, ``establishes a dramatic new esthetic
in fully integrated music systems.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it's pretty good for a portable.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, dial up the Marantz site on the Web
(http://www.marantzamerica.com) or call the company (708-307-2687).
</P>
<P>
   Can't keep it all
</P>
<P>
   Computers seemed at first like the answer to a pack rat's
prayer. Or a historian's.
</P>
<P>
   When you can't decide which sticky yellow notes to keep and
which ones to chuck, well, you understand. There's only so much
room, and some of that stuff really has to go.
</P>
<P>
   But when you have documents by the dozen in your computer, you
figure you can save them all -- or what's a digital memory for? It
may turn out that saving everything is neither easy nor cheap. And
maybe it's not right, either.
</P>
<P>
   Deanna B. Marcum, president of the Council on Library and
Information Resources, wrote recently that when you start talking
about millions of pages and files, the preservation of data for
years and decades is a huge financial investment. It not only fills
the hardware with bits and bytes, it commits the data to software
that might soon be obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in The New York Times, Marcum said the real point is not
expense, anyway. Collections through history have been shaped by
the critical judgment of people who did more than just hit the
``save'' button, she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Librarians and archivists know that a good collection, like a
good book, is made in the editing,'' Marcum writes.
</P>
<P>
   Fax by Net
</P>
<P>
   Makers of gadgets are increasingly looking for ways to use the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Among the newest Net-friendly tools is the Panasonic KX-FP26OM,
a fax machine that includes a copier, speakerphone, printer and
scanner. According to Popular Mechanics magazine, the Panasonic
lets you send a fax anywhere via the Net, saving long-distance
phone charges.
</P>
<P>
   Panasonic says the machine will be available in September for
$279.95.
</P>
<P>
   For information, contact Panasonic (1-800-222-4213).
</P>
<P>
   How're we doin'?
</P>
<P>
   Unlike baseball, business doesn't always provide a scoreboard to
let you know how you are doing.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have benchmarks and goals, and if you can't measure
your progress as a business against where you have been and where
you want to be, then how do you really know where you are? Now, if
all this sounds somewhat New Age, then consider there is software
from various manufacturers that is aimed at letting businesses find
out if they are meeting expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Among the current offerings recommended by Windows Magazine in
its summer issue (http://www.winmag.com) is Business Plan Pro 2.0
from Palo Alto Software and Plan Write for Business 4.0 from
Business Resources Software.
</P>
<P>
   Business Plan Pro, which costs $100, provides a 16-step,
interactive guide that lets you check your numbers against your
original forecast. If you don't like what you see, you can also
concoct a new plan. For more information, call Palo Alto Software
(1-800-229-7526).
</P>
<P>
   Plan Write guides you through creation of business objectives,
product descriptions and customer profiles. It gives you charts for
break-even, cash flow and profit and loss. The software costs $130.
For more information, contact Business Resources Software by phone
(1-800-423-1228 or 512-251-7541).
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
