A5985 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECHNOBUDDY-COLUMN11-     08-10 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Time for a day's break from all-intrusive technology
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I am here today to propose a new national holiday. I
don't think it'll be as much fun as Christmas, or as important as
Mother's Day, but I'm pretty sure it will catch on.
</P>
<P>
   I propose we have a National Low Tech Day. Instead of writing
e-mail to a friend, send them a letter or visit them. Balance your
checkbook by hand. Leave your cellular telephone at home. I'm
suggesting we start right now. Let's make today, the day you read
this column, the first annual observance.
</P>
<P>
   Here's my bet. Instead of finding that your day is more crowded,
you'll have some leisure time for a change. I know computers and
such-like are supposed to make our lives easier. But if computers
and technology continue to make things easier, I'm going to quit my
job and join the Marines.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere along the line I've lost my sweetly naive belief in
the supposition that all this high-tech stuff makes me more
productive and leaves me with more time for leisure. You'd think
I'd be in the catbird seat as far as reaping the benefits of
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Because of my job writing about technology, I have more
electronic and computer gear in my home than the average Navy
destroyer. And when I sit down at my desk at work, I stare at two
computers _ a top-of-the-line Macintosh G3 and a super-fast Pentium
II PC _ that sit close together like two buzzards after a good day
for road kill. At work I stay logged on to the Internet using a T1
line that offers a high-speed connection. I'm well connected at
home, too.
</P>
<P>
   I have computer programs to help me cook a meal, figure my
finances, select a wine, plan a wedding, sue a creditor, buy a
house, build a house, learn to oil paint, figure out why I'm so
neurotic, tell my fortune, discover a new career, do my horoscope,
create my family tree, build a deck and learn to play bridge.
</P>
<P>
   I have a dishwasher with more computer power than the original
Univac; my car has a computer, and so does the exercise bike that I
use, and my cat plays with computerized toys.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever a new gadget hits the market, it's likely that the
manufacturer sends one to the newspaper for us to try. I spend more
on batteries than the average guy.
</P>
<P>
   But _ with all this computing power and gadgetry _ I have no
time at all. In fact, half the time my gadgets and computers
conspire to steal time from me. This morning, I spent an hour
trying to get the office's new e-mail program to work; last week my
car had to have a computer module replaced, so that meant a long
evening at the repair shop. We use a telephone system so
complicated that everyone here had to take a training class just to
be able to use it. I've seen grown men get quivery at the notion of
trying to use our copying machine.
</P>
<P>
   If the computer gurus here at the newspaper upgrade the word
processing system one more time, I'm pretty sure it'll stop working
altogether. And our new high-tech elevators went online here about
two months ago. The day after they went into service, I was trapped
in one for an hour and a half.
</P>
<P>
   That's why I'm ready to celebrate Low Tech Day. I think most of
us need a day when we escape from these electronic servants that
have _ somehow _ become our masters.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not advocating a return to the Dark Ages, but just a day
where we stop and think about how technology often uses us, instead
of us it.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's time to celebrate. So get out your hammock and a good
paperback book. And plug yourself into a lazy day.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Husted writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
