A5982 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMMEUS-EUCHARIST-KAN     08-10 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-EUCHARIST-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTIANITY'S DIVISIONS ARE AS DEEP AS EVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1998 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I never like to learn I was right about something I wish weren't
true. But in the case at hand, the road toward that discovery was
so fascinating that it was almost worth the sad news. Here's what
happened: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Bill Clinton visited South Africa this spring, he attended
Mass at Soweto's Regina Mundi Roman Catholic Church. The priest,
under the false impression that South Africa's bishops had changed
policies and now allowed non-Catholics to receive Communion, passed
that on to the White House advance team in writing. So the
president, a Southern Baptist who regularly attends a United
Methodist Church in Washington, participated in the Eucharist. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, there was an outcry. And an outcry about the outcry.
The Catholic position, after all, is ``transubstantiation,''
meaning the bread and wine used in this re-enactment of Jesus' Last
Supper become Christ's actual body and blood in all but appearance.
The Protestant belief is less literal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I wrote a column about the controversy, bemoaning the rifts in
Christianity from my perspective as an elder in a Presbyterian
church. It ran in not only in my paper, The Kansas City Star, but
also in several other papers around the country because the New
York Times News Service syndicates my work. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately I began receiving e-mail from readers. Some
praised the column. Some thought it theologically ignorant. Some
just wanted to berate Clinton for many sins. Others wished to
educate me about Catholicism. (One nice Cincinnati grandmother
phoned to invite me to join her Catholic church.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail was so fascinating I kept copies of it, without quite
knowing why. Some samples:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Like your poster boy Bill Clinton, you are dead wrong on so
much. . . There is nothing wrong with Christian churches sharing
simple, common things together. . .but you and your kind are asking
that basic tenets of my faith be changed to accommodate yours. It's
like coming to my house this evening and expecting to be fed supper
without being in my family or even invited, and then complaining
about how and what we cook. Get real.'' _ A Roman Catholic. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``It has been one of my greatest pains of faith that, even at
my brother's funeral Mass, following his death at the hands of a
drunk driver when he was 30, I was still denied the sacrament.'' _
A United Methodist pastor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Clinton claims to be a Christian. . .It is clear he has
never known Jesus.'' _ A Protestant. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``. . .I am still astounded at how controversial and difficult
even small steps toward unity can be.'' _ A Presbyterian pastor.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The divisions between the various branches of the Christian
faith are a scandal.'' _ A United Church of Christ pastor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I appreciate what you were trying to do, but frankly you
have it pretty much all wrong. . .To be sure, Christendom is
divided into literally thousands of sects. But this is not the
fault of the Catholic Church but, rather, of the revolutionaries
that tried to rip it apart. There is no `broad umbrella of
Christianity.' There is only the church that Jesus founded and
those denominations that are in revolt against it.'' _ A convert to
Catholicism. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``For anyone to receive Holy Communion in a Catholic ceremony
without believing in transubstantiation is in essence demeaning
this sacrament.'' _ A Catholic. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On and on it went, in some ways proving my column's point that
Christianity's sad divisions won't be healed before history ends.
When the volume of the response began to exceed almost anything I
had experienced in more than 20 years of writing a newspaper
column, it occurred to me that it might be wonderful if all of the
people talking just to me could talk to each other. I'm no
technology genius, but I know how to create an e-mail message to
send to dozens of people at once. So I sent a note inviting them to
participate in this discussion by first responding to the official
Catholic rules on taking the Lord's Supper. We began there but then
roamed widely. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The debate became, in some ways, an intra-Catholic fight.
Transubstantiation hard-liners wanted to keep non-Catholics from
receiving the Eucharist. Other Catholics sought a different
formulation that might lead to common ground. But it's ground we
never found. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The discussion now has almost stopped, but it lasted several
months. There was some deeply personal sharing but also some
nastiness. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I like to think everyone learned something, but when it was over
the main result was that one man in California announced he'd
decided to return to church. My naive dream of reaching a position
all of us could buy, however, remained unfulfilled. Our talk proved
only that Christianty continues to be intractably divided. And that
is both its great sadness and its shame. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
