<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINORITY-TECH11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Classes help minorities bridge technology gap
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Bobby Smith's son, Brico, suggested he try an
evening computer class, he hesitated. After all, he used a computer
at work and wondered what more there was to learn. He took the
plunge anyway, and that's how Brico, Smith and his wife all signed
up for Derrick Brown's class at Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Using the computer just at work, I did not realize all the
things you can do with the Internet and in other ways that are such
fun,'' Smith said. ``I am glad I did it, and now I tell everybody
to try it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Smith family of Decatur, Ga. happens to be African-American,
and their experience underlines the findings in studies that blacks
are often involved less in the computer age than the population at
large. Often, however, encouragement and opportunity can fire their
enthusiasm about computers.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, trained as an electrical engineer, has devoted himself to
teaching others about computers, and this year he has conducted a
summer-long workshop, with twice-a-day sessions. Using space in the
Tech student center donated by the school, and employing equipment
donated by industry, he has attracted some 75 people, including
youngsters and adults.
</P>
<P>
   The material covered has been broad, including familiarization
with the equipment, uses of Windows software, connection with the
Internet and even trouble-shooting so students get deeper
understanding of the equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The classes are pleasantly informal, and Brown _ who received a
master's degree in electrical engineering from Georgia Tech in 1994
_ banters easily with his students.
</P>
<P>
   ``The students have learned, but we have learned plenty, too,''
said Brown. ``We have found that though everybody wants to learn,
they do so at very different speeds, and so we will need to
separate kids, young adults and seniors.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, however, ``I am more determined than ever to continue
to update and refine the program, and get more equipment, to make
the program work ideally.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, through a nonprofit firm he organized called
KnowledgeBase Inc., has spent much of his time in recent years
developing plans for teaching computers and information technology
in metro Atlanta. He has also been an organizer and leader of the
Black Graduate Student Association at Georgia Tech. Although the
summer program in computer literacy concludes Sept. 15, Brown said
he is in the process of planning further studies that may be
available in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I continue to believe that learning computers and more about
technology is important to everybody because it is empowering to
communities and individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech, through its community outreach program, also
coordinates and helps sponsor classes at two of Atlanta's largest
public housing communities _ Red Oak and Boatrock.
</P>
<P>
   Those programs started off at a gallop two years ago, but have
slowed lately, said Teressa Warfield-Francis, the program
coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started with good initial interest,'' she said. ``But
lately we have faced a challenge in getting people to understand
the connection between computer literacy and their future. We have
found that people either have an interest, which grows, or they
have little interest at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Trish Millines of Seattle knows a thing or two about the
problems and challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Millines retired from Microsoft in 1996 as a software developer
to devote her dollars and time to teaching computer literacy in
inner city Seattle. She established a nonprofit organization called
Technology Access Foundation to train youngsters in computers,
instill a love of learning and then reward them with internships in
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has gone well after our first full year of the program,''
she said. ``But there is always a challenge in impressing on
youngsters the importance of the concept we are developing _ that
computer literacy and the accompanying increase in skill and
self-esteem _ are absolutely essential to their future.''
</P>
<P>
   Continuing, she said, ``There is a tremendous amount of work to
be done to close the gap between the technological haves and
have-nots.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the challenges, said Brown, is to find equipment to keep
up with the skills and expectations of the students, especially the
youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like kids everywhere and in every walk of life, they love
speed,'' said Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``And no sooner than they learn the elementary points, they want
to surf the Internet faster.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as we all do.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Holsendolph writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
