<SLUG> BC-TECHTOOLS-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Visual Page program solid tool for editing, creating Web sites
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Symantec's new Visual Page seems primed to give
Microsoft's Front Page some stiff competition in the niche for Web
page creation programs aimed at the casual user.
</P>
<P>
   Visual Page is a fairly straightforward tool for setting up Web
pages with or without frames. The greatest problem I found was with
its documentation, which wastes the entire ``Getting Started''
booklet showing you how to edit and improve an existing Web site.
</P>
<P>
   If for whatever reason you want to switch HTML editors or go
from one of the competing what-you-see-is-what-you-get programs,
this is certainly a splendid feature. But how many people who buy
this product are going to have an existing Web site they want to
edit?
</P>
<P>
   They are going to want to start from scratch, I should think.
All, however, is not lost, since the ``User Guide'' provides plenty
of information on creating a page from the ground up.
</P>
<P>
   Visual Page includes a special edition of Symantec's WebPainter,
a program intended for creating banners and art for your site. It
is, however, so obtuse all I managed to do was continually cause it
to lock up. Of course, there's always the possibility that I'm
obtuse, too.
</P>
<P>
   Pages are created simply by typing and bringing in objects _
lines, bullets and images _ in a very straightforward manner.
</P>
<P>
   Setting up hyperlinks works somewhat differently than Front
Page. In Front Page, when you want to set up a link to another page
within the site, you are given the option of creating that linked
page at once if it doesn't already exist. In Visual Page, the page
to be linked to has to be already available _ not finished, but at
least started.
</P>
<P>
   You can view each page in your browser _ Netscape or Explorer _
as you work, a very nice way of checking up on how things are
looking. As a matter of fact, if you have both of them installed,
you can check the appearance in both.
</P>
<P>
   Like some page design programs, you can create layers, and lines
and spaces can be adjusted in small increments with the cursor
keys, a very nice feature.
</P>
<P>
   You can, of course, create text in Visual Page, and there's a
spell-checker in the program. On the other hand, you can import
text from your word processor in the same way you would import
graphics. Text, incidentally, can be flowed around an image just as
it can be done in a page layout program.
</P>
<P>
   Cascading style sheets and font family management are available
to help keep some continuity in a page. Links can be automatically
checked and updated to keep your site current.
</P>
<P>
   For those who wish to work in HTML code, there is a color-coded
syntax editor, but I should think a real coder would be embarrassed
to use such a tool.
</P>
<P>
   I believe that when winter arrives and I have more time at my
disposal, I shall create a new personal Web page, and unless
something better comes along I'll do it in Visual Page.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Warner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
