<HEADER>
A5991 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOUGH-UNIONS11-COX     08-10 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOUGH-UNIONS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Unions get combative as economy soars
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Corporate America, get ready to rumble.
</P>
<P>
   More confrontations between management and workers are likely if
the economy remains healthy and worker shortages continue.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's prosperity and record corporate profits are
producing gutsier workers. This summer's high-profile strike at
General Motors may be just the beginning of growing confrontation
from workers who held their tongues during the lean times. Despite
vastly improved corporate financial performance, annual pay raises
for the average worker have stayed at about 4 percent. Union wage
boosts have been about 2 percent to 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``CEOs are making and getting raises that blow your mind,'' said
Richard Ray, secretary-treasurer of Georgia AFL-CIO, an umbrella
group representing about 300,000 workers in about 1,000 locals.
About 11 percent of Georgia's workers belong to unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want what we have earned in our workplaces,'' said Ray.
``And for those who have not had the opportunity to be union
members, they're saying, `We want a union in our workplace so that
we can protect ourselves.'''
</P>
<P>
   The same issues that prompted a walkout of the GM workers _ pay,
work rules and job security _ seem to embody the unfolding clash
between workers and management elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, many workers who once meekly accepted whatever
companies gave them are forming unions _ or picket lines _ to get
what they want. Even workers who don't belong to unions feel more
confident about their worth these days, and companies are offering
generous perks to recruit and retain them. Job-hopping is rampant.
</P>
<P>
   Prosperity has turned out to be the much-needed bargaining chip
for organized labor, which seems ill-prepared to make the
transition from an industrialized economy to a business world
increasingly characterized by high technology and global
investment. Union membership has fallen from a peak of about 24
percent of the nation's work force in the 1970s to about 15 percent
today.
</P>
<P>
   No one is predicting unions will regain the power they had in
the 1970s, but organizing and other union activity is up. Just
about every major union _ from the Teamsters to the Communications
Workers of America to the United Auto Workers _ is at the
bargaining table negotiating important contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expectations at the bargaining table have been raised,''
said Jeff Mintz, Atlanta-based partner in the law firm of Jackson
Lewis Schnitzler &AMP; Krupman, which represents management in labor
disputes and has increasingly been called on to give talks on labor
relations and averting strikes. ``We have seen an increase in
organizing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately (for us), business is quite good,'' said Mintz.
``If things don't work at the current place of employment, they
(workers) have many more options today than they had in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Or as electrician Ben E. Myers Jr., a union member, puts it:
``Most workers feel this is the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Myers, a member of the International Brotherhood of Electrical
Workers Local 613 in Atlanta, said: ``Times are very good. Profits
are up, our productivity has gone through the roof. We've taken
concessions in the past, and it's time now to get our living wage
up to a higher standard.''
</P>
<P>
   If recent weeks are any indication, labor-management showdowns
are far from over. Tension is growing across the board.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy turbulence is threatening several of the nation's airline
carriers. On Thursday, talks broke off between AirTran and its
flight attendants, and the union representing them plans a series
of selective strikes around Labor Day. They want their pay brought
in line with the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Northwest, the nation's No. 4 carrier, is at odds
with four of its five employee unions. The pilots are set to walk
at the end of the month if talks disintegrate further, possibly
creating major disruptions in air travel for the public. Machinists
said no to a proposed contract last week and gave union leaders the
go-ahead to strike if further talks fail. And flight attendants
who've been trying to get a new contract staged a series of rallies
around the country late last week in protest.
</P>
<P>
   Little progress has been made since workers at Anheuser-Busch,
which has 520 workers at its Cartersville, Ga. brewery, rejected a
pact in July, the second time in three months. Workers gave union
leaders the go-ahead to strike if a suitable pact couldn't be
reached.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Coca-Cola Enterprises narrowly averted a strike
last week, reaching an agreement with workers at four Toronto
plants.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth, one of Georgia's largest employers, resolved
down-to-the-wire talks, avoiding its first strike since the Baby
Bell was created from the 1984 AT&AMP;T divestiture.
</P>
<P>
   The strikes at United Parcel Service last year and General
Motors this summer were costly. GM alone lost more than $2 billion
in profits. Teamsters are pushing for a contract for about 4,000
workers at Overnite Transportation, the largest nonunion trucking
firm. Workers at Overnite in Atlanta and other cities recently
staged a one-day strike in support.
</P>
<P>
   For many workers, job security is a bigger issue than pay.
Companies are doing well, but workers don't have confidence their
jobs will be there for them long-term.
</P>
<P>
   For companies, the old work rules carved out by unions in the
past don't apply in a global economy that runs on turn-on-a-dime
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies are recognizing that in order to survive they need
more flexibility in who they hire, how they work, when they work
and in what positions, and that flexibility flies in the face ...
of union practices and traditional union agreements,'' says Carol
D'Amico, senior researcher at Hudson Institute, a public policy
research group in Indianapolis. ``Workers aren't going to be doing
the same job every day or every hour in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Such strategic shifts have created the current stalemate between
labor and management.
</P>
<P>
   The healthy economy may give unions more leverage now, but the
investment decisions that companies make may determine the
long-range winners.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may win a short-term victory like GM but lose the war,''
said Bruce Kaufman, a Georgia State University economics professor.
``The companies make short-term concessions, but they go back to
the executive suites and come up with long-range strategies about
their capital investments that ultimately result in unionized
plants being downsized or closed, and over the long run union jobs
go elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Tammy Joyner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
