<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE TUESDAY FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These stories for release Tuesday, August 11, 1998, are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports, business and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. Stories that haven't yet
moved have an ETA of 6 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   HESAID-SHESAID _ She says: The Lewinsky Syndrome -- some women's
compulsion to attach themselves to rich or powerful men --
explained. He says: The Lewinsky Syndrome disputed.
(Downey/Emerson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE-COLUMN _ Michael Skube on ... the quality of listening.
Dr. Laura signing a new contract reminds our columnist that this is
a woman with many, many listeners, but she herself is not much of
one. (Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   NEON _ DAYTON, Ohio _ ``They haven't got a computer that can do
this yet,'' says Richard Lowry, holding a hollow glass tube over a
blue-hot flame. Within seconds, the rigid tube becomes as pliable
as a rubber band, ready to be molded into loops or angles in
Lowry's workworn hands. Like a modern-day Vulcan, Lowry has spent
the better part of 50 years in sweltering shops, creating colorful
neon signs through the unlikely marriage of glass and electricity.
(Hundley, Dayton Daily News.) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GROCERY-RESTAURANTS _ PALM BEACH GARDENS, Fla. _ Kathy Gehrke
wanted something to eat. Something good. Cheap. Fast. And a place
to sit. She got Salisbury steak, $2.99, including two side dishes
and a dinner roll. She was dining in less than five minutes. A new
item at McDonald's? No. She stopped at a grocery store _ Publix.
And judging by the steady stream of people who ordered up and sat
down during a typical lunch hour last week, the supermarket in Palm
Beach Gardens is denting the business of nearby fast-food
restaurants. (Herubin, Palm Beach Post.) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   NOVELIST-HILL _ Novelist Ernest Hill grew up poor in rural
Louisiana, the fourth of nine children in a tiny house with no
running water and no indoor bathroom. But eight of the nine
children went to college _ the first three to Yale, Ernest to
Berkeley and Cornell _ and all are successes. The reason: a mother
who cared and a father who worked two and sometimes three jobs.
Hill's novel, ``A Life for a Life,'' is a powerful tale of how one
humble man saves a teen-age killer from self-destruction.
(O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GEAR _ After successfully launching a music mag alternative to
rolling stone more than a decade ago, publisher Bob Guccione Jr.
now has his eye on shaking up mens' magazines in a similar fashion.
Gear debuts on atlanta newsstands this week. Interview with
Guccione plus react from rivals. (Eldredge, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   NEWSSTAND _ Periodicals available this week. (O'Briant, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MYSTERY-ACTOR _ Harrison Young, 78, is probably not the
household name that, say, Tom Hanks or Christina Ricci is, but he
shows up in two of this summer's most talked about movies _
``Opposite of Sex'' and ``Saving Private Ryan.'' Who is this guy?
Could he be the Gloria Stuart of 1998? (Vejnoska, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GRAVE-LINE _ LOS ANGELES _ ``You'll recall how Jack Haley got a
heart as the Tin Man in the Wizard of Oz ,'' our tour guide says as
the long, gray funeral car approaches his old Beverly Hills home.
``Well, here's where it suddenly stopped ticking on June 6, 1979.''
Hey, any Hollywood tourist can buy a map off a street corner and
see where the stars live. It's much more fun, in a morbid sense, to
take a tour and see where they died. Especially if they went out in
a sizzling blaze of embarrassment. (Larsen, Dayton Daily News.)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   TEEN-RISKS _ ATLANTA _ The CDC opens a three-day conference in
Atlanta Tuesday on teen risk health behaviors, which will include
talks by AIDS czar Sandy Thurman and other notables. At the end of
the conference on Thursday, CDC will release its bi-annual national
report on Youth Risk Behavior that gives state by state data on
smoking, sexual behavior, and other risk behaviors of teens.
(Aldag, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SURGERY-TECHNIQUE _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Eight-year-old
Olivia Bell was the first patient at Joe DiMaggio Children's
Hospital in Hollywood (Fla.) to have open-heart surgery using a
new, less-invasive technique. The procedure, video-assisted
thoracic surgery, allowed Dr. Robert Jaquiss, the hospital's
pediatric cardiac surgeon, to use a much smaller incision to sew a
patch over the hole in Olivia's heart. (McGinness, Palm Beach
Post.) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   RURAL-HEALTHCARE _ WILLACOOCHEE, Ga. _ Their lunch of
hamburgers, slaw, baked potatoes and cobbler had come and gone. Yet
15 of the regulars at the Senior Citizen Center here stayed an hour
longer Wednesday to talk of the upcoming health care crisis in
their South Georgia town. A medical clinic, located a couple of
miles away, is set to close this week. And except for one physician
in his 70s, who is close to retiring, the town would be without
medical services. (Miller, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY (l, f categories)
</P>
<P>
   MINORITY-TECH _ ATLANTA _ Bobby Smith, his son and his wife all
signed up for Derrick Brown's computer class at Georgia Tech.
``Using the computer just at work, I did not realize all the things
you can do with the Internet and in other ways that are such fun,''
Smith said. ``I am glad I did it, and now I tell everybody to try
it.'' The Smith family of Decatur, Ga. happens to be
African-American, and their experience underlines the findings in
studies that blacks are often involved less in the computer age
than the population at large. Often, however, encouragement and
opportunity can fire their enthusiasm about computers.
(Holsendolph, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-REPORT _ ATLANTA _ On portable sound systems. (Kanell,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ If you plan to put your faith _
and perhaps your fortune _ in the hands of the gurus dispensing
free legal advice on the World Wide Web, you can only hope your
next judge has a 17-inch screen. But if you use the legal resources
you find on the Web to prepare yourself for a visit with a lawyer,
it's possible to save money and do a better job of preparing for
that visit. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ You've probably been hearing a lot
about portals on the Internet lately. People buying portals,
selling portals, analysts predicting portals are the future. (Katz,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ I am here today to propose a new
national holiday. I don't think it'll be as much fun as Christmas,
or as important as Mother's Day, but I'm pretty sure it will catch
on. I propose we have a National Low Tech Day. (Husted, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHTOOLS-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ Review of the new Visual Page
program. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
