<HEADER>
A5995 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GROCERY-RESTAURANTS11     08-10 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROCERY-RESTAURANTS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    And dinner, too, as supermarket delis serve food fast
 &HT;    By Danielle Herubin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH GARDENS, Fla. _ Kathy Gehrke wanted something to eat.
Something good. Cheap. Fast. And a place to sit.
</P>
<P>
   She got Salisbury steak, $2.99, including two side dishes and a
dinner roll. She was dining in less than five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   A new item at McDonald's? No. She stopped at a grocery store _
Publix. And judging by the steady stream of people who ordered up
and sat down during a typical lunch hour last week, the supermarket
on Northlake Boulevard in Palm Beach Gardens is denting the
business of nearby fast-food restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   A grocery industry study found that fast-food places have lost
market share: 37 percent of consumers say they eat at a fast-food
restaurant when they want quick meals, down from 41 percent last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ''As consumers have become more time-starved, the supermarket
industry realized that we could provide not only staples, but we
could also provide them their next meal,'' said Sherrie Rosenblatt,
a spokeswoman for the Washington, D.C.-based Food Marketing
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   The trend in dining at supermarkets _ essentially small
restaurants that expand on the old deli concept _ isn't new. But
it's becoming more common in Palm Beach County as market leaders
Publix and Winn-Dixie build new stores and remodel old ones.
</P>
<P>
   Publix began building supermarkets with restaurants about eight
years ago, said Carmen Millares, the Lakeland-based company's
community affairs manager in Miami. The chain is trying to meet all
of a shopper's needs, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We noticed that, when customers go out . . . that they have
many needs to take care of, and we're trying to let them make them
all in just one stop,'' Millares said. ''They want pictures of
birthday parties, they need money for their shopping, they're tired
and want a coffee, or a guy wants to take flowers to his wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach County's two main supermarket chains make decisions
differently on where to offer in-store dining.
</P>
<P>
   Publix does it randomly, Millares said. Jacksonville-based
Winn-Dixie puts the restaurants in most new stores, including its
supermarkets near the RiverWalk subdivision on Okeechobee Boulevard
in West Palm Beach and on Military Trail in west Boynton Beach.
Boise, Idaho-based Albertson's Inc. is offering coffee bars in some
stores and beginning to offer delis with limited seating.
Albertson's spokesman Michael Read said dine-in areas are put in
suburban stores, where residents have higher incomes.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is not full-blown,'' Reid said. ''We are not doing it in
every store. It's fairly limited.''
</P>
<P>
   Albertson's opened its first supermarket restaurant in Texas;
its first in Florida, near Clearwater, opened about seven months
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Diners seem to be satisfied with the fare, which ranges from
salads to sandwiches to hot meals.
</P>
<P>
   The Publix on Northlake was packed during lunch one day last
week.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's convenient, fast, and people here are nice people,'' said
Marc Weinstein, 30, an assistant service manager at the nearby
Schumacher Automotive.
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein said he likes ''everything'' at the deli, and the
prices are right: $2.39 for an Italian sub, $2.29 for a steak
burger, $2.99 for fish and chips.
</P>
<P>
   Publix spokeswoman Millares said 30 to 40 of the company's 465
stores in Florida have dine-in delis. Three are in Palm Beach
County. Martin and St. Lucie counties have none.
</P>
<P>
   Winn-Dixie spokesmen said they were unable to say how many of
their stores have dine-in delis.
</P>
<P>
   Danielle Herubin writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla. Palm Beach Post researcher Barbara Gellis Shapiro
contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
