<SLUG> BC-SURGERY-TECHNIQUE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Less-invasive heart surgery gives many families hope
 &HT;    (EDS: Rerences to ``last'' Tuesday and Friday CQ for Aug. 5th,
7th.)
 &HT;    By Chuck McGinness
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Eight-year-old Olivia Bell will have
quite a story to tell her classmates about how she spent her summer
vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Olivia, who will be a third-grader in Palm City, Fla., returned
home last Friday after surgery to close a quarter-sized hole in her
heart.
</P>
<P>
   But what makes Olivia's tale especially interesting is that she
was the first patient at Joe DiMaggio Children's Hospital in
Hollywood (Fla.) to have open-heart surgery using a new,
less-invasive technique.
</P>
<P>
   The procedure, video-assisted thoracic surgery, allowed Dr.
Robert Jaquiss, the hospital's pediatric cardiac surgeon, to use a
much smaller incision to sew a patch over the hole in Olivia's
heart. This type of operation does not require the breast bone to
be cut open, and allows the patient to recover much quicker than
traditional open-heart surgery. It leaves a scar that is barely
noticeable.
</P>
<P>
   Olivia had the operation last Tuesday afternoon and was running
around the medical center Friday morning as her parents filled out
her discharge papers.
</P>
<P>
   Jaquiss said he learned the technique from Dr. David Bichell, a
cardiac surgeon at Boston Children's Hospital, who is credited with
pioneering the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Olivia was eating popsicles four to five hours after
surgery,'' Jaquiss said. ``I can't imagine how it could have gone
any better.''
</P>
<P>
   Olivia's parents, Rick and Jan Bell, learned about their
daughter's condition on May 20, her birthday. Their cardiologist,
Dr. Harry Bayron, recommended Jaquiss perform the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Artrial Septal Defect is one of the most common heart defects in
children. A small hole between the right and left sides of the
heart allows oxygen-filled blood from the left side to flow back to
the right side. The oxygen-filled blood then passes through the
lungs again, eventually causing lung congestion.
</P>
<P>
   Youngsters with the affliction are usually sluggish and develop
respiratory infection and pulmonary hypertension in the lungs.
Because she wasn't always running around like other kids, Olivia's
parents thought she simply liked quiet activities.
</P>
<P>
   Olivia said she was not scared about the operation, but was glad
to be home so she could play with her friends and 4-year-old sister
Claudia.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said that it was all so easy, it was no big deal,'' older
sister Kate Wells said. ``We're all dumbfounded about how well
she's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck McGinness writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
