<HEADER>
A5997 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RURAL-HEALTHCARE11-CO     08-10 1517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RURAL-HEALTHCARE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No easy cure for rural health care ills
 &HT;    By Andy Miller
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILLACOOCHEE, Ga. _ Their lunch of hamburgers, slaw, baked
potatoes and cobbler had come and gone. Yet 15 of the regulars at
the Senior Citizen Center here stayed an hour longer to talk of the
upcoming health care crisis in their South Georgia town.
</P>
<P>
   A medical clinic, located a couple of miles away, is set to
close. And except for one physician in his 70s, who is close to
retiring, the town would be without medical services.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people get hurt, they'll have to go 20 miles to get to a
doctor,'' said Eddie Perkins, 76, a Medicare recipient. ``A lot of
us don't have transportation.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Link, 85, a diabetic, said a physician assistant at the
clinic had helped her improve her health. ``I walk five blocks now
every morning,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The expected closing of MedCare Willacoochee isn't a matter of
finding medical providers or patients. Clinic operators said the
doors to the double-wide trailer will shut because of a state
policy over payment for services delivered by physician assistants,
known as PAs.
</P>
<P>
   To politicians, business leaders and residents here, the rule
appears unfair, even absurd. The state agency that runs Medicaid,
the Department of Medical Assistance, said it's in the process of
studying its PA regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the clinic's plight also illustrates the fragility of
health care services in rural areas of Georgia and elsewhere. And
it shows how economic development in such communities can hinge on
access to medical services.
</P>
<P>
   Until earlier this year, MedCare Willacoochee was operated by a
Lakeland, Fla., hospital, and received reimbursement from Medicaid
for services delivered by a PA.
</P>
<P>
   But in March, the hospital decided to close the clinic and
another in nearby Pearson. Both communities are between Tifton and
Waycross in south Georgia. At that point, two PAs, Bobby Tucker and
Arlene Gottlieb, and their supervising doctor, Dr. Robert Bowman,
decided to keep the Willacoochee center open themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I care about my patients,'' Tucker said. ``If we are not here,
they're going to suffer. I've got patients who come up here on a
bicycle. They're not going to ride a bicycle to Waycross.''
</P>
<P>
   The three were making a go of it until June, when they were told
Medicaid, the federal-state program serving 1 million low-income
Georgians, can't pay for their PA services anymore.
</P>
<P>
   The reason? Under Medicaid rules, a doctor must be on the
premises at all times for PA payment at a private clinic.
</P>
<P>
   But at a hospital outpatient center, or one labeled a ``rural
health center,'' a physician doesn't have to be on site during all
PA services for Medicaid to reimburse.
</P>
<P>
   The Willacoochee clinic had those labels until the hospital
relinquished control. Bowman, who works as an emergency room
physician in the area, can be there only 10 hours a week.
</P>
<P>
   So despite having the same personnel and patients, and providing
the same services as before, the clinic now can't get Medicaid to
pay it for past months of PA services _ or future ones. And about
30 percent of the clinic's patients are Medicaid recipients.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare, the federal program serving those 65 and older, will
reimburse the PAs at the clinic. And private insurance does, too.
</P>
<P>
   Medicaid's on-site doctor requirement goes beyond the state's
own PA regulations in rural or urban areas, according to the
Georgia Association of Physician Assistants.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Bauer, a legislative consultant for the association, cited
the Georgia medical board's rules on ``remote'' medical sites.
``The doctor has to be there 25 percent of the time,'' Bauer said.
</P>
<P>
   Here and elsewhere, physician assistants can practice medicine
only under the supervision of doctors. But while they must be
available by phone as a PA works, doctors generally don't have to
be physically present during those services.
</P>
<P>
   PAs aren't directly reimbursed, but payments go to the employer
or physician for services delivered by a PA.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of PAs perform primary care. Their duties include
physical exams, diagnosis and treatment of illnesses, orders of lab
tests and suturing of wounds. About 1,700 PAs are working in
Georgia, according to the GAPA.
</P>
<P>
   Medicaid does allow nurse practitioners to be reimbursed without
a physician on site. ``There's a difference in the practice act for
nurse practitioners; they have more authority than PAs,'' said Mark
Trail, deputy commissioner of DMA. ``They have to have a physician
on call. Their practices are limited by protocols.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Trail said DMA has contacted the state medical board to
see whether the Willacoochee clinic would qualify under the board's
``remote site'' designation.
</P>
<P>
   Though Trail said the Willacoochee situation is an isolated one,
GAPA said it's indicative of larger issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern is access,'' said Kathy Kemle, a GAPA leader. ``In
most rural areas, there is not a sufficient patient base to support
a physician.''
</P>
<P>
   Willacoochee has only 1,500 residents. But it does appear to
have an unusual level of industry for a small town.
</P>
<P>
   A new Langboard Inc. fiberboard plant, for example, will employ
130. The clinic's departure, said Langboard personnel director Joy
Schunhoff, ``is going to be a big problem for us. We use the
facility for pre-employment physicals and drug screens, and we were
planning to use them for on-the-job injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   Willacoochee would have had trouble wooing the Langboard plant
without the clinic there, said Lace Futch, of the Southeast Georgia
Regional Development Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're dealing with something that's vital to that community,''
Futch added. ``Someone needs to get across to the Medicaid board
the impact they're having on rural areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Access to health care has worried many rural communities. Some
are in danger of losing their hospital to financial problems.
Medicare and Medicaid have ratcheted down payments, and private
insurance, through managed care, has forced hospitals to accept
deep discounts.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Legislature has taken notice, and some rural
hospitals have formed a for-profit company to attract managed care
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if a hospital goes under, jobs and industry are
endangered. And if doctors and other medical professionals
disappear, an area's medical needs _ and economic ones _ can
multiply.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you lose a (medical provider) in a rural area, it
hurts,'' said Willacoochee pharmacist James Carter. ``If you lose
one in Macon or Atlanta, it doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Willacoochee alone can't sustain a physician, added Jerome
Crosby, a vice president of Peoples Bank in Willacoochee. But he
added: ``A physician assistant can be here daily. But one little
quirk in the law makes them ineligible to be paid. Somebody needs
to step in and waive this policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I use them myself, and my children go there.''
</P>
<P>
   As do other community leaders, such as county commissioners Jack
Taft and Chester Brown. The Fleetwood plant, down Ga. 82 from the
clinic, uses MedCare Willacoochee for injuries and drug screens.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really upset they can't stay,'' said JoAnn Courson,
production coordinator for the mobile home manufacturer. ``When you
have someone hurt on the job, they don't want to ride 20 to 30
minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowman, Tucker and Gottlieb have worked basically without pay
during the first months as a private clinic. It could have sought
designation as a rural center _ and received reimbursement for PA
services _ but the cost of meeting the paperwork burden would have
been prohibitive, Tucker said.
</P>
<P>
   DMA tried to be helpful, added Bowman, the supervising doctor.
But he said the agency, when rejecting their request, also asked
the clinic to continue to see its Medicaid patients _ without
getting paid _ until they could be switched to other doctors.
</P>
<P>
   But residents want the clinic to stay open. Bill Yawn credits it
with saving his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had heartburn or indigestion,'' said Yawn. It was
actually a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   When Yawn dropped by, PA Gottlieb ran an electrocardiogram,
contacted Bowman and a cardiologist, faxed the EKG to both, and
sent Yawn to a Valdosta hospital. ``If MedCare wouldn't have been
there, I wouldn't have gone to see anyone,'' Yawn said.
</P>
<P>
   Patients say they're comfortable with the PA care. Olga
Contreras was hired in the office partly because she can translate
the Spanish spoken by the clinic's Hispanic patients.
</P>
<P>
   At the senior center, Clara Lee Mercer, 61, found a seat at the
long lunch table. She has gone to the Willacoochee clinic for
osteoarthritis, borderline diabetes and other problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have found things wrong (with me) that no other doctors
have found,'' said Mercer, a Medicaid recipient. There were tears
behind her eyeglasses.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been a blessing to me. They treat you like family.''
</P>
<P>
   Andy Miller writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
