<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERSCENE-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Carefully evaluate legal advice on the Web
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If you plan to put your faith _ and perhaps your
fortune _ in the hands of the gurus dispensing free legal advice on
the World Wide Web, you can only hope your next judge has a 17-inch
screen.
</P>
<P>
   But if you use the legal resources you find on the Web to
prepare yourself for a visit with a lawyer, it's possible to save
money and do a better job of preparing for that visit. Whether your
legal needs center on buying a house, getting a divorce or settling
the family estate, you'll find plenty of advice on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the best advice you'll find _ and the best place to
start our tour on sites specializing in the law _ comes from a page
called Online Legal Advice: Let the Browser Beware at http://
www.nolo.com/nn223.html. It offers common-sense advice on how to
evaluate the legal information you'll find.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, you'll be told to consider the source of the
information _ not all sites are equal. You're best served by a
lawyer operating in his or her field of expertise. In other words,
don't get estate planning advice from someone who specializes in
criminal law.
</P>
<P>
   You'll also be smart to make sure the information is up to date,
since the law changes as new legal decisions are made. Since it's
likely your own situation will be decided based on the law in the
state where you live, legal sites located in your state may be the
best bet. Also be wary of the ready-to-fill-in legal forms for
wills and divorces that you'll find on some sites. The real trick
isn't getting the form, it's knowing how to fill it in correctly.
</P>
<P>
   Our next stop is a site called Wired Law: Legal Information &AMP;
Advice on the Web at http://
</P>
<P>
   www.primenet.com/wiredlaw /links.htm. This site is especially
valuable because it contains links to many of the legal sites on
the Web, and because those links are organized according to topic.
So if your question concerns property law, for instance, you can go
directly to a site specializing in that field.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is almost certain. Your particular case or problem is
unique. That's why it's unlikely that simply browsing through the
information you find on the Web will be enough. Sooner or later, if
you decide to do more research before seeing a lawyer, you'll need
to go to a law library. Luckily, the law school at Atlanta's Emory
University has an online presence you'll find at http://
www.law.emory.edu/LAW/refdesk/toc.html. You'll be able to search
legal periodicals, law books and the federal statutes.
</P>
<P>
   Law students will also profit from this site, since it also
offers job search information. The site also offers information on
the laws in some other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Sooner or later, when you've followed the last link and read the
last convoluted legal article, it'll be time to find a lawyer. The
Internet also offers resources to help with that quest.
</P>
<P>
   Just stop by a page called FindLaw: Lawyers and Law Firms at
http://www.findlaw
</P>
<P>
   .com/14firms/index.html. Once there, you can search various
directories of lawyers and even take a look at a database that
offers legal aid advice and pointers. You'll also be able to use a
database compiled by the respected legal publishers, West and
Martindale-Hubbell.
</P>
<P>
   You can search based on location or name, or you can use
keywords to find a lawyer with the right specialty.
</P>
<P>
   Like the rest of the sites visited today, there are no charges
associated with the service. In fact, as a final bit of legal
advice, most lawyers would tell you to avoid the cut-rate,
commercial legal sites you'll find on the Web. If advice is worth
what you pay for it, then the sites that offer to answer legal
questions for fees that range from $20 to $50 may be the most
expensive lawyers you'll ever meet.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Husted writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
