<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEON11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Father and son lead 'exciting lives' in neon business
 &HT;    By Wendy Hundley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ ``They haven't got a computer that can do this
yet,'' says Richard Lowry, holding a hollow glass tube over a
blue-hot flame.
</P>
<P>
   Within seconds, the rigid tube becomes as pliable as a rubber
band, ready to be molded into loops or angles in Lowry's workworn
hands.
</P>
<P>
   Like a modern-day Vulcan, Lowry has spent the better part of 50
years in sweltering shops, creating colorful neon signs through the
unlikely marriage of glass and electricity.
</P>
<P>
   While it's not the only neon business in the area, Lowry's Neon
Art shop remains a small, pop-and-son operation and a fixture in
East Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been an exciting life,'' says Lowry, standing in his
workshop on a muggy summer afternoon. ``I've met some people and
some real corkers too.''
</P>
<P>
   A few fans try to keep the air moving and the heat is stifling
in the shop surrounded by neon enticements for ``Draft On Tap'' and
``Bud Lite.''
</P>
<P>
   People keep telling him he should get air conditioning. Lowry
never got around to it. Probably never will.
</P>
<P>
   At 81, Lowry has no plans to slow down: ``I'll go on as long as
the Lord lets me. What are you going to do? My brothers retired and
they died.''
</P>
<P>
   One of 13 children, Lowry moved with his family from Kentucky to
Dayton, where he attended the old Steele High School.
</P>
<P>
   After World War II, he used the GI Bill to attend a school to
learn the craft that became his life's work.
</P>
<P>
   It was a good time to get into the business.
</P>
<P>
   Las Vegas was arising from the sands of the Nevada desert and
the glitz of the neon-lit casino strip was breathing new life into
bright tubular signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those old theatres downtown used to be lit by lightbulbs,''
says Lowry, recalling Dayton's history from a signage perspective.
``Then after the war, neon came on.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he says with finality, ``it's part of our culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Oblivious to the heat, he holds a glass tube over a blue flame
until it's pliable. Then he molds it by placing it on a prepared
pattern.
</P>
<P>
   Part chemist, part artist, he demonstrates the technique
involved in evacuating air from a tube and filling it with gases
that lend it bright, eye-catching hues.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing about neon,'' says Lowry, peering out from behind
thick lenses, ``it grows on you.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been some concessions to technology. Today, Lowry's
son, Bob, will use a computer to create patterns for signs. But
much of Lowry's work has remain unchanged since his Steubenville
days.
</P>
<P>
   Some consider neon cheap and gaudy, he allows. But now, he adds
with a hint of amusement, old neon signs are considered
collectibles. He spends as much time repairing old signs as
creating new ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all these years,'' says the neon signmaker, ``I'm still
fascinated.''
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Hundley writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
