A6012 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMMEUS-RESULTS-KAN &LR;      08-10 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-RESULTS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYTHING WE DO HAS A RIPPLE EFFECT ON OTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1998 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As I drove to work one recent morning, I had to brake to a full
stop in the center lane of the interstate highway I usually take. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I looked at my wife, with whom I carpool, and said, ``Unless
there's an accident up ahead (which there wasn't), I can't think of
one good reason for this. We're stopping as the result of a series
of bad driving decisions by people ahead of us.'' Which is when it
struck me anew that in a profound way all of our decisions _ good
and bad _ about every aspect of life inevitably have ripple effects
on others, effects we rarely consider. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What else, if not that, are we experiencing in the
Clinton-Lewinsky scandal? As a result of some highly personal
decisions (whatever they were) made months and months ago by the
president and a White House intern, the government threatens to
shake itself apart, and it is no longer clear that Bill Clinton can
serve out his full second term. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, countless lives have been touched by this matter. And I
am not arguing that all of them have been affected for the worse.
After all, this tawdry affair has provided an enormous number of
billable hours for lawyers and employment for all kinds of
journalists. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is, of course, often easy to see the massive effects of
public decisions made by world leaders. The atomic bombs Harry
Truman ordered dropped on Japan still create consequences today.
The evil actions produced by the malignant schemes in Adolf
Hitler's gnarled mind have changed the lives of millions of
families for eternity. Any fool can see those things. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But what is less obvious are the smaller decisions individuals
make in private _ often without much thought for the consequences.
For instance, my daughters were born and reared in Kansas City as
at least an indirect result of my decision _ nearly three decades
ago _ to take a job here. Their lives are, of course, different in
unknown but myriad ways than they would have been had I elected to
continue living and working in Rochester, N.Y. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But even much smaller decisions can have unintended _ or at
least unforeseen _ consequences. Recently one of the computer users
in my house decided to change Web browsers, and tried to remove the
browser already on our machine. It was not, on its face, an
unreasonable decision. But removing it turned out to be a nearly
impossible task _ purposefully made so by Bill Gates' company _
that led to a cascade of problems. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the end, various people, including a friend I hired, spent
hours trying to salvage things, and Gates sold another software
program I hadn't intended to buy _ all to get things working
again. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In still-smaller decisions we influence and change others'
lives, too. When we borrow scissors and don't return them we force
someone to waste time hunting for them. When we fail to set our
alarm clock and oversleep we inconvenience people who were counting
on us. When we snap at each other with caustic words we can cause
wounds that fester for months or years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Our actions _ all of them _ have consequences. Not always are
these results important, of course. Often they get absorbed without
notice. But more often what we do changes things, though most of us
aren't good at imagining how ahead of time. And yet we must not
think we can always control what happens, even if we've taken care
to avoid unintended consequences. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Winston Churchill had it right when he wrote: ``How little we
can foresee the consequences either of wise or unwise actions, of
virtue or of malice! Without this measureless and perpetual
uncertainty, the drama of human life would be destroyed.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, if we can be more considerate and refrain from actions
certain to affect others badly, that drama can have a happier
ending _ for everyone. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
