Department's inspector general affords a rare view of secret CIA
operations. And it poses a troubling question that may arise when
intelligence agencies intercede in prosecutions: Are they
protecting true national-security interests, or avoiding public
accountability? By SETH ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   DROUGHT-TREES (Undated) _ The Texas Forest Service, which grows
and distributes pine seedlings for the state's private pine land
owners, said 1998 was a record year, with nearly 53,000 acres
planted in baby pines. But the dry hot summer of 1998 may claim up
to 90 percent of those trees. The crisis is threatening the
billion-dollar East Texas timber industry. By ALLAN TURNER.
</P>
