test new, ultra-refined, ground-penetrating radar, a device that
could revolutionize archaeology. For the scientists, the aim was to
prove the capabilities of the tool by flying over a region in the
Andes rumored to be the last bastion of Inca life. They hoped to
find evidence beneath the trees, or under the earth. By JANE
GANAHL.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Houston) _ A reader asks about the pregnant
onion, or ``Ornithogalum caudatum,'' a curious plant that also goes
by the common names false sea onion, German onion and healing
onion. The name pregnant onion is appropriate, since tiny bulbs
appear on the mother bulb. These small bulbs grow larger, then fall
to the soil's surface and become new plants. By KATHY HUBER
</P>
