<HEADLINE>
CONVICTIONS, NOT COLOR, MAKE JUSTICE THOMAS A TARGET OF CRITICISM 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CARY CLACK  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Clarence Thomas is right. Clarence Thomas is also
a hypocrite.
</P>
<P>
   Just recently, the most controversial of the U.S. Supreme Court
justices spoke at the national convention of the National Bar
Association, the largest organization of black lawyers in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas is controversial because he's a black conservative, a
fact that has never sat well with many African Americans. And he's
not just any black conservative, but the highest-ranking African
American in government, who followed the legendary Thurgood
Marshall on the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas' appearance marked the first time he had ventured into
the lion's den of his critics. To his credit, he accepted the
invitation to speak before the group and didn't back down when some
members of the Bar attempted to disinvite him. Courageously, he
didn't retreat from his convictions or tailor his words to pacify
his audience.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas is right when he asks, ``Isn't it time to move on? To be
angry with me solves no problems.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right when he asserts his right to think for himself and to
hold views that may not be popular with many, if not most, African
Americans. There is no black party line or monolithic black
mind-set. The range of views among African Americans is as varied
as skin tones.
</P>
<P>
   To accuse him of being the intellectual puppet of Justice
Antonin Scalia and other white conservatives on the court is to
deny him his independence. If Scalia and other justices aren't
criticized for their opinions because they're white, Thomas should
not be vilified for his because he's black.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas is a hypocrite for his stance on affirmative action. He
alleges that such programs are based on black inferiority. This
from a man who got into Holy Cross College and Yale Law School on
affirmative-action programs. Which leads to a couple of questions
for white conservatives who oppose affirmative action: How do you
explain Clarence Thomas? And, isn't he an example of the good that
affirmative action can produce?
</P>
<P>
   Thomas is also a hypocrite if he believes that opposition to him
is based solely on race. If Thomas were white his comments and
legal opinions would still be worthy of criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Before being appointed to the court, Thomas, in his eagerness to
impress his political patrons, made speeches belittling his sister
and using her as an example of a lazy welfare dependent. What he
failed to mention was that she was on welfare because she'd quit
work to care for their aunt who'd been incapacitated by a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   During his confirmation hearing, in an effort to display his
compassion, Thomas said that from his Circuit Court judge's office,
he could see handcuffed prisoners being led away from the federal
courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas claimed to be moved by the sight. ``There but for the
grace of God go I,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But given the power of a Supreme Court justice, Thomas didn't
have the grace to vote with the majority in a 1992 case when he
wrote that a prisoner's constitutional rights weren't violated even
though the prisoner was shackled and beaten by two guards who split
his lip, broke his dental plate and loosened his teeth.
</P>
<P>
   There should be more gatherings where Thomas confronts his
critics and engages in vigorous but respectful dialogue. Thomas is
under no obligation to conform his thoughts to theirs. And his
critics aren't obligated to do likewise.
</P>
<P>
   If they don't like him, it's not because of the color of his
skin but the content of his convictions.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Cary Clack is a columnist for the San Antonio Express-News,
P.O. Box 2171, San Antonio, TX 78297.)
</P>
</TEXT>
