<HEADLINE>
CLEANER AIR MAY BE A WHISTLE-STOP AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HUEY JOHNSON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ An interesting phenomenon of this century has
been to observe various technologies hit the wall of limits. Air
travel is the one I see next as getting a dose of reality and
shrinking, or at least adjusting back.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier examples include nuclear energy, freeways and filling
the San Francisco Bay. Remember then-President Dwight D. Eisenhower
assuring the nation that this new gadget, nuclear energy, would
supply free electricity, that we wouldn't even use meters on our
buildings any more? Accidents like Three Mile Island and Chernobyl
could ``never happen,'' but they did. Deadly waste, bankrupt
utilities and citizen opposition buried the nuclear dream.
</P>
<P>
   Freeways were another example. San Francisco residents shut down
a half-built freeway and started a movement that ended the national
freeway juggernaut. And the movement to fill the San Francisco Bay
was stopped by the citizen-based Save the Bay Association.
</P>
<P>
   Why is air travel next to reach its limit? Because breathing
healthy air is a subject of interest to everyone. Air travel and
airports immediately catch my eye as huge sources of pollution that
have gotten little attention.
</P>
<P>
   We have a better alternative: Go back to trains. New-generation
trains run about as fast as planes, pollute very little and are far
more comfortable. Europe already is making the change to high-speed
rail to beat the airplane air pollution. A new-generation train
between Los Angeles and San Francisco _ or even better, Los Angeles
and Seattle _ would get rid of a huge belch of air pollutants.
</P>
<P>
   When the history of environmental recovery in the United States
is written, the San Francisco area will be remembered for the two
great citizen-based revolts _ stopping the freeway and stopping Bay
filling. In both, citizens rose up to correct a condition that was
out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   We will never get these trains unless we stop believing we can
fly jets and pollute forever in unlimited ways. We need to go back
to the barricades to make history for a third time.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Huey D. Johnson, former secretary of the California Resources
Agency, is president of the Resources Renewal Institute in San
Francisco.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
