<HEADLINE>
TREE GROWERS FACE WOES AS HEAT, FIRES TAKE TOLL IN TEXAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: La. and Texas) 
 
By ALLAN TURNER  
 c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Crimson, gold, tobacco brown. From the Red River to the Coastal
Plains, the forests of East Texas are aflame in a burst of autumnal
glory.
</P>
<P>
   But this is no change-of-seasons woodlands rhapsody. This is a
song of death.
</P>
<P>
   The region's 12 million acres of pine and hardwood forests are
in the grip of the worst drought in decades _ one that has combined
scant rainfall with weeks of searing 100-plus-degree temperatures.
Even when welcome rains pelted the area last week, experts worried
that much serious, irreversible damage has been done.
</P>
<P>
   Already, millions of loblolly pine seedlings have withered and
died. Countless mature trees have gone dormant as moisture in their
trunks reached critically low levels and others _ seemingly healthy
_ have been stunted by the heat. Roughly 75,500 acres of forest and
grassland have been charred in drought-fueled blazes in East and
East-Central Texas since May 1.
</P>
<P>
   It still is too early to assess financial costs of the disaster.
Some commercial operators won't scrutinize their timber lands until
October. But, everywhere one goes, said U.S. Forest Service
spokeswoman Gay Ippolito, ``it almost looks as if fall has begun.
... The leaves are turning, changing colors as the trees are in
different stages of dying.''
</P>
<P>
   The crisis threatening the billion-dollar East Texas timber
industry has reduced some timbermen to impotent frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think you're a good timber man and manager and without the
good Lord's help, you can't manage things at all,'' one lamented
last week.
</P>
<P>
   As raindrops skittered off the roof of the Forest Service's
Lufkin headquarters the other day, tree expert Ron Haugen glumly
noted: ``This is not a turnaround.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent rains, he said, realistically will give forests a five-
to seven-day break.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would need rainfall like this every week or every other
week,'' he said. ``We really need a tropical storm _ 10 to 12
inches of rain in three or four days. If it goes back to 100
degrees and no rain, we'll be in the same old situation before you
know it.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Forest Service fire specialist Mahlon Hammetter said the
same holds for the recent rain's fire-retardant effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps for the short term,'' he said, ``but we need some
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Haugen described the East Texas forest fire potential as
``explosive.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, 1998 started out as a pretty good year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got most of our rainfall in the spring,'' Temple-Inland
spokesman Tony Bennett said from company headquarters in Diboll.
``We aren't real behind in total rainfall. But very little of that
came in the summer. That, with heat, has led to the obvious
results.''
</P>
<P>
   Longview, heart of the Northeast Texas pine belt, received only
0.38 inch of rain in July, a month that also was characterized by
23 consecutive days of 100-degree temperatures. Average May-July
rainfall for the city normally is about 13 inches; this year, 2.4
inches have been recorded.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
HEAVILY FORESTED &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the heavily forested tier of counties bordering Louisiana
north of Beaumont _ a region where rainfall annually exceeds 50
inches _ there is a 10- to 12-inch rainfall deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't see this more than every 30 or 40 or 50 years,''
said Roger Erickson, coordinating meteorologist with the National
Weather Service in Lake Charles, La. ``It is very unusual for it to
be this dry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Trees contain an awful lot of moisture,'' said the Forest
Services's Haugen, ``normally about 100 percent by weight.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, he said, moisture levels have dropped to 40 percent,
a point at which trees have become dormant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tree self-defense mechanism,'' he said. ``They just
shut down the respiration process of releasing water through the
leaves. You have brown leaves all over the place.''
</P>
<P>
   While an early dormant phase doesn't necessarily mean a tree
will die, it does the plant no good. Haugen worried that tree loss
might be extensive should next summer also be hot and dry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day of heat and drought matters,'' said Brad Barber, a
forest resource development expert with the Texas Forest Service in
College Station.
</P>
<P>
   One of the ways the state forest service aids private land
owners is by providing pine seedlings at nominal cost for
reforestation. The trees, only 6 to 12 inches tall when planted,
take about 25 years to reach a commercially usable size.
</P>
<P>
   ``We administered plantings on a record number of acres this
year,'' Barber said. ``We had about 53,000 acres. But it's been
pretty grim. We don't know for sure yet, but it may be turning out
to be our worst survival year.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
LOSS OF SEEDLINGS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, it has been typical to lose roughly a third of
all newly planted seedlings. This year, Barber estimated, close to
90 percent might be lost. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``I've talked to foresters who have been in the field,'' he
said, ``and they have even seen pines planted the previous year,
second-year plantings, starting to die. That's fairly uncommon.''
</P>
<P>
   While the seedlings themselves usually cost pennies apiece _
typically, 700 trees are planted per acre _ the cost of preparing
the land for replanting can reach $150 an acre, making the
proposition of replanting a costly one, Barber said.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy F. Thompson, president of the 73-member Cass County Forest
Owners Association based in Linden, reported a similar plight.
</P>
<P>
   ``My observation,'' he said, ``is that it's almost a complete
loss on newly planted seedlings. They have a very short root system
and, in that first year, adequate water is very, very critical.''
</P>
<P>
   Temple-Inland's Bennett said that of the 30,000 acres his
company planted in seedlings, 6,000 acres will need to be
replanted.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond seedling loss, the drought may reduce the growth of
mature trees by 25 percent, timber experts said.  &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Jerry Graves, owner of a Longview area Christmas tree farm,
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bigger trees that are surviving, they look real good,'' he
said. ``But they're not growing. What should have been an 8-foot
tree is going to be 6 or 6{ feet.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the extent of his good news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lost everything I planted this year,'' he said, ``and at
least a third of the trees I planted last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Graves began his farm in 1978. His first drought experience came
two years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to water that year. I was out watering by hand with a
garden hose,'' he recalled. ``It didn't do me any good. I didn't
even try that this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm losing trees every day.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
