u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YIP-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-10 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YIP-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING THE MOST OF EXPERT ADVICE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA YIP 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In my years of writing about personal finance, certain bits of
time-tested money management advice pop up over and over again.
</P>
<P>
   It pays to review these chunks of wisdom and how you can use
them to manage your finances better. Here are some of my favorites
gleaned from conversations with personal finance experts and from a
collection of business and economics quotations:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Don't let the tax tail wag the investment dog.''
</P>
<P>
   Make your investments in the context of your overall financial
picture, not just the tax implications of your decision.
</P>
<P>
   For example, given the stock market's recent falls, some of you
may want to cash out of your riskier investments into ones that
would enable you to sleep better at night.
</P>
<P>
   If a stock you own has had hefty gains since you bought it but
now has poor prospects, don't be afraid to dump it. Yes, you'll
have to pay tax on the gain, but getting out of it will save you
more money in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Cut your losses and let your profits run.''
</P>
<P>
   A major mistake that many investors make is getting so
emotionally involved with a stock that they lose all common sense
when the stock is going down the toilet.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be in denial and hold on to a stock when it's clear that
it's heading nowhere. Take your profits and get out.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Riches come rather from management than from revenue.''
</P>
<P>
   In my dealings with financial planners, many have told me that
they have seen people who make oodles of money, yet have very
little in the bank because they spend it all.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, it's not how much you make, but how much you keep.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Our incomes are like our shoes; if too small, they gall and
pinch us, but if too large, they cause us to stumble and to trip.''
</P>
<P>
   The larger our income, the harder it is to live within it
because supply creates its own demand.
</P>
<P>
   How many times have you gotten a raise or come into some other
financial windfall and salivated over what you could buy with that
extra money? The amount of goods and services we want has a funny
way of increasing in proportion to our ability to afford them _ and
regrettably sometimes to our inability to afford them.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Don't gamble. Take all your savings and buy some good stock
and hold it until it goes up, then sell it. If it doesn't go up,
don't buy it.''
</P>
<P>
   The stock market itself is a big gamble. There's no scientific
law that says a stock that falls will go back up.
</P>
<P>
   Another thing, the whole idea of good investing is coming in at
the right time before a stock goes up so far that it's hit a
plateau and you're buying in too late.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Bulls make money, bears make money, but pigs get
slaughtered.''
</P>
<P>
   There are only two emotions that count on Wall Street: fear and
greed.
</P>
<P>
   Fear of missing out on the action can make you snap up a stock
when its heyday has gone. Fear also can make you bail out of a
falling stock without rationally analyzing the prospects of the
issuing company and whether the stock's decline reflects investors'
skepticism of the firm or of the market as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   Greed can make you gather up all your profits from a stock and
still not sell all of your shares because you believe maybe there's
just one more runup left in the stock. More often than not, the
stock tanks.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``People do not grow rich by keeping their money unused. They
must be willing to spend in order to gain.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone who keeps money under the mattress will lose in the
battle against inflation.
</P>
<P>
   In order to keep ahead of inflation, you need to put your money
in the best inflation-fighting tool _ stocks. However, you must be
willing to spend some money to invest in order to reap that gain.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Stock prices have reached what looks like a permanently high
plateau.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing is permanent on Wall Street, especially peaks.
</P>
<P>
   When stock prices reach what investors think is too high a
level, they start to worry about a crash.
</P>
<P>
   That's what we're seeing today. Analysts are questioning whether
we're seeing a fundamental shift in mood among investors.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The safest way to double your money is to fold it over once
and put it in your pocket.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem with that is you're still left with the same single
dollar bill. You really haven't gained anything, and with
inflation, you could actually lose half the buying power of that
dollar bill.
</P>
<P>
   Hiding your money in your pocket or under your mattress isn't
going to help you double your money. You've got to be able to risk
some in investments and put your money to work for you.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pamela Yip can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to pamela.yip(at)chron.com, or call
(713) 220-2000 and enter access code 1003. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
