<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVING ON THE EDGE OF THE `BOOM' ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Unlike so many letters I receive, Sharon Hodge's
hand-written, eight-pager asked for nothing. Not money. Not pity.
Not a public forum.
</P>
<P>
   But I'm giving Hodge a forum, anyway. She deserves it. And all
of you in thrall to Wall Street, you who think this is the best
economy in a generation, you need to hear a voice from the other
America.
</P>
<P>
   Hodge and her husband James live in Bellflower, Calif. She wrote
after reading a column of mine about a group of rich folks who are
aware and ashamed of the gross imbalance in our economy and want to
do something about it.
</P>
<P>
   Cuts have been made for space but, except for minor style
changes, this is Sharon Hodge's letter:
</P>
<P>
   ``We are like many struggling people out there. My husband and I
were hit more than once, and you get to a point when you just feel
hopeless and give up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been married almost 36 years, bought one first-and-only
home years ago that was to be our retirement security. It was an
old home, small, two-bedroom, one-bath and needed much work. But
raising two children came first so our plans were to repair and
remodel when our kids went out on their own. We both worked
full-time and refinanced to take care of much-needed repairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little did we know. After we completed our home, the company
my husband worked for went out of business, and shortly after that,
I became ill and lost my job. We lost our home because no one
wanted to hire a hard-working man in his early 50s.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband was out of work over two years, and we struggled to
pay rent when we had to walk away from our home. Finally, my
husband found a job making $8 an hour but plenty of overtime. With
that, my artwork and a small retirement check of $275 per month
from my former job, we were struggling to get back on our feet and
plan for our retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight dollars an hour isn't much to work with but the overtime
was God-sent and our hope for our future. Then Gov. (Pete) Wilson
came along and wiped out daily overtime, stating companies would
not abuse the new law. Wrong! As soon as the new law went into
effect, not only did the company my husband works for stop all
overtime, they cut hours, making sure no employee got 40 hours for
fear of the possibility of overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to cancel plans for saving and once again we are going
to lose our rental home because we can't survive on less than 40
hours a week at $8 an hour ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Only the middle class and wealthy can survive in this country.
The government claims we should be responsible for our own
retirement. How, when someone is always in your pocket? We should
be responsible to train for new jobs. Why, when my husband was
jobless for over two years because he was `too old'?
</P>
<P>
   ``We are proud, hard-working people who could only afford two
vacations in 35 years; the last one was in 1985 ... We have to
decide between eating less or paying an overdue utility bill. We
can't even afford to buy a computer to catch up with the world. We
both drive old cars; even hobbies cost money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we think about people who have less than we do, children
going hungry ... We send $20 a month (to a fund for needy children
in Appalachia) even though it's hard, but we can do without
something to help feed children.
</P>
<P>
   ``No wonder there's so much stress, anger, hopelessness and
suicide in this world ... Greed is destroying this country, and
people don't care about people anymore. No wonder people don't care
to vote anymore, don't care to get involved and see no light at the
end of the tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband and I will be married 36 years this November, and
the love we share for each other has been the only thing that has
gotten us through so much heartache. We had to sell everything we
owned and accumulated over 35 years to pay for a place to live when
we lost our home. Now we're on the edge of probably having to move
again, finding some small place to live, giving up our yard and
nice area where we feel safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``No wonder our youth is so troubled and lacks respect. They see
the greed, downsizing, companies moving to other countries because
of the all-mighty dollar, parents struggling and needing two
incomes to survive, leaving children without a parent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too late for us. We're in our 50s and our goals and
dreams were shattered, but we need to save our children, our
grandchildren. Even athletes have priced us out of taking our
9-year-old grandson to a ballgame. We can't afford the price of a
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel sorry for myself. I just see others hurting. I
see my husband with high blood pressure, losing his dignity and
worrying about me and our future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the answer is or if there is one. I hurt for
so many. We're used to doing without and, at our age, no one cares
anyway, but many do need someone to care. Our country is falling
apart and being destroyed ... Our children are hurting, towns are
hurting, the elderly are hurting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't anyone see what's happening, or does anyone care as long
they keep building their financial wealth? Do they think their
money will buy their way to Heaven?''
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, I spoke at length with Sharon Hodge and learned a
lot more about her. She and James, a truck driver, live from
paycheck to paycheck but haven't lost their rental home. Yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some days you almost want to feel sorry for yourself,'' she
said. ``But then you've got to sort of slap yourself in the face.
You have to believe something will come along.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
