<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREGNANT ONIONS CRAVE SUNLIGHT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Sarasota, Fla.) 
 
By KATHY HUBER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Q: A friend gave me a pregnant onion. Will you give me
some information on this plant?
</P>
<P>
   A: The pregnant onion (``Ornithogalum caudatum'') is a curious
plant that also goes by the common names false sea onion, German
onion and healing onion. The name pregnant onion is appropriate,
since tiny bulbs appear on the mother bulb. These small bulbs grow
larger, then fall to the soil's surface and become new plants.
</P>
<P>
   The pregnant onion likes sun or partial sun. Do not overwater.
The mother bulb is planted with most of its girth above the soil
line. I'm guessing yours is in a container, as these are often
grown as pot plants. A potting soil amended with a little composted
manure and sharp sand is an ideal growing medium. You can plant
pregnant onion in the garden in a protected area, in an enriched,
well-draining soil. A little sand under the bulb will help. Mulch
well in cold weather. Again, plant with the top half of the bulb
above the soil.
</P>
<P>
   Long, straplike leaves will grow from the bulb. The numerous,
half-inch white blooms appear on long stems in spring or summer.
When the mom has finished flowering, hold off on the water for a
while and let her rest.
</P>
<P>
   Q: On trips to Bermuda and Florida I have seen fascinating
banyan trees. I obtained some seeds from the Sarasota, Fla., area
and would love to grow a banyan tree here. I don't recall seeing
any in Texas and would like to know if they can do well in the
Houston area.
</P>
<P>
   A: I have seen the curious banyans in the Sarasota area, too,
but, like you, have never seen them here, only relatives in the
genus Ficus. The banyan tree, ``Ficus benghalensis,'' is also
called East Indian fig tree, and it is remarkable in that it
produces aerial roots from the branches. These aerial roots grow
toward the ground, then root and become trunks. The banyan is a
fast grower, and, as additional trunks are developed, the tree can
have a crown that spreads 100 yards in diameter. You can see why it
would be valued as a shade tree.
</P>
<P>
   The problem here would be protecting it from freezing weather.
It prefers a more truly tropical climate.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a plant _ and its seeds _ sent to me from
Pennsylvania. It was classified as a hosta. It disperses large
quantities of seeds after blooming, dies in the fall, but returns
in the spring. My plant is doing well but has not bloomed yet. The
seeds that I planted last year have sprouted but have remained
small, only about 3 inches in height. I'm wondering if this is
something other than a hosta, since none of mine throw seeds.
</P>
<P>
   A: The leaf you sent looks like that from a hosta. And what
you've described is typical of hostas. These perennials do
disappear in the fall and return in spring.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, various hostas have been tested in our area to find
those that do best in our climate. Certain hybrids have proven to
be more vigorous than others, but many hostas take their time in
gaining any size, so 3-inch seedlings don't surprise me. Some of
those I'm testing have flowered sooner than others. Yours may have
needed a longer adjustment period, or it may be one that typically
flowers later in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   The original hostas in your garden may be hybrids that aren't
big seed producers, or they could be sterile and produce no seed.
</P>
<P>
   We have a shady back garden, so I'm constantly looking for
plants with striking foliage as well as those with colorful
flowers. Hostas have traditionally been grown for their bold or
textural leaves, but lately more attention is being directed at
those with better flowers.
</P>
<P>
   The key to growing any hosta here is a fertile, well-draining
soil; an hour or two of morning sun followed by bright shade or a
day in bright shade; and sufficient moisture to encourage good
growth. However, the most surprising thing about the established
hostas in our garden is their ability to even survive in this
drought. I water them, but they have not required watering as
frequently as some other plants. And varieties such as `Francee'
don't look that bedraggled by the heat.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I purchased red canna bulbs last summer and planted them in
the fall. Nothing came up, and the company replaced them this
summer. I don't know whether to plant them or not. I placed the
bulbs in a clean plastic bag and put them in the refrigerator
vegetable bin. Can I plant them now?
</P>
<P>
   A: Cannas are extremely popular these days. Tropicals are a
growing gardening trend, even up North.
</P>
<P>
   Canna rhizomes do not need to be refrigerated. I would remove
them (you don't want them to rot), check to make sure they are in
good condition and plant them now in a moist but well-draining soil
that you've enriched with compost.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Do not store bulbs in refrigerator bins with fruits and
vegetables, as the ethylene gas produced by these foods can destroy
the bulbs' ability to flower.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, Garden Editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston, Texas 77210. The bulk of mail
prevents individual replies to all unpublished letters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
