<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 12:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6108 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRAHAM-CHILDREN-2TAKE     08-10 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAHAM-CHILDREN-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMOUS PREACHER'S CHILDREN BLAZING THEIR OWN TRAILS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CECILE S. HOLMES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The heir to Billy Graham's evangelical mantle ducked
his head, tugging on his baseball cap as his older sister confessed
her difficulties remembering her busy speaking schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to remember where the last place was I spoke,''
said Anne Graham Lotz. ``You know I'm taking those herbs that are
supposed to help with your memory.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You've already turned 50, right?'' William Franklin Graham
III, her younger sibling, said, eyes twinkling. ``Ought to try a
Diet Coke. That's what I do.''
</P>
<P>
   His almost-as-famous sister ignored him. ``Let's see now: Labor
Day weekend I'm doing Cross Seekers in New Orleans. I'll have
15,000 college kids for that. Then I have three weekends at the
Billy Graham Training Center in the fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Like her brother, Lotz is a respected Christian author, teacher
and public speaker with her own outreach project, AnGel Ministries.
Friends talk about her common sense and sensitivity.
</P>
<P>
   Like his sister, Graham is winning accolades for offering the
Gospel in a way that reaches his own generation.
</P>
<P>
   Both promoted their new books during a recent Christian
Booksellers Association meeting in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Lotz's new book, ``God's Story: Finding Meaning For Your Life In
Genesis'' (Word, $17.99) helps average believers approach the
Christian Bible's first book as ``God's eyewitness account of
Creation.'' Written with a personal, poetic style, the volume takes
readers inside Lotz's head and heart. Her writing reveals a
searching soul with an intense, passionate faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flashing-red-light warning for you and me is to beware
getting so caught up in the way everyone around us is living that
we get swept away by the current of wickedness and waste our own
lives in a meaningless existence,'' she writes. ``In the midst of
spiritual dwarfs, we must strive to be giants.''
</P>
<P>
   It takes prayer and self-discipline to keep that goal in sight,
say Lotz and Graham. She talked about the importance of daily
private devotions; he stressed conveying God's word in preaching
and outreach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think preaching is something God honors and something he
blesses,'' Graham said. ``We're using his Word. It's not my word. I
think people are tired of the overweight preacher in a three-piece
suit with slick hair and rings on his fingers and kind of talking
down to them. I don't want to do that. I want to try to relate on
their level.''
</P>
<P>
   At 45, Graham operates his own emergency relief agency,
Samaritan's Purse. Headquartered in Boone, N.C., it has an annual
budget of nearly $50 million and provides assistance in Africa,
Asia, Eastern Europe and other areas of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Graham writes about others' faith and his own in his new book,
``Living Beyond the Limits'' (Thomas Nelson, $19.99.) His faith has
taken him into danger-filled, war-torn regions where he has met
people determined to serve God by helping others.
</P>
<P>
   Aviation metaphors run through the volume. ``I love to fly
airplanes,'' he confesses, ``especially the Mitsubishi MU2. The MU2
is known in the aviation industry as `the rice rocket.' It will get
me where I need to go really quick. In the Christian life, just
like in a plane, you need a good take-off _ salvation in Jesus
Christ. But just as important, you want to be able to fly safely,
navigate around the storms, and eventually land at the ultimate
destination without crashing.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Graham family and friends, Franklin's exploits as a child
and adolescent were famous. He is the fourth of Billy and Ruth Bell
Graham's five children. In his youth, he loved fast cars, his
beat-up pickup, dirt bikes and pranks that drove his mother and
sisters crazy.
</P>
<P>
   The devilish youngster so taxed his mother that once, in
exasperation, she shut him in the trunk of the family's car en
route to a fast-food restaurant after he wouldn't quit pinching his
sisters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Franklin would agree, my mother raised five of us
pretty much without Daddy,'' Lotz recalled. ``I had somebody
actually say to me that they knew Daddy had preached all over the
world but they never thought about that he had to leave home to do
it. So we were in one sense raised by a single parent.''
</P>
<P>
   Today all five Graham offpspring are grown with children. All
are Christians involved in outreach. Gigi Graham Tchividjian, the
oldest, who lives in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., is an author and
speaker. Ruth McIntyre, the third daughter who wrote a Bible
storybook for children, is a teacher and speaker. She lives in
Virginia, and works for Samaritan's Purse. Ned Graham, the
youngest, who lives in Seattle, heads East Gates Ministries
International, which has distributed 2 million copies of Scriptures
in China.
</P>
<P>
   Lotz says her own determination to keep seeking God even when he
seemed faraway springs from her mother's stalwart faith and her
father's devoted evangelizing.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a girl, I loved the Lord and I loved his Word. When I
drifted from him, I looked back and I could see my mother raising
the five of us without a husband present in the home everyday. And
I never saw her lose her temper, just completely come unglued. And
after being with Franklin all day, you could have had the tendency
to lose your temper!''
</P>
<P>
   In his 20s, her younger brother says, he turned to Christ after
meeting energetic people ``living exhilarating lives without the
shallowness that plagued my own.'' He began serving on the board of
his father's ministry in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, the Billy Graham Evangelistic Association _
which organizes the crusades led by him and his father _ elected
the younger Graham as its first vice-chairman. That puts him in
line to succeed his father as the association's chairman and CEO.
He is expected to take the reins of an evangelical empire with an
operating budget of $91 million. Gradually, the elder Graham, 79,
who has Parkinson's disease, is passing responsibilities to his
son.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Graham still does several crusades annually, with an
upcoming one in Tampa, Fla. Franklin Graham leads six-10 crusades
each year, speaking in 1998 in Louisiana, Virginia, New Mexico,
North Carolina, and in Australia and Peru.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While he still insists no one will ever fill Billy Graham's
shoes, Graham's strength as a preacher is growing. In evangelical
and celebrity circles, he cuts a higher and higher profile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a little different type style,'' he says. ``I give the
invitation (altar call in his father's day) at the beginning and
the end of the meeting, hoping people will understand what I'm
really trying to do. We use music a lot, but then, so did my
father. He came out of the big band era.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham, married with four children, travels like his dad did,
but is rarely gone more than two weeks at a time. He tries to keep
his work and family separated.
</P>
<P>
   He likes to preach, but admits he'll never lose his love of the
hands-on relief ministry of Samaritan's Purse. Its outreach
includes the now-famous Operation Christmas Child. In that project,
American children and parents prepare shoeboxes of Christmas gifts
and necessities that Samaritan's Purse airlifts to needy kids
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's outreach in countries such as Bosnia amazes Lotz, who
notes that he ``goes to places nobody else goes to around the
world.'' Her brother praises his sister's work, complimenting her
dedication and wide following.
</P>
<P>
   When the two were part of an interfaith meeting of religious
leaders with President Clinton several years ago, it was Lotz, not
Graham, who was most eloquent, Graham said. After she challenged
U.S. leaders, including Clinton, to admit the nation needs a
spiritual anchor and to follow God and the Ten Commandments, people
came up and said, ``Franklin, you have some kind of sister.''
</P>
<P>
   Lotz, soft-voiced and naturally shy, says it took her years to
learn to speak before crowds. Married to a dentist in Raleigh,
N.C., she has three grown children. Her move into public life began
with Bible Study Fellowship, a Scripture class she started in 1976.
Her first weekly class attracted hundreds of women. She never
missed teaching a class for 12 years. Today, Bible Study
Fellowship, headquartered in San Antonio, is worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   As their parents age and their contemporaries return to church,
both Graham and Lotz are carving niches suited to their gifts. Each
has star qualities. Graham's thick shock of hair and piercing eyes
are reminiscent of his dad's good looks. Lotz, whose style is
gentle and authoritative at the same time, has the contagious smile
and tanned, long-legged beauty of her mother.
</P>
<P>
   Typical of the individualistic Graham children, they agree on
many issues. But they explore, teach and preach about them in
different ways.
</P>
<P>
   Graham possesses the fiery preaching style of his father's early
years, stressing that turning to Jesus is the only way to achieve
salvation. In sermons, he is critical of errant lifestyles,
including homosexuality and declining family values. But his
outlook on women in ministry is open-minded. So is his sister's.
She attended a Southern Baptist congregation in Raleigh, N.C.; he
goes to the Mount Vernon Baptist Church in Boone.
</P>
<P>
   Lotz is comfortable preaching, but believes God has
``forbidden'' her to be ordained and calls her to a different kind
of ministry. ``I have really some wonderful friends. One of the
women who was a mentor to me was an ordained woman in a
congregation in California. If other women feel God is leading them
to that, I respect what God is leading them to. I don't think the
Scripture is black and white on that.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Graham says he has no objections to women in ministry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think there are problems that come up in a church that
probably a man needs to handle. There's a lot of politics that goes
on in churches. Sometimes you just need somebody who can be
half-mean, who can be real tough,'' Graham said, noting that
doesn't mean women are too gentle-spirited to preach or pastor. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Growing up a Graham wasn't always easy, but being the offspring
of the world's most famous, most traveled evangelist made it
interesting. Growing up in the western North Carolina mountain town
of Montreat, they endured some of the trials peculiar to the
offspring of the famous. Franklin rebelled. Anne married young, had
three kids and felt distanced from the certain faith of her
childhood.
</P>
<P>
   Both credit the common sense, sound judgment and good parenting
of their mother, Ruth Bell Graham, for imparting to them the faith
and values they hold so dear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew she drew her strength from spending time in God's
word,'' Lotz said. ``She had a big flat-top desk with 14 different
translations of the Bible laid out. If she had any time during the
day, she was back there reading her Bible. At night, I would slip
down to her room and find her on her knees in prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Often she asked for help with her kids, the siblings say.
Watching them spar verbally, it is easy to imagine rearing five was
a task worthy of a drill sergeant and saint.
</P>
<P>
   Did Graham and Lotz always get along so well?
</P>
<P>
   Lotz is sweet, even laudatory: ``I've always loved Franklin. He
goes into areas of the world others won't touch.''
</P>
<P>
   Didn't they ever fight? Lotz demurs, and Graham grins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to get beat up,'' says Billy Graham's successor.
``Remember, she's older than I am.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
