<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ShortTakes: Spielberg's Normandy
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan,'' Steven Spielberg's account of D-Day,
richly deserves the box office and praise it is receiving.
``Private Ryan'' is three movies. The first is a searing depiction
of Omaha Beach. The second, the finding of Pvt. Ryan, is long and
in search of a larger theme. The third is a fight for a French
village, every battle scene you've ever seen done better. Omaha
Beach carries the rest to greatness.
</P>
<P>
   The middle film deserves a weightier theme. For such a theme,
find a tape, if there is one, of Stanley Kubrick's 1957 ``Paths of
Glory,'' starring Kirk Douglas, a seldom-discussed movie that may
be the best war film ever made. The film concerns the World War I
French troop mutinies, and the incompetence, indifference and
careerism that produced them. Some soldiers are tried for cowardice
and defended by their regimental commander, Douglas as Col. Dax.
The theme is the responsibility of governments and command. It is a
terrible indictment of war. If the final scene does not break your
heart, nothing will.
</P>
<P>
   Good as ``Private Ryan'' is, Spielberg gives us something less:
Is Pvt. Ryan worth dying for? Given the Omaha Beach scene, that
falls short as an ultimate question. American filmmakers have just
about exhausted the potential of our World War II involvement. For
a reason. You couldn't get 10 people out on a Sunday afternoon to
see, for instance, one of the Eastern front's obscure daily
slaughters.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
