<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SACRE BLEU,' IT'S A NEW REVOLUTION! 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The natives are restless across the pond.
</P>
<P>
   The feisty French are squabbling about food again. And the
normally placid Brits are replaying the Battle of the Sexes, this
time in the name of _ gulp! _ travel writing.
</P>
<P>
   First, the hors d'oeuvres:
</P>
<P>
   We can always depend on the annual designation of Michelin's
revered restaurant stars to create outrage among chefs whose
kitchens are demoted or ignored. But at least Michelin's system is
steeped in French tradition. And only a true connoisseur of
gastronomy _ certainly not the fellow staring at me from the
mirror, the guy who confuses ``veau rognons'' for ``escalope de
veau'' on a menu _ is admitted into the hallowed judging process.
</P>
<P>
   But now, heresy. Common diners are evaluating eateries in Paris.
More than 1,700 diners. At 330,000 meals. And, horror of horrors,
in a survey designed and perfected by Americans.
</P>
<P>
   On Bastille Day (July 14), 80,000 copies of the first Zagat
Survey of Paris restaurants hit the ``rues'' of the capital. And as
Zagat publicists delight in suggesting, a new French Revolution
commenced.
</P>
<P>
   No matter that previous Zagat surveys covering 44 cities or
regions in the United States and Canada are considered the culinary
bibles of North America. Or that Zagat already had invaded London.
As a Parisian aristocrat might say between nibbles of Pyrenees lamb
at Taillevent, who can go wrong grading fish and chips?
</P>
<P>
   The Zagat approach is ``a scandal,'' sniffed Alexandre Lazareff,
head of the French Culinary Writers' Association. He elaborated:
``It's the very negation of a guidebook; it's done by polls.''
</P>
<P>
   Gault Millau, heretofore the upstart challenger to Michelin in
evaluating Parisian restaurants, called the Zagat Survey
``z'agacant,'' a play on the French word for ``annoying.''
</P>
<P>
   Fueling the fire were kinder comments in the French press. While
conceding that the survey has ``spread terror through kitchens,''
Le Monde suggested that Zagat has made ``the client finally king.''
Paris Match termed the guide ``the ultimate in good taste.'' And Le
Figaro boldly ordained it ``as good as Michelin.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey results themselves brought little surprise. The three
highest rated restaurants _ Taillevent, Arpege and Ambroisie _ all
possess the maximum three Michelin stars. So why the uproar? ``This
is the first time that French diners have been asked to vote on
their restaurants,'' co-publisher Nina Zagat says. ``Our guides are
founded on the simple, but seemingly revolutionary, premise that
many palates are better than one.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, unlike the handful of critics overseeing Michelin's
composite three-star system, Zagat surveyors gave individual grades
for food, decor and _ don't you wish American tourists were allowed
to participate? _ service.
</P>
<P>
   One palate or 1,710 palates _ these are still French palates.
With French pride. (Did someone say ``arrogance''?) The average
grades were lower (15 for food, 13 for decor and 14 for service on
a 30-point scale) than in London (18, 15 and 16) or New York (19,
16 and 17). But when diners were asked to pinpoint their main
complaints, less than 1 percent cited French food. And all of the
highest-rated eateries _ and the vast majority of 825 restaurants
covered _ serve some variant of French cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   Two last bits of intrigue: The average meal in this survey cost
$48.23, compared with $30.69 in New York. And unlike most Zagat
surveys, in which male and female participants are usually
balanced, 71 percent of respondents in Paris were men.
</P>
<P>
   Which takes us across the channel to England.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Guardian newspaper, 11 female authors have
declared war on gung-ho travel writing (by men), claiming that the
genre is dying and should be put out of its misery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had enough (men) in the jungle,'' said Dea Birkett,
co-editor of Amazonian, an anthology of women's travel writing
published by Penguin in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men want to conquer the territory they travel through and put
a flag on it,'' Birkett told the newspaper. ``But women want to be
conquered by the territory, to be enchanted and intrigued by it.
That makes for better writing.''
</P>
<P>
   The real essence of travel, Birkett said, is the inner journey.
</P>
<P>
   Balderdash _ or something like that _ responded explorer Wilfred
Thesinger, 88, who shot 70 lions in Sudan and 2,000 boars in Iraq.
``I don't think it's right that (women) should dominate,''
Thesinger told the Guardian. ``They're not equipped for
exploration.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast, chimed in traveler Redmon O'Hanlon, who suggested
women are better travelers. ``All the so-called primitive groups
respond better to women,'' O'Hanlon said. ``Women are better at
gossiping; they get information faster.''
</P>
<P>
   That's THESINGER and O'HANLON speaking, not Shattuck. I'll leave
the Brits to their gender dispute. I'm still juggling ``rognons''
and ``escalope.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
