<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-SHIP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHIP CASTS AWAY DOUBTS ABOUT DISNEY'S LATEST VENTURE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By SYD KEARNEY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CANAVERAL, Fla. _ In 1928, Mickey Mouse made a splash as
Steamboat Willie in the world's first sound cartoon.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy years later, ol' Mickey is back at the helm. This time,
he's aboard the 83,000-ton cruise ship dubbed Disney Magic.
</P>
<P>
   And while the four-fingered fellow may not be physically at the
ship's wheel, don't be fooled. Mickey is steering this ship.
</P>
<P>
   The neophyte Disney Cruise Line, which launched its inaugural
cruise July 30, isn't just selling a cruise. It is also selling the
Disney experience.
</P>
<P>
   From the pool-side pizzeria named for Pinocchio, the G-rated
audience-participation game shows, the Captain Hook-themed indoor
playground and the mock-tails served at an under-age-only coffee
bar, the theme is family fun.
</P>
<P>
   The Magic doesn't even have a casino, a sacred cash cow for most
cruise lines.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Disney is gambling on seven-day Walt Disney
Resort/cruise vacation packages with double-occupancy prices
starting at $1,295 per person. Guests choose from a three-day
resort stay with four-night cruise or four-day land stay with
three-night cruise. The ship's Bahamian ports of call are Nassau
and a private island known as Castaway Cay.
</P>
<P>
   (When the Disney Wonder, the Magic's twin sister ship, begins
sailing in March, it also will offer three- and four-day cruises,
alternating its itineraries with the Magic.)
</P>
<P>
   On a two-day cruise for the media, we checked out the Disney
Magic and compared it to the hype. The ship was elegant and
impressive and, overall, the cruise satisfactory, but there simply
wasn't enough time or young people aboard to judge the children's
programs, which are the centerpieces of the Disney cruise
experience.
</P>
<P>
   That said, here are some observations:
</P>
<P>
   _ The best space on the ship is Common Grounds, a teen coffee
house where you'd expect to find Jennifer Aniston and pals perched
on the overstuffed sofas. A bar serves coffee drinks and
exotic-looking mock-tails to teens seeking a temporary escape from
parental units and younger siblings. A jukebox spins the latest
music CDs. Don't like what's playing? Reach for one of the many
headphones stationed throughout the room and select alternative
tunes. A large-screen TV, computers and game tables round out this
space.
</P>
<P>
   _ The variety of children's programs is unprecedented on a
cruise line. The Oceaneer Adventure, which takes up nearly a full
deck, provides counselor-supervised programs for children ages 3 to
12. Onboard programs, which are divided by six age groups, may
involve costumes and computers, while shore excursions may feature
scavenger hunts or silly relays.
</P>
<P>
   With supervision provided from 9 a.m. to 1 a.m., ``our
children's programs allow parents to become adults,'' says Erling
Frydenberg, Disney Cruise Line's vice president of operations.
These newly emancipated parents can then enjoy the many adults-only
venues offered on Disney Magic. Among them:
</P>
<P>
   _ Beat Street, a collection of themed nightclubs that includes a
comedy club, piano bar and dance hall with live music.
</P>
<P>
   _ Vista Spa and Salon, which features a state-of-the-art fitness
center, aromatherapy steam rooms and pampering treatments such as
massages and facials.
</P>
<P>
   _ Palo, the romantic, reservations-only Italian restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of restaurants, Disney Magic's rotation dining plan is
unique to cruising. Each evening, passengers rotate to one of three
themed restaurants. While your dining room changes, your table
mates and servers remain the same.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurants include Lumiere's, an attractive, French-tinged
dining room that pays tribute to ``Beauty and the Beast''; the
casual and colorful Parrot Cay, a salute to the vibrant style of
the Bahamas; and Animator's Palate, where Disney Imagineers seemed
to have had the most fun.
</P>
<P>
   Animator's Palate is really a dinner show. Guests arrive to find
the restaurant _ and the server's uniform's _ starkly black and
white. As the meal progresses, sketches on the wall begin to show
color. By the time dessert _ here it's called a ``mouseterpiece'' _
is served the room is ablaze with color. Even the wait staff's
jackets _ in a quick-change trick _ are now brightly colored.
</P>
<P>
   For guests not wanting to eat at scheduled seatings, Topsider
Buffet serves lunch and dinner. Poolside snacks can be found at
Pinocchio's Pizzeria, Pluto's Dog House and Scoops, an ice cream
stand.
</P>
<P>
   So what about the food?
</P>
<P>
   Let's just say that it is what you'd expect from a company that
has built its travel reputation on theme parks. A Palo pizza
appetizer was tasty, but a poolside slice was barely passable.
Barbecue served on the cruise line's private island was jeered and
the Parmesan and Herb-Crusted Veal Cutlets at Animator's Palate
needed work.
</P>
<P>
   Service was friendly, earnest and surprisingly smooth
considering that only 40 percent of the crew had cruise experience
before the ship's five two-day shakedown cruises.
</P>
<P>
   While the kitchen could _ and should _ improve, it would be hard
to beat the Disney Magic's entertainment lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to raise the bar here, and we have succeeded in a
number of ways,'' says Disney Cruise Line president Art Rodney,
stopping short of earlier boasts that the entertainment giant would
``revolutionize'' the cruise industry.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Disney has raised the entertainment bar. Its 975-seat
Walt Disney Theater is unrivaled at sea. The stage uses three decks
above and three decks below to hold the scenery and props used in
three original, Broadway-style musical productions.
</P>
<P>
   The productions, all featuring sophisticated lighting and
special effects, include ``Disney Dreams,'' a ``bedtime'' story
starring beloved characters such as Peter Pan and Cinderella;
``Voyage of the Ghost Ship,'' an action tale with pirates and
illusions; and ``Hercules: A Muse-ical Comedy,'' which director of
entertainment Cliff Perry describes as Henny Youngman meets Jon
Lovitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we did our homework,'' Perry says of the productions.
``We found out what guests wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   What guests wanted were entertainment options. In addition to
the musicals, the Disney Magic also offers the trio of Beat Street
clubs, Studio Sea, a family dance club that hosts
guest-participation game shows, and ESPN Skybox, where guests can
gather to watch sporting programming including live events in a
high energy setting. The ESPN Skybox takes its name from its unique
position inside the ship's front funnel on Deck 11.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, guests will find a movie theater, video arcade,
three pools and a sports deck for activities such as basketball,
paddle tennis, volleyball and badminton.
</P>
<P>
   First-time cruisers, which Disney expects will make up a large
percentage of its customers, may not appreciate the size of the
Magic's cabins. The staterooms are about 25 percent larger than the
average cruise ship. One- and two-bedroom suites can sleep as many
as five in relative spaciousness. More than 70 percent of the
cabins have ocean views, many with private verandahs.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you must pay for this spaciousness.
</P>
<P>
   A Disney cruise will cost an average of 20 percent more than a
similar cruise with another line. With the Disney resort-and-cruise
vacation, guests also get air fare; a three- or four-day stay at a
Walt Disney World Resort; unlimited admission to the four WDW theme
parks, including the new Animal Kingdom; unlimited admission to the
three Disney water parks, as well as admission to Pleasure Island,
the resort's evening entertainment complex, and Disney's Wild World
of Sports; unlimited use of the WDW transportation system; a three-
or four-day cruise to the Bahamas; and ground transfers between the
resort, the ship and the Orlando airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't sell price,'' explains Disney Cruise Line president
Art Rodney. ``We're not the economy cruise. We sell value.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want people to leave the ship saying this was the best
vacation they've ever had. You can't put a price on that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rodney did.
</P>
<P>
   Vacation packages start at $1,295 per person based on double
occupancy. Children ages 3 to 17 sharing a cabin with two adults
pay $999.
</P>
<P>
   Call 800-WDW-CRUISE or a travel agent. You also can visit Disney
Cruise Line's Web site at www.disneycruise.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-98 1300EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
