<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-ISLAND-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTYING IN DISNEY'S PARADISE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By SYD KEARNEY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Private islands are not new to the cruise scene.
</P>
<P>
   Norwegian Cruise Line started the trend when it bought a
four-mile strip in the Bahamas in 1977. Now most cruise lines claim
their own isle.
</P>
<P>
   Disney Cruise Line's Castaway Cay was designed to fulfill the
traveler's dream of paradise: towering palm trees, acres of
white-sand beaches and incandescent blue water. Toss in a
snorkeling course, biking and hiking trails, sea kayaks,
watercraft, two bars, a massage cabana, a barbecue shack,
umbrella-shaded lounge chairs and a rockin' reggae band.
</P>
<P>
   Whew, it's a nonstop party. In paradise.
</P>
<P>
   And Disney folks are quick to say that they didn't do much to
improve the island _ if you don't count the 500-foot dock that
allows Disney Magic guests almost instant access to the beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We enhanced what already was there,'' says Jim Durham, Walt
Disney Imagineering Project Manager for Castaway Cay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just let Mother Nature show her beauty,'' Durham says,
adding, ``We didn't kill a tree'' as they added guest services such
as restrooms and bars.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-five Disney staffers live on the island, but Disney has
no plans to open it to overnight guests.
</P>
<P>
   The only way to see ``paradise'' is to book a Disney cruise.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-98 1300EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980810.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 13:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6123 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-10 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STICKY WICKET IN PRIVATIZATION OF WELFARE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ There is money to be made from welfare. Or so
the decision-makers at Gtech Corp. thought when they bid for _ and
won _ a contract from state government to operate the Lone Star
Card.
</P>
<P>
   That's the debit-type card system that electronically provides
welfare and food stamp benefits to low-income Texans.
</P>
<P>
   Gtech was eager to keep cashing in on the expanding popularity
of government privatization. Instead, its welfare venture has cast
some more doubt on public-private partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   Gtech already was making millions off the Texas lottery, which
it operated under a separate state contract, when it formed a
subsidiary, Transactive Corp., to bid for the welfare business.
</P>
<P>
   Transactive outbid a competitor, Citicorp Services, for the Lone
Star contract in 1994 but soon started regretting it.
</P>
<P>
   When welfare rolls started dropping, thanks to an improved
economy and welfare reforms, Gtech discovered the welfare business
wasn't so lucrative after all.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Gtech asked the state for a better deal, but state
officials refused and held the company to its contract. Now, Gtech
is trying to sell its Lone Star Card business to Citicorp, the
losing bidder in 1994, and the U.S. Department of Justice is
raising a red flag.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department has filed a federal lawsuit to block the
proposed sale because, government lawyers argue, it would reduce
competition in the welfare delivery business and threaten savings
that state governments _ and their taxpayers _ hope to realize from
electronic transfer systems.
</P>
<P>
   Gtech also wants to sell to Citicorp other electronic welfare
systems that it operates in Illinois, Indiana and Sacremento
County, Calif. Citicorp already has contracts for similar systems
in 28 other states.
</P>
<P>
   Some may say it's un-American and anti-free enterprise for the
government to try to keep a private company from selling a business
the company doesn't find profitable _ or profitable enough to be
worth the trouble.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, however, the Justice Department's anti-trust
division, which initiated the suit, isn't trying to keep Gtech from
selling its welfare delivery contracts. It is only trying to block
a sale to Citicorp, which, it said, would give that company a
virtual monopoly on running electronic benefits systems in states
that already have them.
</P>
<P>
   And the monopoly could grow, because federal law will require
all the states to put welfare benefits on electronic transfer
systems by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of electronic transfers _ Comptroller John Sharp has
been one of the biggest advocates in Texas _ say they are a more
efficient way of distributing benefits and also reduce fraud by
eliminating paper food stamps, which some people used to illegally
sell.
</P>
<P>
   By requiring states to use electronic systems, federal lawmakers
may have thought they also were encouraging competition and cost
savings in the private sector because this is the type of work that
state governments would likely contract out to private operators.
</P>
<P>
   It is true the states are contracting the systems out, but only
two corporate giants have expressed much interest in operating
them. And one of those companies, Gtech, is now trying to bail out
to concentrate on the more lucrative business of running lotteries.
</P>
<P>
   So one arm of the federal government, Congress, may have
inadvertently encouraged the development of a monopoly that now
another government arm, the Justice Department, finds it necessary
to fight.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be the first time that government has ended up
contradicting itself.
</P>
<P>
   Privatization of some government services still offers the
promise of savings through the expertise and efficiency that free
enterprise can offer. But it must be approached with care.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, private companies consider their business records
private, an attitude that often conflicts with the public's right
to have its business conducted and recorded in public, even if the
business is conducted by a private company.
</P>
<P>
   And businesses, unlike government, have to make a profit.
</P>
<P>
   If Texas' state government had operated its own electronic
welfare system, state officials _ and taxpayers _ would have simply
applauded their budgetary savings when the welfare rolls started
dropping.
</P>
<P>
   But Transactive, whose payments are based on the number of
people receiving food stamps and cash assistance, considered the
reduced welfare caseload a disaster because the reductions were
more than had been projected when its contract was bid.
Consequently, the company started trying to change or get out of
the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Transactive negotiated a bad contract. Maybe Texas chose
the wrong company to operate the Lone Star Card.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe privatization and welfare, at least in this case,
weren't a natural fit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
