<SLUG> BC-FBN-SIMMS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER GIANT GEARS UP FOR APPEARANCE ON NEW TEAM: CBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PETE DOUGHERTY  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Game days were the worst. Although he took his last
snap with the New York Giants in 1993, for Phil Simms the urge
lingered every time he entered a stadium in his new career as a
broadcaster. He wanted to be out there throwing passes, running the
two-minute drill, even handing off.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do get addicted to it,'' Simms said, ``to the life, to the
playing, to the fun, to the work.'' Over the course of last season,
Simms' third with NBC and fourth as an NFL analyst, the player
finally was exorcised and the broadcaster emerged. Not that he let
the withdrawal symptoms from football affect his work in the booth.
He was on NBC's lead announcing team and will do the same for CBS,
which won the American Conference rights from its network rival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably for the first time, I really relaxed and said it's
over,'' Simms said. ``I didn't go to the game thinking, `I'd really
like to be in uniform today.' That's over now. It's good. It's a
little more relaxing. It makes me more committed to my job than
ever before.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS has high hopes for this rising star, who spent 15 years in
one NFL uniform but already is with his third network. Simms showed
his potential in a one-year stint at ESPN, enough to warrant NBC
gambling not only to hire him, but putting him with Dick Enberg and
Paul Maguire to cover the network's ``A'' game each week.
</P>
<P>
   Simms proved to be a worthwhile risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a quarterback got hurt, he is so up on the game plan and
the trends of the game, he could dress up and play,'' said Mark
Wolff, the lead NFL producer for CBS. ``He studies as hard as
anybody I know.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a lot of guys who we've shown how to do that,''
director Larry Cavolina added, ``but he does naturally.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This has slowly weaned me off of playing,'' Simms said. ``It's
good to be around it. I love going and hanging out and watching
practice, watching the personality of the coach. We have pretty
good access where we get to talk to the coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he rarely gets interviewed where he isn't asked about
whether he can be critical of coaches and players he shared the
sidelines with only a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Simms said he just gives his views of the game, regardless of
consequence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never, since I've been in the booth, have I thought, `Well,
I'd better not say that, because somebody might get upset,''' he
said. ``It just doesn't cross your mind. I said something once
about Bill (Parcells) that was pretty critical. People applauded
me. So I see Bill, and I say something to him about it, and he
says, `Simms, I don't care. If you said it, it was probably true.'
He trusted my opinion because he knows I know what was happening.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like having a current player sitting there in the booth
and saying exactly what's happening on the field and what's going
through their minds,'' said Greg Gumbel, Simms' new partner. ``He's
a contemporary. He just happens to be in the booth. That's a
tremendous advantage over someone saying, `Well, the way I used to
do it ...,' back in the days of the leather helmets. His ability to
perceive what's happening on the field is exceptional.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What Gumbel and CBS hope adds to the telecasts is that Simms
should have more air time. CBS won't use a three-man booth,
although Armen Keteyian has been hired as a sideline reporter for
the ``A'' team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe Phil had the time, from a pure mathematics
point of view, to say the things he could say during a game,''
Gumbel said. ``He won't have those problems with me. I'll tell you
what down it is and how many yards to go, then get the hell out of
his way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Three people in a car compared to two _ the road is less
crowded,'' Simms said. ``It just makes it easier. Now, can you make
it better? Just because it's easier, it doesn't make it better.
That's what we're going to try to accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   Simms was at Giants' camp last week doing some homework and
renewing acquaintances. He didn't leave Albany until 10 o'clock
that night, spending most of that time with head coach Jim Fassel,
Simms' former quarterback coach and offensive coordinator with the
Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great being around Jim, seeing the team and the guys,''
he said. ``I got a chance to really sit back and watch football
again. I felt like a player in camp. It was awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   At least it wasn't game day.
</P>
</TEXT>
