<HEADLINE>
CAIRO'S $7 BILLION SUBWAY SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO _ On the streets of a city known for its horrific traffic,
only the beggars move.
</P>
<P>
   Weaving between cars stuck in a mile-long backup stretching from
Tahrir Square, an army of street kids and old men on crutches hold
out their hands to trapped motorists. A scorching midday sun makes
the filthy air feel like an industrial furnace. Those condemned to
this existential nightmare honk their horns in vain protest.
</P>
<P>
   This is the ``Triangle of Hell'' where Cairo's three main
squares meet. The streets are so overcrowded _ more than a million
vehicles clog the roads in a city of 15 million people _ that 10
years ago city planners dreamed up a $7 billion subway system.
</P>
<P>
   And with the largest phase of the project nearing completion,
shiny new subway cars run beneath the madness above ground in an
air-conditioned world that is quiet, clean, and efficient. The
metro has the feel of a museum. Statues and bronze murals that tell
of Egypt's ancient past are exhibited along the walls of the subway
platforms. Commuters can also watch television while they wait for
trains, which have a record of running on schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Begun in 1986 and scheduled for completion in 2003, the project
is on such a grand scale that the chairman of the bureaucracy
overseeing the metro boasts that it is ``the fourth pyramid, being
built by modern-day pharaohs.''
</P>
<P>
   The only other transportation project in the world that
surpasses it, in terms of cost and scope and traffic headaches, is
Boston's $10.8 billion Big Dig.
</P>
<P>
   By 2005, the expanded Cairo metro system, and a new one to be
built in Alexandria, will carry 7 million passengers a day over 100
miles of track.
</P>
<P>
   The project has also become a gold mine for large multinational
engineering firms. Most of the major players in the industry have
gotten a piece of the action. The United States' Parsons
Brinckerhoff, a participant in the Big Dig, nabbed the management
contract. Japan's Mitsubishi is building most of the coaches.
Germany's Herrenknecht GmbH has named two tunneling machines for
ancient Egyptian royals ``Hatshepsut'' and ``Nefertiti'' that are
cutting a path under the Nile to Giza, site of Egypt's ancient
Sphinx and three most famous pyramids.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Stacey, the Cairo program manager for New York-based
Parsons Brinckerhoff has worked on many of the world's largest
engineering projects, including the new tunnel connecting England
and France and Hong Kong's metro system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cairo hasn't gotten the same press attention, but this is a
very big project,'' said Stacey. ``The thing that makes it unique
is the sense of immediate improvement on people's lives. You don't
always get that feeling in these big projects. This project isn't
flashy. There aren't a lot of engineering marvels, but it is making
it possible to move a lot of people through the city.''
</P>
<P>
   But the new metro lines, despite their efficiency, have barely
affected Cairo's horrific traffic. This is due in part to Egypt's
surging population, now 60 million, which may outstrip the capacity
of the metro system.
</P>
<P>
   Planners estimate there are still some 6 million commuters who
waste as much as 10 million hours a day in traffic. The congestion
has severely damaged Egypt's struggling economy. And pollution is
undermining air quality, causing a national health problem as well
as serious damage to the ancient monuments that are the lifeblood
of the tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
   Cairo has some of the worst traffic in the world. Driving
through Boston is a breeze by comparison. Many international
experts say that traffic in Mexico City and Tokyo is equally
nightmarish. But others say that Cairo is in a class by itself
because unlike drivers in Tokyo, few here obey traffic laws and
unlike public transit in Mexico City, buses here are in short
supply.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traffic problem is greatly exacerbated by the culture of
our drivers,'' conceded Mohammed Mitainy, an engineering professor
at Cairo University and a traffic expert who is a consultant to the
Egyptian government on the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``The primary problem is that people do not obey traffic laws
and the police do not enforce them,'' said Mitainy. ``Egyptians
seem to favor chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   Another major obstacle, he said, is Egypt's Kafkaesque
bureaucracy. Worse, one must negotiate it in person to achieve
results.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot change a national culture even with the most
advanced engineering in the world. To some extent, it will never go
away,'' Mitainy said. ``But we hope to alleviate it.''
</P>
<P>
   One must be in its center to comprehend how chaotic Cairo's
traffic is. Automotive hulks that are 30 years old vie with
overcrowded buses belching black smoke as they lurch through
potholed streets. The vehicles compete for narrow road space with
boys on bicycles who balance bread trays on their heads, farmers on
donkey carts loaded with produce, and pedestrians who risk their
lives crossing the street. Traffic police who begin their days
dressed in spotless white usually end up at dusk perched on median
strips, defeated, their uniforms dark with soot.
</P>
<P>
   The mayhem above ground helps explain why the new metro system
is a source of immense national pride, especially for Egypt's
middle class, which is squeezed between a huge underclass and a
tiny government and business elite that controls most of the
wealth. The system is designed to serve middle class neighborhoods,
so the metro has become their signature mode of transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmad Hassan, 30, works in the accounting department of a
private company and lives in a suburb north of the city. He rushes
home to his family from Sadat Station, named for Anwar Sadat, the
slain president, in Cairo's downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Hassan used to spend an hour and a half traveling by bus to his
office in Tahrir Square. But since the metro line from his suburb
to Cairo's center was finished two years ago, he has cut his
commute to a mere 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has changed my life,'' Hassan said. ``That is not an
exaggeration. I have more time and I don't have to fight for my
life on the buses. This is the greatest thing'' President Hosni
``Mubarak has done for this country.''
</P>
<P>
   The trip to the University of Cairo for Nermine Hassanein, 24, a
graduate student in art, has been pared from two hours to half an
hour on a new line that opened last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look around you. There is art, and it is cool and
comfortable,'' she said. ``It's like a different world. The same
people as up on the street, but a different world.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitainy, the engineering professor, bristled at the comparison
of the metro project to another Egyptian engineering marvel _ the
pyramids.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pyramids were built by slaves for mystical reasons to
honor the pharaohs,'' he said. ``This project provides some 25,000
paying jobs and its goals are very practical _ to improve people's
everyday lives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
