<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN'S PLAN TO CURB TRAFFIC: MAKE 'EM PAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ When John Prescott, the deputy prime minister, unveiled
his 170-page plan on how to get more people to use public
transportation, he arrived at Westminster via the Underground,
London's ubiquitous subway system.
</P>
<P>
   But Mike Dukakis he ain't. After announcing the first serious
attempt at curbing Britain's burgeoning traffic problem in 20
years, Prescott left Parliament the old fashioned way: in a Jaguar.
</P>
<P>
   Prescott's departure from the House of Commons didn't exactly
inspire confidence in the masses, many of whom think the British
government has a better chance of restoring the empire than it does
of improving traffic flow in the capital, let alone the rest of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, a musician in an anarchist band threw a bucket
of cold water on Prescott at Britain's version of the Grammy
awards. Many Britons are giving Prescott's ideas on reducing
traffic a similar dousing.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, motorists will be charged tolls to drive into
towns, and businesses that provide parking spaces to their
employees will be taxed. Businesses will get socked an average of
about $250 per parking space, but in central London, where space is
at a premium, companies will have to fork over about $850 per year
for each spot.
</P>
<P>
   The government hopes those charges will push commuters and
shoppers onto trains and buses, which will be beneficiaries of the
$1.65 billion the new fees are expected to raise.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The government says about 10 percent of the people who take
their cars to work must switch to public transportation over the
next few years or Britain in general, and London in particular,
will experience gridlock.
</P>
<P>
   Such dire predictions make little impression on the average
Brit, however. Londoners, in particular, are cynical about the
government's plans, and about the traffic problem overall.
</P>
<P>
   Harriet Cundy, a real estate agent, lives in Fulham, in the
center of London near the River Thames. But she works in Hampstead,
4 miles north. She says her commute in the morning rush hour is
only about a half-hour. Even if it were two or three times that,
she said, she would do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I simply need a car to work,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   John Porter, doorman at the Park Lane Hotel in Mayfair, is
typical of Londoners who think traffic has gotten worse in recent
years, but believe there's little government can do to change the
car culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every other advertisement on the radio or the telly is for a
car,'' he said. ``If you have the money to buy a car, tolls aren't
going to put you off.''
</P>
<P>
   Automobiles are becoming more ingrained in British life.
Recently, companies in London's financial district have started
giving employees company cars to dissuade them from jumping ship.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Traffic here can be maddening, but it appears no worse than
Boston, Manhattan, or Dublin. Recently, the Metropolitan Police
closed off lanes on Cromwell Road near South Kensington, creating
midday gridlock. Asked for an explanation, a cop just smiled and
said, ``Security.'' Traffic reports on the radio refer mysteriously
to ``incidents'' that lead to lane closures, but that's about as
detailed as the explanations get.
</P>
<P>
   The government, meanwhile, says it wants to reduce the number of
people using cars to ferry children to school. Just how they'll do
this is still a little vague. While America has the yellow school
bus, the family car serves that purpose in Britain. Driving
children to school by car is very much a part of British life,
accounting for an estimated 20 percent of traffic.
</P>
<P>
   A few mothers who were picking their children up at summer
classes at Annemount Nursery School in Hampstead Garden Suburb were
asked whether they would consider walking their children to school
instead. They all guffawed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Kevin Cullen is chief of the Globe's London bureau.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
