<SLUG> BC-WESTON-CASE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPITOL SLAY SUSPECT'S MIND AN ISSUE OF LIFE, DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ They went to Russell Eugene Weston Jr.'s remote
Montana cabin and his Illinois hometown hoping to find evidence and
answers, but last week's FBI search only complicated the question
facing Justice Department lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Was the tragedy that unfolded in the US Capitol on July 24 the
work of a delusionary psychotic or the product of a calculating
mind bent on destruction? Was there a method to the madness? Or
only madness?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, legal specialists say, could determine whether the
federal government seeks the death penalty for the shooting deaths
of US Capitol Police officers, Jacob Chestnut of Fort Washington,
Md., and John Gibson, a Waltham, Mass., native.
</P>
<P>
   Weston, 41, is a diagnosed paranoid schizophrenic who refused
his medication. He shouted at satellite dishes believing they were
the tools of spies, applied to the CIA for a job, sued an
86-year-old woman for assault, and said the federal government
planted land mines on his property.
</P>
<P>
   The same man, however, reportedly stashed away a personal diary
and highly organized notes and correspondences with various
branches of the federal government, and kept a ``CIA packet,'' a
.22-caliber handgun, a shotgun, gunpowder, and a box of Remington
.38 Special cartridges in his Montana cabin, according to FBI court
documents unsealed last week.
</P>
<P>
   Government prosecutors are sorting through these contradictory
strands of behavior _ one indicating forethought and planning, the
other seemingly irrational and uncontrolled _ as they hash out
their legal strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is early in the investigation, high-ranking federal
law enforcement officials and legal specialists say the Justice
Department will be struggling for weeks, if not months, over the
death penalty question. The final decision will be made after a
panel of high-level department officials present the facts to
Attorney General Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   Two factors will be considered: the severity and nature of the
crime, and the nature and mental state of the defendant, according
to David Schertler, former homicide chief in the US attorney's
office in the District of Columbia, which is prosecuting Weston.
</P>
<P>
   The government, Schertler said, has been chastened by the
Unabomber trial, during which prosecutors agreed to drop the death
penalty against Theodore Kaczynski in exchange for a guilty plea
and four life sentences. The trial was lengthy, messy, and widely
considered a tragedy that bordered at times on farce. It was acted
out by a defendant who refused to admit to his mental illness and
rejected the advice of his legal team in a proceeding that could
have ended with his own death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government saw Kaczynski's mental state, which only
revealed itself during the trial, as a strong factor against
getting the death penalty,'' said Schertler. ``This lesson may be
applied to Weston.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors will need to weigh public sentiment, which may
clamor for swift and severe punishment for a wrenching crime _ or
recoil at putting someone who is mentally ill to death.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question at a very profound level is, `Does this person
deserve the most extreme form of punishment, the ultimate
retribution?''' said Richard Bonnie, director of the University of
Virginia's Institute of Law, Psychiatry and Public Policy. ``Even
if we say the person is blameworthy and responsible, the issue of
diminished responsibility because of mental illness comes to the
fore.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Bonnie adds, a claim of insanity means, ``Don't convict
me or blame me or punish me _ treat me ... a claim all of us are on
some level disturbed by.''
</P>
<P>
   With emotions running high and incriminating evidence _
including a security videotape of the crime and shells matching
those found at the scene _ mounting against Weston, legal
specialists say prosecutors may have no choice. ``There are degrees
of vigor in prosecution, and if they are forced to go for the death
penalty, it will be with no real intent to see things through,''
said one high-ranking government law enforcement official who
requested anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Weston's lawyers will have to decide whether to strike a deal
with prosecutors, go for a guilty plea, and spare their client's
life, or try to prove he is legally insane _ a much tougher
standard that goes beyond a medical diagnosis of mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   While Weston remains under heavy guard at a Washington hospital
recovering from the Capitol shootout, his lawyers last week were
granted a two-week delay in his arraignment. They also won
permission to bring in two more prominent psychiatrists to evaluate
their client, an action that legal specialists say strongly
suggests they are considering an insanity defense.
</P>
<P>
   The insanity defense is used in only 1 percent of all criminal
proceedings, and succeeds in 25 percent of those cases. Congress
made it more difficult to win an insanity defense after John
Hinckley Jr. was found not guilty by reason of insanity after
shooting and wounding President Reagan in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way I know to assess criminal culpability is to ask,
did the defendant know what he was doing, could he control his
actions, did he hear the voice of a dog telling him what to do,''
said Steven Lapham, a prosecutor in the Unabomber trial who says he
never believed Kazcynski was severely mentally impaired.
</P>
<P>
   Under today's law, Weston's lawyers would have to prove not only
that he is mentally ill but also that his illness prevented him
from knowing that killing two police officers was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors, however, would probably call their own
psychiatrists and FBI behavioral specialists to show that Weston
may be disturbed but not criminally insane.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it becomes a battle of the experts, what the jury
sometimes does is throw both arguments out and become junior
experts themselves,'' said Laurie Levenson, the associate dean of
Loyola Law School and a former federal prosecutor in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two things juries hate, planning and covering up,''
said Jack Evans, a criminologist at Northeastern University and
author of several books on homicide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-98 1318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980810.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6148 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS &LR;      08-10 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT GIVES THE OCEAN ITS SMELL? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Why does the ocean smell the way it does?
</P>
<P>
   E.R., Concord, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Dimethylsulfide. That ``smells like the ocean'' smell of
fresh salt air is a gas that comes from phytoplankton, the tiny
plants that are the base of the ocean's food chain.
</P>
<P>
   According to John Dacey, associate scientist at the Woods Hole
Oceanographic Institution, the water inside phytoplankton cells is
less alty than the water outside. The salt in the ocean tries to
chemically draw the less-salty water out of phytoplankton cells. To
prevent this, the microscopic plants have evolved a way to produce
dimethylsulfonioproprionate (DMSP), which floats around inside the
cells, counteracting what the salt is trying to do outside.
</P>
<P>
   When phytoplankton die, or get eaten by tiny marine animal
organisms, the DMSP breaks down and releases dimethylsulfide (DMS),
a gas that bubbles up into the atmosphere. At sea level,
concentrations of a few hundred parts per trillion are enough to
tell your nose that you're on or near the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   The strength of the odor depends on the concentrations of DMS.
The smell is often stonger near the coast, where phytoplankton
concentrations are generally higher. And it's less like the ocean
where phytoplankton levels are lower _ where the water is clear _
like the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   We're not the only creatures who enjoy a good whiff of DMS.
Certain sea birds can zoom in on the highest concentrations of the
gas, apparently because the smell indicates an area rich in
phytoplankton and the biological processes involved in breaking it
down. In other words, a good place to look for food.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why do people get crushed when they dive deep in the water,
but whales don't?
</P>
<P>
   L.C., Peabody, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. It's actually only our lungs, sinuses, and auditory canals &UR;  &LR; _
the cavities that contain gas _ that are affected by pressure. The
rest of us, made up mostly of water, is no more affected by
underwater pressure than water itself. That's why fish don't squish
under pressure; they're mostly water, too.
</P>
<P>
   Whale lung tissues have evolved to tolerate levels of
compression that would rip ours apart. They also have bigger lungs,
compared to the rest of their body, than we landlubbers do. So even
after they're compressed, they still have oxygen-holding capacity.
Whales' sinuses and inner ear structures are protected deep inside
thick bones that resist pressure. And they have something in their
outer ears that we're supposed to clean out of ours: a thick plug
of wax that keeps sea water from pushing into their auditory
canals.
</P>
<P>
   And besides that, most whales (including the right and
humpbacks) don't dive all that deep. ``They spend most of their
time in the epipelagic zone, the sunlit layer of the ocean within a
few hundred feet of the surface, where their food is,'' says
Charles Mayo of Provincetown's Center for Coastal Studies.
</P>
<P>
   The real pressure test comes for species like the sperm whale,
believed to swim to depths of at least 7,000 feet on dives that
last up to two hours. Mayo says he and researchers, for fun, used
to put Styrofoam cups into research nets lowered to such depths.
``They'd come back up the size of shot glasses. All the air had
been compressed out of them.''
</P>
<P>
   So how do sperm whales take that plunge and not come back up the
size of a mackerel? ``We believe that sperm whales evacuate their
lungs before they dive,'' says Roger Payne of Lincoln's Whale
Conservation Institute. ``Then they use the oxygen stored in
myoglobin.''
</P>
<P>
   Myoglobin is what lets whales stay down longer than we can. The
underwater-hold-your-breath record for humans is around 11 minutes.
Myoglobin is an oxygen-carrying protein which releases the oxygen
more slowly into the body. It can even store oxygen in muscle
tissue. Whales have a lot more of it than we.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write
to How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
