<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6149 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALEXANDER-PACS-BOS &LR;      08-10 1254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALEXANDER-PACS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP HOPEFUL FINDS A WAY TO EXCEED THE CONTRIBUTION LIMIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a move that could reshape presidential
fund-raising, Lamar Alexander is using a little-known campaign law
in his home state to collect contributions of up to $100,000 per
person, 20 times the federal limit.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander's use of a Tennessee-based political action committee
is significant because he is turning much of the money over to his
federal PAC, which is financing the former governor's pre-campaign
travels around the country.
</P>
<P>
   During the first six months of this year, the former Tennessee
governor transferred $1 million to his federal committee for
``overhead'' costs, according to records filed in Tennessee last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander's fund transfer has not been previously reported. Some
of Alexander's rivals expressed surprise when they heard about the
transfer, saying they were unaware such cash movements were legal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's incredible,'' said Craig Whitney, political director
for former Vice President Dan Quayle's PAC, Campaign America. ``I
didn't know you could do that. I'm flabbergasted.'' Other
presidential prospects might copy the tactic of raising unlimited
contributions in a state PAC. Quayle is already doing that. Quayle
lives in Arizona, where campaign laws prohibit unlimited
contributions to a state PAC. So Quayle recently set up a PAC in
Virginia, where the laws are lenient and allow unlimited
contributions. So far, Quayle has not collected much money for the
Virginia PAC and has not transferred money between his funds.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Alexander is not the only presidential prospect to find a
way around contribution limits. Steve Forbes is using a private
company to raise unlimited contributions, an unprecedented tactic
that has helped him collect $10 million since last year. Alexander
comes in second in total contributions, with his two PACs receiving
$4.9 million. Quayle is third with $3.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the possible field of candidates lags behind,
relying on the traditional method of using a federal political
action account to accept contributions no greater than $5,000 per
person annually. For example, House Democratic leader Richard
Gephardt has collected $694,000 during the same 18-month period for
his Effective Government PAC.
</P>
<P>
   But the race for cash among White House prospects could change
dramatically as they realize how Alexander and Forbes are gaining a
head start with their unorthodox tactics. Alexander's method is
most likely to be copied because donors would rather contribute to
a political committee than a nonprofit company, specialists in
campaign finance said.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander's operation creates a state-based ``soft money''
machine, paralleling the way the major national political parties
collect unregulated and unlimited contributions. The collection of
soft money has led to complaints that the campaign finance system
is out of control, but efforts to control it have failed repeatedly
on Capitol Hill. Last week the House passed an overhaul plan and
sent it to a reluctant Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee is one of 28 states that allow PACs to accept
unlimited contributions. Massachusetts limits PAC contributions to
$500 per person annually. Senator John F. Kerry, who is considering
a presidential bid, has not established a PAC and is paying off his
debt from the 1996 Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   Records show that Alexander has the ability to collect a large
amount of money from a small group of wealthy people. For example,
the $1.8 million he raised the first six months this year came from
just 61 people.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, meanwhile, set up his not-for-profit company called
Americans for Hope, Growth and Opportunity, which takes unlimited
contributions used to pay for his travels and advertisements that
promote his views.
</P>
<P>
   While Forbes financed much of his own 1996 presidential
campaign, he has relied solely on contributions to raise $6 million
this year and $4 million last year, according to an aide, William
Dal Col. In the process, Forbes has collected a database of 130,000
dues-paying members of the private Americans for Hope, Growth and
Opportunity, Dal Col said. Forbes has also set up a PAC with the
same name as his vehicle for donating money to other candidates,
but the effort is minuscule in comparison, with only $32,000
collected.
</P>
<P>
   These tactics provide a window into the way a race for the White
House can be financed below the national radar screen, even before
a candidacy is officially announced. As the 1996 campaign showed,
only a handful of the best-financed candidates make it to the first
primary, and most of them quickly fade unless they have spent a
year or two collecting money. Money, of course, is no guarantee of
success. The well-financed Senator Phil Gramm, the Texas
Republican, dropped out before the New Hampshire primary in 1996
due to his poor showing in the Iowa caucus.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Alexander knows about the need for huge amounts of early
cash as well as anyone. After losing the Republican nomination in
1996, Alexander wrote that the $1,000 limit on individual
contributions to presidential campaigns should be eased.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the limits, voters are more likely to see a comet
than meet a presidential candidate, unless they have $1,000, or
live in Iowa and New Hampshire,'' Alexander wrote in Campaigns and
Elections magazine, referring to the states with the first caucus
and primary. But with no fanfare, Alexander has in effect tossed
aside the limits during this precampaign phase by taking advantage
of Tennessee laws.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Alexander recently took Iowa businessman Donald
Lamberti to breakfast. As the conversation turned to money, the
former education secretary said Lamberti could give an unlimited
amount of cash to Alexander's Tennessee-based committee, and exceed
the $5,000 limit on the federal PAC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted it to be legal. I said, `Can I give that?''' recalled
Lamberti, chairman of Casey's General Stores, a chain of 1,120
convenience stores. ``He said that in Tennessee, a state PAC has no
limits. I said, `Yes,' right on the spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamberti then contributed $95,000 to Alexander's state PAC _ 19
times what he could have given to the federal PAC.
</P>
<P>
   Lamberti said he assumed that much of the money would be
contributed to Iowans running for office this year, because it was
in Alexander's interest to gain favor with Iowa politicians.
Alexander did not respond to a request for comment. Instead, his
consultant, Stan Huckaby, stressed that the PACs operate legally.
And Alexander's press spokesman, Dan Wolter, said the $1 million
transfer to cover overhead for six months includes rent, salaries,
and travel.
</P>
<P>
   The typical purpose of PACs is to collect money from a wide
variety of people and distribute the funds to candidates favored by
the PAC's leader. But in reality, many PACs are vehicles to promote
the committee's leader, paying for travel, lodging, food, staff,
and even radio advertisements, all of which help a presidential
prospect remain visible and build a network of supporters.
</P>
<P>
   In the first three months of this year, while Alexander's state
PAC was spending so much on overhead, it gave $14,750 to Tennessee
candidates. The PAC also spent $14,296 on radio ads to boost his
possible presidential candidacy in the first-primary state of New
Hampshire, and it gave $14,000 to the Iowa Republican Party.
</P>
</TEXT>
