<HEADLINE>
INSURANCE INDUSTRY, COMMUNITY GET A BREAK AFTER ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT JORDAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until recently, most members of the Massachusetts Legislature
considered giving insurance companies a tax break the equivalent of
taking a poison pill, since such a move probably would have ended
their political careers.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance industry has not exactly been popular among voters
or legislators. Many people have, over the years, had run-ins with
life, property, or casualty insurers. As a result, few legislators
have been eager to give the industry a break.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that other kinds of companies received requested tax
breaks to stay in, or move to, the state; a tax break for insurers
was deemed unpassable.
</P>
<P>
   Then things began to change _ due to the work of a few key
legislators (particularly one state senator), a few insurance
lobbyists who could give the profession a good name, and a few
community groups.
</P>
<P>
   The senator was the same one who helped pass legislation, such
as the mutual funds bill, that led to important job growth in the
Bay State: Senator Warren Tolman, the Watertown Democrat who is
candidate for lieutenant governor and a strong ally of labor.
</P>
<P>
   With Tolman's help, an insurance industry bill that once was
considered unpassable became this summer the first law of its kind
in Massachusetts. The legislation finally gave the insurance
industry the tax relief it had been seeking for at least 15 years.
But the bill also brings some reform.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for up to $50 million in tax relief over the next
five years, insurers would contribute a total of $200 million to
community investment. The money would be used to build affordable
housing and help minority-owned and women-owned businesses. It
would also aid other programs aimed at revitalizing low-income
areas. Insurance companies who choose not to participate simply do
not get a break.
</P>
<P>
   The evolutionary process that resulted in this law began in the
early 1990s, when the insurance companies realized they needed tax
relief to remain competitive. Lawmakers said they wanted something
in return.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike other industries that had been involved in this quid
pro quo, insurance companies could not guarantee job growth.
Perhaps they could find other ways to invest their money. That's
when the insurers and community groups such as the Massachusetts
Affordable Housing Alliance began to consider each other as
mutually beneficial.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get tax reform, we needed to do what is required,'' said
Frank O'Brien, regional manager and counsel for the Alliance of
American Insurers. ``So the logical thing was to work toward some
kind of community investment.''
</P>
<P>
   So two years ago, insurers and community groups began to talk.
Slowly, they began to realize they had common ground.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the two groups had different ideas of what a ``good
deal'' was, O'Brien recalled. ``Our idea was to get a decent rate
of return on our investment,'' he said. ``Their idea of a good
investment was a good return to the community, such as a new health
center.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the two sides committed to working together, the next step
was to draft a bill that everyone could live with. It was not easy.
</P>
<P>
   Various versions of a tax relief-community investment bill were
drafted, but failed to win wide support. Tolman, chairman of the
Joint Committee on Taxation, remained committed to getting a bill
that would pass muster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although I was in the midst of a statewide campaign, I still
had 30 days left as an active state senator, so I knew I had to do
everything I could to get my legislative priorities passed,''
Tolman said. He continued talking to both sides.
</P>
<P>
   A version of the bill passed the House, but as the close of this
year's legislative session drew near, it became clear that various
involved parties had problems with the bill. Senate passage was
seriously in doubt. Insurance industry officials and community
activists looked to Tolman not just as &UR;  &LR; a key player, but as the
key player.
</P>
<P>
   Tolman _ having improved his relationship with Senate President
Thomas F. Birmingham after the two were potential rivals in the 8th
District congressional race _ worked to get at least portions of a
bill acceptable to all parties. Working with him were Democratic
Senators Stan Rosenberg of Amherst, Linda Melconian of Springfield,
and Dianne Wilkerson of Roxbury. In addition to O'Brien, key
insurance lobbyists were Vin Shanley and William Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   On the community side, key players were Marc Draisen of the
Massachusetts Community Development Corporation and Thomas Callahan
of the Massachusetts Affordable Housing Alliance, and the Rev.
Charles Stith, who helped to forge a workable alliance with the
insurance industry.
</P>
<P>
   Their efforts paid off, and the measure passed. The person who
is given, and deserves, the most credit for finally getting it done
is Tolman. ``Warren was an absolutely key player,'' O'Brien said.
``He got people to move.'' And that, in essence, is what Tolman is
all about.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
