<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-HARSHBARGER-ART-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCOTT HARSHBARGER: PEACHY ACTIVIST 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It's an image that sticks with his Harvard classmates
some 34 years later: halfback Scotty Harshbarger carrying the
football, knees churning, arms pumping, carrying would-be tacklers
with him as he charged for the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   He was neither stylish nor flashy nor particularly fast. But he
was intent, focused, the personification of drive and
determination. If he couldn't elude opponents, he'd put his head
down and try to run through them.
</P>
<P>
   In the years since he left the Ivy League gridiron, that same
drive has taken Harshbarger from improbable underdog to winner in
almost every political race he has run. But it has also won him a
host of enemies.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years after he first entered politics, Harshbarger's
drive has carried him by the flashier US Representative Joseph
Kennedy II, sidelined last year by family misdeeds, to a
front-runner's position for the Democratic gubernatorial
nomination, and into a near tie with Acting Governor Paul Cellucci,
according to polls.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike at Harvard, where the Pennsylvania minister's
gregarious son was so popular he was elected a class marshal,
Harshbarger is a controversial figure as he runs for governor,
liked by some, but loathed by others.
</P>
<P>
   That same hard-charging style, combined with a moralistic _ some
would say preachy _ tone has led some to charge that he's run
roughshod over reputations and trampled on fairness as he's plunged
ahead in politics.
</P>
<P>
   At its best, his determination to find a way or to make one has
seen Harshbarger pioneer approaches, by, for instance, pressing
banks to invest in poor urban neighborhoods, demanding more
community commitment from nonprofit &UR;  &LR; organizations, helping lead a
nationwide fight against big tobacco, or stretching civil rights
laws to fight domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   But at other times, such as his attempt to regulate handguns
through the state's consumer protection laws, which Superior Court
Judge Diane Kottmyer just blocked, that determination has seen
Harshbarger stretch the law to the rending point, or to overreach
on problematic prosecutions, angering substantial parts of his own
party.
</P>
<P>
   In part, that's because of the moralism that informs his
politics and sometimes runs against the grain of a laissez faire
state. Just because something is not illegal doesn't mean it's OK,
Harshbarger argues.
</P>
<P>
   That moral sensibility is evident in Harshbarger's crusade
against legalized gambling, a stand that has alienated some
southeastern Massachusetts residents who hope for a casino to draw
dollars to their struggling area.
</P>
<P>
   Former US Representative Chester Atkins, who helped Harshbarger
in his early campaigns, sees a huge cultural clash between
Harshbarger's sensibilities and Massachusetts political norms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are talking about a strait-laced minister's son,'' said
Atkins, who supports former state senator Patricia McGovern for
governor. ``I think that a lot of the grease of politics _ the
thousand little deals, the looking the other way, the cutting of
corners _ is not something he is comfortable with or tolerates.''
</P>
<P>
   It's in the area of public corruption that Harshbarger's
zealousness has earned him rancor that still dogs him as he tries
to make the transition from prosecutor to party leader.
</P>
<P>
   One person who has been unwilling to forgive and forget is no
less important a figure than US Representative J. Joseph Moakley,
dean of the Massachusetts delegation. When Harshbarger called him a
couple months ago and asked to sit down and talk, Moakley, still
seething over Harshbarger's futile attempt to prosecute former
state Attorney General Edward J. McCormack Jr., a close Moakley
friend, rebuffed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not interested in sitting down,'' Moakley told the Globe.
``I lived and died with Eddie McCormack.''
</P>
<P>
   That same prosecution so angered Harshbarger's own mentor,
former attorney general Francis X. Bellotti, that Bellotti stopped
speaking to his protege for several months, though the two have
since made up.
</P>
<P>
   Still, one joking remark Bellotti used to make to caution his
aggressive underling back when Harshbarger served as head of his
bureau of public protection has sometimes seemed prophetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was such an activist, I used to say: `Scott, you never let
the law get in your way, ''' Bellotti recalls.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To know 56-year-old Scott Harshbarger, one must understand the
era and influences that forged his character. During Harshbarger's
days at Harvard, from 1960 to 1964, John Kennedy was in the White
House, his example of public service in every young man's mind.
</P>
<P>
   But Harshbarger was pulled by the example of an even stronger
role model: his father, Luther Harshbarger, the chaplain at Penn
State University.
</P>
<P>
   A conscientious objector in World War II with a fervent
commitment to civil rights and social justice, the elder
Harshbarger inculcated conscience in his son. Even today, the
attorney general remembers running afoul of his father almost 45
years ago, when he and his cousins went swimming in a community
pool even though the attendant had turned away a black youth
staying with the family as part of the Fresh Air Fund program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five minutes later, my dad is standing at that pool,'' said
Harshbarger, his voice rising to mark his father's outrage at that
American apartheid: ```You guys get out of that pool and over here.
That is racism. That is wrong.'''
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger, like his father, is a member of the Church of the
Brethren, a religion similar to the Quakers. The denomination
doesn't have any churches in Massachusetts, and Harshbarger no
longer attends church regularly, though he does sometimes visit
other churches, such as the Morning Star Baptist Church in
Mattapan.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up, Harshbarger never dreamed of following his father
into the cloth, despite meeting theologians like Martin Luther King
and Reinhold Niebuhr, whom his father brought to Penn State as
speakers and to the family home. Although his grades were very
good, he was more athlete than intellectual.
</P>
<P>
   But at Harvard, a course on the New Testament had sparked his
interest, and he applied for and won a Rockefeller Fellowship to
encourage students to try the seminary.
</P>
<P>
   The September after graduation, he, his wife, Elizabeth, whom he
had married before his senior year, and their young son, moved to
New York City, where Harshbarger went to Union Theological
Seminary, doing field work at the Chambers Memorial Baptist Church
in East Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   In a neighborhood of poor blacks and Puerto Ricans, the church
was the center of social activism, and there Harshbarger taught
Sunday school, led a Bible study group in nearby housing projects,
ran youth sports programs, and worked with gang-intervention
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the defining year of my life,'' Harshbarger recalled.
``It crystallized everything my parents had taught me: caring about
others, equal rights, equal justice, that you are supposed to act
out your values, that you have obligations to others ... that you
never, ever, ever, allow prejudice or bias to stand in the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching what a committed church could accomplish, Harshbarger
could only imagine how much more government could get done. From
that experience would come some of his initiatives as district
attorney and attorney general _ programs such as his safe
neighborhood initiative, coordinating social service and law
enforcement to address the problems of the urban neighborhoods;
Operation Clean Sweep to broom low-level drug dealers out of city
neighborhoods; his fight to prevent red-lining and to promote fair
lending; and his drive to make hospitals and HMOs improve care for
community members.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-98 1324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980810.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6157 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-HARSHBARGER-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     08-10 1438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-HARSHBARGER-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... community members.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Regrets over the individual effort not made would haunt him. He
and Betsy were so taken by Skeeter Dennis, a black sixth-grader in
his Sunday school class, they thought of bringing him back to the
family farm, near the town of State College, Pa. Three years later,
on a return visit, Harshbarger learned that Skeeter had died of an
overdose _ and he blamed himself for not acting on his impulse.
</P>
<P>
   The Harlem youth comes to mind, Harshbarger says, whenever he
hears someone say nothing can be done about kids and gangs and
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we could have involved ourselves in the life of Skeeter
Dennis, we could have prevented a lot of tragedy,'' he said, voice
rising, gestures animated. ``That was a kid who had pure
potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Then it was back to Harvard for law school. Back, that is, to
Kennedy's clarion call of public service _ but with the values of
social justice, equal rights, and equal opportunities firmly
activated.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After graduation, he would spend several years as a private
lawyer, and several more working as a legal reformer and a public
defender. His big chance would come in January 1975, when Bellotti
hired the 33-year-old activist to run the public protection bureau,
supervising 200 attorneys charged with protecting civil rights,
consumers, and the environment, and enforcing antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   It was an assistant attorney general, where he was immediately
plunged into issues as explosive as court-ordered busing, that
Harshbarger really came into his own. ``He did an excellent job,''
said Bellotti. ``I always used to say he was my social conscience.
He had a great deal of integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   After three years with Bellotti, Harshbarger was ready to run
for office himself. In 1978 he came within three percentage points
of defeating longtime Middlesex District Attorney John Droney. Four
years later, after a stint as general counsel to the newly created
state Ethics Commission and two years in the private sector, he was
back.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Harshbarger won handily, garnering 47.5 percent of
the vote against the ailing Droney and two other Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   His record as DA, where he refocused the office's attention
toward early intervention and crime prevention, is considered
strong. But one case, the Fells Acres Day School child-abuse
prosecution that sent Gerald and Violet Amirault and Cheryl
Amirault LeFave to jail for long sentences, has been a continuing
source of controversy.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Superior Court Judge Isaac Borenstein granted Cheryl
LeFave a new trial, ruling the children had been manipulated by
overzealous prosecutors, their testimony tainted and compromised by
faulty interviewing techniques. Despite nagging doubts here and
judicial reversals in similar cases across the country, Harshbarger
remains adamant about the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe today, as I believed based on the investigation and
prosecution, that justice was done,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The mid-1980s also saw some personal and career troubles for
Harshbarger. After years of drifting apart, he and Betsy separated
in 1983, then divorced in 1985. (He married his second wife, Judith
Stephenson, in June 1987.)
</P>
<P>
   The next election would mark the first time Harshbarger was
thrown for a career loss. Or rather, took himself out of a game.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1986, when Bellotti announced he wouldn't run for
reelection, Harshbarger set his sights on a run for attorney
general. But only two months later, disappointed that Bellotti
wouldn't back him and rattled by headlines about his fund-raising
from his staff _ something he had criticized Droney for _ he bailed
out of the race.
</P>
<P>
   It was a decision that by some accounts led to a personal funk.
Several sources say he became only an occasional presence in the
DA's office, losing focus and energy. Said one: ``AG was the job he
had always wanted. He took it hard. It was a very deep blow. He
wasn't engaged in his job, and it took him several months to
recover.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so, says Harshbarger, who remembers he was glad to be out of
the AG's fight and back to complete his work at a job he loved.
Though his supporters were disappointed, ``I don't recall it as a
depression or feeling particularly down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But if he had stumbled in 1986, he had regained his nerve by the
next election cycle. Buoyed by 1990's strong anti-incumbent
sentiment, he challenged and beat Democratic Attorney General James
Shannon, a former US representative, in a campaign devoid of real
issues beyond his claim to be a professional prosecutor to
Shannon's career politician.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In general, Harshbarger has won good grades as an activist
attorney general committed to defending the public interest, though
some complain that on issues like the tobacco settlement and
electric utility deregulation, the rhetoric ended up being stronger
than the results.
</P>
<P>
   But a recurring question has been his pursuit of public
corruption cases, where several high-profile cases have backfired.
Several long-time observers see troubling tendencies to indict on
iffy charges.
</P>
<P>
   One case that aroused rancor on Beacon Hill was his 1995
prosecution of state Senator Henri Rauschenbach, a Brewster
Republican, on influence-peddling charges. Rauschenbach was
acquitted. In February 1993, he negotiated a settlement on
conflict-of-interest charges with former Democratic state Senator
William Q. MacLean that required MacLean to repay the state
$512,000 he had received in hidden commission from state contracts.
That case also earned Harshbarger criticism.
</P>
<P>
   In May, there followed the case many think marked Harshbarger's
nadir as attorney general: his indictment of former attorney
general Edward J. McCormack Jr. on conflict-of-interest and
conspiracy charges.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general alleged that McCormack, through his
insurance company, paid $30,000 in a series of monthly installments
to Paul Fanning, then a retirement analyst in the state treasurer's
office, at a time when McCormack received pension business that
earned him a $1.8 million commission.
</P>
<P>
   That, Harshbarger said, was a clear violation of the state law.
It wasn't even a quid pro quo he had to prove: State law prohibits
anyone from giving compensation to a state employee in a matter in
which the state has an interest.
</P>
<P>
   But McCormack told a different story. Fanning had been his
partner in Pilgrim Insurance Co., his firm; McCormack said the
payments were to buy out his interest in the firm.
</P>
<P>
   After the prosecution presented its case, Superior Court Judge
Thomas E. Connolly ordered the jury to find McCormack not guilty,
ruling that the evidence prosecutors presented actually helped
prove McCormack's innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Moakley says McCormack, who died in 1997 of complications from
lung cancer, &UR;  &LR; was devastated by the 17-month ordeal between
indictment and acquittal, so much so that he felt uncomfortable
visiting some of his old haunts. ``I know how much he agonized
about it,'' said Moakley. ``It really destroyed him.''
</P>
<P>
   That prosecution also led to a temporary falling out with
Bellotti, another friend of McCormack's. When pressed, a reluctant
Bellotti, who supports Harshbarger for governor, admits he was
livid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had never believed Eddie had done anything wrong,'' Bellotti
said. ``I was angry about that for a long, long time.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Harshbarger said he ``fully understood'' the
anger McCormack's friends feel toward him. His record, which
includes 180 public-corruption prosecutions and an 83 percent
conviction rate, is his record, he said. Harshbarger suggested it
would seem dishonest and self-serving to try to make amends after a
failed prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I say to the McCormacks, `I made a mistake,' what good does
that do to them?'' he asked. ``Their life has been affected by this
decision. We do that all the time in decisions that I make. I think
I have a responsibility to take the heat.''
</P>
<P>
   That failed prosecution, and the harm it caused, are legitimate
issues for voters to consider, Harshbarger said. But, he added,
showing a flash of anger, they should consider the rest of his
record as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``What about the thousands of elderly people that I have
protected?'' he asked. ``What about the consumers, the
environmental cases, the civil-rights cases, the hundreds of people
who are protected from hate crimes, the thousands of victims of
domestic violence and child abuse that I have protected and stood
up for? I am proud of my record ... I have stood up for people, and
that's what I was taught to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
