<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MISCHIEVOUS VOTE IN THE HOUSE SENDS STARR A MESSAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (k and w coding.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- The day before Monica Lewinsky finally showed up
at the federal courthouse here, there was an interesting but barely
noticed vote a few blocks away in the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   The vote resolved not a single important question but it
revealed part of the very long political road the slim pickings
from Kenneth Starr's lengthy investigations will have to travel.
And it also suggested why Starr himself will not be the person to
lead that journey toward a goal called impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   To oversimplify, the House was playing politics that day,
believe it or not. There was an appropriations bill on the floor
and a bipartisan duo of two former subjects of prosecutorial
interest (Republican Joe McDade and Democrat John Murtha of
Pennsylvania) threw in an amendment setting up a review panel to
which people could take claims of abuse or other misbehavior by
federal prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the ranking Democrat on the Judiciary Committee, John
Conyers of Michigan, offered a mischievous amendment to the
amendment that would expand the concept to cover independent
counsels.
</P>
<P>
   As shots go, it was on the cheap side, but the ensuing debate
quickly became a gripe session about Starr. And Newt Gingrich's
lieutenants quickly began a counter-mobilization to keep
Republicans in line against Conyers. But in the end, fully 48 of
them defected, and the proposal ended up with 249 votes.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Republicans are rather radical, antiauthority types,
bordering on the libertarian _ like Ron Paul of Texas, Dana
Rohrbacher and Elton Gallegly of California, and Joel Hefley of
Colorado. But the ranks also included Brian Bilbray of California,
John Fox and Phil English of Pennsylvania, Amo Houghton and Peter
King of New York, Frank LoBiondo and Pill Pascrell of New Jersey,
Jim Leach of Iowa, and Jim Ramstad of Minnesota. They are
deservedly called moderates.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Gingrich nor Starr was amused, and for good reason. In
case no one has noticed, Starr's investigation exists primarily in
its waning weeks as a prelude to impeachment proceedings against
President Clinton. That is the biggest of all political and
constitutional words, and also not exactly appropriate to what
remains the smallest of cases.
</P>
<P>
   For the last few weeks, while gonzo House Republicans have
received attention for confrontationalism, quiet House Republicans
have been trying to send private word to Starr about what will and
will not produce movement, sentiment that was to an extent recorded
in last week's unnoticed roll call.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's testimony, according to her camp, sought to establish
one version of a physical relationship that may or may not be
called ``sex'' by more ordinary peoplebut certainly contradicts
past statements by President Clinton. Whether there is coroboration
and what Clinton himself has to say, are for the next two weeks to
determine. But what many House Republicans are saying is that they
don't care, that they have no interest in or intentions about
moving a sex or sex-based case. A sizeable chunk is also not
interested in an alleged coverup case based more on inferences in
some Starr report than on direct, incontrovertible testimony from
witnesses or clear documents.
</P>
<P>
   And behind that, is a broad-based GOP unwillingness to move an
impeachment process into gear that requires them to do much further
investigating to establish basic facts, given all the torture the
country has already gone through this year. There is a willingess
to consider clear-cut evidence of a real crime if any is produced,
but many a wise Republican would be unwilling to spend time on a
case that is even in the slightest squishy. And that is an attitude
worthy of something as awesome as impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   As in Watergate a generation ago, it is a process that should
require _ and as a political matter does _ a genuine national
outrage over a specific act abusing the office about which there is
no reasonable dispute. Back then, it was the Saturday Night
Massacre of prosecutor Archibald Cox for the specific purpose of
withholding supoened evidence. And it took that scary event just to
get the process started.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing like that exists today.
</P>
<P>
   Starr controls his grand jury and the legal process, though his
conduct is under official scrutiny, and his zeal has squandered his
political standing to generate a serious impeachment inquiry. And
in a mirror image, President Clinton faces legal machinery he
cannot really hope to disable, but it is headed toward a political
arena where his standing is far more formidable. That is why his
Aug. 17 testimony date is so critical.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, this all will be about politics in the best sense,
and in part that is the message sent by those Republicans who lined
up to vote for Conyers's otherwise meaningless amendment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
