<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6166 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHOR-LEMBCKE-BOS &LR;      08-10 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-LEMBCKE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR TAKES ON SPITTING IMAGE OF ANTIWAR PROTESTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. _ Sociologist Jerry Lembcke had finished his
research into reports that antiwar protesters spat at Vietnam
veterans and concluded that those reports were myths, when a
workman at his house and then one of his students told him they
knew veterans who had been spat at.
</P>
<P>
   But both stories collapsed, just like all the others he had
tracked down, Lembcke said. ``An unending series of pop-up
targets,'' he called them.
</P>
<P>
   Lembcke, 55, is an associate professor of sociology at the
College of the Holy Cross and himself a Vietnam veteran, who was
drafted after the 1968 Tet Offensive and served 13 months in
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   He was in the final stages of writing ``The Spitting Image:
Myth, Memory and the Legacy of Vietnam,'' published last month by
New York University Press, when he heard the two close-to-home
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   When he told the workman at his house what he was writing,
Lembcke said, the worker said that ``had happened to a lot of us.''
Not to him, ``but to guys I knew.'' Not in Worcester, though, ``but
mostly in Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the space of a minute,'' Lembcke said, ``the story goes
from not `me' to someone else, and from not `here' to somewhere
else.''
</P>
<P>
   His student told Lembcke he should talk to his roommate
``because his dad had been spat at.'' But it turned out it wasn't
the roommate's father, but his uncle _ and then not him, either,
but someone he had heard about.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to prove something didn't happen,'' Lembcke said.
But after extensive research, ``I'm confident these things didn't
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   There were news reports of protesters being spat at during the
unpopular Vietnam War, Lembcke said, ``and while I don't rule out
the possibility that reporters did see protesters spitting at
soldiers and veterans and didn't report it, I think they would have
seen it as too good a story not to report.''
</P>
<P>
   Lembcke was drafted just short of his 26th birthday when his
deferment as a junior high school math teacher was canceled. After
basic training, he volunteered for training as a chaplain's
assistant and was assigned to the 41st Artillery Group, stationed
in the Central Highlands of Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   One of the chaplains he worked with _ a Roman Catholic (Lembcke
was Protestant) _ started talking with Lembcke about the
righteousness of the war. By the time he returned home, he was
ready to join the Vietnam Veterans Against the War. At the
University of Northern Colorado, where he began his graduate work
in sociology, he became active in antiwar activities.
</P>
<P>
   It was the resurfacing of ``spitting-at-veterans'' stories
during the buildup to the Gulf War that prompted Lembcke to
investigate the subject. ``I saw this image being invoked by prowar
people to rally opposition to the antiwar side,'' Lembcke said.
</P>
<P>
   The image was cited in prowar letters in the Telegram &AMP; Gazette
of Worcester, Lembcke said, and one of his colleagues at Holy Cross
taped a prowar demonstrator saying that people had to support the
Gulf War ``because my brother was traumatized by the hostility he
experienced after returning from Vietnam.''
</P>
<P>
   What was happening, Lembcke said, was an attempt by the Bush
administration ``to discredit peace activism'' in order to build
support for the war.
</P>
<P>
   The belief that Vietnam War protesters spat at soldiers and
veterans ``began to hatch,'' Lembcke said, several years after the
war was over _ and lost. ``At that point,'' he said, ``the country
was having to learn how to deal with losing the war.'' And one way
that it did, he said, was to create the alibi that ``we did not
lose to the Vietnamese, but were betrayed by the antiwar
movement.'' And the myth of the spat-at veterans ``fits as part of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the earliest embodiments of the ``betrayal,'' and one of
the best known, was in the 1978 film ``Coming Home.'' A key scene
is that in which Bob, a Marine captain (played by Bruce Dern), is
returning from Vietnam and is met by his wife Sally (played by Jane
Fonda).
</P>
<P>
   He asks her: ``Where's all the demonstrators?'' Someone ``on the
plane told us there would be a bunch of flowerheads out here.'' As
they drive out of the airbase, there is a small group of antiwar
demonstrators chanting, ``One, two, three, four. We don't want your
rotten war.'' One flashes the peace sign at Bob, and he responds by
saying, ``Peace on you too, brother,'' as he gives the two-fingered
victory sign, slowly letting his index finger drop.
</P>
<P>
   ``In reality,'' Lembcke writes, ``antiwar activists approached
Vietnam returnees, if at all, with informational leaflets offering
services and inviting them to join the movement.'' But the scene in
the film ``misleads the viewer by suggesting that the animosity
displayed by antiwar demonstrators toward returning veterans leads
to Bob's downfall,'' his abuse of Sally, his paranoia, and his
eventual suicide.
</P>
<P>
   A series of films, such as ``Tracks'' and ``Go Tell the
Spartans,'' added to the belief, culminating in 1982 with ``First
Blood'' in which John Rambo, a returned Vietnam veteran (played by
Sylvester Stallone) has these lines: ``I did what I had to do to
win. But somebody wouldn't let us win. Then I came back to the
world, and I see all those maggots at the airport. Protesting me.
Spitting. Calling me baby killer, and all kinds of vile crap. Who
are they to protest me? Huh?''
</P>
<P>
   In his analysis of the cultural dimension of the spitting myth,
Lembcke expands on earlier studies of the subject, ``Homecoming,''
by journalist Bob Green, and ``Working-Class War,'' by MIT
historian Christian Appy.
</P>
<P>
   As his stance gains publicity, Lembcke is already receiving
letters, phone calls, and e-mails on whether the spitting happened.
``They're running half-and-half, agree and don't-agree'' he said.
``People are really hung up on: `Did it happen or didn't it?' But
that's the nature of myths _ you can't lay them to rest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
