<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6168 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-10 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING IN SHAPE FROM THE INSIDE OUT
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Lately people are talking about Pilates, Pilates, Pilates. They
do it, want to do it, are desperate to do it, have tried and failed
to find an instructor who'll teach them how to do it. Suddenly a
physical conditioning system that has been around for more than 70
years is the exercise du jour, which rankles Martha Mason, a
certified Pilates instructor. She says she's tired of reading
``fluffy'' articles about celebrities doing Pilates. ``It's not a
fad,'' she said. ``Who cares if Madonna does it?''
</P>
<P>
   A great many people, apparently, because there's a two-year
waiting list for private instruction at the Pilates Studio in
Cambridge, Mass., where Mason and her partner, Lisa Silveira, teach
women and men of all ages. Not everyone is drawn to Pilates because
of the celebrity connection. It's an intense, gentle form of
exercise long popular with dancers but also suitable for aging
bodies, and for people with injuries and physical limitations. It
focuses on posture, alignment, flexibility, and strengthening the
``power center'' _ the stomach, lower back, and rear end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pilates is not for everyone,'' Mason said. ``It's not about
getting a perfect stomach, or getting legs that you need in LA.
It's a thinking person's exercise. You really have to concentrate.
It's not like going to the gym and working out.''
</P>
<P>
   Silveira, reached on Nantucket where she spends summers
teaching, said Pilates tends to disappoint people looking for
instant exercise gratification. ``This works from the inside out,
and it appears over time,'' she said. ``And that's not good enough
for a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Mason and Silveira aren't trying to discourage interest in
Pilates, but to emphasize that it requires effort and commitment.
``It's very effective if you're consistent,'' Mason said. ``I've
seen people transformed.'' Consistency involves twice-a-week
sessions. Private classes at the pilates studio are $60 each, group
classes $15 each.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Pilates called his system of 150 different exercises
Contrology, because it trained the mind to control the body.
Pilates moved to New York from his native Germany and opened a
studio in 1926. Photographs of him in his 70s and 80s show an
amazingly fit man who looked half his age. ``I drink a quart of
liquor a day, plus some beers, and smoke maybe 15 cigars,'' he
claimed in a 1964 New York Herald Tribune story. He was 83 at the
time, 5-foot-8, 170 pounds. He was still able to do a full split,
quite a feat in itself, never mind the booze, beer, and cigars.
</P>
<P>
   Only in recent years has Pilates's system attracted a large
following. Mason, who trained as a ballet dancer, spent 2 1/2 years
learning the Pilates system, a total of 600 hours as a student and
apprentice. She and Silveira are two of only a handful of certified
Pilates instructors in the Boston area. Their studio is equipped
with machines used in the Pilates system: the Cadillac, the Throne,
and the Reformer. The latter, despite its intimidating name, is a
bed-like device equipped with springs and pulleys that provide
tension during the exercises.
</P>
<P>
   Mason put me through a few beginner-level exercises on and off
the Reformer. The movements were extremely subtle and precise,
different from any exercise I've done. Mason shoved her fingers
hard into my stomach and led me through a Pilates-style sit-up,
which concentrates on the innermost layer of abdominal muscles. The
movement demanded an acute awareness of body movement and
breathing. Mason said that even people who, unlike me, are
considered fit by other standards find the Pilates exercises
difficult at first. ``I had a triathlete in here recently and he
was humbled, just humbled,'' she said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is a columnist for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
