<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6170 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONSUMER-NELLIE-MAE-B     08-10 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-NELLIE-MAE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSUMER GROUP QUESTIONS FOUNDATION'S INDEPENDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA WEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is a new foundation on the block giving away money for
education, but its creation a month ago has set off alarm bells
among consumer advocates who worry that it will not have the
financial independence it needs.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Nellie Mae Foundation say its endowment of $250
million makes it the largest independent foundation in the region
dedicated to making education grants. Within a few years,
foundation officials hope to give up to $10 million annually to
students _ particularly the underprivileged _ from preschool to
college levels.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation, however, had a curious birth _ and some consumer
advocates fear the high hopes for its good work might not be
realized.
</P>
<P>
   They worry about the foundation's close ties to a for-profit
subsidiary, Nellie Mae Inc.: The two groups currently share office
space and some employees at the Braintree, Mass. headquarters. And
the foundation's entire endowment comes from 100 percent ownership
of the corporation's stock.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups fear that these tight financial and personal
bonds may keep the foundation from making detached and rational
decisions necessary to protect its endowment. If the corporation's
profits are poor, for example, can the foundation cut its losses
and sell it off?
</P>
<P>
   ``In reality, the for-profit will be pulling the strings for the
nonprofit,'' said Kim Comart, a consultant working for Consumers
Union, a nonprofit consumer group.
</P>
<P>
   Comart and others also say they have a right to get into the
foundation's business because they believe the $250 million
endowment, in a way, belongs to the public.
</P>
<P>
   This view goes back to the origin of the foundation. It was
created as a result of recent federal legislation allowing
nonprofit student loan companies around the country to split into
two parts. A foundation would keep the accumulated assets of the
nonprofit group and preserve them for the public good, and a
for-profit, taxable corporation would continue the loan business.
</P>
<P>
   So in the case of Nellie Mae Foundation, it kept the $250
million in assets accumulated from two related nonprofit student
loan organizations, the New England Education Loan Marketing
Corporation and Nellie Mae Inc. The assets are to be used for
philanthropy, on the theory that the money came from tax breaks and
federal subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   And the newly created for-profit, taxable corporation _ Nellie
Mae Inc. _ will resume the federal and private student loan
business. As a for-profit, it now is free of many investment
restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Bell, director of Consumers Union's West Coast office in
San Francisco, said she thinks the current setup will lead to
inevitable problems. She said the foundation will be blind to the
corporation's defects. And that is a major problem when the
foundation's assets _ or, as her group sees it, the public's assets
_ are 100 percent with one company.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interests of the foundation are not always in sync with
the company,'' she said. ``What happens if the company starts to
fall apart at the seams. Nobody says, `We should be selling off the
stock of the company. We should fire the top managers.' How do you
do this when you have split loyalties?''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many top managers now represent both the foundation and
corporation. As a spokeswoman, Diane Saunders currently speaks to
the media for both the foundation and corporation; Larry O'Toole is
president and chief executive officer for the corporation, and also
acting president for the foundation while it seeks a permanent
head.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure public input, Consumers Union wants the foundation to
work with a community advisory board, which would nominate people
to the foundation's board.
</P>
<P>
   But Richard Dooley, the new chairman of the board of the Nellie
Mae Foundation, said he wants a tight relationship with the
corporation, so board members can oversee the work of their major
investment.
</P>
<P>
   The criticism from Consumers Union is frustrating Nellie Mae
officials, who say it deflects attention from the foundation's
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing out that Consumers Union is funded to investigate
nonprofit conversions, spokeswoman Saunders said, ``They have to
bark because they've been given money to bark.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-98 1332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980810.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6171 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLF-PGA-OMEARA-SPI &LR;      08-10 2352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-PGA-OMEARA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'MEARA'S GOT THE MARK OF A CHAMPION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO _ Mark O'Meara's sister turns the key in her white Volvo
and starts to back out of her brother's spotless driveway. She
looks up and, of course, O'Meara has the Windex bottle in hand and
is cleaning the car's headlights.
</P>
<P>
   Brown Bear Car Wash would be out of business if the world was
full of Mark O'Mearas.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would never pay anyone to wash his car,'' his sister,
Leslie Malfitano, said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara believes everything should be as immaculate as Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   But while he has always been a first-class person, O'Meara did
not become a world-class golfer until recently. For 18 years,
O'Meara rambled along as a pretty good professional, winning 14 PGA
titles along the way. Then, this year at the age of 41, he became
the oldest player to claim two major championships in the same
season.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if he can win the PGA Championship at Sahalee, O'Meara will
join Ben Hogan as the only other three-time major champion in the
same year.
</P>
<P>
   What turned an otherwise decent professional into a dominant
one?
</P>
<P>
   His relationship with Tiger Woods, a neighbor in their gated
Florida housing community, has been influential. Undoubtedly,
O'Meara discovered if he could beat his phenomenal friend in an
informal round, the rest of the tour was conquerable.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there was another factor, perhaps more important.
Sometimes, you have to hit 40 before learning that when you try too
hard, you produce very little.
</P>
<P>
   Mark O'Meara had to let it go. To decide that it would be all
right to leave a few divots in the manicured life he led. To
realize his potential, friends and family said, O'Meara needed to
realize that the car will still run if there's a smudge on the
fender.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time, he wouldn't give himself permission to win if
he wasn't hitting it perfect,'' said Hank Haney, his swing coach.
</P>
<P>
   Like one of his wedge shots, Mark O'Meara has risen from
anonymity, from his childhood home at sea level in Mission Viejo to
his current standing at the pinnacle of golf. After winning the
Masters and British Open, he now soars above all of his
contemporaries, trading reluctance for moments of magnificence.
</P>
<P>
   ``By realizing it is not a life-or-death situation, you free
yourself up and you tend to play better,'' O'Meara said in a recent
telephone interview as he was preparing for Sahalee.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, while O'Meara's game is on an almost unprecedented
trajectory, his approach to life remains a contradiction.
</P>
<P>
   He resides at Isleworth, the exclusive development, suggesting
an opulent lifestyle. Shaq lives down the street. Tiger is across
the way. Ken Griffey Jr. is a good 3-wood downwind. But if you're
driving by, O'Meara is the one in the yard wearing a baseball cap,
T-shirt, shorts and his Oakley sunglasses. He's the one watering
the plants or, naturally, washing the car.
</P>
<P>
   At 6-feet and 180 pounds, you will notice he is fittingly
common. The pre-sets on his car radio are probably dialed into
classic rock, top-40 and sports talk stations. In the early '90s,
he actually liked the Pet Shop Boys.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara is not a night-on-the-town-kind-of-guy unless the NBA
Magic or the Solar Bears, a minor-league hockey team, are playing
at Orlando Arena. He enjoys skiing with his wife and their
daughter, 11, and son, 8, at Park City, Utah, or bass fishing in
the Butler chain of lakes, one of which is right off his backyard.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just an average Joe,'' said his wife, Alicia.
</P>
<P>
   On the golf course, though, O'Meara is below par and above
average. He has won nearly $1.5 million this year, $10 million in
his career. He is entitled to hobnob _ and does _ but O'Meara would
prefer to talk with you.
</P>
<P>
   His home phone doesn't have call waiting. If O'Meara is on the
line, there will be no interruptions.
</P>
<P>
   In a 90-minute appearance on the Golf Channel after his British
Open victory at Royal Birkdale, he even answered questions from
viewers like George in Texas. He demonstrated flaws in his own
swing, right there on the set. Imagine Gary Payton discussing
fundamentals of the jump shot with some doorknob from Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because I play good golf doesn't make me much different
than any other human being,'' said O'Meara. ``I try to respect
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   If you sat across the bar from O'Meara, he could tell you why he
aims to be considerate of others. He's like his father. Bob O'Meara
grew up on Long Island and still retains his New York accent and
old-school values.
</P>
<P>
   At 69, he could retire, but continues to work in the furniture
sales business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a thing about being dependent on my son,'' Bob
O'Meara said. ``Pride is an important issue. Whatever you earn,
you've got to feel like you earned.''
</P>
<P>
   With their four children, Bob O'Meara and his wife, Nelda, moved
around the country, ricocheting like a drive into a thicket of
Douglas firs, his line of work taking the family everywhere. Along
the way, Bob O'Meara preceded Haney, becoming Mark's first golf
teacher.
</P>
<P>
   At her home in Orlando recently, Leslie Malfitano watched her
brother giving another interview on TV. She sat back with her
husband, Matt, and smiled as O'Meara recycled his modest replies in
an engaging manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being in furniture sales, dad has a way with people. It's not
schmoozy, it's genuine interaction,'' Malfitano said. ``Mark is
definitely his father's son.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob O'Meara has a saying: ``Monkeys learn from other monkeys.
Just be sure you learn from the smartest monkey.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark O'Meara was paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   He also listened to his mother. O'Meara recently recalled the
day in his youth when his mom asked him to pull weeds in the yard.
He pulled them, every single one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm done,'' he said to his mom.
</P>
<P>
   ``No you're not,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes I am. Look, they're all gone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to tell you this, but I was watching,'' she said. ``You
didn't get the roots. If you don't get the roots, the weeds will
come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes moms can be a tough crowd, but another lesson was
dispensed in that flowerbed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That molds a person,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   You could say that O'Meara has never since forgotten his roots.
</P>
<P>
   He does his own planting and gardening and watering. If he is at
his parents' house and sees that they just brought home some plants
from Home Depot, he wants to plant them. Right then.
</P>
<P>
   He has always been Meticulous Mark O'Meara, a human spot
remover, and Alicia is his identical twin. You might find golf
balls in their house, but you could look forever for dust balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can eat off their garage floor,'' said Matt Malfitano,
Mark's brother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara owns several cars but mostly drives a Porsche 930 turbo,
the shiny one of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see somebody's dirty car and I can't stand it,'' O'Meara
said. ``You work so hard to get the things you have, you've got to
take care of them so they last longer.''
</P>
<P>
   You get the feeling that Porsche will never die, that it will
continue to cruise like the O'Mearas' marriage of 18 years.
</P>
<P>
   If you believe in stereotypes, Alicia O'Meara appears to be a
blaring affirmation. She is the beautiful blonde with the glowing
white teeth situated greenside, waiting with satisfied smiles and
congratulatory hugs for her triumphant husband.
</P>
<P>
   But Alicia has had a bigger impact on her husband's career than
any of the bubble-shafted woods in O'Meara's bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's my best friend. She makes life easy for me,'' O'Meara
said. ``The No. 1 reason I've had success is directly related to
our relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   When they met, Alicia was one of the on-course scorekeepers at a
benefit tournament in Mission Viejo featuring the musicians Seals
and Croft. She was a 17-year-old high-school senior at Dana Hills.
O'Meara was a 21-year-old senior at Long Beach State who was
playing in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to talking to her because she was an attractive girl,''
O'Meara said. ``I was totally blown away when I found out she was
only 17.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara might have been an All-American, a supposed stud in golf
circles, but Alicia was unimpressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a little older than me,'' she said. ``I was not that
interested.''
</P>
<P>
   After some prodding from her mother, Alicia agreed to go out
with O'Meara. Their first date was a Halloween costume party. It
seems they haven't been able to mask their excitement since.
</P>
<P>
   They were going to get married on Valentine's Day in 1980 but
moved it up to Dec. 20, 1979, because O'Meara was preparing for a
January start to his first year on the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to go at it by myself. It doesn't work, this
boyfriend-girlfriend deal,'' he said. ``I told her: `We love each
other.' And she said: `You're right, let's just get married.' Those
were great days.''
</P>
<P>
   With around $3,000 between them and most of their belongings
stuffed into Alicia's mom's garage, the newlyweds hopped into
</P>
<P>
   their Volkswagen Rabbit and went tournament-hopping.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a nice car,'' O'Meara said. ``Then we got an
Oldsmobile Cutlass and I thought we were really stylin'.''
</P>
<P>
   He pocketed $1,600 at his first tournament, the Bob Hope Classic
in Palm Springs, and $8,000 for an eighth-place finish at the
Phoenix Open the following week.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seemed to be too nice to be true,'' Alicia said. ``From the
beginning, we've always had fun.''
</P>
<P>
   With Mark O'Meara there are conflicting characteristics that
simultaneously enhance and hinder his game.
</P>
<P>
   A perfectionist, he is recognized as one of the hardest-working
players on tour. And yet he has stumbled over his modest manner in
the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish he would be a little more confident,'' Alicia said.
``He is so humble that it's held him back. That's why he's a late
bloomer. I have always tried to tell him how talented he is.''
</P>
<P>
   The self-assessments are understated. O'Meara consistently says
he is a nice player, a good player, never a great one. Great
players are named Nicklaus, Hogan, Palmer, he explains.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider myself a player that tries to do the best I can at
all times,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara is comfortable being himself. ``I don't have any desire
to trade places with Tiger or Griffey or Michael Jordan,'' he said.
``I want to be a good player, a good father, a good husband and
take care of my friends. That's what my father taught me: be the
best you can be and have a normal lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   He's serious when he talks about taking care of those around
him. Just ask his brother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   What's better than a stripper at your bachelor party? Nothing,
really. But consider this: at Matt Malfitano's, O'Meara played
three holes with all six threesomes at Isleworth. Then when he
spotted PING clubs in Malfitano's bag, O'Meara Federal Expressed a
new set of Taylor Mades to his brother-in-law the next day.
</P>
<P>
   After the wedding, O'Meara told his father he wanted to pay for
half of the expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``That meant a lot to me,'' Leslie Malfitano said. ``He didn't
tell me. To this day, we haven't talked about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, though, O'Meara forgets that he makes maximum wage
and others do not. When the Malfitanos' house was being built, he
thought a bigger window should be put in to take advantage of the
lake view. But the wall was already up. To change construction
plans would raise the price.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said: `What's the big deal, knock the wall out, put up a
new one,''' said his sister. ``It's like: `Mark, hello.'''
</P>
<P>
   On the golf course, until this year, O'Meara has largely gone
unnoticed. At the Masters, someone mistook Mark O'Meara for Mark
McCumber.
</P>
<P>
   Although he carefully avoids controversy, last September at a
PGA European Tour event in Paris, Sweden's Jarmo Sandelin accused
O'Meara of mismarking his ball on the 15th green. Sandelin _ who
lost the Trophee Lancome tournament to O'Meara by a stroke _
claimed O'Meara moved his ball a quarter-inch closer to the hole.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara argued otherwise. It was only a two-foot putt. He wrote
a rebuttal for Golf World magazine, saying: ``I'm one of the better
putters in the game; I don't need help on a putt like that.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara isn't terribly outspoken, but he also generated
criticism after suggesting that players should be paid for
participating in the Ryder Cup, the every-other-year battle between
the Americans and Europeans. A West Palm Beach writer renamed him
Mark O'Money.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the sudden prominence that has ended his
anonymity, skeptics hover. Some still call his big wins
``O'Mearacles.'' In the PGA Championship, O'Meara is listed at 18-1
by the non-believers in Las Vegas. Woods is the top choice at 8-1.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara's drives often stray and his best finish in 15 previous
PGAs was a tie for sixth at Riviera in 1995. Yet, there are
numerous reasons to invest in O'Meara. A fine putter anywhere, he
is even better on poa-annua greens like the ones at Pebble Beach,
where he has won five times, and at Sahalee.
</P>
<P>
   If he gets in position, O'Meara is known as a player who closes
the deal no matter the competition. Starting the pattern, he won
his first tournament in Milwaukee in 1984, beating Tom Watson
during his prime.
</P>
<P>
   Consider, too, that even though his hair is graying, it has
given him the distinguished look of an unflappable champion _ an
aging warrior who defies time because, in fact, he has.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is this with 41 being old?'' asked Bob O'Meara, 69. ``He
will go there (Sahalee) with the intention of winning. He's got a
lot of wisdom because he's so old.''
</P>
<P>
   After getting some fatherly advice, O'Meara just might continue
to rewrite this year's tale of the nondescript.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, you know what, you really screwed up,'' Bob
O'Meara said. ``You won the Masters and the British Open in the
same year and the press is going to write about you no matter what.
Your picture is all over the place. You've loused up the whole
program.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you think I should do?'' his son asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't back off now,'' Bob O'Meara said. ``Win the PGA.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
