<HEADER>
A6172 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-ERMINE-2TAKES-BOS     08-10 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-ERMINE-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PILGRIMAGE TO A CLASSIC LEADS TO CONTEMPORARY SURPRISE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARSAW, Poland _ My main art mission in Poland had nothing to do
with contemporary work. It was to see Leonardo's mesmerizing ``Lady
with Ermine'' in the Czar-toryski Museum in Krakow. For years I'd
daydreamed about making the pilgrimage to Poland to see the
``Lady,'' a picture that intrigued me more than the ``Mona Lisa.''
But that was just in reproduction: Would the reality be as good?
</P>
<P>
   Part of the fantasy was a frisson of fear that the ``Lady''
wouldn't be in residence when I showed up. Like other cash-strapped
museums in other post-Communist countries, the Czartoryski
sometimes rents its rarities to wealthier museums in the West. The
Polish museum offered to rent ``Lady with Ermine'' to Boston's
Museum of Science for its Leonardo show last year for $1 million
for the show's six-month run. The Museum of Science declined.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was ``Lady'' on the premises the day of my visit, she
and I were the only occupants of the room where she lives. No one's
ever alone in the Louvre with the ``Mona Lisa,'' or with other
Leonardos in museums in more accessible locations than Poland.
</P>
<P>
   The serene and secretive ``Lady'' is even more enigmatic than
her more famous sister in the Louvre. While the ``Mona Lisa'' has a
detailed landscape background, ``Lady'' is set against a plain dark
ground that removes her from any specific time or place. Both she
and the ermine she cradles look off to their left. What has
captured their attention? We'll never know.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing ``Lady with Ermine'' fulfilled a fantasy. Finding the
Center for Contemporary Art in Warsaw's Ujadowski Castle was a
complete surprise. Poland was one place where I thought I was safe
from contemporary art. About the only living Polish artists I could
even name were Warsaw-born Krzysztof Wodiczko, who teaches at MIT,
and Magdalena Abakanowicz, who has become one of the most
celebrated sculptors on the international scene. Born on the
outskirts of Warsaw to an aristocratic family, Abakanowicz survived
the horrors of both the Nazis _ she saw them shoot her mother's arm
off _ and the Soviets. I'd seen her work recently in European
museums including Spain's Guggenheim Bilbao, as well as in a
temporary show at Boston College's McMullen Museum of Art and a
long-term installation at Wellesley College's Davis Museum. The
Davis piece, still on view, is chilling, and quintessentially
Abakanowicz. Called ``Iron Cage,'' it is a hollowed-out burlap
torso trapped behind rusting bars, evoking Abakanowicz's own
tortured history, humanity's as a whole _ and Poland's in
particular.
</P>
<P>
   Younger Polish artists were a blank to me, though, until I
stumbled onto them in the Ujadowski, which has been home to
adventurous shows for almost a decade. The property, however, has a
far longer history, one sadly typical of Warsaw. The first building
on the site was a 13th-century stronghold of Mazovian princes,
followed by a hunting lodge, then, in the 17th century, by a
baroque castle that later served as both military barracks and
hospital. The Nazis burned the castle during the Warsaw uprising;
the Soviets finished the job later on, blowing up the remaining
walls. Like virtually all of historic Warsaw, the Ujadowski Castle
is being rebuilt with great attention to authenticity, an ongoing
process that will result in a 17th-century building that's 10 years
old.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the concierge at my hotel nor my half-Polish guide knew
about the Center for Contemporary Art, which I found while walking
in one of Warsaw's vast parks. Overgrown trees shield the view of
the Ujadowski; coming upon it is like discovering Sleeping Beauty's
bramble-covered castle. The major summer show, ``At the Time of
Writing,'' up through Sept. 13, was likewise a revelation: 13
artists, all under 40, none of whom I knew, all of more than
passing interest.
</P>
<P>
   The 28-year-old British curator Nigel Warwick organized the
show. Warwick notes that a few years ago, Catholic forces flexed
their muscle to get Andres Serrano's notorious ``Piss Christ''
banned from a CCA exhibition. Since then, the climate has relaxed
sufficiently for Warwick to be able to show Dominik Lejman's
``Powerpray (Praying Machine),'' an exercise machine modified to
become a prie-dieu, suggesting that prayer is as routine,
repetitious, and mindless as an aerobic workout. Lejman extends the
exercise metaphor in ``Powerprayer I,'' a video of a helmet-wearing
biker, seen from above, projected on a flat surface that looks like
an abstract ``veil'' painting a la Morris Louis _ the sweaty
superimposed on the sublime.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, Ewa Lowzyl's video projection looks like a large,
throbbing sun _ almost like one of Arthur Dove's painted haloed
forms come to life _ until you realize it's an eyeball, blown up to
gigantic proportions, watching you watch it.
</P>
<P>
   Piotr Jaros is the stylist and stage manager of large photos he
doesn't actually shoot himself. His ``Modern Hero'' is another sly
comment on the church and contemporary life, with a bare-chested
man sitting in a tanning machine and offering a sacramental wafer
to a second man who kneels before him.
</P>
<P>
   Mirek Kaczmarek combines the forms of futuristic furniture with
new technologies in eerily inter-active work. You sit in front of
his ``Dressing Table'' and contemplate a video that is at first
hazy, then slowly comes into focus: It's you.
</P>
<P>
   Tomasz Vetulani's paintings on sponges _ a material cheap,
readily available, and not at all durable _ suggest the ephemeral
and elegiac. His subjects in the CCA show are animals, their images
sunk into the hunks of sponge, looking like a cross between cave
painting and the horses of Susan Rothenberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
