<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6174 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLF-PGA-SPOKANER-SPI     08-10 1903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-PGA-SPOKANER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH THE WORLD AT WAR, SPOKANE PROVIDED AN EMOTIONAL BOOST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPOKANE, Wash. _ If the unthinkable happened, and only one major
golf tournament could be played anywhere in the world for 36
months, where would it be played?
</P>
<P>
   Augusta National? Pebble Beach? Maybe St. Andrews?
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-four years ago, as World War II disrupted everyone's
lives, the choice was Manito Golf and Country Club. The game's best
available players came to Spokane to decide the 26th PGA
Championship on a short, user-friendly course well beyond the
streetcar lines on the city's south side.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the great things that happened during the war,''
the legendary Byron Nelson, 86who finished second, told the
Post-Intellgencer in a recent interview. ``The PGA had that
tournament there because they realized the more they could get
before the public, the better it would be for everyone. They used
us to keep golf going.''
</P>
<P>
   As the 80th PGA Championship and all of its glitz and legions of
money-waving fans descend on the Seattle area this week, the
private Spokane club remains in the shadows, 275 miles away, not
much more than a footnote in the annals of tournament golf.
</P>
<P>
   Manito, the Algonquin Indian name for ``magical power,'' hosted
the world's only major golf tournament played between August 1942
and August 1945, when war forced the closure of several courses and
pressed most PGA Tour players into military service. And until this
year, the course was also the site of the only grand-slam event
played in the state of Washington. In what news accounts proclaimed
then as ``the most spectacular upset in the history of the
tournament,'' Bob Hamilton captured that 1944 PGA Championship by
beating Nelson 1-up in 36 holes of match play.
</P>
<P>
   Controversial at the time, Hamilton's victory remains one of the
most widely unexpected outcomes in PGA Championship history: The
archives say the Evansville, Ind., man _ who had five tour
victories in his career to Nelson's 52 _ won with his putter. But
Jimmy Shriver, a former Manito club pro and a spectator at the 1944
event, insists Hamilton did it with other means.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Hamilton's unsportsmanlike conduct was unreal,'' said
Shriver. ``Whenever Nelson would get ready to putt, Hamilton would
clear his throat, anything to distract him on the greens. It was
just frightful. How in the world could a guy play golf and conduct
himself like that?''
</P>
<P>
   The 79-year-old Shriver, a longtime friend of Nelson's and his
personal guest at the Byron Nelson Classic in Irving, Texas, last
May, said Hamilton received a warning on the course from then-PGA
president Ed Dudley over the alleged antics.
</P>
<P>
   But, by then, Shriver said the damage was done.
</P>
<P>
   ``It went on too long,'' Shriver said. ``When a guy hits you
with the first holler, you never know when you're going to get the
next one. You get gunshy.''
</P>
<P>
   In a hole-by-hole, recap, the Spokane Spokesman-Review reported
that the normally unflappable Nelson missed a two-footer on the
first hole, four-footer on No. 2 and a three-footer on the ninth
hole. Over 36 holes, with or without Hamilton's alleged
harrassment, the recap said Nelson botched nine short putts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Hamilton was a pretty good player, but that was the only
tournament he won of any importance,'' said Nelson, now
86-years-old, a 10-1 betting favorite for the final round.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was of the school to do little things to keep you off
guard; nothing too bad, but just a little bit to be obnoxious. He
did little things to break up my concentration. I didn't putt
really well.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton is not around today to answer these charges. He died in
1990, at 74, after building a driving range and an 18-hole public
facility, the Hamilton Golf Course, in Evansville. But his son,
Jim, who runs the family-owned links, has an answer for why his
father seemed to make noises at awkward times during the final
round.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might have been nervous,'' the younger Hamilton said.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 2, 1943, just nine months before the event was held, a
brief item in the Spokesman-Review reported that the Athletic Round
Table, a collection of prominent Spokane businessmen led by Joe
Albi, had made a written bid for the PGA Championship. They offered
financial guarantees and would meet soon with PGA President Dudley,
the paper said.
</P>
<P>
   There was no other mention of the major in the newspaper until
mid-February, when it was referred to as a ``scheduled'' event, as
if it was tentative. Sports sections in those days were filled with
stories about the demise of leagues, teams and events because of
the war. Consequently, hype was noticeably absent.
</P>
<P>
   After touring war-torn England, PGA tournament manager Fred
Corcoran said that he had seen putting greens and courses near
hospitals and wounded soldiers responding positively with the game
within reach. So, when there was a national cry to restore
baseball, golf and other sports to lift the spirits of the troops
and fans, it was heard in Spokane.
</P>
<P>
   The Athletic Round Table, which is still in operation today,
amassed considerable wealth by running slot machines (legally),
invested the money wisely and was big on golf. ``Back in those
days, anybody who could come up with $10,000 could have a
first-class event on the PGA Tour,'' Shriver said.
</P>
<P>
   While most cities were scrambling for war-time cash, the Lilac
City apparently had a stockpile. Albi and his peers produced a
$20,000 purse _ then the richest ever for a PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   As front-page headlines screamed of Allied victories overseas,
the showcase tournament was held in mid-August at Manito. It was
promoted as a fund-raiser for the military and the return of golf _
the other three majors wouldn't resume until 1946 _ and all
proceeds , which ultimately totaled $25,000, were pledged to the
Fort George Wright convalescent center and Baxter General Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   During the tournament, 100 soldiers served as course marshals,
and three dozen wounded servicemen on crutches were brought to the
course to watch the final round.
</P>
<P>
   The only trouble was finding players. The war had pulled 410
golf pros into active duty. A field of 140 was originally
announced. It dropped to 100. Then 85. Military commitments and
transportation problems were the reasons. When the golfers finally
teed off for the first of two rounds of medal play, there were 66
entries, including eight club pros recruited from statewide courses
and a Spokane-based soldier.
</P>
<P>
   John Hoetmer is the only local pro alive today who teed it up in
Manito's major. At 85, the North Seattle man still plays nine holes
at Sand Point Country Club, three times a week. His only 1944 PGA
Championship keepsake is a white pin, with two clubs crossed, stuck
to a framed photo of him playing in the 1955 U.S. Open at San
Francisco's Olympic Club. It was handed to him in the locker room,
in an envelope.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got invited because not enough guys showed up,'' Hoetmer
recalled. ``All the Northwest pros who could play and get away were
invited.''
</P>
<P>
   He worked the graveyard shift at Lake Washington Shipyards, ran
Meadowbrook Golf Course during the day and slept in between. He
remembers flying to Spokane in a prop plane with Wayne Golf Club
pro Bob Connolly, staying at the Ridpath Hotel and hitching rides
to Manito. Paying his own expenses, including a $25 entry fee, he
shot 78 and 83, and failed to qualify for match play. But he was
glad he went.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a real experience,'' Hoetmer said. ``It was quite a
memorable feat for them to put that on, with what was going on.
Those were times that were really heartbreaking.''
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the noticeably shrunken field, Manito had headliners
in Nelson and Harold ``Jug'' McSpaden. Other notable players in the
field included: Olin Dutra, Sam Byrd, Craig Wood, Tony Manero, Tony
Penna, Jimmy Hines and Harry Cooper. Slacks, dress shirts, ties and
brimmed hats made up the standard golf wardrobe. There were no
clothing logos, no walking billboards.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson was classified as 4F, unable to serve in the military,
because he was hemophiliac. Instead, his World War II obligation
centered on entertaining, not fighting, and Spokane was part of
that effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``McSpaden and I were called the `Golddust Twins,''' he said.
``We flew across the country four times in one year. We went to USO
camps and rehab camps. I made 110 appearances for the war effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Indicative of the war and its demands, some people were at
Manito just long enough to find out they were needed elsewhere. One
such person was Denny Spellecy, now 78 and a Mesa, Ariz., resident.
</P>
<P>
   A Navy enlisted man, Spellecy spent a few days on the course
moonlighting as a sportswriter for the Spokesman-Review. Military
walkie-talkie radios were a new innovation at the 1944 PGA
Championship, used to relay scores and messages, whereas previous
events had gone without. This modern convenience did Spellecy no
good at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was out on the golf course and this Air Force guy with a
walkie-talkie asked if I was Spellecy, and said I had a phone
call,'' he said. ``I was told I was getting shipped out to
Hutchinson, Kansas, before the finals. I wasn't happy to see that
airman.''
</P>
<P>
   Manito, at 6,478 yards with wide fairways, smallish trees and no
water, offered little resistance off the tee. Fast greens made up
for that, taking all but the surest putters out of contention.
</P>
<P>
   Living up to their advance billing, Nelson shot a pair of 69s
and McSpaden a pair of 70s to finish 1-2 in medal play. McSpaden,
however, went down in the quarterfinal round of match play,
unexpectedly losing 2-up to Hamilton. With three lopsided
victories, including one over Tacoma's Chuck Congdon in the semis,
Nelson easily advanced to the final round.
</P>
<P>
   With 6,500 fans following them around course, Nelson and
Hamilton were even when they broke for lunch in the clubhouse after
18 holes. They were still even after 33 holes, thanks to Nelson's
continuing putting difficulties. But on the 34th hole, a 197-yard
par-3, Hamilton dropped a 30-footer coming up and over a ridge for
a birdie and the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Two holes later, on the 300-yard par-4 18th, Nelson birdied from
18 feet for a momentary tie. But Hamilton responded, sinking a
15-foot birdie putt for the win. The winner celebrated by tossing
his putter in the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only good putt I remember making was on the 36th hole,''
Nelson said. ``I thought I could make one putt, and I made it.
Unfortunately for me, he made his, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Jim Hamilton: ``Dad said he didn't remember the ball
hitting the putter face. It just seemed like the ball was glued to
the hole.''
</P>
<P>
   The two golfers posed for pictures, listened to long-winded
speeches and met with wounded soldiers. Hamilton, after accepting
the winner's check for $3,500, would report to the Army a week
later. Within a year, he was be back in the area, stationed at Fort
Lewis, playing exhibitions and a Seattle tour stop.
</P>
<P>
   A replica of the 1944 PGA Championship trophy sits inside the
clubhouse at Hamilton Golf Course. Framed pictures replay the
major, and his week in Spokane never strayed far from Hamilton's
thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always said if it was raining in Evansville, it must be a
beautiful day in Spokane,'' Jim Hamilton said. ``He liked it out
there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-98 1334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980810.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6175 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-ERMINE-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-     08-10 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-ERMINE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 WARSAW, Poland; ... Susan Rothenberg.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The artists in Warwick's show are mostly in their early 30s,
which in the West would be old for the ``emerging'' category. ``You
only graduate from art school here at 27 or so,'' the curator
explains, ``and the system is that your teacher puts his stamp on
you and it takes you several more years to find your own voice. The
training is still in figurative painting and monument making, and
there is no crossing over from one medium to another. If you're a
painter, you paint. You're supposed to express your existential
angst on canvas. Art school professors discourage students from
coming here to hear our speakers, people like (the American video
artist) Gary Hill. It's a completely hermetic system.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only are the artists in his show unknown in the West,
Warwick says, they're also virtually unknown in Poland, even to
each other. ``Poland is so decentralized that artists aren't known
outside their own cities,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   There's almost no commercial gallery scene here, he says. Nor
are there national art magazines with listings for different
cities, no equivalent to Art in America. Warwick says the only
place in Poland with a complete, up-to-date array of international
art magazines is the CCA library. To make the point that there
aren't any art magazines, he intentionally had the catalog for his
current show designed to look like one _ right down to glossy ads
for Philips's home media systems and Suzuki cars. It resembles the
sleek magazine affiliated with London's Tate Gallery, only the
CCA's is a one-off: There isn't money for sequels. By Western
standards, the catalog is a bargain, about $6. But, then, books _
even lavish art tomes _ are relatively cheap in Eastern Europe. So
is labor, even in the post-communist age. As a CCA curator, Warwick
earns under $200 a month, an income he supplements by teaching
English.
</P>
<P>
   How many staff members do I think the CCA has? Warwick asks me.
I guess 10, on the basis of the number a similarly scaled
contemporary space in America might employ. The answer is 100.
``It's communist overmanning,'' says Warwick. ``Anything goes
wrong, throw more people at the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Warwick, who first came to Poland on a field trip while he was a
student at London's Royal College of Art, gravitated to the country
because, he says, ``I've always been interested in how ideology
impacts culture and vice versa.'' He's spent three years traveling
all over Poland, becoming an authority on its contemporary art,
which he wants to introduce to the wider world. He travels not
because he loves Polish trains, but because of the dearth of art
magazines and the other means of disseminating images that his
Western counterparts rely on as screening devices. ``In Poland, if
you don't go to where the art is, there's no way to see it,'' he
says, mentioning that Polish artists, lacking the marketing savvy
of those in the West, don't even routinely document their work in
slides.
</P>
<P>
   The CCA, which collects and shows art by major international
figures as well as by Poles, seems poised to help shape Poland's
contemporary art scene. It's already succeeded in creating
world-class amenities in a part of the world where you can't always
count on finding a clean toilet in a museum. The center rents space
to a first-class bookshop, a fine restaurant with funky decor and a
terrace with terrific view, and a shop with a dazzling array of
contemporary Polish crafts. My favorite is a chair made entirely of
pliant twigs bunched together, some sliced off to form a contoured
seat, the rest left to form a fanlike back that suggests a rustic
throne. It's a Polish version of a cross between Appalachian twig
furniture and the corrugated cardboard chairs of Frank Gehry, who
is, by the way, of Polish extraction.
</P>
<P>
   To the casual visitor, the CCA seems to be humming along
splendidly. But, says Warwick, its future is uncertain. The
current, rather raw interiors are perfect for contemporary art, but
``I'm frightened that when the restoration of the building is
finally complete and the floors are marble, it will be offered to
someone else,'' says the curator. ``It's already been offered to
the Military Museum twice _ but they've refused to move into an
unfinished building.'' Warwick predicts the government will evict
the CCA, forcing it to move elsewhere. ``Contemporary art is
marginalized by the government,' he says, ``but that also means we
can do more, and no one notices it.''
</P>
<P>
   Freed from Soviet domination that virtually demanded lying in
public, Polish curators and art writers are making up for lost time
with a kind of candor you wouldn't find in Western art circles,
where a little-white-lie tactfulness prevails. Consider this
sentence from writer Lukasz Gorczyca in his essay in the catalog
for ``At the Time of Writing'': ``The CCA ... works on a totally
spontaneous basis while flaunting its financial problems, an
activity spiced by the curators' struggle with institutional
inertia and with each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Warwick has picked up that frankness. ``People talk about
painting being dead,'' he says. ``Well, for me, sculpture is dead.
We see the world in 2-D, thanks to television. At the end of the
20th century I see no role for sculpture.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more startling is his view of Warsaw's infamous Palace of
Culture, a monster Stalinist structure inflicted on the city by the
Soviets. Everyone else I talk to loathes it, for both its symbolism
and style. But Warwick insists that ``a lot of young people love
it. I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, there's constant debate in Warsaw over how to
camouflage it. A Christo-like wrap? Kudzu? A circle of even bigger
buildings to surround it? The CCA tweaked the building a few years
back, inviting American artist Jenny Holzer, the word-woman whose
truisms turn up on electronic signs and granite benches all over
the world, to put one of her phrases on a billboard in front of the
Palace of Culture. The meanings of Holzer's words are tantalizingly
slippery. That's part of their allure. It's possible to interpret
her Palace of Culture message as a creepy warning to a nation whose
artists yearn for full membership in the international art club:
``Protect Me From What I Want.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-98 1334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
