<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSUMERS OFF BALANCE OVER UNSOLICITED CARDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL AND PATRICIA WEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Rosanne Lipe opened her mail last month and pulled out a
shiny card with a ``MasterCard'' logo, she knew something was
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The accountant had not applied for a new credit card, but this
one had her full name, an account number, a magnetic strip, and
expiration dates. Issued by First USA Bank, the ``Platinum
Connect'' card is a combined MasterCard and telephone calling card,
and each feature can be activated by calling an 800 phone number.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never sent for this,'' Lipe said to her husband when she
saw the card.
</P>
<P>
   Recoiling at this unrequested piece of plastic, her husband,
Dick, sent us an e-mail: ``Just wondering: Is it legal to send out,
unsolicited, a combination credit card/
</P>
<P>
   calling card?''
</P>
<P>
   It turns out the Lipes are part of a large consumer outcry
against these controversial cards, which have been showing up in
mailboxes throughout the country since last September. Many are
worried that these cards, so casually thrown in the mail system,
could easily get into the wrong hands. Consumer advocates also are
concerned that such unsolicited cards will cause recipients to get
deep into debt.
</P>
<P>
   Banking regulators, prosecutors and consumer advocates in
several states have questioned the legality of these cards.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law prohibits companies from sending anyone an
unsolicited credit card. You cannot even _ as First USA originally
tried to do _ send an unsolicited calling card in which the company
bills you each month. That is seen as an extension of credit.
</P>
<P>
   With some legal finesse, however, First USA officials have
modified their card to the satisfaction of federal regulators,
largely by highlighting a prepaid calling card feature, said
Anthony Ricko, section head of the compliance department at the
Federal Reserve Bank in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Ricko said the card was acceptable because it offers two
substantial services, a credit card feature, which is inactive when
mailed, and a calling card feature with a prepaid system.
</P>
<P>
   The calling card feature now requires that the consumer identify
a credit card that will, in advance, pay for all phone calls. It
could be the accompanying First USA MasterCard or VISA card, if
activated, or another credit card.
</P>
<P>
   The calling card becomes a ``stored value'' card, which always
operates in the black. For example, a customer could deposit $100
to the calling card's account, by asking First USA to bill the
credit card for that amount. All calls simply would be deducted
from that sum. When the account dwindles to nothing, additional
money must be paid for more calls to be made.
</P>
<P>
   To address security issues related to the credit card, David
Webster, spokesman for First USA, which is based in Wilmington,
Del., said the card must be activated by the consumer, so there is
no way someone could steal it and rack up huge bills. He said the
bank would not hold prospective customers liable for misuse from
theft. He said the credit card can be activated on the phone, so
the customer could use it right away.
</P>
<P>
   He also noted the 9.99 percent fixed annual percentage rate,
though the rate goes up to anywhere from 19.99 percent to 22.99
percent if you miss some payments. And calling card calls are 50
cents for the first minute and 25 cents for each additional minute,
anytime.
</P>
<P>
   As perks, the calling card also comes with 60 free minutes of
long-distance calling as a sign-up bonus. Webster said every time
the consumer ``loads'' the calling card with money, he or she
receives 10 percent of the amount in reward dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Webster didn't want to get into the details, but he said First
USA would be issuing a similar card later this month, Plantium
Supreme, that involves discounts related to gas purchases. He said
the Platinum Connect card has been ``well-received nationally,''
though he declined to say how many people have been sent the card
and how many have signed up.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Platinum Connect is legal, many consumer advocates are
not comfortable with this kind of card. They say the 60 free
minutes of calling and the easy activation of the credit card make
it too tempting for those least able to manage another credit card.
</P>
<P>
   Jacqueline Dowd, an attorney with the Florida attorney general's
office, said her office now is satisfied with the legality of the
card, based on current laws. Still, she believes lawmakers need to
consider different ways to protect consumers from the new tactics
of credit card marketers.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Brobeck, executive director of the Consumer Federation
of America in Washington, D.C., said he also is not happy with the
marketing tactics of this card. He noted that 80 percent of US
households have at least one card, and of those card-carrying
households, the average one has 10 credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the case of most households, they should be tearing up
credit cards, not getting new ones,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Just the money flew away
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For travelers, there may be some lessons to be learned in the
recent arrest of a travel agent who took more than $14,000 from
customers without giving them any tickets.
</P>
<P>
   On July 31, Adolph (Al) Mondele, 48, of Medford, Mass., was
arraigned on larceny charges. For the past few years, Mondele
operated International Travel and Tours, Tropical Air Services
International Inc., and other travel agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Mondele, who is from the new Democratic Republic of Congo
(formerly Zaire), has turned over his passport to authorities and
is currently free on $2,500 cash bail.
</P>
<P>
   Mondele's business focused largely on travelers going to foreign
destinations, particularly his homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Schlaver, director of the Cambridge Consumers' Council,
said consumers must be careful in dealing with travel agencies,
which do not need to be registered in Massachusetts. He said one
way to measure an agency's reputation is by checking for any
complaints lodged with the Better Business Bureau or state attorney
general's office. Mondele had numerous complaints on file with the
attorney general's office.
</P>
<P>
   Schlaver also said Mondele ran a broker-type business, in which
he took consumers' money with the promise of obtaining cheap
tickets elsewhere. He did not issue tickets himself. Schlaver said
that practice can be a warning sign, and consumers are safest
dealing with an agency that will issue the tickets immediately
after you pay for them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Odds &AMP; Ends
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Dialaround glitch: Callers trying to use Telecom USA's 10321
``dialaround'' service may have found they were charged higher
rates than expected. That's because of a technical glitch that
caused them to be billed at MCI's nonsubscriber rates. (Telecom USA
is a subsidiary of MCI.) Federal officials announced last week an
agreement with Bell Atlantic and MCI to identify all consumers
overcharged by this problem, and credit them in the next several
months. If you have more questions, call MCI/Telecome USA at
1-800-621-4230.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a consumer tip, e-mail mohl(at)globe.com or
wen(at)globe.com, or write Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
