<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-SAFETY-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE COST OF LIVING DANGEROUSLY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; It's a dangerous world out there. But what is more frightening
than the risks in everyday life is that we ignore ways to eliminate
them.
</P>
<P>
   Today there are products or laws that would go a long way toward
making us safer. But they are shunned by industries who say the
cost is too high, by politicians and bureaucrats worried about
excessive regulation _ and by individuals who play the odds.
</P>
<P>
   The products range from the inexpensive _ needles that protect
health care workers from accidental hepatitis C and HIV
contamination, or $10 valves that prevent natural gas explosions in
homes _ to the expensive, such as satellite-based systems designed
to keep trains from colliding. And the potential legislation
requiring everything from trigger locks to seat belts to life
preservers, just to name a random few, could make the world a safer
place. Yet we aren't rushing to use them, buy them, endorse them,
or enact legislation requiring them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic rule of thumb is that regardless of the prescription
_ whether it is to take your penicillin or wear your seat belts _
roughly one third of the people will do it, one third will do it
sometimes, but not on a level that is therapeutic, and one third
will blow it off,'' says Philip Levendusky, a psychologist and vice
president of network development at McLean Hospital in Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   And why are we so lax? It's partly a lack of public education,
partly the efforts of industry lobbyists who squelch safety
legislation, and partly a matter of consumers simply continuing bad
habits.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's human nature _ what Levendusky calls ``wishful
thinking, the this-isn't-going to-happen-to-me phenomena.''
</P>
<P>
   Each year, as many as 1 million health care workers _ nurses,
lab technicians, paramedics, janitors, and doctors _ accidentally
stick themselves with needles. About 1,000 become infected with
hepatitis B or hepatitis C _ for which there is no cure _ or with
HIV, the virus that causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is amazing that 1 million people a year go through the
anxiety of being stuck with a needle and not knowing if it is a
death sentence,'' says Andrew Stern, president of the Service
Employees International Union, which represents about 500,000
health care workers around the country. &UR;  &LR; Safety needles cost 20 to
30 cents more than conventional needles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could stop all this for the price of a postage stamp, but
the worst sort of greed and poor government regulation prevent it.
So more people die each year from needle sticks than in coal mines
or construction sites.''
</P>
<P>
   If Stern is frustrated, so are many other safety officials. Take
the National Transportation Safety Board, which investigates
aviation, marine, rail, highway, and pipeline accidents and makes
safety recommendations. Since 1990, the NTSB has produced a ``Most
Wanted'' list of recommendations that would improve safety but have
been ignored. Five items have been on the list since its origin.
Two involve train separation and natural gas line explosions.
</P>
<P>
   Satellite systems are available to closely track trains and make
certain they do not collide. Some railroad companies have balked at
the cost of implementing such a system, but that is a red herring,
says Barry Sweedler, the NTSB's director of the Office of Safety
Recommendations and Accomplishments. The close monitoring of train
movements such a system would require, would also create great
efficiencies in track and rolling stock use, proponents say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each year there are train accidents where trains are going too
fast, or going where they are not supposed to go, and there needs
to be a firm commitment from the industry to do this,'' Sweedler
says. ``There are pilot programs here and there but there is still
no commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   Burlington Northern Santa Fe is one railroad testing the system,
but has not yet decided to use it. A spokesman said that for the
system to be truly effective it would have to extend beyond BNSF
locomotives to all of the rail industry. And railroad officials say
in a few more years, the equipment will be less expensive than it
is now.
</P>
<P>
   Cost is certainly no obstacle for a device called an excess flow
valve, which prevents gas from building up in a house if a service
line is ruptured.
</P>
<P>
   While it can be costly to put the device in existing homes, the
NTSB recommends them for every new or replaced line, but the
federal government refuses to require them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had some horrendous accidents that this device would
have prevented _ nursing homes, schools, and homes _ and it is so
cheap that there is no reason not to have it,'' Sweedler says.
</P>
<P>
   After years of debate, the Department of Transportation ruled
customers with new gas lines will have to be made aware of the
device by utility companies. Most gas companies do not routinely
use them and Boston Gas is no exception. ``They have an
intermittent performance record and they are not part of our
installations right now,'' says spokesman Mike Connors.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
