<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6213 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CULTURE-SAFETY-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     08-10 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-SAFETY-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... Mike Connors.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But John McGowan, president of UMAC Inc., a manufacturer of the
valves, says they are extremely reliable. In 20 years, only 30
times has a valve shut off service when there was no ruptured line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is like most safety issues,'' McGowan says. ``People tend
to be reactive rather than proactive. It's only when they have a
problem that they tend to focus on what to do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, it is a matter of grudging acceptance developed over
years.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, members of the lunatic fringe were the ones
who wore bicycle helmets. Now, the strange ones are the bare-headed
riders. Why then, don't we routinely wear life jackets when we go
boating?
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the US Coast Guard in Boston released a study of
drownings in the Northeast and found nearly 90 percent of drowning
victims in New England, New York, and New Jersey in the first seven
months of 1998 were not wearing life jackets, or personal flotation
devices. Those figures mirror national statistics. In 1996, 500
people drowned while boating; of that number, 440 were not wearing
life jackets, or personal flotation devices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps people think the life jackets are like the ones they
remember from 20 or 30 years ago that were uncomfortable and
bulky,'' says Senior Chief Petty Officer Glenn Rosenholm. ``But
there are lots of comfortable PFDs that offer great freedom of
movement and they can make all the difference in saving your
life.''
</P>
<P>
   While there has never been a law in Massachusetts requiring
adults to wear life jackets, we did have a seat belt law. We saw it
repealed, reinstated, vetoed by a governor (William F. Weld) for
libertarian reasons, and then the veto overridden. The
Massachusetts law _ unlike those in many states _ does not allow
police to stop motorists for not wearing seat belts. Only if a
motorist is stopped for some other traffic violation and is not
using a seat belt can he be ticketed for that offense.
</P>
<P>
   The legislative roller coaster, and the watered-down form of the
bill, may help explain why only Arkansas, Mississippi, and North
Dakota have lower seat-belt usage than Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Using a seat belt is the single most imporant thing someone
can do to protect themselves, and Massachusetts has one of the
lowest rates of usage in the country,'' says Chuck Hurley,
executive director of public affairs for the National Safety
Council. In Massachusetts, only 53 percent of &UR;  &LR; drivers and
front-seat passengers use seat belts.
</P>
<P>
   Why don't more of us buckle up?
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an admission of vulnerability, that an accident could
happen to you,'' says Hurley. ``The highest-risk people, teenagers
and drunk drivers, have the lowest belt use.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that involves government intervention is inherently
controversial, and people, generally, are not looking for more for
government to do. On the other hand, the best way to save lives is
through government intervention.''
</P>
<P>
   Just what does it take for government or business to enact
safety recommendations? Consider the following:
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, an American Airlines jet made an emergency landing in
Nashville because mislabeled toxic chemicals reacted on board,
creating heat and fumes in the passenger compartment. Although no
one was seriously injured, the NTSB quickly recommended the
installation of fire detection and suppression systems in cargo
holds of commercial jets.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the FAA thought it was a good idea, NTSB staffers
recalled. But after meeting with industry groups, the FAA came back
in 1993 and said the proposal would be too expensive to install and
maintain and rejected it.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on May 11, 1996, a ValuJet DC-9 heading from Miami to
Atlanta crashed in the Everglades killing all 110 people on board.
The fire, which probably started before the plane took off, was
undetected until it was too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that is most frustrating in this business,'' says
Sweedler, ``is when we respond to a tragedy, spend a lot of time
and effort to find out what happened. We find out, make
recommendations and the recommendations do not get implemented and
the same thing happens again and again.''
</P>
<P>
   After ValuJet, the detection and suppression systems no longer
cost too much. They are now required in all commercial jets. But
the price for the industry's epiphany was 110 lives.
</P>
<P>
   On many safety questions, advocates are doing the public
education work that some say should be the work of the government.
For example, tomorrow, hundreds of people will gather in Washington
for a conference on health care worker safety and blood borne
diseases in the workplace. Needle sticks and so-called ``sharps''
will be a prime topic.
</P>
<P>
   Stern, the SEIU president, says large purchasing groups, which
buy in bulk for hospitals, prevent the more expensive safe needles
from gaining market share, a charge the purchasing groups deny.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Becton Dickinson, the New Jersy-based company that
has about 70 percent of the hypodermic needle market, says safer
needles cost more. ``With the increased pressure of managed care,
every cost is looked at with tremendous scrutiny,'' says Bill Kozy,
president of worldwide injection system for Becton Dickinson,
noting that the price of safe needles would drop considerably if
more were purchased.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, each time a health care worker is accidentally
stuck with a needle, testing cost and prophylactic drug treatment
cost anywhere from $1,000 to $2,500. Those costs would vanish with
safe needles. Says Kozy, ``We have been very much frustrated by
this penny-wise, pound-foolish approach.''
</P>
</TEXT>
