<SLUG> BC-KIDDIE-POOLS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIDDIE POOLS HELP KEEP THINGS COOL WHEN TEMPERATURES RISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.H. _ When temperatures soar, it's great to be able to
cool off. Especially in water.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry if you don't have a traditional swimming pool: Space
permitting, try a kiddie pool, or as it's more commonly called, a
wading pool. They fit just about anywhere and require little water.
</P>
<P>
   Always choose a pool with safety in mind, without sharp edges or
a slippery bottom. Make sure the pool is sturdy enough that a child
can hold onto the sides to pull themselves up without the sides
sagging inwards. Soft sides are considered safer for toddlers.
</P>
<P>
   There are inflatable kiddie pools, ones made of sturdy plastic,
which can be filled with an air hand pump, and molded polypropylene
pools with rigid sides. Sizes vary, with most 16 inches deep, with
a 45-inch or 60-inch diameter.
</P>
<P>
   Most kiddie pools feature a themed, patterned design for the
interior and exterior, such as fish, animals or favorite cartoon
characters.
</P>
<P>
   Kiddie pools are also a favorite for adults, who use them on
rooftops or decks. They can also be filled with ice to keep party
beverages cool, or to bathe the family dog.
</P>
<P>
   When the weather turns cooler and it's no longer needed as a
pool, it can be filled with sand to use as a sandbox, before going
into winter storage.
</P>
<P>
   If storage space is limited, consider an inflatable pool, which
can be deflated and rolled or folded up and tucked away in a
corner.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the pools are shallow to an adult, you must still
take care with a child and never leave them alone by the pool. A
child can drown in as little as 30 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Always secure a filled pool when not in use with fencing, a
sturdy safe cover or to be on the safe side, simply empty it. Never
situate your pool where it can be punctured. Placing it on grass or
sand is recommended.
</P>
<P>
   A 45-inch-diameter laminate pool costs approximately $7.50; the
60-inch laminate, around $11.50. Prices may vary, depending on the
materials and construction. Inflatable pools can cost anywhere from
$5 to $70 or more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
