<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-RENO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO FIGHTS BACK AFTER CITATION FOR CONTEMPT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno is said to harbor a
``Thelma and Louise'' fantasy: Jump in the car, drive across
America, and leave behind those who have made her life so
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the dream of freedom, to turn in the keys to her
rented apartment, cancel her newspaper subscription, and bid
farewell to her fierce loyalists in the Justice Department, was
only that, as a House committee cited Reno for contempt of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristically, Reno stood tall. She refused to turn over
confidential memos subpoenaed by Representative Dan Burton, the
Indiana Republican who chairs the House Government Reform and
Oversight Committee and who is determined to use whatever muscle it
takes to make Reno name an independent counsel to investigate
alleged Democratic fund-raising abuses in the 1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things I try to do is to make sure I don't let the
pressure push me over backward or push me over forward,'' Reno told
reporters last week, acknowledging how hard it has been, buffeted
by the political crosswinds, to keep on course during her five
years as attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Reno has emerged as the role model for character,
sobriety, and steel under pressure in an embattled Clinton
administration that did not even want her around in a second term.
She would not resign, and the president was afraid to fire a woman
who likes to say ``the buck stops here.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno has named seven independent counsels to investigate
allegations of various crimes by high administration officials, and
she allowed Kenneth W. Starr to widen his Whitewater probe to the
sex scandal that now threatens Clinton. But it is her stubborn
reluctance to appoint an outside counsel for campaign fund-raising
abuses that has the attorney general on the hot seat now.
</P>
<P>
   Editorial pages scream she is misguided, Republicans blast her
as a partisan tool, and Washington insiders say she is naive and a
little weird. Unlike other attorneys general, she is no crony of
the president _ long ago she was shut out by his tight circle of
male advisers _ and she hasn't learned to pal around with the Right
People or schmooze on the cocktail circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it's her un-Washington ways, and the ways she stands up to
Washington, that have won over many Americans. White House
officials regard her as the most respected and admired member of
the Clinton Cabinet. ``My mother loves her,'' said a former Reno
deputy at the Justice Department, ``because she isn't scared of the
bullies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The more Dan Burton attacks her, the more credible Reno
looks,'' said Thomas Mann, director of governmental studies at the
Brookings Institution. ``The public sees her as a nonpolitical
straight-shooter who is no friend of the president's.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Hampton, editor of the Miami Herald, has known Reno for more
than 20 years. Reno grew up in the Everglades on a wild piece of
land where peacocks roamed and was the state's attorney in
Florida's Dade County from 1978 until 1993, when she came to
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not surprising that people inside the Beltway would call
Reno weird, because integrity is weird to them,'' Hampton said.
``She is the soul of integrity, and she embodies, along with her
dedication to the law, a kind of rugged individualism that we don't
see among urban people very often.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have come to believe that her view not to appoint an
independent counsel is incorrect, but I would never ascribe to her
partisan motives,'' Hampton said. ``I've known her too well for too
long. She believes she is acting on her best interpretation of the
law.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno's resistance puzzles people who have supported her
no-nonsense approach to law enforcement. Some say she is willfully
disregarding the law. Others think she has simply dug in her heels
and has been deaf to advice that the politically charged campaign
fund-raising case is too hot for the Justice Department to handle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Reno runs the risk of appearing that she is just
stonewalling on the issue, and that could harm her legacy,'' said
Don Simon, executive vice president of Common Cause, a
public-interest group that has called for an independent counsel
since October 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Reno says Americans understand what Washington doesn't: She must
stand on principle, both in her reading of the independent counsel
law and in her defiance of a congressional subpoena for internal
Justice Department memos. Disclosing the documents, she said in
three separate news conferences last week, would have a ``dramatic
and adverse'' effect on the cases Justice Department lawyers are
trying to build.
</P>
<P>
   ``I simply have to draw the line and stand up for what I believe
to be a very important principle: Prosecutions in America must be
free of political influence,'' Reno said Thursday after the
Republican-led House committee, divided along party lines, voted to
cite her for contempt.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Lewis, the White House communications director, said, ``My
sense is that that people think of her as someone who is honest,
principled, and does not duck hard decisions. That's character. She
is just so straightforward, plain-spoken, human, and unadorned _
everything that people wish Washington was more of.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno may be the genuine article, as her aides insist, but she is
also savvy enough to have cultivated the image.
</P>
<P>
   To wit: Reno is so straight that she has become one of the most
popular targets for Jay Leno and David Letterman jokes and
``Saturday Night Live'' skits. Reno is so painfully plain-spoken
that her weekly news conferences are mocked as never-say-anything
sessions. Reno is so unadorned that her simple haircut is now
featured on a Web site, where the style is superimposed on the
heads of Demi Moore, Courtney Love, and Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Reno, not doing the usual Washington spin is the greatest
spin of all,'' said John Hogan, who went to work for her in 1979
and was the attorney general's chief of staff until May. ``The fact
that she is who she is, doesn't pussyfoot around, and calls it like
she sees it is exactly what America wants in its public figures.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Klayman, chairman of Judicial Watch, a private government
watchdog group, says the public has bought into the Reno lore,
believing that she is apolitical when in fact she won elections
five times in Florida to be state's attorney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Janet Reno is a tremendous actress. She comes across like Jack
Webb in `Dragnet,' the sincere cop who commands authority and has
an imposing presence,'' Klayman said. ``In reality, she is a
politician of the highest magnitude who has been co-opted by the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Reno seems an odd one to become the first Cabinet officer
in history to be cited for contempt of Congress. Few think the
committee's recommendation will actually come to a vote in the full
House. Reno said she will try to reach some accommodation with
Congress on the subpoena, and she has hinted that she may call for
an independent counsel on the fund-raising issue before lawmakers
return in September.
</P>
<P>
   But the prospect of a nasty fight that could produce a contempt
citation and criminal penalties doesn't faze the attorney general,
aides said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's handling it with the same amazing cool that comes forth
in every crisis,'' said Kent Markus, who, until Friday, was Reno's
deputy chief of staff. ``She knows exactly what is happening, she's
confident and comfortable ... that she is doing the right thing,
and she just doesn't care what others think about her.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
