<HEADLINE>
AFRICAN BLASTS PUT OTHER CRISES ON BACK BURNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Commentary  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The Nairobi and Dar es Salaam terrorist attacks on
American embassies have made allied intervention against the Serbs
in Kosovo less likely in the near future and have put off yet
another showdown with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb blasts probably also mean there will reduced U.S.
pressure for the time being on Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu to cede control of additional West Bank territory to the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Few governments find it easy to deal simultaneously with more
than one major foreign crisis. This is especially true of the U.S.
government, which depends to such a large extent on popular support
at home for its foreign policy initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody has to remind President Clinton that Americans will now
have little interest in cracking down on Serb leader Slobodan
Milosevic over his repression of the Albanians in Kosovo or even in
twisting the arm of Iraq's Saddam Hussein violating United Nations
sanctions stemming from the 1991 Persian Gulf War. The U.S.
public's concern has shifted. People are burning with anger over
last Friday's bombings, which have so far killed at least 210 and
injured more than 5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if it turned that Saddam played a role, no matter how
indirect, in the terrorist assaults, the situation would be
instantly transformed. There would be an almost irresistible demand
in the United States to eliminate the Iraqi strongman once and for
all by force.
</P>
<P>
   But that's a long shot. As in past terrorist outrages of a
similar kind, it may take months, perhaps years, to piece together
what happened and identify those responsible. Or the whole thing
could remain a mystery as suspects are eliminated one by one.
</P>
<P>
   Each time a big terrorist outrage occurs, the authorities
announce that they ``will not rest'' until the culprits are
apprehended. We've all learned by now that this is mostly rhetoric
and doesn't necessarily mean much.
</P>
<P>
   As fury at the bombings begins fading with the passage of time,
the Clinton administration and the public will, naturally, turn
their attention to other issues. Yet the twin blasts are likely to
leave an imprint on U.S. policy.
</P>
<P>
   For example, U.S. officials had been getting tougher with
Netanyahu over his intransigence at making further territorial
concessions to Yasser Arafat's Palestinian Authority. But rightly
or wrongly, Clinton may be less willing to put pressure on the
Israelis as long as Islamic groups remain the prime suspects in the
African assaults.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat and those close to him aren't being accused of
involvement. On the other hand, some analysts already claim that if
Netanyahu had been more flexible in negotiations with the
Palestinians, the bombings might not have happened.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the suspicion of a Middle East link will
inevitably improve Netanyahu's standing and lessen good will toward
Arafat among many U.S. officials and lawmakers as well as the
public.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
