<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6225 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-VANDROSS-BOS &LR;      08-10 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-VANDROSS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUTHER VANDROSS BROADENS HIS RANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perennial Grammy god Luther Vandross was just called the ``Frank
Sinatra of R&AMP;B'' in Billboard magazine. It's a term of endearment
that he cherishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved it. I couldn't have loved anything more, because it
implies longevity,'' Vandross says of the Si-natra comparison. ``It
implies a standard that's hard to keep or measure up to. It implies
a whole lot and I like that. I like that metaphor.''
</P>
<P>
   For Vandross fans, there's more to like on his 14th album, ``I
Know,'' which comes out Tuesday. He again displays his impeccably
smooth voice in a broadening range of R&AMP;B and pop, accompanied by
guests Stevie Wonder, Cassandra Wilson, and rapper Guru of Gang
Starr. He also lets his guard down more than usual to share
personal memories of his Harlem childhood, about singing on the
stoop and harmonizing with friends.
</P>
<P>
   These experiences are recalled in ``Nights in Harlem,'' which
also is being released as a single to urban radio. It splices
together funk, rap, and soul, with the usual Vandross polish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to write a song about the fun we used to have,''
says Vandross. ``I mean, we used to sing in the streets and in the
hallways at school. You know how teachers usually say, `Cut off
that noise and go to class'? We didn't have that. Our teachers used
to listen and close their eyes and just groove, because we really
sounded good. And when the song was over, they'd clap and then say,
`Hurry up and go to your class before the bell rings.' So we kind
of knew we were good, even back then.''
</P>
<P>
   Vandross came from a musical family. One of his two sisters,
Pat, was the only woman in the vocal group the Crests, which scored
a nationwide hit with ``Sixteen Candles.'' Says Vandross: ``They
used to rehearse in my living room when I was very young. I used to
disturb the rehearsals and my sister would yell, `Mama, would you
come and get him, please, and make him stop.'''
</P>
<P>
   Vandross didn't stop. And the rest is R&AMP;B history. In the past
10 years, his hits have included ``Power of Love,'' ``Don't Wanna
Be a Fool,'' ``Here and Now'' (a popular wedding song), and
``Endless Love,'' a duet with Mariah Carey that went to No. 2 on
the pop charts in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   He has become, arguably, the most sophisticated R&AMP;B singer in
the market; an identity that developed early, when he moved from
street-corner harmonies to the more complex influences of '60s acts
on the Motown label.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doo-wop stuff had that 1-4-5 chord progression and you got
a lot of songs out of that same chord progression,'' says Vandross.
``Then along came the Shirelles songs and certainly early Motown,
where no two songs were alike. So we used to sing that stuff and
then, Lord knows, Aretha (Franklin) and Dionne Warwick came into
the picture and the standard for everything just stopped and
elevated. It was like an elevator that goes from the second floor
to the 17th floor in one jump. Then you had to really understand
about texture and tone and the effect you're having on the
listener. When you're young, who cares what the listener thinks,
you know? You're just doing what you know how to do. But, after a
while, it was, `Oooh, we're getting a reaction from what we're
doing, so let's do more of it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Vandross has now attained such legendary status that he can put
the word out and get virtually any guest that he desires on his
records. That's what happened with recruiting acclaimed jazz singer
Cassandra Wilson on the new ballad, ``I'm Only Human.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was to have a female voice do the chorus chant in
that song,'' he notes. ``I was saying, `Well, what about Cassandra
Wilson?' I knew she doesn't make many guest appearances and
certainly not in this genre of music. But we got her in there and
she kept saying, `This is different than anything I've ever sung.
This is such a different way to approach music.' So I took that as
a big positive, because it was a challenge for her and she did it
so well.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting Stevie Wonder for the title track, ``I Know,'' was
another coup. It's the first single from the album to be sent to
Top 40 radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how there's a 16-bar section in the middle between
the bridge and the last chorus? That's especially true in a
commercial format, and one thing we wanted to do with `I Know' was
make sure it was commercial. A harmonica solo seemed like a great
way to do that. So who else could we call but Stevie? He came right
on in. He's just so soulful. It's just so unspoken with him.''
</P>
<P>
   The new album means even more to Vandross because it's his first
since switching to a new label (Virgin Records) and the first in
which he's had complete creative control _ something he didn't have
at his former label, Epic Records, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (Virgin reps) showed up in the studio and said encouraging
things that really made a wonderful difference in how I felt about
recording,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   In the upcoming months, Vandross will star in a PBS special with
Patti LaBelle and then start touring, likely overseas first, before
gigging domestically.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a big lesson once when I was on tour with Anita
Baker,'' he says. ``She had released an album Sept. 28 and mine had
been released Sept. 30, because we were both trying to beat that
Grammy deadline, which was Sept. 30. But our first show was Oct. 1
in Washington, D.C. Consequently, all the rehearsing for the six or
seven new songs you're going to do live was really ill-advised
because people didn't yet recognize the new songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I realized we were out there too soon. So this time I want
to tour off of the second or third single on the album. I think
we're going to go abroad first and then come back to what we hope
is a successful album and tour back here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
