<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLOBE CRITICS RATE FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 ! poor, !! fair, !!! good, !!!! excellent  
 
 (FU) !!! ``Snake Eyes'' _  Entertaining claptrap that gets by on
the stylish and propulsive camerawork of Brian De Palma and the
contrasting styles of Nicolas Cage's over-the-top cop and Gary
Sinise's supercontained naval security officer trying to catch the
killer who assassinated a cabinet official during a heavyweight
title fight in Atlantic City. (R)
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! &UR; ``Billy's Hollywood Screen Kiss''  &LR; Sweet, funny and realistic
mediation on modern attraction and romance, seen through the eyes
of a young gay photographer (Sean P. Hayes) who goes ga-ga for an
impossibly handsome waiter (Brad Rowe) who may or may not be gay.
(R) (Renee Graham)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! &UR; 1/2 ``Full Speed''  &LR; An ocassionally engaging film about a group
of young people in a Paris suburb, and what happens when one of
them, a talented writer, finds widespread success. The film's
biggest fault is failing to flesh out that writer's character so
that his transition into a heel is sharper, and the effect on his
friends more poignant. (Unrated) (Renee Graham)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! &UR; 1/2 ``The Governess'' _  &LR; Minnie Driver cuts an impressive figure
as a 19th century London Jew who passes herself off as a WASP to
get a governess' job with a dysfunctionally gothic family on a
Scottish island. The film darts off in too many directions to
really satisfy as it echoes previous works ranging from ``Jane
Eyre'' to ``Angels and Insects,'' but its pungent emotions, rich
textures and Driver's intelligence make it watchable. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! &UR; ``Safe Men'' _  &LR; This eager-to-please comedy about two
going-nowhere musicians drafted into safecracking duty by the
Jewish mafia of Providence, R.I., plays like Coen brothers Lite.
It's just too mild to be as eccentric as it wants to be, although
Christina Kirk, as a kingpin's daughter with a mind of her own,
makes a delightfully scatty debut. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! &UR; ``Western'' _  &LR; The West here is Brittany, on France's west
coast, and there isn't a cowboy in sight, just two gentle
outsiders, a Spaniard and a Russian, trying to fit into a not
altogether welcoming new multi-cultural France. Warmth, charm and
humane waywardness carry this film that believes there's such a
thing as being lucky in love. (French, subtitled)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (FD) &LR; ! &UR; 1/2 ``Halloween: H20'' _  &LR; ``Scream'' and ``Scream 2'' were
better ``Halloween'' sequels than this one, which returns Jamie Lee
Curtis to her original scream queen role 20 years later. But her
character, her character's nemesis, Michael Myers, and the film are
dragged down by tired blood. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe movie critic Jay Carr's entire archive of reviews may be
retrieved from Boston.com, the Globe's on-line service on the
Internet's World Wide Web; key words ``movie reviews.'')
</P>
</TEXT>
