<HEADLINE>
GOT A SUNBURN? GET MILK 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Phone numbers and Web sites are CQ.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE BARNES  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ In the mail from the American Dairy Association
we find sunburn remedies and other medicinal uses for milk and milk
products. Among them:
</P>
<P>
   _ To ease sun-reddened skin, fill a quart jar with equal parts
milk and ice and two tablespoonfuls of salt. Soak a washcloth in
the mixture and apply to the affected area for 15 minutes, three or
four times a day. For sunburn on the face, apply a mask of sour
cream or yogurt for 20 minutes, which soothes the burn and, as a
bonus, makes pores appear smaller.
</P>
<P>
   _ The itch from poison ivy or poison oak can be lessened
quickly, if medication is not immediately available, by soaking the
area in milk or covering with a cloth dunked in milk.
</P>
<P>
   _ Finally, for the inside as well as the outside: Warm milk
actually does help you fall asleep, because it contains tryptophan,
an amino acid that increases the amount of the neurotransmitter
serotonin in the brain.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ARE VW GOLF CARTS NEXT?
</P>
<P>
   Here is further proof of how much times have changed: golf club
covers that resemble the Dead's mascot, the dancing bears. Price:
$40 for three.
</P>
<P>
   We can't imagine a genuine Deadhead going golfing; Deadheads are
not duffers. In 1969, a Deadhead might have earned some bread by
driving the tractor that sweeps up golf balls on a driving range.
Not nowadays, though. Nowadays you can get, also from the Command
Performance catalog, two tickets to Jerry Garcia's final concerts,
in July 1995, encased in a plastic frame and suitable for mounting
on the wall. Price: $90 for two. Order either or both from Command
Performance by calling 800-873-8263.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COOL HANDS
</P>
<P>
   Now your disposable coffee cup can wear Thinsulate, too. Coffee
bars are slowly catching on to the idea of sliding cardboard
sleeves onto their paper or plastic-foam takeout cups to prevent
scorched fingers. Now you can have your own, permanent java jacket.
</P>
<P>
   Koffee Kompanions, as a Kolorado kompany kalls itself, makes
fabric sleeves, lined with Thinsulate, that fit 12- to 20-ounce
to-go cups. The fabric absorbs drips, the insulation protects
fingers and keeps liquids hot or cold longer, and you can simply
rinse the sleeve or toss it in the washing machine. The sleeves,
available in a variety of patterns, including sheet music, roses,
sports equipment, bagels and coffee sacks, cost about $7 apiece,
including shipping. For info or to order, call 719-594-9679 or
visit the World Wide Web site, http://www.koffeekompanions.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
