<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-DELIVERANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATHER AND SON REUNION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
SUMMER OF DELIVERANCE 
A Memoir of Father and Son 
By Christopher Dickey. Simon &AMP; Schuster. 287 pp. Illustrated. $24. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until now, perhaps, few would have thought to pair John Cheever
and James Dickey as literary twins. Cheever, the mordant chronicler
of suburban WASP angst, was principally a master of the short
story, whereas Dickey was a poet by trade, and a superb one, as
well as a swaggering, bare-chested Southern man of letters. The
private Cheever came to be identified with dogs and tweed jackets,
cold martinis and frozen skating ponds. Dickey preferred to
surround himself with guitars, hunting knives, bows, and canoes _
props calculated to burnish his image (of which he was keenly
conscious) as a slightly menacing good ol' boy drunk on equal
measures Faulkner, moonshine, and machismo.
</P>
<P>
   What the two men turn out to have in common, however, goes
beyond their National Book Awards and contributions to the pages of
The New Yorker, the magazine that helped build their reputations.
Each also wrote a breakthrough novel in his 40s that irrevocably
reshaped his career. Cheever's coup was ``The Wapshot Scandal,''
which when published in 1957 confirmed the suspicion that his
genius was not limited to the short-story genre. In 1970, Dickey
produced ``Deliverance,'' a savage, novel-length tale of four
suburban men navigating the backwaters and backwoods of rural
Georgia. The book was made into a popular _ and even more savage _
movie a year later, catapulting Dickey to widespread fame and the
covers of several national magazines.
</P>
<P>
   And the parallels hardly end there. Cheever and Dickey both took
their families to Italy at pivotal moments in their careers, where
each would recharge his creative batteries and, momentarily at
least, escape whatever private demons pursued him. Both Dickey and
Cheever were prodigiously self-destructive alcoholics and, to be
charitable about it, marginally functional family men. Cheever
veered off into bisexuality, Dickey into compulsive womanizing (he
once claimed to have bedded a thousand women), yet the carnage
visited on wives and children is depressingly the same; while
Cheever's marriage managed somehow to survive, Dickey's first wife
apparently drank herself to death in despair over her husband's
many affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, both writers produced offspring who grew up to be
writers themselves and who, in the shadows of their fathers'
deaths, memorialized the relationship in memoirs that separated
truth from fiction, man from myth. Susan Cheever's ``Home Before
Dark'' shocked a lot of Cheever readers when it appeared in 1984,
two years after her father died. Christopher Dickey's ``Summer of
Deliverance,'' which appears less than two years after James
Dickey's passing, may not have the same shock value, but only
because the Era of Pathography is firmly upon us. Or,
alternatively, because many of us who followed Dickey's career
reasonably closely have less reason to be surprised. (I heard
Dickey read publicly on two occasions: at Harvard in 1970, when he
was drunk enough to make you notice his behavior more than his
verse; and in Washington, D.C., in 1977, at President Carter's
pre-inaugural soiree at the Kennedy Center, an event described
briefly in this book, which to this day remains one of the most
breathtaking displays of public inebriation I have ever witnessed.)
Christopher Dickey's is certainly as unsparing and honest a book as
Susan Cheever's, with a similarly uplifting message of redemption
and reconciliation. Dickey, the Paris bureau chief for Newsweek, is
also a crackerjack reporter and savvy writer _ his previous books
include a novel and two volumes of war reportage _ who in no sense
is unequal to this difficult and psychologically delicate task.
</P>
<P>
   The book opens in 1994, with James Dickey severely ill from
alcoholic hepatitis, a disease with a mortality rate of 80 percent.
Father and son have barely seen or spoken to each other in 20
years. It has been two decades as well since Maxine Dickey, Chris's
mother, died. Within weeks of her death, Dickey had remarried, to a
much younger woman with whom he later had a daughter. His two sons
read about the wedding in People magazine. Fury at his father and
competition with his legacy have driven Chris, the older son, to
seek peace among the world's hottest war zones: El Salvador,
Nicaragua, Lebanon. His father's second wife, Deborah, is lost in a
war zone of her own, one consisting of drug addiction and mental
illness. There is evidence that she has brutally assaulted her
husband on more than one occasion. Into this Dante-esque setup
wanders the prodigal son.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that I could save my father's life,'' Chris Dickey
writes, having found the poet frail but sober and nursing a
powerful thirst to live. ``We both saw that we had been given this
tremendous gift: the chance to set everything right.''
</P>
<P>
   From that departure point, the two undertake a remarkable
journey together back through time and memory. The opening chapters
jump-cut cinematically between biography and memoir, a fitting
device not only because James Dickey loved movies but because he
also liked to embellish his own resume (the decorated World War II
radar operator, for instance, insisted on passing himself off as a
decorated fighter pilot). From his early struggles as a poet and
teacher, and having cut short a burgeoning career as an advertising
copywriter, Dickey makes his mark with dazzling collections of
verse like ``Buckdancer's Choice'' and ``Helmets.'' Then comes
``Deliverance,'' and everything disreputable about Dickey _ the
drinking, the boorish narcissism, the petty cruelties _ become
magnified by the lens of Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``James Dickey had not made this movie, he had let it make
him,'' the son observes, having worked as an extra on the set
alongside director John Boorman and the film's stars, Burt
Reynolds, Jon Voight, and Ned Beatty.
</P>
<P>
   Although shooed off the set by Boorman, James Dickey returns to
play a memorable cameo as a small-town sheriff. During the filming,
meanwhile, a series of disasters and near-tragedies befell the cast
and crew. It was, Chris Dickey writes, ``like the whole film was
becoming some kind of macho gamble in which each man was out to
prove he could take the risks the characters were running,
characters that James Dickey had only imagined.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Deliverance'' was a turning point for both Dickeys, the son
suggests. Chris, who married when he was 18, began living a ``pale,
strained imitation'' of his father's life, drinking heavily and
conducting what he calls ``guilt-ridden affairs.'' His father's
adulteries became more brazen, his own marriage more transparently
a sham. By 1977, Chris had left his wife and found a new home at
The Washington Post. The more distance he put between himself and
his father, the more he found his own richly expressive voice.
</P>
<P>
   It is a voice put to fine use in ``Summer of Deliverance,'' as
unsentimental a father-son memoir as one can imagine. James Dickey
may have died a broken man, but he fixed something important before
he died. He was given a tremendous opportunity to get at least one
thing right. By the evidence of this book, he succeeded, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-98 1359EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980810.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6237 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS &LR;      08-10 1356
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET CAN HELP INFLATION-PROOF A RETIREMENT FUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I are 57 and 53. I make $77,000 a year and she
earns $100,000. We would like to retire in three years and have a
retirement income of $6,000 per month. We have checked with Social
Security and both of us will be qualified for benefits at nearly
the highest level. With the information below, how close can we
come to achieving our goal? We own three houses, worth $315,000,
$95,000 and $82,000; we have four mutual fund accounts totaling
$159,500. We have two late-model cars worth $30,000, and I own
$200,000 worth of S stock in the small company where I work, which
can take out over a 10-year-period.
</P>
<P>
   N.B., Beaverton, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. This is going to be a little iffy, since some of the values
appear (at least to me) to be imprecise. But one things does seems
clear to me -- you re pretty far away from a comfortable retirement
along the lines you propose. If we add up all of your assets
(except the cars, which as you know represent a fast- depreciating
asset,) I come up with a grand total of $851,500. Since you wouldn
t be eligible for Social Security until two years after you retire,
and your wife not until three years after that, let s start with
what it takes to generate a $72,000 annual income stream. If we
presume a 6.5 percent income stream from a retirement portfolio,
the number would be a little more than $1.1 million. Now of course
you might decide that you wouldn t need quite that much, since you
could dip into principal in the early years of retirement and then
begin rebuilding your savings after Social Security kicks in.
</P>
<P>
   But there s also the question of that S corporation stock. Does
the stock pay dividends? Or would your sale simply represent a
contract under which you were entitled to $20,000 a year for 10
years, or perhaps $1,666 a month. If such is the case you might,
with the sale of some of the real estate, be able to work out a
plan to take you through those 10 years -- but at that point your
finances would fall off the table.
</P>
<P>
   Here s where I end up: If you were to sell the two lesser-valued
real estate parcels and add the proceeds to your current mutual
fund portfolio, the total would be $336,500 -- enough, if invested
in a fixed-income portfolio, to produce $1,822 a month. If you were
to use your $1,666 a month from your company stock for living
expenses during the first two years, that would mean withdrawals of
$4,333 a month from that pool, and your principal would fall to
$271,115 by the time your Social Security kicked in. Let s suppose
that during the next three years you were to then cut withdrawals
to $2,733 a month. The result is that by the time your wife s
Social Security eligibility begins you would be down to $219,449 in
principal and you would have used up half of the money from your
company stock. It s a position from which you would not recover.
You might manage to stay near that $6,000 monthly level for the
next five years, but when the last payment from the company stock
arrived, you d be cooked.
</P>
<P>
   Blacker still, none of these calculations take inflation into
consideration. A rough rule of thumb is that a people have a nice
degree of financial security in retirement if they have two sides
ing expenses, and a $275,000 growth portfolio designed to protect
you from inflation in later years.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry to be such a grouch, but at bottom the only advice I can
propose is, first, to save like mad until you do retire, and
second, consider whether you might not be better off in the long
run if you deferred retirement a few more years than you now plan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I m 64, single, and retired last year. I have pensions from
two companies totaling $23,000 a year and $12,000 from Social
Security. My IRAs consist of $100,000 in Fidelity Growth and Income
fund, $50,000 in a Fidelity money market fund,, and $50,000 in a CD
currently paying 5.75 percent. Non-IRA investments consist of
$25,000 in AARP Capital Growth fund $50,000 in AARP Growth and
Income, and $25,000 in a CD paying 6.08 percent. The pension and
Social Security money currently provides for all my needs, and
income from investments is reinvested, with the occasional
withdrawal for overseas travel.
</P>
<P>
   However, the pensions are fixed, and buying power will suffer in
the event of inflation. Further, I have reservations about the bull
market continuing. I had consisted selling Fidelity Growth and
Income and the AARP funds and buying bond funds, but this would
leave me paying capital gains taxes on the AARP funds. What do you
suggest?
</P>
<P>
   B.H., Palm Springs, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I can understand your nervousness about the market, but I
think you may be going too far. As a recent retiree, one of your
major concerns should be protecting yourself against the ravages of
inflation in the later years of your retirement, and unless you
have a terrific amount of money, the stock market is certainly the
best bet. If you were to move most of the $100,000 of IRA money
that s now in Fidelity Growth and Income fund to the fixed- income
side, the two AARP stock funds would represent only 25 percent of
your retirement savings, and especially since you re not counting
on any of these savings for a day-to-day income stream, I suggest
you stay put with them. One reason for this is that it s almost
impossible to time the market; if you get out now and you re like
most investors, you ll probably mis-time your re-entry, and the
worst part of such mis-timing is that people tend to come in too
late, missing the first few heady days or weeks of the next bull
market.
</P>
<P>
   The second reason, of course, is that I assume you hate paying
taxes as much as the rest of us do, and there s no way to exit from
the two AARP holdings without tax consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Notice that I suggested you move most of the money from Fidelity
Growth and Income. As I m sure you know, that excellent fund is now
closed to new investors; therefore I suggest you leave the door
ajar, leaving the minimum required to hold your account open. This
would allow you to restore your investment in this fund should you
become more comfortable with the market in the future.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My grandchildren have shares of Lindner Growth Investors fund
in trust accounts. The results have been poor, with changes of
managers, etc. Should we wait for a hopeful improvement or sell? If
we sell, where should we put the proceeds?
</P>
<P>
   M.K., Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, the last management change at Lindner Growth Investors
came late last year, and it s hard to see any improvement since.
Entering this week, year-to-date figures for the fund showed an 8.1
percent loss, which puts it in the bottom quartile of the small-cap
value fund arena. The average small-cap value fund had a 3.3
percent loss year-to-date, and even the top quartile wasn t getting
anywhere, showing an average return of precisely -- nothing. Do you
blame it on a tough market sector and wait a little longer of do
you head for the doors?
</P>
<P>
   Let s look at the longer record. Over three years the fund had
average annual gains of 8.1 percent, comparing unfavorably to a
peer average of 17.5 percent. Its last above- average performance,
according to Morningstar Mutual funds, came in 1994 (and it lost
money that year, albeit losing a bit less than its peers).
Mornignstar rates it below average overall -- above-average for
risk, low for performance. Yes -- that s enough; I d dump it.
</P>
<P>
   As an alternative investment, if you want to stay in the
small-cap arena (and if your grandchildren are at least 10 years
away from college age) I d suggest Vanguard Small-Cap Index. If
they re older than that, I d look at a balanced fund such as
Vanguard Balanced Index. And if you want to stay within the Lindner
family, Lindner Dividend Investor seems to me to be its strongest
offering.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass.
02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
