<P>
   COLOMBIA-U.S. (Washington) _ The Clinton administration says
that the inauguration of a new president in Colombia should mean
the end of years of ill will between the two countries, especially
if President Andres Pastrana moves quickly on his pledge to stem
the flood of Colombian cocaine into the United States. By Philip
Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   CONGO-REBELLION (Abidjan, Ivory Coast) _ Claiming its first
major success against a week-old insurrection, Congolese officials
said Monday that government troops today had beaten back rebels who
had captured several strategic towns in the southwest of the
country, encircling many of them at a rebel-held military base. By
Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-CORRUPTION (Tokyo) _ Earlier this year, it seemed that a
sweeping corruption investigation might send a good number of the
bureaucrats who largely run the country to prison. But the only
government employee who has gone anywhere is Katsuhiko Kumazaki,
the prosecutor who led the investigation into scandals involving
expensive lavish entertainment for government employees paid for by
businessmen who wanted their favor. By Sheryl WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   NEVIS-INDEPENDENCE (Dateline to kumn) _ Nevis, part of the
Federation of St. Kitts and Nevis, one of tiniest countries in the
world, votes today on becoming an independent and even tinier
country. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
