<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTS OF SELFISH FOLK CONTRIBUTE TO LONG, HOT SUMMER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sitting in a line of interminable traffic recently, waiting for
the light to turn green, I witnessed what had to be one of the most
unbelievable sights imaginable during an unrelentingly hot Texas
summer.
</P>
<P>
   The ignoramus in the pickup ahead of me threw his still glowing
cigarette out the window and onto the pavement.
</P>
<P>
   Mind you, North Texas was in the middle of a 29-day streak of
100-degree or more temperatures. It had been so long since the
ground had absorbed water that giant fissures had opened in the
earth. The color of the vegetation along the access road was a
parched golden brown _ not unlike the Colonel's extra-crispy
chicken.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking grass so dry that the heat from a car's engine can
be enough to spark a fire, and this moron flicks a lighted
cigarette out his window. It lands inches away from the tinder-dry
blades.
</P>
<P>
   Two things were on my mind as I threw the Beamer into park and
jumped from the car. First, make sure that cigarette is
extinguished. Second, give Bubba a butt-chewing he'll never forget.
But just as I crushed the cigarette into the pavement with the
bottom of my shoe, the line of traffic began to move forward and
Bubba drove off.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure he even saw me. My fellow travelers thanked me by
honking their horns. It was not, however, a sign of support,
judging by the looks on their faces.
</P>
<P>
   Bubba's blatant disregard for the overall public good just beats
out the water hogs for stupid acts perpetrated this summer by
selfish and thoughtless people.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone living in an area that has experienced on-again,
off-again water rationing made necessary by soaring temperatures
and busted pipelines has no doubt seen at least one water hog in
town. These are the swine who don't think policy applies to them,
that they are somehow exempt from not watering during a time when
city and utility officials are asking folks to cut down or
eliminate outdoor use of water.
</P>
<P>
   This act of selfishness is not confined to just the neighborhood
lawn freak who has planted a variety of grass not normally found
south of the Mason-Dixon Line and now must lay on 6 inches of water
everyday to keep it green. Businesses with automatic sprinkler
systems are prime offenders, particularly if the water rationing is
announced during a weekend and there's no one available to turn off
the timers at the company.
</P>
<P>
   I have a couple of suggestions for folks who have moved to Texas
from somewhere up in the Great North, which would be anywhere above
Oklahoma. Don't waste your time and money trying to re-create a
Michigan landscape in a Texas front yard. The result will be
anything but positive. Instead, plant grasses, bushes and trees
that are native to this area, and can handle the heat and lack of
moisture.
</P>
<P>
   Conserving water is everybody's business and what we are being
asked to do is not onerous or unreasonable. In fact, a few simple
changes in our everyday habits, suggested by the Texas Natural
Resource Conservation Commission, could make a tremendous
difference in our water reserves.
</P>
<P>
   _ Only wash full loads of clothes and dishes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't leave the water running throughout the tooth-brushing
process. Wet your brush, turn the water off while you do the
scrubbing, then rinse.
</P>
<P>
   _ You'd be surprised how much water is wasted by leaky faucets
and toilets. True confession here. The Labbe household has a leaky
faucet in a bathtub. We haven't had a plumber out to fix it yet,
but the water isn't going to waste. We use a bucket to catch the
drops _ more than a gallon a day _ then use that water for the
household plants and a tiny little scrub pine my husband has been
nursing through the summer drought.
</P>
<P>
   If the water hogs have a hard time playing by the rules, wait
until the day arrives when they turn on the tap and nothing comes
out. Right now, officials are just asking us to limit outdoor water
use. Let's hope we don't get to the day when curtailing indoor
activities _ doing laundry, using automatic dishwaters, limiting
the number of showers or toilet flushes _ becomes necessary.
</P>
<P>
   And to the Bubba in the pickup with the potentially dangerous
littering habit, I'll be watching.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist at
the Star-Telegram. Her e-mail address is
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com andher phone number is (817) 390-7599.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
