<HEADER>
A6255 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RENAISSANCE-HNS &LR;      08-10 0465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENAISSANCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARRING IN THE LAND OF CREATIVE ANACHRONISMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALAN WECHSLER  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SLIPPERY ROCK, Pa. _ Once Kristina Schroeder .MDNM/arrives at
the Pennsic War, you can stop calling her by that name.
</P>
<P>
   For the next couple of weeks, she'll be going by the name
Andromache Magdelena de Venezia (``Andromache'' to her friends), a
Venician woman of the early Renaissance period.
</P>
<P>
   She's one of about 10,000 people who have gone back in time _
about 500 years or so. They're participating in a plague-free and
slightly user-friendly version of the Age of the Renaissance, less
than an hour from Pittsburgh and a world away from modernity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never seen anything like Pennsic,'' said Schroeder, of
Niskayuna, N.Y., who is here for the third time. ``It was almost
like walking into a fairyland.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who have never worn a doublet and trunk hose or a chemise
under a heavy Tudor gown might wonder why so many people are
interested in the Renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   Blame the Society for Creative Anachronisms, which sponsors the
event. This worldwide organization that began in 1965 now has
20,000 dues-paying members.
</P>
<P>
   An anachronism, by the way, is a person or event out of time.
And at SCA there are a great many of them, and they can be pretty
creative.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, at events such as Pennsic (a play on
``Pennsylvania''), participants celebrate the best of the
Renaissance period: the clothes, the architecture, the plays and
music. Gone are the more morbid aspects of that era, such as rats
and lice, poverty and feudal slavery, open sewage and extreme
torture in the name of Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to stay away from the bad parts,'' said JoAnne Williams
of Schenectady, N.Y., president of the Barony of Concordia of the
Snow chapter.
</P>
<P>
   Battles have also been cleaned up. No more inconvenient
disemboweling, no bloodstains to stain the expensive armor.
Instead, rattan swords are used and combatants are expected to fall
when a ``fatal'' blow has been struck.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sound of all that rattan hitting armor, it's really quite
amazing,'' Schroeder said.
</P>
<P>
   Not every anachronism is happy.
</P>
<P>
   Take the play Schroeder and her fellow thespians will perform.
It's called ``Euripides Trojan Women,''a Greek tragedy that takes
place after the fall of Troy, when the royal woman are killed or
sold into slavery. The play talks about how women are left to
suffer after their men are heroically killed in battle.
</P>
<P>
   As Troy's queen says after her only son is thrown to his death,
``Lost city, lost child, what climax of suffering lacks now? Have
we not reached in a headlong plunge the abyss of pain?''
</P>
<P>
   What would the Dark Ages be like without at least a little
angst?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
