<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TYSON-ART-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW KIMBELL MUSEUM DIRECTOR IS A BRILLIANT ACQUISITION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JANET TYSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ When Kimbell Art Museum officials asked
Timothy Potts to be their new director, they were looking to take
care of museum business _ not to take the museum world by surprise.
They were looking for new leadership for the Kimbell, not a
revitalizing transfusion for American art museums in general.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Potts is a surprising choice _ if only because he comes
from Australia, rather than from the shrinking pool of U.S.
administrative talent, and is a relative unknown in America.
</P>
<P>
   He is not unknown, however, in Australia, where he's director of
Melbourne's National Gallery of Victoria _ Australia's oldest (137
years), largest (70,000 artworks) and best attended (1.2 million
visitors annually) art museum.
</P>
<P>
   Potts, 40, whose appointment was announced Thursday, is a great
fit for the Kimbell, with his youthful dynamism, his scholarly
depth and diverse range of professional experience. (How many
museum administrators have taught at Oxford AND worked as an
investment banker?)
</P>
<P>
   And he's also a fresh and unexpected addition to a U.S. museum
scene that is suffering an institutional identity crisis in the
midst of a purported Golden Age of American art museums.
</P>
<P>
   So, pardon me if I make this sound like the Second Coming. Potts
not only will hone the Kimbell's already distinguished identity,
but I think he also will help American museums (and their
directors) sort themselves out in general.
</P>
<P>
   He says he's attracted to America's ``can-do'' attitude although
these days, I'm not so sure that attitude extends to our museums.
We live in a time when art institutions are enjoying unprecedented
popularity, yet seem plagued by confusion over priorities. What
comes first: Attendance? Cultural diversity? Money? Education? Art?
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Kimbell enjoys relative freedom from these
concerns, Potts will refine its identity in ways that will inspire
many of his American colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Just look at some of the remarkable things he accomplished
during his three-year tenure in Melbourne. He increased the
museum's earned income _ while eliminating admission fees to the
permanent collection. He doubled attendance. He boosted its
acquisitions endowment by 40 percent, increased corporate and
private support for the museum, and oversaw publication of catalogs
of the NGV's Old Master and 19th- and early 20th-century paintings.
</P>
<P>
   Under his leadership, the NGV acquired major works from
antiquity, from Asia and in the area of European painting.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Potts oversaw renovation of the museum's building
and development of plans for a new NGV Museum of Australian Art.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he has accomplished so much and is justifiably
admired in Australia, Potts was eager to come to the United States,
where he believes his diverse experiences can contribute even more
to the field.
</P>
<P>
   He also is eager to come to a museum renowned for its
collections, exhibitions and beautiful building.
</P>
<P>
   So what might we expect from Potts, once he has had a chance to
settle in sometime this fall?
</P>
<P>
   Look for him to:
</P>
<P>
   _ Develop a master plan for renovation and modest remodeling of
the Kimbell's Louis Kahn building _ one that encompasses developing
an adjacent property that the Kimbell Art Foundation recently
purchased.
</P>
<P>
   _ Continue making important acquisitions _ with an understanding
that there are fewer works of high quality available for purchase
with every passing season.
</P>
<P>
   _ Continue developing and presenting important exhibitions _
with, perhaps, less emphasis on blockbusters.
</P>
<P>
   _ Work with the Amon Carter Museum and Modern Art Museum of Fort
Worth on cooperative programs that enhance learning about works
from all three collections.
</P>
<P>
   _ Work with those museums and with Texas Christian University to
support TCU's new museum studies graduate program.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nurture scholarly research by presenting and documenting
symposiums and other programs, and expanding museum publication
overall.
</P>
<P>
   The Kimbell has flourished under the stewardship of its wise
trustees and its two brilliant past directors. Ric Brown, as
Kimbell president Kay Fortson is wont to say, built the building
and took the Kimbell to the nation; Ted Pillsbury, who ended his
17-year tenure in June, built the collection and took the Kimbell
to the world.
</P>
<P>
   The Kimbell is poised to achieve new greatness under Timothy
Potts. And, as it does, let's not forget that art lovers and art
institutions around the nation and world will be watching.
</P>
<P>
   (Janet Tyson is art critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
