<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following
 &UR; ScienceTimes &LR;  stories for papers of Tuesday, Aug. 11:
</P>
<P>
   Photos, where indicated, are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphics, to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.
</P>
<P>
   Some ScienceTimes stories are available to international clients
only by special arrangement, and are so marked. Asian and European
points: contact Karl Horwitz in Paris for details and prices
(Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX: 47-42-80-44). Latin American points:
contact Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX:
310-996-0089).
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-U.S.-SPACE (Undated) _ After concluding that sensitive
U.S. space information was improperly disclosed to Russian and
Ukrainian engieerns, the State Department suspends most work on an
innovative project in which Boeing plans to launch satelites aboard
rockets lifting off from an ocean-going oil rig on the equator. By
William J. Broad. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-OCTOPUS (Undated) _ Octopus biologists never tire of their
subject, never question their career choice, and never hesitate to
flak the beauty and sophistication of the octopus. Some will talk
about how clever the octopus is: ``The most intelligent
invertebrate in the world, there's no denying it,'' according to
Roland Anderson, a biologist at the Seattle Aquarium. In fact, they
are even smart enough to have fun. Last month, a researcher
documented that the animals actually engage in play behavior, a
mark of relative mental complexity and normally considered the
province of young mammals. By Natalie Angier. (2150 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENE-SNIPS (Undated) _ A new word is edging into the study
of human genetics: the snip. Snips, variations in the DNA that make
each individual unique, are the genetic determinants of health and
disease. Now, because of machines that rapidly decode DNA, the
chemical chain that embodies the genetic instructions, snips are
becoming more accessible and more highly prized. Snips will help
population geneticists reconstruct the size and timing of the early
human migrations that peopled the globe. And they should enable
medical geneticists to trace elusive links between genes and
disease, particularly the common diseases to which many genes
contribute. By Nicholas Wade. (1925 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LEMUR-WRIGHT (Undated) _ Patricia Wright's trail to
Madagascar and environmental heroism began with an act that is now
considered the antithesis of conservation _ the purchase in a
Brooklyn pet store of an owl monkey. Today, Ms. Wright is one of
the nation's foremost authorities on the lemurs of Madagascar. By
Jane E. Brody. (1850 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DECLINING-DISEASES (Undated) _ Newsworthy new and unusual
infections have been attracting so much fanfare this year that we
have yet to hear a fitting recessional for the handful of great
infections of history that are slowly fading from view. So what's a
medical school to do, keep on teaching about diphtheria and
measles? By Abigail Zuger. (935 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-RESTORING-SPEECH (Undated) _ Doctors have long been trying
to give people their voices back. In the 20th century, ear and
throat specialists have treated the voiceless with a variety of
what they call larynoplastic phono surgeries operations to make
vocal cords work again. For the future, some surgeons see a return
to electricity in the form of tiny pacemakers helping the vocal
cords to open and close normally. And, another group is putting
together implants for vocal cords. By Erin St. John Kelly. (940
words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STANDARD FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ Ambitious efforts are under way
to meld machines in several areas of research, including one to
develop a computer that can be implanted in the human brain to
complement memory. By Rob Fixmer. (830 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ Shorts on science: Researchers at Arizona
State University, Randall S. Cerveny and Robert C. Balling Jr.,
have shown that there may be a correlation between work-week
pollution and increased precipitation on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FINN-TWINS (Undated) _ On an archipelago off Finland,
researchers discover the selective advantage of twins. By Jane E.
Brody. (500 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Science questions answered: What gives
clouds color.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HEALTH PAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ Many people make significant changes in
what they eat, drink, take or do based on research that is far from
conclusive. Some become unduly alarmed about suspected but unproved
risks to health that they cannot control. Others decide that
because what is ``fact'' one week is sometimes contradicted by a
new study finding the next, they won't change any habit. But few
people, including many who report health findings in print or on
the air, know how to interpret scientific research or understand
the certainties. By Jane E. Brody. (``l'' code)
</P>
