<DOCNO> NYT19980810.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 14:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6317 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YADDO-HNS &LR;      08-10 1337
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YADDO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN UPSTATE NEW YORK, WRITERS AND ARTISTS FIND AN ESCAPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By THOMAS CHRISTIAN  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ The roar came from a camouflaged area
beyond a thicket of woods: ``Nevermore!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Forevermore!''
</P>
<P>
   Young James Barhyte stared into the bleak forest from whence the
sound came. ``Nevermore!?'' the 12-year-old mimicked incredulously,
``What a name for a bird! Whoever heard of a bird named
`Nevermore'?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have it,'' muttered the poet Edgar Allan Poe as he emerged
from the woods, a black slouch hat shading his eyes. ``Just the
thing that will make the very stanza I need to complete the poem.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was that the legendary prose of ``The Raven'' had roots in
Saratoga Springs on the grounds of what would become the writers'
colony called Yaddo. At least that is the account of Schenectady
minister William Griffis, who wrote about the exchange in a 1924
edition of The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   In the same densely wooded Saratoga landscape where Poe roamed
150 years ago, the secluded 400-acre Yaddo estate sits in between
the race track and Exit 14 of the Northway. Upon the estate is a
sprawling terrain of blue stucco barns and tranquil ponds,
blossoming gardens, a pair of spooky graveyards and a grand 55-room
Victorian mansion that looms creepily atop a hill.
</P>
<P>
   Since its incorporation in 1900, Yaddo has been a creative
catalyst to many of the 20th century's most talented writers and
poets, and to a lesser extent, musicians and artists.
</P>
<P>
   It's where, among the subtle clang of the wind-triggered chimes,
William Carlos Williams completed Book IV of his inspirational poem
``Paterson''; James T. Farrell created ``Studs Lonigan''; Saul
Bellow wrote ``Henderson The Rain King''; James Baldwin produced
``Giovanni's Room''; and a young Delmore Schwartz poured over
translations of Rimbaud's ``Une Saison en Enfer.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, contemporary artists such as David Sedaris and Maggie
Estep continue to tread the same manicured lawn avenues as Sylvia
Plath, Truman Capote and Dorothy Parker had generations ago.
</P>
<P>
   American Revolutionary soldier Jacobus Barhyte purchased the
land where Yaddo would be built in 1784, operating a tavern that
became a favorite stopover among distinguished Spa visitors of the
early 19th century. Along with Poe, James Fennimore Cooper,
Washington Irving and future president Andrew Jackson were known to
visit.
</P>
<P>
   In 1874, 21-year-old Brooklyn poet Kate Nicholls and New York
financier Spencer Trask were wed. Turning their Saratoga summers
into a permanent residence, they purchased the old Barhyte Estate
in 1881, renovated the existing Italian Villa into a Queen Anne,
then proceeded to erect a 55-room Tudor-style Victorian mansion
atop the original house's cindered ashes when it burned to the
ground a decade later. Fitting its interior with customized marble
sculptures, oil paintings, and hand-carved wooden decor, its
centerpiece is a Tiffany glass mosaic Phoenix rising over a
fireplace that reads: ``Unconquered by flames, Yaddo is reborn for
peace.''
</P>
<P>
   It was 4-year-old Christina Trask, the couple's eldest of four
children _ all of whom died before reaching their teen-age years _
who gave the sweeping estate its name. ``Call it Yaddo, mama, for
it makes poetry, Yaddo shadow, shadow Yaddo.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1899, the Yaddo Gardens were built. It remains the one area
of the estate open to the public. The gardens are a multitiered
charm nestled at the foothills of the mansion. Comprised of four
oblong beds of white, pink, and red Radiance roses, a pyramidal
structure of dolomite rock sprouts one of nature's springs nearby.
Statues of Italian marble rest upon a myrtle base, and a lengthy
pergola designed of 38 symmetrically aligned Greek columns are
adorned with the brilliance of budding roses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Katrina's Sundial'' of brass sits on a pedestal, inscribed
with the verse of poet Henry Van Dyke, its poetry selected by Lady
Jane Fellowes for recital at the funeral last year of her sister,
Princess Diana.
</P>
<P>
   The Trasks bequeathed Yaddo to the artists of the future and in
accordance with their mutual agreement, the project began in
earnest after they had both passed away. The first group of
official Yaddo guests arrived in the summer of 1926, the poet
Louise Bogan among them.
</P>
<P>
   A varied and talented group of artists has since followed.
Langston Hughes and Erica Jong. Paul Bowles and Henri
Cartier-Bresson. From the notorious word-slingers Lionel Trilling,
William Gass and David Foster Wallace, to contemporary culturalists
Alice Walker and Amy Tan. Postwar poets John Ashberry, Robert
Lowell, and Theodore Roethke have each enjoyed residencies here,
the latter two of which saw their efforts realized in the
respective publications of ``The Mills of The Kavanaughs'' and ``A
Field of Light.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenwich Village painter Robert DeNiro Sr. had a residency
there, delivered to the door by his son, Robert, acting as his
father's chauffeur.
</P>
<P>
   The guests, who number as many as 35 at any one time, congregate
for morning and evening meals inside the main mansion. The hours in
between 9 a.m. and 4 p.m. are reserved for the quiet isolation of
work; a black Thermos and lunchbox emblazoned with their name and
stocked with fruit, sandwiches, carrot sticks and a cookie their
sole companion.
</P>
<P>
   After a day of uninterrupted work, the guests congregate for
evening conversation, or may gather for recreational games of
pingpong or croquet.
</P>
<P>
   Some head for town to enjoy Saratoga, and to add to the
legendary cannon of tales, half-truths, and wild rumors that have
circulated through the ages befitting a group of creative stylists
sequestered in the woods.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Saratoga was an absolute wide open city, anything went,''
Malcolm Cowley told Robert McNeil in a 1986 PBS documentary on
Yaddo, recalling his residency in the early 1930s when he scripted
the ``Paris'' chapters of his Lost Generation memoir ``Exile's
Return.'' Edward Hotaling recounted the general mayhem in his
Saratoga racing book ``They're Off!'':
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes these giggling geniuses would jump in a station
wagon to go rollicking down to the movies at The Community Theatre
on Broadway, where the lady at the candy counter would take one
look and wonder what the hell they would think up next.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, like 1956 Pulitzer Prize-winning poet Elizabeth Bishop,
sought more wholesome avenues of escape, disappearing for morning
strolls through Yaddo's woods to the adjacent practice track with
blueberry muffin in hand, and finding a seat among the benches
watching the trainers exercising their horses.
</P>
<P>
   Yaddo's philosophy of offering respite to literary veteran and
relative newcomer alike has been a prosperous mix. Terry McMillan
wrote the first draft of her debut novel, ``Mama,'' while residing
at Yaddo, and Jules Feiffer scripted his first screenplay there.
Mario Puzo visited Yaddo in parts of 1958 and 1960, coming away
with the strands of his early novel, ``The Fortunate Pilgrim.''
Puzo would later reapply for residency in 1967 with the expressed
purpose of ``writing a story about a Mafia family'' that would
become ``The Godfather.''
</P>
<P>
   Yaddo's most famous young author arrived in May 1946. By the
time his residency concluded 11 weeks later, 21-year-old Truman
Capote had attained national recognition in a Life magazine photo
spread of his visit, and had created the prose that would become
``Other Voices, Other Rooms.''
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Highsmith wrote her debut thriller ``Strangers On A
Train,'' during a residency in 1948. The work was later adapted for
a film of the same name by Alfred Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting musicians and composers orchestrate their own circle of
notoriety, among them Leonard Bernstein, Marc Blitzstein, Oscar
Levant, Ned Rorem and Aaron Copland.
</P>
<P>
   To date, Yaddo alumni have been awarded 48 Pulitzer Prizes and
45 National Book Awards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-98 1459EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
