 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, Aug. 11:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Africa Bombings &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-BOMBINGS (Nairobi) _ Ledeall on the rescue effort in
Nairobi and the investigation. By Raymond Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-TANZANIA (Dar Es Salaam) _ Developments: Arrests reported
of two suspects in the Tanzania bombing. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-U.S. (Washington) _ Washington developments in the
terrorist attacks on two embassies.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-FUNERAL (Dar Es Salaam) _ The scene at a funeral for a
victim in Tanzania. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-DEAD (Ramstein Air Base, Germany) _ American dead are
brought to Ramstein. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   Other stories as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Other international &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-U.S. (Washington) _ The Clinton administration says
that the inauguration of a new president in Colombia should mean
the end of years of ill will between the two countries, especially
if President Andres Pastrana moves quickly on his pledge to stem
the flood of Colombian cocaine into the United States. By Philip
Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   CONGO-REBELLION (Abidjan, Ivory Coast) _ Claiming its first
major success against a week-old insurrection, Congolese officials
said Monday that government troops today had beaten back rebels who
had captured several strategic towns in the southwest of the
country, encircling many of them at a rebel-held military base. By
Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-CORRUPTION (Tokyo) _ Earlier this year, it seemed that a
sweeping corruption investigation might send a good number of the
bureaucrats who largely run the country to prison. But the only
government employee who has gone anywhere is Katsuhiko Kumazaki,
the prosecutor who led the investigation into scandals involving
expensive lavish entertainment for government employees paid for by
businessmen who wanted their favor. By Sheryl WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   NEVIS-INDEPENDENCE (Dateline to kumn) _ Nevis, part of the
Federation of St. Kitts and Nevis, one of tiniest countries in the
world, votes today on becoming an independent and even tinier
country. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ Developments in Kenneth Starr's
investigation of the president.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-REPUBS (Washington) _ Republicans go home for summer
with divisions as deep, though not as vocal, as last year's. Fault
lines between social conservatives and business conservatives get
deeper and mess up all kinds of legislation. By Alison Mitchell.
(1250 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-HEALTHCARE (Louisville, Ky.) _ The president discusses
the patient's bill of rights and ends up in Chicago at a fund
raiser. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-MEGAN-SUIT (San Francisco) _ A federal judge is to rule on
a challenge to California's sex offender notification law by a man
forced to move several times, who asserts its unconstitutional. By
Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-MURDER (Chicago) _ Chicago is reeling as two boys, seven
and eight years old, are charged with first degree murder in the
killing of an 11-year-old apparently killed for her bicycle. By Pam
Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   NY-PHONE-STRIKE (New York) _ Developments in the Bell Atlantic
strike. By Terry Pristin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BLACKS-BUSINESS (Undated) _ Corporate giants are chasing the
increasingly lucrative African American market. Black-owned
businesses that prospered by catering to an underserved market
during segregation-era America are gaining the attention of big
competitors seeking to sell products and services to consumers
whose needs and neighborhoods they once overlooked. By Dana Canedy.
</P>
<P>
   UNITED-HUMANA (Undated) _ United Healthcare's acquisition of
Humana, once valued at $5.5 billion, collapses because a $2.9
billion drop in the value of United Healthcare's stock last week
had sharply lessened the value of the deal to Humana shareholders.
By David J. Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stock market developments: At 1:20 p.m., the
Dow industrials were up 26 points, Nasdaq down 2 points. London was
down 1.9 percent and Frankfurt 2.5 percent. Earlier, Hong Kong
shares rose 0.2 percent and Tokyo stocks fell 1.3 percent. Back in
this country, at midday the long bond was up 6/32 point, with the
yield at 5.62 percent. By Sharon R. King.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDMAN-IPO (New York) _ Goldman Sachs's partners will vote
today on terms of their initial public offering. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Undated) _ Some Microsoft court filings in
their antitrust case. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ECON (Shanghai) _ Examining the question of whether China
will devalue its currency. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   CBOT (Undated) _ More about the Chicago Board of Trade's
decision to begin electronically trading all the major products
that the New York Board of Trade now trades. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   NYSE-Y2K (New York) _ Results of the Big Board's Year 2000
tests. By Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   ROYAL-DOMINICK (Undated) _ Folo on reports that Royal Ahold has
offered about $2 billion for Dominick's Supermarkets of Illinois.
The Dutch company has already bought four supermarket chains on the
East Coast and is currently acquiring a fifth, Giant Food. By Dana
Canedy.
</P>
