<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: You think it's hot now
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   (''Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in which readers share
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or
at least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
</P>
<P>
   The summer of 1998 will go down in the books as one of the
hottest on record. But Sarah T. Hayes of Longview, Texas, remembers
when summers seemed even hotter _ back before air-conditioning.
Here's her story:
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then, there was a summer way of life. One had summer
clothes, food and ways of doing things to coexist with the heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunate folks had water coolers in their windows, and the
whirling, gurgling sound of the fan and water contraption promised
a cooler interior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before air-conditioning, people did their work early in the
day, rested or coasted through the heat of the day and finished the
day at a summer-slow pace. Most things could wait until tomorrow
when _ who knows? _ it might cool off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fathers like mine wore lighter-weight business suits with a
short-sleeve white shirt and straw hats. The ubiquitous necktie was
there, but sometimes Pop carried his suit coat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mama wore cotton dresses with open-toed shoes. We girls wore
shorts and tops, sandals or sneakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lived in Dallas and as soon as school was out Mama would
start planning our annual visits to her relatives in smaller towns
all over Central and East Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``First on the list would be Waco to see her father, who was
known locally as Big Thom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we might go to Aunt Mab in Cleburne, Uncle Al and Aunt
Lela in Palestine, and then on to Mama's sister Sue and her
husband, El Jay, in Longview.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pop would gallantly stay behind in Dallas to work and hold
down the fort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our normally quiet and unassuming mother would become the
fearless leader of those grand expeditions. For us city kids,
little towns were foreign soil indeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mama's relatives were not quite as sophisticated as Pop's
were, but, oh, how I remember the love and the laughter amid the
vast quantities of delicious food.
</P>
<P>
   ``I drool a bit as I recall really fresh fried chicken, corn on
the cob, cakes, berry cobblers and on and on.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had room left, there was drippy, juicy watermelon on
the back porch where one could spit seeds out _ if Mama was busy
talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember going barefoot in grass that had stickers and grass
burrs to make you hop and holler, but that was better than the
sidewalks that charbroiled tender soles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember we kids hated having to stop playing to come inside
to rest. I know now that mothers worried about polio and heat
strokes. We thought that naps were for babies and the elderly, not
for regular kids like us. We must have been a handful, even though
we look sweet in the old photos.
</P>
<P>
   ``One summer my sister and I tried to fry eggs on the sidewalk
in front of Big Thom's house.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might have worked if we had not been missed and, thus,
caught in the act. Compounding our crime was the fact that we not
only sneaked out of the house when we were supposed to be napping
but, the worst part, that we stole eggs from our grandfather's
prized Rhode Island Reds out in the chicken house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess we will never know for sure if the radio was right,
that you could fry eggs on the sidewalk that summer in Waco so long
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is only now that I realize that we were able to see Texas
cities before they outgrew themselves, and the little towns at
their Southern Americana best.''
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story to share, mail it to ``Dreamsville,'' c/o
Joe Murray, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin, Texas, 75915. Joe Murray,
editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas) Daily News,
</P>
<P>
   is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
AWEW18A(at)prodigy.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
