<HEADER>
A6442 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEAT-RANCHERS-1000(2T     08-10 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEAT-RANCHERS-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAUGHT BETWEEN PARCHED EARTH AND DRY HEAVENS, RANCHER WAITS FOR
BETTER DAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM MADIGAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ One day last week the clouds were finally
different, and when they do change, Jack Birdwell is among the
first to notice.
</P>
<P>
   When his wife, Billie, married into the ranching life 21 years
ago, she could not believe how much time Jack spent studying the
sky, as if he tried to parse out the meaning of every cloud, like a
sage over tea leaves. But she soon came to understand why Jack got
in the lifelong habit of looking up: Those clouds decided his
ranching fate.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, while pouring cement for a cattle scale, Jack Birdwell
sees what he has been looking for _ pregnant, billowing clouds,
some bordered in dark blue, dressing up the northwest sky. It's
been too long.
</P>
<P>
   This summer's historic drought has already drained many of
Birdwell's stock tanks and burned up the grasses of his pastures.
He and other Texas ranchers, no longer able to feed their herds,
are selling off cows, driving market prices to the basement,
causing the spiral of catastrophe to continue. All this because of
bleached-out skies and wispy, worthless clouds.
</P>
<P>
   But Birdwell's family has been in ranching for a century, and
during that time droughts have always ended. That is the value of
experience. Things always change. The puffy clouds he sees are a
welcome reminder that even in this terrible summer of 1998, that
will certainly be true again.
</P>
<P>
   SOMETIMES THERE'S GLAMOUR. NOT THIS YEAR: Birdwell drives from
his spacious ranch home and eventually turns off the blacktop of
Palo Pinto County back roads 80 miles northwest of Fort Worth. He
inches along bumpy dirt trails that traverse his land. Usually he,
Billie and teen-age son Jay come here on horseback to count and
tend to young cattle, nursing them through the critical period of
the first year when the animals are most prone to illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they're fresh weaned, they're pretty skittish, and they
won't be where you can see them,'' Jack Birdwell says. ``And if
they're sick, they're not going to be laying where you can see
them. So you've got to ride and look in the spots that a pickup
can't get to.''
</P>
<P>
   It sounds like such fun to a city dweller, riding after cattle,
and it's hard not to envy Birdwell, who has been riding a horse
since he was old enough to walk. As a boy, he followed his father
into the pastures every day, and never really considered doing
anything else with his life. He was drawn by the tradition begun by
his grandfather, by a deep attachment to the cedar and
mesquite-studded land, the freedom, working outside. But the
romance is deceptive.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, when the weather's pretty, and you don't find any
sick cattle, when it's all working in the right direction, then
everything's fine. It's enjoyable,'' Jack Birdwell says. ``But when
it's raining straight down and it's 35 degrees out there, you've
got to do it anyway. Or the fog's so thick that you can't see in
front of your face, you've still got to find them. All the glamour
has gone out if it then.''
</P>
<P>
   And all the glamour has gone out of it now. It is midafternoon
as the pickup bumps along, another day when the temperature climbs
past 100. The land is brown and dead. Two lethargic young cows
kneel in the shade of a live oak, a scene illustrating the
rancher's dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want out in this heat any more than people do,''
Jack Birdwell says of his cattle. ``They won't eat. You'll catch
them grazing until maybe 8:30 in the morning, then they'll shade up
for the rest of the day. More than likely, it's not until 6:30 or 7
at night before they'll come out, and they won't have but an hour
or an hour and a half to graze, unless the moon's up.''
</P>
<P>
   In other years, when rain is more plentiful, the heat less
intense and the grass knee-high, cows graze all day, fattening
themselves up for sale and the slaughterhouse. This year, cattle
are losing weight, and every pound lost is money from the rancher's
pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Birdwell pulls to a stop in a broad pasture, watched by dozens
of other cattle that linger in the shade. He steps from the truck
onto brown, burnt grass that is crisp beneath his boot. Grass that
has lost its green color has also lost its protein, he says, so he
must hand-feed his herd protein supplements, adding to his costs.
</P>
<P>
   Across the pasture lies a dried, sun-baked patch of mud that
used to be a stock tank. The mud is cracked and broken and
resembles a jigsaw puzzle. There are occasional deep gouges where
cattle have tried to trudge through the muck toward what was left
of the water. Stagnant water left in the tanks has made Birdwell's
calves sick.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Another nearby tank is also dwindling fast. Without rain,
Birdwell will not have enough water to get his herd through the
winter and will have to sell more cattle.
</P>
<P>
   He also fears an infestation of grasshoppers. Range fires nip at
his land. The grim litany of this summer goes on and on.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we got to thinking about it,'' Billie Birdwell says,
smiling in the hot sun, ``we might get depressed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you find yourself talking to yourself,'' her husband
says.
</P>
<P>
   HE FINALLY SEES HOPE: Jack Birdwell checks the cattle markets
twice a day, and this summer the news has always been bad. The
drought and heat have decimated hay crops, forcing ranchers to sell
cattle they won't be able to feed in winter. Largely as a result, a
cow and calf that might have brought $700 just last winter might be
worth $500 now, Birdwell says. He's gone below the break-even point
on most of his stock.
</P>
<P>
   But he still sleeps better than his wife does. Birdwell was
raised in a life where ranchers often lived on the edge of
calamity. Billie is the daughter of a butane company owner in
nearby Mineral Wells, and far less accustomed to the uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just know it's going to get better,'' Jack Birdwell says.
``It always has; it will again.''
</P>
<P>
   On his way from the pastures, he drives to the top of a hill for
a bit of sightseeing. Far below is the Brazos River as it snakes
through a broad valley. The country is beautiful from here.
</P>
<P>
   And in the sky, Jack Birdwell finally sees hope _ big, puffy,
pregnant clouds building across the prairie sky he has studied all
his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something's broken up,'' he says of the sky. ``These clouds
are trying. It looks more promising than anything we've had in
days.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, his ranch will receive a good rain.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
