<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 (jt)  
 By C. CLAIBORNE RAY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Silver Linings
</P>
<P>
   Q. What determines the color of clouds?
</P>
<P>
   A. A cloud's color depends chiefly on its own relationship to
the light of the sun, said Todd Miner, a meteorologist at
Pennsylvania State University. In some cases, it depends on the
color of the surrounding sky.
</P>
<P>
   If a cloud covers the whole visible area of the sky, the depth
of the cloud determines the color of the cloud; the deeper it is,
the darker it is. As a ray of sunlight impinges on the cloud, the
water in the cloud can either reflect the light back toward space
or absorb the light, Miner explained. Either effect will dilute the
strength of the sunlight that gets through.
</P>
<P>
   If the wavelengths of the sun's visible light, in the familiar
red-to-violet spectrum, are not blocked, but scattered equally, the
result is white light, Miner said. So, if the sun is shining and
the cloud is not covering the sun, in general the cloud is white.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes particles in the atmosphere and the angle of the path
the sun's rays must travel through it can result in preferential
scattering of wavelengths so that a particular color, like gold,
predominates in a cloud, Miner said. This is the same reason the
sky is predominantly blue, because the blue wavelengths are the
most scattered.
</P>
<P>
   At other times, when the sky is orange, for example, some of
that light is reflected off a cloud, just like a colored light
shining on a mirror, so the cloud appears orange.
</P>
<P>
   Readers are invited to submit questions about science to
Questions, Science Times, The New York Times, 229 West 43d St., New
York, N.Y. 10036. Questions of general interest will be answered in
this column, but requests for medical advice cannot be honored and
unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
