<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6498 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-DECLINING-DISEASE     08-10 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DECLINING-DISEASES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACING MODERN PERILS, MEDICAL SCHOOLS PONDER THE CLASSICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (af)  
 By ABIGAIL ZUGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The humble microbe E. coli showed up all green and evil on the
cover of Time magazine recently and made it official: This is
becoming the year of the germ.
</P>
<P>
   During the winter the public got a crash course in anthrax and
plague, putative weapons of biological warfare past and future. In
the spring, the news swung around to E. coli 0157:H7 in ground
beef, cheese and swimming pools, salmonella in breakfast cereal and
cryptosporidium on fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Antibacterial goo has appeared for sale in the vegetable aisle
of the supermarket; a local New York television station ushered in
the summer with a cheery two-part series on coliform contamination
of the city's soft ice-cream machines.
</P>
<P>
   Newsworthy infections have been attracting so much fanfare this
year that we have yet to hear a fitting recessional for the handful
of great infections of history that are slowly fading from view.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in
Atlanta recorded 138 confirmed cases of measles in the United
States. There were 612 reported cases of mumps, 161 of German
measles, scattered hundreds of the vicious childhood meningitis
caused by the Hemophilus influenzae bacterium that only 10 years
ago still left thousands of children deaf or mentally retarded each
year.
</P>
<P>
   Before vaccination against these common childhood diseases
became routine, case numbers ran to tens or hundreds of thousands a
year; no ordinary American doctor could get through a year of
practice without seeing them all.
</P>
<P>
   Now, no ordinary American doctor is likely to run into any of
them ever again. Along with diphtheria, cholera and polio they all
still roam the world _ but not here, not any more.
</P>
<P>
   Except in the classrooms and lecture halls of the country's
medical schools, that is, where the professors are trying to figure
out what to keep in their curriculums.
</P>
<P>
   In a few weeks, Dr. Franklin D. Lowy, a professor of medicine at
the Albert Einstein College of Medicine in the Bronx, will begin to
plan the microbiology and infectious diseases course that the class
of 2001, now second-year medical students, will study next winter
and spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to know what the students should learn,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The long lecture segments on measles and German measles _ should
Lowy keep them intact, condense them, or discard them completely
and tell the students to read their textbooks instead? The hour
lecture devoted to Hemophilus influenzae and its relatives _ should
it be kept, abbreviated or given over to E. coli and the other
intestinal infections so often in the news this year?
</P>
<P>
   What about Howie S., an imaginary young man exposed to measles
on a hospital ward, that Einstein instructors have used to teach
about the transmission and diagnosis of measles? Is Howie still
worth a dedicated half-hour of classroom time?
</P>
<P>
   Medical students do learn vital lessons about patterns of
infection and the ways microbes cause disease by studying classic
diseases they will never see, Lowy said. Hence the sacrosanct hour
devoted to leprosy in his course (109 new cases of leprosy were
diagnosed in the United States last year).
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the medical student is nothing if not a
supremely pragmatic organism. Faced with mountains of details to
learn, students are merciless at finding the chaff. Last year, an
Einstein student greeted the happy news of the imminent departure
of measles from her purview with a roll of her eyes and a slam of
her pen right down on the obsolescent case of Howie S.
</P>
<P>
   ``So then why don't they teach us things we need to know
instead?'' she said to general applause.
</P>
<P>
   The question of what infections an American doctor will need to
know in the year 2001 is not an easy one to answer. The world has
become too small to call any of the diseases that are disappearing
from the United States really extinct.
</P>
<P>
   They all still roar through other countries with enough ferocity
that they will continue to trickle into ours: diphtheria from
Eastern Europe, German measles from Central and South America,
measles from Africa and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as medical students may sense with a surer instinct than
their professors, doctors need to focus on the patients directly in
front of them, not those half a world away. Our society's new
microbes are clamoring for time and attention too.
</P>
<P>
   The organism called chlamydia caused almost half a million
infections here last year, and some evidence now connects it with
heart attacks as well. Should a share of the lecture time for
measles be handed over to chlamydia? Or should it go to
Helicobacter pylori, the newly discovered bacterial cause of
stomach ulcers?
</P>
<P>
   Or to the tick-borne bacteria called Ehrlichia that can fatally
poison the bone marrow; or the Sin Nombre viruses that cause a
fatal pneumonia; or a whole new species of bacteria, called the
nanobacteria, that may be responsible for many kidney stones?
</P>
<P>
   New forms of venerable bacteria like the pneumococcus are
resistant to more and more antibiotics; when should the students
start hearing less about polio and cholera and more about all of
them?
</P>
<P>
   The germs are all out there, knocking at Lowy's syllabus,
demanding to be let in. He has 45 hours of lecture time and 12
hours of classroom time to apportion among them. So far, he said,
no disease is definitely off the list, but Howie S. may soon be
heading for retirement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
