<SLUG> BC-SANANTONIO-GOP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN ANTONIO TOUTS ETHNIC MIX TO GOP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Civic boosters in San Antonio, a city famous for
the Alamo and the Riverwalk, think they have a new trump card in
their bid to host the next Republican National Convention: the
city's growing Hispanic population.
</P>
<P>
   ``If San Antonio is chosen, it's a clear extended hand by the
Republicans to the national Hispanic community,'' said Tom
Loeffler, a former Republican congressman who is spearheading the
city's campaign to host the GOP gathering in 2000. ``It's a very
important item that Republicans must consider.''
</P>
<P>
   The Alamo City seems all but certain to make the first cut when
Republicans narrow the list of potential sites from eight to as few
as three, possibly within the next few days. The other contenders
are New Orleans, New York, Chicago, Philadelphia, Indianapolis,
Minneapolis and Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Although party leaders say political considerations are far less
important than such mundane items as the number of hotel rooms, San
Antonio backers are convinced that they have the winning
combination of good facilities and the right population mix.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio's Hispanic population officially stands at about 56
percent, making it the nation's largest majority-Hispanic city.
</P>
<P>
   The city grew up around a string of Spanish missions constructed
in the early 1700s and has never abandoned its cultural ties. A
surplus of Mexican restaurants and attractions like El Mercado, a
Mexican-style market, and La Villita, an arts and crafts village on
the site of the original settlement, add to the city's reputation
as Mexico's northernmost city.
</P>
<P>
   With both political parties courting the Hispanic vote, San
Antonio boosters are marketing the home town as a vital link to the
nation's fastest-growing voting bloc. Hispanics make up about 11
percent of the U.S. population, but they are expected to comprise
25 percent by 2050, if not sooner.
</P>
<P>
   The trend is particularly evident in vote-rich Texas and
California, states that traditionally play a big role in
presidential politics.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Opinsky, a Republican consultant who is assisting in
preparation of San Antonio's convention bid, said GOP leaders
cannot ignore political realities in selecting a host city.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can read the demographics as well as anybody. If we don't
start doing better in the Hispanic community, we're not going to
win the White House in the year 2010 because the votes won't be
there,'' he said. ``Being able to show the party wrapped around the
imagery of a Hispanic city and in the middle of the Hispanic
culture says a lot to the viewers at home.''
</P>
<P>
   The economic stakes are huge. The convention is expected to
generate more than $100 million in direct economic benefits. Nearly
2,000 Republican delegates will be accompanied by an equal number
of alternates, 15,000 journalists and about 20,000 lobbyists,
political groupies and assorted hangers-on.
</P>
<P>
   The indirect benefits of international attention are impossible
to measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are larger conventions and trade shows, but none of them
attract a press corps of 15,000 journalists,'' said Tim
Fitzpatrick, a spokesman for the Republican site selection
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Texas has hosted two Republican National Conventions in recent
years _ Houston in 1992 and Dallas in 1984. Democrats haven't
gathered in the state for their national convention since visiting
Houston in 1928.
</P>
<P>
   Cities bidding for the 2000 Democratic National Convention
include Los Angeles, Boston, Miami and Denver. New Orleans,
Philadelphia and Minneapolis are competing for both major-party
conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties hope to make the final selection by year's end,
although the GOP pick will not be officially ratified until
January. In the meantime, members of the two site selection
committees are getting the red-carpet treatment from the potential
hosts.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio treated members of the Republican delegation to
dinner on the Alamo grounds and gave each visitor a personalized
Spurs basketball jersey. The city's $21.3 million convention
commitment _ $6.3 million in municipal services and $15 million in
cash and in-kind contributions from private donors _ includes the
promise of a car and driver for all 165 members of the Republican
National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the site selectors received carriage rides in
Central Park, tickets and back-stage passes to a Broadway show, and
dinner at Tavern on the Green. Indianapolis passed out copies of
the movie ``Hoosiers'' autographed by Bobby Plump, the former high
school basketball player whose exploits inspired the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better than a normal business trip where you're cooped up
in a hotel for a couple days,'' Fitzpatrick acknowledged. Although
the GOP spokesman carefully avoided any signs of favoritism, he
offered assurances that this summer's Texas heat wave will not
count against San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to find a city that can best physically accommodate
us, weather or no weather,'' Fitzpatrick said. ``It would be a
great chance for San Antonio to show us how well their air
conditioning works.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
