<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INCA-GOLD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSION POSSIBLE: HUNTING FOR INCA GOLD AT 18,000 FEET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE GANAHL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUITO, Ecuador _ My eyelids jolt open at 5 a.m. and I look
anxiously at the skylight above my hotel bed. For the first time in
days no rain splatters on it. Today we will fly over the Andes.
</P>
<P>
   The tension was thick last night among the expedition crew, a
high-testosterone group of scientists, fly-boys, documentary
filmmakers and treasure hunters. Weather and other technical
adversities had forced postponement of the flight for several days
and time was growing short.
</P>
<P>
   They had come to South America to test new, ultra-refined,
ground-penetrating radar, a device that could revolutionize
archaeology. For the scientists, the aim was to prove the
capabilities of the tool by flying over a region in the Andes
reputed to be the last bastion of Inca life. They hoped to find
evidence beneath the trees, or under the earth.
</P>
<P>
   For the treasure hunters on the periphery of this group, the
hope was cracking the mystery of where the Inca buried their gold.
Would the radar turn up indications of mines? Roads? Structures?
For the Berkeley, Calif.-based documentary crew headed by Adam
Ballachey and David Ultan, the goal was to film the final scenes of
``The Search for Inca Gold,'' an hour-long film they were making
about the project for the A&AMP;E Network series, ``The New
Explorers.''
</P>
<P>
   Ballachey and Ultan, both 30 and friends since childhood, have
been pursuing this story for two years, interviewing prominent
treasure hunters, compiling historic leads, even trekking into the
Llanganati, the viciously rugged area of the Andes that history
claims is where Inca general Rumanahui hid some 40 tons of gold
from Spanish conquistadors in the mid-1500s.
</P>
<P>
   History books suggest it could be the largest cache of
undiscovered treasure in the world, worth up to $4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Heading the science experiment is Dr. Roger Vickers, 60, who
possibly has the most at stake in how this test flight pans out. He
developed the radar technology.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot, Sky, has too many gnarly missions _ some say for the
CIA _ under his belt to be anything less than completely
trustworthy as he guides this twin-engine Beechcraft through
18,000-foot Andean peaks.
</P>
<P>
   On board is an array of computer screens, keyboards and other
high-tech gizmos. I cram myself into a corner seat and try not to
kick out any of the hundred electrical cords running through the
cabin.
</P>
<P>
   Taking off, the plane must quickly climb, such is the sharp bowl
of the valley. Soon we are traveling directly toward the volcano
Cotopaxi, a stunning sight in the bright sun. I anxiously wonder if
we are going to clear the summit, which crowds the entire
windshield. Then I realize we are going to fly by so close it feels
like I'll be able to scrape off the snow with my hands.
</P>
<P>
   Soon the clouds part and ahead of us lies a patch of jagged,
green peaks: the Llanganati.
</P>
<P>
   Looking down, I am amazed by the amount of water _ rivers and
waterfalls and streams _ all brown and rushing. It is not jungle,
exactly, but rugged high-altitude scrub and forest. The mountains
rise so sharply it's hard to imagine an army traversing them, but
the Inca people were a hardy lot.
</P>
<P>
   The team decides that the conditions are so perfect they will go
ahead and do the survey now, rather than coming back later. In a
trice, Vickers has set the equipment, and Sky gives him the
coordinates to start the radar.
</P>
<P>
   Diving down into the valley, the plane follows the slopes off to
the right side. After one low sweep of the area, Vickers asks Sky,
``Can you keep going a bit longer?'' The pilot quips that it would
be impossible, ``unless you want to eat some trees.''
</P>
<P>
   Straight ahead, there is a hillside looming, which we skim over
just higher than the treetops.
</P>
<P>
   After the second pass things become a bit less tense. Peering
down into the bottomless valley, Vickers quips, ``Damn, there's
that gold again!''
</P>
<P>
   Back on the ground, the drama is awaiting the survey results,
which will have to be compiled in the coming weeks. And Vickers and
Sky already have their next mission assigned _ this time by the
U.S. military _ which will most likely be filmed again by Ballachey
and Ultan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to fly over some abandoned military sites and use
the radar to look for unexploded munitions!'' Sky says brightly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
