<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY CALL IT STORMY SATURDAY?  
 BACTERIA FEAST ON TNT  
 ADULTS KEY TO SAVING SPECIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ariz., Calif.)   (af)  
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You work hard during that Monday-through-Friday grind, and what
do you get for your efforts?
</P>
<P>
   Rainy weekends, perhaps. Two researchers at Arizona State
University, Randall S. Cerveny and Robert C. Balling Jr., have
shown that there may be a correlation between work-week pollution
and increased precipitation on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have long known that some pollution varies in weekly
cycles corresponding to human activity. The phenomenon even has a
nickname: the Sunday effect. It is thought to be related to heavier
use of cars during the work week.
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind the current study, Cerveny said, is ``if we show
weather that has a seven-day cycle, the likelihood is that it is
created by something that we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The scientists analyzed climate data for a zone of the western
Atlantic, out to 400 miles from the East Coast. They found that
rainfall in the area was higher on Fridays and Saturdays than the
rest of the week. By Sunday the average rainfall had begun to
decline. Their results are reported in the journal Nature.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers theorize that airborne pollutants, built up
during the week along the urbanized East Coast and swept in by the
prevailing winds, are to blame for the wet weather. Solid pollution
particles trap heat and in turn heat the surrounding air. This
creates greater uplift of air, and results in more clouds and
rainfall.
</P>
<P>
   So if your bosses want you to work a weekend, tell them yes,
provided you can take Monday off. And enjoy the weather. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bacteria, of course, work seven days a week, 365 days a year.
But that doesn't mean they cannot occasionally have a blast.
</P>
<P>
   A strain of Enterobacter cloacae bacteria has been demonstrated
by researchers in Britain to have an appetite for trinitrotoluene,
better known as the explosive TNT.
</P>
<P>
   The bacteria produce an enzyme that can break down the ring
structure of TNT, which is resistant to degradation. The scientists
say the organism holds promise for helping to decontaminate weapons
manufacturing and testing sites that are rife with the explosive.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, a strain of cold-adapted bacteria has been shown to
be effective in breaking down hydrocarbons in low temperatures. The
Canadian researchers who studied the bacteria, a strain of
rhodococcus, suggest that it could be used to help clean spills of
diesel fuel or kerosene in the Arctic. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is natural to think that whether a species thrives depends on
the survival of its young. But researchers have shown that in the
case of the cheetah, at least, deaths of adult animals have a
greater impact on population than deaths of cubs do.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, at the University of California at Santa Cruz,
used a computer model of a cheetah population based on field
studies of the animal in the Serengeti plains in East Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The model, which could be adjusted for different mortality rates
and other parameters, showed that survival of adult animals is the
force that drives population growth. This despite the fact that in
some areas of Africa and Asia, up to 95 percent of cheetah cubs do
not survive to adulthood, most falling victim to lions, hyenas and
other animals.
</P>
<P>
   The reason involves cheetah reproduction. Field studies have
shown that when a female cheetah's cubs die, she quickly enters a
period of sexual readiness, or heat, and breeds again.
</P>
<P>
   For the same reason, the loss of an adult can be traumatic for
the reproductive abilities of a population. (The ability to breed
again rapidly seems to be an evolved trait, suggesting that
cheetahs have been losing their young for a long time.)
</P>
<P>
   The researchers say their work holds lessons for wildlife
conservationists who are struggling to protect cheetahs. It may be
more important to save adult animals from human predators like
poachers than to save cubs from animal predators like lions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
