<DOCNO> NYT19980810.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6582 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-OCTOPUS-ART-760(2     08-10 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-OCTOPUS-ART-760(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MOST INTELLIGENT MOLLUSK: THE OCTOPUS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ill., Texas, Wash.)   (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(js) 
 By NATALIE ANGIER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When you pet a cat, the cat purrs.
</P>
<P>
   When you pet an octopus, the octopus pets you back.
</P>
<P>
   OK, maybe it doesn't quite pet. It loops a limb around your
hand, and it explores you. And at first you jump, and then you
laugh, and then you practically yodel with joy, for the sensation
of an octopus fondle is unlike anything you have sensated before.
Its flesh is slippery and silky, like the inside of your cheek, or
a spoonful of flan. And arrayed in pairs along the underside of its
eight arms are its extraordinary suckers, the animal's way of
knowing the world.
</P>
<P>
   An octopus has 1,200 or more muscular suckers, and each one can
move as an independent operator, sucking and plucking and nuzzling
at an object like a tiny infant mouth rooting at his mother's
breast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watch out for your rings!'' Carrie Reidel warned. ``He can
pull them right off your fingers.'' Ms. Reidel is a keeper at the
Invertebrate House of the National Zoo in Washington, home to the
giant octopus now engaged in an act of hominid-cephalopod groping.
She hovers over the tank, a long pole at the ready. Sometimes the
octopus suctions hard enough to leave behind a mark. ``We call that
an octopus hickey,'' Ms. Reidel said.
</P>
<P>
   But no hickeys today, alas. Today the octopus, a 2-year-old,
30-pound male of the species Octopus dofleini, is in a gentle,
languid mood, and he soon releases his mesmerized guest. As he
swims off, his limbs snake around him like the scarves of Chinese
dancers, the membranes between them billowing into a translucent
orange parachute.
</P>
<P>
   An octopus is an invertebrate, a mollusk, no less, and thus in
the same taxonomic category as clams, oysters and snails. Yet the
octopus stands head and multiple shoulders above other
invertebrates in its capacity to elicit human affection and
fascination.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to the National Zoo express their admiration with
hoots, sighs and aahs, and a comparative disdain for other
creatures in the vicinity, even the tarantulas. Keepers at
aquariums and zoos say they will name their octopuses, a thought
that never crosses their mind for the anemones or the fish _ and
did the Beatles ever write a song about a trout? The ancients
revered octopuses: the Minoans painted them on vases 3,500 years
ago, while the early Hindus may have used them as inspiration for
depictions of such poly-limbed gods as Siva and Vishnu.
</P>
<P>
   Most smitten of all are octopus biologists, who never tire of
their subject, never question their career choice and never
hesitate to draw attention to the beauty and sophistication of the
octopus. Some will talk about how clever the octopus is, ``the most
intelligent invertebrate in the world, there's no denying it,''
said Roland Anderson, a biologist at the Seattle Aquarium. How
smart is smart? Smart enough to want to have fun.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Jennifer Mather, an associate professor of psychology
and neuroscience at the University of Lethbridge in Canada,
reported at the Animal Behavior Society annual meeting that
octopuses engage in play behavior, a mark of relative mental
complexity and normally considered the province of young mammals.
But Dr. Mather described her observations of an octopus in an
aquarium that deliberately took a bottle over to the current of
water in its tank, watched it float along the current, and then
brought it back to do the same thing again, and again. ``If that
isn't play behavior,'' she said, ``I don't know what is.''
</P>
<P>
   The octopus also has real personality. Dr. Mather and Anderson
recently described their laboratory studies suggesting that
octopuses come in at least three different temperamental humors:
passive, aggressive and paranoid. Working with the red octopus, a
small species found off Seattle in Puget Sound, the researchers
repeatedly tested 44 individuals under 19 defined circumstances _
for example, how each octopus reacted when somebody opened its tank
and looked in, how it responded to a ``threat'' in the form of a
touch with a bristly brush, and how readily it pounced on proffered
prey like a crab.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the octopuses attacked the brush, and grabbed the crab
immediately upon seeing it. Those subjects the researchers labeled
aggressive. Others cringed from the brush and would wait until they
were alone, after nightfall, to eat their crabs _ the passive ones.
Still others, the paranoids, would respond to a threat by letting
out a burst of ink and jetting away. Each animal was consistent in
its behaviors from one round of testing to the next. ``We feel
strongly that octopuses have personalities,'' Anderson concluded.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   Octopus biologists love octopuses even though they are
notoriously hard to study in the wild, and even though there is
little financial support for their passion. None of the 100 or so
described species of octopus is thought to be in danger of
extinction, and so the field lacks the cachet of eco-consciousness.
Nevertheless, biologists love octopuses living and they love them
dead.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Voight of the Field Museum in Chicago has a lab full of
pickled octopuses in jars, specimens dredged up from oceanic depths
of two miles or more by submersible vehicles. She dissects each
rubbery, distorted corpse delivered to her, seeking to determine if
it is a familiar species or an entirely new one.
</P>
<P>
   She and others suspect that there are at least as many octopus
species out there to be discovered as are already described. Dr.
Voight also watches hour upon hour of videotape taken by cameras
aboard the submersible vehicle Alvin, of ghostly octopuses creeping
along the moonscape floor of the sea, or near the thermal vents.
She is trying to understand how the biology and behavior of
deep-water octopuses differ from what is seen in their cousins
closer to shore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at that, look at that!'' she said, pointing excitedly to
the video screen. ``It's doing a breast stroke! I don't know if
I've ever seen another octopus do that.'' She turns sheepish. ``I'm
like a parent with videos of my babies, aren't I?''
</P>
<P>
   Yet while Dr. Voight will never see many of her babies alive,
still she loves octopuses. ``There's something magical about
them,'' she said. ``They remind us of ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   They have big, human-like eyes that gaze out at you, she said,
with pupils that can dilate and contract. Their mantle, the large
sac that bulges up from the arms, resembles a giant, brainy head,
although the mantle in fact is where an octopus' visceral organs
are stored, while the real head is a small thatch right around the
eyes. ``And they're such bloodthirsty killers,'' Dr. Voight said.
``I like predators. I'm not going to study some sort of boring,
grazing thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Octopuses are not boring, but they are common. They abound
throughout the earth's oceans, from shallow waters to deep. The
smallest known octopus is Octopus micropyrsus, found off the shores
of California, which reaches barely an inch in length, while the
largest is the giant Octopus dofleini of the North Pacific, which
can grow to 15 feet long and weigh more than 100 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   The octopus has a catholic diet rather than a kosher one. It
loves just about any type of shellfish _ shrimp, lobster, clams,
gastropods, crabs. ``An octopus is like a vacuum cleaner as it
moves along the reef,'' said John Forsythe, a marine biologist at
the University of Texas Medical Branch in Galveston. ``All eight
arms are working at once, investigating every crack and crevice
with its suction cups, and pulling things out from deep inside.''
Upon yanking forth a crab or bivalve, the octopus balloons its
entire body around the prey and brings it up toward its beak-like
mouth, located at the center of its arms. The octopus then injects
a paralyzing neurotoxin into the prey, followed by an enzyme to
dissolve the meat away from the shell. With its mouth, radiating
arms and all those suckers, Forsythe said, ``what an octopus
amounts to is the most extraordinary set of lips on earth.''
</P>
<P>
   But they are not loose lips. An octopus makes good on
practically everything it eats. Humans convert maybe 10 percent of
ingested food into usable energy. An octopus' conversion rate is
greater than 50 percent, allowing it to bulk up from a birth size
so tiny it floats on plankton to its adult size in a matter of
weeks or months. And nearly all of what it puts on is pure muscle.
``An octopus in a lab can lift cinder blocks to get out of its
tank,'' Forsythe said. ``It's like having Arnold Schwarzenegger's
biceps in your aquarium.''
</P>
<P>
   The octopus' musculature stands in for a skeleton, and gives it
structure. That structure is flexible, and can nearly vanish when
an octopus chooses, allowing a very large animal to squeeze into a
space the size of, say, an empty beer bottle. Octopuses like to
hide in a den _ any crevice or hole that is protected. Often they
conceal the opening to that den by piling up rocks, broken shells,
broken glass, bottle caps, lost wedding rings, anything they can
find or sucker. That pile is called an octopus midden _ or garden,
if you prefer.
</P>
<P>
   The octopus' history is a tale of triumph and sorrow. Octopuses
are descendants of shelled mollusks that date back 500 million
years, but with the rise of the bony fishes, the octopus and its
cephalopod kin, the squid and the cuttlefish, had to take drastic
measures if they were to compete with the swift-swimming
vertebrates. They had to get fast and mobile in a hurry, which
meant losing the shell, their protective armor. They did get fast,
for an octopus can burst away by taking water into its mantle and
squirting it out through its siphon. But without a shell, it became
terribly vulnerable to other carnivores. ``An octopus is a good
hunk of protein,'' Forsythe said. ``You're talking sushi here.''
</P>
<P>
   And so the octopus evolved a new method of defense, a capacity
to camouflage itself that may be the finest in the animal kingdom.
It can change from orange to green to bone to blue in a fraction of
a second. While most animals that can change color, the chameleon,
for example, rely on blood-borne signals that take a few seconds to
reach the skin, the octopus manages the switch with its nervous
system.
</P>
<P>
   In its skin are cells called chromatophores, and each has little
sacs of red, black and yellow pigments. With a simple twitch of a
nerve impulse, the chromatophores release the appropriate mixture
of those pigments to blend in with the octopus' background. To
further widen the palette of disguises, the skin is stippled with
crystalline cells that reflect external light. Moreover, dermal
muscles can instantly pucker up the skin to make it resemble sand
or coral reef, or flatten it out to make it resemble smooth stones.
</P>
<P>
   Australian scientists have recently discovered a spectacular
group of octopuses, called mimic octopuses, which can change shape
to impersonate other marine animals. The mimics can take on the
appearance of a flounder, shrimp, sea snake, stingray, brittle star
or giant crab, a repertory that suggests the animals use their
camouflage not just for defensive purposes but also, in the spirit
of a wolf in sheep's clothing, to help them hunt better.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure of competition from vertebrates may also explain
why the octopus is comparatively supple in its behavior and can
learn at least a few things from experience.
</P>
<P>
   However they defend or offend, octopuses and other cephalopods
have flourished, and now account for a large fraction of the
ocean's biomass. Yet in living fast, they also die young. Octopuses
survive no more than two or three years, and they have but one
episode of reproduction. Their mating is frenzied and violent, a
writhing bowl of spaghetti, as the male and female arm-wrestle,
thrust at each other with their hard beaks and flash their colors
as if they were traffic lights and warning signs. The male has one
specially designed tentacle that is shorter than the other seven,
and unsuckered at its tip, and he uses that limb as a penis
equivalent, to pull his sperm from his mantle and thrust it into
the female's oviduct. Shortly after the mating ritual, the male
rapidly declines. He loses the sharpness of his camouflage. His
eyes cloud over, he stops eating, and he dies of starvation.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, the female still has a job to do. She is a good
mother, as invertebrates go. Several weeks after copulation, she
releases tens of thousands of eggs on a long, sticky strand and
attaches them to a protective surface. She stays with the eggs
until they hatch, all the while grooming them obsessively. But once
her young are born, neither her arms nor suckers nor personal charm
can keep her hanging on, and she dies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
