<SLUG> BC-CYBER-TRAVEL-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVELING THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., Aug, 16)  
 (JT)  
 By L.R. SHANNON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ON THE ROAD &QL; 
The Kuralt Approach &QL; 
 &UR; www.hiddenamerica.com &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to gather information about, say, Disney, on the Web.
You don't even have to look up the address; it is of course
www.disney.com, and it is stuffed with information about cruises,
shopping, videos and everything else to which an image of a smart
mouse or a dumb dog can be attached. But finding less obvious
things to do and places to go, local events little known outside
their immediate areas, is not as easy, and that is a need that
Hidden America intends to fill. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hidden America site on the Web, started a few months ago by
Eric Model of OTR (On the Road) Travel Information Services of
River Edge, N.J., focuses on annual festivals and events around the
country, especially ones you might drive to when you have a few
days off. Model also plans to have guides to ``village shops,''
where you can buy regional books, crafts and indigenous foods. Like
many Web sites, Hidden America is a work in progress; so far the
only shop listed on what will be an old-fashioned Main Street in
cyberspace was a bookstore, the ubiquitous Amazon.com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hidden America map looks like this: Road Compass, highlights
of coming events; Weekends on the Road, nearby activities;
Eventsamerica Annual Events; Newsletter from the Road Online, with
departments on such matters as roadside food, books and music, and
local language oddities; Backroads Forum, for exchanging
information; Village Shops; In My Hometown, and the American Travel
Experience, where a travel package, including air fare, auto
rentals and accommodations, eventually can be put together.
Accommodations will be largely bed-and-breakfasts, inns and small
hotels. If it all works out. Books and magazine and newspaper
articles are finished when they are printed; Web sites often are
not. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When I sampled Weekends on the Road in the days when July was
turning into August, I found a long list of events in the
Northeast, many of which had already taken place. A sample: ``Great
Falls Balloon Festival, August 21-23, Lewiston-Auburn, Maine. Hot
air balloons fill the downeast skies. Info: (207) 783-2249.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A handful of featured August events _ Elvis Week in Memphis, the
Delicato Charity Grape Stomp (California), Ketchum Wagon Days
(Idaho) and the Iowa State Fair _ were links to their respective
Web pages. From one I learned that the Delicato Vineyards, started
in Manteca, Calif., in 1924, will offer a tour on Aug. 30 while
grapes are being crushed. ``If you are 21 or older,'' the Delicatos
say, ``you will be able to taste the wine at three different
stages: juice, half wine/half juice, and wine.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the Charles Kuralt experience,'' Model said, referring
to the television personality's ``On the Road'' digressions. I
certainly will tune in again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ON-LINE PLANNING &QL; 
Age Discounts &QL; 
 &UR; www.aarp.org  &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Less adventurous baby boomers, and older folks, should drop into
the Web site of the American Association of Retired Persons. One
section, Trips n' Travel (click on What's New), lists hotels,
cruise lines and such that offer discounts to AARP members. A dip
into the hotel section brought up a long directory of mostly
familiar names _ Days Inn, Ramada, Marriott and the like _ with
discounts of 10 percent or more off the regular rates. Experienced
travelers know that the first rate mentioned is seldom the last
word, and the site points out that occasionally hotels offer rates
that beat the AARP discount. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is reading matter that may inspire a trip. In early
August, an eight-day road trip through Tennessee, ``from Davy
Crockett to Dolly Parton,'' was the featured article, and there
were also separate pieces on Iceland and northern Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
KEYSTROKES FOR BACKSTROKES  &QL; 
Swimming Across the World &QL; 
 &UR; lornet.com/SGOL/ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is the time of year for swimming around here, but every
time of the year is the time for swimming somewhere. SGOL stands
for Swimmers Guide On Line, a data base of ``full-size,
year-round'' pools _ 4,937 in 55 countries _ and if you can't find
a place to swim from this Web site, you are just not trying. The
listings include name, address, telephone number, a description of
the pool, length and whether it is indoors or outdoors, admission
information and often the water temperature and number of lanes.
The founders of Swimmers Guide, Bill Haverland and Tom Saunders,
began it as a book, now out of print after two editions. After they
gave up on the idea of making a living from the book, they took
jobs as accountants in Raleigh, N.C., but maintained the
information as a free Web site, depending on users to provide
updated information. This is the 16th update in just over two
years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-98 1710EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
