<DOCNO> NYT19980810.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6625 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-LEMURS-WRIGHT-ART     08-10 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-LEMURS-WRIGHT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 SAVING A SPECIAL ISLAND FOR LEMURS AND MAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JANE E. BRODY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Patricia Wright's trail to Madagascar and environmental heroism
began with an act that is now considered the antithesis of
conservation: the purchase in a Brooklyn pet store of an owl
monkey, and then a second one to keep it company. Within a week of
the birth of her own daughter, Amanda, the monkeys too produced a
Brooklyn baby, and the mother/housewife became increasingly
intrigued by the behavior of these nocturnal monkeys. The female
monkey's only responsibility appeared to be breast-feeding. The
male did all the parenting, carrying and caring for the baby.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Wright, who had loved the woods growing up in upstate New
York and had a college degree in biology, decided she wanted to
study these monkeys in the wild. Books in the New York Public
Library told her that the ``wild'' meant the jungles of Peru, home
to wild boar, jaguars and deadly fer-de-lance snakes. She consulted
Warren Kinzey, then an anthropologist at City University of New
York, pumping him for guidance on how to do field research.
</P>
<P>
   Kinzey told her, in effect, that unless she earned a graduate
degree and acquired a university affiliation, no one would give her
the money she would need. But she was undeterred. Through a friend
who knew a dean at the New School for Social Research, she wangled
an affiliation with the school and persuaded Nancy Mulligan, a
wealthy widow interested in wildlife who lived in Rochester, N.Y.,
near Ms. Wright's hometown of Avon, to underwrite the expedition
for herself, her husband, their 3-year-old daughter and a native
guide.
</P>
<P>
   Her library research had led her to a site that turned out to
have long since been converted from jungle to coffee plantations.
No monkey had been seen there for 25 years. The next stop was a
six-day canoe ride into the jungle, family in tow. Her guide soon
got bored looking for monkeys in the dark, so one night Pat Wright
ventured alone into the jungle. Frightened by what sounded like
wild boar and with her flashlight growing dim, she spent the night
in a spiny tree, only to be scolded by none other than two owl
monkeys whose territory she had invaded.
</P>
<P>
   They were the first of many for Pat Wright. Six months later,
she returned to Brooklyn with notebooks filled with observations of
the monkeys, the first data ever gathered on nocturnal monkeys in
the wild. Kinzey was more than a little impressed.
</P>
<P>
   At his urging, she enrolled in graduate school at the City
University in 1977. Nine years later, including time out for child
care, a divorce and another 14-month trip to the Amazon, she
received her degree.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was off to Madagascar, known for its rare species and
especially lemurs. Armed with a grant from the World Wildlife Fund,
Ms. Wright hoped to find the ``probably extinct'' greater bamboo
lemur. Madagascar, a poor island country east of Kenya, had
physically split from the African mainland about 150 million years
ago, subsequently becoming a Darwinian laboratory of isolated
evolution. The ever-shrinking Malagasy jungles harbor thousands of
species of plants and animals known nowhere else on earth.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty percent of Madagascar's wildlife is unique to the island,
including nearly all of its mammals, 90 percent of its reptiles and
amphibians, 80 percent of its plants and half of its birds. The
rosy periwinkle that is the source of the life-saving leukemia drug
vincristine is one of 8,000 plants that are native to Madagascar.
</P>
<P>
   But all of this bounty was imperiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flying over the island,'' she recalled, ``all I saw was
devastation,'' the result of decades of slash-and-burn farming.
</P>
<P>
   En route to establishing that the greater bamboo lemur, a little
primate with big, watchful eyes and charcoal-grey fur, was indeed
alive and doing better than expected in the remaining Malagasy rain
forest, Ms. Wright discovered an entirely new species of lemur with
golden red fur, the golden bamboo lemur, which thrives on the
cyanide-laced shoots of young bamboo, though how this
three-and-a-half-pound primate tolerates an amount of poison that
could kill a man is still anyone's guess.
</P>
<P>
   ``But no sooner had I found this new species than I heard
farmers sawing down 200-year-old rosewood trees, each of which
takes about nine smaller trees with it,'' Ms. Wright recalled
recently. An appeal to the Ministry of Water and Forest to protect
the forest ended with a challenge to Ms. Wright to help establish a
national park.
</P>
<P>
   She explained that the repeated inroads into the Malagasy rain
forests were nothing more than Band-Aids for the farmers living in
one of the ten poorest countries in the world. After only two years
of farming on newly cleared land, the soil would be depleted,
forcing them to cut down yet more forest. Meanwhile, the runoff of
ochre-tinted soil ruined waterways and the loss of trees threatened
the watershed. And since few Malagasy were aware of the economic
potential of ecotourism, the farmers gave little thought to the
fast-disappearing habitats of Madagascar's unique flora and fauna,
which include 32 species of lemurs (16 of the largest ones have
already become extinct).
</P>
<P>
   By the time Ms. Wright arrived there in 1985, more than 80
percent of the forests had disappeared from this Indian Ocean
island and there were only two national parks in Madagascar, the
last one established in 1930.
</P>
<P>
   It took her five years to create the new park, five years of
days-long treks to visit with surrounding farmers and explain the
purpose of the park and its potential value to their families and
future, five years of negotiations with village elders and
government officials, five years of international phone calls and
grant proposals to raise the millions of dollars needed, not just
to create the park but to give the villagers something in return
for the land they would sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, with the help of $6.27 million from the U.S. Agency
for International Development and the support of various
conservation groups, there was not only a 108,000-acre park but
eight new schools, 10 renovated schools, four health-care
facilities, a team of visiting doctors and nurses, rural libraries
with books on conservation and 133 villagers working in the park.
In addition, the villagers receive half the entrance fees to the
park, now visited by 10,000 tourists a year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat's extraordinary contribution has been her ability to see
the intimate link between the beauty and fascination of the animals
and the lives of the people,'' said Alison Jolly, a primatologist
at Princeton University who studies ring-tailed lemurs in
Madagascar. ``It's so easy to say that what matters is the animals
or what matters is the people. Pat has been able to say that what
matters is both and, through her enthusiasm, devotion, energy and
courage, to make both happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Among her many prized honors is the Knight of the National Order
of Madagascar, a national medal of honor bestowed in 1995 by the
president of a country that now knows the rewards of saving its
once-raped rain forests.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wright serves as executive director of the Institute for the
Conservation of Tropical Environments at the State University of
New York at Stony Brook and as international coordinator of
Ranomafana National Park, the rain forest in Antananarivo,
Madagascar, that was rescued by her dogged determination to save
the only known home of the newly found lemur.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wright is now in her thirteenth year of studying lemurs,
most recently the diademed sifaka, a large, black diurnal primate.
``I've finally come out of the dark,'' she noted, which makes her
work attractive to Earthwatch volunteers, amateur researchers who
pay to help support environmental research in interesting spots all
over the world.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, Ms. Wright and an expanded research team work
intensively during the six months a year that are not cyclone
season. Though Ms. Wright and co-workers still sleep in tents
without electricity, the campsite now has two buildings: a research
station and a dining hall. The onetime rice-and-beans diet has been
enhanced as well by a local cook who persuaded Ms. Wright to send
him to cooking school.
</P>
<P>
   During the off-season, Ms. Wright teaches graduate and
undergraduate courses on primate conservation and behavior and
ecology at Stony Brook. There she is joined by her second husband,
Jukka Jernvall, a Finnish paleontologist and developmental
biologist, who works at the University of Helsinki when she is in
Madagascar. He visits her there and they spend a month together
each summer in Finland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a tricontinental marriage,'' she said, obviously
pleased with the unusual arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   She is also pleased with her study subjects. The sifaka, a
spectacular leaping lemur that at 15 pounds is the biggest of the
living lemurs, is a lot easier to track than owl monkeys. One by
one, each animal is tranquilized and fitted with a color-coded
nylon necklace. Once a year, the animals are weighed and measured,
tooth impressions are taken and their reproductive condition noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``As with most other species of lemurs, the female sifaka rules
the roost,'' Ms. Wright explained. ``The female is first into the
fruit tree where she gets the best and most fruit. Her mate dares
not enter the tree until she's finished. If the male forgets and
starts up the tree, she'll slap him in the face. If he persists,
she'll lunge at him and may even nip him. He then backs away
saying, `I'm sorry, I'm sorry, I didn't mean it.'''
</P>
<P>
   The female also decides where the family group goes. Often two
or three females lead the way, with their mates trailing behind the
young. At six to nine months of age, young females start to play at
leadership, walking ahead of their mothers while the young males
stay with the mothers and eventually drift back to be with their
fathers, Ms. Wright has found.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, when it comes to courting, the females do the
choosing. The males do fight each other, she said, but often the
females don't choose the winners. According to the ``wimpy male
hypothesis'' formulated by Alison Richard, anthropologist at Yale
University, the female, by selecting a loser, may insure her
dominant status in the family.
</P>
<P>
   With the sifaka's habitat protected, Ms. Wright said the main
loss of research animals these days is the work of another endemic
species, the fossa, ``a fierce mongoose-like animal with big teeth
and a big appetite and retractible claws that enable it to climb
trees fast. The fossa is long, lean and mean and it eats lemurs.''
</P>
<P>
   Those interested in participating in future Earthwatch teams
with Ms. Wright should call 1-800-776-0188 for more information.
The next teams, each of which spends two weeks on the project,
depart on Nov. 1 and Nov. 15, 1998. See also the Earthwatch Website
at www.earthwatch.org for more information on lemur research.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
