<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFF TO THE BEACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The republic is safe for the summer _ Congress is
now on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   No more political damage can be done on Capitol Hill until
September, when our worthy legislators will return to a stack of
unfinished business.
</P>
<P>
   This hiatus is a good thing if you believe in minimalist
government but a problem if you believe there are national problems
that urgently demand national solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, members of Congress have been figuratively if not
literally out to lunch for months. They just haven't officially
admitted taking a perpetual holiday.
</P>
<P>
   There are several reasons why nothing much has been accomplished
thus far this year. High among them is a widespread boredom among
voters, who seem content these days to leave the nation's capital
to its own devices. Incumbents are looking good and feel no
pressure to demonstrate their usefulness.
</P>
<P>
   And Washington suffers from a pre-election disposition in both
parties toward confrontation rather than compromise, putting a
priority on building campaign issues instead of a legislative
record.
</P>
<P>
   All of which points to another last-minute federal budget
standoff in which nobody wins, including the public.
</P>
<P>
   The two government shutdowns in late 1995 and early 1996 over a
budget stalemate proved so politically unpopular that President
Clinton and the Republican majority are wary of taking that route
again. Yet both sides are already threatening to close the
government in October over seemingly irreconcilable differences in
major spending bills. It is down-to-the-wire bluffing that in the
name of political sanity ought to collapse in the clutch.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP in particular took a heavy hit for being inappropriately
gleeful over those past federal closings. The party cannot afford
to repeat that mistake. But if worse comes to worst, congressional
GOP leaders are trying to set up President Clinton for the fall
this time.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans inserted in seven major spending bills
right-wing ideological provisions they knew the president had vowed
to veto. They involve abortion, the environment and other issues
that he is firmly committed to.
</P>
<P>
   Their defense of this provocation is innocent surprise that he's
sticking to his guns, coupled with the sly assertion that he's
merely trying to distract us from his personal legal problems.
</P>
<P>
   It's a transparently partisan tactic and unlikely to either
force him to buckle or stick him with the blame if budgetary
disaster strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have suggested they might pass a so-called
continuing resolution to freeze the budget at this year's fiscal
levels if the president doesn't capitulate. But he's threatened to
veto that approach too. Fighting an image of declining political
power, Clinton is loathe to give up any remaining leverage to
reverse the congressional rejection of his budget initiatives for
domestic programs like education and managed health care.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, congressional strategy has been to slow government to
a leisurely crawl to allow plenty of time to put on a display of
partisan differences for voter consumption.
</P>
<P>
   After the legislators return, they plan to spend only one month
on the job before leaving town again to campaign for re-election.
That does not leave much time to reach agreement on major
controversies.
</P>
<P>
   It also doesn't leave much time to begin dealing with whatever
evidence is included in Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's report
to Congress on alleged presidential wrongdoing. And that's just the
way Congress likes it. Only partisan anti-Clinton zealots have much
stomach just before an election for a sex-scandal probe that could
easily backfire.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans figure they can deal more smoothly with leftover
topics later _ even a debate about presidential sex and lies _ if
they strengthen their grip on both houses of Congress in the
November elections. The Democrats also figure they can cut a better
deal later if they narrow their minority margin or even,
miraculously, take back control of the House of Representatives.
Wishful thinking predominates in both parties.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has yet to pass 13 contentious appropriations bills for
the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1, if it is to avoid a government
shutdown or a shootout with the president over a continuing
resolution. Campaign finance reform, anti-smoking legislation and
managed care revisions are already dead in one house or the other.
</P>
<P>
   House and Senate GOP leaders can't agree on how large to make
new tax cuts or whom they should go to. The Republicans wasted
their time passing several anti-abortion measures, some of which
are irrelevant amendments to important bills and none of which will
get past presidential vetoes. Sharp ideological differences over
the correct remedies for classroom ills have stymied comprehensive
education legislation. Competing managed care reforms are too
complex to resolve in one month.
</P>
<P>
   Congress did reform the Internal Revenue Service and hand out
gobs of money for new highway construction, developments popular
with voters and both parties. Republican members re-named
Washington National Airport after Ronald Reagan, over anguished
Democratic objections. And that's about it.
</P>
<P>
   Having exhausted their teeny political repertoire, members of
Congress accidentally timed their August retreat to their
advantage. President Clinton will now have the national political
stage all to himself, for better or worse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
