<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Aug. 11, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Monday the droughty interior Northeast received much-needed
rain as over an inch of precipitation fell in many locations. On
Tuesday beneficial rain from scattered thunderstorms will douse
much of New England as a cool front crossing the region aids in
lifting the humid air in place. Local flooding is possible in a few
locations, especially from near the Berkshires to interior Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Farther west, clouds will yield to intervals of sunshine and
less humid air from the Ohio Valley to the eastern Great Lakes.
Isolated thundershowers will develop in the afternoon, as a trough
of low pressure presses east through the region. Behind the trough,
cool and very dry air will spread into the upper Great Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   Sultry air will persist from the southern Plains to the
Southeast. As the sun heats the damp ground, rising currents of
moistening air will induce towering cumulus clouds to form, some of
which will produce strong thunderstorms. A cluster of more numerous
showers and thunderstorms will accompany a jet-stream disturbance
sliding through the lower Mississippi Valley while Texas stays
mainly sunny and hot.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated potent thunderstorms, replete with small hail and gusty
winds, will also surround a disturbance crossing the western high
Plains. Meanwhile, mostly sunny and warm conditions will cover an
expansive region from the northern Rockies to the northwest coast.
Elsewhere, moisture from the remnants of Tropical Storm Frank will
fuel scattered thunderstorms over the southern Rockies and Front
Range of Colorado and New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Frankly Hot
</P>
<P>
   As the remnants of Tropical Storm Frank moved toward southern
California on Sunday, its circulation reversed the normal summer
weather pattern in the region. Clouds covered the deserts and
bright sun graced the coast. Winds from the southeast directed
tropical moisture and showers from the Gulf of California into the
Imperial Valley, causing readings to stay in the low 90s in the
deserts. These winds then descended the San Bernardino Mountains
and brought record heat to the Los Angeles Basin. The mercury rose
to 100 degrees at the Civic Center, eclipsing a record set in 1935.
</P>
</TEXT>
