<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYLITE(SMILE)-NYT </SLUG>
  
 No. 2668 Mon., Aug. 10: 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (NYLite items can be published if desired; &LR;  please credit the
contributor. Contribute to NYLite and get a NYT rolling-writer
style pen.)
</P>
<P>
   Dr. NYlite can now be reached by e-mail:  &UR; nylite(at)nytimes.com &LR; 
(use ``at'' sign sted (at)).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS &LR; : Given the recent hubbub up in Boston, we should
reflect on the above suggestion that Nylite items can be published
if desired. Where attributable, we do so. Many items are sent in by
friends without telling me where they came from. Most, of course,
pass through, at some time or another, the ever-swinging doors of
the Internet. The jokes and anecdotes are here for all to enjoy. If
an item is not attributed you should certainly strain to refrain
from using. Or whatever.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GOOD DAY, WIRE WANDERERS!!!!! &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Offer not available in any store! (Or any other news service!)
</P>
<P>
   Looking for contributors with wit, style, depth, charm and
genius with jokes, anecdotes, humorous news items, bonus NYLite
offerings, or filler material.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. NYLite will respond with a GENUINE New York Times rolling
writer-style pen if your item is used. (But see coffee mug offer
above.)
</P>
<P>
   All items fit to fax to 212-556-3535 (24 hours), via uniformed
government courier, or, now by e-mail (nylite(at)nytimes.com).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUOTABLES FROM NBC'S 'THE TONIGHT SHOW WITH JAY LENO' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody know what D.C. stands for? Dry Cleaning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember the old days when the biggest laundry problem in this
country was ring around the collar?''
</P>
<P>
   ``This Ken Starr, he's a loser. 40 million bucks to get one
woman to talk dirty to you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Pressure seems to be building on President Clinton. People
want him to explain his relationship with Monica Lewinsky. Forget
that! I'd be happy if Clinton would just explain his relationship
with Hillary. That's the one I want to know about.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, Hillary Clinton spoke out about this whole stain
business. She blamed it on a vast right-hand conspiracy.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUOTABLES FROM NBC'S 'LATE NIGHT WITH CONAN O'BRIEN' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``According to a new poll, 66 percent of Americans think that
President Clinton had an affair with Monica Lewinsky. The other 34
percent think he just had an affair with her dress.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The FBI has just finished the first round of testing on Monica
Lewinsky's dress. So far they've concluded that the dress is 50%
rayon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A North Carolina man has been accused of putting the cremated
remains of his aunt in movie theater popcorn. Apparently, people
are outraged, saying that his aunt isn't worth $4.75.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The other day, 15 boy scouts from Minnesota had to be rescued
after they became lost in the Cascade Mountains. At first rescuers
tried to find the boys with bloodhounds and when that didn't work,
they brought in Michael Jackson.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Barry Manilow announced he's coming out with an album of Frank
Sinatra songs. The title song is 'I Did it My Way and It Sucks.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Scientists on Long Island have discovered a drug that may be
effective in treating cocaine addiction. Unfortunately, the drug
they're talking about is crack.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday, Irish swimming champion Michele Smith was banned
from international competition for tampering with her drug test by
putting alcohol in her urine sample. They asked her for a comment
and Smith said, 'Look, where I come from, everyone has alcohol in
their urine sample.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``This week, burglars broke into a Tennessee pharmacy and stole
450 Viagra pills. The suspects are reported to be armed, dangerous
and wearing extremely baggy pants.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CITY STREETS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Remember the Soup Nazi? Well, recently I came across the Shoe
Nazi. It was my first visit to his store near Lexington and 77th
Street.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, as a customer, I was a bit trying.
</P>
<P>
   I found a perfect pair of evening shoes and thought I should
take advantage of the store's sale and buy a pair of sandals.
</P>
<P>
   As the clerk was writing up the sale, I began to waver about the
nice-but-not-perfect sandals. I told the clerk to forget them.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, they were nice, and I did need them. ``OK, OK, I'll
take them.''
</P>
<P>
   Hot flash about another pair bought earlier in the year but
never worn. ``No, no, forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   The owner, listening nearby, grabbed the sales slip, ripped it
up and demanded that I leave the store with neither pair.
</P>
<P>
   Is my memory playing tricks, or did he actually say ``No shoes
for you''?
</P>
<P>
   The acute desire to walk away was trumped by my deep love and
need for the evening shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Mortified, I said, ``But I must have the first pair.'' He was
adamant.
</P>
<P>
   I begged: ``Please, please let me buy the shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No! Out!''
</P>
<P>
   Degradation: ``I beg you. They're perfect. Please don't do this
to me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then you'll take both pairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowed and broken: ``Yes, I will take both.''
</P>
<P>
   End note: The dubious sandals are working out well. I wonder how
long I'll have to lie low before I show my face there again.
</P>
<P>
   _ BARBARA S. GINSBERG
</P>
<P>
   Just one more ``Titanic'' story: Meryl Wiener's 11-year-old son
did not know the history of the ill-fated vessel, so she told him
all about it before taking him to the movie.
</P>
<P>
   After two hours, with still no hint of impending disaster, he
tapped her on the shoulder and asked, ``Are you sure this ship
sinks?''
</P>
<P>
   The dog, a young, muscular pit-bull mix with a thick chain-link
collar, had dug his paws in near the West 91st Street exit of
Central Park and refused to move.
</P>
<P>
   The owner _ black baseball cap, large sunglasses, tall, tough as
his pet _ was tugging on the leash trying to persuade him to walk
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on,'' he said. The dog did not budge. ``Get moving.'' No
response. ``It's time to go home.'' Still no motion.
</P>
<P>
   Katherine T. Becher watched as the man, exasperated, scooped the
dog up in his arms and said, in all seriousness: ``Look here, we
have to get this straight right now. I don't speak dog so you'd
better plan on learning English.''
</P>
<P>
   Scene: A crowded crosstown bus headed east during the 57th
Street morning rush.
</P>
<P>
   I signal for an exit at Seventh Avenue, and the driver pulls
alongside the bus stop _ with a cab smack dab in front of the back
exit. I try to exit, but the doors barely open, because of the cab.
</P>
<P>
   I politely ask the cabby to move his empty cab, as there is
nothing between his cab and the corner. The cab moves about 2 feet.
I still cannot exit the bus without really squeezing between the
dirty bus doors and the dirty cab. I ask the cabby to move some
more. He doesn't move.
</P>
<P>
   A large male passenger behind me is also yelling at the cabby,
angry and kicking the cab. The cabby is now angry too, but seeing a
large male he stays in his cab, still not budging.
</P>
<P>
   I say to my fellow passenger, ``Shall we go through?'' He
answers, ``Of course.''
</P>
<P>
   So I step out through the partially open bus door, open the back
door of the cab and slide through, with the fellow following. We
exit onto the sidewalk _ and leave both back doors of the cab wide
open as we go our separate ways.
</P>
<P>
   _ KAREN LUERSSEN
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Spitz's second-grade class had a ``show and tell''
during snack time. Dawn told about a visit to her grandfather, an
optometrist. Ms. Spitz asked where he practiced, to which Dawn
replied: ``He doesn't practice anymore. He knows how to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The young panhandler on Park Avenue was getting an unusual
reaction from passers-by. They would read his sign, smile or laugh
and pass on without giving him a contribution.
</P>
<P>
   As Grace Grant approached the sign, she understood their
reluctance. In his case, honesty wasn't the best policy. In big
letters he had written: ``Why lie, I need a beer!''
</P>
<P>
   Vanessa Hoffman spent more than an hour on a recent humid day
deciding what to wear. She finally pulled together a stylish
