<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6679 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEACH-BLANKET-BABYLON     08-10 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEACH-BLANKET-BABYLON-650(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SAN FRANCISCO, HIGH JINKS, BIG HAIR AND A SPIRIT THAT LASTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (js) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Try to follow this.
</P>
<P>
   Snow White is looking for love, preferably a handsome prince.
She meets up with Glinda the Good Witch and then embarks on a trip
around the world, during which she encounters President Clinton,
Hillary Rodham Clinton, Chelsea Clinton, Newt Gingrich, Paula
Jones, John Travolta, Mr. Peanut, Mayor Willie Brown Jr. of San
Francisco, the Spice Girls, a king of France, Whoopi Goldberg,
Richard Simmons, Carmen Miranda, Chiquita Banana, Ellen DeGeneres,
Janet Reno, the Village People, Barbra Streisand, Tina Turner,
James Brown, Monica Lewinsky, Linda Tripp, Kenneth Starr and Martha
Stewart (among others), after which she morphs into Madonna and
marries Elvis.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the people she meets have very big hair.
</P>
<P>
   Ladies and gentlemen, welcome to ``Beach Blanket Babylon.'' If
``Seinfeld'' was about nothing, this is about everything, a wild
musical homage to popular culture that has become no less a part of
San Francisco than the Golden Gate Bridge, the Coit Tower and fog.
It has played eight times a week 51 weeks a year for the last 24
years, and every show is a sellout in the 400-seat Club Fugazi.
</P>
<P>
   Are we talking quirky, or what? The producers are now planning
next year's 25th-anniversary celebration in which Sen. Dianne
Feinstein, a native of San Francisco, has agreed to play Snow White
for at least one performance. That means she will have to sing,
dance and wear about 16 pounds of makeup. Good thing she does not
face re-election until 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's said she'll sing and dance,'' said Jo Shulman Silver,
the show's producer, leaving aside the issue of makeup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beach Blanket Babylon'' was the brainchild of Mrs. Silver's
husband, Steve Silver, a one-time street performer whose sense of
comic absurdity gave rise to lavish costumes, altered lyrics and
clever segues that deny the audience any pause from the moment Snow
White first appears onstage with a suitcase that says on the side
``A Prince or Bust, www.snow.com.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver died in 1995 at the age of 51, but his presence permeates
the production through the company's Zen-like reverence for him,
which has never faded. Mrs. Silver, who married him several months
before his death, talks of him in the present tense as if nothing
has changed, and in a sense it hasn't.
</P>
<P>
   The show has proceeded essentially as Silver first staged it, a
set piece with 10 cast members in multiple roles and Snow White's
search as the unifying theme. Over the years, characters and songs
have come and gone to highlight contemporary issues. But whomever
Snow White meets along the way, the look and sound of every
character reflects Silver's fractured view of life and a comic
sensitivity that amuses but never offends.
</P>
<P>
   That perspective remains a guiding force for Mrs. Silver and
Kenny Mazlow, the director, who plays a number of characters,
including King Louis, of no specific Roman numeral, in a towering
pink wig and Peanut with a walking stick.
</P>
<P>
   Ever open to new ideas, they acknowledge nonetheless that they
always consider how Silver would have visualized a change. Mrs.
Silver, in fact, is convinced her husband can still hear her mental
gymnastics. ``I always think, `How would Steve do this?' '' she
said, sheepishly admitting that once last year she actually asked
him: ``Steve, what should I do? Give me a sign.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, at least, she and Mazlow continue to push the right
buttons. When the show made one of its rare trips outside San
Francisco, visiting London for several weeks last year, they
recognized the need to tailor certain scenes to a British sense of
humor.
</P>
<P>
   As one example, they turned the character of Richard Simmons, a
well-known American exerciser, into someone a British audience
would more easily recognize, a television muscle man known as
Motivator.
</P>
<P>
   ``The audience loved it,'' Mrs. Silver said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Some of the standard characters in ``Beach Blanket Babylon,''
like John Travolta and the Dancing Poodles, have endured over the
years. And much of the humor is timeless shtick, like the four
dancing Hasidic Jews, whose rendition of ``Hava Nagila'' comes out
``Have a Tequila.'' The show's version of the Village People turns
``Macho Man'' into ``Matzoh Man,'' and when the Spice Girls sing
``Tell me what you want, what you really, really want,'' they
include Old Spice, a dancing cologne bottle.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the show's bite evolves from its topical humor,
these days _ what else? _ the White House scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The Monica Lewinsky character, who is usually played by Erica
Wyman in a giant beret, walks out with Tracy Chiappone as Linda
Tripp, carrying a huge tape recorder, and sings ``Wedding Bell
Blues,'' a Fifth Dimension song that begins, ``Bill, I love you
so.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week a Kenneth Starr character was added for the first
time. A backdrop opened to reveal Mazlow wearing a five-pointed
star helmet and singing a version of '`New York, New York'' that
began, ``Starr's spreading the news. Subpoenas today. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the show avoids any mention of the real Ms. Lewinsky's
blue dress, which is being examined by investigators for genetic
evidence of a sexual encounter with Clinton _ standard fare for
late-night television comedians. Mrs. Silver said she and Mazlow
considered adding the song ``Devil With the Blue Dress On'' but
then decided against it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve would not have wanted that in the show,'' she said. ``He
always had the highest of standards. That would not be appropriate
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   What all the characters look like also plays a major role in the
show's popularity, almost to distraction. Val Diamond, who as a
20-year veteran is the longest-serving cast member, greets Snow
White everywhere along the way and always in a different silly
outfit and hairdo.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Diamond's stunning voice is a centerpiece of the production.
She actually belts out one song, unadulterated to its conclusion,
``Anyone Who Had a Heart.'' She is dressed as a sequined French
apache dancer with a lamppost poking out of her head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beach Blanket Babylon'' was first performed in 1974 in the
back room of a North Beach bar as a spoof of old beach-blanket
movies that starred people like Frankie Avalon and Annette
Funicello. A year later it moved several blocks away to Club
Fugazi, where it has been evolving ever since.
</P>
<P>
   By some estimates, the show has been seen by more than three
million people over the years, including some who return dozens of
times. Cyril Magnin, the city's former chief of protocol, who died
in 1988, holds the unofficial record. He claimed to have attended
more than 500 times, occasionally as a member of the cast.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Mrs. Silver said, much of her time is occupied by plans
to stage 25 25th-anniversary benefit performances next June, each
for a different charity her husband supported. But tugging at her
is an idea that she said her husband might not have supported.
</P>
<P>
   More and more, she said, celebrities who see the show, as well
as close friends, ask why she has not taken ``Beach Blanket
Babylon'' on tour. Despite a few touches that link the story to San
Francisco, like the giant skyline hat Ms. Diamond wears in the
finale, the production could be tailored to anywhere, as it was for
London when Ms. Diamond's hat had a London skyline.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Silver is not yet convinced it is the right thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' she said, looking perplexed. ``We've had
offers to go to New York, Los Angeles, South Africa, Australia,
Germany, France, Chicago, everywhere. But Steve never wanted to go
anywhere. What if we got a bad review? We've never gotten a bad
review. Never. I wouldn't do anything that hurts the show. I have
to do what's right for the show. What happens here is always my
priority. That's what Steve would have wanted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
