<SLUG> BC-TV-MONTY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`REAL FULL MONTY': TACKY? IT BEATS PIPE FITTING, MATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(nk) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you enjoyed the movie, you might get a kick out of what
purports to be ``The Real Full Monty.'' Well, not 100 percent real,
since Tuesday night's ``Inside Story'' report on A&AMP;E doesn't come
through with full frontal nudity. But if you're willing to settle
for active buttocks, the display may serve.
</P>
<P>
   The BBC camera accompanies Centaur, an all-male troupe of four
or five strapping strippers on a tour of ladies' nights at
workingmen's clubs in the English Midlands. We meet Richard, the
group's impresario, and Jeff, Barry, Doc and Dale, and catch
glimpses of their act, which Richard concedes is flat-out ``seedy
and tacky.'' The prancing, grinding and other exertions will win no
awards for stagecraft, but maybe that's not the point.
</P>
<P>
   The Centaur audience is divided over whether the show is just
nasty, especially when volunteers serve as onstage props for
fondling, nuzzling and this and that, or good unclean fun. But the
shrieks suggest that the fastidious are in the minority. Richard
reports that when the lads stopped taking off their G-strings,
interest flagged.
</P>
<P>
   The main consideration for these sturdily built lads is that
this line of work is more profitable than other employment
opportunities. As one says, it's a lot more enjoyable than pipe
fitting. Moreover, Barry notes there are perks in the form of
audience interaction. Not only are the men the beneficiaries of
kisses and cuddles during the show, but Barry confesses to being
available for private showings.
</P>
<P>
   The performers' wives, insofar as I could understand the
north-country accents, seem wishful about what their men are up to
away from home and aren't about to inquire too closely. ``Hopefully
he doesn't do anything,'' one says. But resistance may be
difficult. One performer reports that while dancing with audience
members, ``all of a sudden, you find two hands in your pants.''
</P>
<P>
   Are the shows humiliating for women? Are they humiliating for
men? Who is exploiting whom? This entertaining hour does not go in
for heavy moralizing, but it would not be the first time that the
pleasures and rewards of the marketplace were deemed to be worth a
touch of humiliation for everybody involved.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `INSIDE STORY: THE REAL FULL MONTY'
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. ET Tuesday on A&AMP;E
</P>
<P>
   A co-production of A&AMP;E and the BBC. Olivia Lichtenstein, BBC
series editor; Michael Cascio, A&AMP;E executive producer; Gayle
Gilman, A&AMP;E supervising producer. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
