<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6690 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAIN-BOOK-REVIEW-845&AMP;     08-10 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAIN-BOOK-REVIEW-845&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GAIN': COMPANY TOWN'S PROSPERITY AND PAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes at end of review.) 
(lb) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``Gain,'' his ambitious but flawed new book, Richard Powers
takes on the same large themes that animated his highly acclaimed
debut novel, ``Three Farmers on Their Way to a Dance'' (1985): the
impact of history on individual lives and the collision of huge,
public enterprises with private fears and dreams.
</P>
<P>
   In this case the public enterprise is a sprawling American
conglomerate named Clare Inc., which manufactures everything from
soap to cosmetics to fertilizers; the individual is one Laura
Bodey, a small-town real-estate broker and divorced mother of two.
</P>
<P>
   The most accessible and straightforward of Powers' novels thus
far, ``Gain'' lacks the cerebral razzle-dazzle and eccentric
free-associative riffs that have distinguished his earlier work.
</P>
<P>
   Its narrative does not spin off dozens of complex ideas about
time and art and technology, but instead pivots around one simple
idea: namely, that there are limits to the growth and profit that
American business is obsessed with, that there are unreckoned
consequences to our messianic faith in progress.
</P>
<P>
   As he has done so frequently in the past, Powers tells his story
by cross-cutting cinematically between two separate narratives.
</P>
<P>
   The first chronicles the birth and spectacular growth of the
Clare company, which began as a small, family-run business and
eventually grew into a gigantic corporation that sells its products
in 83 countries to half a billion consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The second chronicles Laura Bodey's harrowing battle with
ovarian cancer _ cancer that has apparently been caused by exposure
to chemical wastes produced by Clare's giant factories.
</P>
<P>
   Laura's story, by far the more compelling of Powers' two
narratives, shows off his eye for the absurdities of modern
American life and his uncanny ear for the disjunctions of
contemporary speech.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed his portrait of the world Laura and her children inhabit
is indebted, in many ways, to the portrait Don DeLillo created in
``White Noise'' of another small Midwestern town trying to come to
terms with the fallout of an industrial accident.
</P>
<P>
   Once again we are given a glimpse of a community reeling from
information overload and consumer lust; once again we see this
world through the prism of a wryly ironic sensibility.
</P>
<P>
   The fictional town where Laura lives _ Lacewood, Ill. _ has come
of age in the shadow of Clare Inc. Three out of five workers in the
county are employed by Clare, and the town attributes its
prosperity to the corporation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Clare, the town would have dozed forever,'' Powers
writes. ``It would have stayed a backwoods wasteland until the age
of retrotourism.'' As it is, the town is booming: Even the local
farmers wear ``clip-on cellular modems so they can receive
commodities reports while out hoeing the north 40.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Laura does not work for Clare, she realizes that the
company has insidiously permeated her daily life: Its products
``paper her cabinets. They perch on her microwave, camp out on her
stove, hang from her shower head. Clare hiding under the sink,
swarming her medicine chest, lining the shelves in the basement,
parked out in the garage, piled up in the shed.''
</P>
<P>
   As Laura discovers that she is suffering from cancer and begins
several long, painful bouts of chemotherapy and radiation, Powers
exchanges his sardonic humor for a more empathetic voice, a voice
capable of rendering her ordeal with unsentimental compassion.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the passages in ``Gain'' devoted to Laura's battle with
cancer emerge as the most emotionally affecting work Powers has
done to date. He not only makes us understand her determination to
live and her simultaneous urge to submit to the pain, but he also
conveys the subtle, surprising ways in which the illness alters her
relationships with her children and ex-husband.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the reader, Laura's story is broken up by
long, tedious sections detailing the history of Clare Inc.
</P>
<P>
   We learn how the company was founded by a merchant family named
Clare that stumbled across a gifted candle maker and turned his
craft into a thriving cottage industry. We watch as this
mom-and-pop operation slowly grows into a profitable business, and
how this business in turn becomes a national corporation and later
an international consortium.
</P>
<P>
   We see the company pass out of the hands of the Clare family and
diversify from candles and soaps into detergents, pesticides,
makeup and bathroom cleansers _ basically whatever consumers want.
</P>
<P>
   Although the early chapters of the company's history are
enlivened by colorful portraits of members of the Clare family _
Samuel Clare, who sees the company as a divinely blessed
enterprise; Ben Clare, who dreams of doing pure scientific research
_ things slow down considerably as the business is taken over by
pallid, money-grubbing managers and bureaucrats.
</P>
<P>
   The reader becomes numbed by Powers' repetitious recitations of
the company's ups and downs and of how the firm was affected by
historical events like the Civil War, Emancipation and the two
World Wars.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The lessons Clare Inc. would like its customers to take from its
history are familiar ones: Nothing succeeds like success; what's
good for Clare is good for America; cleanliness is next to
godliness.
</P>
<P>
   What makes ``Gain'' so disappointing in the end is that the
lessons Powers wants his readers to draw from his novel are
similarly predictable: that greed isn't good, that marketing has
become an American way of life, that there are incalculable costs
to progress.
</P>
<P>
   For an intelligent and cerebral writer like Powers, these are
fairly obvious points. Certainly they are not points that need to
be made over and over and over again, throughout a 350-page novel _
a novel that, for all its affecting moments, is ultimately dragged
down by its simplistic message.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `GAIN'
</P>
<P>
   By Richard Powers
</P>
<P>
   355 pages. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. $25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
