<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: BACK TO YASGUR'S FARM; NEW THEATER PARTNERSHIP;
SIGNING OFF;   MORE FOR SEINFELD FANATICS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Canada, Ireland)  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pete Townshend will be there, as will Richie Havens, Stevie
Nicks and the band Ten Years After. And the site, as usual, is Max
Yasgur's farm in Bethel, N.Y. But beyond that, very little of this
year's version of Woodstock will resemble the original. Called ``A
Day in the Garden,'' the concert is scheduled to run from Friday
through Sunday and is heavy on performers who weren't even born
when some 300,000 revelers first descended on the site in 1969,
like the Goo Goo Dolls and Third Eye Blind.
</P>
<P>
   The event is also heavy on rules: no camping, no bikes and no
outside food or beverages, although cellular phones will be
allowed. Organized by Alan Gerry, a cable television executive, the
concert may have one authentic 1960s element: dissent. A local
group, the Woodstock Nation Foundation, is threatening to protest
over organizers' plans to bar unticketed crowds from the site.
</P>
<P>
   Stratford Heads South
</P>
<P>
   The Stratford Festival, the esteemed Ontario-based classical
theater company, will bring two productions to New York in November
as part of a new partnership with City Center, Judith Daykin, the
center's president and executive director, has announced. The
partnership's two-week inaugural run will kick off on Nov. 12 with
``Much Ado About Nothing,'' with Brian Bedford, Martha Henry and
William Hutt, and continue with a production of Moliere's ``Miser''
in repertory.
</P>
<P>
   Both shows will be directed by Richard Monette, the artistic
director of the 44-year-old company. City Center's 1998-99 season
will also include engagements by the San Francisco Ballet, American
Ballet Theater and the Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Going Off the Air
</P>
<P>
   Gay Byrne, a fixture in Irish radio and television for nearly
four decades, has announced plans to retire. Byrne, 64, known as
Uncle Gaybo by his fans, has both a top-rated radio show and a
weekly television program, the ``Late Late Show,'' which he has
presided over for 36 years.
</P>
<P>
   He told Agence France-Presse that he planned to step down from
the radio program at Christmas and end his television show next
June. ``I want to try and see what might happen doing absolutely
nothing for a short period of time,'' he said. ``Then see what
might attract me after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Pass the Ketchup
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't yet had a complete ``Seinfeld'' overdose, a new
show at the Museum of the Moving Image in Astoria, Queens, may be
just the thing. Starting on Saturday, the museum will display the
``Monk's Cafe'' stage set where the sitcom's four lovably
dysfunctional characters held court. The show will also include
Jerry Seinfeld's infamous ``puffy shirt,'' original scripts and
props like ketchup bottles. Yada, yada ...
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
