<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER SALUTE TO THE MILITARY  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ever since Yves Saint Laurent turned the sailor's pea
jacket into fashion in 1962, military surplus clothes have become
sources of inspiration for many a designer. This year, multipocket
cargo pants turned up in men's and women's fashion collections on
both sides of the Atlantic and will certainly be filling store
racks in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, shoppers' choices range from men's khakis in
Army-Navy stores for less than $30 to women's suede versions by
Ralph Lauren for a whopping $2,295.
</P>
<P>
   The Gap has miniskirts with cargo pockets for $34, and
Bloomingdale's has ankle-length cargo skirts by Urban Outfitters
for $46.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomingdale's also has cargo pants by Theory in black chino
($165) and by Shelli Segal for Laundry in black stretch twill ($138
and $148).
</P>
<P>
   Neiman Marcus has cargo pants by Narciso Rodriguez in cotton
drill cloth ($565), by Ralph Lauren in cavalry twill ($695) and by
Theory in charcoal flannel ($190).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
