<SLUG> BC-WEB-MARKETING-1199-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELLING A TO Z ON THE WEB VIA `AFFILIATE NETWORKS' 
</HEADLINE>
  (ll) 
 By EVAN I. SCHWARTZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They are akin to franchising without the franchises. Or, in
worst cases, a pyramid scheme without the pyramid. But ``affiliate
networks'' is what the electronic commerce industry calls them, and
they are a World Wide Web company's way to get other people to do
its marketing.
</P>
<P>
   The most notable example of an affiliate network is probably the
Amazon.com Associates Program, which recently signed up its
100,000th affiliated Web site. Each affiliate earns commissions of
up to 15 percent on sales of books and audio CD's _ just for
enticing online shoppers to click over to Amazon.com's online
superstore and buy something.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Amazon.com's affiliate network, despite being the first and
largest, is by no means unique. Hundreds have been cropping up all
over the Web, in almost every conceivable product category, from
artwork to Zambonis. And even as some analysts wonder whether the
proliferation of links will dilute the potency of the idea, many
Web entrepreneurs see it as the perfect way to capitalize on the
medium's networking and linking capabilities _ to turn the
time-honored business tradition of word-of-mouth referrals into a
new, word-of-mouse era.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see it as the future,'' said Phillip Rose, managing
director of the Lobster Net, a Web venture based in Beverly, Mass.,
that offers quick delivery of live Maine lobsters packed in
Styrofoam, wet newspapers and seaweed to customers around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Rose has recruited hundreds of Web sites into his
revenue-sharing program. In return for including an ad banner on
its site that links to thelobsternet.com, an affiliate earns a 5
percent commission for each referred customer who orders a lobster.
</P>
<P>
   Though such click-through sales now account for perhaps 4 of his
40 or so daily shipments, Rose expects his affiliated sites to
eventually drive the majority of sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``To survive on the Internet, we have to make our affiliates as
productive as possible,'' he said. ``It's a numbers game, and 1,000
is better than 1.''
</P>
<P>
   A main goal for affiliate programs is to lure first-time
cybershoppers: consumers who might not otherwise seek or find their
way to a retail site. For the retailers, there are no initial costs
to setting up an affiliate network, except for any phone calls and
employee hours to recruit a base of partners. For the thousands of
affiliates, whether commercial sites or amateur, there seems to be
nothing to lose. Since there are no joining fees, the only cost is
maintaining banner ads and product information on their own sites.
</P>
<P>
   But is this a good idea growing out of control? Every day, an
average of 10 affiliate programs apply for a listing on
Refer-It.com, an online directory of about 400 such programs, which
makes its money from the affiliate networks and software providers
that sponsor the site.
</P>
<P>
   James Marciano, chief executive of the service, based in New
York, says he typically lists half of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We turn down a lot of stuff that's really schlocky,'' Mr.
Marciano said. ``We look for companies that are established and
selling their own products.''
</P>
<P>
   The kinds of applicants he tends to reject are ones with the
potential to turn into pyramid schemes. The National Consumers
League defines a pyramid as a marketing operation in which any
profits are from recruiting others, not from actual sales of goods
or services _ schemes that often wind up being prosecuted for
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   But even the activity generated by legitimate affiliate networks
has led to a free-for-all atmosphere, in which greater numbers of
Web sites that sell something are recruiting even greater numbers
of affiliates, which range from lone college students to well-known
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   In more traditional businesses, a manufacturing company or a
retail chain sells lucrative franchises that cover exclusive rights
to a specific sales territory. On the Web, such geographic
exclusivity is not possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you tried to locate a new Saturn dealer a half-mile away
from an existing one, they'd both freak,'' Marciano said. ``But on
the Web, you can't stake out territories.''
</P>
<P>
   So, rather than allowing a select few to act as their authorized
agents, the operators of affiliate networks seem to be operating
under a philosophy of ``he with the largest horde wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Online music retailers, for instance, are scrambling to amass as
many affiliates as possible. CD Now, based in Jenkintown, Pa.,
already has more than 11,000 partners in its Cosmic Credit Program.
The Music Boulevard site of N2K, based in New York, has 7,000
members in its affiliate program. And CD referral sites are a
primary reason that Amazon.com has seen membership in its
two-year-old affiliate program triple since the company began
selling CD's last spring.
</P>
<P>
   All told, affiliate programs will directly account for 11
percent of the $5.8 billion of consumer transactions over the Web
this year, says Nicole Vanderbilt, an analyst with Jupiter
Communications, based in New York. Ms. Vanderbilt projects that the
figure will grow to 24 percent of $37.5 billion in total sales by
2002.
</P>
<P>
   These numbers do not include business-to-business transactions
on the Web, but they do include special revenue-sharing deals
between so-called portals like AOL.com and Web-commerce sites like
Music Boulevard. As with the affiliate relationships, those deals
usually work on a commission-only basis, although they often
involve higher commission rates.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, that higher commission is based on the realization
that these more formal referral relationships result in a higher,
steadier volume of paying customers. After all, even Amazon.com,
the most prolific recruiter of ad hoc affiliates, still counts on
big-fish partners like Yahoo for a large proportion of referred
sales.
</P>
<P>
   There are drawbacks to relying too heavily on affiliate
networks. A growing number of the affiliates themselves, for
example, are finding that if they click through their own sites to
shop at, say, Amazon.com, they can earn a commission on their own
purchases. So in addition to the discount off hardcover prices
(perhaps 40 percent) that Amazon.com gives any customer,an
affiliate could get 15 percent in commission.
</P>
<P>
   The tactic subverts the program's original intent: to land new
customers. Shawn Haynes, who runs the Amazon.com Associates
Program,says that such abuses violate the associates' agreement and
that he has removed some members caught in them. But Haynes
acknowledges that Amazon.com cannot police every purchase.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, as the business world continues to discover ways to put
the Web's considerable networking and data-sifting powers to use,
affiliate networks have emerged as a powerful new tool that seems
likely to endure in one form or another.
</P>
<P>
   At Amazon.com, which lists about three million book titles,
Haynes said the company could rely on an almost endless variety of
niche affiliates to highlight much smaller portions of its list for
specific target audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``This extends our editorial expertise into unique areas and
spheres of influence,'' he said, ``from personal finance to poetry
to fly-fishing to kayaking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-98 1744EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
