<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICAL-HISTORY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHYSICIAN THROWS A DIFFERENT LIGHT ON CHAPTERS OF ENGLISH HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. CRONKLETON  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is undisputed that the British monarchy saw its power decline
in the 17th century. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Historians generally have attributed this loss to a natural
evolution, partly economic, partly religious. People and Parliament
just gained more and more power as the country developed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Frederick Holmes, a physician turned historian, has a different
idea. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``My theory was that Parliament got power and the monarchs lost
power because of disease and death,'' said Holmes, a professor of
medicine at the University of Kansas Medical Center in Kansas City,
Kan. ``The Stuarts (the family who reigned at the time) had a lot
of illness and a lot of limiting physical problems.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Holmes' research has been received well enough that professors
at the University of Kansas are encouraging him to turn it into a
book. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He brought an insight that professional historians just can't
bring, because they just don't have the medical knowledge,'' said
Rose L. Greaves, professor of Middle East history at KU. ``By
looking into the medical history, he was able to bring new ideas on
how illnesses impacted the course of the dynasty.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for someone who spent 40 years as a doctor of internal
medicine before turning to history five years ago at age 60. He
graduated with his master's degree in May. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   History has always interested Holmes. He said growing up during
World War II fed that interest. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a very mind-expanding time, because the entire world
was suddenly in the newspaper every day,'' he said. ``I had
numerous cousins and uncles who were in the military scattered all
over the world. I think I acquired an appreciation of the world.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1960s he and his wife, Grace Holmes, a pediatrician
also at KU Medical Center, became medical missionaries and traveled
to what was then Malaya and British East Africa, both of which had
just left the British Empire. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I became really interested in the history of England as a
world power and the people who made it work,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Holmes has spent his career studying cancer, but he decided he
needed a new intellectual challenge. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I chose (history) really because it wasn't related,'' he said.
``I wanted to see if I could do it.It was very difficult, and it
really stretched my mind.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At KU, Holmes studied under John Kenyon, who until his death in
1996 was one of the world's leading authorities on the Stuarts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I started looking at the medical problems of the Stuarts, and
I knew I found my niche,'' Holmes said.
</P>
<P>
   There were remarkably many Stuart rulers in a span of 111 years:
James I reigned from 1603 to 1625; Charles I from 1625 until his
beheading in 1649; Charles II from 1660 to 1685; James II from 1685
to 1688; William III and Mary II beginning in 1689; and Anne from
1702 to 1714.
</P>
<P>
   There were so many Stuart rulers in a relatively short period
because of illnesses and death, and because in that era Parliament
was able to wrest away power from the monarchy.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes points to France, Spain and Austria, which did not see a
similar decrease in the power of their monarchies at that time. Nor
did they have much in the way of parliaments. Their rulers, he
said, generally were healthier and lived longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their monarchies were more stable,'' he said. ``They didn't
have trouble finding heirs, and they did not have the health
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The health of the Stuarts is not the sole reason the monarchy
lost power. Economics, religion and other issues certainly played a
hand. Their health, however, did have a major effect on the
stability of the monarchy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one important factor that no one else has brought
forward,'' Holmes said.
</P>
<P>
   Scouring medical records and other writings from the period,
Holmes has concluded:
</P>
<P>
   James I, who was unable to walk until he was 4 or 5 years old,
probably had a mild form of muscular dystrophy. He also had kidney
stones, arthritis and in later years dementia.
</P>
<P>
   The death of James' oldest son, Henry, at 18 left a major
vacancy. His death was a blow to the Stuarts because he was being
groomed to become king and it was believed he would have made a
great king.
</P>
<P>
   Charles I, who also had similar problems walking, had a mild
form of muscular dystrophy, too, and stuttered.
</P>
<P>
   Charles II, an amateur chemist with a unventilated palace
laboratory, died of acute mercury poisoning. Previously he was
thought to have died of apoplexy.
</P>
<P>
   James II had a bloody nose that occurred off and on for three
days before he lost the throne in 1688. It was commonly thought
that this prevented him from organizing his army to defend the
throne. Holmes, however, says this was a minor problem. The main
reason he was unable to defend the throne was the defection of key
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Mary, daughter of James II, was unable to produce an heir and
died of smallpox. She had two pregnancies but no live births.
</P>
<P>
   Anne, whose story Holmes said is the most tragic of all the
Stuarts, died of complications from a form of lupus, not gout as
had been thought. A convincing clue was that she was still
menstruating until her death at age 49. It is a medical fact,
Holmes said, that a woman cannot have gout until after menopause.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the library over in Lawrence, I found quite by chance a
copy of the diary of Anne's gynecologist,'' Holmes said. ``He
stated unequivocally that she had menstrual periods right up to the
end of her life.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, of her 17 pregnancies, only three babies were born alive.
Those three died within 10 years of their births.
</P>
<P>
   Had half of her children survived, Holmes said, there is a
chance her descendants still would be ruling today.
</P>
<P>
   It is Holmes' use of such primary sources _ what historians call
records by those who witnessed the event firsthand _ that is
winning him praise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tracking down the evidence to support his thesis is the
impressive part,'' said John F. Sweets, a professor of history and
director of graduate studies at KU.
</P>
<P>
   ``The extent of the research he had done, the digging up of
clues, is what is truly impressive,'' Sweets said.
</P>
<P>
   Finding the material was not always easy, Holmes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physicians have always been reluctant to write for posterity
things about their patients,'' Holmes said. ``There is something to
the idea that a person's medical records should be kept
confidential.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, he said, not every physician believed that. Also,
autopsy reports can be found, he said. Those records were preserved
to quash rumors that monarchs had been poisoned.
</P>
<P>
   By delving into these records, Holmes said, he was able to use
modern medical knowledge to decipher what doctors then could not.
Often some of the maladies, including muscular dystrophy and lupus,
were not then identified or diagnosed.
</P>
<P>
   While Holmes would like to publish a book based on his thesis,
he said he first must reorganize his thoughts into something a
publisher might consider.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a sense, who cares what James I died of?'' he said. ``You
can't change it. I can't go back and make him better so that he can
live longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he sees studying the actual causes of death of historical
figures as worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can have a better understanding of history, we can have
a better understanding of why we are where we are now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
