<SLUG> BC-WASHINGTON-DOGDAYS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE AUGUST RECESS, TALK OF SCANDAL KEEPS WASHINGTON BUZZING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In August, Washington usually undergoes a
transformation.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling class on Capitol Hill flees the city and fans out
across the land to take the political pulse. The president and
others in the administration escape, too. With both gone, the
engines of government slow, and Washington settles into a monthlong
political torpor.
</P>
<P>
   But not this year.
</P>
<P>
   Washington this August is anything but the sleepy town it
traditionally becomes when the powerful take a powder. Sex and
scandal don't take a vacation.
</P>
<P>
   The frenzy over the president's alleged affair and cover-up has
intensified, and political Washington remains on high alert, August
recess or not. The prosecutors and the pundits are still here, and
there's no rest for the scandal-weary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington is like Salem,'' said veteran Republican lobbyist
Tom Korologos. ``If we're not lynching somebody 24 hours a day,
we're not happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking about the Palm, one of Washington's power restaurants,
Charles Conconi, an editor at Washingtonian Magazine and a longtime
capital observer, said: ``It was just hopping. We were all talking
about `the dress.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Not the dress former White House intern Monica Lewinsky wore to
her grand jury appearance, of course, but the one that she spirited
away to her mother's New York apartment and that has now emerged as
the most talked-about piece of evidence since the bloody glove in
the O.J. Simpson trial.
</P>
<P>
   And for some, that's reason enough to be glad to be out of town.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, an Arizona Republican, expressed his disbelief
about the current political events when he recently spoke with Tom
Ridge, governor of Pennsylvania and McCain's former congressional
colleague.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `When you and I came into the House, if you had said
we're going to be dealing with this kind of stuff, you'd have both
of us saying we were crazy.' The whole thing is bizarre,'' McCain
said.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving town, however, leaves a political vacuum. With
politicians spread across the country, it's difficult to coordinate
a message when developments happen on the scandal front _ and this
could be particularly harmful to Republicans, who have had a hard
time sticking with a coherent message.
</P>
<P>
   Korologos said he was only half-joking when, on the eve of
Congress' recess, he told a group of Republican senators: ``For
heaven's sake. Leave somebody behind. Don't ever leave this town
alone. We'll get killed from the media juggernaut in the White
House. They are the best I've ever seen in 37 years in this town.''
</P>
<P>
   What members of Congress find back home could be instructive to
what they do with independent counsel Kenneth Starr's report on
four years of investigations when it lands in their lap as early as
next month.
</P>
<P>
   Polls, however, show the country is nowhere near as spellbound
by all this as Washington is. The public may be more inclined to
share the view of Anne M. Burford, a former Reagan administration
official enmeshed in a scandal back then, who once described the
capital as ``too small to be a state, but too large to be an asylum
for the mentally deranged.''
</P>
<P>
   The past week did have an air of unreality. There was Lewinsky,
heading into the grand jury to possibly say the very words that
could topple the president. There was the president, the Marine
Band playing ``Stars and Stripes Forever,'' going about his
business, just like a normal day in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like you have water-cooler discussions in the White
House about this,'' one presidential aide said about the scandal.
``The president himself is focused, and we're just following his
example.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress used to meet only about half the year, up until the
1930s. In a crisis the president might call the members back and
they'd take up the rugs, open the windows and try to be comfortable
amid the sweltering heat. It wasn't until the 1970s that Congress
passed a law to make the August recess official.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Senate Watergate committee, which held hearings
throughout the summer of 1973, took August off. Still, President
Nixon resigned the following August.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, said Donald Ritchie, a Senate historian,
``probably the only major event that took place in Washington in
August was when British troops invaded in August 1814 and burned
the Capitol and the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   And Congress was out of town then, too, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
