<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6745 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN11-COX     08-10 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Note to political hopefuls: Get off our backs
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ The horror stories are in. Our country is
awash in lousy teachers locked into lucrative positions by tenure.
</P>
<P>
   A typing teacher in Florida goes bonkers with her kids and joins
in when the class begins throwing books and dismantling
typewriters. It took a year to fire her. In the meantime, she wrote
a rambling defense of her actions and changed her surname to God.
</P>
<P>
   Okay, so Ms. God's behavior was a little odd and nobody was
learning to type. Bad teachers happen, but so do bad firemen, bad
investment brokers, and bad paper hangers. Even bad pilots happen
but they have a way of weeding themselves out.
</P>
<P>
   Good teachers don't like bad teachers because their iniquities
smudge all of our reputations, and even though most of us have
never engaged in a book flinging session (not that we haven't
considered it once or twice) or helped our students cheat on state
exams (as did a teacher in Connecticut), we suffer by comparison.
Bad teachers short change
</P>
<P>
   everyone: kids, parents, entire communities.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers try not to judge each other's methods because we know
they're as varied as the personalities involved. And they should
be. My classroom approach wouldn't work for the math teacher and
his would be useless in a creative writing setting.
</P>
<P>
   A teacher's most valuable classroom asset is honesty because
kids can sniff out a faker a mile away. ``Whatever you do,'' I
remember one of my methods teachers at the university warning us,
``don't let your students see you angry.'' My younger classmates
bought into that but not I.
</P>
<P>
   I had lived 30-some years longer than anybody in there,
including the professor, and had raised a son. I knew better. Anger
happens. Ticked-off happens. And when it does, I generously share
it with my studets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow!'' I overheard an eighth-grader warning another between
classes. ``Ms. Schuett lost it all over Freddy last period. Man,
don't even think of coming to class without your rewrite.'' Mission
accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   Not that I hadn't tried the psychological bull with Freddy,
appealing to his higher aspirations only to discover he had none.
His sole academic aim is to graduate before he outgrows his desk.
Once I reminded him of how good he'd feel if his homework were
finished BEFORE he sat down to watch TV. He said he wouldn't feel
good at all if he wasted all of that time on school work. Said he'd
miss the Montel show. I assured him that would indeed be a tragic
loss and immediately launched into a non-traditional disciplinary
approach. I yelled at Freddy. He caught on and delivered the
rewrite and it didn't bother me one little bit that his only
motivation to write was to shut me up.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers don't ask for a whole lot - a little respect, some new
textbooks from time to time, and once in a while, a raise would be
nice. Most of us aren't militant and know little of the function of
much maligned teacher's unions. Many of us belong for the legal
protection they provide, like in case twenty years down the line
Freddy's mom decides to sue me because Freddy lost out on his bid
for the Pulitzer.
</P>
<P>
   But you know what we'd like most of all? We'd like for ambitious
politicians to stop using teachers and education as political
footballs.
</P>
<P>
   It's no game folks!
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
