<P>
   BELLSOUTH-STRIKE _ Following developments in the wake of the
last-minute strike settlement by CWA and BellSouth. (Kanell,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   TOUGH-UNIONS _ ATLANTA _ Corporate America, get ready to rumble.
More confrontations between management and workers are likely if
the economy remains healthy and worker shortages continue. The
nation's prosperity and record corporate profits are producing
gutsier workers. (Joyner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WALLSTREET-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ The way for investors to get
through the kind of stock market we've had in the last month is to
know why they're investing and to have enough self-discipline to
stay the course. (Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GEEWAX-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ Eventually, the kids will move away,
the mortgage will get paid off and deceased parents will leave
behind an inheritance. That patrimony may be considerable:
Economists estimate $12 trillion is now in the hands of the fading
World War II generation whose heirs are the 76 million Americans
born between 1946 and 1964. (Geewax, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GRASSROOTS-GAS _ ATLANTA _ Deregulation of Georgia's natural gas
market doesn't officially begin until Nov. 1. But don't tell that
to Dave Rich, who represents more than 7,000 Georgia consumers and
is ready to make a deal on their behalf for the best gas price once
the market is opened to competition. (Quinn, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK-COLUMN_ ATLANTA _ Here's an alluring idea: The next
time you need some ready cash, borrow it from yourself. As you
repay the loan, both principal and interest will go to you, not to
a lender. That may sound outlandish. But for many workers _ those
who have a 401(k). retirement plan with loan provisions _ it is an
increasingly attractive alternative. (Ezell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   INSURANCE-SHOPPING _ ATLANTA _ Georgia drivers paid an average
of $627.47 for auto insurance coverage in 1996, the latest data
available _ an average for all drivers, all cars, all locations.
But many drivers paid far more. That happened for several reasons,
including one often overlooked: They failed to shop around.
(Tharpe, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) MOVED. WITH LAYOUT AND
GRAPHICS.
</P>
<P>
   INSURANCE-PREMIUMS _ ATLANTA _ In terms of what it costs to
insure a car in Georgia, the average annual expenditure for auto
insurance was $627.47 in 1996, latest data available, the 25th
highest in the nation _ placing Georgia right in the middle of the
50 states. New Jersey has the highest average costs, $1,100. The
cheapest is Iowa at $445.39 annually. And even lower premiums are
expected, in Georgia and nationwide. (Tharpe, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.) MOVED. WITH LAYOUT AND GRAPHICS.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   MINORITY-TECH _ ATLANTA _ Bobby Smith, his son and his wife all
signed up for Derrick Brown's computer class at Georgia Tech.
``Using the computer just at work, I did not realize all the things
you can do with the Internet and in other ways that are such fun,''
Smith said. ``I am glad I did it, and now I tell everybody to try
it.'' The Smith family of Decatur, Ga. happens to be
African-American, and their experience underlines the findings in
studies that blacks are often involved less in the computer age
than the population at large. Often, however, encouragement and
opportunity can fire their enthusiasm about computers.
(Holsendolph, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-REPORT _ ATLANTA _ On portable sound systems. (Kanell,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ If you plan to put your faith _
and perhaps your fortune _ in the hands of the gurus dispensing
free legal advice on the World Wide Web, you can only hope your
next judge has a 17-inch screen. But if you use the legal resources
you find on the Web to prepare yourself for a visit with a lawyer,
it's possible to save money and do a better job of preparing for
that visit. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ You've probably been hearing a lot
about portals on the Internet lately. People buying portals,
selling portals, analysts predicting portals are the future. (Katz,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ I am here today to propose a new
national holiday. I don't think it'll be as much fun as Christmas,
or as important as Mother's Day, but I'm pretty sure it will catch
on. I propose we have a National Low Tech Day. (Husted, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHTOOLS-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ Review of the new Visual Page
program. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) MOVED.
</P>
