<P>
   BBN-BROWN-TRADE _ SAN DIEGO _ Kevin Brown didn't like it at
first. Not one bit. It was Dec. 15, and the Florida Marlins had
just traded Brown to the San Diego Padres for three minor-league
prospects. And the prospect of moving almost a continent away from
his Macon, Ga., home, his wife and two sons was pretty unappealing.
Well, it's eight months later, the Padres are sitting atop the
National League West, the Marlins are languishing in last, and
Brown himself his the proud owner of a 14-3 record and an 11-game
winning streak. (Graziano, Palm Beach Post.) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE-COLUMN _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ All right, so it's
football season again and you're ready to drop baseball like a bad
habit. That's the problem with our remote-control generation, so
eager to surf from one hot topic to the next. (George, Palm Beach
Post.) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NUHN-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ She hit ``rock bottom,'' as she
calls it, in October of 1996. Karen Noble had lost her playing card
after a promising start on the LPGA Tour, was back at Qualifying
School, it was Day One, and she was in the process of shooting 81.
Golf can do that to you; can grab you like a bouncer and start
tossing you around until you're bruised in both body and spirit.
Noble was to that point and beyond. (Nuhn, Dayton Daily News.)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ARCHDEACON-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ It was a voice she never
dreamed she'd hear again. It came to Judy Dickinson Thursday by
overnight mail. The unexpected package had been sent to Dayton by a
woman in Macon, Ga. When the woman's husband had been dying of
multiple sclerosis and could no longer see, Judy's husband _
Gardner Dickinson _ wanted to do something special. He and the guy
had gone to high school together in the early 1940s. And so,
Gardner _ one of the pioneers of the PGA Tour and Senior PGA Tour _
decided to read the golf book he had written, as well as special
notes and asides, into a tape recorder. He sent the labor of love
_10 cassettes in all _ to his dying friend. Now the guy's widow
thought Judy might like to have the tapes back....``It's been hard,
it still is,'' Judy said. ``People come up to me along the way and
tell me how they lost a husband or a wife. Most everyone says it
takes at least two years until you feel you're not just going
through the motions. You don't realize the void that's there. I
think of Gardner all the time. I can't tell you how many times I go
to call him and then it hits me. No one is there.'' Then last
Friday morning, he was. (Archdeacon, Dayton Daily News.) MOVED.
</P>
