<SLUG> BC-BLACK-FILM-AWARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK FILMMAKERS WIN PRIZES AND AN AUDIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By KATHRYN SHATTUCK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Urbanworld International Film Festival, a
competitive festival for black independent filmmakers now in its
second year, announced its winners on Sunday after presenting more
than 70 commercial and independent films over five days to an
audience of 5,000 at the Cineplex Odeon Worldwide Plaza Cinemas in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the gravy part,'' Darryl LeMont Wharton said after
winning the award for best director for his feature ``Detention,''
which he described as ``an urban `Breakfast Club.''' Wharton added,
``I'm happy just to have people see the film.''
</P>
<P>
   Wharton, a former writer for the NBC series ``Homicide: Life on
the Streets,'' left the show to make ``Detention,'' which he wrote,
directed and produced with Donna Lynne Comegys. ``Being a black
filmmaker is sort of like the tree in the forest. If you make a
film and nobody sees it, did you really make the film?''
</P>
<P>
   Other winners included Clement Virgo's ``Planet of Junior
Brown,'' based on the novel by Virginia Hamilton, for best picture;
``Classified X,'' Mark Daniels' look at the history of Hollywood's
portrayal of African-Americans, for best documentary; and ``The
Foreigner,'' Zola Mazeko's story about people from other African
countries who fled illegally to post-apartheid South Africa, for
best short. ``Park Day,'' Sterling Macer Jr.'s rite-of-passage
story set at a town picnic, won the Audience Favorite award.
</P>
<P>
   All of the filmmakers received $1,000 worth of Kodak film
donated by Eastman Kodak, a festival sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel A. Tolliver and Jake Ann Jones were awarded the
screenplay prize, sponsored by HBO, for ``Spook City.'' They
received $1,000 jointly, donated by the actor Samuel L. Jackson and
his wife, LaTanya Richardson Jackson, who is a member of the
festival's advisory board.
</P>
<P>
   Derek M. Cianfrance's ``Brother Tied'' and Stephen Winter's
``Chocolate Babies'' received honorable mentions in the
best-picture category.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
