<HEADER>
A6773 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-GAIA-VOLK-2TAKES-     08-10 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GAIA-VOLK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYLER VOLK: USING FLOWS AND FLUXES TO DEMYTHOLOGIZE THE UNITY OF
LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(HLW) 
 By JILL NEIMARK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes science and myth merge to make a kind of chimerical
beast, and perhaps the most magical of those Chimeras is the Gaia
hypothesis, developed a quarter century ago by James Lovelock, a
British atmospheric chemist, and Lynn Margulis, an American
microbiologist. The notion that our planet's surface functions like
a giant organism, one interconnected whole, was named after the
Greek earth goddess, and it has attracted not just pagans and
mystics but also atmospheric chemists, ecologists, oceanographers,
microbiologists and geologists.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler Volk, 47, is an associate professor of biology at New York
University and a member of the board of directors of Gaia: The
Society for Research and Education in Earth System Science, which
was formed to inspire interdisciplinary research into the Gaia
hypothesis. Volk is a principal investigator with the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration who studies crop growth in
closed systems. He divides his time between New York City and New
Mexico, where he spends summers in a trailer in the Mogollon
mountains.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote the recently published Gaia's Body: Toward a Physiology
of Earth (Copernicus).
</P>
<P>
   Q. When Lovelock first discussed the Gaia hypothesis, he
admitted it was at the outer bounds of scientific credibility and
he had a hard time even finding a journal to publish his ideas.
What do you think of the original theory?
</P>
<P>
   A. Gaia started with a stupendous metaphor and a unique
scientific insight, and I think Lovelock has a special charisma. In
a simple sentence, traditional Gaia theory postulates something
called ``comfortable conditions for life,'' and asserts that the
Gaian system maintains those conditions. It looks at the constancy
of temperature, climate, gasses, the ocean environment.
</P>
<P>
   The million-dollar question that Lovelock first asked was, Why
is atmospheric oxygen constant at 21 percent, the level needed to
maintain complex life? But I think there's been too much emphasis
on the ill-defined idea of comfort and on environmental stability.
I think the key is almost the opposite: the flow and flux of life,
of the chemical processes of organisms over the entire planet. The
sheer, raw power of life.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How do you actually measure something as diverse as life
spread across an entire planet?
</P>
<P>
   A. I'm looking at chemical, global productivity. I study the
ratio at which different elements crucial to life are recycled, or
passed from organism to organism. The cycling ratio of an element
instantly reveals the power of life. Take carbon, the heart of life
on our planet. If all that was available was the amount shed from
rocks and volcanoes, a carbon atom might be released into the
environment, utilized just once by an organism, and then buried.
But that's not what happens. Carbon is taken up into an organism
and then recycled, either because the organism dies and becomes
part of the biosphere's resources again, or because it's eaten by
another organism, or because it sheds carbon as waste. A single
atom of carbon is actually recycled 200 times before it is buried.
So you can see the power of the flow of life.
</P>
<P>
   Q. So the cycling ratio of an element is kind of like a
basketball team that keeps passing the ball, and after 200 passes
finally retires it? We know that life is carbon-based, but how
important are the cycling ratios of other elements?
</P>
<P>
   A. The fluxes of all the elements are profoundly revealing,
because they tell us what life needs. Nitrogen's cycling ratio can
be as high as 1,300, which is a huge amplification. And it's no
coincidence that the fluxes of the dozen or so most important
elements in our environment are in rough proportion to the fluxes
of those same elements in our own living bodies. That shows the
unity of life. What's also interesting is how these amplitudes vary
across the planet. I had an epiphany when I was working on the
equatorial belts of the ocean, trying to understand why they
outgassed so much carbon dioxide. I was turning a globe, and I
remember suddenly ``seeing'' this huge loop of carbon dioxide
flowing from the Pacific Ocean to the North Atlantic, and
understanding that the two are one coupled system.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What does the notion of a global breath tell us?
</P>
<P>
   A. In part, how much respiration (breathing out carbon dioxide
as waste) and photosynthesis (utilizing carbon dioxide as fuel) is
occurring in both places. And that tells us about the different
organisms there, and about the fact that there is indeed a global
metabolism, with one ocean coupled to the other. And once we can
build this large, coherent kind of picture, we can start to
formulate questions about the planet and how it works.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Will understanding the global metabolism give us a window
into the possibility of life on other planets?
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   A. It might. We know, for instance, that oxygen could not exist
at its current level on the planet without life _ it's far too
reactive a gas, and would on its own combine with other elements
and quickly plunge to low levels. In the case of life,
photosynthesis constantly pours out oxygen and maintains it at high
levels. So the proportion of gasses in a planet's atmosphere may
give us a clue to organisms hundreds of light years away. We may be
able to look at the spectrum of light reflected off a planet, as
Lovelock originally pointed out, and translate that wobble of light
waves into knowledge about the proportion of gasses we're seeing.
And then we'd know if organic life was driving them.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What else do the cycling ratios of elements tell us about our
own planet?
</P>
<P>
   A. They show us the fundamental mechanism of Gaia, which is that
waste equals resource. We're more than just predator and prey.
Eating is only one form of chemical transfer. When an organism's
waste goes out into the world, it can become part of the
atmosphere, ocean, or soil, and become part of a vast chemical web.
The carbon dioxide you exhale while walking in your back yard has
almost as much chance of being taken in by a tree in a forest in
China as by local photosynthesis.
</P>
<P>
   The fluxes of chemicals also give us a whole new way of
classifying life forms by their actual functions rather than as
species or even kingdoms. I think of the world as a symphony of
what I call biochemical guilds. Plants, algae and many bacteria are
members of different kingdoms, but they can be classed as a single
biochemical guild of photosynthesizers. Then there's the guild of
the respirers, which breathe out carbon dioxide and include
everything from frogs to amoeba. There is the guild of nitrogen
fixers, which take gaseous nitrogen and transform it. Nitrogen
fixers are all microbes, although certain kinds of plants like
legumes and some trees harbor the microbes in their roots. If you
order our global metabolism by these guilds you can instantly see
the unity of Gaia. One of the neatest proofs of the existence of
the biochemical guilds is the universal molecular mechanisms shared
by their members, the common metabolic machinery down at the
molecular level.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Can you give an example of a universal molecule?
</P>
<P>
   A. The green of chlorophyll in all photosynthesizers. I remember
when I first saw this guild, in California. I was looking across a
lake and suddenly the thicket of trees, shrubs and grasses blended
into a single entity. Green. Chlorophyll is the molecule of our
most visible guild. Now wherever I go, this guild speaks to me of
its presence, even in the winter in the desert in New Mexico. It's
as if the guild is saying to me: ``Green is forever.'' The
individual parts aren't as important.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What guild are we part of? The respirers?
</P>
<P>
   A. I call us the guild that knows all other guilds. We're not
only respirers. We're alchemists, too; we can actually fix nitrogen
without the help of bacteria. They use enzymes. We use heat in
factories, and manufacture fertilizers that way. And we take fossil
fuel carbons like coal and oil and burn them. We're the first guild
that is adding to the chemical fluxes with devices set up outside
our bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Q. This use of technology to augment or replace natural
processes sounds like a monumental shift. Or are we just doing what
life always does, and amplifying cycling ratios?
</P>
<P>
   A. That's the classic question. I think we've taken over the
planet in many ways, and, though we will probably never wipe out
the microbes, we need to think about what kind of world we want,
and the disruption we may cause by changing our ecosystems.
</P>
<P>
   Q. We're losing species at a tremendous rate, and, it seems,
drastically altering the climate through the greenhouse effect. Can
Gaian science help us preserve ourselves? It sounds like the whole
system is hinged together in an exquisitely subtle way.
</P>
<P>
   A. We can measure the biomass of algae and launch satellites to
monitor ozone and pull up sediment from lakes to learn which trees
lived during the last Ice Age. And then we can start to understand
the critical points where the system would collapse. So we can
learn, for instance, how to apply nitrogen fertilizer at the proper
times and doses, to limit the runoff that endangers ecosystems. Or
we can phase out the release of chlorofluorocarbons. Gaia shows
that our actions affect all other life and always come back to us.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Your Gaia sounds almost as romantic and mythic as Lovelock's.
Do you really feel you've stripped the metaphor from the science,
or are you still seduced by it?
</P>
<P>
   A. I've tried to be more exact with the phrase ``global
metabolism'' rather than ``global organism.'' But I may have only
partly succeeded. I was walking in a canyon the other day and
listening to the thunder, and I thought to myself: ``There's Zeus
talking.'' And recently I stopped a truck from running over a
rattlesnake, and as the snake crawled off into the bush I thought:
``Well, now all the rattlesnakes will know I'm a good guy and I'll
have a little bit of coinage next time I hike in the canyons.''
That way of thinking is so deep and so important to us. This mixing
human qualities into nature runs deep in civilization.
</P>
<P>
   Q. It's our way of connecting to the world by seeing and feeling
it as self, rather than other.
</P>
<P>
   A. It's why we painted lions' heads on human bodies, why we
turned rain and wind into gods. If I really feel I'm living inside
Gaia, if the whole body of the biosphere becomes my self, then I'm
truly part of the world. It's important to loosen up the concept of
self because if you extend it into the world you're more likely to
want to engage with the world, to play in it, not just to see it as
a resource for food.
</P>
<P>
   Q. So in that sense, the Gaia metaphor is as powerful a siren
song as ever.
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes. As is the science. If you want to worship mystery,
studying the global metabolism is a great way to go.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
