<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 HEALTH WATCH: A LEG UP FOR THE HEART; EATER-FRIENDLY SPICES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Muscle cells transplanted from rabbits' legs to their hearts
boosted cardiac performance, possibly by having ``learned'' within
days how to act like neighboring heart cells, a new study shows.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the transplanted leg cells functioned for as long
as 16 weeks after being inserted into the heart muscle, far longer
than expected, Duke University researchers reported.
</P>
<P>
   The molecular biologists who conducted the study believe cells
extracted from leg tissue may have even developed the bioelectrical
properties that enable the heart to contract and pump blood. How
the transplanted cells work is not known, and other researchers
warned that concluding that the cells had changed would be
premature.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to be very careful in concluding they turned into
another type of cell,'' said Dr. David Diechek of the University of
California at San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists said that even if the transplanted cells did not
fundamentally transform, the Duke procedure, reported in the August
issue of the journal Nature Medicine, was a preliminary
demonstration that one type of muscle cell can help another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something is clearly happening when you put these cells in,''
said Loren Field, a molecular biologist at Indiana University.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most muscles, heart tissue does not regenerate after it
is damaged, because it contains no reserve of embryonic muscle
cells, or myoblasts, that could quickly mature and restore the
heart's normal function.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the dead cells form scar tissue that does not flex when
the remaining healthy heart muscles pump. Blood flow and pressure
are diminished with potentially fatal results.
</P>
<P>
   In the Duke experiment, Doris Taylor, a biologist, and others
damaged the hearts of 17 rabbits to mimic the scar tissue that
forms after a heart attack. Five of the rabbits were control
animals that received no further treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers took muscle biopsies from the legs of the 12
remaining rabbits and grew myoblasts in cell cultures. The rapidly
dividing cells were then transfused into the rabbits' damaged
hearts.
</P>
<P>
   Within five to 10 days, the cardiac performance of seven rabbits
had improved noticeably.
</P>
<P>
   Microscopic analysis showed that the transplanted cells had
developed intercalated disks, ``a distinctly cardiac feature,'' Ms.
Taylor said, that is involved in transferring from cell to cell the
electrical charge that powers the heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
   Other researchers said more experiments were necessary with
higher ratios of successful transplants _ and possibly using other
species.
</P>
<P>
   Killer Spice
</P>
<P>
   Clove-burgers, anyone? The idea might turn some stomachs but
might also be good for digestive tracts, say researchers who
examined the ability of common spices to kill E. coli 0157:H7, the
much discussed, much feared, food-contaminating bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   Spices have been used for centuries to make food safer to eat in
hot countries, and other studies have tested the ability of spices
to kill bacteria. But in this country, worries about E. coli have
risen since 1993, when four children died after eating hamburgers
contaminated with it in the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   With these fears in mind, biologists at Kansas State University
applied 23 spices to raw ground beef and salami containing E. coli
to see which was most effective in destroying it. Their findings,
which were presented this summer at a meeting of the Institute of
Food Technologists, showed the winners were garlic, clove,
cinnamon, oregano and sage.
</P>
<P>
   A mixture of 7.5 percent clove to 92.5 percent ground beef
killed 99 percent of the bacteria, said Dr. Daniel Fung, while a
more palatable level _ 2.5 percent clove _ killed 90 percent.
Similarly, 99 percent of the bacteria died when salami was
fermented with about three times as much garlic as even a garlic
lover would want, but a more moderate dose still killed about half,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fung stressed that a heavy hand with spices should not be
considered a substitute for cooking meat thoroughly.
</P>
</TEXT>
