<HEADLINE>
POULOS LOSES IN STRAIGHT SETS TO MIYAGI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WELLESLEY, Mass. _ Life at the collegiate level, where Jennifer
Poulos was a three-time All-American at Cal-Berkeley, was never
like this. In the pros, there are no teammates, no coaches, no one
to greet you whether you win or lose. That is, unless you have the
money to allow a coach to travel with you, which Poulos doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Poulos, a Brookline, Mass. native, is in her second year as a
pro. She's ranked No. 320, while her twin sister, Valerie, who also
played at Cal, is No. 720. They're together about half the time,
giving each other someone to commiserate with after losing a match,
someone to go to dinner with, someone to take practice strokes
with.
</P>
<P>
   Monday at Babson College, in a center-court match in the Boston
Cup, part of the Corel WTA Tour, MondayNina Miyagi of Japan
defeated Poulos, 6-4, 6-4. In her 10th pro year, Miyagi, who is
ranked 95th, has been part of her country's Fed Cup team since
1987, both in singles and doubles, and she owns victories over
Martina Hingis and Lindsay Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   Poulos, playing in her first WTA event, was nervous when she
took the court, knowing Miyagi was better than most of the players
she has been facing. She had seen Miyagi play in qualifying Sunday
and went into the match concerned about Miyagi's quickness.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a very good player,'' said Poulos, whose serve was
broken six times, three in each set. ``I like to hit the ball flat
as well as move in, but I didn't feel in control of the points. She
hit the ball pretty deep and hard and it's difficult to play
someone at her level. She moves the ball very well and she's pretty
consistent. My serve wasn't very consistent and I knew she would be
aggressive with the returns and put pressure on me.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a lot different than when I was in college, with the
girls here pressuring me a lot more, these girls are much better
players. I played positive most of the time and I kept playing the
way I wanted to _ that was to stay on the baseline and hit
aggressively. I didn't think about playing in the main draw,
though, or I would have played worse. I just have to practice and
get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Poulos, who made the NCAA round of 16 each year as a collegian,
received a wild card to get in here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough playing against a wild card,'' said Miyagi. ``They
have nothing to lose, and I'm the one with a lot of pressure. I
didn't play well, though. I didn't feel comfortable. I was giving
too many free points away. I was spraying a lot of balls.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of Poulos's traveling has been in the United States since
January, but she's been to Brazil, France, England, and Italy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to travel alone and to play well and motivate
yourself,'' said Poulos, who is supported financially by her
parents. ``It's hard to find people you like to stay with in a
hotel and to watch you play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sometimes frustrating to play a match and to lose and not
to have someone there to help you. Maybe I'll be upset and maybe I
won't play the next day. You need someone to analyze your game
because you're more negative about yourself. A coach or someone to
watch you can put it in more perspective for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Thank goodness Poulos has her sister.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
