<SLUG> BC-CAPEZIO-DANCE-AWARD-469-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANCE AWARD GOES TO JACOB'S PILLOW
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)   (ll) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Jacob's Pillow Dance Festival has won the
47th-Annual Capezio Dance Award. The summer festival, in Becket,
Mass., was honored in a ceremony on Saturday night at the Ted Shawn
Theater there. The award is given to dancers, choreographers, dance
companies and institutions in recognition of their contributions to
dance in the United States. The Pillow is the first producing
organization to win the prize.
</P>
<P>
   Calling Jacob's Pillow ``a total environment for the art of
dance,'' Gayle Miller of the Capezio/Ballet Makers Dance Foundation
presented a check for $10,000 to Ella Baff, director of the
festival. Three previous festival directors _ Liz Thompson, Sam
Miller and Sali Ann Kriegsman _ joined Ms. Baff on stage for the
event, with officials of the foundation and Neil D. Chrisman,
chairman of the Pillow board.
</P>
<P>
   Barton Mumaw, a member of Ted Shawn's first Men Dancers company
and a longtime Pillow teacher, represented Shawn, who in 1930
bought and built up the Pillow grounds as a home for the men's
dance troupe. Shawn, who with his wife, Ruth St. Denis, was a
pioneering figure in American modern dance, directed the festival
through 1971.
</P>
<P>
   The four directors onstage, whose tenures span the last eight
years, are widely perceived as representing a new era in the
history of the festival. Ms. Thompson, who led the festival in 1989
and 1990, is credited with having taken the first steps to open the
Pillow to a somewhat wider range of dance, music and performance
art.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt a need to make a wonderful home for dancers,'' Ms.
Thompson said in an interview after the ceremony. ``And the place
is magic.'' She said her background in traditional, modern and
postmodern dance and in Broadway and television, along with her
commitment to ``cultural equity,'' inspired her to extend the range
of a festival already known for its eclecticism.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Baff said the Capezio money would go to artists and their
projects at the Pillow.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is one other really important thing about the award,''
she said. ``It is a great honor beyond any dollar value. It is both
recognition and encouragement to achieve and reach our next
destinations, and we have a lot of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The festival runs through Aug. 29, with engagements by the Jose
Greco II Flamenco Dance Company and the performance artist Ann
Carlson this week and by the Twyla Tharp and Urban Bush Women
companies from Aug. 18 to 23. It closes with ``Invisible Wings,''
an outdoor work by Joanna Haigood's Zaccho Dance Theater from Aug.
25 to 29, about the northward journeys of escaped slaves through
the Pillow grounds, a stop on the Underground Railroad.
</P>
<P>
   The award ceremony also honored the memory of Alfred Terlizzi,
the foundation's president, who died this year. A brother, Donald,
has been named to succeed him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
