<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 TIMES SQUARE VISITORS TO GET HIGH-TECH HELP  
 TOURS OF PARIS FOR THE FRENCH-IMPAIRED  
 THOMAS WOLFE'S HOUSE IS DAMAGED BY FIRE  
 GETTING A HEAD START ON A VAN GOGH SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Aug. 16) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Times Square, in the midst of its big cleanup, is
about to open a new visitors center in a restored movie theater.
The center, on the east side of Broadway between 46th and 47th
streets, will even provide public restrooms, that rarest of
Manhattan amenities, when it opens next month.
</P>
<P>
   The center, which will be open from 8 a.m. to 8 p.m., will sell
Metrocards for subway travel and provide six ATMs, free Internet
access at six terminals, and a machine that converts currency. The
human race is represented in an information booth with live
attendants.
</P>
<P>
   The theater-ticket booth will offer full-price tickets to all
Broadway shows (no off-Broadway yet, and the TKTS booth across the
street will remain the place for discounted tickets), and Gray Line
and Circle Line tour tickets will be sold as well. For those who
need some news from home, Hotalings will sell out-of-town
newspapers. And official New York City souvenirs will be sold.
</P>
<P>
   The Times Square Business Improvement District will run the
center in the former Embassy Theater, a Louis XVI style movie house
that opened in 1925. It has two lobbies _ one with marble trim, the
other with ornate woodwork.
</P>
<P>
   The theater itself was adorned with six landscapes by Arthur
Crisp, a New York muralist whose work appeared in numerous
commercial buildings from the 1920s, and two of these have been
restored, along with the original Rambusch ceiling lights.
</P>
<P>
   Tours of Paris for the French-Impaired
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, nearly all walking tours of Paris were given
in French. The English-speaking tourist usually had to be content
with a sheet containing the essential facts to be covered by the
guide.
</P>
<P>
   There always came a moment as the group walked through castle or
street when the guide would say something and all the French
tourists would laugh while the Americans would just look down at
the written sheet, feeling slightly left out. Now Americans can be
in on the joke, too.
</P>
<P>
   Paris Walking Tours, run by an engaging and well-informed young
English couple, Peter and Oriel Caine, takes English-speaking
tourists through Notre-Dame, Sainte-Chapelle, the Luxembourg
Gardens, Hemingway's Paris, the old village of Montmartre, medieval
Paris, the Invalides, Cluny, the Arcades of Old Paris and the
Palais Royal, Paris of the impressionists, the Ile St.-Louis and
the Seine, the Conciergerie, the Marais and the Opera House, as
well as on bus trips to Vaux-le-Vicomte, Malmaison and Versailles.
</P>
<P>
   The tours, which vary from week to week, last about 90 minutes
and are full of historical gossip and humor. Paris Walking Tours
offers one tour a day, usually at 10:30 a.m. or 2:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't like to plan ahead, you can find a list in
Pariscope. Reservations are not required _ just show up at the
designated Metro stop.
</P>
<P>
   For information, call (33-1) 48.09.21.40 or fax (33-1)
42.43.75.51. The fee is $10, $5 for children.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Wolfe's House Is Damaged by Fire
</P>
<P>
   The Asheville, N.C., boardinghouse that was the childhood home
of Thomas Wolfe and the setting for his autobiographical novel
``Look Homeward, Angel'' stands empty and charred after a fire on
July 24 that authorities believe was set deliberately.
</P>
<P>
   The house, a national historic landmark that attracts 25,000
visitors a year, will be restored but will probably remain closed
for at least a year, according to Mary Cook, director of public
affairs for the North Carolina Department of Cultural Resources.
</P>
<P>
   An arsonist apparently threw combustible objects through the
first-floor dining-room window to start the fire, according to
Harley Shuford, director of the Asheville-Bruncombe County Arson
Task Force. After destroying dining-room furniture and melting
display silver, flames crept up the side of the building and
consumed the attic and roof.
</P>
<P>
   Much original furniture was saved by firefighters, who rushed to
recover what pieces they could as they hosed down the 115-year-old
Victorian house, Ms. Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   Other artifacts, including Wolfe's writing desk and typewriter,
had recently been moved to the nearby visitors center in
anticipation of a restoration in the fall, when a fire-alarm and
security system were to be added.
</P>
<P>
   The visitors center, where the desk, the typewriter and other
artifacts are on display, along with exhibits pertaining to Wolfe's
life and works, will remain open. Hours: Monday through Saturday 9
a.m. to 5 p.m., Sunday 1 to 5 p.m.; (828) 253-8304.
</P>
<P>
   Getting a Head Start on a Van Gogh Show
</P>
<P>
   Vincent van Gogh is so popular that the National Gallery of Art
in Washington has decided to start issuing passes for its
exhibition this fall two months before the show opens.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy van Gogh paintings, on loan from the Van Gogh Museum in
Amsterdam, the Netherlands, will be on view from Oct. 4 to Jan. 3.
</P>
<P>
   It is quite possible that attendance for the show, ``Van Gogh's
Van Goghs,'' will exceed that of the gallery's 1995-96 Vermeer
exhibition, which drew more than 300,000 people, and will challenge
the record set by its biggest show, last year's survey of the works
of the young Picasso, which drew more than 500,000.
</P>
<P>
   Passes, which are free, will be required for admission and will
be available beginning Aug. 30 at the gallery's East Building
during its regular hours, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Monday to Saturday, and
11 a.m. to 6 p.m. on Sunday. A visitor may have up to six passes.
</P>
<P>
   Advance passes may also be obtained in the Washington area at
Ticketmaster locations and Hecht's stores for a service charge of
$2 each. They can also be bought through Ticketmaster Phone Charge
for $2.75 each plus $1.25 an order.
</P>
<P>
   The Ticketmaster number to call outside the Washington area is
(800) 551-7328.
</P>
<P>
   The local numbers are (202) 432-7328 in Washington, (703)
573-7328 in northern Virginia and (410) 481-7328 in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Same-day passes will be issued each day, also with a limit of
six to a person.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
