A6797 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAY-VOTE-HNS &LR;      08-10 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-VOTE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGHTS GROUP SEEKS TO HELP CANDIDATES UNDERSTAND GAY ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NICOLE TSONG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A leading gay rights organization is urging
candidates not to discount homosexual issues in the upcoming
elections, encouraging campaigns to speak out against
discrimination based on sexual orientation and support the role of
government in combating AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The Human Rights Campaign, the nation's largest bipartisan gay
political group, has published a pamphlet to help candidates
understand gay issues and answer questions about gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   The 32-page pamphlet includes a forward with advice from Sheila
Burke, who served as chief of staff under former Senate Majority
Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., and former White House senior adviser and
Democratic campaign strategist George Stephanopoulos.
</P>
<P>
   Burke said gay voters are ``increasingly important in the
electoral process.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to understand the issues, be knowledgeable and speak
about them in a way that respects and includes their perspective,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Five percent of the general election voters in 1996 were gay,
the Human Rights Campaign said, citing exit poll interviews. Burke
said issues gay voters are concerned about _ equality in the
workplace, health care and AIDS _ transcend political lines.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanopoulos wrote that the Human Rights Campaign could help
candidates ``be a pioneer for change.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The gay and lesbian community is organized, educated and it
votes,'' Stephanopoulos wrote for the booklet.
</P>
<P>
   The organization urged candidates to consider these issues, and
responses, important to gay constituents:
</P>
<P>
   _ Fairness in the workplace. The Human Rights Campaign said
federal labor laws do not protect gays from discrimination based on
sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   _ HIV and AIDS: Candidates should emphasize the role of the
government in the fight against HIV _ the AIDS virus _ and AIDS.
``We can't let down our guard in the fight against AIDS, '' the
pamphlet says.
</P>
<P>
   _ Violent hate crimes: According to the FBI, anti-gay sentiment
is number three on the list of reasons for hate crimes. The
pamphlet includes an incident in which two gay man were ridiculed
and assaulted.
</P>
<P>
   _ Families and adoption: Parents and professionals should make
the decision about gay and lesbian partners adopting children, not
the government, the pamphlet advises.
</P>
<P>
   _ Marriage: Candidates should advocate marriage, regardless of
sexual orientation. ``The government should not interfere in
personal matters like marriage. The choice of a spouse is a very
personal decision that should be left up to the individual,'' the
pamphlet says.
</P>
<P>
   _ Equal compensation: Health insurance and other workplace
benefits should be available to domestic partners, including
homosexuals, the pamphlet says.
</P>
<P>
   _ Discrimination in the military: The Human Rights Campaign
booklet urges candidates to tell voters that gays have served with
distinction in the military. ``We need a military that is trained,
equipped and ready, and we can't waste anybody with skills and
dedication,'' it says.
</P>
<P>
   The manual is available from the Washington-based Human Rights
Campaign by calling 202-628-4160.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
