<HEADER>
A6801 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEAR-COX     08-10 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEAR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ex-Spin controller launches a new magazine
 &HT;    By Richard L. Eldredge
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Publisher Bob Guccione Jr., creator of Spin magazine, is scared
again. And he's enjoying every sweaty-palmed second of it.
</P>
<P>
   In launching Gear this month, the son of Penthouse publisher Bob
Guccione is aiming for the same Generation X readers that made Spin
a success. The bimonthly's inaugural issue arrives on newsstands
this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same feeling all over again,'' says the younger
Guccione, who is Gear's editor. ``It's a little frightening and a
lot exciting. With Spin, so many people told me: `You can't take on
Rolling Stone and survive.' My point was that there was a need
there for some different, something more.''
</P>
<P>
   After selling Spin last year to Vibe magazine founder Quincy
Jones for ``a fantastically high price'' _ published reports put it
at $42 million _ Spin's ``bored'' creator searched for a new
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   His solution: Take on industry mainstays GQ, Esquire and
Details, his closest competitor for readers younger than 40. The
42-year-old didn't exactly scour the competition for ideas. He paid
more attention to Cosmopolitan and European music and men's
magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want the self-consciousness of GQ or Details. It's
hollow journalism,'' he says. ``I wanted Gear to have the courage
to really probe the culture, something that would go against the
consensus.''
</P>
<P>
   Guccione isn't above resorting to his dad's stock in trade,
though. In the debut issue, Guccione's parish priest, Michael
Holleran, writes a column headlined ``God wants you to be sexy.''
The accompanying photo shows a bikini-clad woman posing in front of
a monumental crucifix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, sex would be a part of it. Attraction is a very powerful
thing and something you shouldn't feel ashamed of,'' Guccione says.
</P>
<P>
   That explains the revealing photos of ``La Femme Nikita''
actress Peta Wilson. But there are also serious pieces, like an
investigative take on Iraq in the aftermath of the Persian Gulf War
and a profile of Texas Gov. George W. Bush, a possible presidential
contender. More traditional men's magazine fare includes an
unpublished, four-year-old interview with actor Matt Damon, a
fashion spread and movie, album and video game reviews. The slick
European design is reminiscent of Spin.
</P>
<P>
   The first assignment Guccione gave himself was an interview with
his father's longtime rival, Playboy publisher Hugh Hefner.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you can imagine, there was a natural tension but in a
positive way,'' the younger Guccione says. ``He gave our readers
some great fatherly advice. He was gracious about my father and
their rivalry.'' And did the elder Guccione help with a list of
questions for Hefner? ``No,'' Guccione says matter-of-factly. ``He
didn't know about it and I didn't give him an advance look at the
story.''
</P>
<P>
   Guccione realizes he faces a formidable battle in starting
another men's magazine. Gear's estimated circulation of 200,000 is
still dwarfed by the estimated circulation of GQ (688,752), Esquire
(657,718) and Details (484,563). He hopes he can beat the odds
again, as he did when he started Spin in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want Gear to be different spiritually,'' Guccione says. ``I
will always want to challenge the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
