<SLUG> BC-COYOTE-ATTACK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTE ATTACK ON TODDLER REMAINS A MYSTERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ State wildlife officials say they are stumped in trying
to figure out why a coyote attacked a toddler on Cape Cod, the
first documented case in Massachusetts and one of only a handful
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Lab results released Monday indicate the coyote did not have
distemper, mange or any other disease that might prompt an animal
to attack a human.
</P>
<P>
   Rabies was ruled out immediately after police shot the animal
following the July 29 attack on 3-year-old Daniel Neal, who was
playing on his backyard swingset.
</P>
<P>
   With no answers to why the attack occurred, the anxiety among
Cape residents who seem to encounter coyotes at every turn is
likely to continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are very concerned still,'' said Steven Chapman, the
animal control officer in Sandwich. ``They are very scared.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators last week interviewed the boy's mother, who had to
kick and punch the coyote to get it to release her son, and
neighbors in Sandwich, but they found no evidence that someone had
been feeding or caring for the coyote.
</P>
<P>
   Wild animals that have become accustomed to people sometimes
lose their normal predatory skills and attack humans if their food
supply is interrupted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't leave us in a good position,'' said Rob Deblinger,
the state's assistant director for wildlife. ``We have not answered
the question of why this animal attacked a human.''
</P>
<P>
   The coyote's right front leg had been fractured and healed some
time ago, possibly an indication the coyote was hit by a car and
picked up and nursed back to health. But so far, no one has
admitted caring for the coyote.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman said police received a call shortly after the coyote was
killed from an unidentified man who claimed he had been feeding the
coyote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know who it was that called,'' Chapman said. ``We're
trying to get information on that now, but that's going to be
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Although coyotes are normally skittish around humans, officials
said this particular coyote may have been just abnormally
aggressive. ``There is always the possibility that this animal was
on the extreme edge of the curve in terms of aggressiveness,''
Deblinger said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the handful of coyote attacks on humans nationwide, most have
taken place out West, many in California. But Deblinger said
California officials have told Massachusetts officials that a
campaign to educate people about how to deal with wild animals has
all but eliminated the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Deblinger said Massachusetts plans to develop its own campaign
in the wake of the attack on the toddler. He said Massachusetts
residents would be urged not to feed a wild animal and keep pets
and their food inside.
</P>
<P>
   While Deblinger has said state wildlife officials would like the
right to use padded leg-hold traps to deal with nuisance coyotes,
he said the agency has no plans to try to overturn a 1996 law
passed by referendum that bars the use of the traps.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's going to be a change in that law, it's going to
come from the people,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
