A6803 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HESAID-SHESAID-COX     08-10 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HESAID-SHESAID-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's too bad a girl's looks matter most
 &HT;    By Maureen Downey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A baby girl dozing on an airplane last week wore more jewelry
than Ivana Trump.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all Wal-Mart specials,'' I overheard her mother tell a
seatmate. ``She'll have to work on getting herself a rich man to
afford the real stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   I fought the urge to turn around and suggest that her daughter
could buy her own ankle bracelets if encouraged to focus on her
school books rather than her datebook.
</P>
<P>
   I've bristled at such comments about little girls ever since my
daughter was a newborn and a woman in a hardware store announced,
``She's going to make some man very happy some day.''
</P>
<P>
   She meant it as a compliment; I found it a startling reminder
that women are still prized for their ability to attract men. That
attitude helps explain Monica Lewinsky, who wasted the most coveted
internship in the country to hone skills that can't go on a resume.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky somehow got the message that her self-worth depended on
grabbing the attention of powerful older men. No matter that the
man was married and the attention was hooded and brief.
</P>
<P>
   My hopes that things had changed were dashed recently when I
interviewed a mother who insisted that her 13-month-old daughter
``loves'' kiddie beauty contests. Sure, the $300 sequined pageant
costumes strain the household budget, but the women viewed these as
an investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being really good-looking,'' she explained, ``is still a
girl's best chance in life.''
</P>
<P>
   High status is what counts for the guys
</P>
<P>
   By Bo Emerson
</P>
<P>
   c. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Maureen is hard on powerful, dumpy men who get babes. In her
idealized world, the Donald Trumps would be lonely.
</P>
<P>
   She's even harder on the girls who go for these louts. Why, she
wonders, do they still buy into the myth that they need a
successful man?
</P>
<P>
   I have bad news for Maureen. Women are genetically selected to
dig lead dogs. It's a biological imperative.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a certain sense it's beyond choice,'' says Dr. Randy
Thornhill. ``Female brains are designed to prefer high-status
males.''
</P>
<P>
   Thornhill, an evolutionary biologist at the University of New
Mexico, studies the mating behavior of scorpion flies, red jungle
fowl and humans. He finds that creatures great and small have
similar strategies for procreation. Out there in the wild,
good-looking females get together with successful males. ``These
rules are universal, wherever there are critters.''
</P>
<P>
   Feminists cry that our warped attitudes make a Monica Lewinsky
yearn after a Big Enchilada like Bill Clinton, instead of depending
on her own achievements. But Thornhill says it's Monica's DNA
pushing her toward a date with the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   Theoretically, high-achieving but unpalatable women like
Margaret Thatcher and Roseanne could reverse this trend. With a few
million more years of evolution.
</P>
<P>
   Glad I'm going to miss it.
</P>
<P>
   Write married staffers Maureen Downey and Bo Emerson at Cox News
Service, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. E-mail them at
mdowney(at)ajc.com or bemerson(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
