<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6804 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MSKUBE-COLUMN11-COX     08-10 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MSKUBE-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: For a few minutes, Dr. Laura claims to be listening
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The news story didn't report it, but they had to be doing
cartwheels at WSB-AM in Atlanta last week when Laura Schlessinger
signed on for another two years. What the story did say was enough
_ that Dr. Laura's nationally syndicated show was No. 1 in her time
slot. For three hours, from noon to 3, no one in Atlanta has more
listeners.
</P>
<P>
   That's not surprising, just ironic.
</P>
<P>
   She's getting rich telling people to go take on the day. She
tells them more than that, of course, and therein lies the irony.
</P>
<P>
   They are the listeners; she is the talker.
</P>
<P>
   They start out as the talkers, telling Dr. Laura what fresh
crisis (``Do you think I should tell my father-in-law we'd rather
he not smoke in our house?'') has sent them forth into Gethsemane.
But they don't talk long and she doesn't listen long.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Laura may have listeners, legions of them. But she is not
herself a listener.
</P>
<P>
   She is an unusually poor listener, when you think about it. She
listens long enough to set someone straight, to tell them how to
think and what to think. She doesn't have time for them, and the
listener without time is no listener at all.
</P>
<P>
   It is radio, of course, and not the confessional. The phone
lines are backed up. You have to get 'em on and get 'em off. That
is the nature of the business, but it is not the face the show
presents to its audience. The face it presents is one of advice and
understanding. It is to counseling what the drive-in window is to
eating. You are handed your bag of moral absolutes and sent on your
way, reassured for the moment, chastised but not changed.
</P>
<P>
   Hanging up, callers return to their crummy lives and their daily
doubts. The same doubts and uncertainties they had before they
called Dr. Laura.
</P>
<P>
   In her view of life, there are no uncertainties. She is like the
soldier who claims not to know the meaning of fear, only duty.
</P>
<P>
   All of us should be so lucky. Getting through the day could be
reduced to an instruction manual.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to talk impartially about Dr. Laura. Listeners hang on
her every word with the devotion of disciples. Critics, in their
bitterness, betray the very failings she sees in them _ pretense
and falsity.
</P>
<P>
   Give her credit for this: She is a tocsin in a culture gone
nutty with ``self-esteem,'' one that believes feelings are
paramount. This is one of the reasons the therapy crowd doesn't
like her _ feelings are their bread and butter. Her views are not
so different from those of Robyn Dawes, an academic psychologist at
Carnegie-Mellon University(Penn.) whose book ``House of Cards''
sharply criticizes clinical psychologists for palming off bogus
ideas as reliable advice.
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, they are not so different from those of one of
the seminal American thinkers, William James. ``The hell to be
endured hereafter,'' James wrote, ``is no worse than the hell we
make for ourselves in this world by habitually fashioning our
characters in the wrong way.''
</P>
<P>
   You know Dr. Laura would second that. But I wonder if she'd
agree with James on something else: ``In the deepest heart of all
of us there is a corner in which the ultimate mystery of things
works sadly.''
</P>
<P>
   If it has a melancholy ring to it, so much the better. Most
people, sooner or later, encounter the truth of it. When they do,
they often want someone to talk to. They seek out pastors and
parish priests, rabbis, therapists, trusted friends, bosses, even
bartenders.
</P>
<P>
   Religious people have been thought to possess, it not an in with
God, at least a higher spirituality that somehow qualifies them to
understand mere humans. It doesn't always work that way, as many
have found out. In this century, psychology and psychiatry compete
with religion, with therapists and analysts as secular substitutes
for clergy.
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't matter what they are _ this is one of Robyn
Dawes' points. What matters is that they know how to listen. It's
not so much something they've learned, but part of their makeup.
Some people listen better than others, just as one person can carry
a tune and another can't. Most people make a show of listening, if
only as a gesture. But they're not really there. They are somewhere
else _ in their own thoughts, readying their reply, doodling,
checking their watch, anywhere but in the heart of another.
</P>
<P>
   Or they might be in a hurry to get to the next caller.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a bad racket. And you can't beat the hours.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
