<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6805 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-MULLINS-COX     08-10 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MULLINS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    After nine years of trying to make it, Atlanta musician Shawn
Mullins is enjoying overnight success
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   How long does it take to become an overnight success?
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Mullins can do the math. But he'd rather sing and play
guitar which, after nine years kicking around Atlanta's acoustic
music scene, is about to make him famous.
</P>
<P>
   And if you haven't yet heard ``Lullaby,'' the 30-year-old
performer's out-of-the-blue breakthrough, you will. Oh yeah. You'll
be hearing a lot of it.
</P>
<P>
   It was only a month ago that Atlanta modern rock radio station
99X (WNNX-FM) added the songwriter's ballad _ a track from his
latest self-produced album ``Soul's Core'' _ to its playlist.
</P>
<P>
   Within two weeks, Mullins signed a lucrative recording deal with
Columbia Records.
</P>
<P>
   What happened in between was a blur.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were so many (record) labels on my answering machine it
was out of control,'' says Mullins, a Decatur, Ga. native who
became the prize in a corporate tug of war that also included
Atlantic Records and Universal Records, among an estimated 10 to 15
labels that expressed viable interest. ``This is the kind of thing
that happens in movies,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The song is a haunting vignette about a lost, jaded soul amid
the Hollywood glitter, complete with prominently strummed guitar
and a vaguely hip-hop drum track that echoes the grunge-folk of
Beck's ``Loser.'' What sets ``Lullaby'' apart is the juxtaposition
of Mullins' sweetly sung refrain _ ``Everything's gonna be all
right/Rockabye'' _ with spoken segments that confide the story,
emphasizing a gruff, knowing edge in the singer's voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great, wonderful, classic rock song,'' says Will
Bottwin, general manager for Columbia Records, and a former manager
of such songwriters' songwriters as Steve Earle, John Hiatt, Lyle
Lovett, Nanci Griffith and Rosanne Cash. ``Everybody who hears it
gets it right away. The first time I heard it I thought, wow, this
is a hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottwin likens the tune's appeal ``to a great Don Henley song,
like 'Boys of Summer,' or a 'Memphis' from Mark Cohn.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 99X launched the song into heavy rotation, it's rippled
onto about six other playlists, including that of Q101 in Chicago.
A remixed version of ``Lullaby'' is being aggressively promoted to
alternative rock stations nationwide, with a slightly revised
version of ``Soul's Core'' to be rush-released Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   The rock'n'roll domino effect is a tribute to synchronicity:
right song, right place, right time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the whole reason I got into radio in the first
place,'' says Leslie Fram, the program director of 99X whose ears
are becoming increasingly influential. ``You hear something
terrific and want to share it with the listeners.'' Fram heard
``Lullaby'' after Mullins sent a copy of the song _ as he routinely
does with new material _ to Steve Craig, host of the station's
``Locals Only'' program, which features original music by Atlanta
and Athens-based acts. ``I was blown away,'' Fram continues. ``The
song begins with that sort of Lou Reed vocal/speak thing but then
the chorus hits you. It's amazingly hooky. Sometimes you just know
a hit record the first time you listen to it. I called Shawn into
my office and said: 'We're going to add `Lullaby' to our playlist.
Get ready because your life's going to change.' Immediately, we had
very strong phone calls on it. Everyone was asking, `who is
that?'''
</P>
<P>
   The station's clout is such that prominent new additions to its
playlist can establish a chain reaction. ``We're in a cycle right
now where radio is all powerful,'' says Russell Carter, the Decatur
manager of Atlanta's most successful folk-pop act, Indigo Girls,
who has signed on to help direct Mullins' career. ``It's highly
unusual for a seasoned singer-songwriter as talented as Shawn to
all of a sudden have a pop hit, prior to being signed to a label.
That's why everyone descended on Atlanta within a week's notice.''
</P>
<P>
   What they found is what local audiences have enjoyed for a
decade. ``He has such a good rapport,'' says Eddie Owen, owner of
Eddie's Attic and former manager of the Trackside Tavern,
epicenters of the acoustic scene that propelled the Indigo Girls to
fame in the late '80s. ``He's a real personable onstage kind of
guy, and he's always aw-shuckin' 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Mullins, who lives in Ormewood Park with his girlfriend and
business partner, Kelly Hobbs, and his beagle, Roadie, grew up in
Decatur as the youngest of three siblings, and attended Clarkston
High School. Both his father, John Mullins, and grandfather, Layton
Mullins, worked for the old Southern Railway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure I heard a lot of train stories,'' he says, while
noting that he was more directly influenced by Joni Mitchell,
</P>
<P>
   Kris Kristofferson and Isaac Hayes. ``I played street hockey and
ran track. I played Little League football, but I didn't really do
too well. I always went back to my room and played guitar. I always
prefered that to rolling around with a bunch of guys, bumping my
head.''
</P>
<P>
   Makes sense, though Mullins couldn't know then that his early
focus on making music would pay off so handsomely.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a phenomenal deal,'' Mullins says of his freshly inked
contract, which allows him to keep rights to his back catalog --
eight albums in all -- and provides for tour support, among other
``must-haves'' the singer wrote down on a piece of scratch paper
before he began meeting with label honchos.
</P>
<P>
   It's a phenomenal enough deal that no one's mentioning specific
sums. ``He has enough money to buy a new guitar,'' allows Bottwin,
``but he might not be able to buy a tour bus.''
</P>
<P>
   And, for certain, he won't need to sell CDs out of his car trunk
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stopped shopping myself to record companies five years
ago,'' he says. ``I used to try every year, and get rejection
letter after rejection letter. I thought, 'Damn, what am I doing
with my life?' But I hit the road really hard and kept making
records and it paid off. My change of focus was a reason why these
people were interested. Once they got me and I sat in front of them
with a guitar, they went `Oh!'''
</P>
<P>
   _Contributing: Richard L. Eldredge, c. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   H
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
