</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980810.0269 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6806 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWSSTAND11-COX     08-10 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vanity Fair offers `Full' look at Tom Wolfe
 &HT;    By Don O'Braint
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The jury is still out on what Tina Brown's departure will mean
for The New Yorker, but obviously her absence hasn't hurt Vanity
Fair ($3.50). The September issue is one of the best ever, with a
profile of Tom Wolfe, a dissection of Laura Schlessinger and a
juicy excerpt from Joyce Maynard's soon-to-be-published memoir of
her teenage affair with the reclusive J.D. Salinger.
</P>
<P>
   In his first interview about ``A Man in Full,'' Wolfe talks
about the evolution of his 750-page novel and his determination to
make it bigger than ``The Bonfire of the Vanities.'' Wolfe got the
idea for the story on a 1989 visit to some South Georgia
plantations with Atlantans Mack and Mary Rose Taylor. Originally,
the novel was to be set in New York, with protagonist Charlie
Croker traveling to Georgia on weekends. When Wolfe realized it was
beginning to read like another variation on ``Bonfire,'' he shifted
the scene to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Contributing editor David Kamp, one of a handful of people to
see the almost-finished manuscript, reports that the novel is told
from five narrative points of view and centers on Croker, a
real-estate developer and former Georgia Tech football hero who
finds himself $1.3 billion in debt and in danger of losing his
29,000-acre plantation. Other narrators are Roger White, a black
lawyer who defends Fareek Fanon, a football star accused of raping
the daughter of a prominent white Atlanta businessman; Conrad
Hensley, an employee at Croker Global Foods in Oakland, Calif.;
Raymond Peepgass, a loan officer at Croker's bank; and Martha
Croker, Charlie Croker's middle-aged first wife. After being
granted an exclusive interview by Wolfe's publisher Farrar, Straus
&AMP; Giroux, Kamp shamelessly proclaims ``A Man in Full'' as ``a
better novel than its predecessor.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the magazine, Leslie Bennetts dishes up a
deliciously malicious look at the darker side of Dr. Laura.
According to Bennetts, the holier-than-thou radio shrink hasn't
spoken to her mother in years, has a sister she never mentions,
prefers to ignore her first marriage and slept her way to the top.
</P>
<P>
   And, finally, Joyce Maynard reveals just how weird Salinger is
in a memoir about her affair with the reclusive author 26 years
ago, when she was 18 and he was 53. Obsessed with privacy even
then, the cranky author preferred a diet of raw food, practiced
bulimia after eating pizzas and refused to publish anything after a
certain point because he couldn't stand for his characters to be
criticized. One redeeming quality: He loved ``The Andy Griffith
Show.''
</P>
<P>
   GAY THERAPY: The ads are appearing more frequently in major
newspapers promising hope for homosexuals who want to convert to
the straight and narrow. In a fascinating cover story, Newsweek
($2.95) looks at the controversial Transformation Ministries and
other conservative groups who believe that gays can change through
willpower and therapy.
</P>
<P>
   NOT WASTING AWAY: Jimmy Buffett had just one Top 10 single,
``Margaritaville,'' and that was 21 years ago. But that hasn't
stopped hundreds of his fans from flocking to his concerts. Time
($2.95) visits the laid-back entertainer at midlife to learn why
fanatic Parrotheads spend more than $50 million a year on tickets,
albums and merchandise (including margarita mix and salt shakers).
The answer: ``He's like an old friend,'' says one supporter. ``No
surprises.''
</P>
<P>
   QUICK READS: If Judith Rich Harris' radical new theory catches
on, we won't be able to blame our parents for the way we've turned
out. In a New Yorker ($3) interview, the New Jersey grandmother
talks about her book, ``The Nurture Assumption,'' which
persuasively assaults conventional ideas of child development.
Peers, not parents, mold children's personality, she says. And lots
of experts agree. ... Just when the controversy over the Modern
Library's 100 best English language novels of the century is
waning, along comes Entertainment Weekly ($2.95) with its list of
all-time greatest lists. Ranked right after ``People's 50 Most
Beautiful People'' are The Ten Commandments and Luther's 95 Theses;
``50 Ways to Leave Your Lover'' weighs in at No. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
