<DOCNO> NYT19980810.0271 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6808 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEN-RISKS-COX     08-10 0465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEN-RISKS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Three day conference to discuss teen risk health behaviors
 &HT;    By J. Matthew Aldag
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Car crashes. Murder. Suicide. Teens are still dying
from them. Tobacco. Drugs. Unprotected sex. Teens are still doing
them.
</P>
<P>
   Experts from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention have
become concerned with the death rates of teenagers and the habits
they pick up that may be fatal in adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our young people are not nearly as healthy'' as teens in other
areas of the world, said Dr. Lloyd Kolbe, the CDC's director of the
Division of Adolescent and School Health. Kolbe is concerned with
nationwide health efforts that have been unsuccessful in lowering
death rates for those 10 to 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have successfully attained the mortality reduction goals
for every age group except for adolescents and young adults,'' said
Kolbe.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that teen national health objectives for 1990 still
have not been obtained in 1995, leaving grim predictions for the
future.
</P>
<P>
   That problem and others will be discussed when more than 130
experts from across the nation speak at this week's National
Leadership Conference to Strengthen HIV/AIDS Education and
Coordinated School Health Programs. Over 600 health workers are
expected to convene over the next three days at the Omni Hotel
downtown to attend presentations and discuss how to educate teens
about high-risk behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Studies show that the teenagers and young adults are killed most
often by car accidents, followed by homicide and suicide. CDC
experts are concerned not only with what kills people while they
are teens, but the habits they pick up that can be fatal later in
life _ drugs, alcohol abuse, poor diet, obesity, lack of exercise,
and high-risk sexual behavior that can lead to acquiring the AIDS
virus.
</P>
<P>
   Adults 25 years of age and older die most often from
cardiovascular disease and cancer, frequently the result of habits
learned in childhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to try to understand how we could explain the
problem better to people,'' said Kolbe.
</P>
<P>
   CDC experts hope to increase teen awareness through education,
media influence and parental awareness.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kind of problems aren't going to be fixed by medicine.
Getting the nations schools together with the nations state and
local health departments and having them work together is what is
necessary,'' said Kolbe.
</P>
<P>
   In a 50-nation study of mortality rates, the United States
ranked 31st for teen males and 22nd for females. Fatality rates for
U.S. male teenagers were more than twice the top-rated Sweden; U.S.
female fatality rates were 2 1/2 times those of the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
