   CLINTON-PRESIDENCY (Washington) -- President Clinton's fight
with the independent counsel has made the White House a lonely
place. He has to be careful whom he talks to these days and what
confidences he divulges. The presidency Bill Clinton is living in
is not the one he sought in 1992. By Ann Scales. 1500 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PHILOSOPHY-CRITIQUE (Boston) -- The world's largest gathering of
philosophers, meeting in Boston, turns its attention to truth and
meaning in today's technological society, and away from linguistic
debate. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   MA-LEGISLATE (Boston) -- Acting Gov. Paul Cellucci signs a $50
million tax cut for the insurance industry and vetos $290 million
in proposed spending. By Scott Lehigh. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   COYOTE-ATTACK (Boston) -- Officials are stumped in trying to
explain why a coyote attacked a toddler on Cape Cod, the first
documented attack in Massachusetts and possibly on the East Coast.
By Bruce Mohl. 600 words.
</P>
<P>
   VIKING-TRIP (Undated) -- W. Hodding Carter and his nine-man
crew, attempting to recreate Leif Ericsson's voyage, have nearly
completed the crossing of the Davis Strait and were expected to
reach Baffin Island. By Lois Shea. 500 words.
</P>
