<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6817 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRAFFITI1-AZR &LR;      08-10 1840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAFFITI1-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARD WORK, AD-LIB GEMS MADE `AMERICAN GRAFFITI' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVE WALKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS _ Where were you in '72? The cast and crew of
``American Graffiti'' were in northern California, shooting a
nostalgic little movie that would make history.
</P>
<P>
   The 1973 release _ its poster pitch line: ``Where were you in
'62?'' _ may be most notable as the project director George Lucas
did before ``Star Wars,'' but it got five Academy Award nominations
(including Best Picture), generated a superb soundtrack album,
introduced to the world a dazzling cast of young actors and may be
the most profitable movie ever made. Shot on a budget of $700,000,
it has generated total profits exceeding $50 million, which, in
today's movie-industry dollars, equals more than $1 bazillion.
</P>
<P>
   To read the old reviews, ``American Graffiti'' was mostly about
the loss of ``innocence,'' a cultural state of being so foreign now
as to be nearly mythical. To see it again is to remember that it
was also about the endless allure of cool American muscle cars, the
one-time omnipresence of Top 40 radio and that unobtainable blonde
in the fine, white T-bird.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, a 25th anniversary video and DVD release will offer
fans an opportunity to revisit Mel's Diner and its habitues. Some
of them, including Lucas, participated in a recent celebration of
the film sponsored by the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and
Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   The event was a sellout, and a long line for standby tickets
wrapped around one side of the Academy's Wilshire Boulevard
headquarters. Inside, a pristine print of the film was screened,
then Lucas and his cast had a panel discussion, moderated by critic
Leonard Maltin.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Dreyfuss, Harrison Ford, Ron Howard and Suzanne Somers _
the movie's actors who achieved the greatest fame _ weren't
present, though a host joked that Somers, who played that elusive
blonde, might occasionally be spotted peeking out of the projection
booth.
</P>
<P>
   Through one long last night of summer, ``American Graffiti''
told the story of friends ``on the verge of adulthood, about to
leave a special time,'' Maltin said. Lots of coming-of-age movies
came before, he continued, and a lot have come since.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Graffiti'' is the only film of all of them that
really went beneath the surface and caught something about what it
was really like.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Young filmmaker rules &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   George Lucas spent the summer of '62 recovering from an auto
accident. A high school senior in Modesto, Calif., he was an
underachieving car nut who miraculously survived a two-car crash
that totaled his Fiat Bianchina.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years later, he had emerged from the University of Southern
California film school as a promising young writer and director,
and had already made his first feature, ``THX 1138.'' Lucas had
also alreadyapprenticed under and partnered with Francis Ford
Coppola, who had just released his masterwork, ``The Godfather.''
</P>
<P>
   Coppola signed on to produce his buddy's next project _
described by Lucas as his ``rock `n' roll movie'' _ and proved most
valuable running interference between Lucas and Universal, the
sponsoring studio. (Maybe the music wasn't always so great in the
1970s, but young American filmmakers ruled the world.)
</P>
<P>
   Lucas' script (refined by Willard Huyck and Gloria Katz) spun
the stories of four main characters into one seamless saga. The
four were the brainy future writer Curt (played by Dreyfuss),
clean-cut future insurance salesman Steve (Howard), aging
hot-rodder John (Paul Le Mat) and the lovable geek Terry ``The
Toad'' (Charles Martin Smith).
</P>
<P>
   Embedded in Lucas' main plot _ would Curt depart for college the
next morning with his pal Steve? _ were smaller lines coupling
members of the quartet with ominous characters like rival
hot-rodder Bob Falfa (Ford), greasy gang leader Joe (Bo Hopkins)
and some indelible females, including Steve's girlfriend Laurie
(Cindy Williams), morally flexible Debbie (Candy Clark) and kid
nuisance Carol (Mackenzie Phillips).
</P>
<P>
   Above it all howled Wolfman Jack, the fabled Mexican-radio disc
jockey, playing a non-stop soundtrack of songs from the '50s and
early '60s. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Casting trials  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Casting the film was ``agony'' for Lucas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat in a little room and talked to people for five minutes
all day long, eight hours a day, for six months,'' he said. ``I
talked to every young person, I think, in Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, most of the cast wasn't picked from those cattle-call
tryouts.
</P>
<P>
   A casting director spotted Phillips, the then-12-year-old
daughter of John Phillips of the Mamas and Papas, singing with her
teen band at the famed Troubadour nightclub in Hollywood. ``I was
this rock chick in my mind,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Clark first met Lucas at one of the five-minute interviews, but
she showed up in a '50s costume and feared she'd blown her chance.
After seeing the script a few weeks later she begged for a second
chance, and eventually got to shoot a screen test, on a wooden park
bench simulating the front seat of a car, with Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I'd never get it,'' she said. ``I was taller than
Charlie.''
</P>
<P>
   Much later, Clark asked Lucas about the screen test (several of
the cast's tests will be included in a 25th anniversary DVD edition
of the film, which has a new, two-hour making-of documentary).
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Well, it came out black,' '' Clark said. ``I said,
`Why'd you hire me?' Then he said, `I liked what I saw through the
viewfinder.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams read the script and ``begged George to give me either
Mackenzie's part or Candy's part,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Then 25, Williams screen-tested for the Laurie role with
``Ronny, as we called him until just a little while ago. And my
first thought was _ I loved Ronny, but _ `Oh my God, I'm going to
be kissing Opie.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, still an acting student at California State-Northridge,
had been in England during primary casting, but was spotted by
Lucas on the MGM studio lot just a few days before final screen
tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``George walked by, looked at me and said, `Are you an actor
person?' '' Smith said. ``I read the script and thought, `This is
really good writing. Nobody may notice it, but this could be really
good.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Quinlan, who played the small part of Peg (Laurie's
ladies' room confidant), was actually a student at the Petaluma,
Calif., high school where those scenes were shot, and was
discovered in a cattle-call audition for extras.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can watch that film and I can look in that gym where the
sock hop is and I can see my ex-gymnastics teammates,'' said
Quinlan, who would one day be nominated for a supporting actress
Oscar for ``Apollo 13,'' directed by Ron Howard. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Month of all-nighters &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Filming ``American Graffiti'' proved no easier than casting it.
The limited budget allowed just 28 shooting days. Or, rather,
nights. The dusk-to-dawn story called for a month of all-nighters.
``I was tired most of the time,'' said Lucas, who often nodded off
during scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Filming in darkness was also a huge technical challenge. Advance
location scouts actually walked the streets of northern California
towns holding light meters to test the illumination provided by
street lamps. Lucas recalled that San Rafael, where the production
was based for the first few nights of the shoot, was much brighter
than Petaluma, where most of the filming occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Hair, and the special effects required to achieve the film's
greasy, pre-Beatles look, was obviously a preoccupation. ``They put
so much of that stuff in my hair, a fly just slid right off,''
Hopkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he was ``horrified'' by his greaser-geek hairstyle.
``George had to give me lessons on how to comb it. When I said, `My
hands are all greasy,' George said, `Wipe `em on your jeans, that's
what they're for.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing I remember is how hard the actors worked,'' said
Smith. ``We took this movie really seriously. We'd sleep until 2 in
the afternoon, have something that resembled breakfast in the
Holiday Inn there, and then we'd all go to one room or another and
rehearse. We thought the movie had a chance to be good, and we
worked hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``These scenes are a combination of that and mistakes, all of
which George put in the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   One such scene was Ford's impromptu rendition of ``Some
Enchanted Evening.'' Snipped from the original release, the scene
was later restored by Lucas, who admitted to nodding off during the
scene. Another unscripted gem was a Dreyfuss contribution: Curt's
wistful attempt to remember the combination of his old school
locker.
</P>
<P>
   Smith recalled a spontaneous keeper from the drag-race scene, as
the Toad and John walk away from the crash. Lucas surprised the
actors by having them shoot the scene before they'd had a chance to
rehearse, or even fully learn their lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul and I did some acting-school improvisation,'' Smith said.
``One thing I could remember was that I had a line that had the
word `wheelchair' in it, but I couldn't remember the whole line. As
I'm walking back, I say, `The guy should get in a wheelchair and
roll home.' And I'm thinking, `What was that?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to George afterwards, and said, `I really screwed that
up.' And he said, `Oh, no! It was great!' And it was.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Studio haggling  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not everybody was convinced of the film's potential.
``I remember flying home on weekends and rehearsing with Burt
Reynolds, who was doing ``White Lightning,'''said Hopkins. ``And I
thought that was going to be the biggie.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas said Universal's executives at first thought ``American
Graffiti'' was ``unfit'' to release. Two legendarily successful
test screenings failed to fully win over the studio, which, Lucas
said, at one point proposed converting it to a TV movie.
</P>
<P>
   The director and the studio haggled for months over a
meaningless five-minute trim in the running time. (The film had
already been cut from a ``great'' three hours to less than two,
Lucas said. After ``Star Wars'' made Lucas one of the most powerful
figures in entertainment history, those five minutes were restored
and`` American Graffiti'' was re-released.)
</P>
<P>
   Phillips was at boarding school when ``American Graffiti'' was
first released. She returned in time to see it play in a theater
and quickly became one of its biggest fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went almost daily and I brought all my little friends with
me,'' said Phillips, who later struggled with well-publicized
substance-abuse problems. ``It opened a million doors for me, which
I promptly closed all by myself.''
</P>
<P>
   For many in the cast, the recent Academy screening was the first
time they'd seen the film in years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as beautiful as I always remembered it,'' Williams said.
``I feel delighted and blessed that I'm a part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I remembered it was funny,'' said Le Mat. ``I remembered it
evoked this era, caught what it was like back then. But I had
forgotten how touching it was. Very touching.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
