<HEADLINE>
MODERN VIKING SAILORS APPROACHING BAFFIN ISLAND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Viking-Row)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOIS R. SHEA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The most treacherous part of the journey is nearly over.
</P>
<P>
   W. Hodding Carter and his nine-man crew, who are making a second
attempt to recreate Leif Ericsson's voyage to the New World, have
nearly completed the crossing of the Davis Strait. They were
expected to reach Baffin Island Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Sailing in the Snorri, a 54-foot replica of a knarr, or Viking
ship, Carter and crew began the crossing eight days ago.
</P>
<P>
   The crossing, over 200 miles of open ocean, is the most
dangerous leg of the 1,500-mile voyage to Newfoundland from
Greenland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, now that I've been doing this for four days, that
crossing the Davis Strait in an open boat is a crazy thing,''
Carter said by e-mail on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, in attempting to make the same journey, the Snorri
lost a rudder in the middle of the Davis Strait and had to be towed
back to Greenland.
</P>
<P>
   The Maine-built Snorri is an open boat, powered only by oars and
a sail. It has no shelter below decks; crew members sleep under
tarps on deck. The boat is equipped with radios, a compass, a
global positioning system unit, and a laptop computer. Otherwise,
conditions on board closely mimic those of an actual Viking ship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a huge range of conditions,'' said Carter, a
writer-adventurer from West Virginia and son of former State
Department spokesman Hodding Carter. ``Strong winds from the south,
strong winds from the north. Huge swells _ huge in an open boat at
least, because they were eight to 12 feet high and would send waves
of water right over the bow watch at 2 in morning _ my least
favorite job.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter said his crew is ``holding up well, sleeping in shifts in
our little underway tarp. It's a little ripe in there from all the
spray and rain and sweat, but we barely notice it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Snorri left Nuuk, Greenland, on June 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're much closer'' to completing the voyage, ``and we seem to
be able to make tiny repairs as needed,'' Carter said. ``I don't
know what will happen, but I have complete confidence in our boat,
our captain, and our crew. This is a great experience, and it makes
the Viking accomplishments so much clearer and incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter and his crew hope to reach L'Anse aux Meadows,
Newfoundland _ identified as an early Viking settlement _ by
mid-September.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
