<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6821 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN     08-10 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORE CONDITIONS LEAVE WORKER HOT UNDER COLLAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Ken Lloyd _ a specialist in organizational behavior _ is a
columnist for the Los Angeles Daily News. His column moves Mondays
in the ``f'' financial news file. Send your questions to P.O. Box
260057, Encino, Calif. 91426 or by electronic mail to
LloydOnJobaol.com. Names will be withheld upon request.) 
By KEN LLOYD  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I work at a large department store where men are required to
wear sport coats or suits. The store gets extremely hot in places,
and I am not the only one complaining. Even the customers complain.
Management does not enforce the same rules for the women, and they
are allowed to wear nonbusiness attire such as dresses, short
skirts and open-toed shoes. What if I refuse to wear a jacket?
I.D. &QL; 
A. Unless you are looking for a heated confrontation with
management, your first option should not be to refuse to wear a
jacket. In addition, there are many who would dispute your point
about dresses and short skirts not being business attire, so that
too is not an avenue you should pursue.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than seeing this as a problem, you should view it as an
opportunity. You should meet with management and present some
suggestions to deal with a source of dissatisfaction for a number
of employees and customers.
</P>
<P>
   Let management know that you and several of your associates
believe there is something wrong with the ventilation or air
conditioning, at least in your area of the store. Give specific
examples of the difficulties that this is causing, and then
indicate that you would like to be part of any plan to investigate
and correct this situation.
</P>
<P>
   It is safe to assume that all of your customers are not wearing
coats and ties, but many are still complaining about the heat. In a
word, it is the environment, not the dress code, that is causing so
many people to get hot and bothered. &QL; 
Q. In a meeting with my manager yesterday, he told me that he does
not think I have what it takes to be a good leader. Granted, I
haven't had much leadership experience, but I resent his comment
and I am not sure what to do from here. L.J. &QL; 
A. The more accurate message from your manager is that he does not
have what it takes to be a good leader. No good leader would make
that kind of comment.
</P>
<P>
   The most effective managers understand the importance of
coaching, guiding, and developing their employees. Such managers
work with their employees to establish realistic yet challenging
goals, and they provide their employees with constructive feedback
and numerous opportunities for two-way communication. None of this
sounds like your manager.
</P>
<P>
   The larger problem is that your manager has established an
expectation that you will not succeed as a leader, and this can
cause him to act in ways that fulfill this prophesy.
</P>
<P>
   If your objective is to move into management, it will be
important for you to develop your leadership skills, no matter who
your manager may be. In this regard, you should consider taking
classes and seminars, as well as participating in projects or
programs that place you in leadership roles, whether on the job or
in your community.
</P>
<P>
   There is no point in telling your manager right now that you
have what it takes to be a leader. Get some leadership expertise
and experience and let them do the talking. &QL; 
Q. I have an employee who always blames others for his mistakes. As
far as he is concerned, he is never at fault. How do you deal with
this type of person? S.D. &QL; 
A. For any number of reasons, this employee attaches grave
consequences to anything resembling a failure, and when one occurs,
he puts up his psychological deflector shield up so that the blame
will be bounced onto someone else. He has probably been allowed to
get away with this behavior for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does this behavior create problems for you as his
manager, and for whomever ultimately receives the blame that he has
deflected, it is also a problem for him. By denying responsibility
for his own failures, he is also denying himself the opportunity to
learn and grow from them. And, this means that he is destined to
repeat them.
</P>
<P>
   In order to deal with this behavior, one approach is for you to
work more closely with him, giving him appropriate feedback and
guidance to hopefully reduce the number of mistakes in the first
place. And, when he does make a mistake, give him some specific
feedback that identifies his behaviors that caused the error,
followed by some direction as to how the error could have been
prevented.
</P>
<P>
   Let him see that when errors are made, the key point is not
focused on blame. Rather, it is to try to identify what may have
caused the mistake, how to learn from it, and how to establish a
strategy to prevent it from occurring again.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &UR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
