<HEADLINE>
`AMERICAN GRAFFITI' SOUNDTRACK PUT THE WRITING ON THE WALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVE WALKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS - Once, a full soundtrack made entirely of pop
hits was unthinkable. But to George Lucas, who had written the
original draft of the ``American Graffiti'' screenplay by matching
scenes to specific songs from his personal record collection, the
story couldn't be told any other way.
</P>
<P>
   Music licensing ultimately ate more than 10 percent of the
film's already-tiny budget.
</P>
<P>
   During the recent Motion Picture Academy panel, Lucas said a
music official at Universal once suggested saving on licensing fees
by having an orchestra re-record the original records Lucas had
suggested. He also noted that no Elvis tunes made the soundtrack
because his record company, RCA, wouldn't cut a deal.
</P>
<P>
   According to Geoff Mayfield, director of music charts for
``Billboard'' magazine, the ``American Graffiti'' two-LP soundtrack
went triple platinum (more than 3 million sold) and spawned two
sequels. The or iginal stayed on the ``Billboard'' album charts for
60 weeks, peaking at No. 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been bigger soundtracks,'' Mayfield said. ``But
this is not an embarrassing thing, to have these old '50s hits
chart well in '73.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, before ``American Graffiti,'' film soundtracks
generally didn't sell in such numbers.
</P>
<P>
   According to the sales charts compiled by author Joel Whitburn
in the book ``Top Pop Albums 1955-1996,'' the only smash
soundtracks to predate ``American Graffiti'' were from movies based
on Broadway shows (such as ``Oklahoma!'' and ``West Side Story``)
and the score for Franco Zeffirelli's ``Romeo and Juliet.``
</P>
<P>
   Albums taken from movies starring the Beatles did pretty well,
too, but ``American Graffiti'' pioneered the
soundtrack-as-ancillary-product concept later exploited for films
like ``Saturday Night Fever,`` ``Urban Cowboy,`` ``Flashdance'' and
``The Bodyguard.` ` &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
