<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S TV PRODUCER FRIEND TO TESTIFY IN FRONT OF GRAND JURY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Less that a week before President Clinton is to
tell a grand jury about his relationship with a former White House
intern, prosecutors prepared to question a presidential friend,
television producer Harry Thomason.
</P>
<P>
   Thomason was scheduled to appear Tuesday at the U.S. District
Courthouse where independent counsel Kenneth Starr is overseeing
the grand jury inquiry into whether the president tried illegally
to cover-up an alleged extra-marital affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The 57-year-old sit-com producer is an Arkansas native who
befriended Clinton earlier in his political career. In January,
Thomason was summoned by first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton to help
advise the president shortly after Starr launched his investigation
and the public learned of the White House sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's team of prosecutors wants to question Thomason about any
private talks he had with Clinton concerning Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Thomason reportedly coached Clinton before he issued his
nationally televised, finger-wagging denial of a sexual affair with
Lewinsky on Jan. 26. In addition to spending the early days of the
scandal inquiry at the White House, Thomason and his wife, Linda
Bloodworth-Thomason, spent a long weekend in February with the
Clintons at Camp David, the presidential retreat.
</P>
<P>
   While in Washington to testify before Starr's grand jury, it was
uncertain whether Thomason would stay in town long enough to meet
with Clinton about the president's pending session with the panel
via closed-circuit television. The president, who has agreed to
answer prosecutor's questions Aug. 17, was scheduled to be in
California until early Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Lewinsky told the grand jury that contrary to sworn
denials in January by the president, her relationship with Clinton
involved a dozen sexual encounters at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying with an agreement that she would not be prosecuted
unless it was proved that she lied, Lewinsky also told grand jurors
that she and Clinton discussed ``cover stories'' or ways to conceal
their relationship, a legal source said. The discussions included
how to return gifts she had received from the president by routing
them through his personal secretary.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Thomason was linked to the firings in the White House
travel office. He had contacted the Clintons on behalf of a
Cincinnati-based consulting firm seeking a contract for some of the
travel business associated with the president's travels. Thomason
and his wife, who held a minority interest in the consulting firm,
were criticized for trying to use their White House contacts for
personal gain.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
