<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6838 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WAGE-REBATES-ART-2TAK     08-10 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAGE-REBATES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE STATES USING WAGE REBATES TO LURE COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Okla., Ohio, N.J., N.C., Maine, Md., Ky., Va., Calif.,
Conn.)  (ART ADV: A map showing the states that use wage rebates is being
sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since the 1950s, state governments have lured corporations with
expensive incentives such as free factories, canceled property
taxes, low-interest loans, free access roads and special tax
credits. Now in the 1990s, the competition among states and even
Mexico to attract companies has spawned a new incentive, one
strikingly uncharacteristic for a free-market economy: wage
rebates.
</P>
<P>
   Wage rebates allow companies to lower their labor costs through
taxpayer-financed subsidies. For each job created by a relocated or
existing company, a state reimburses the company for part of the
wages paid. These subsidies, offered by only eight states in 1989,
are now offered by 21 states, mostly in the South and Midwest,
according to the Council of State Governments, a research group
financed by the states.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Whirlpool, which opened a stove factory in Tulsa,
Okla., two years ago and hired more than 1,100 workers. For 10
years, it will get back 4.5 cents of every dollar paid in wages to
those workers.
</P>
<P>
   In all, nearly 1 million jobs appear to be covered by the
rebates, judging from the few states that report new jobs. In some
states, including Oklahoma and Ohio, the wage subsidy has become
the single most expensive corporate lure. It is costing Ohio
taxpayers more than $25 million a year. In other states, including
New Jersey, North Carolina and Maine, it is the fastest-growing
corporate incentive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wage rebates have become a very important modern-era incentive
for companies,'' said Joseph Kramer, vice president for economic
development of the Greater Cincinnati Chamber of Commerce. ``And
they are pay as you go, much more than other incentives. A company
does not get the rebate until after the new worker is actually on
the payroll.''
</P>
<P>
   When wage rebates began to spread in the mid-1990s, the
unemployment rate was higher than it is today, and states were
struggling to generate new jobs. Now, a robust economy is
generating millions of new jobs, pushing the unemployment rate to
its lowest level in decades. That is raising questions about the
value of taxpayer-financed wage rebates, which increasingly reward
companies for creating jobs they would have created anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real issue is whether, in a tight labor market, these
rebates have turned into a windfall for the companies,'' said Van
Doorn Ooms, research director of the Committee for Economic
Development, a research group supported by business. ``In a
high-unemployment situation, wage rebates are useful as a stimulus
for creating jobs. In a tight labor market, they are more likely to
simply pass on some of the cost of labor to the taxpayer from the
employer.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell Gold shares that view, although he does not put it that
bluntly. Mitchell Gold Co., which he owns, makes upholstered
furniture in Taylorsville, N.C. _ furniture sold through Pottery
Barn and Crate and Barrel stores. With business thriving, Gold
decided to expand a year ago. He looked into the incentives
available from North Carolina and found that his company qualified
for a wage rebate.
</P>
<P>
   So for the 80 workers being added to the company's 250-member
work force, Mitchell Gold will get back a portion of the state
income taxes withheld from each employee's check for four years.
The rebate is equal to roughly 2 percent of the typical worker's
annual pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly I would have stayed in North Carolina and expanded
without the wage rebate,'' Gold said, ``but in a competitive,
labor-intensive business, every little bit helps.''
</P>
<P>
   The subsidies are almost always restricted to manufacturers and
high-end service companies that bring ``good jobs'' to a state;
that is, jobs paying more than $7.50 an hour. The Oklahoma rebate
law, for example, applies only to jobs that pay at least $9 an hour
and carry health insurance benefits. Temporary workers are ruled
out. So are people who move to the state for the new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Such rules let the states alter the marketplace in a form of
industrial policy much criticized by those who advocate a reduced
role for government. ``We are becoming more regulated at the state
level even as we become less so at the federal level,'' said John
Bishop, a Cornell University labor economist.
</P>
<P>
   Mimicry plays a big role in the spread of wage subsidies. The
Maryland Legislature, for example, enacted a subsidy in 1996 and
expanded it last year to cover more industries because neighboring
Virginia had such a subsidy. Similarly, the Ohio Legislature
quickly followed Kentucky's lead in 1992, prodded by the Greater
Cincinnati Chamber of Commerce, which feared that companies would
choose to build in Cincinnati's suburbs on the Kentucky side of the
Ohio River.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio will soon have 100,000 jobs covered by wage rebates, state
officials say. And Kentucky is moving up quickly, having recently
agreed to rebate a portion of the wages for 6,000 jobs that United
Parcel Service is creating at a distribution hub being built in
Louisville. UPS officials have pointed to the wage credits,
totaling $3.5 million a year for 10 years, as a key reason for
choosing Kentucky for the new hub. And such thinking pops up
frequently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to have a wage-reimbursement program today is a terrible
thing,'' said Jerry Wade, a research economist at the Department of
Business and Economic Development in Maryland. ``When Virginia
adopted a wage subsidy next door, we found ourselves telling
companies that we would have one, too. The perception was that
Virginia, because of its subsidy, had a better overall business
climate than we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexico also looms in the equation. Oklahoma's subsidy, lowering
the cost of labor, led Whirlpool to put its stove factory in Tulsa
rather than in another state or in northern Mexico, where the
company already has factories.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``We had four states and Mexico under consideration, and
Oklahoma gave us the Quality Jobs Act,'' as the wage-rebate
legislation is known, said Thomas Vining, a Whirlpool vice
president. ``That incentive, along with another incentive, were the
tie-breakers.'' The second incentive was a diversion of the county
sales tax revenue for a year to pay for construction of the
Whirlpool factory.
</P>
<P>
   The wage reimbursements take several forms. Some states, like
Ohio, offer a credit against corporate income taxes, and if the
corporate tax is not sufficient, they send out checks to cover the
difference. Other states cap the reimbursement. The state income
tax provides the other most common way of handling the rebates. In
this version, states return to the company a portion of the taxes
withheld from qualified employees at the end of each year.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the mechanism, officials in states with the rebates
increasingly argue that they are the most efficient incentive in
creating jobs. Unlike the other incentives _ investment tax
credits, for example, or state-financed factory construction _ no
taxpayer money goes for wage rebates until the jobs exist. Even
then, the jobs must last for a certain number of years or the
companies must give back the rebates.
</P>
<P>
   In many states, a company must create 25 jobs a year to qualify
for a rebate. Maryland has set the minimum at 60, pointedly
undercutting the 100-job requirement in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We view wage reimbursement as revenue neutral,'' said Lisa
Cruz, spokeswoman for the Department of Commerce and Economic
Development in New Jersey, the only state in the New York
metropolitan area that has adopted the rebates. In the two years
since New Jersey began to provide rebates, some 30,000 new jobs
have qualified for the credit, which goes as high as $3,800 a year
for a single $75,000-a-year employee. ``These workers,'' Ms. Cruz
said, ``generate sales taxes and corporate income taxes that would
not otherwise have existed.''
</P>
<P>
   Such big corporations as Raytheon, Hewlett-Packard and
Bristol-Myers Squibb, having put new operations in New Jersey over
the last two years, are now receiving wage rebates for more than
1,700 of their employees, all of them earning the minimum of $7.73
an hour required by New Jersey law, or 150 percent of the federal
minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   Competition with nearby Maryland played a role in Gov. Christie
Whitman's decision to ask the Legislature for a wage rebate
program. ``Our strategy has been to tie state-funded incentives
directly to the creation of good jobs,'' said Gil Medina, secretary
of the Department of Commerce and Economic Development in New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Wage subsidies have existed for years in a different form, as
part of a social welfare program. In these programs, companies
receive wage rebates to create jobs in inner cities and other areas
of high unemployment or hire people on welfare, ex-felons and
others who have trouble finding work. More than 40 states offer
such wage rebates, usually in the form of a tax credit, as does the
federal government. The programs aim to help the disadvantaged, who
would otherwise not have jobs, even in tight labor markets.
</P>
<P>
   California, New York and Connecticut have such programs, arguing
in effect that taxpayer-financed wage subsidies should be aimed at
encouraging employment of the needy and not employment of people
who are already sufficiently skilled to be attractive to
corporations. The legislatures of these three states have never
enacted wage rebates for high-skilled, high-wage jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not had to take that step,'' said Chris Holben, an
under secretary of trade and commerce in California. ``Yes, we are
constantly told by companies considering California that other
states will give them a wage rebate, and why not us. We believe the
package of incentives that we do offer is sufficient. And we have a
strategic advantage: We serve the Pacific Rim and the Mexican
market.''
</P>
<P>
   At the national level, Congress enacted a broad wage rebate
program in 1976, like those now proliferating among the states. The
program was intended to stimulate job creation in the wake of the
mid-1970s recession. To qualify, a company had to increase its
employment by 2 percent in a single year. If it did, it received a
corporate income tax credit equal to half of the first $4,200 of
each new worker's wages.
</P>
<P>
   The program did generate jobs, according to a study done by
Bishop of Cornell. But it was phased out after two years as too
expensive, having cost $4.5 billion in 1978 alone.
</P>
<P>
   The wage rebates and all the other incentives used by states to
entice companies face a similar criticism today. ``We are funneling
tens of billions of dollars into shifting jobs from one state to
another,'' said Charles Horn, a Republican state senator in Ohio.
``That money should be going to schools and roads and other public
outlays that would make states truly more competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   The House of Representatives has before it a bill, introduced by
Rep. David Minge, D-Minn., that would force corporations to declare
as income all the state incentive payments they receive each year.
These would then be taxed at the federal level. Arthur Rolnick,
research director at the Federal Reserve Bank of Minneapolis,
supports the measure, and even goes a step further. He wants state
incentive payments outlawed as illegal obstacles to interstate
commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress has the authority,'' he said, ``under the commerce
clause of the Constitution to end this war between the states.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
