A6841 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLASSICAL-CEEDEES-NYT     08-10 0522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASSICAL-CEEDEES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S CHOICE: DIVIDED BY CENTURIES, UNITED IN FUN 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``John's Book of Alleged Dances,'' the name of the set of pieces
for string quartet on the latest album of music by John Adams
(Elektra Nonesuch 75455), could have been used as the title for
either of two new CDs as a whole. Adams' other piece, his clarinet
concerto ``Gnarly Buttons,'' is just as allegedly danceable, and no
doubt it will soon be danced in reality, just as the quartet book
has been taken up by the Paul Taylor Company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gnarly Buttons'' is thoroughly enjoyable and at the same time
shows its composer continuing to grow. Much of the first movement
is a wandering unison line, with the solo clarinet present most of
the way, joined in patches by members of the accompanying ensemble
on a deliberately disjointed, often countryish array of
instruments: two reeds, trombone, string quintet, banjo (doubling
on mandolin and guitar) and two samplers (alternating on pianos).
The line takes off from a hymn tune, and travels, fractal wise,
through figures that are always similar but never quite the same.
</P>
<P>
   The middle movement is a hoedown with one bellowing ``moo,'' a
reference to the troubles in British cattle farming at the time of
the first performance, which was given by Michael Collins and the
London Sinfonietta in October 1996. (This recording is by the same
musicians, with Collins a splendid soloist, engaging and athletic.)
Finally comes an adieu something like Chou's concluding song in
Adams' opera, ``Nixon in China,'' but with the tune going up into
the air near the end and waving its legs furiously.
</P>
<P>
   The quartet set, played by the Kronos Quartet, is a looser
collection with some cross-references to the later ``Gnarly
Buttons.'' For example, most of the pieces are again fractal-like
in the omnipresence of similarity without sameness: motifs are
rearranged, beats shift and seemingly repetitive patterns keep
shifting their ground. Also, the fourth alleged dance, ``Pavane:
She's So Fine,'' already knows about the hoedown theme.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Philippe Rameau is the other John, whose alleged dances, in
the spectacular new recording by Nicholas McGegan and his
Philharmonia Baroque Orchestra (Conifer 75605 51313), come from two
of his operas: ``Platee'' and ``Dardanus.'' Across the gap of a
quarter of a millennium there is a lot in common between the two
Johns. One shared trait is a love of vernacular music, whether
represented by hoedowns and ballads or drone-based musettes and
drum-accented tambourins. No doubt connected with this is a love,
too, of syncopation, the ``Passepieds'' from ``Platee'' being just
as exciting as what Adams gets up to. Above all, both composers are
evidently having fun.
</P>
<P>
   Of the two Rameau suites, the most extraordinary movements come
from ``Platee'' and include a dance with monotonous croaks (as of
frogs), an exciting storm scene and a number in which slow and fast
music go on at the same time. But everything sounds wonderful in
these whipcrack performances, full of color and nuance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
