<HEADLINE>
EMC ACQUIRES CONLEY CORP. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANN MULLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Underscoring its commitment to build a larger software business,
EMC Corp. has acquired Conley Corp., a small software firm.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, while valued at less than $50 million, is of strategic
importance to EMC as it seeks to expand its lead in the market for
giant computer storage networks that help companies manage huge
volumes of information.
</P>
<P>
   EMC's sales and profits have been growing more than 30 percent a
year, partly because of the rapid growth of its software business.
EMC has developed nearly a dozen value-added software programs as a
way to stay ahead of competitors in the storage equipment business
such as IBM and Hitachi.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, EMC's software sales more than doubled to $177
million and software revenue is expected to hit $400 million this
year, making making EMC one of the fastest-growing major software
companies in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Conley's Cambridge, Mass. operations, which employ about 50
workers, will be renamed the EMC Cambridge Software Development
Center, and will serve as a recruiting base for talented software
engineers who aren't interested in commuting to EMC's Hopkinton,
Mass. headquarters, said company spokesman Mark Fredrickson.
</P>
<P>
   Ric Calvillo, Conley's founder and president, will be general
manager of the new software development center, which will also
host other EMC software operations over time.
</P>
<P>
   Conley specializes in high-availability, high-performance
storage management software for UNIX, Windows NT and other
platforms. The two companies collaborated on the development of EMC
PowerPath software, which was introduced in February and has
quickly become the fastest-growing product in EMC's stable of
software programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``EMC and Conley share a common view of information-centric
computing, in which intelligent enterprise storage will continue to
play an increasingly strategic role for large organizations that
depend on information to run their businesses'' EMC's chief
executive, Michael C. Ruettgers, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, two other Conley executives, Jean Hamilton and Kuo
Hsieh, announced formation of a new company, Lexias Inc., based in
New York. Lexias will provide ongoing sales, support and service
for current Conley storage customers, and will also expand its
scope beyond data protection to encompass such emerging markets as
Internet security.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
