<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-REPUBS-685&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTY INFIGHTING HOBBLING REPUBLICAN EFFORTS IN CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans in Congress left for their summer
vacation last week deeply divided, fighting themselves as hard as
they fought Democrats, and unable to fill the policy vacuum left by
the hobbled Clinton presidency.
</P>
<P>
   With only one month left in the Congressional session before
mid-term elections that could decide control of the House,
Republicans in both Houses have been unable to agree on a budget.
They are squabbling over tax cuts. They have yet to send the White
House even one of the 13 spending bills needed to keep the
government running when the new fiscal year begins in October.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans now say they may not move forward with their
own scaled-back antismoking bill, which they promised when the
Senate legislation to regulate tobacco died. ``Trying to craft a
bill that will garner a majority has been elusive,'' said Rep. John
Boehner of Ohio, chairman of the House Republican Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Across the board, the divisions among social conservatives,
Republican moderates and the party's business wing have resulted in
high-profile broken promises and stalled spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   Even tax cuts no longer seem to be the unifying force they once
were for Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Speaker Newt Gingrich sent his rank and file home with
instructions to gin up a public outcry in August for a House
Republican plan to devote $700 billion of a projected $1.5 trillion
federal surplus over the next decade to tax cuts and dedicate the
remaining surplus to Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   But the tactic seemed as much about putting pressure on Senate
Republicans who balk at the proposal as it was about staking out
ground against the Democrats for the midterm election.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the American people learn about the size of the
surplus,'' Gingrich said on Friday, ``when the American people
learn about the power of economic growth to save Social Security,
when the American people learn about what we're proposing to do, I
am confident that by September you will see virtually all of the
senators on the Republican side in favor.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate leaders are adamantly opposed to tax cuts of such
magnitude this year, and since the first days of the 1995
Republican revolution, the Republican Senate has usually been wary
of the sweeping changes sought by the Republican House. Gingrich
has conceded to other House members that, partly because of this
stance, the House may end up getting only about $70 billion in tax
cuts this year.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the problems facing the Republicans are endemic to
Congressional parties without a president to articulate an
overarching message. Making matters worse for the Republicans is
Clinton's skill at stealing their rhetoric, leaving them flummoxed
with little to oppose. And not only do the Republicans lack one
dominant figure, their Congressional leadership is hampered by one
of the smallest House majorities this century.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans say the party lost the unifying ideas that
allowed the disparate elements of the Republican coalition to unite
in the past _ anticommunism and the battle to erase the federal
budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
   And so elements of the party check, or perhaps checkmate, each
other.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has stalled legislation sought by social
conservatives but opposed by business that would require sanctions
against nations that practice religious persecution.
</P>
<P>
   And despite Gingrich's pledge to business groups that he would
push in July for financing for the International Monetary Fund, the
House abruptly put the issue off until September, with Rep. Dick
Armey, R-Texas, Gingrich's second in command, leading the battle
against the money.
</P>
<P>
   In an odd pose for a party that once projected itself as
internationalist, Armey recently took pride in his lack of interest
in foreign travel. ``I've been to Europe once,'' he said. ``I don't
have to go again.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb., recently called the split between his
party's business and social conservative wings ``terribly
dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It could undermine our party,'' he said. ``It could defeat us
in 2000 if we don't put our party back together.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Democrats _ accusing the Republicans of running a
``do-nothing Congress'' _ are hoping the Republican infighting can
be turned to their advantage in their struggle to retake the House.
And they underscore the lack of action constantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a Bart Simpson Congress _ underachievers and proud of
it,'' House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt of Missouri said as
the House left for August. ``Instead of working to address the real
challenges, which most American families face, the Republicans
continue to run out the clock.''
</P>
<P>
   But voters, when asked which party they would prefer to lead
Congress, have put the two at a tie for months. And Democrats say
surveys earlier this year by two White House pollsters, Mark Penn
and Douglas Schoen, found that the public did not necessarily think
a do-nothing Congress was bad _ as long as the economy was good.
</P>
<P>
   So the Democrats are trying to highlight particular issues to
show voters what it means to them if Congress has a scaled-back
agenda. Their list of legislation left undone includes an
antitobacco measure, a bill regulating health maintenance
organizations, overhauling the campaign finance system and spending
increases for education programs.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, House Republicans and Democrats each seemed to be
spoiling for precisely the political confrontation that most scares
Senate Republicans _ a debate over whether the Republicans'
proposal for a large tax cut would risk the long-term health of
Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   That allows each party to play to its traditional strengths.
``We will fight together to make sure Republicans don't betray our
obligation to Social Security and the American people,'' Gephardt
said. ``If that's what they want to run on, that's good. Let's
engage.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich, anticipating the Democratic line of attack, said that
under current economic projections of the surplus, a tax cut of
$700 billion would still leave $761 billion over 11 years to be set
aside for Social Security. ``They want to keep all the money in
Washington, frankly, so they can spend it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The entire political mood could change in the fall, depending on
the investigation of Whitewater and Clinton's relationship with
Monica Lewinsky by Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel. That in
turn could have some effect on whether Clinton and the Congress
hurtle to another government shutdown instead of reaching an
agreement on tax cuts and spending.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans last week, after receiving a veto threat from the
White House on seven spending bills, preemptively began accusing
the administration of seeking such a confrontation as a diversion
from Clinton's troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich himself was cautious about predicting the session's
outcome. ``In my judgment,'' he said, ``we'll get something done
this fall unless the whole place melts down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-98 1855EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980810.0295 </DOCNO>
