<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE HOPES NEW BOGOTA GOVERNMENT WILL LEAD TO IMPROVED
RELATIONS  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By PHILIP SHENON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration says the inauguration of
President Andres Pastrana of Colombia should mean the end of years
of ill will between his nation and the United States, especially if
he moves quickly on a pledge to stem the flood of Colombian cocaine
into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana was sworn in on Friday, less than a week after
returning from Washington, where he met with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's decision to offer Pastrana a
pre-inauguration meeting at the White House was in stark contrast
to its treatment of his predecessor, Ernesto Samper, who was denied
a travel visa to the United States after evidence indicated that a
drug cartel had provided $6 million for his 1994 election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said that during his meeting with
Clinton, Pastrana, 43, a Conservative, had promised that he would
try to shut down drug trafficking operations in Colombia, which are
the source of most of the cocaine that ends up on American streets,
and to end a decades-old guerrilla war.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia, a country of 37 million, has been in the grip of an
armed insurgency for 30 years. In many areas leftist guerrillas
have allied themselves with drug traffickers, who underwrite their
purchase of weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana, a former television anchor who understands the value
of dramatic images, ventured into the Colombian jungle last month
to meet with the leaders of the largest insurgent group. He has
promised to begin formal peace talks in the first three months of
his administration.
</P>
<P>
   James Dobbins, senior director for inter-American affairs at the
National Security Council, said Clinton had ``expressed admiration
for the courage Pastrana had shown in his election and in his steps
immediately after the election.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials said they believed that by
tackling the insurgency, Pastrana might be able to curb the
narcotics trade.
</P>
<P>
   During his Oval Office meeting, Dobbins said, Pastrana said the
two problems were inextricably linked, since the drug cultivation
and trafficking generally took place in the areas where the
insurgency was most active.
</P>
<P>
   Dobbins said Clinton had told Pastrana that ``the United States
wanted to support an integrated approach to the problems of drug
trafficking and bringing peace, ending Colombia's civil conflict.''
Pastrana, he said, already accepted an invitation to return to
Washington in the fall for a state visit.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Pastrana replaced his top military commanders after a
series of embarrassing defeats in clashes with the guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration made Pastrana's job easier with its
decision earlier this year to lift economic sanctions that had been
imposed on Colombia for two years out of dissatisfaction with
Samper's drug policies. The lifting of the sanctions, Dobbins said,
offers ``both governments the opportunity for a new start.''
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana swept into office with the largest margin in his
country's history. A former senator and mayor of Bogota, the
Colombian capital, Pastrana will govern without a majority in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
