<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION NOTES AND NEWS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Frette to Wear &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Frette, the high-end Italian linen maker whose sheets
and pillowcases grace not only luxury homes but many of Europe's
top hotels, is introducing clothing. It's the reverse of the
increasingly common move of fashion designers into the home.
</P>
<P>
   Like almost every other global brand today, Frette sees an
opportunity to capitalize on its good name. ``The fact that women
have touched it, felt it, and the fact that you can take that same
feeling to clothing makes this a good opportunity,'' said Chris
Christiansen, the chief executive of Frette USA.
</P>
<P>
   The Frette Collection of lounge wear and sportswear will be
available in stores in spring 1999. The clothes, however, will not
necessarily be available in Frette's 43 stores worldwide, but the
apparel will be sold in department stores. ``To make the definitive
presentation, you really have to present all the different looks,''
Christiansen said. Many Frette stores, like the one in New York at
799 Madison Ave. (67th Street), are too small to do this.
</P>
<P>
   Six months ago, the company hired Brigitte Langevin, a former
fashion editor for French Glamour and more recently French Vogue,
as creative director. Ms. Langevin will oversee the creation of the
new collection.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Azria Backs Herve Leger &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fashion executives have bemoaned the dearth of
investors willing to back designers these days. The trend _
personified in Bernard Arnault, the chairman of LVMH Moet
Hennessy-Louis Vuitton _ is to buy established designers' talent to
breathe life into an existing brand.
</P>
<P>
   It took as unlikely a person as Max Azria, the chairman of BCBG
Max Azria in Los Angeles, to buck that trend by announcing Thursday
his agreement to purchase a majority interest in the company of
Herve Leger, the French designer whose bandage dresses can turn
hip-flask dimensions into Coca-Cola bottles.
</P>
<P>
   Azria, considered no friend of designers because he has copied
ideas from European lines and dared to bring his reasonably priced
stylish clothing to the tents of Bryant Park, may have the last
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   He has worked hard in the last year to prove he has his own
inspirations by giving a preview of his collection in New York
before the European shows. He will stage a small presentation in
New York during the week of Sept. 14, when Calvin Klein, Donna
Karan and Helmut Lang are showing their spring 1999 lines. A
second, larger show will still be held during American show week,
scheduled for Oct. 30 to Nov. 6.
</P>
<P>
   The sales of BCBG, a privately held company, have grown at an
astonishing rate, a projected $180 million by December, up from
$109 million in 1997, Azria said. Volume last year for Herve Leger
was close to $10 million, little of it in the United States, where
Azria plans to market the Leger collection most aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Crawford and Clarissa Bronfman, the wife of Edgar Bronfman
Jr., are among Leger's most prominent promoters. Bronfman is the
chief executive of the Seagram Company, which is selling Azria his
Leger stake.
</P>
<P>
   Leger's limited repertoire of bandage dresses has kept his
customer base narrow. Herve Leger boutiques and perhaps a secondary
collection will help expand sales, said Azria, who will own 95
percent of the company to Leger's 5 percent. This fall, Proctor &AMP;
Gamble is to market a Herve Leger fragrance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the way he looks at women,'' Azria said of Leger.
``It's very chic and elegant, yet sexy.''
</P>
<P>
   But sex was not on Azria's mind when he agreed to purchase the
company. Diversification was, he said. His business will now have
five divisions. In addition to Leger's and Azria's signature lines,
the others are Maxime, a line of traditional mid-price sportswear;
To the Max, a collection for juniors, and Parallel, contemporary
sportswear.
</P>
<P>
   Fashion designers and editors may have been perturbed about
Azria taking over the New York runways. Now, he will be on even
more sacred ground: the Paris catwalks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
