<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OCEAN-PEPSI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OCEAN SPRAY SUES PEPSI OVER TROPICANA DISTRIBUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ocean Spray Cranberries Inc., a cooperative of cranberry and
citrus growers, is seeking an injunction to block PepsiCo Inc. from
using its distribution channels to deliver Tropicana juices to
convenience stores.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Pepsi announced plans to acquire Tropicana from
Seagram Co. Ltd. for $3.3 billion, but Ocean Spray claims such a
deal would violate a contract under which Pepsi distributes
single-serve Ocean Spray juices and juice drinks to retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Under a contract that expires at the end of the year 2000, Pepsi
agreed that Ocean Spray would be the only line of single-serve
juice drinks it would distribute, Ocean Spray claims.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean Spray describes Tropicana as ``a primary competitor.''
Ocean Spray had sales of $1.44 billion last year; Tropicana had
sales of $1.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   If Pepsi were also to distribute Tropicana single-serve juices
following an acquisition, that would violate Pepsi's contract with
Ocean Spray and cause Ocean Spray ``irreparable harm,'' argues a
suit filed in US District Court in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsi disputed Ocean Spray's interpretation of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've said all along we're fully prepared to perform under our
distribution agreement so it's hard to understand the merits of a
lawsuit,'' said Pepsi spokesman Larry Jabbonsky.
</P>
<P>
   While the injunction that Ocean Spray seeks does not
specifically ask the court to block Pepsi's plan to buy Tropicana,
an injunction barring Pepsi from using its distribution network on
Tropicana's behalf would seem to undermine some of the business
rationale for the acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Ocean Spray and Pepsi entered an alliance that gave
each company something it didn't have. Ocean Spray got access to
Pepsi's fleet of delivery trucks, and Pepsi was able to offer
retailers a single-serve juice line.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen months ago, Pepsi said it wouldn't renew its agreement
with Ocean Spray, in part because it wanted to test-market a juice
line of its own.
</P>
<P>
   When that didn't work out, Pepsi said in March it would continue
to distribute Ocean Spray juices until the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement has been important to Ocean Spray. At a time when
the Lakevill, Mass. cooperative's annual sales have been roughly
flat, its $225 million single-serve category has been one of Ocean
Spray's fastest growing businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Pepsi announced plans to acquire Tropicana, a deal
that could give Pepsi the juice line it has wanted so long.
</P>
<P>
   One of the synergies from such a deal could be exploiting
Pepsi's distribution system on Tropicana's behalf, said Tony Vento,
an analyst with Edward Jones.
</P>
<P>
   How the lawsuit between Ocean Spray and Pepsi is resolved may
depend on the precise wording of the contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did Ocean Spray protect itself'' adequately against the
contingency of Pepsi acquiring an Ocean Spray rival? asked Robert
Berry, a professor at Boston College Law School.
</P>
<P>
   Given that Pepsi renewed its agreement with Ocean Spray only a
few months ago, one might assume that Pepsi's lawyers believe that
the Tropicana acquisition does not violate the distribution
agreement between Pepsi and Ocean Spray, Berry said.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, Pepsi shares fell 1 11/16 to
close at 35 13/16 .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
