<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, Aug. 16)  
 (JT)  
 By RAY CORMIER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Sacred Music Festivals &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How can I find out about two musical events next year _ the
Fez Festival of World Sacred Music in Morocco and the Sacred Voices
festival in London. _ Adolph Paul, Milwaukee
</P>
<P>
   A. The program for the fifth annual World Sacred Music Festival,
planned for May 29 to June 5, has not been set, but it will
presumably be similar in scope. The best source for information is
probably the official travel coordinator for the festival in the
United States, Sarah Tours, 1803 Belleview Boulevard, Alexandria,
Va. 22307; (800) 267-0036, fax (703) 765-7809; its site on the
Internet is www.morocco-fezfestival.com.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah has put together a festival tour leaving New York on May
27 and returning June 8. Besides attendance at festival events, the
tour includes visits to the Medina of Fez and Marrakesh, and
excursions to the hot springs of Moulay Yacob, the Sidi Ahmed al
Barnoussi shrine and to the Roman ruins at Volubilis. Prices, with
choices of three-, four- or five-star hotels, are $4,285 to $5,355
a person, double occupancy, including business-class air fare from
New York. Extensions to the Sahara or Spain are available.
</P>
<P>
   The 16th annual Music Village festival, scheduled for June 23 to
July 11, will have as its theme Sacred Voices, according to Carolyn
Axtell, administrative coordinator of Cultural Cooperation, the
group planning it. The full schedule is not yet ready, though some
events will be free, including open-air concerts in parks on
weekends, Ms. Axtell said. There will also be weekday concerts and
workshops.
</P>
<P>
   The festival expects to feature singers from around the world,
presenting music as diverse as that of Southern Baptists, Brazilian
Candomble believers, Tibetan Buddhists and Lebanese Maronites.
</P>
<P>
   For information, contact Cultural Cooperation, Toynbee Studios,
28 Commercial Street, London E1 6LS; (44-171) 247-8808, fax
(44-171) 247-8809.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A South Pacific Tour &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I plan to visit Australia and New Zealand for
three weeks. What are your suggestions to see and how to get
around? _ Bernard P. Gropp, Summit, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   A. Since Australia is about the size of the United States minus
Alaska, and New Zealand is bigger than all but a few states, there
are myriad choices. But Renata Gombac of the Australia Tourist
Commission and Clyde H. Farnsworth, a former Times correspondent
living in Australia, agreed on several must-sees. These include
Sydney, with its famed opera house and Harbour Bridge, the Great
Barrier Reef and rain forest in the northeast, and Ayers Rock, one
of the most sacred sites for Aborigines.
</P>
<P>
   They also differed somewhat. Ms. Gombac suggested an itinerary
would take you to New Zealand for a week and two weeks in
Australia, starting in Melbourne. From there, you would fly to the
Red Centre region for a taste of the Outback and a visit to Ayers
Rock. Then, it would be on to North Queensland for several days
around Palm Cove to visit the rain forest, the Undara Lava Tubes
and the reef. Finally, you would head for Sydney and its outlying
areas, like the Hunter Valley wine region or the Blue Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Such a tour would start at $3,875 a person in low season (April
to August) and about $500 more peak. It is available from Swain
Australia Tours, (800) 227-9246.
</P>
<P>
   Other places Farnsworth suggests are Alice Springs in the Red
Centre desert; Tasmania and its former penal colony at Port Arthur;
Adelaide, noted for its literary and music festivals, and rugged
Kangaroo Island, ``a microcosm of what Australia must have been
before the Europeans came.'' And he expresses a special fondness
for Perth and Fremantle, on the west coast.
</P>
<P>
   Train travel in Australia is quite good, but for long distances
you might want to get a Qantas Airways Boomerang Pass _ a minimum
of two vouchers for travel within or between three national zones
and New Zealand _ $175 within a zone, $220 between zones. The
airline says it saves money on flights of more than an hour, and
offers flexibility. The pass must be bought before getting to
Australia. Call (800) 227-4500 for details.
</P>
<P>
   Discussing New Zealand's North Island, Anna Sinnott, East Coast
manager of the New Zealand Tourism Board, suggested visiting
Auckland's wharf area, seeing the Maritime Museum and Kelly
Tarlton's Undersea World, and taking a Pride of Auckland cruise,
then going to Rotorua, the home of the Maori people, to see the
thermal springs and the Agridome, with its sheep shows.
</P>
<P>
   On the Alpine-like South Island, she recommended touring
Queenstown, taking a jet boat river ride, and visiting the
Fiordland, including an excursion to Milford Sound.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, contact the Australian Tourist Commission,
(805) 775-2000, fax (805) 775-4448, or at www.aussie.net.au/, and
the New Zealand Tourism Board, (800) 388-5494, fax (212) 832-7602,
or www.nztb.govt.nz/.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Side Trip to Majorca &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I will be going to Barcelona on business and I would like to
take a short trip afterward to Majorca. Can I arrange to get on a
small group tour? _ Linda E. Goodman, New York, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. Groups usually go to Majorca as part of broader tours,
according to Jordi Castello of the New York office of El Corte
Ingles Travel, a large Spanish agency. He does not know of a tour
specifically from Barcelona to Majorca.
</P>
<P>
   But Castello says a customized trip to Majorca is easily
arranged. His company can book the half-hour flight from Barcelona
to the island and a hotel, where you can buy single-day tours. You
could also rent a car and visit the pearl factories and island's
natural wonders, from the famed beaches to the surprisingly wild
northern Sierra.
</P>
<P>
   El Corte Ingles is at 500 Fifth Ave. (42d Street), Suite 1730,
New York, N.Y. 10110; (212) 944-9400, fax (212) 944-9827. For
general information, contact the Tourist Office of Spain, 666 Fifth
Ave., New York, NY 10103; 265-8822, fax (212) 265-8864.
</P>
<P>
