<SLUG> BC-AUTO-PRICES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD TO LOWER PRICES FOR 1999 CARS AND TRUCKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ll) 
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Ford Motor Co. announced on Monday that the average
price of its 1999 model cars and trucks would decrease three-tenths
of 1 percent, or about $61, from comparably equipped 1998 models.
Ford made significant decreases in the prices of its highest-volume
cars, the Ford Taurus and the Mercury Sable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, for the first time in over 30 years, we were able
to hold the line on prices,'' Lloyd Hansen, controller for Ford's
marketing and sales operations, said in an interview. ``This year
is the first time in over 30 years we've actually reduced prices.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 model year, which starts on Oct. 1, will mark the
second consecutive year that all major automakers hold the line on
prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen outright deflation in car prices over the last two
years,'' said William P. Wilson, vice president and economist for
Comerica Bank, Detroit. The bank's tracking of new-vehicle
transaction prices, the price for which vehicles actually sell,
show an eight-tenths of 1 percent drop this May compared with May
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said worldwide excess capacity in auto production had
created an extremely competitive environment in North America that
prevented automakers from increasing prices.
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler Corp. announced in July that its overall prices
remained essentially unchanged from 1998 prices, up 0.1 percent, or
about $35 a vehicle, due largely to regulatory emission costs.
Chrysler's 1998 prices remained virtually the same as those in
1997. Price increases in 1995 and 1996 were under 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors Corp. said its prices, only a few of which have
been announced, would be relatively flat. In June, the GM Saturn
division said its 1999 prices would include a price reduction on
its coupe. Saturn, which does not offer incentives and prohibits
price haggling in the showroom, reduced prices and added equipment
to some models last year as well.
</P>
<P>
   GM does not plan to announce an overall percentage of price
change, but will announce prices on individual 1999 models as they
are introduced.
</P>
<P>
   With a few exceptions, GM's 1999 models will not arrive in
dealerships for a couple months because of a 54-day strike by the
United Automobile Workers union at two parts plants that shut down
almost all of GM's North American assembly plants. Most plants are
back in full operation and will produce 1998 models through
September to use up the inventory of parts designed for those
vehicles before changing over to 1999 models.
</P>
<P>
   Import manufacturers typically announce prices in late summer or
early fall.
</P>
<P>
   At Ford, prices of cars dropped an average of 1.7 percent; truck
prices fell 0.5 percent. Prices of Ford-model cars and trucks
dipped 0.2 percent; prices of Lincoln-Mercury vehicles, which are
mostly cars, fell 0.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the Ford Taurus LX dropped $1,000, to $17,995,
including destination fees. A typically equipped SE sedan will have
a base price of $18,995, down $1,080, and the SE station wagon
drops $1,840, to $19,995. Prices of the Taurus cousin, the Mercury
Sable, also dropped $1,000 to $1,800.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to put a price on the car that is a recognized
value,'' said Hansen, the Ford official. ``We're hopeful over time
we will not have to resort to incentives.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford is hoping the lower prices will stimulate sales, as it did
last year. For example, Ford lowered the prices for the Mustang,
the two-door Explorer and the Escort ZX2 for the 1998 model year,
resulting in double-digit sales increases.
</P>
<P>
   Prices were decreased for the small Ranger pickup, and sales
doubled. For 1999, the Ranger will be offered with a flexible fuel
engine _ one that burns ethanol and gasoline _ for no extra charge;
flexible fuel engines typically cost more than gasoline-only
engines.
</P>
<P>
   Ford also claims to be the first auto manufacturer to eliminate
the added charge for emissions equipment required in California,
New York and Massachusetts. Ford previously charged $170.
</P>
<P>
   On other cars, particularly the Escort and the Contour, Ford
added equipment for the same 1998 price. Hansen said that beyond
competitive pressures, Ford's pricing strategy has been to not
increase prices. This year's lower prices have been made possible
by reducing costs. Ford reported a total of $4.3 billion in cost
reductions in 1997 and through the first half of 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
