<DOCNO> NYT19980810.0308 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6865 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACKS-BUSINESS-ART-2     08-10 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKS-BUSINESS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK BUSINESSES ARE ATTRACTING CORPORATE GIANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Ga., N.M., N.C., Va., Wis.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic showing
blacks' purchasing power as a percentage of U.S. total is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(lb) 
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long before other girls her age were torturing their tresses
with hot combs and chemical straighteners, Terri Gardner and her
dog, a mutt named Cinnamon, became testers for the shampoos and
pomades her father mixed in the basement of their brick bungalow on
Chicago's South Side.
</P>
<P>
   One day, Edward Gardner would slather Cinnamon with creams he
concocted to condition coarse, curly hair. The next, he would coat
his 8-year-old daughter's dark-brown locks with a thick glaze he
envisioned other black women and girls using to style their bobs
and finger waves.
</P>
<P>
   On occasion, the experiments would go horribly wrong, including
one that left the girl's hair and hands tinted mauve for weeks. In
time, though, Gardner perfected his techniques, and the business he
created with his wife, Bettiann, grew into Soft Sheen Products
Inc., one of the largest ethnic hair-products companies in the
United States with sales last year of $80 million.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, though, Ms. Gardner, 42, who is now Soft Sheen's
president and chief executive, and the rest of the Gardner family
took a hard look at market trends and decided to sell their company
to L'Oreal SA of France, the world's largest cosmetics company.
</P>
<P>
   The Gardners figured that with corporate giants chasing the
increasingly lucrative African-American market, their growth
prospects were dim without access to more capital.
</P>
<P>
   L'Oreal, for its part, saw Soft Sheen as a gateway to consumers
whose needs and neighborhoods it had overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, the same calculations that lay behind the
L'Oreal acquisition are powering lots of other deals around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Black-owned companies in fields such as beauty products, funeral
services and insurance, which first thrived in a segregationist
era, are deciding that it makes more sense to join big corporations
than to fight them.
</P>
<P>
   And though blacks are steadily creating businesses in a wider
range of fields than ever before, some see the recent acquisitions
as an unfortunate end of control by the pioneers of black
entrepreneurship in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, corporations buying the companies are doing so
because they are waking up to an explosion of black economic
strength. A study released last month by the University of
Georgia's Selig Center for Economic Growth calculated that black
purchasing power would reach $533 billion in 1999, up 73 percent
from $308 billion in 1990, compared with a 57 percent increase
projected for all Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Such income growth ``should create tremendous opportunities for
businesses that pay attention to the needs and preferences of
African-American consumers,'' said Dr. Jeffrey Humphreys, a
University of Georgia economist.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, companies born in storefronts and basements in the
1950s and '60s that grew into thriving enterprises in the '70s and
'80s have become guests at corporate America's latest merger party.
It is a little-noticed trend that stands in contrast to the
deal-making boom of a decade ago, when black-owned companies stayed
largely on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there have been high-profile sales of black-owned
companies in the past, like the acquisition of Motown Records by a
consortium headed by MCA Records in 1988. But though no one has
exact figures, marketing specialists say the pace has picked up in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest transactions was IVX Bioscience Inc.'s
purchase of Johnson Products Co., which makes ethnic cosmetics and
hair-care products, in 1993 for $67 million in stock. (IVX sold the
unit last month to Carson Inc. for $85 million.)
</P>
<P>
   Also in 1993, Shorebank Corp. of Chicago bought Indecorp Inc.,
the second-largest black-owned banking firm in that city.
</P>
<P>
   The following are among the deals concluded since then:
</P>
<P>
   _ the acquisition in 1996 of U S Radio, then the largest
black-owned radio group in the country with 25 stations, by Clear
Channel Communications
</P>
<P>
   _ the purchase by Stewart Enterprises, a multinational
conglomerate of more than 500 funeral homes and 135 cemeteries, of
the Hillcrest funeral parlor in Albuquerque, N.M., in 1996 from its
black and Hispanic owners for $1 million
</P>
<P>
   _ the 1997 merger of Garrett &AMP; Davenport in Raleigh, N.C., the
state's oldest minority-owned certified public-accounting firm,
with Cherry Bekaert &AMP; Holland of Richmond, Va., the largest
accounting firm in the Southeast
</P>
<P>
   _ the sale last March by Universal Life Insurance Co., a
venerable firm started 75 years ago, of the bulk of its business to
American Capital Life Insurance Co. for $13 million
</P>
<P>
   _ the acquisition in May of McNeely &AMP; Associates in Milwaukee,
one of Wisconsin's largest African-American law firms, by the
Milwaukee firm of Domnitz Mawicke Goisman &AMP; Rosenberg
</P>
<P>
   _ L'Oreal's agreement last month to buy Soft Sheen for an
undisclosed price that one analyst estimated at well above $160
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are starting to see a lot of larger black-owned companies
becoming attractive targets for other large companies that want to
reach in and expand their market,'' said Alfred Edmond Jr.,
executive editor of Black Enterprise magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Though the owners of the acquired companies can expect a
handsome payoff, not everyone views the changing of the guard as
cause for celebration. ``It is the alligator eating up the
goldfish,'' said the Rev. Jesse Jackson, whose Rainbow/Push
coalition has been calling for more career opportunities and access
to investment capital for members of minorities so they can more
often be the acquirer in these deals.
</P>
<P>
   Some large corporations, of course, have long been developing
products and services aimed at black consumers. But now more
corporations are looking for a quicker route to African-Americans'
pocketbooks by snapping up businesses whose legacies and brands,
like Ebony magazine and Soft Sheen's Optimum hair relaxer, are as
well known in ethnic households as Tide and Colgate are.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about the numbers,'' said Lafayette Jones, chief
executive of Segmented Marketing Services Inc. in Winston-Salem,
N.C., an ethnic-marketing consultant. ``The American population is
increasingly becoming ethnic, and by ethnic I mean
African-American, Latino and Asian. We are talking about $750
billion in collective spending power.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's not just Americans that big multinationals are aiming
at. Many believe that brands that have become cultural icons
representing ethnic Americana hold huge appeal in Africa and other
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
   L'Oreal, for example, is adding to its arsenal such popular
products as Soft Sheen Hair and Scalp conditioner, which softened
Afros in the 1960s, and Care Free Curl activator, which was used to
create the trendy mop of glossy ringlets in the 1980s known as
``the curl.''
</P>
<P>
   Soft Sheen products are key to the company's strategy to expand
into countries with a need for ethnic hair and cosmetics products.
``Africa is the new major area of development for us,'' said Guy
Peyrelongue, president and chief executive officer of L'Oreal's
U.S. subsidiary, Cosmair Inc.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The cosmetics giant's international ambitions helped persuade
the Gardners to let go of their company. ``We knew we had to
compete with bigger players with deeper pockets,'' said Ms.
Gardner, who will continue to run Soft Sheen for L'Oreal and will
join the board of Cosmair.
</P>
<P>
   As for Edward Gardner, he was once so singularly focused on the
business brewing in his basement that his two sons and two
daughters often waited for dinner until Ms. Gardner retrieved her
pots and pans and washed off the chemicals. Now, at 73, he takes a
remarkably unsentimental view of relinquishing his venture.
``Selling the company to me is just a phase, just like starting the
company,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Jackson's lament that old-time black companies are being
picked off by corporate America, there is plenty of evidence that
black entrepreneurs have broken into industries that were largely
closed to them in the days when Jackson was marching alongside Dr.
Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Blacks are pursuing their entrepreneurial ambitions in
industries ranging from computer software to musical production to
cable-television programming.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, some black business pioneers are resisting pressures
to sell. One is John H. Johnson, founder and chairman of Johnson
Publishing Co., which puts out Ebony and Jet magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big companies have been asleep and are awake now and
realize there are great opportunities out there,'' said Johnson,
who founded Johnson Publishing in 1942 when he was 24 and who added
a cosmetics business to his empire in 1973 to cater to women with
skin tones that range from dark to coffee with cream. ``They are
making offers that are hard to refuse,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said that he saw nothing wrong with others selling their
businesses but that he did not expect his family name to be peeled
off the office door.
</P>
<P>
   He said he routinely receives calls from investment bankers
whose clients want to buy his business _ and has instructed his
secretary not to put them through. ``I have a granddaughter who is
9 years old, and she is already saying she is going to take over,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Shaw Jr., the great-grandson of the founder of Universal
Life Insurance, grew up with similar aspirations but is now reeling
from poor succession planning and a failure to keep pace with
changes in technology.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw, 35, who heads the company's underwriting division, said
the financial outlook had become so bleak that in March the company
was forced to sell $53 million in life-insurance-premium
obligations to American Capital Life for $13 million. The company
now believes the best option might be to unload the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a challenge for me personally and professionally to have
to try to make something happen out of this,'' Shaw said, his voice
trailing off. ``But it will come down to prudent and real business
decisions, not emotion,'' he added more forcefully.
</P>
<P>
   Like Universal Life, Hillcrest, the funeral home in Albuquerque,
faced the same fate when much bigger corporate rivals intruded on
its turf. At first, the owners pinned their hopes on the loyalty of
the black and Hispanic communities that they served. But those
hopes faded fast after the big rivals began hiring black employees
and slashing prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would open a cut-rate facility and sell services for
$2,000 complete, and at the other end of town sell them for $6,000
_ and the same company owned both places,'' said Eddie White, a
Hillcrest partner. When Hillcrest fell behind on its taxes, he
said, he and his partner sold out.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart Enterprises, Hillcrest's current owner, says it does not
try to drive local operators out of business when it enters a
market.
</P>
<P>
   Though Jackson acknowledges that market forces are altering the
complexion of black business, he worries that something precious
will be lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, we'll have less pride, we'll have less control,''
Jackson said, ``and a level of infrastructure that took years to
build will go in a minute or two.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
