<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Tuesday, Aug. 11 and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Jeremy Bagott at the Daily News, (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   LA-PROPERTY-ASSESS (Los Angeles) _ A new report by the Los
Angeles County Assessor's Office indicates that the county's net
property assessments have posted their biggest gain in six years,
increasing by $15 billion this year, or 3.1 percent over last year.
By Douglas Haberman. (Will move in the ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   LA-COPDEAD (Los Angeles) _ Los Angeles police wore black bands
across their badges today in memory of a fellow officer gunned down
as he drove his patrol car in the Crenshaw area, and the manhunt
continued for his killer. At roll calls, watch commanders convened
somber sessions, where they reinforced advice for officers to
ensure their safety: constantly be aware of their surroundings,
always look up and down the street, be safe in approaching radio
calls, be aware of possible ambushes. Funeral arrangements were
pending for Officer Filbert Cuesta, 26, of Norwalk, who was shot in
the back of the head about 12:35 a.m. Sunday near Carlin Street and
South Cochran Avenue. By Jesse Hiestand. (Will move in the ``n''
California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   LA-BUGS (Los Angeles) _ It is a summer only a bug could love.
High temperatures and a sudden surge in humidity have the local
insect population in pest heaven, following a spring practically
designed for their procreation. Ants are everywhere, anything that
feeds on grass is having a field day and the spiders that eat other
bugs couldn't be doing better. Los Angeles County officials have
even discovered a eucalyptus-loving pest from Australia that
somehow just popped up in El Monte, although El Nino probably isn't
responsible for that one. A look at the legions of critters showing
up during this summer of bugs. By David R. Baker. (Will move in the
``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   LLOYD-COLUMN -- Let the hire beware. Daily News columnist Ken
Lloyd, Ph.D., a specialist in organizational behavior, answers
readers' questions on workplace ethics and relationships.
</P>
<P>
   ELECTRO-GE (Los Angeles) _ Electro Rent Corp. said it's entitled
to reduction in the $241 million it paid General Electric Co. for a
computer and test equipment rental business because it found
``material issues'' in a balance sheet audit and the unit's recent
results. Los Angeles-based Electro Rent, the largest short-term
rental company for computers, workstations and general testing
equipment for electronics in the U.S., said it expects fiscal
first-quarter earnings to fall from the year-earlier level, partly
from problems at the acquired business. By Enrique Rivero. (Will
move in the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
