<HEADER>
A6878 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-TOMJANOVICH-HNS &LR;      08-10 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TOMJANOVICH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
TOMJANOVICH EARNS INSIDE TRACK TO OLYMPIC COACHING JOB
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ATHENS, Greece _ Rudy Tomjanovich was whipped.
</P>
<P>
   He had just draped a bronze medal around his neck after a
whirlwind 33-day adventure coaching stand-in American players
during the 13th World Championship of Basketball. Before that, he
had exhausted himself with an NBA draft in which the Rockets had
three first-round picks.
</P>
<P>
   All this came after an 82-game regular season and the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need a break,'' Tomjanovich said.
</P>
<P>
   It's true that putting in the equivalent of five weeks of
overtime to coach the U.S. national team was a grueling prospect.
But Tomjanovich couldn't help saying that if he had it to do all
over again, he would. Without hesitation.
</P>
<P>
   He may get the chance.
</P>
<P>
   Warren S. Brown, executive director of USA Basketball, said
after the U.S. charged to third place in the World Championship
that Tomjanovich would ``be the first name on the list'' of
coaching candidates to guide the Americans in the 2000 Olympics in
Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   The only question is whether Tomjanovich would be interesting in
investing another summer _ probably one that will require him to be
busier than this one, which came during the lockout of NBA players
with Rockets basketball operations at a standstill.
</P>
<P>
   He removed all doubt after leading the U.S. to a 7-2 record in
the World Championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know I'd do it,'' Tomjanovich said sheepishly after being
pinned down on the question of whether he would like to coach the
Olympic team. ``I'd have to. It's your duty.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown doesn't have the job of selecting the coaches who will
lead U.S. teams into international competition. A selection
committee handles that process.
</P>
<P>
   But Brown does have a strong leadership role with USA
Basketball, and he was thrilled to learn Tomjanovich is amenable to
the 2000 job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't make that decision,'' Brown said. ``But I can't
believe that he won't be the first name on the list. It would be
wonderful if he would. I don't make that decision. But I can tell
you he's going to get every consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think that whole (coaching) staff, with Rudy leading
it, would be leading the pack.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said the way Tomjanovich, along with assistant coaches Del
Harris of the Los Angeles Lakers and Lon Kruger of the University
of Illinois, handled the situation of NBA players being removed
from the U.S. squad and replaced by Americans from the Continental
Basketball Association, college and European leagues has left a
strong impression on the higher-ups with USA Basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where we started with this thing about a month ago, we didn't
have any names on the team,'' Brown said. ``We had a coaching staff
that stepped up to the starting line, despite whatever else was
going on. It's hard to put a worth on that, because that kind of
drive was going to happen from then on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rudy and Del and Lon stepped up and said: `It doesn't make any
difference (who they coached). We want to coach for our country.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So I think the coaching staff drove the whole thing. And what
can you say about the team? They didn't ask for anything, just to
be able to play and represent their country,'' Brown said. ``And I
couldn't be more proud of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sure makes you appreciate what players and coaches who want
to do a job will do. And the results are that much more
pleasurable. I do think it has more meaning in that light.''
</P>
<P>
   As Tomjanovich was quick to point out, the commitment of the
players deserves recognition. And if they hadn't respected
Tomjanovich's philosophy and strategy, they probably never would
have gotten to the medal stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we stepped into a difficult situation, and we fought
hard,'' said Ashraf Amaya, one of three centers who shined as a
strength of the team. ``I believe we represented our country to the
best of our ability and think we did a very good job of it. I hope
the majority of people back home will believe that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing is clear: The people at USA Basketball have come to
know and love the effort of Tomjanovich and his staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rudy is just terrific,'' Brown said. ``The players listen to
him, and they know where he's coming from. He treats them even and
tells them the way it is. They won because his philosophy of being
tough-minded and keeping focused prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to discount the players. But the combination of
the coaching staff we had and the kind of players who wanted to
step up results in this. It's a great, great feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   The reward was equally gratifying for Tomjanovich.
</P>
<P>
   ``My association with USA Basketball has been great,'' he said.
``They're good people, and they've supported me. It was a great
tournament, with a lot of guys out there playing their hearts out
for their country.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich coaching in the Olympics makes more sense now than
ever before.
</P>
<P>
   Until NBA players were involved, coaches worked their way up the
international ladder with USA Basketball before coaching in an
Olympic Games, perhaps coaching in Pan American Games or other
competitions first.
</P>
<P>
   But in the past two Olympics, Chuck Daly and Lenny Wilkens were
the coaches to lead the U.S. teams, despite limited prior
international experience, because the decision was made to have NBA
coaches leading NBA players.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Tomjanovich has international coaching experience in
addition to being a well-respected NBA coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a thought that NBA players need an NBA coach and
everybody should get an opportunity, because it doesn't come along
very often,'' Brown said. ``But this is kind of an unusual
circumstance. I think Rudy is a front-runner (for the 2000 job)
going in, if he wants to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't make the decision, but I know in conversations with
those who do that they really respect the way he stepped up. And
then how he handled this team. He's proven he can do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
