<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6879 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-CLINTON-RECORD-$A     08-10 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-CLINTON-RECORD-$ADV16 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: CLINTON'S EDUCATING OF AMERICA
 &HT;    For release on or after Sunday, August 16.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Nearly six years ago, a youthful Bill Clinton
strode into the capital, armed with ``Putting People First,'' a
book that set out his sweeping promises for America and great
expectations for his energized new presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Now as he faces a grand jury appearance that could determine his
place in history, Clinton's exuberant charm and public appeal are
little diminished by the anxiety that surrounds him in the Monica
Lewinsky matter. But the prospects for fulfilling the promises of
his presidency are growing ever dimmer.
</P>
<P>
   So many opportunities have been lost already. His health care
overhaul plan crashed; his vow to have the most ethical
administration in history was buried in independent counsel probes
of himself and six of his appointees; and he receives little credit
for balancing the budget, since that came after heavy pressure from
the Republican-led Congress and a windfall of revenues from the
soaring economy.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the public links that economic boom to Clinton and
gives him high ratings for job performance. But historians give few
points for greatness to presidents who merely preside over a period
of prosperity. Moreover, this upswing began the year before Clinton
took office.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton last year openly launched a campaign to secure a legacy,
and the White House even consulted academics about how he might
build one. But his second term has been consumed by road trips to
raise millions of dollars for his party (with events to boost his
policies sandwiched between fund-raisers to assure that most of the
costs will be paid by taxpayers), travel abroad that accomplished
little, and the current scandal over his unexplained relations with
former 21-year-old White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Who can recall the central goal that he set for his last term as
an elective official introduced in his State of the Union address
in 1997?
</P>
<P>
   ``(M)y number one priority for the next four years is to ensure
that all Americans have the best education in the world,'' Clinton
said as he unfurled his easily forgettable action plan before
Congress. By singling out education, Clinton picked a concern that
ranks high on public opinion surveys, but he also chose an area
where the federal government has only a modest role.
</P>
<P>
   More than a year and a half later, what has happened to the
``national crusade for education standards'' that he announced?
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  National testing in reading and math: Never implemented.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Federal assistance to repair crumbling school buildings: Never
implemented.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A proposal to hire 100,000 new teachers to reduce class size:
Going nowhere in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Increasing the Head Start preschool program to one million
children: Ignored by Congress amid studies indicating that the
popular program for low-income youngsters offers few lasting
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Two other proposals have passed, but their contribution to
education is debatable:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Clinton's much publicized plan to wire up every classroom to
the computer Internet's ``information highway'' has hit potholes on
the on-ramp. His federal subsidy program, approved in 1996, has yet
to distribute its first dollar to a school. And telephone fees that
finance the program are being challenged in court as an
unconstitutional tax.
</P>
<P>
   And there's another big catch. Computerizing all classrooms
could turn out to be a colossal waste of billions of dollars. It is
widely acknowledged that research has yet to prove that computers
or the Internet boost academic achievement, and some experts say
high tech teaching could be a detriment in the early grades.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The president's proposal to give $1,500 in tax credits for two
years of college tuition was enacted in 1997. That's a boon to
eligible families, but it makes the tax code more complex and less
fair. And if history is a guide, the federal aid will eventually
prompt colleges to hike tuitions that have long far outpaced the
rate of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Among his less visible moves, Clinton pressured Congress to
spend more for education. He also established a new literacy
program in which colleges provide volunteers as tutors for
elementary students. But he stopped repeating his 1996 election
campaign vow that this ``America Reads'' program would be a
nationwide ``army of volunteers'' assuring that every child will be
reading proficiently by the end of the third grade by the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
   And for all of his proposals for education, Clinton's
significant impact could be the one that involves neither money nor
programs, but the example that he has set for the younger
generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Character education must be taught in the schools,'' he said
in his State of the Union message last year. ``We must teach our
children to be good citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has taught a lesson in questionable character for the
past seven months by leaving a cloud of suspicion over his office
so thick that it's difficult to find anyone who truly believes
Clinton's adamant denial that he had a sexual liaison with ``that
woman Miss Lewinsky,'' as he has told the nation last January.
</P>
<P>
   This Clinton character course has brought into family living
rooms, live from the White House and delivered by sometimes
blushing newscasters, reports that would have been unthinkable not
long ago _ about oral sex, a semen-stained dress, and presidential
kneepads.
</P>
<P>
   Children, who can hardly have missed the gist of the adult
conversations, have asked, ``Did the president lie?'' as their
parents have been left to answer, ``Well, if he did, you still must
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless Clinton can explain himself this coming week, that will
be his legacy to education and to the country.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
