<DOCNO> NYT19980810.0319 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6887 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRICA-U.S.-NYT &LR;      08-10 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUARD'S PRE-BOMB SIGHTING OF TRUCK MAY PROVIDE CLUE TO IDENTITY OF
TERRORISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: AFRICA-BOMBINGS, AFRICA-TERRORISM, AFRICA-FUNERAL,
AFRICA-DEAD, AFRICA-SURVIVE) 
(JT) 
 By PHILIP SHENON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Kenyan guard at the shattered American Embassy in
Nairobi and others who saw a light truck approach the embassy
compound minutes before the explosion may provide important clues
to the identify of the terrorists who carried out the attack,
Clinton administration officials said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The embassy guard, whose name has not been released, has told
American investigators that he refused to allow the truck through
the gate and that, as a result, one of the occupants of the truck
jumped from the car and opened fire on him, possibly throwing hand
grenades. The guard said he ran for his life. Moments later, he
said, a bomb in the truck exploded.
</P>
<P>
   ``This story has to be verified, but if it's true, he really did
a tremendous job,'' Under Secretary of State Thomas Pickering said
of the guard. If the truck had gotten past the gate and into the
basement parking lot of the embassy, Pickering said in an
interview, ``the whole building might have come down.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Kenyans who say they witnessed the blast offer a similar
account of a truck bomb.
</P>
<P>
   American investigators hope their description of the pickup
truck and its passengers could help identify the terrorists who
carried out the attack in Nairobi last Friday and the nearly
simultaneous bombing of the American Embassy in Dar es Salaam, the
capital of neighboring Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on Monday in Nairobi, Ochieng Okwach, a
42-year-old driver for the Kenyan national parks service, said that
he was stopped in traffic about 50 yards from the embassy when he
saw a yellow pickup truck with an enclosed cargo area try to back
through the embassy's rear gate toward the underground parking
garage, stopping about five yards from the gate.
</P>
<P>
   Seconds later, he said, a man leaped from the back of the truck
wearing a blue guard uniform that appeared identical to the ones
worn by security guards who protect both the parking lot and the
embassy's front entrance.
</P>
<P>
   The man, who carried a black object the size of a walkie-talkie
in his right hand, made a throwing motion toward the embassy,
Okwach said. A small explosion followed.
</P>
<P>
   According to Okwach's account, the uniformed man ran back to the
truck and jumped in, a moment before the pickup truck exploded in a
powerful fireball that rocked the embassy and caused the collapse
of a nearby office building. ``I thought it was some robbers
wanting to rob the bank,'' he said. ``When I heard that blast, I
said, `Oh, God, it is the end of the world.'''
</P>
<P>
   Although his account would suggest that the passengers in the
truck were killed in the explosion, possibly in an act of suicide,
American officials say they have no evidence to date to show what
happened to the terrorists _ whether they died in the explosion,
were among those injured, or fled.
</P>
<P>
   Okwach said that he had not been interviewed by any American
officials, nor by the local police.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Pickering, who has helped direct the State
Department's response to the explosions in Kenya and Tanzania, said
that the guard at the embassy in Nairobi has reported that he first
noticed the light truck ``as it approached the embassy gate that he
was guarding.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the guard's account, Pickering said, the truck
``made a circle or turned around or something of that sort and
someone in the front seat asked the guard to open the gates.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When he refused, somebody got out of the truck with what
appeared to be hand grenades,'' he said. ``He threatened the guard
and then began to throw hand grenades at him _ hand grenades or
some sort of long tubes. He did not open the gate and he ran. And
as he ran, there was a huge explosion that threw him to the
ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Pickering said that he did not know the condition of the guard
or whether he had been hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very important to say that this is a story that
has to be confirmed,'' he said. ``But if it indeed is true, then
obviously it appears that the guard did not allow the truck to
penetrate the gate. He obviously did a very helpful thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials said that investigators are
sifting through rubble at the embassy in Nairobi in search of
evidence of the truck that may have carried the explosives. Even
tiny fragments of the truck, they say, may allow them to identify
the make and model of the vehicle and its owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ideally, we want to match the eyewitness accounts to the
physical evidence of the truck,'' said an administration official
who is involved in the investigations in Kenya and Tanzania,
speaking on condition that he not be identified. ``If we can match
it up, history shows that we're on our way to identifying the
perpetrators.''
</P>
<P>
   American investigators and embassy officials in Nairobi have
dismissed other reports about the explosion that have supposedly
come from witnesses, including one report suggesting that a truck
used in the bombing had American diplomatic license plates. ``There
are lots of rumors,'' said William Barr, an embassy spokesman in
Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
