A6898 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APPLE-MACINTOSH-ORDER     08-10 0450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE-MACINTOSH-ORDERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPLE REPORTS 150,000 ORDERS FOR NEW IMAC MACINTOSH IN ONE WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ll) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Apple Computer said on Monday that it had
received more than 150,000 orders for its new iMac Macintosh
computer since the company began taking orders a week ago. The
iMac, which is aimed at the consumer and education markets, goes on
sale on Aug. 15 at a suggested retail price of $1,299.
</P>
<P>
   Apple, based in Cupertino, Calif., has high hopes for the iMac,
which features a translucent green case, an integrated monitor and
an illuminated mouse, and some analysts have estimated that the
company could sell more than 1 million of the new machine in its
first year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the largest first week order Apple has ever gotten for
any new product,'' Steven Jobs, Apple's interim president and chief
executive, said in a telephone interview. ``The channel is going
pretty crazy for this,'' Jobs added, referring to personal computer
dealers and distributors, many of whom have been accepting advance
customer orders for the iMac for months, but could only order from
Apple beginning on Aug. 3.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Apple shares closed at $37.9375, up $1.4375, in
Nasdaq trading. For three consecutive quarters, a resurgent Apple
has reported earnings that exceeded Wall Street analysts'
estimates, and many have been counting on a strong start of the
iMac to continue that trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will go nuts in the fourth quarter,'' said Kimball
Brown, an analyst with Dataquest, who said his only reservation
concerned Apple's reliance on a new connection scheme, called USB,
for printers, floppy disk drives and other peripheral devices. But
in schools and offices, where such devices are often shared on a
network, USB is not an issue. ``In education, this is a dream
machine,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   The use of USB, or universal system bus, means that the iMac
cannot connect directly to older printers, and there are fewer new
devices using USB than many industry watchers had anticipated at
this time. Yet several companies already offer adaptors that allow
the use of non-USB devices with the iMac, so the problem is not
insurmountable.
</P>
<P>
   Apple also had good news on the software front, saying that more
than 460 new or upgraded software applications had been announced
for the Macintosh since the introduction of the iMac on May 6.
</P>
<P>
   Apple's declining market share in recent years had prompted
numerous software developers to abandon the Macintosh, but the
return of Jobs, and Apple's return to profitability, coupled with
excitement over the new machine, have brought many back to the
fold.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-98 1938EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980810.0324 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6899 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EMBASSY-FUNDING-BOS &LR;      08-10 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMBASSY-FUNDING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAST FALLOUT: DEBATE OVER EMBASSY FUNDING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Embassy-Reward; i and w coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS AND ESTELLA DURAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The devastation in Nairobi and Dar es Salaam last
Friday is about to rekindle a political fight in Washington over
the proper funding of embassy security that began over a decade ago
during the Reagan administration.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said the State Department
will ask Congress for more money to secure embassies and consulates
around the world. Budget planners, diplomatic security agents and
architects have started culling requests from ambassadors for
everything from steel doors and bulletproof windows to 24-hour
Marine guard details and other measures at nearly 300 buildings
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   These requests will total billions of dollars, despite the fact
that Congress has not yet approved a foreign affairs budget for
next year that includes a mere $36.1 million for security upgrades
and construction of embassies.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, after an independent panel recommended $2.5 billion in
security improvements, Congress balked at spending the money. Even
Senator Richard Lugar, Indiana Republican who is a respected
foreign policy expert, criticized the notion of ``gold-plated''
embassies.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Congress has approved less than $1 billion of the
projects, according to Patrick Kennedy, who oversees the State
Department's administrative offices.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Congress rejected a plan to build a new $200 million
embassy in Beijing and a new embassy of unspecified cost in Berlin,
Germany's new capital. Instead, appropriations committees approved
several million dollars for planning and design of the buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress predicted that there will be sentiment after
the August recess for increased spending on embassy security.
Friday's extraordinary blasts dramatized the issue more than any
bureaucrat could. Also, the attacks came just two weeks after a
gunman entered the Capitol, killing two police officers. After
that, Republicans and Democrats alike agreed to increase security
in the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to protect our citizens, we've got to protect our
people who work with us,'' said John F. Kerry of Massachusetts, a
Democrat who serves on the Senate Foreign Relations Committee.
``Obviously we're going to have to broaden the existing security.
But it's premature to start giving out amounts of money or say
which embassies need more security.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Joe Biden, the top ranking Democrat on the committee,
Monday sent letters to Albright and Foreign Affairs Comittee
chairman Jesse Helms, a Republican, calling for a hearing on
embassy security and more money. Aides to Helms did not return
phone calls, but in the past he has called on the State Department
to use its money more efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Fisher, a spokesman for Lugar, who also serves on the
committee, said, ``He has said that we needed to have a larger
request to Congress to begin with.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Jack Reed, a Rhode Island Democrat, estimated Congress
will approve an additional $100 million for security. ``Sure, it
will cost a significant amount of money, but it's also costing a
significant amount to pick up all the rubble,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The best of intentions still might be sidetracked by political
reality. The 1999 foreign affairs budget is stalled in Congress
because of an unrelated argument over how the next census will be
conducted.
</P>
<P>
   And while the powerful explosions in Nairobi and Dar es Salaam
will increase support for the State Department's security plans,
there is a practical problem as well: simply to rebuild those two
buildings will exhaust the department's budget for new construction
for the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department has said it is too early to say how much it
will need to rebuild the embassy in Nairobi, which was gutted by
the blast. But a new embassy of comparable size in Riyadh, Saudi
Arabia's capital, cost $140 million. And a medium-sized embassies
such as the one that was shattered in Tanzania cost about $30
million.
</P>
<P>
   There is yet another costly complication: since Friday, the
State Department also has had to increase security at several
embassies. ``We're getting a large number of threats coming in,''
Kennedy said. ``Some of them could conceivably be real. Some of
them simply may be copycats.''
</P>
<P>
   Some foreign service officers Monday complained that the US
efforts to save money have unfairly jeopardized their security. By
law, the State Department must do business with the lowest bidder
of all the companies that want to provide security agents at
embassies. In Kenya and Tanzania and many other countries,
officials said, the companies did not provide life insurance or
retirement plans for the guards.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, State Department employees were asked to donate money to
the widows of several guards who were killed. ``That's an
outrage!'' one veteran Foreign Service officer said. ``Can't our
government provide that benefit for people who risk their lives for
us?''
</P>
<P>
   The State Deparment keeps a list of embassies that need to be
``hardened,'' starting with those in the most dangerous regions.
But the simultaneous attacks in two tranquil East African countries
have rocked the notion of high- and low-risk sites.
</P>
<P>
   Even one of the administration officials familiar with overseas
security operations was skeptical of the talk of pouring money into
new embassies. ``You can spend billions of dollars,'' he said about
the fight against terrorists, ``but a lot of it comes down is
getting human intelligence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-98 1939EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980810.0325 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6901 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-FELICITY-AZR &LR;      08-10 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FELICITY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FELICITY' STAR'S PRIMED FOR PRIME TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JAIMEE ROSE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD - Keri Russell perches on a make-up chair in Hollywood
Saturday night with a cellular phone glued to her ear and harried
photographers hovering around her.
</P>
<P>
   She's on the set of the WB Network's most touted and envied new
sitcom, ``Felicity,'' and everyone is competing for the 22-year-old
Mesa, Ariz., native's attention. With filming going on and
interview requests pouring in from such media moguls as ``Time,''
``Newsweek,`` `` Rolling Stone,`` ``Entertainment Weekly,`` ``USA
Today ''and ``Seventeen,'' Russell's learning how quickly life can
change.
</P>
<P>
   Already, she has been been featured on ``Entertainment
Tonight.'' Already, ``USA Today'' has noted the heaps of hype
heading Russell's way. And her show doesn't debut for another six
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's horrifying, to tell you the truth,'' she said. ``I don't
know how to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The hubbub is a far cry from her childhood spent at a ballet bar
in the Mesa Stars dance studio, though even then Russell seemed
primed for prime time.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the kind of person you believe would do it,'' said Stars
director Bobbi Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   That's also what TV critics, advertising agencies, and competing
networks are saying about ``Felicity,'' a sitcom about a freshman
(Russell) at New York University that is billed as ``Ally McBeal
goes to college.''
</P>
<P>
   How did the mostly unknown star of an unseen show on an itty
bitty startup network become the hottest new TV face of 1998?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've ever seen anything like this,'' said Laura
Caraccioli, director of TV programing for the Chicago advertising
agency Leo Burnett. ``Not with a new face. Nobody's familiar with
her. It's happened before when people come to TV from the theater
or move from theatricals to the small screen, but nothing like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Caraccioli doesn't directly buy commercial time for advertisers,
but advises her agency's clients on television trends. Her thick
preseason report is widely distributed in the TV world, which began
to stir about ``Felicity'' and its young star way back in March,
when the WB brought a short clip of scenes from the show to
preliminary meetings with advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   The WB had just launched the teen-appeal drama ``Dawson's
Creek.'' Thanks to that show and ``Buffy, The Vampire Slayer,'' the
fledgling network was beginning to generate some buzz of its own.
The ``Felicity'' clip stood out, and Russell made an excellent
first impression.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the buzz started there, back in March,'' said
Caracioli.
</P>
<P>
   Another thing ``Felicity'' has in its corner is its Imagine
Television production auspices. Its young creators, J.J. Abrams and
Matt Reeves, have bankable feature film credits (``Armageddon,``
``Regarding Henry,`` ``The Pallbearer``), and Ron Howard is one of
its executive producers.
</P>
<P>
   Russell lived in Mesa from age 1 to 13. Her family - parents
David and Stephanie, older brother Todd and younger sister Julie -
now live in Dallas, but when ``Felicity'' premieres, there will be
a hometown fan section in the Phoenix area. Friends have tracked
Russell's budding career since her years on the ``Mickey Mouse
Club.''
</P>
<P>
   Fellow Stars dancer Joni McKeen hasn't seen Russell since a trip
to Florida in 1994, but sometimes she'll catch a glimpse of her
famous friend on the living room TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just turned it on, saw her, and called my mom _ `guess who's
on TV!' '' said Manguso on Russell's ``Seventh Heaven'' sitcom
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   When dance teacher Rogers caught Russell as the babysitter on
``Honey, I Blew Up the Kids,'' her reaction was similar.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going `oh my gosh _ is that Keri? We knew her when she
was little,' '' she said. ``You just don't think . . . but everyone
always wanted to be like her.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially her hair, says Manguso, who followed Keri's curls in
Mesa as closely as she follows her career now.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sister and I paid extra money so we could go to Keri's
stylist and have her hair, but it never looked the same,'' said
Manguso. ``We were all going through our ugly stage then, and she
was still so pretty.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Russell's superiors took her lead. ``I even went to Jo
(Keri's stylist),'' said Rogers. ``But I look back at those
pictures and want to die!''
</P>
<P>
   Russell is flattered, but doesn't understand the idolatry. ``You
are killing me right now,'' she said, laughing at the story. ``It's
an afro!''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, come the show's Sept. 29 debut, watch Keri's curly
look be as requested as Jennifer Aniston's sought-after ``Friends''
shag _ a sign of true stardom.
</P>
<P>
   But the 'fro fans may run into trouble, because Russell's locks
turned naturally wavy at 16. And that's OK with Russell, who thinks
natural is the way to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lack of real girls on TV right now,'' she said.
``There's all of the thick eyeliner and fake boobs, but Felicity is
more like girls in real life _ she's smart and wears big sweaters
and ponytails, and I think girls need to see that.''
</P>
<P>
   This ``real'' quality is what attracted Russell, who ``never
wanted to be an actor,'' to the role in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fell in love with this story and what she represents,'' said
Russell. ``I think and feel everything Felicity says, but I don't
always show it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have this editing device in our brain that tells us
`oh, that won't make you very cool,' but Felicity doesn't have that
emotional relationship savviness.''
</P>
<P>
   This raw style is part of what critics say is making Russell
great.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was so powerful (in the pilot), she just jumped right out
of the screen at you. Something in her eyes,'' said ad exec
Caracioli.
</P>
<P>
   ``She doesn't have to speak, and she speaks volumes.''
</P>
<P>
   This May, when the expanded ``Felicity'' pilot began making the
rounds of advertisers and TV critics, the buzz grew into a small
roar.
</P>
<P>
   Among the nearly 40 new shows that will debut this fall,
``Felicity'' clearly was one of the few with a chance to become a
critical and commercial hit. ``It just blew most of us away,`` said
Caracioli. ``It was one of the most well-done pilots. You felt like
you were watching a theatrical release.''
</P>
<P>
   But all of this buzz about Russell is making her job harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``There definitely is more pressure when everyone's expecting
you to deliver,'' she said. ``But on the flip side, it's really
great to have this much attention _ it feels too good to be true.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell, however, hits ground quickly as she realizes she's been
working until 5 a.m. each morning without a weekend off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm exhausted,'' she said. ``Sleep would be a good thing right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   But an agent beckons and Russell is summoned from her dreams of
restful felicity to the flurry of photographers awaiting their new
shining star.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Republic TV writer Dave Walker contributed to this story. Jaimee
Rose can be reached at Jaimee.Rose(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
