<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6905 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELLSOUTH-STRIKE11-CO     08-10 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-STRIKE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Now that agreement has been reached, BellSouth has unique
opportunityBy Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Having passed a high-stakes contract confrontation and
avoided a strike, BellSouth has a chance to use cooperation _ and
advice _ from workers as a way to maintain fast growth.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement hashed out late Saturday with the Communications
Workers of America sets BellSouth apart from other regional phone
companies _ especially from Bell Atlantic, where contract talks
broke down and 73,000 workers headed for picket lines.
</P>
<P>
   The deal between Atlanta-based BellSouth and the CWA produced a
three-year contract that would cover 48,000 of the company's 86,188
employees. Assuming the agreement is ratified, workers will receive
a 12.39 percent wage increase and a healthier pension package,
although BellSouth budged only a bit on its policy of forcing
employees to work overtime.
</P>
<P>
   But the two sides also created a committee that could oversee
operations, recommend rules for revision and monitor the way change
is carried out.
</P>
<P>
   The joint operations board would include CWA and company
officials and have power to consider worker proposals for changing
how jobs are done, to propose training that will let workers shift
into new jobs and to suggest bonuses. Mainly, the board would give
union members an alternative to filing formal complaints or waiting
until the next set of contract negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   In a rapidly changing industry, both company and union wanted
another option.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth spokeswoman Deborah Spicer cited the changes since the
1995 agreement: passage of the Telecommunications Act, increased
competition and BellSouth's growth. ``Doing things in the same old
environment and expecting better results will not work.''
</P>
<P>
   The joint board will review employee suggestions for improving
the way work is done, she said. ``Changing processes under the old
system can be clunky.''
</P>
<P>
   The board will have no official power _ but it will include
members who do.
</P>
<P>
   Noah Savant, CWA assistant to the vice president for the
Southeast, said the board will protect worker rights and give union
workers a better shot at taking jobs that BellSouth has been
all-too-willing to contract out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have positioned ourselves well for the long-term,
positioned ourselves to add jobs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Few precedents for the board exist. However, a similar
arrangement helped end a bitter strike against the British Columbia
phone company in 1980, ushering in an era of relative labor peace.
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Bernard, director of the Trade Union Program at Harvard
University, said unions see their future depends on giving
companies more flexibility, and, in return getting more say in
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You talk to anybody in the CWA and they know that quality is
about jobs. And they think that management of the industry is too
important to leave to management.''
</P>
<P>
   But how well the board will function and how much influence is
hard to predict, she said. ``Flexibility is often thinly disguised
code for 'anything that management says, goes.'''
</P>
<P>
   At least right now, BellSouth's deal provides a measure of
cooperation that dramatically contrasts with the conflict at Bell
Atlantic. That walkout _ which is made up mostly of CWA workers _
took CWA officials here by surprise. Issues at Bell Atlantic were
similar and the deadline was the same.
</P>
<P>
   What made Bell Atlantic different was partly a history of
confrontations that the CWA does not have in the Southeast.
Relations between the CWA leadership and that of BellSouth have
been mostly amicable _ unlike at Bell Atlantic. For instance,
Nynex, which was purchased by Bell Atlantic, endured a bitter
strike in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   But the CWA may also see an opportunity. Bell Atlantic has
recently announced a $55 billion plan to purchase GTE, an idea sure
to confront skepticism among regulators. A grueling strike would be
a public relations black eye, distracting the company when focus is
critical.
</P>
<P>
   While the CWA's northern and southern approaches seem to
diverge, all telecommunications unions face a future radically
different from the world they knew before the 1984 breakup of AT&AMP;T.
Back then, telephone workers had virtual life tenure in a monopoly
industry that was regulated by government and nearly all unionized.
Now, all that has changed.
</P>
<P>
   For at least five years, BellSouth has joined other regional
phone companies in trimming workforces. BellSouth, for instance,
has slashed its payroll by 16 percent while adding some jobs in
wireless, cable television and international units. Those jobs are
mainly non-union.
</P>
<P>
   More ominous for the union has been the stunning growth of
non-union companies like Sprint and MCI, and even newer entrants
like Qwest and WorldCom who see the old phone companies as
dinosaurs in the coming world of high-speed data.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
