<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holyfield-Bean card holds something for nearly everyone
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Evander Holyfield's homecoming fight card shouldn't be
short of at least two elements: tickets and diversity.
</P>
<P>
   The Holyfield-Vaughn Bean heavyweight title fight Sept. 19,
staged in a Georgia Dome set up for 40,000 seats, will have an
undercard that includes at least one other men's title fight, a
bout featuring women's lightweight champion Christy Martin _ and
possibly a kick-boxing event and musical entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The main event, Holyfield's first fight in Atlanta since a title
defense against Bert Cooper in 1991, will be announced officially
today at a Georgia Dome news conference. Ticket information has not
been completed, but tickets are expected to go on sale Wednesday,
with prices starting at $25. Promoter Don King will push the event
in Atlanta as the last chance for most area residents to see
Holyfield fight live, with the remaining bouts of his career
probably in Las Vegas or Atlantic City. The IBF has ranked Bean No.
1, mandating that Holyfield give him a title shot. But Bean has
built a 31-1 record against largely obscure competition and lost a
decision to his only noteworthy opponent, Michael Moorer, in March
of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The the fight will be shown nationally on Showtime during a
``free preview'' weekend, but officials of the cable network are
considering blacking out the broadcast in the Atlanta area.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
