<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6907 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-SCAROLINA-COX     08-10 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SCAROLINA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gamecock fans looking for Scott to produce FSU-esque season
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When South Carolina named Brad Scott its head football coach in
December 1993, the hiring raised more than a few eyebrows across
the SEC. Scott had earned a reputation as an offensive genius,
after helping Florida State to the 1993 national title as its
offensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   As Scott enters his fifth season in Columbia, however, Gamecock
fans are still waiting to catch a glimpse of the success he helped
orchestrate in Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   Since leading South Carolina to its first-ever bowl win during
his rookie season in 1994, Scott has limped to a 15-17-1 mark over
the past three years. Worse, since Scott's arrival, the Gamecocks
have gone just 1-11 against SEC East opponents Florida, Georgia and
Tennessee. And he has split four games with intrastate rival
Clemson.
</P>
<P>
   ``A .500 record is mediocre, either the best of the worst or the
worst of the best,'' Scott said. ``It's certainly not good enough
for me or the program. Our fans and players need to be involved in
some bowl games. I'm embarrassed our team isn't better,
record-wise.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the mediocrity, Scott doesn't appear to be in immediate
trouble at South Carolina. The Gamecocks are coming off a 5-6
campaign, in which starting quarterback Anthony Wright was lost for
the final two games with a season-ending knee injury. Wright is
near full-recovery, and Scott is armed with a contract through the
2002 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this day and time, any head football coach is always under
the microscope,'' Scott says. ``Expectations are out there every
year. I don't have to buy a publication or listen to talk radio to
figure that out.''
</P>
<P>
   But Scott must have listened to some of the criticism _ he
pushed out offensive coordinator John Eason and
quarterbacks/passing game coach John Reaves after last season, when
the Gamecocks finished eighth in total offense and ninth in
rushing.
</P>
<P>
   Former Baylor coach and Clemson assistant Chuck Reedy is the new
offensive coordinator and quarterbacks coach, and former Alabama
assistant Woody McCorvey was hired to coach receivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to run the ball with more authority,'' Scott said.
``We have to be able to convert third-and-shorts. We have gotten
away from a commitment to the run. Chuck Reedy brings us toughness.
He'll have more responsibility than most of my past coordinators.''
</P>
<P>
   A running game would ease some of the pressure on Wright, who
probably won't see full-contact until the Sept. 5 season-opener
against Ball State.
</P>
<P>
   But establishing a ground attack could be tough for Carolina.
Returning tailbacks Troy Hambrick and Boo Williams of Blackshear
combined for just two 100-yard rushing performances last season.
The Gamecocks could start as many as three redshirt freshmen on its
offensive line, including left guard Phillip Jones of Brookwood
High.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot easier teaching running blocks than drop-back
passing protection,'' Scott said. ``Our success will depend on how
quickly these guys will adjust to being starters. We play our first
four games at home, and I think that will help our young players.''
</P>
<P>
   After the season opener, South Carolina hosts Georgia, Marshall
and Mississippi State in consecutive games at Williams-Brice
Stadium. It will be an important stretch, as South Carolina closes
the regular season with a home game against Tennessee and
back-to-back road dates at Florida and Clemson.
</P>
<P>
   For Wednesday: A report on the Kentucky Wildcats.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
