<DOCNO> NYT19980810.0330 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6909 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-PRESIDENCY-BO     08-10 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PRESIDENCY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR CLINTON, AN UNEXPECTED KIND OF PRESIDENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House dinner had gone well. But as the
dozen or so guests headed for the exits, President Clinton cornered
a few of them and shared his thoughts on the investigation
engulfing his presidency: Kenneth W. Starr was feeding an appetite
for trivia when he, Clinton, had far more important work to do.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton dared not talk about the specific accusations or his
feelings about his accusers, reflecting a new reality for the
president.
</P>
<P>
   His fight with the independent counsel has made the White House
a lonely place for Clinton. In just a few short months, Starr has
won the right to question Secret Service agents who protect him,
and the White House lawyers whose advice he depends on. He has to
be careful whom he talks to these days and what confidences he
divulges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give people the power to question the president under oath and
this is what you get,'' said David A. Strauss, a University of
Chicago law professor who helped represent Clinton before the
Supreme Court in Clinton v. Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides in the titanic struggle between Starr and Clinton
blame the other for setting in motion a process in which
presidential bodyguards and government lawyers can be summoned
before a grand jury to testify in an investigation stemming from
what most Americans regard as a private matter, a person's sex
life.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's case will be the principal example for future scholars
examining what can happen to the occupant of the nation's highest
office when he is subjected to the uncertainty of a civil lawsuit.
In 1997, the Supreme Court ruled that Paula Jones could go forward
with her sexual-harassment claim against Clinton while he was in
office, though with some deference, such as consideration of his
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the discovery process by Jones's lawyers, Monica
Lewinsky became a household name. And Starr's investigation of an
Arkansas land deal has mushroomed to whether Clinton had sex with
the former intern and committed perjury and obstructed justice to
hide it. Along the way, Starr's probe has also focused on possible
improprieties in the White House acquisition of the FBI files of
top Republicans, the suicide of Deputy White House Counsel Vincent
Foster, and the firings of White House travel office employees.
</P>
<P>
   Lost in the public chatter about the FBI testing of Lewinsky's
navy blue dress that may contain genetic material from Clinton,
Strauss said, is ``the erosion of the president's ability to
govern.''
</P>
<P>
   For that, he blames Starr. ``If there is going to be a case in
which you are going to force the president's lawyers to talk about
their conversations with the president, it ought to be a much more
important case than this one,'' Strauss said.
</P>
<P>
   C. Boyden Gray, a White House counsel under President Bush,
agrees for different reasons. The Clinton administration is at
fault, he said, for trying to block the testimony of the Secret
Service agents and government lawyers. ``They took the weakest
possible case to legitimate'' those privileges.
</P>
<P>
   Fred F. Fielding, a White House counsel under President Reagan
and deputy counsel under President Nixon, embraces the issue from
both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``The power of the presidency hasn't been diminished only by
these legal setbacks, but by the entire conduct of the White House
during this investigation,'' he said. ``In prior investigations in
the face of criminal charges, every president has waived privileges
and directed his staff to testify, including Richard Nixon.''
</P>
<P>
   The court decisions in Starr's investigation have drawn clear
lines around legal issues that most think were better left fuzzy.
Even so, many legal scholars are hard-pressed to disagree with the
rulings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't that these decisions are necessarily wrong,'' said
Abner Mikva, former Clinton White House counsel now teaching law at
the University of Illinois at Chicago. ``It's that we have pushed
these legal propositions to the extreme. Hard cases make bad law.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton can still consult his private attorneys, and he has two
from the best law firms in town. Attorney-client privlege protects
those private lawyers from divulging their confidential
conversations with Clinton, just as it would for any lawyer hired
by the average American.
</P>
<P>
   This president, any president, also retains the right to wield
the powerful tool of executive privilege, which allows the
country's chief executive to claim certain information as
off-limits. Though a federal judge has ruled against the president
on this issue, the White House may yet test it again in court.
</P>
<P>
   The legal rulings regarding privilege could further isolate the
office of the presidency by limiting the candid advice needed from
White House aides, Clinton's supporters say.
</P>
<P>
   In one scenario, a White House lawyer's memos to the president
about a possible nominee might become less explicit. If, for
example, a nominee contributed to the president's election campaign
and later was involved in a criminal investigation, the White House
lawyer could be summoned to testify about his advice to the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Garment, who was a White House counsel to Nixon during
Watergate, said his former boss started the ``ball rolling'' by
prompting the independent counsel law. ``It's one of the things he
lamented to me and other people thereafter. He said he really got
them boiled up in the country,'' Garment said. ``Anytime a
president becomes embroiled in litigation, the presidency is
terribly weakened.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Charles O. Jones, a scholar of the presidency at the
University of Wisconsin, said the presidency will bounce back.
``The system has incredible recuperative powers,'' he said. ``We
thought, following Watergate, that the presidency would never be
restored or would take a great long time to be. That just wasn't
so.''
</P>
<P>
   Future presidents will still have the option of invoking
executive privilege for goverment lawyers if they face legal
challenges to their official duties, said Peter J. Wallison, a
White House counsel to Reagan during Iran-Contra. ``I don't see all
this about the presidency being diminished as having any
validity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Zelikow, a former US career diplomat who taught until
recently at Harvard University's Kennedy School of Government,
agrees. He said he is ``struggling to think of a circumstance for
how you could repeat this precedence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a supporter of presidential power,'' said Zelikow, who now
heads the University of Virgina's Miller Center of Public Affairs.
``I just have a different notion of what I want the president to
have the power to do. None of this, so far, is a problem for me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
