<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6911 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-MAIN11-COX     08-10 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-MAIN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves-Padres series a probable prelude to October
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ They each have made a mockery of their divisions.
They have arrived at August's doldrums winning almost by rote. Now
the Atlanta Braves and San Diego Padres simply are buying time for
October.
</P>
<P>
   Denny Neagle isn't buying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody tries to give the same old cliches about this being
just another game,'' Neagle said, ``but it is important to go into
these three games and prove something to ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves and Padres open a three-game series tonight at
Qualcomm Stadium, with Neagle (11-9) facing Joey Hamilton (9-9).
The night begins an 11-day stretch in which the two best teams in
the National League play each other five times. And while these
games are meaningless in some ways, they also can mean plenty, from
home-field advantage through the playoffs to the mind-games that go
on at baseball's highest level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard plenty of guys saying in the locker room that we
need to go out and prove to ourselves that we're ready for
competition,'' Neagle said. ``Because, let's face it _ barring some
freak things, we could be squaring off against these guys, whether
in the divisional series or the NLCS.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres' rise this season has been the story of the National
League. San Diego went into Monday night's game against Florida
with 76 wins, matching its season's total from a year ago. San
Diego has picked up nine games on the rest of the NL West just
since the All-Star break. A chance exists that Andy Ashby could win
the Cy Young, Greg Vaughn could win the MVP, closer Trevor Hoffman
could win the Rolaids Award, Bruce Bochy could be manager of the
year and GM Kevin Towers could win executive of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it could happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we have a tremendous record (79-39),'' Braves
catcher Javy Lopez said. ``But when I look back, I see the Padres
right behind us (76-41). They're playing great.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves took three of four from San Diego in early May and
have dominated the Padres throughout the decade. Atlanta is 16-5 at
Qualcomm since 1994. But this club is different and has been
waiting for this series to measure itself against Atlanta again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we can beat a team before we play them,''
Neagle said, ``but when I played with Pittsburgh, the Braves were
such a dominant team. It's not that way anymore, or at least I
don't think so. I don't think the San Diego Padres are moaning,
'Oh, Neagle and Maddux or whatever.'
</P>
<P>
   ``They got a pretty good rotation to match up against us.
They've got, in my opinion, the best closer in the game. And
they've got one of the toughest lineups in the NL this year. I've
always said when you come around to August and you play a series
like this, it means a lot. You want to establish in your mind, hey,
look, we want to play some good ball games against this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
