<P>
   AFRICA-TERRORISM (Nairobi, Kenya) _ Lede-all on the bombings: As
the United States offered a $2 million reward for information about
the U.S. embassy bombings, witnesses told of a truck that may have
carried the Nairobi bomb. Officials from the CIA and the FBI are
evaluating leads that include a terrorist manifesto delivered in
Cairo and reports of vague warnings that an Islamic terrorist group
might be planning an attack. And CIA officials, convening here in a
borrowed office, mourned one of their colleagues, who died in the
explosion. 1,300 words. By Tim Weiner. (This story is scheduled to
move by 8:30 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-U.S. (Washington) _ A Kenyan guard at the shattered
American embassy in Nairobi and others who saw a light truck
approach the embassy compound minutes before the explosion that
killed an estimated 200 people may provide important clues to the
identify of the terrorists who carried out the attack. 1,000 words.
By Philip Shenon. (Story has moved.)
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-FUNERAL (Dar Es Salaam, Tanzania) _ Mtendje Rajabu was
laid to rest Monday, three days after a terrorist bomb killed her
at the American Embassy here, and only hours after American
forensic experts finally finished inspecting her body for evidence.
The bodies of the others killed in the bomb blast were also
released to their families, so that their simple but emotional
funerals could proceed. By Jane Perlez. (Scheduled to move by 8
p.m.) 800 words.
</P>
