<SLUG> BC-MOB-HEARINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNOLLY HOPED BULGER `NEVER CAUGHT,' AGENT TESTIFIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When former FBI agent John Connolly was interviewed by
a pair of agents who were tracking down fugitive James ``Whitey''
Bulger, his prized informant, Connolly told them he hoped Bulger
was ``never caught,'' one of the agents testified Monday in federal
court.
</P>
<P>
   During that interview, which took place at Connolly's executive
office at Boston Edison in March of 1997, more than two years after
Bulger had disappeared, Connolly told the agents that former
supervisor John Morris &UR;  &LR; had promised Bulger and criminal sidekick
Stephen Flemmi protection from prosecution because they were such
``good informants,'' according to testimony from Agent Walter J.
Steffens Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Connolly also shared an anecdote about how Bulger bought him and
his young buddies ice cream cones at a South Boston soda fountain
when he was a kid, Steffens said. Connolly said he planned to use
the story in the first chapter of the book he hoped to write on his
relationship with the notorious South Boston crime boss.
</P>
<P>
   Yet nothing Connolly said that day was included in an FBI report
filed after the meeting or in a series of reports compiled last
summer after US Justice Department investigators began an inquiry
into the Boston FBI's dealings with its top criminal informants.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until this past June that the full details of that
March 21, 1997 meeting among Connolly and FBI agents Walter J.
Steffens Jr. and Charles Gianturco were written down -- and turned
over to defense attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  The lawyers are entitled to see statements that could support
Flemmi's claim that he and Bulger were given immunity from
prosecution in exchange for information they provided the FBI as
informants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are FBI agents trained or instructed to leave out information
that might be helpful to a potential defendant?'' asked US District
Judge Mark L. Wolf, who is considering whether to dismiss charges
against Flemmi.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, your honor,'' Steffens replied.
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi's co-defendants, New England Mafia boss Francis P.
Salemme, Mafia soldier Robert DeLuca, and Winter Hill Gang member
John Martorano are challenging whether the government legally used
several wiretaps and bugs, including one that captured a Mafia
induction ceremony in Medford in 1989. Steffens helped prepare the
affidavit used to get that bug.
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning by Flemmi's lawyer, Kenneth J. Fishman,
Steffens said he accompanied Gianturco to Connolly's office.
</P>
<P>
   Besides what Steffens called ``the ice cream cone story,''
Connolly ``also told us that he hoped Mr. Bulger was never
caught,'' Steffens testified. Connolly went on to describe a dinner
party that he, Bulger and Flemmi attended at Morris's Lexington
home at which Morris was ``in his cups.
</P>
<P>
   According to Connolly, Morris told Bulger and Flemmi ``that they
were so good (as informants) that he could get them off for
anything short of murder,'' Steffens testified.
</P>
<P>
   Morris, who testified earlier in the hearings under a grant of
immunity, denied ever giving Bulger and Flemmi permission to commit
any crime other than murder.
</P>
<P>
   Connolly has refused to testify without immunity but reiterated
in a telephone interview Monday that Bulger and Flemmi were
authorized to continue their loansharking and gambling operations
while working as FBI informants, but nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   In his conversation with Steffens and Gianturco, Connolly said,
``I made it clear to them that (Bulger and Flemmi) were indicted
for things they were guaranteed they would not be indicted for ...
(Bulger) probably felt he was framed by the government ... What
ever happened to keeping your word?''
</P>
<P>
   Connolly said his literary agent is sifting through several book
offers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
