A6919 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRICA-BOMBINGS-NYT &LR;      08-10 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-BOMBINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. LAW ENFORCEMENT, INTELLIGENCE TEAMS SEEK DEBRIS FOR CLUES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: AFRICA-TERRORISM, AFRICA-U.S., AFRICA-FUNERAL,
AFRICA-DEAD, AFRICA-SURVIVE) 
(JT) 
 By RAYMOND BONNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ As rescue teams dug through the deep rubble of
a collapsed building on Monday in a final, desperate search for
victims of the bombing at the American Embassy here, American law
enforcement and intelligence teams began sifting through the
scattered debris, in an equally painstaking search for the tiniest
clue that might provide evidence about the perpetrators.
</P>
<P>
   Across Haile Selassie Avenue from the embassy and the collapsed
Ufundi House office building, FBI agents, wearing their agency's
logo on hard hats or baseball caps, wielded rakes and shovels on
the first full day of their demanding investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Their task will be frustrated by the need to sift through many
rumors, the difficulties compounded by the fact that many
individuals close enough to the site to have been witnesses
probably died in the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   At least 192 people were killed in the explosion, according to
the Kenyan government. At the U.S. Embassy, 12 Americans and 27
Kenyans were killed. Fears that the toll of Kenyan employees might
rise diminished considerably on Monday when the embassy determined
that 9 were still missing; on Sunday it had put the number over 30.
</P>
<P>
   In a solemn military ceremony at Jomo Kenyatta airport on Monday
afternoon, American soldiers in camouflage uniforms loaded 11
flag-draped coffins onto a giant Galaxy cargo plane for the flight
to Frankfurt and eventually to the United States. The 12th American
victim, Jean Dalizu, was married to a Kenyan and will be buried
here.
</P>
<P>
   There were no speeches, no sounds other than the distant murmur
of aircraft as Prudence Bushnell, the American ambassador, paid
tribute to her fallen colleagues with her bandaged hand over heart,
and the soldiers saluted.
</P>
<P>
   Back in downtown Nairobi there was a brief glimmer of hope for a
miracle: that a woman who has become known among rescuers as Rose
might still be alive under the tons of concrete and twisted steel
that was once Ufundi House, adjacent to the embassy. At midday, the
Israeli and Kenyan rescue teams that have been working around the
clock stopped briefly when they thought they heard tapping, but
then they resumed clearing the site.
</P>
<P>
   As the possibility that someone was still alive under the debris
seemed to fade, they moved less gingerly. Thick dust filled the air
as cranes and bulldozers tore away a 20-foot-high mound of rubble.
Workers said they hoped to be finished by late on Monday evening or
early on Tuesday. By late on Monday night, they said they had
virtually given up hope of finding survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of students held a vigil at the site on Monday night,
many of them carrying candles or waving palm leaves or flowers. But
as they marched some chanted: ``Down with the Americans! Down with
the Arabs! Down with the terrorists!'' Their leader said they were
protesting the location of embassies in the center of the city.
</P>
<P>
   While the rescuers' work is almost over, the investigators are
just beginning. On the lawn of the stately headquarters of the
Kenya Railways Corp., across the street from the embassy, FBI
agents raked the grass and combed through it on their hands and
knees looking for anything that could be a clue.
</P>
<P>
   A sense of the awaiting difficulties and frustrations was
present in a conversation with two senior officers of the
Cooperative Bank, just behind the American Embassy.
</P>
<P>
   One of the men, dressed in a white shirt, tie and sport coat,
said he had heard gunfire and three blasts. The other, wearing a
suit and a gauze mask over his face because of the dust, disagreed
with his colleague. It had been two blasts and no gunfire, he was
certain.
</P>
<P>
   As the men talked, employees were bringing out computer
equipment that had survived even though every window in the
high-rise building had been blown out. On Monday, there was a
momentary panic when shrapnel fell from one of the higher floors,
and there were fears that the building might collapse.
</P>
<P>
   The sound of glass being swept up marked the work in the
low-rise shops in the vicinity of the embassy, as life here
returned to normal. The streets were bustling with pedestrians, and
most shops were open.
</P>
<P>
   But there was an undercurrent of tension and fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm worried about putting glass back in again,'' said Sonny
Wanjigi, general manager of an office equipment company whose shop
windows were blown out.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Njoroge, an employee in the Nairobi water department, was
at the end of a two-block-long line outside the Kenya Commercial
Bank. His face was bandaged, from injuries suffered in the blast.
``I'm scared right now, just standing here,'' he said. ``Anything
can happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
