<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KIDS-SWITCHED-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY LOVE DOESN'T SWITCH  
 (THIS EDITORIAL WILL APPEAR IN TUESDAY'S ARIZONA REPUBLIC) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Tragedy on top of tragedy unfolds with this story that
begins three years ago when two blonde, blue-eyed girls born at the
same Virginia hospital were sent home with the wrong mothers.
</P>
<P>
   And so apparently does triumph.
</P>
<P>
   Callie Johnson lost her biological parents, but she still has
her mom. Rebecca Chittum is not an orphan, even though the parents
who have loved her since the day she was born died in a July 4 car
accident. She is blessed with caring and sensible grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   The families are teaching a world audience nosing in on a very
private matter important lessons in love and humility. If we're
going to watch, we ought to learn.
</P>
<P>
   Both toddlers' relatives, blood or not, show the wonderful human
capacity, too rarely seen, to do what's best for the children. At
this early stage of a tragedy when shock and anger often compound
matters, both families appear focused on their precious gifts.
Neither side wants to wipe away either child's identity.
</P>
<P>
   Callie and Rebecca are loved for who they are. Children whose
identities are unquestioned should be so blessed.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody makes mistakes. Most of the worst mistakes hurt
children. Good people try to suffer through mistakes, to right
wrongs as best they can _ to forgive.
</P>
<P>
   The families of Rebecca and Callie are good people. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
