A6925 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      08-10 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS MANAGEMENT NOT RUSHING TO JUDGMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ After the Patriots' second straight exhibition loss,
vice president of business operations Andy Wasynczuk says the team
will not panic and abandon its current crop of running backs and
cornerbacks until there's more evidence that the personnel in place
can't do the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still early in the preseason and we can't overreact
right now,'' said Wasynczuk. ``We need to play better, and the
coaching staff and football people are going over things and taking
a look at what's happened the past two games to see if they can
make the proper adjustments to put us on a better course.''
</P>
<P>
   Some would say the Patriots have played Russian roulette with
their roster. They traded cornerback Jimmy Hitchcock because they
thought they had a veteran in Steve Israel to fall back on while
Tebucky Jones was learning the position. But Israel's recovery from
knee surgery is still ongoing and may last into the regular season.
That has led to Plan B: Chris Canty. Oops.
</P>
<P>
   After losing Curtis Martin as a restricted free agent _
declining to match the New York Jets' offer _ they felt second-year
running back Sedrick Shaw or first-round pick Robert Edwards could
do the job. Oops again. Shaw hasn't proven anything, and Edwards
has been injured. While the Patriots were experimenting with the
Shaws (Sedrick and Harold), Edwards, Derrick Cullors, and even free
agent pickup Robert Green, other teams were signing Greg Hill and
Raymont Harris, two runners who might have been able to step in and
play right away.
</P>
<P>
   Now what?
</P>
<P>
   In two exhibition games, the Patriots have averaged 2.8 yards
per carry. Is the problem the backs or the line or both? There are
three games to solve the problem before the Patriots open the
season in Denver Sept. 7. What if Edwards isn't well enough to
play? What if the injuries continue?
</P>
<P>
   What options do the Patriots have?
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have conclusive evidence right now to jump into
signing other personnel,'' said Wasynczuk. ``Edwards has been out
with an injury and the two Shaws have only played two games.''
</P>
<P>
   In Green Bay, contract talks with holdout running back Dorsey
Levens haven't gone anywhere. Levens is looking for a significant
raise _ something slightly less than Martin got _ after one
breakthrough season. Could the Patriots get Levens for a No. 1
draft pick next year (they have two of them, thanks to Bill
Parcells)?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, trades are rare in the NFL, and doing something that
drastic would be a sign of panic and perhaps admitting a mistake.
The Patriots are also trying to sign Ted Johnson to a long-term
contract and would have to bump his $403,000 salary this season to
do it.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have been cool about the situation, strolling
through minicamp, training camp, and two exhibitions as if what
they have is good enough to compete in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Kirby remains in waiting in Miami. He has drawn interest
from Kansas City, Oakland, San Francisco, and Tampa Bay. The
Patriots have continually told his agent, Mike Battle, ``We'll call
you if we need you.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, after watching the Patriots struggle for the second
consecutive week, Battle phoned Wasynczuk.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Terry's sake, he really can't wait beyond this week,''
said Battle. ``He wants to get with a team right now. He's been
patient and I've asked him to be patient so we can see what
situations develop where he might have the best and biggest role.
He doesn't want to go somewhere and be a third-down back only. He
wants to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andy said that he wished he could have said, `No, the Patriots
won't be interested in Terry,' but he said he thought the football
people wanted to give it one more week in Mexico to see if
something could emerge. I don't think we'll wait that long.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirby, who is Chris Slade's cousin, has never been a No. 1 back.
He's been effective as a third-down back because he's a superb pass
receiver. After the 49ers let Ricky Watters go, he gave them some
threat of a running game, a threat the Patriots do not have this
morning. Kirby played for San Francisco when Pete Carroll was the
defensive coordinator there, and Carroll earlier seemed to lean
toward Kirby as a player who could add something to the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Also out there is former Giant Rodney Hampton. He has been a No.
1 back, but he's an eight-year veteran. He runs straight-ahead, no
nonsense, and has the savvy to pick up extra yardage when there's
seemingly nothing there. The current stable of Patriots backs sees
nothing there and can't make anything happen.
</P>
<P>
   Also available: Herschel Walker.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots offensive coordinator Ernie Zampese, who had Walker in
Dallas, is a big fan, and Walker would definitely add veteran
leadership in what would be his 13th season.
</P>
<P>
   A sorrier state of options is available for defensive backs.
Former Bear and Steeler Donnell Woolford remains a free agent. The
Patriots brought him in for a look this spring. Scooter McGruder is
running a couple of Blockbuster Video stores in the Atlanta area.
Terry Ray is available.
</P>
<P>
   The best option appears to be watching the waiver wire to see if
anyone better than Jones, Canty, Steve Lofton, Kato Serwanga, or
Terry Billups becomes available. Of course, if teams are cutting
veteran cornerbacks, chances are they aren't better than what the
Patriots already have.
</P>
<P>
   While Wasynczuk is correct in pointing out how early it is,
panic has gripped some corners of Patriots Nation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
