<HEADLINE>
CONGOLESE GOVERNMENT TROOPS CLAIM FIRST SUCCESS AGAINST REBELS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast _ Claiming its first major success against
a week-old insurrection, Congolese officials said on Monday that
government troops had succeeded in beating back rebels who had
captured several strategic towns in the southwest of the country,
encircling many of them at a rebel-held military base.
</P>
<P>
   According to the government's account of the fighting, which is
largely supported by Western diplomats, troops loyal to President
Laurent Kabila operating out of the town of Boma have contained the
rebel forces in an area between the coastal towns of Banana and
Kitona, where fighting between both sides continues.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-government forces opened a western front in the war
last Tuesday, when in a surprise maneuver, they flew hundreds of
rebels by commandeered aircraft to Kitona from the far-eastern city
of Goma, one of the first Congolese towns to fall under rebel
control.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila's government has charged that the airlift was
masterminded by neighboring Rwanda, which it says is sponsoring the
uprising. The two countries had previously been close allies, and
Rwandan forces are widely seen as having borne the brunt of the
fighting in a previous rebellion that brought Kabila to power in
May 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's loss of Kitona, the site of one of western Congo's
most important military bases, was seen by most military analysts
as a dramatic setback for Kabila's government, after the quick fall
of several major eastern cities at the start of the war.
</P>
<P>
   From its toehold there, many analysts predicted that the rebels
would quickly seize control of the Congo's only sea port, and move
rapidly toward the capital, Kinshasa, to the northwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kabila's forces do indeed seem as if they are having some
success in the southwest,'' a European diplomat said. ``It is hard
to know exactly what is going on there, but the rebels certainly
don't seem to be advancing.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, residents of Kinshasa said conditions on the main
highway to the sea seemed normal, at least as far as the major port
city of Matadi, which is the railhead for sea traffic and supplies
the capital with most of its imports and many food supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spoke to my sister this morning in Matadi, and she was
leaving by road for Kinshasa today,'' said Roger Kabue, a Congolese
trader reached by telephone. ``People are going about their lives
normally there, it seems.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing heavily on the allegations of Rwandan involvement in the
uprising, Kabila's government has had great success in recruiting
new members into the country's army, and has managed to turn the
conflict, for many Congolese, into a question of national
resistance against foreign domination.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Witnesses in Kinshasa said Monday that for the second
consecutive day a government enlistment drive had signed up at
least 5,000 volunteers for the war effort.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila's government has generated strong support by claiming
that the uprising is the work of Congolese of Tutsi descent and of
the Rwandan and Ugandan governments. The Tutsi are a tiny minority
in Congo and are a minority also in Rwanda, but control the
government and armed forces in that country.
</P>
<P>
   Uganda, another former supporter of Kabila and ally of Rwanda,
has denied any involvement in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, Western diplomats and international human rights
groups have expressed concern over reports of widespread arrests
and other abuses of Congolese and Rwandan Tutsi in Kinshasa by the
government, as it whips people up for the war effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot let a bunch of Tutsi take over our country,'' Kabue
said. ``Rwanda is a tiny country compared to the Congo. They should
have known better than to have provoked us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
