<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Tuesday, Aug. 11. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-TERRORISM (Nairobi, Kenya) _ Lede-all on the bombings: As
the United States offers a $2 million reward for information about
the U.S. embassy bombings, witnesses tell of a truck that may have
carried the Nairobi bomb. Officials from the CIA and the FBI are
evaluating leads that include a terrorist manifesto delivered in
Cairo and reports of vague warnings that an Islamic terrorist group
might be planning an attack. And CIA officials, convening here in a
borrowed office, mourn one of their colleagues, who died in the
explosion. By Tim Weiner. (We plan to move the story by 8:30 p.m.
ET in ``i'' news file.) 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   Story runs next to 3-column photo.
</P>
<P>
   With: AFRICA-BOMBINGS, AFRICA-U.S., other sidebars inside.
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   INDEPENDENT-COUNSELS (Los Angeles) _ They are a rarefied roster
of not quite two dozen, the men and women who have served as
independent counsel investigating high level government officials
over the past 20 years. And they describe it as one of the
loneliest jobs in the world. But now the law has come under attack
as almost never before. Interviews last week with seven of the
people who have held the job since it was created by the Ethics in
Government Act of 1978 in the wake of Watergate produced broad
consensus that the law is needed but may have to be overhauled
substantially if it is to be renewed by Congress when it expires
next year. By Todd S. Purdum. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in
``a'' news file.) 2,100 words.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-MURDER (Chicago) _ Chicago is reeling as two boys, seven
and eight years old, are charged with first degree murder in the
killing of an 11-year-old apparently killed for her bicycle. By Pam
Belluck. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   WAGE-REBATES (Undated) _ Since the 1950s, state governments have
lured corporations with expensive incentives such as free
factories, canceled property taxes, low-interest loans, free access
roads and special tax credits. Now in the 1990s, the competition
among states and even Mexico to attract companies has spawned a new
incentive, one strikingly uncharacteristic for a for a free-market
economy: wage rebates. By Louis Uchitelle. (The story has moved in
``f'' news file.) With map. 2,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   Reefer to: MEDICARE-HMOS (Washington) _ An investigative report
on Medicare payments to HMOs. By Robert Pear. (Scheduled to move by
9 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   MET-ROTHSCHILD (New York) _ The Metropolitan Museum's
retrospective on a little-known artist, the late Judith Rothschild,
raises a question of whether the museum's interest in her family
foundation's art holdings is the reason? By Judith H. Dobrzynski.
(The story has moved in ``e'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-REPUBS (Washington) _ Republicans go home for summer
with divisions as deep, though not as vocal, as last year's. Fault
lines between social conservatives and business conservatives get
deeper and mess up all kinds of legislation. By Alison Mitchell.
(The story has moved in ``w'' news file.) 1,250 words.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   MCDOUGAL-TRIAL (Los Angeles) _ After years of delays and legal
wrangling, jury selection began today in Susan McDougal's
embezzlement trial in a Santa Monica courthouse. By Don Terry. (The
story has moved in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-LIVENT (Undated) _ Livent Inc., the Toronto-based theater
company and producer of such Broadway shows as ``Ragtime'' and
``Show Boat,'' announces that an internal investigation has found
serious accounting problems involving millions of dollars.
(Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.) With sidebar.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-BEANIE-BABIES (New York) _ Baseball's beanie baby promotions
and how they almost guarantee a sellout as sports' hottest
promotional giveaway. Forget Mark McGwire, Sammy Sosa, Ken Griffey
Jr., Kerry Wood and Juan Gonzalez _ baseball's real stars this
season, the ones almost guaranteed to pack the house, are Peanut,
Glory, Stretch, Valentino, Derby, Chip and Tuffy, baseball's
fuzziest saviors. By Richard Sandomir. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m.
ET in ``s'' news file.)
</P>
