<HEADLINE>
JOBS, `OUTSOURCING' STICKING POINTS IN PHONE WORKER STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Future jobs and the contracting of non-union workers continued
to be major issues in negotiations Monday between Bell Atlantic
Corp. and 73,000 striking telephone workers.
</P>
<P>
   As talks continued late Monday, the second day of a potentially
crippling walkout, members of the Communications Workers of America
used picket lines to focus attention on union demands for a cap on
subcontracting and greater opportunity for CWA workers to move into
future jobs involving the Internet, cable, multimedia, wireless
communications and other new technology.
</P>
<P>
   Customer service representatives, phone operators, installation
workers and other CWA members walked off their jobs in 13 Eastern
states and Washington, D.C. after the expiration of a three-year
contract at 12:01 a.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   CWA represents 2,800 customer representatives in New England.
</P>
<P>
   A second union, the International Brotherhood of Electrical
Workers, is dominant in New England, where it represents some
17,000 technicians, installers and operators. IBEW members honored
the CWA picket lines, although IBEW workers stayed on the job in
places without picketers.
</P>
<P>
   The IBEW is negotiating a separate contract with Bell Atlantic,
but said it expects to have an agreement soon.
</P>
<P>
   There were some signs the strike could be short-lived.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials said they have introduced a proposal that
``meets all the (CWA) demands,'' and seemed hopeful an accord would
be reached at any moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The offer we are currently negotiating addresses all the
union's concerns,'' John Johnson, a Bell Atlantic spokesman in
Boston, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking from a hotel room in New York, Melissa Morin, president
of CWA Local 1400, which represents 2,800 customer service
representatives in New England, said negotiators had reached an
agreement on overtime, flexible scheduling, and other work-life
issues. But she added: ``We are still looking for guarantees that
our people will have access to future jobs when the company expands
into other fields. And we are still concerned about the outsourcing
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The union notes that even as the Internet and other new
technologies are creating new work, jobs are being shifted to
non-union contractors and non-union subsidiaries. Morin estimated
that at least 50 new subsidiaries have been created by Bell
Atlantic over the past year.
</P>
<P>
   CWA contends that Bell Atlantic has moved the management of
200,000 accounts from New Jersey and Pennsylvania to outside
offices.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic declined to discuss the outsourcing issue Monday,
saying the matter should not go beyond the bargaining table.
Tensions rose last year, however, when the company created Bell
Atlantic Plus, a subsidiary in Norfolk, Va. The nonunion
telemarketing center is staffed by customer service representatives
who earn, on average, $7 per hour and receive no benefits, union
officials said. Unionized customer service representatives
currently earn $21 per hour, with a full benefits package, the
union sources added.
</P>
<P>
   The Bell Atlantic strike is among several job actions in recent
years that have stemmed from labor's attempts to limit employers'
use of subcontractors and outsourcing to boost profits and slash
labor costs.
</P>
<P>
   Such fights are likely to continue as outsourcing spreads among
big US firms. This year alone, more than $140 billion will be spent
on outsourcing services, up from $100 billion in 1996, according to
a report by The Outsourcing Institute in New York. Not surprising,
information technology firms such as Bell Atlantic are the leading
users of outsourcing and represent approximately 30 percent of all
outsourcing expenditures, according to the Outsourcing Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that outsource tend to have ``complex and constantly
changing processes or functions,'' said Frank Casale, executive
director of the institute. ``It would take so much money and
manpower to master all of these functions so why even bother?
That's why companies are outsourcing.''
</P>
<P>
   From General Motors Corp. to Boeing Co., CHK outsourcing has
been a key issue at the bargaining table as companies move to
streamline and unions fight to retain jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, GM and the United Auto Workers fought during a strike
over the company's right to transfer steel wheel assembly to an
outside contractor, a move that eliminated 80 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, nearly 4,000 workers threatened to strike at Ford Motor
Co. on several issues, including the automaker's decision to
subcontract seat-making work to Johnson Controls. And at Boeing
plants around Seattle and Portland, Ore., the issue of job security
and outsourcing has led to labor unrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``For labor unions, contracting out or outsourcing will be the
major fight over the next five to 10 years,'' said Thomas Juravich,
a labor expert at the UMass Amherst. ``Companies say it's
inevitable, that this is the way globalization is moving.''
</P>
<P>
   As Bell Atlantic and other phone companies adopt Internet
technology and build sophisticated new networks to handle voice and
data traffic, new jobs ranging from software designers to computer
networking technicians are being created. But union officials fear
their workers will be shut out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call them the jobs of the future,'' CWA spokeswoman Candice
Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials also fear that increased competition from new,
nimble rivals may drive Bell Atlantic to farm out many of these
technical jobs to non-union subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Bell Atlantic serves 27 million customers from Maine to
Virginia, providing them with telecommunications, wireless
communications, cable, digital TV, Internet and data services.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which plans to merge with GTE Corp., was formed
from the union of the orginal Bell Atlantic and Nynex, two of the
so-called Baby Bells that were spun off from AT&AMP;T in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
