<HEADLINE>
TANZANIAN GUARD ON DUTY AT U.S. EMBASSY WHEN BOMB EXPLODED IS LAID
TO REST 
</HEADLINE>
   (See related AFRICA-BOMBINGS, AFRICA-SURVIVE, AFRICA-DEAD,
AFRICA-TERRORISM, AFRICA-U.S.)  
 (JT)  
 By JANE PERLEZ    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAR ES SALAAM, Tanzania _ Mtendje Rajabu was laid to rest on
Monday in a deep, sandy grave under a grove of coconut trees, three
days after a terrorist bomb killed her as she stood on duty at the
entrance to the American Embassy in a snappy uniform with red
epaulets on her small shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday morning, the American forensic experts with their bags
of equipment and the Tanzanian radiologists had finally finished
inspecting her body for the smallest hints that might aid in the
hunt for the attackers.
</P>
<P>
   Draped in a bloody and torn sheet, the body of Ms. Rajabu, 31,
who used to have a smile for everyone, was handed over to her
grieving husband, Shaban. He, their two young sons and an extended
family of aunts and uncles and friends had waited long hours for
the body under a hot sun on the mortuary grounds.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd filled two open trucks and several cars and
immediately left to follow the coffin, placed on the back of a
pickup truck and draped in a ceremonial black and gold cloth, for
the ride to Mrs. Rajabu's ancestral village on the capital's
outskirts.
</P>
<P>
   On the way, the procession wound through the bustle of city
streets, stopped to gather neighbors at Mrs. Rajabu's usual bus
stop and then threaded its way through the tracks of Segerea, the
village where generations of her family have been buried.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies of the others killed in the bomb blast were also
released by the forensic experts on Monday, and, for the most part,
simple but emotional funerals were held. Among the nine who died
were Abdurahman Abdalla, a Kenyan who is married to an American,
Susan Hirsch, and three Tanzanian colleagues of Mrs. Rajabu who had
worked with her as security guards.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the focus was on Mrs. Rajabu, because she seemed
to rejoice in the job of greeting American diplomats and visitors
who passed by her reception desk at the outdoor guardhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had a wonderful, big smile,'' said John Lange, the charge
d'affaires at the embassy. ``She was well known and loved around
the embassy.''
</P>
<P>
   Her cousin Rashid Khamis, 31, an air traffic controller,
described her as effervescent and a woman of great warmth. ``I wish
you could see the picture of when she got married,'' he said. ``She
looked like an angel.''
</P>
<P>
   In this impoverished society, working at the American Embassy
was a big deal, no matter how lowly the post. It meant security and
prestige.
</P>
<P>
   But for Mrs. Rajabu, her husband said, it was not enough to be a
guard for a privately run firm, Ultimate Security, which had a
contract with the embassy. On the morning of her death, she left
home with a bigger ambition on her mind: to work directly for the
American government inside the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was to be interviewed that Friday for a job as a telephone
operator,'' Rajabu said. ``She was happy and excited. She spoke
excellent English, and at night she was taking secretarial courses
to improve her skills.
</P>
<P>
   Rajabu said that when he heard the explosion at the embassy last
Friday, he rushed to the morgue, knowing that his wife was in an
exposed position and fearing that she was among the dead. An hour
or so later, he saw her body, still in the uniform she liked so
much, emerge from a van.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew as soon as I saw her,'' he said. ``She had only a cut
on her head. She still had her identity card here,'' he said,
pointing to the left side of his chest. Apparently, she was thrown
to the ground and killed instantly.
</P>
<P>
   When Mrs. Rajabu's coffin arrived at the tin-roofed home of her
parents, several hundred people were waiting under a canopy of
towering mango trees. The women in the crowd greeted her with a
chorus of wails and paid their last respects to her coffin in the
privacy of the house. The men gathered outside on straw mats laid
out on the earth and listened to the Imam from the local mosque
offer prayers. ``We hope she died with a peaceful heart,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Large trays of soupy beans, prepared by the women of the
village, were served to the men before they lifted Mrs. Rajabu for
the walk to the freshly dug grave on the edge of the village.
</P>
<P>
   There, according to the Islamic tradition here, Mrs. Rajabu's
body was removed from the coffin and wreathed in a white shroud.
Her body was lowered into the six-foot-deep grave, where her
husband covered her body with layers and layers of grass. Then,
with hands and a few shovels, the men of the village filled the
chamber with sand, leaving two stark wooden boards as markers for
her burial place.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Africa, it is very easy to accept death through sickness,''
said Khamis as he walked away. ``But it is very hard when there is
no reason.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
