<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves on deck: San Diego Padres
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ When: Today at 10:05 p.m., Wednesday at 10:35 p.m. and
Thursday at 5:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _ Where: Qualcomm Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   _ TV: TBS will telecast tonight, Fox Sports South Wednesday and
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Probable starting pitchers: Today, LHP Denny Neagle (11-9,
3.73; 4-1, 2.75 lifetime vs. Padres) vs. RHP Joey Hamilton (9-9,
4.70; 1-7, 6.08 lifetime vs. Braves). Wednesday, RHP Greg Maddux
(15-5, 1.53; 18-10, 2.62 lifetime vs. Padres) vs. RHP Andy Ashby
(15-6, 2.55; 3-2, 4.63 lifetime vs. Braves). Thursday, LHP Tom
Glavine (15-4, 2.47; 15-10, 3.75 lifetime vs. Padres) vs. LHP Mark
Langston (4-4, 5.66; 1-0, 0.00 lifetime vs. Braves).
</P>
<P>
   _ Series history: Atlanta leads the all-time series 270-213 and
is 64-27 (.703) against the Padres since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   _ Past meetings: The Braves took three of four from San Diego,
May 7-10. Andres Galarraga had three homers during the series,
while Braves pitchers held the Padres to a .227 average.
</P>
<P>
   _ Padres leaders: Avg.: Tony Gwynn (.325); HRs _ Greg Vaughn
(39); RBIs _ Vaughn (93); SBs _ Quilvio Veras (21). Wins _ Andy
Ashby (15); ERA _ Trevor Hoffman (1.67). Saves _ Hoffman (38).
Strikeouts _ Kevin Brown (180).
</P>
<P>
   _ Quickly: The Padres were 57-31 at the All-Star break, when
they held a 5 1/2-game lead on San Francisco. San Diego has since
gone 19-10, entering Monday's game with Florida, and picked up nine
more games on the fading Giants. The Pods have been in first place
since June 10 and, at 76-41, are on pace to win 105 games. The
franchise record for victories is 92, set in the 1984 World Series
season. . . . The frightening thing is that San Diego is doing it
while hitting just .258, 10th in the NL and the lowest by any Padre
team in the last four years. But improved pitching has made a
tremendous difference. After posting an NL-high 4.99 team ERA last
year, the 1998 Padres have cut it down to 3.68 with the additions
of Kevin Brown, Mark Langston, Dan Miceli, Brian Boehringer and
Donne Wall. . . . The Padres entered Monday night 4-1 on their
current 11-game homestand. Before that, they went 3-4 on a road
trip to New York and Montreal. The NL East has been San Diego's
least-favorite division with a 16-11 (.593) record. Against the NL
West and NL Central, the Padres are 54-23 (.701). . . . The Braves
will miss Brown this trip but will have to face Ashby, who was the
first NL pitcher to win 15 this year. He beat Tom Glavine 3-2 on
May 8, allowing nine hits while striking out only one in eight
innings. Ashby is 5-1 in his last seven starts and is 10-2 dating
back to May 30. ... On the DL: LHP Ed Vosberg (shoulder
tendinitis).
</P>
<P>
   _ Who's hot: Although he lost a game in extra innings to
Philadelphia on Thursday, closer Trevor Hoffman's 38 saves lead the
major leagues. He is four saves away from tying his career high,
set in 1996. Center fielder Steve Finley has hit in seven of his
last eight games.
</P>
<P>
   _ Who's not: 3B Ken Caminti had been in a 2-for-21 skid until
hitting a homer Sunday night. OF Greg Vaughn entered Monday's game
in a 7-for-58 slump that has seen his average drop 27 points to
.283. Vaughn has 21 strikeouts in his last 13 games.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
