<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Steeler Stewart still transforming from athlete to QB
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LATROBE, Pa. _ The majestic tree just beyond the end zone, once
described by author Roy Blount as ``the camp willow,'' was weeping
here last week under an oppressive sun that forced even veteran
visitors to St. Vincent College to seek shady relief.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 yards upfield, Kordell Stewart was crying crocodile
tears, loudly feigning incredulity as new offensive coordinator Ray
Sherman forced the Pittsburgh Steelers young quarterback to
simulate his drop into the pocket and then verbally identify the
coverage in the secondary. Time after time, and without a football
in his hand, Stewart would fade back and focus in. For 20 minutes,
the lone pupil in a class that could have been titled
``Drop-and-Read 101'' continued the tedious exercise.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of the lengthy primer was simple: In 1997, his first
season as the starter and the year in which the former ``Slash''
became more than just an offensive novelty, Stewart proved he could
pass. This season, however, he must pass the next test and
demonstrate to the skeptics that he is more than a wondrously
gifted athlete trying to make himself into an NFL quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``You meet fans when you're out shopping or whatever, and
they'll say, `Oh, you exceeded our expectations last year,' ''
Stewart said, when asked to assess his '97 performance. ``Or
they'll tell you something like, `You're so young; it's only going
to get better.' Don't get me wrong, it's all very heartfelt and I
appreciate the interest. But I expected more from myself last year.
And this year, I expect a ton more. I know everyone is watching.''
</P>
<P>
   In that regard, Stewart, 25, may be fortunate to have Sherman
around to serve as both tutor and confidant.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart is one of five starting quarterbacks of African-American
descent in the NFL, Sherman one of 11 coordinators. Both are record
numbers for the league, but it hardly represents an age of
enlightenment. Sherman aspires to be an NFL head coach and knows
Pittsburgh offers the kind of high-profile position that could
catapult him into consideration. He agrees that his relationship
will be scrutinized.
</P>
<P>
   The Kordell Stewart file
</P>
<P>
   _ Height, weight: 6-1, 212.
</P>
<P>
   _ Born: Oct. 16, 1972, New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   _ High school: John Ehret, Marrero, La.
</P>
<P>
   _ College: Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   _ NFL Draft: Selected by the Pittsburgh Steelers in the second
round of the 1995 draft, 60th pick overall.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
