<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6947 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEVIS-INDEPENDENCE-AR     08-10 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEVIS-INDEPENDENCE-ART-550(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WESTERN HEMISPHERE'S SMALLEST COUNTRY MAY SOON BE EVEN
SMALLER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(js) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTOWN, Nevis, _ Barely two miles of water separate the
pair of islands that make up this tiny Caribbean nation of St.
Kitts and Nevis. But if the 10,000 or so people who live on the
36-square-mile speck of land called Nevis voted as predicted Monday
in a referendum on secession, the smallest country in the Western
Hemisphere will soon be severed in two.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and leaders of other Caribbean nations may
worry that Nevis is too small to stand on its own. But local
leaders here say they cannot wait to leave behind their status as
junior partners to St. Kitts, to take control of their own destiny
and to become an independent state with its own voice at the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people in St. Kitts don't know what the problems are over
here,'' said Vance Amory, the premier of Nevis who has led the
drive for secession. ``Nevis is something they have forgotten
about, and we cannot continue to operate on the basis of tokenism.
The days have passed when we can be told to be quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   On one level, the issue on the ballot in this charming,
cloud-capped island 250 miles southeast of Puerto Rico could not be
simpler and more direct. ``Do you approve of the Nevis secession
bill and Nevis becoming an independent state separate from St.
Kitts?'' voters were asked. Voters in St. Kitts, which has about
36,000 people, were not eligible to take part.
</P>
<P>
   For the proposal to be approved, two-thirds of the ballots cast
must respond in the affirmative. An informal poll conducted by The
St. Kitts-Nevis Observer, a weekly newspaper here, found that more
than 70 percent of potential voters were in favor of secession, and
in a nonbinding ballot conducted back in the 1970s, 80 percent of
the votes cast favored independence.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Denzil Douglas has said he will honor the result
of the vote, whatever it is. ``My government stands ready to assist
with whatever choice you make,'' he said in parliament last week,
so that St. Kitts and Nevis ``can continue to live in harmony and
prosperity.''
</P>
<P>
   But Douglas has also made it clear that he regrets that ``the
secessionist genie is out of the bottle'' and predicted
``disastrous consequences'' if the nation splits apart. To take
such a step, he argued, is an act of provincialism that defies the
logic that has led to the creation of the European Union and a
global economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of St. Kitts and Nevis have more in common than the
people of Germany and France,'' he argued. ``If it were not for the
water that separates us, there would be no justification for
secession.''
</P>
<P>
   To outsiders, the differences between Kittitians and Nevisians,
as residents of the two islands call themselves, are indeed
virtually imperceptible. But Nevisians have always complained about
being forced into union with St. Kitts, a step that Britain took
during colonial rule more than 100 years ago for administrative
convenience, and they have clung to the notion that they have a
separate identity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only two miles of water, but if you travel, you'll find
there's a big difference between the people,'' said Bernard Brooks,
43, who works as a taxi driver in the U.S. Virgin Islands but came
home to vote for secession and take part in summer carnival.
``Nevis people are more gentle, more polite.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   St. Kitts and Nevis became independent of Britain in 1983, with
a constitution that established the country's capital in
Basseterre, on St. Kitts, and created a parliament that reserved
eight seats for St. Kitts and three for Nevis. The charter also
included a provision allowing Nevis to secede unilaterally, and
after much debate, the Nevis Island Assembly last year unanimously
approved a vote on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Since independence, both islands have depended heavily on
tourism and respective offshore financial sectors. But even on
those points there are disagreements, with people in Nevis
complaining that St. Kitts is trying to strangle the Nevis economy
with offshore legislation and that too much of the revenues that
Nevis generates from upscale tourism remain on the other island.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nevis is for high net worth individuals,'' attracting
Hollywood celebrities and English royalty, explained Mark Brantley,
an Oxford-educated Nevis lawyer who has been one of the leaders of
the independence drive. In contrast, he maintained, St. Kitts
attracts ``low-scale package tours, the secretary who saves up all
year for a week in the sun,'' but has the more modern airport.
</P>
<P>
   The vote is being watched with some anxiety by members of the
Caribbean Community, or Caricom, a regional trade and political
grouping of 16 small and predominantly English-speaking nations.
Several of those nations are also multi-island states whose smaller
components have been known to chafe at their status, among them
Trinidad and Tobago, Antigua and Barbuda and St. Vincent and the
Grenadines, and there are fears that secession fever could spread.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a source of great concern to us if there is to be a
fragmentation of St. Kitts and Nevis and a creation of yet another
micro-mini-state in our region when all the implications and
dangers that it entails come at a time when we are to integrate and
not disintegrate,'' Edwin Carrington, secretary-general of the
group, said last week. He called the vote here the region's most
serious challenge since the American invasion of Grenada in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, evidently alarmed at the prospect of the
emergence of a ministate that might be vulnerable to the pressures
or blandishments of drug cartels, has echoed those worries.
``Maintaining the federation would be more compatible with the
trend toward greater regional integration, with all its
considerable benefits and advantages,'' State Department spokesman
James Rubin said recently.
</P>
<P>
   But premier Amory rejected any suggestion that Nevis will be
worse off on its own. ``Size is not an indication of viability,''
he said in an interview. ``There are some large countries in Africa
that are not viable states,'' while several small island states,
among them Singapore, Nauru, and Tonga, are flourishing.
</P>
<P>
   Because of ``technology and the way institutions are
established,'' he added, ``that idea of a critical mass can no
longer be used as a criteria.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who favor remaining in a federation with St. Kitts stress
practical issues, none of which have been negotiated in advance of
the vote. Fishermen wonder whether they will be barred from St.
Kitts' waters, storeowners fear that tariffs may be imposed on
goods moving from one island to the other, and others wonder where
the money will come from to pay for public services.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're in a sufficient state of preparedness,''
said Trevor Chapman, owner of a grocery store here. ``There hasn't
been enough education, and there are still too many unanswered
questions, the primary of which is what will be the source of our
income? It's not going to be no bed of roses.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
