<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-POISON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POISON IS SUSPECTED OF SICKENING 10 IN JAPAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ll) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Ten people in Niigata, a port city on the western coast
of the largest island in the Japanese archipelago, were
hospitalized on Monday morning after drinking tea and coffee made
with hot water that appeared to have been poisoned, police
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The police said the incident could have been a copycat crime
inspired by a poisoning on July 25 in Wakayama, southwest of Tokyo.
In the Wakayama case, four people died and dozens more were ill
after eating curry containing arsenic and possibly cyanide that was
served at a local festival.
</P>
<P>
   Although initial tests of the Niigata victims' vomit showed
traces of cyanide, the police said that further tests had found no
trace of cyanide in the victims' bodily fluids or in the tea or the
water used to make it.
</P>
<P>
   The victims were among 13 workers at the Niigata branch of
Xyence, a company that makes preserved lumber used in construction.
The victims had made themselves tea or coffee after taking part in
morning exercises. Immediately after sipping their drinks, many of
them detected a strange taste and spit the beverages out, the
police said.
</P>
<P>
   They were taken to three local hospitals shortly after 8 a.m.
with symptoms that included fainting, impaired vision, vomiting,
and numbness in the hands and feet.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshiaki Sugai, a division director at Xyence, said that the
Niigata plant used two preservatives in its manufacturing
processes. One, Tanalith CuAz, is in its original state classified
as a deadly poison in Japan. When diluted in water, as it is in
Xyence's manufacturing process, the preservative is not designated
a poison, Sugai said. ``We are cautious in storage and handling,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Wakayama, the police suspect that a community feud may have
led to the poisoning. The victims were two community leaders, as
well as a 10-year-old boy and a 16-year-old girl.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary tests in that case pointed to cyanide poisoning
because cyanide was found in the blood of one of the men who died
and in various samples of vomit.
</P>
<P>
   But later tests, conducted at the National Research Institute of
Police Science, found traces of arsenic in all three pots in which
the curry was served. The institute found no evidence of cyanide,
which could have evaporated before more extensive tests were run,
and the police now suspect that the deaths were caused by arsenic
poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   Arsenic is commonly used in pesticides and for the extermination
of rodents, even though its use in Japan is prohibited.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are still puzzling over how the poison got into
the curry. About 10 percent of the local police force in Wakayama,
or 217 officers, is working on the case.
</P>
<P>
   Poisoning is not uncommon in Japan, where the ownership of guns
is strictly limited. Adding poison to food is a favorite tactic of
extortionists and those seeking revenge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-98 2014EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
