<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6955 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICARE-HMOS-600&AMP;ADD     08-10 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-HMOS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY HMOS `PROFIT EXCESSIVELY' FROM MEDICARE, REPORT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa)  (mk) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Health maintenance organizations have been
receiving more than $1 billion a year in overpayments from the
Medicare trust fund because their administrative costs are ``highly
inflated,'' federal investigators said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Medicare is paying a disproportionate share of HMOs'
administrative costs'' _ much more than its ``fair share'' _ and
the government should try to recover the excess payments, the
inspector general of the Department of Health and Human Services
said in a new report.
</P>
<P>
   The report came at a delicate time for the managed care
industry, which is being encouraged by Congress to play an
increasing role in serving the nation's 38 million Medicare
beneficiaries. Spokesmen for many HMOs have complained in recent
months that the federal government did not pay them enough to care
for Medicare patients, but this and other studies suggest that in
some cases they have been paid too much.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general, June Gibbs Brown, said that many HMOs
``profit excessively'' from Medicare, because they bill the
government for administrative costs attributable to their private
commercial customers as well as their Medicare patients.
</P>
<P>
   In short, she said, HMOs have received ``an unreasonable
amount'' from Medicare because their administrative costs were
grossly and artificially inflated, by a total of $3 billion to $4
billion in the three years of financial reports that she reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy-Ann Min DeParle, administrator of the Health Care
Financing Administration, which runs Medicare, responded that her
agency was making changes to reduce overpayments in the future. But
in a written response to the inspector general, Ms. DeParle
disagreed with the recommendation that she seek legislation
allowing Medicare to recover the excess payments. In effect, she
said, the overpayments help HMOs finance extra benefits for
Medicare patients, and this is apparently what Congress intended.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, the chairman of the
Special Committee on Aging, urged the administration to try to
recover the overpayments. ``Can't we get back that money for the
trust fund?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Ignagni, president of the American Association of Health
Plans, the national trade group for managed care companies, said:
``HMOs have not done anything wrong. We have followed the rules.
The Medicare payments to HMOs were all reviewed and approved by the
Health Care Financing Administration.''
</P>
<P>
   HMOs say that if the government cuts their payments for
administrative and other costs, it will be more difficult for them
to offer extra benefits, like eye care and prescription drug
coverage, which have attracted elderly people in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown, the inspector general, said the overpayments were
cause for concern because of the precarious financial condition of
the Medicare program, which finances health care for more than 38
million people, including 6 million in HMOs. Under current law,
with no action by Congress, the Medicare trust fund is expected to
run out of money in 2008, three years before the first baby boomers
reach the age of 65.
</P>
<P>
   Administrative costs include marketing, taxes and profits,
salaries and fringe benefits for certain executives, rent,
depreciation, interest expenses, data processing, legal fees and
other overhead costs associated with the management and operation
of an HMO.
</P>
<P>
   HMOs get a fixed monthly payment, set in advance, for each
Medicare patient. The payments are based mainly on data that HMOs
submit to the government. Ms. Brown said many HMOs were ``aware
that the amounts that they submit for administration are inaccurate
and result in unjustified expenditures of Medicare funds.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Examining the financial records of HMOs with Medicare contracts
in 1996, Ms. Brown found that Medicare paid 31.7 percent of their
administrative expenses, but accounted for only 8.9 percent of
their enrollment.
</P>
<P>
   For 1994, 1995 and 1996, Ms. Brown said, ``the presently used
methodology allowed HMOs to overestimate their anticipated needs
for administrative costs by as much as $1 billion, $1.3 billion and
$1.9 billion, respectively.''
</P>
<P>
   Medicare payments to HMOs have grown significantly, to $25.6
billion last year from $8.6 billion in 1993. The Congressional
Budget Office predicts that 10 million beneficiaries, or 25 percent
of the Medicare population, will be in HMOs by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is encouraging the trend, in the belief that HMOs can
help control costs in the long run. But some HMOs have pulled out
of the program, saying that Medicare payment rates are inadequate.
United Healthcare Corp., one of the nation's biggest HMOs, took a
$900 million charge against earnings last week, in part to abandon
unprofitable Medicare plans.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. DeParle, the Medicare administrator, agreed that the
accounting techniques used by HMOs had ``almost certainly resulted
in overstated administrative costs.'' But she expressed concern
about possible cutbacks in benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have received reports that some HMOs have reduced benefit
levels and increased premiums'' for Medicare patients this year,
she said, and ``it is possible that beneficiaries will again
experience reduced benefit levels'' in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Medicare has operated on the principle that it should
pay its share of costs for various services.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown found that the administrative costs assigned to
Medicare were more than three times the amounts that HMOs charged
to commercial customers, even though ``a large portion of
administrative costs are fixed'' and do not vary with a patient's
age. In 1997, she said, the average monthly HMO premium for
administrative costs was $20.87 for commercial customers and $77.30
for Medicare patients.
</P>
<P>
   For one HMO, Ms. Brown said, the disparity was ``even more
egregious.'' On its financial statements, she said, this health
plan reported $287 million in administrative expenses, but Medicare
payments for administration totaled $366 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unbelievably,'' Ms. Brown said, ``the Medicare program covered
127 percent of the plan's administrative expenses.''
</P>
<P>
   If Medicare payments to an HMO exceed the cost of the standard
package of benefits, the health plan can use the money to provide
extra benefits like prescription drugs, eye examinations, dental
care and foot care.
</P>
<P>
   But the inspector general said there was some evidence that HMOs
had not provided all the extra benefits they indicated in their
annual reports to the government. And that, she said, is one reason
Medicare officials should try to recover the ``excess payments'' to
HMOs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
