<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIV-NATIONALS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dumias' diving is 'freaky and scary' of late
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Troy Dumais had no time for reflections on the 1996
Olympics as he trained at the Georgia Tech Aquatic Center Monday.
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't see beyond reflections on the surface of the pool.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not able to see the water,'' America's top male junior
diver said, bewildered at his prospects for the 1998 National
Diving Championships. ''It's one smack after another.''
</P>
<P>
   On about 20 practice dives from the 10-meter platform (about 33
feet), Dumais landed mostly on his stomach.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I see the water, I stretch for it, and I guess I get a
reflection of something,'' he said. ''No matter what I do, I'm
going short.''
</P>
<P>
   Dumais is the first to admit, ''All that is excuses.'' He knows
he has to adjust. After all, conditions were the same at the
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ''But I'm having a hard time,'' Dumais said. ''It's just some
people don't understand how freaky and scary it is when you're
supposed to land straight up and down and you don't see the
water.''
</P>
<P>
   Dumais, 19, of Ventura, Calif., has one more day to get his
bearings: Nationals begin today, but he won't begin competition
until Wednesday on the 10-meter platform. He'll also compete in the
1- and 3-meter springboard events. His brother Justin is competing
in synchronized diving, which makes its Atlanta debut in a major
event.
</P>
<P>
   Dumais, who won three junior national titles last week in Largo,
Fla., is one of 13 divers who won crowns at spring nationals,
including Katie Beth Bryant of Moultrie (1-meter), Laura Wilkinson
(10-meter), who is also the Goodwill Games champion, Mark Ruiz
(platform) and Bryan Gillooly (1-meter).
</P>
<P>
   However, Jenny Lingamfelter, the double gold medalist on
individual and synchronized 3-meter, is out while she recovers from
shoulder surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 1996 Olympians have retired; David Pichler, fifth at
the Games, is still competing.
</P>
<P>
   Dumais, who will attend the University of Texas this fall, said
it's hard for younger divers to establish themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ''(The judges) know the older kids,'' he said. ''Like Dmitry
(Sautin of Russia), he's made a name for himself. It's easy to give
him an 8.5 versus a little kid who might get lucky on a dive. You
gotta earn your name and earn your scores.''
</P>
<P>
   But for this meet, his goal is simple. ''Right now,'' Dumais
said, ''I'm just trying to do the dives.''
</P>
<P>
   Diving Championships
</P>
<P>
   _ When: Today through Sunday
</P>
<P>
   _ Where: Georgia Tech Aquatic Center, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   _ Who: More than 120 of the nation's top divers
</P>
<P>
   _ At stake: Top two in each event qualify for 1999 World Cup in
New Zealand; also divers earn points toward 2000 Olympic Trials.
</P>
<P>
   _ Schedule: Today: Men's and women's 3m and 10m synchronized
semis 6 p.m. Wednesday: women's 3m prelims/semis 12 p.m., men's 10m
prelims/semis 6 p.m. Thursday: Men's 1 m prelims/semis 12 p.m.,
women's 10 m prelims/semis 6 p.m., men's 1m finals 9 p.m. Friday:
Women's 1m prelims/semis 12 p.m., men's 3m prelims/semis 6 p.m.,
women's 1m finals 9 p.m. Saturday: Men's and women's 3m inals 3
p.m. Sunday: Men's and women's 10m finals 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tickets: $5-$25 today-Wednesday; $10-$50 Thursday-Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Information: 404-894-9600
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
