<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNITED-HUMANA-470&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNITED HEALTHCARE DROPS PLAN TO ACQUIRE HUMANA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky., Minn.)  (lb) 
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a much anticipated parting, United Healthcare Corp.'s
$5.5-billion acquisition of a rival health-care giant, Humana Inc.,
collapsed over the weekend after the value of United Healthcare
stock fell $2.9 billion late last week.
</P>
<P>
   The breakup, announced early on Monday, was no surprise. On
Thursday, United Healthcare reported an unexpected $900 million
charge in its second quarter, causing its stock to plunge 28
percent to $37.875.
</P>
<P>
   After the selloff, Humana's shareholders would have only
received $3.1 billion from the acquisition, far less than the $5.5
billion the company had agreed upon.
</P>
<P>
   But Humana had other reasons to walk away from the deal.
Analysts said Monday that company executives were worried that
United Healthcare's charge could be just the beginning of other
financial troubles.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies also appeared to have differing views on the
Medicare market. While part of United Healthcare's $900 million
charge was to scale back its Medicare offerings in some areas,
Humana was one of the industry's most prosperous competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We disengaged because United Healthcare identified some
problems with its operations,'' said Greg Donaldson, a spokesman
for Humana, which is based in Louisville, Ky. ``That made it clear
that Humana would be more successful on our own.''
</P>
<P>
   While analysts said that Humana and United Healthcare, of
Minneapolis, would both prosper independently, the collapse of the
deal left investors and analysts wondering about what might have
been.
</P>
<P>
   A combined Humana and United Healthcare would have been the
United States' largest health-maintenance organization. With 10
million members, the combined company would have dominated the
South Florida and Chicago markets as well as those in several other
Midwestern cities.
</P>
<P>
   But most important, Humana and United Healthcare would have had
a significant advantage in controlling costs. When the acquisition
was announced in May, Dr. William McGuire, the chairman of United
Healthcare, predicted the deal would bring eventual savings of $100
million to $250 million, largely by eliminating administrative
costs and lowering payments to hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has also been the thought in health care that bigger is
better,'' said Arun Kumar, a director at Standard &AMP; Poor's. ``But
this is not always true. Several of the smaller players are
performing well. One can hope that now this deal is over, Humana
and United Healthcare will get back to blocking and tackling,
concentrating on the fundamentals of the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors seemed disappointed that the deal had collapsed.
United Healthcare's shares took another beating Monday, ending
trading at $33.375, a new 52-week closing low. Since Wednesday
afternoon, United Healthcare stock has plunged 36.8 percent. Humana
closed on Monday at $17.9375, down 37.5 cents.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   United Healthcare's aborted acquisition of Humana may not be the
last of its troubles, analysts said. Several health-maintenance
organizations have struggled in the last year _ notably Oxford
Health Plans, which has posted heavy losses _ leaving many
investors skittish about health-care stocks. Humana's walking away
from the deal has made investors only more suspicious of United
Healthcare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Humana's executives may have wondered if the charge was just
the tip of the iceberg,'' said Linda Varoli, an analyst with Merger
Insight. ``They may have believed there were other charges to
come.''
</P>
<P>
   United Healthcare executives declined to comment beyond the
company's announcement on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Even though subscribers should not notice any change in service
or coverage as a result of the deal's cancellation, Humana and
United Healthcare could face different short-term futures.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expect Humana to concentrate on its operations, while
keeping an eye out for smaller acquisitions in several of the
company's key regions.
</P>
<P>
   United Healthcare now has a double mission. Not only must it
avoid any further financial surprises, but it has to squeeze more
profit from Medicare services.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said on Monday that United Healthcare might not have
been able to sign up enough Medicare patients in several of its
rural areas to enable it to negotiate discounts with hospitals and
other medical providers, a common problem among managed-care
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``What companies have to do is cut back on the benefits,'' said
Kenneth Abramowitz, a health-care analyst with Sanford C. Bernstein
&AMP; Co. ``The industry is offering $1,000 in benefits, when they can
only afford to provide $750.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said on Monday that the demise of the Humana
acquisition by United Healthcare should have little effect on other
deals. Because today's stock mergers are strategic, they are more
likely to be renegotiated than scrapped.
</P>
<P>
   In July, for example, two oil-service companies, Baker Hughes
Inc. and Western Atlas Inc., renegotiated the exchange ratio when a
slump in oil-service stocks dragged down the value of Baker Hughes
shares.
</P>
<P>
   And then again, a canceled deal may not be a bad thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deal between Humana and United Healthcare breaking up may
be a blessing in disguise,'' Abramowitz said. ``Now they can
concentrate on their operations and how to perfect managed care and
eventually disease management. You know, for HMOs to work, they
eventually have to prove they can upgrade the quality of care.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
