<HEADER>
A7002 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MARTINEZ-COX     08-10 0464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MARTINEZ-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Martinez passes Marichal _ at last
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox NewS Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ He could see the brass coming down the aisle Sunday
night, as the Braves flew south from San Francisco. Dennis Martinez
looked up to see John Schuerholz and Bobby Cox coming toward him
and before the pitcher knew where this was headed, he general
manager was in the midst of a toast at 30,000 feet in front of all
the Braves, a final testimonial on Martinez's night of achievement.
</P>
<P>
   There might have been times earlier this year that the sight of
Schuerholz and Cox coming for him might have alarmed the
43-year-old pitcher. But not this time. Martinez had finally passed
Juan Marichal with a 244th career victory. This flight could have
lasted all night.
</P>
<P>
   ''It hasn't been easy,'' Martinez said Monday, ''but I guess
everything comes in its time. Yesterday just happened and I never
expected it to happen in the place where the man used to play a
long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's day was filed with more calls than he cared to
accept, congratulations coming from around baseball and throughout
the Caribbean. Marichal, who has had some sharp words for
Martinez's coming back from retirement, did not phone. But that's
not to say he won't.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would be nice to hear from him,'' Martinez said. ''I would
do it sometime along the line when someone else steps in and does
the same thing. I have a lot of respect for him. He's a Hall of
Famer. He was an outstanding pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   And if Marichal didn't call from his native Domincan Republic,
it seemed everybody else did.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been crazy,'' Martinez said. ''People from everywhere,
people from Nicaragua, writers, friends, family members. Even
though we tried to keep hotel from letting all the calls come
through, they were reaching us through the pager.''
</P>
<P>
   It had been 68 days since his last win, 18 appearances over
which time he went 0-2 with a blown save. His ERA, which has never
dropped below 4,00 since the first two weeks of the season, has
been 7.10 since the All-Star break. But if his cause seemed
forgotten in some quarters, it remained a national cause in
Nicaragua, where the celebrations continue.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wish he had gone somewhere else and won the game but I'm
happy for him. I'm not going to lie,'' said San Francisco's Marvin
Benard, the only other Nicaraguan in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you look at the size of our country and the amount of
players we have get to the big leagues, he was the first one and
he's still here. When the call him El Presidente, it's not for
nothing. If he ran for president of Nicaragua, he'd probably win.
He's an inspiration for our country.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
