<HEADER>
A7003 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CHARISMA-SFCH     08-10 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CHARISMA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCANDAL HASN'T HURT CLINTON'S FUND-RAISING ABILITY 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARC SANDALOW  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    WASHINGTON _ Salacious allegations, subpoenas and talk of
impeachment have done little to diminish President Clinton's star
quality on the campaign trail, where Democrats are counting on his
help to propel them to victory in November.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clinton is scheduled to embark Monday morning on a three-day
fund-raising trip that will bring him to San Francisco for a $1,000
per plate luncheon with Lieutenant Governor Gray Davis, the
Democratic candidate for governor.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he returns to Washington on Wednesday, he will have
attended five money-raising events in four states and collected
several million for Democratic candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton continues to be a very big draw and very
strong asset to the Democratic Party,'' said Olivia Morgan, a
spokeswoman for the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The next seven days will be pivotal for the president and
Democrats: Clinton is preparing to give testimony to a grand jury
next Monday, and the FBI will probably complete tests on a dress
that may contain physical evidence of a relationship with former
White House intern Monica Lewinsky. Although the president
continues to enjoy a high public approval rating, Republicans say
that Democrats campaign with Clinton at their own peril.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``If the American people are ever confronted with the reality
that their commander in chief, the leader of the free world, is
lying to them . . . that will take a very heavy toll, not only on
(Clinton's) presidency, but on those who stand with him,'' said
Steve Merksamer, a Sacramento attorney and informal adviser to the
Republican candidate for governor, Dan Lungren.
</P>
<P>
   California Democrats have so far shown no fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope he's out here so often that he'll be going door to
door for our candidates,'' said Bob Mulholland, a consultant to the
state Democratic Party. ``California loves Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Befitting a president who has visited California more than any
president before him, Clinton has already committed a considerable
amount of time to the state's two highest profile contests and he
has plans to spend even more. After attending four money-raising
events for Democratic Sen. Barbara Boxer's re-election bid, he is
scheduled for three fund-raisers and two public appearances with
Davis in the next two days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very excited the president is coming,'' said Michael
Bustamante, a spokesman for the Davis campaign. Bustamante said the
campaign never considered scaling back its appearances with the
president because of the recent controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is extraordinarily popular because he is talking
about issues that California and America care about _ education,
assault weapons, a woman's right to choose,'' Bustamante said.
</P>
<P>
   California Republicans hope they will be able to capitalize on
the president's recent troubles, though few are as willing to go as
far as party consultant Dan Schnur, who suggested that 500 young
Republicans show up at the Clinton-Davis events carrying blue
dresses on hangers as a vivid reminder of the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Although they do it in less creative ways, other GOP operatives
do not need to be pushed to raise the issue of Clinton's character.
</P>
<P>
   ``The contrast between Dan Lungren and mainstream conservative
values, and the liberal values of Gray Davis and Bill Clinton is
one that I welcome,'' said Lungren spokesman Dave Puglia. ``I do
think character matters when we choose candidates for high
office.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Schmidt, a spokesman for Republican Senate candidate Matt
Fong, said it is ``premature to speculate whether (the scandal)
will be an issue in November,'' but insisted that Boxer's failure
to distance herself from Clinton, in light of her vocal criticism
of others accused of sexual harassment, ``is a testament to how
partisan she is.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of California believe he has done a good job as
president,'' said Boxer spokesman Roy Behr. ``And Sen. Boxer has
supported those same policies that have helped turn around the
states fortune.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the president raised more than $1 million at the
first in a series of fund-raisers that is expected to raise $18
million for the party by November.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, he will attend fund-raisers in Kentucky and Chicago
before he continues on to San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans concede that Clinton is a prolific money-raiser.
However, on election day, they say the ethical and moral questions
regarding Clinton will likely send loyal Republicans to the polls
and keep disenchanted Democrats at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton's presence in California will further energize the
Republican base, and off-year elections are won and lost based on
turnout,'' said Todd Harris, a spokeswoman for the National
Republican Congressional Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans point to the 1974 mid-term election _ just after
President Gerald Ford pardoned former President Richard Nixon _
when Jerry Brown defeated Republican Houston Flournoy by just
176,000 votes out of more than 6 million cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Watergate, Republicans didn't lose votes because people
switched parties, but because they stayed home,'' said Schnur. ``A
lot of Democratic women may not switch sides in November, but may
not be particularly motivated to vote when their president is in
the middle of sex scandal.''
</P>
<P>
   In California, the race for Senate and governor are close enough
that even a modest swing of votes could easily effect the outcome.
The same goes nationally, where the difference between GOP and
Democratic control of the House is at its narrowest margin in 40
years.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans took some satisfaction in the victory last week of a
candidate who exploited the president's troubles. In a Republican
primary for a Tennessee congressional seat, Walt Massey distributed
flyers featuring a picture of Clinton and the White House below big
red letters that read: SCANDAL.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the brochure detailed the ``scandal a day
administration,'' touching on matters ranging from Whitewater to
Lewinsky. Massey emerged as the victor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most analysts believe that turnout in this election is going
to be very low'' said Harris. ``To the extent that Bill Clinton
energizes the Republican base, it's very good news for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
