<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-TERRORISM-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE INVESTIGATION: TRUCK MAY PROVIDE CLUE TO IDENTITY OF
TERRORISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: AFRICA-BOMBINGS, AFRICA-U.S., AFRICA-FUNERAL,
AFRICA-DEAD, AFRICA-SURVIVE) 
(JT) 
 By TIM WEINER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ As the United States offered a $2 million
reward for information about the American embassy bombings,
eyewitnesses told investigators that they had seen a truck that may
have carried the bomb, possibly providing clues to the identity of
the terrorists who carried out the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the CIA and the FBI were also evaluating other
preliminary leads. They included a terrorist manifesto delivered in
Cairo that praised Osama bin Laden, a Saudi financier whom American
officials have identified as a possible suspect, and reports that
intelligence organizations had received vague warnings that an
Islamic terrorist group might be planning an attack in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   The work of CIA officials took on a personal as well as
professional intensity as they mourned the death of one of their
own, an intelligence officer killed in the Nairobi explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said in Washington that
the reward would be paid for information leading to the arrest of
those responsible. The bombings killed more than 200 people and
wounded nearly 5,000 others in Nairo and Dar es Salaam, Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   FBI officials here and in Dar es Salaam continued a grisly
search for evidence, meticulously combing through the rubble near
the ruined embassies and examining bodies in a hospital morgue for
pieces of metal.
</P>
<P>
   The CIA and the FBI investigators _ two teams of 60 FBI agents
each in Nairobi and Dar es Salaam and CIA officers from around the
world _ want to reconstruct the events leading up to the bombings.
To help pinpoint the identities of the bombers, they are
interviewing eyewitnesses like a Kenyan guard who told
investigators that he refused to allow a truck through the rear
gate of the embassy. The guard said that a man jumped out of the
truck and opened fire on him, possibly with a hand grenade. Other
Kenyan witnesses provided similar accounts, including a Kenyan
driver who said he saw a man leap from the back of a yellow pick up
truck and throw something toward the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI team is larger than the one sent to investigate the 1996
bombing at the Air Force apartment complex in Saudi Arabia. FBI
officials are trying to determine what kind of explosive was used
in the attack, which will help focus their investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Israel army radio said investigators suspect Semtex was used. If
the bomb was made of Semtex, a plastic explosive, it could lead the
investigators toward a network of known terrorist groups. In the
1970s and 1980s, Czechoslovakia sold 100 tons of Semtex to Libya,
according to the Czech president, Vaclav Havel. If the bomb was
made of a commercially available explosive, like dynamite or
ammonium phosphate, the investigation may have to branch out in
other directions.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators must check ports of entry by land, air and sea
on Kenya's porous borders. They must search commercial records like
bills of lading for suspicious shipments. The movements, intentions
and capabilities of known terrorists must be reviewed. The task
could take years, American officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Among the facts the investigators had in hand Monday were a few
tantalizing leads.
</P>
<P>
   Tanzanian police said that they had detained ``several''
suspects, but Susan Rice, the assistant secretary of state for
African affairs, cautioned that the detentions were part of a
routine roundup and should not be taken too seriously.
</P>
<P>
   A foreign diplomat here said in an interview Monday that a
foreign intelligence service reported indications months ago that
an Islamic terrorist organization with bases in Afghanistan and
Pakistan might be planning an attack in Kenya. An American official
confirmed that U.S. intelligence agencies were aware of that
report.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were told to take care for flights coming from Pakistan,''
the foreign diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   But, like most such warnings, the information obtained by the
foreign intelligence service was indefinite _ too fuzzy for any
effective countermeasures. The embassy here never went on alert, an
American official said.
</P>
<P>
   A senior official of a foreign intelligence service also
confirmed Monday night that his service had received the reports of
a possible terrorist attack in Nairobi. But he and other
intelligence officials said such reports come in constantly, and
are often understood only in hindsight. ``Intelligence pours in all
the time,'' he said. ``You can't cry wolf every time.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The investigators were also analyzing the statement was a
statement issued by a previously unknown Islamic group claiming
responsibility for the attack. American and foreign intelligence
officials said that they were still evaluating whether the
terrorist manifesto, from a previously unknown Islamic group, was
credible, and they cautioned that claims of responsibility were
easily made and difficult to verify.
</P>
<P>
   In the communique, the group said it would ``pursue U.S. forces
and strike at U.S. interests everywhere'' unless revolutionary
changes were made in American foreign, economic and military policy
in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   The statement included several signs pointing toward bin Laden,
who has financed and otherwise supported previous terrorist attacks
on American outposts, according to U.S. officials.
</P>
<P>
   The communique, issued to a French news organization and made
public in Cairo Monday morning, said the group was inspired by the
statements of bin Laden. Four Saudis beheaded for bombing an
American installation in Riyadh, killing five Americans, in
November 1995 said in televised confessions that they, too, were
inspired by bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   The statement demanded the withdrawal of American forces in
Saudi Arabia and an end to U.S. support for Israel. It called for
an end to American economic sanctions against Islamic republics and
the release of imprisoned Islamic militants - ``first and foremost
Sheik Omar Abdel Rahman,'' the blind cleric convicted and
imprisoned for his role in a plot to bomb the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden has voiced similar demands in the past. He not only
sheltered Sheik Rahman but also harbored Ramzi Yousef, the
convicted mastermind of the 1993 bombing of the World Trade Center,
in homes bin Laden owned in Peshawar, Pakistan, near the Afghan
border.
</P>
<P>
   The statement also said ``a man from Egypt who belongs to the
Abdallah Azzam battalion.'' carried out Friday's attack on the
American Embassy in Tanzania, which came almost simultaneously with
the bombing here. Abdallah Azzam, who died in 1989, was a
Palestinian who fought alongside the CIA-supported Afghan rebels
battling Soviet invaders in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was bin Laden's partner'' in extremist politics, a U.S.
government official said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   That same year, in 1989, bin Laden, whose family made a fortune
building mosques, royal palaces and government offices for the
Saudi royal family, began to pursue a grand vision: ``a
multinational organization for jihad, to purge the world of Western
corrupters and their Arab friends,'' the American official said.
Jihad is the Arabic word for holy war.
</P>
<P>
   The goal was ``a huge alliance of like-minded groups,'' the
official said. Today bin Laden, by funneling tens of millions of
dollars a year through Islamic charities and banks, supports or
sustains terrorist organizations and extremist political movements
in Algeria, Egypt, Lebanon, Sudan and Yemen, among other nations,
the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Now the men, the money and the violent potential of these
organizations are being scrutinized by hundreds of American
intelligence and law-enforcement officers here and around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   The CIA revived its station here Monday, led by officers from
the agency's headquarters outside Washington. American intelligence
officers in Germany who track developments in Iran, Iraq and
Afghanistan, where the United States has no embassies, are also
investigating. The Israeli government has offered the United States
the help of its intelligence agencies in tracking down the
attackers, whom Israeli officials believe were almost certainly
Islamic militants.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI officials include a Rapid Start unit of FBI computer
analysts who inventory and collate evidence. Their presence
suggests that the FBI hopes to play a substantial role in the
forensic examination of the bomb scene and may expect to
participate in any prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
