<HEADLINE>
(HLW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 CHICAGO BOYS, 7 and 8, CHARGED WITH MURDERING 11-YEAR-OLD GIRL   By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ In a case that has sent chills across this city, two
boys, ages 7 and 8, have been charged with murdering an 11-year-old
girl, striking her with a rock, sexually molesting her and
suffocating her with her own underwear, apparently in order to take
the bright blue bicycle she had been riding, the police said on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Juvenile justice experts said they do not know of a case in this
country in which younger children have been prosecuted for murder.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors and the police said on Monday that on Sunday evening
the boys confessed to the killing two weeks ago of the girl, Ryan
Harris, an honor student who had just finished fifth grade. After
killing Ryan in an alley behind a building on Chicago's South Side,
the 8-year-old rode his bike home and watched cartoons and the
7-year-old went home to play with a puppy, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the boys appeared for a probable cause hearing in
Juvenile Court, their feet swaying above the floor as they sat
before the judge. The 7-year-old, using colored pens, spent most of
the hearing drawing hearts, a house, and a rainbow on one of his
lawyer's yellow legal pads.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago has seen several horrifying crimes involving children in
recent years, including a 1996 case in which two boys, 10 and 11,
dropped a 5-year-old boy to his death from the 14th floor of a
housing project. But the Ryan Harris case has struck an especially
painful nerve.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this era, the ages of these offenders is very frightening
to hear about,'' said Mayor Richard M. Daley. ``Children are
growing up much, much faster.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
