<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-JUSTICE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT INSISTS IT ISN'T A MONOPOLY, ASKS SUITS BE SCRAPPED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Microsoft does not have a monopoly on computer
operating systems, nor is it poised to gain a monopoly on Internet
browsers, the company's lawyers argued in court filings Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the lawyers said, the company is driven by fear of its
thriving rivals.
</P>
<P>
   After months of being depicted by its critics as a ravenous
giant that consumes or crushes its competitors, Microsoft offered a
new picture of the company as it urged a federal judge to dismiss
anti-trust lawsuits filed against the Redmond-based software
company by federal and state governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft would not continue to operate on the principle that
it must innovate or die if it believed for a moment that its
current market position was durable,'' the company argued in briefs
filed yesterday in U.S. District Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft spends hundreds of millions of dollars each year on
research and development precisely because it is afraid of being
overtaken by powerful competitors such as IBM, Novell, Oracle and
Sun or by companies that Microsoft does not know about or that may
not yet exist. That is hardly the image of the fat and lazy
monopolist from a Thomas Nast cartoon.''
</P>
<P>
   Company officials said that even if Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson doesn't throw out the cases, they are hopeful that he will
narrow them.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the government was unimpressed with the
company's latest legal briefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft said nothing new today,'' said Gina Talamona, a
spokeswoman for the Department of Justice. ``Ever since we brought
this case, Microsoft's position can't be squared with the company's
own documents, much less with the large body of evidence that will
be introduced at trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the company is a monopoly is a central question in the
legal dispute between the attorneys general and Microsoft. The
government lawyers have argued that Microsoft has a monopoly on
computer operating systems and is violating the nation's anti-trust
laws by attempting illegally to extend that monopoly into the
market for Internet browsers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft possesses (and for several years has possessed)
monopoly power in the market for personal computer operating
systems,'' the government wrote in its complaint May 18. ``To
protect its valuable Windows monopoly against such potential
competitive threats, and to extend its operating system monopoly
into other software markets, Microsoft has engaged in a series of
anti-competitive activities.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the illegally anti-competitive practices alleged by the
government: ``tying other Microsoft software products to
Microsoft's Windows operating system; exclusionary agreements
precluding companies from distributing, promoting, buying, or using
products of Microsoft's software competitors or potential
competitors; and exclusionary agreements restricting the right of
companies to provide services or resources to Microsoft's software
competitors or potential competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   But in its filings Monday, the company denied the illegally
anti-competitive practices alleged in the government complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you step back from all the heated rhetoric and apply
well-established legal principles to the actual facts of the case,
it is clear that the government will not be able to prove its
case,'' said William Neukom, Microsoft's senior vice president for
law and corporate affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft insisted that, despite supplying the operating system
used on at least 80 percent of personal computers, it has no
monopoly to protect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Notwithstanding the popularity of Microsoft's operating system
software, Microsoft does not have the power unilaterally to raise
prices or exclude competition,'' the company argued. ``The software
industry is characterized by rapid and relentless innovation.
Microsoft's operating system competitors include IBM and Sun,
companies with enormous resources at their disposal.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft said a company with a true monopoly on operating
systems would have dramatically raised prices for Windows 98 and
would not spend as much on research and development as does
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Relatively rapid reversals in the fortunes of companies that
once had seemingly commanding leads are a frequent occurrence in
the software business,'' the company wrote. ``Products that provide
customers with significantly more value tend to leapfrog over
existing products, even those that were market leaders: witness the
collapse of Wang Laboratories in the now-defunct market for
standalone word processors.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft argued that a June 23 appeals court decision upheld
its right to integrate its browser into its operating system _ an
action that the government believes is illegal. Microsoft also
argued that its actions have not hurt its major competitor in the
browser market, Netscape Communications Corp., because Netscape is
still widely distributing its product.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an effort to disguise the many problems with their legal
theories, which fly in the face of an opinion issued by the Court
of Appeals less than two months ago and are also contradicted by
the uncontested facts, plaintiffs seek to create the false
impression that Netscape posed a dire threat to Microsoft's
operating system software business and that Microsoft
systematically set about to destroy Netscape in order to eliminate
that threat,'' Microsoft wrote. ``It is a nice story, but that is
all it is _ a story.''
</P>
<P>
   To prove that it did not integrate its browser into the
operating system simply to squash Netscape, Microsoft said it
``began its consideration of providing support for Internet
standards in Windows 95, including web browsing functionality, in
1992,'' two years before Netscape was founded, and ``publicly
announced its intention to include web browsing functionality in
Windows 95 in April 1994.''
</P>
<P>
   But Netscape insists that Microsoft has limited its ability to
distribute its product by restrictive contracts with computer
manufacturers and Internet Service Providers. The company cites in
part a new study by Net Action, a consumer group critical of
Microsoft, that finds ``almost none of the largest Internet Service
Providers even give consumers the option to order an alternative to
Microsoft's Internet Explorer browser and many will not give
technical support to consumers who install Netscape Navigator or an
alternative browser on their system.''
</P>
<P>
   Netscape General Counsel Roberta Katz said Microsoft's practices
are hurting her company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our distribution is like a faucet, where we had a lot of water
coming through the pipes, and Microsoft, using its monopoly power,
started turning the faucet off,'' she said. ``They didn't turn the
faucet off (completely), so now they're saying, `why should
(Netscape) complain?' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
