u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VINEYARD-SCANDAL-COX     08-10 0422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VINEYARD-SCANDAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vineyarders talking about scandal, too
 &HT;    (EDS: With VINEYARD and VINEYARD-BOX. DUPLICATION ALERT: Moving
in (l) Lifestyle and (w) Washington categories.)
 &HT;    By Bob Dart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAK BLUFFS, Mass. _ This harbor town was founded on notions of
sin and redemption, so it is not surprising that scandalous
goings-on in Washington are a hot topic of conversation as Martha's
Vineyard prepares for President Clinton's vacation visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he has demeaned the presidency,'' said Sue Chase,
sitting in a rocking chair on a front porch overlooking the
open-sided Camp Meeting Tabernacle where the Clintons often attend
church on their visits to the island.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the 19th Century, the Tabernacle was the preaching
point for Methodist tent revivals that drew devout thousands to Oak
Bluffs. Over 300 cottages have been built on the former tent sites
and are summer homes to well-to-do folks like the Chases, who split
their year between Martha's Vineyard and Vero Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   In their past three visits, the Clintons have attended Sunday
services at the Tabernacle. ``The only time it fills up is when
he's here,'' said Gordon Chase.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Bill and Hillary Clinton stopped at the Chases' front
porch on their walk to brunch and chatted awhile. That was before
the world had heard of Monica Lewinsky and Linda Tripp's tapes, of
course, and now Sue Chase has a harsher assessment of the
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a brilliant man, but I don't have much respect for him,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Not that anyone on Martha's Vineyard is likely to be rude enough
to bring up the subject when Clinton is actually around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I think he's done an exceptional job as president
and that should take precedent over a lot of other things,'' said
Thomas DeMont, owner of the Edgartown Scrimshaw Gallery. ``I'll
give him the benefit of the doubt until he testifies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some talk on the island _ just like there is
everywhere else _ on the scandal. But I think it mirrors what the
national polls say: Let's get on with business,'' said John Alley,
chairman of the West Tisbury Board of Selectmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody really doesn't give a (expletive) about that no
more. It's gone on too long,'' said Geno Courtney, who owns several
island businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do souvenir T-shirts,'' he said. ``I'll probably do four for
his visit. But none about his personal life.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
