<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-98 2054EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980810.0380 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7013 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VINEYARD-COX     08-10 1512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VINEYARD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Laid-back Martha's Vineyard awaits Clintons' fourth visit
 &HT;    (EDS: With VINEYARD-SCANDAL and VINEYARD-BOX. DUPLICATION ALERT:
Moving in (l) Lifestyles and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By Bob Dart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDGARTOWN, Mass. _ When the Clintons come to Martha's Vineyard
next week, some local folks will pack up and leave their beloved
island until the First Family finishes its vacation.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that they dislike President Clinton or even that they
dread the congestion and commotion that have accompanied him on
three previous late summer stays. But housing is scarce during
August, the seasonal peak, so some residents now rent their homes
to the legions of Secret Service agents, White House staffers and
journalists who descend on the picturesque isle seven miles off
Cape Cod.
</P>
<P>
   Even the rush for lodging has become routine as laid-back
Martha's Vineyard awaits another presidential visit. Clinton is
scheduled to arrive the evening of August 17, the same day he
testifies on closed-circuit TV to the federal grand jury
investigating allegations that had a sexual affair with former
White House intern Monica Lewinsky and sought to conceal it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Folks on the Vineyard are used to the First Family coming here
for their vacation so it's not as exciting and as thrilling as it
was the first time,'' said John Alley, chairman of the West Tisbury
Board of Selectmen. ``The year-round residents have become rather
matter-of-fact about the whole thing, but the tourists who are here
for that particular day are all anxious to see the president. Of
course, we're pleased that he chooses to come to our community.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a community where celebrity is hardly a stranger. Seasonal
residents include Spike Lee, William Styron, Carly Simon, Walter
Cronkite, Ted Danson and wife Mary Steenburgen, Mike Wallace,
Robert McNamara and Diane Sawyer. A local couple, actress Susan St.
James and NBC Sports President Dick Ebersol, last year paid $4.2
million for a three acre compound with a stretch of beachfront. The
late Jackie Kennedy Onassis had a summer home here.
</P>
<P>
   Money _ old and new _ is also a familiar resident. The word
``summer'' is a verb here _ as in ``We summer on the Vineyard.''
Driveways on secluded coves can end at an information-industry
magnate's new beachfront mansion or the weathered, shingle-sided
cottage where a New England family has summered for five
generations.
</P>
<P>
   For the second year in a row, the Clintons will stay in the
waterfront home of Boston real estate developer Richard Friedman in
this historic whaling town, one of the half dozen villages on the
wooded, 100-square-mile island. Realtors said they must find houses
or hotel rooms for 200 or so White House staffers and Secret
Service agents and nearly that many reporters and media
technicians. Rents range from about $1,600 to $4,000 a week for a
suitable three-bedroom house, with federal taxpayers picking up the
tab for the Secret Service agents and presidential aides. That's on
the modest end of the island scale, however, as beachfront
properties rent for up to $80,000 for the month of August.
</P>
<P>
   With regular vacation housing booked long in advance, residents
have been recruited to leave while the Clintons stay. Last year,
four Secret Service agents stayed at the Sobotka home and the
family went sailing for three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It worked very well. They were extremely low impact,'' said
Trina Sobotka. She said some of the agents' families must have
visited because her neighbors described a backyard barbecue with
``kids running around in Secret Service T-shirts.''
</P>
<P>
   This island _ spectacularly scenic where its bluffs and harbors
and beaches meet sparkling blue waters _ was discovered in 1602 by
English explorer Bartholomew Gosnold who was on his way to
Virginia. He named it for his daughter, Martha, and for the
abundant wild grapes found growing there.
</P>
<P>
   Nathaniel Hawthorne and Daniel Webster visited on the Vineyard
in earlier centuries. But the island's fame has grown globally
since the Clintons made it their vacation site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton has put us on the map. If people didn't know where we
are after 'Jaws', (which was filmed on Martha's Vineyard), they
know now,'' said Barbara St. Pierre, owner of a real estate
reservations service that has been working with the White House
travel office.
</P>
<P>
   Until the Clintons arrive, at least, the highlight of this
social season has been the 20th annual ``Possible Dreams'' auction
which drew 1,500 islanders to the Harborside Inn courtyard on Aug.
3 and raised $460,000 for community services such as drug
counseling and visiting nurses. Columnist Art Buchwald served as
auctioneer and celebrity islanders fulfilled dreams for a price.
</P>
<P>
   Carly Simon's guitar, a personally written composition and
peanut butter sandwiches went for $40,000, for instance. Lunch with
Diane Sawyer and husband Mike Nichols at their home called Chip
Chop brought in $30,000. ``We'll play some tennis, too,'' promised
Nichols. A walk-on role in an episode of ``Ally McBeal'' _ the TV
series set in nearby Boston _ brought $21,000. The winning bid for
a beach walk with singer James Taylor was $13,000, and for an
afternoon sail with Walter Cronkite, $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, the Clintons will be welcomed with a round of
exclusive dinner parties, such as the affair they attended several
years ago honoring David McCullough, the Pulitzer Prize-winning
historian, at the home of Katharine Graham, whose family owns the
Washington Post. During the long summer days, though, the First
Family ventures into the villages to shop and eat at restaurants.
Indeed, during one of these forays, the president is alleged to
have bought souvenirs of the Black Dog Tavern _ trademark Vineyard
keepsakes _ for Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``He makes a few visits into most of the towns, not just
Edgartown. But he's mostly here to swim, sail, play golf _ to do
what normal people do on vacation,'' said Thomas DeMont, owner of
the Edgartown Scrimshaw Gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Geno Courtney came to the Vineyard from South Boston over 30
years ago as a barber. Now he owns Scoops ice cream parlor in
Edgartown and several T-shirt stores on the island. Among his
customers are hundreds of daytrippers who come by ferry for
shopping, seafood and sun but usually don't spend the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton's coming does boost the economy and it gives the
working stiffs a chance to get a good look at the guy,'' said
Courtney. ``The only ones who might have a legitimate bitch (about
the presidential visit) are the golfers.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, during past visits, the president has played a round
almost every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty routine now _ almost just as if anyone else was
coming to play, with just a few special accommodations,'' said Mike
Zoll, head pro at the Farm Neck Golf Club where Clinton played in
the past with Vernon Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   An aide calls ahead to let the club know about when the
president will arrive, said Zoll. ``He generally hits a few balls
on the range, then lets us know when he's ready to play. We ask the
foursome on the first tee if they'd rather play in front of or
behind the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Most pass up the chance to watch Clinton drive and putt and go
first _ afraid of being held up by slow presidential play. But
that's an unfounded fear, said Zoll. ``The president is pretty
good. He's very strong. And he loves to play. He has a youthful
enthusiasm for the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton usually plays with a member, the course is open
to any island visitor who calls two days ahead to reserve a tee
time. Greens fees are $80 and cart rental is $13.25 for 18 holes.
</P>
<P>
   The Secret Service last year gave about 20 minutes notice that
the Clintons were going to have brunch at The Sweet Life Cafe,
recalls Lesley Doctor, owner of the gourmet restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The president had duck hash and poached eggs. The First Lady had
oatmeal with dried cherries. They ate on the porch. And brunch
business picked up on the following Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   A presidential vacation ``does pump a lot of money into the
economy. I couldn't tell you exactly how much dollarwise, but I
expect there's a couple of million in transactions,'' said Alley,
the selectman.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an immediate effect and a residual effect after he's
gone,'' said Randi Vega, executive director of the Martha's
Vineyard Chamber of Commerce. ``A lot of people want to go to the
restaurants where he ate. Some visitors heard of the island because
the Clintons come here. And we hear from some folks who don't want
to be here when he's here for whatever reasons and want to plan
their stays accordingly.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Trina Sobotka, who celebrated her 50th birthday last
year on a sailing cruise financed by renting her house to Secret
Service agents, is again considering leaving Martha's Vineyard to
the Clintons for their stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Homeowners say the agents leave the houses cleaner than they
found them,'' laughed St. Pierre.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
