<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRS-REVAMP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRS CHIEF TO NAME EXECUTIVE TEAM TO REMAKE AGENCY
</HEADLINE>
   (ll) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRS Commissioner Charles Rossotti, using the broad powers
Congress gave him last month to pick his executive team to remake
the beleaguered agency, will appoint two deputies and a chief
computer executive on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   John LaFaver, the Kansas revenue secretary, will be named the
deputy commissioner for modernization, said two officials familiar
with the selections. LaFaver, who previously was tax commissioner
in Maine and Montana, built a name for himself in the last three
years by installing new technology and adopting a new attitude
toward Kansas taxpayers, whom he calls customers.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Wenzel, a career IRS official, will be named deputy
commissioner for operations. Wenzel was running the IRS service
center in Fresno, Calif., which processes tax returns filed in
California, when he was summoned back to Washington this year to
work on improving service to taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   The third major post, that of chief information officer, will be
filled by Paul Cosgrove, who was president and chief executive of
Claremont Technology Group and previously was a managing director
for Anderson Consulting, which has contracts to modernize tax
systems in California, Texas and several foreign countries. For the
past month, Cosgrove has been working as a technology consultant to
the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   The three are expected to work from a blueprint developed by
Arthur Gross. That blueprint showed how to use mainframe computers,
coupled with servers and work stations, to allow individual IRS
workers to have all the information needed to work with taxpayers.
In February, Gross resigned as chief information officer after he
and Rossotti clashed on how to implement the blueprint. Gross is
now chief information officer at Albany Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   The kind of taxpayer service that Rossotti envisions can be seen
on a small scale at the Kansas Department of Revenue, which
collects as much money in a year as the IRS does in a day.
</P>
<P>
   LaFaver posted every Kansas tax policy on the Internet and had
the department's computer systems so thoroughly integrated that
when a taxpayer calls with a problem, all the information needed to
resolve it, including images of tax returns, can be called up
almost instantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most tax problems can be solved in about nine seconds if the
tax people have the information needed to help their customer,''
LaFaver said in June.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
