<HEADLINE>
AUTOMATION LESSENS PHONE STRIKE IMPACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic Corp. customers waiting for directory &UR;  &LR; assistance,
installations, and other services can expect more delays as the
strike continues, but the overall impact Monday was muted because
so much of the phone company's operations today are automated &UR;  &LR; and
because Bell Atlantic managers filled in.
</P>
<P>
   Local phone customers in Massachusetts found some directory
assistance calls taking slightly longer than usual. In New York,
directory assistance callers faced longer delays and were greeted
by the recorded message, ``Due to a work stoppage, we are unable to
provide an operator at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   A directory assistance call to New Hampshire and another to New
Jersey were answered immediately.
</P>
<P>
   A Bell Atlantic spokesman said several other customer services
were experiencing ``a slowdown,'' including billing inquiries,
ordering new telephone services, or changing existing services.
</P>
<P>
   The company's 23,000 managers are filling in for the striking
workers in the 13 states between Maine and Virginia that Bell
Atlantic serves. Nearly all the managers are expected to work
six-day, 12-hour shifts, said a Bell Atlantic spokesman.
Anticipating a possible strike, the managers were told in June to
cancel any vacation plans in August, a source close to Bell
Atlantic said.
</P>
<P>
   The strike by 73,000 members of the Communications Workers of
America, which began Sunday, is the first since local telephone
service was officially deregulated by the 1996 Telecommunications
Act.
</P>
<P>
   Monday Bell Atlantic shares closed at 41 3/16, down 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   Several Wall Street analysts said a short strike will not affect
the company financially, but the interruption could lead some Bell
Atlantic customers to explore other options for local service.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still early, but if this is a protracted strike and
business customers need more phone lines, service, and maintenance
performed, they may turn to us,'' said John F. Kelley, director of
operations in Boston for Teleport Communications Group, an AT&AMP;T
Corp. unit that is a Bell Atlantic rival and has more than 500
business customers.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic customers and competitors said the impact from the
strike will be minimal because all are increasingly using computers
and highly skilled software engineers, reducing the need for phone
company personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much of 80 percent of our work does not need human
intervention,'' said Robert T. Hale Jr., president of Network Plus
Inc. of Quincy, which provides Internet and phone services. some of
which overlap with Bell Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the increasing dependence on computers and other
technologies that could reduce the number of unionized jobs is at
the heart of the strike at Bell Atlantic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-98 2104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
