<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WILDCARD-RACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS TRUMPING CRITICS IN QUEST FOR WILD CARD  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The problem _ one of the problems _ with wild-card contenders is
that they are also-rans, and worse, they often play like also-rans.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few weeks, the National League's collection of
wild-card contenders has demonstrated precisely that condition.
These teams have shown why they are not contenders for division
championships.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Cubs, for example, have led the wild-card division
for the last three weeks since overtaking the San Francisco Giants,
who tumbled out of the lead by losing 12 of 15 games. But the Cubs
just dropped all three games of a weekend series to St. Louis, a
team that deservedly has a losing record.
</P>
<P>
   While the Cubs were enduring a lost weekend in St. Louis, the
Giants had one of their own right at home, losing all three games
to Atlanta. At least the Giants had an excuse. The Braves are the
best team in the league.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets could have supplanted the Cubs in first place in the
league's fourth division by sweeping their three weekend games in
Colorado, but they lost the third game Sunday, leaving them half a
game behind going into Monday night's games. Two out of three isn't
bad, just not good enough.
</P>
<P>
   But that's the way the NL wild-card chase has gone. The Mets
actually have been the best team in the group recently.
</P>
<P>
   Since they and the Cubs evenly divided a four-game series the
last week of last month, leaving the Mets three and a half games
behind the Cubs, the Mets have won two of three from San Diego,
split a four-game series with Los Angeles and taken two of three
from the Giants and Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs won two and lost two to Arizona, took two of three from
the Rockies, lost two of three to the Diamondbacks and lost three
to the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants have had one good series in that same span, sweeping
four games in Philadelphia and virtually knocking the Phillies out
of wild-card contention. The Phillies went on to lose two of three
to San Diego and all three weekend games to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are the other contender. After suffering a
near-death experience in New York, emerging with a split because
the Mets' incendiary bullpen gave them two victories, they went to
Montreal and, incredibly, lost all three games.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Phillies, the Dodgers could have declared themselves
out of the race right then and there, before they even re-entered
the country, but the Cubs graciously let them back in. The Dodgers
provided some self-help, too, beating Pittsburgh two of three times
during the weekend and slicing their deficit from six games to
four.
</P>
<P>
   It is a waste of time and energy to belabor the question of
where the Mets might be if their relief corps hadn't torpedoed
their recent efforts. That John Franco has a weird way of showing
he deserves a two-year contract extension; that the Mets might have
been wiser leaving Greg McMichael in Los Angeles, where he could
have thrown volatile pitches for the Dodgers and undermined their
wild-card chances; that Mel Rojas is more frightening when he comes
into pitch than a haunted house, are all givens.
</P>
<P>
   Let's go from there. If these are the potholes the Mets must
avoid, if they are the obstacles they have to overcome, that is
their fate; that is their task. The point is that the Mets, with
seven weeks left in the season, are in excellent position to make
the playoffs as the wild-card team.
</P>
<P>
   No team has enough talent to dominate the race the rest of the
season. All of the teams have holes and shortcomings; otherwise,
they would be challenging the Braves, the Padres and the Astros for
division championships.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs, for example, either playing poorly or conceding to the
Astros now that they have Randy Johnson, entered their game in San
Francisco Monday night farther away from Houston _ seven and a half
games _ than they had been at any time this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants have scrambled to acquire hitters and relief pitchers
to shore up their sagging chances, but Joe Carter, one of the
hitters, isn't hitting .200, and Jose Mesa, one of the relievers,
has given away as many games recently as Franco.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have shuffled and reshuffled themselves throughout
the season, like a person changing hairstyles and clothes in an
attempt to create an acceptable personality. They may still not
have it right.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, too, have done their share of scrambling and
bolstering, not all of which has been beneficial. But here they
are, within grasp of a playoff spot their critics were convinced
would be beyond their reach this season.
</P>
<P>
   With Tony Phillips igniting their offense, John Olerud and Brian
McRae supplying key hits, Mike Piazza showing glimpses of being the
productive hitter they thought they acquired and a starting
pitching rotation that keeps them in games, the Mets could snatch
the spot in spite of their bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   They no longer are Terry Malloy of ``On the Waterfront,'' who
coulda been a contender. They are a contender and have good reason
to believe they will be the successful contender.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
