<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7041 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANADA-LIVENT-ART-765     08-10 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-LIVENT-ART-765&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROADWAY PRODUCER HAS ACCOUNTING PROBLEMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Mass.)  (With sidebar, LIVENT-DRABINSKY) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(lb) 
 By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Livent Inc., the producer of such Broadway shows as
``Ragtime'' and ``Show Boat,'' announced Monday that an internal
investigation had found serious accounting problems involving
millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The company's new managers, led by Michael Ovitz, the former
Hollywood power broker, said that they were ``virtually certain''
that the company's financial results dating back to the beginning
of 1996 would have to be restated.
</P>
<P>
   After an emergency meeting of the board in Toronto on Monday
morning, the company suspended Garth Drabinsky, the impresario who
built the company from a single production in a Toronto theater
into a roster of shows in a network of theaters from Times Square
to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Drabinsky had been in charge of both the creative and the
financial sides of the company before Ovitz and other executives
took over on June 12. Also suspended from his job was Myron
Gottlieb, a vice president, who co-founded the company with
Drabinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Livent's management said in a written statement that the
accounting irregularities involve the improper recognition of
revenue and the failure to record expenses. But executives said
they could not yet say precisely how much money was involved.
</P>
<P>
   Executives said that the financial problems would not affect any
of the company's current shows or its ambitious plans for the
future. Last week, Livent agreed to lease the last unclaimed
historic theater on 42nd Street, the long-dormant Times Square
Theater. The 500-seat theater is next door to the company's Ford
Theater, where ``Ragtime'' is selling out almost every night.
</P>
<P>
   But some entertainment-industry analysts said Monday that the
announcement was another sign of the trouble at a company that has
been struggling to pay its millions of dollars of debts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This doesn't bode particularly well for Livent,'' said Edward
Lawrence, an entertainment-industry analyst at Standard &AMP; Poor's,
the bond-rating agency. The agency lowered the company's credit
rating Monday to ``B plus'' from ``BB minus'' after management's
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last five years, Livent has borrowed heavily to build
theaters _ notably the Ford Centers for the Performing Arts in New
York, Chicago, and Vancouver, British Columbia. The Chicago theater
is scheduled to open in October.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence said it was ``too early to tell'' if the company could
continue with its plans, because management had not yet given
enough details of the problems that it began uncovering late last
week. ``Most people are still in the dark,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Ovitz, who left Disney Corp. in December 1996, paid
$20 million for a 12 percent stake in Livent, the world's only
publicly held company whose primary business is live theater
production. The deal also gave Ovitz control of 36 percent of the
voting rights in Livent.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz joined the company as a board member and chairman of the
executive committee in June. And he brought with him Roy Furman, an
investment banker who replaced Drabinsky as chairman and chief
executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   While Drabinsky gave up his financial responsibilities, he
remained the company's chief creative director. And Gottlieb, who
had been the company's president, became a vice president for
Canadian administration.
</P>
<P>
   Livent had long been known on Broadway for its aggressive
accounting techniques. But early this year, Ovitz and Furman had
brought in the accounting firm KPMG and the Wall Street law firm
Skadden, Arps, Slate, Meagher &AMP; Flom, to review the company's
records for problems before they took over in June. Nothing in
those reviews found anything that deterred the new management from
taking over.
</P>
<P>
   Sources familiar with the situation said that management began
uncovering accounting problems late last week that were
``significantly different'' from anything that the company had been
criticized for before. Those problems were discovered as
accountants were preparing the second quarter's financial results.
</P>
<P>
   Management had found that some of the company's ``transactions''
contained arrangements that the board had not known about that
could financially hurt the company, those sources said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, management had found that certain costs had been
shifted between accounts, the sources said, so that they could
remain on the accounting books as a capitalized asset instead of
being written off and reducing profits.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in one case, the costs of a show that was about to
close might have been moved to another account so that they would
not reduce the company's profits.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Many of the company's board members had long known and been
friends with Drabinsky. But at Monday's meeting, the board voted
unanimously to suspend both Drabinsky and Gottlieb and to hire KPMG
for a detailed investigation of the accounting problems. After more
review, the board will decide whether the men should keep their
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an unhappy and tragic situation,'' said one source
when asked about the events at Monday's board meeting.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Drabinsky and Gottlieb said the men were not
available for comment. But in a written statement, the men said
they were ``surprised and dismayed at concerns raised by the new
senior management.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The company has provided few details,'' the statement said,
``and no practical opportunity for us to address or respond to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The men's statement noted that KPMG had reviewed Livent's
accounting practices before Ovitz and Furman took over in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``New management was provided ample opportunity, prior to
closure of the transaction, to raise any accounting concerns,'' the
statement said. ``We are hopeful of a resolution that will be in
the best interests of Livent's shareholders and business partners,
and that will respect its artistic relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's auditing firm, Deloitte &AMP; Touche, said Monday that
it was ``deeply concerned'' about Monday's announcement. A
spokeswoman for the accounting firm said that the auditors would
fully cooperate with the company's board as the investigation
continues.
</P>
<P>
   Management said that the accounting problems should not have
significantly hurt the company's cash flow. But the problems could
cause the company to default on its debt obligations, executives
said. On Monday the Canadian exchange stopped all trading on the
stock because of management's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Livent's newest musical, ``Fosse: A Celebration in Song and
Dance,'' opened on Sunday in Toronto, just hours before the company
announced the accounting problems. The show is scheduled to play in
Boston in September.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Gersten, executive producer for Lincoln Center Theater,
said that the company's announcement took him by surprise, because
he had met with Drabinsky and Furman only last week. But Gersten
said that ``Parade,'' a musical developed by Livent that is
scheduled to open at Lincoln Center in September, would go on.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Livent fell to $10.15 (Canadian) on the Toronto Stock
Exchange before trading was halted. On the Nasdaq market, the stock
rose to $6.75.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-98 2111EDT &QL; 
