<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HEALTHCARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNEASY ABOUT TIMING OF FUND-RAISERS, CLINTON SHORTENS TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE  
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ President Clinton began a transcontinental
fund-raising spree Monday, but his spokesman said that the
president felt uncomfortable on the political circuit so soon after
the bombings at two United States embassies in Africa, and as a
result he was cutting short his time on the road.
</P>
<P>
   But he is missing only one fund-raising event and plans to
attend five others, three in California for Lt. Gov. Gray Davis,
who is running for governor. At each of the receptions on Tuesday
for Davis _ one in San Francisco and two in Los Angeles _ Clinton
is expected to raise $1 million from some of the Democratic Party's
biggest donors, in all $3 million in eight hours.
</P>
<P>
   Combined with a dinner here Monday night for Sen. Carol
Moseley-Braun and other Democratic candidates, and a luncheon
Monday afternoon in Louisville, Ky., for Rep. Scotty Baesler, who
is running for the Senate, Clinton is expected to raise more than
$4 million in two days.
</P>
<P>
   But as television screens filled with images of bodies being
removed from the rubble in Kenya and Tanzania, Clinton decided late
Sunday to return to Washington on Wednesday morning instead of
early on Thursday, as originally planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president felt it was important to come back,'' said his
spokesman, Joe Lockhart. ``He was not really comfortable being out
three days.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who is preparing to testify to a grand jury next Monday
in the Monica S. Lewinsky investigation, is scheduled to take a
late-night flight back to Washington, arriving at dawn on
Wednesday. He plans to meet with his national security advisers
later on Wednesday and to attend a memorial ceremony at Andrews Air
Force Base on Thursday, when the remains of the 12 Americans killed
in Africa are scheduled to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   But his change in plans will not affect much else. He is
canceling an anti-crime event in Los Angeles that has yet to be set
up anyway, the kind of quasi news, issue-related set piece that
presidents typically stage so they can charge taxpayers for at
least part of the cost of their political fund-raising trips.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will also miss a nighttime rally in Milwaukee for
Wisconsin Democrats, including Sen. Russell D. Feingold. This event
was the smallest money-wise on Clinton's schedule, with 700 people
contributing a total of $100,000. But they will still see a
Clinton: his wife, Hillary, was to fill in for him.
</P>
<P>
   In their enduring efforts to portray Clinton as not being
distracted by the Lewinsky investigation, White House officials
Monday cast the president as overseeing the latest developments in
the bombings in Africa. But they were quick to assert that he could
stay in charge even while traveling because of the advanced
communications systems aboard Air Force One.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the ability to fully fulfill his responsibilities as
Commander in Chief,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Given that ability, it was not entirely clear why Clinton felt
it was so urgent to cut his trip short _ or if it was that urgent,
why he even left Washington. But Clinton has not allowed much time
to prepare for his testimony regarding his relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he wanted to keep his financial commitments to
Davis and to his hosts, Jeffrey Katzenberg, the Hollywood producer,
and Bruce Karatz, the biggest home-builder in California.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton suggested in Louisville that teams in Africa were
successfully tracking clues to the bombings. ``They are searching
and finding evidence,'' he said. But otherwise, his public comments
on the bombing were restricted to asking for a moment of silence in
honor of the dead, stating the nation's resolve in the face of
terrorism, and vowing to bring the ``murderers'' to justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must be strong in dealing with this,'' the president said.
``There is no way out if we start running away from this kind of
conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   But the main event in Louisville concerned the ``patients' bill
of rights'' that is moving through Congress. Clinton told an
enthusiastic crowd at the Commonwealth Convention Center that he
would veto the bill being backed by the Republican leaders, a bill
that he said did not offer enough protection for patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a bill of rights, not a bill of goods,'' Clinton said.
If Congress passes the Republican bill, ``I will be forced to veto
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
