<DOCNO> NYT19980810.0398 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7053 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLAMOUR-AD-COLUMN-NYT     08-10 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLAMOUR-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: COSMO'S EDITOR MOVES TO GLAMOUR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ll) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ruth Whitney, who made her multifaceted vision of
young women the trademark of Glamour magazine for more than three
decades, is retiring as its editor. S.I. Newhouse Jr., chairman of
Advance Publications, has recruited Bonnie Fuller, editor of its
archrival, Cosmopolitan, to succeed her.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Whitney's departure, coming just 18 months after Helen
Gurley Brown, for three decades the reigning spirit behind the
Cosmo girl, retired from her perch atop Hearst Magazines'
best-known publication, leaves the world of women's magazines shorn
of the two women whose sensibilities defined it for a generation.
</P>
<P>
   But while Ms. Brown's vision of modern women focused on sexual
freedom and relationships, Ms. Whitney, an advertising agency
executive said, tended to look beyond those two factors and provide
more practical advice on everything from work to sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more sex in Cosmo than there is in Glamour,'' said
Roberta Garfinkle, a senior vice president of McCann-Erickson New
York. ``But I think they're both essentially talking to the same
audience, the same young women. They're just talking in different
tones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Glamour is a little more how-to, hands-on, how to do it,
whether it's dressing or men or our careers,'' she added. ``They're
saying, `This is what you need to do and this is how you need to do
it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Newhouse's successful attempt to recruit Ms. Fuller to Conde
Nast Publications from the Hearst magazines, where she had made
most of her career, signals a new round of sharp competition
between the two magazines, both aimed at the upscale 18- to
35-year-old woman who likes to shop, relax and relate.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fuller, 41, who joined Cosmopolitan as Ms. Brown's heir
apparent two years ago, was approached about a week ago by Newhouse
_ ``in the recent past,'' in his phrase _ as he was having
discussions with Ms. Whitney, 70, about her departure. Ms. Fuller's
arrival at Glamour also marks the second transfer of editorial
power at a high-visibility Conde Nast publication this summer,
coming less than a month after David Remnick replaced Tina Brown at
The New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very orderly transition,'' Newhouse said, ``though
in fact, even The New Yorker had an orderly transition. But this
was probably more so. Ruth's been there 31 years. And she said to
me she realized it was time. I don't feel that this was an event
that came out of nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   If the New Yorker whirlwind was the focus of comment in the
worlds of literature and journalism, advertisers were the ones
paying the closest attention to the shift in these ad-rich women's
publications. Glamour has for years played Avis to the more opulent
and larger-circulation Cosmopolitan's Hertz, but last year, for the
first time ever, the smaller magazine nosed out its perennial rival
in advertising pages.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of 1997, according to the Publishers Information
Bureau, Cosmopolitan had sold 1,893 ad pages, while Glamour had
sold 1,940. Through the second quarter of 1998, according to the
bureau, Cosmopolitan has sold 1,099 ad pages; Glamour, 1,078.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things Bonnie has done with Cosmo,'' said Ms.
Garfinkle of McCann-Erickson, ``is that, because there's more
beauty and fashion editorial pages, there's more beauty and fashion
advertising now.''
</P>
<P>
   But, she added, there is no clear category of advertising _ like
beauty products or fashion _ that is likely to follow Ms. Fuller
and leave Cosmopolitan behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if there's a category that Glamour has and now
Cosmo won't get,'' Ms. Garfinkle said. ``They are very head-to-head
on the advertising side.''
</P>
<P>
   Cathleen Black, the president of Hearst Magazines, who learned
of Ms. Fuller's impending departure at a meeting last Thursday,
announced on Monday that Kate White, the editor of Redbook, would
succeed Ms. Fuller as editor of Cosmopolitan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have loved Bonnie to stay at Cosmo because she was
very successful,'' Ms. Black said on Monday. ``But I'm thrilled
Kate is here. Plus I think Bonnie's nuts _ why would anyone leave
the largest young women's magazine in the world to go to Glamour?''
</P>
<P>
   Cosmopolitan's current circulation is 2.7 million, according to
its publisher, Donna Kalajan. Glamour, the largest of Conde Nast's
17 magazines in both advertising and readership, has a circulation
of 2.3 million, said a Conde Nast spokeswoman, Maurie Perl.
</P>
<P>
   Newhouse, chairman of Conde Nast's parent, Advance Publications,
offered a farewell paean to Ms. Whitney on Monday, saying: ``I was
present at the creation 31 years ago when Ruth came into our lives,
and she is a consummately dedicated capable and quite brilliant
editor. She's all business, totally committed to her magazine. She
also played an important part in the whole change in women's roles
since 1967. I think she's a remarkable editor.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he wanted in her successor, he said: ``It's not a
question that is part of my thinking. I don't look for something as
a finite thing.''
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Fuller, following Ms. Whitney at Glamour had some
parallels with following Ms. Brown at Cosmopolitan.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you inherit a successful magazine, your biggest fear is
that your going to muck it up,'' she said. ``The challenge is to
build on the strengths, to invigorate and energize and not lose the
reader who likes so many things in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. White, 46, said she had once been sent to interview Ms.
Brown by her editor at GQ, Art Cooper, who sent her off saying,
``Kate, I can see you as the editor of Cosmo.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Sunday, when Ms. Black called her into the city from her
country home in Bucks County, Pa., to offer her the job, Ms. White
has been mapping her strategy for a magazine that has twice as much
editorial space as Redbook.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just plan to get in there and run with the formula,'' Ms.
White said. ``I just did a book called `Nine Secrets of Women Who
Get Everything They Want.' Two of the chapters were called `Bite
off more than you can chew' and `Wear your heart on your sleeve.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to make every issue fresh and exciting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-98 2115EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
