<DOCNO> NYT19980810.0399 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7054 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REFUGEE-RELATIVES-COX     08-10 0395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFUGEE-RELATIVES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    One family grieves, another waits at hospital after Hatian
refugees abandoned
 &HT;    (EDS: Runs with REFUGEES-COX and ASHORE-COX. Stories will move
on (a) National and (i) International wires.)
 &HT;    By Seth Mnookin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DELRAY BEACH, Fla. _ Jean-Renold Camille of Boynton Beach, Fla.
hasn't seen his wife in almost six years; not since he came to
Florida from Haiti in 1992 seeking political asylum.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, he got a phone call from the small town in Haiti he
comes from. Myrtha, his wife, told him she was going to sail to
Florida Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her not to do it,'' said Camille, 42, a prep cook in
suburban Boca Raton. ``It is crazy, so dangerous. But someone gets
in their mind to come to America, and no one can say no.''
</P>
<P>
   Myrtha Camille, one of 33 Haitian refugees forced onto a sandbar
before dawn Monday near Florida's Jupiter Inlet, was hospitalized
after officials found the group. Jean-Renold Camille said he was
waiting to be granted political asylum so his wife could legally
join him.
</P>
<P>
   ``She swallowed so much water. ... They have still not let me
see her,'' Camille said late Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Camille and Joseph Dorsonne _ whose daughter, Benette, 25,
drowned while trying to make it to shore _ were at the Haitian
American Community Council in Delray Monday seeking help from
council President Daniella Henry. They also talked with a Palm
Beach County sheriff's detective at the council's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughter, Benette,'' Dorsonne sobbed in Henry's office.
</P>
<P>
   Dorsonne, 56, has lived in Delray Beach since 1980. He last saw
Benette in July, he said, when he visited Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her mother does not even know yet,'' Dorsonne said. ``She is
at work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is crazy to do this in a boat. You get caught, or the boat
is not good, and it crashes,'' Dorsonne said.
</P>
<P>
   Dorsonne said he received a call from Benette on Sunday and
urged his daughter not to attempt the trip. He said he applied in
1990 for her legal passage to the United States, but she didn't
want to wait anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the political situation, everyone wants to leave,''
Camille said. ``But then this is what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Seth Mnookin writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
