<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDMAN-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: GOLDMAN PARTNERS VOTE TO SELL SHARES TO PUBLIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also GOLDMAN-RUBIN) 
(af) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. partners voted overwhelming
Monday to sell shares in Wall Street's most profitable private
investment bank, formally approving an offering plan that values
the firm at $28 billion and promises employees a big cut of the
riches.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was expected after the decision in principle in June to
take Goldman public. But it showed that some of the investment
world's savviest underwriters remain confident that the stock
market will stay strong enough through the fall to reward Goldman's
owners with the lofty premium they expect for their shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``Full steam ahead,'' one Goldman partner said after the firm's
early morning balloting, adding that his colleagues were not
unnerved by the recent sharp drop in stock prices. ``It's the right
thing to do at the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   The offering, scheduled for late October, will give Goldman
stock, a tool it has lacked during the furious round of mergers and
acquisitions among its rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. and Salomon
Smith Barney have all used their stock to expand at home and abroad
and lure top banking talent. Goldman is now expected to join the
fray, though its leaders insist they will stick to their core
mission of providing investment banking services to blue-chip
companies, governments and wealthy private clients.
</P>
<P>
   Though Goldman partners rejected the idea of selling shares half
a dozen times in recent years, fearing public ownership would
dilute its culture, they are solidly behind the plan to sell shares
this time. One reason is the historically unprecedented prices the
public is willing to pay for the best financial companies, a
premium that will make Goldman's initial public offering one of the
richest ever.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the Goldman offering plan will not be made public
until late this month or early next month when the firm registers
with the Securities and Exchange Commission to issue shares.
</P>
<P>
   But Goldman partners familiar with the plan approved Monday said
the firm anticipates selling 10 percent to 15 percent of its shares
to the public, raising about $3 billion. The offering will price
the whole firm at $28 billion, possibly a little more or less
depending on stock market trends between now and October.
</P>
<P>
   That is slightly below the high end of the range anticipated
earlier in the summer, reflecting a cooling in the share prices of
other big investment banks since that time. But it would still
represent a much larger premium _ about 3.5 times book value _ than
Morgan or Merrill received when they went public, in 1986 and 1971,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Acting on a pledge to share the wealth, the partners will set
aside $5 billion to $6 billion worth of Goldman shares for the
11,300 employees below the level of partner, Goldman executives
familiar with the plan said.
</P>
<P>
   The shares will be granted immediately but cannot be sold for
three to five years, a way of tying employees to the firm after the
public offering.
</P>
<P>
   Some of that compensation pool would be distributed according to
an automatic formula that applies to every full-time Goldman
employee worldwide, maid to managing director. Every worker will
get shares equivalent to half of their total compensation this
year, plus a bonus for each year the person has worked at the firm.
</P>
<P>
   Partners will dole out the rest of the compensation pool to
senior and mid-range employees based on their performances, like a
bonus fund. Some of the 211 managing directors who have yet to make
partner, especially those who have produced big revenues for the
firm, could receive up to $15 million. Many others would receive
much smaller bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman has also agreed to pay a premium to its outside
investors, including limited or retired Goldman partners who keep
money in the firm and several passive investors, including Sumitomo
Bank in Japan and Kamehameha Schools/Bishop Estate in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman has offered limited partners a return of between 25
percent and 55 percent on their investment, depending on whether
they want cash or stock.
</P>
<P>
   The 189 general partners, Goldman's sole legal owners, will get
the remaining shares for themselves. That will give them a new
collective net worth of $15 billion to $17 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The junior-most partners, those given the title as recently as
1996, would receive at least $40 million in shares. The
senior-most, including Jon S. Corzine and Henry M. Paulson Jr., the
firm's co-chairmen and chief executives, and Roy J. Zuckerberg,
Goldman's longest-serving partner, would receive up to $200
million, people familiar with the plans said.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman has already begun to think like a public company, using
stock as a lure for new hires. The hope is that the firm will add
to its roster of talented bankers as it prepares to market itself
to the investing public.
</P>
<P>
   It is believed that Goldman is offering some prospective
recruits multiyear packages worth $10 million to $25 million in
cash and stock. In the past, Goldman has not offered new hires that
kind of money, in large part because it would have come directly
out of the partners' own capital.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman recently hired Michael Carr, co-head of mergers and
acquisitions at Salomon Smith Barney. Carr is a specialist in
industrial companies.
</P>
<P>
   But Goldman failed to attract another Salomon star, the
telecommunications analyst Jack Grubman. Grubman turned down an
offer this weekend after Sanford I. Weill, the chairman of
Salomon's parent, Travelers Group, made a personal pitch to keep
him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
