<HEADER>
A7061 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-FAME-NYT &LR;      08-10 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-FAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALL OF FAME JOINS PAST AND PRESENT  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH DURSO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ Ansel Williamson, the onetime slave who
trained the first winner of the Kentucky Derby in 1875, was
inducted into the thoroughbred Hall of Fame on Monday as a legend
of racing's past. He was joined by 45-year-old Bill Mott, who
saddled Cigar and is a legend of the present, the youngest trainer
ever enshrined.
</P>
<P>
   ``It came awfully early in life,'' Mott said, sounding a bit
awed. ``It was never planned; it was never expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Racing put its best foot forward for its 43rd annual ceremony,
which attracted a standing-room crowd of 1,200 under a tent pitched
on a field next to the National Museum of Racing across Union
Avenue from the Saratoga Race Course, which is booming in its 130th
year. Dozens of famous trainers and jockeys of the past sat
together as footnotes to history, applauding the six racing figures
being honored.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Williamson and Mott, they were Jacinto Vasquez, the
jockey who rode 5,231 winners, won the Kentucky Derby twice and won
268 stakes races, and three celebrated horses: Riva Ridge, the
stablemate of Secretariat and the juvenile champion of 1971, who
went on to win the Kentucky Derby and the Belmont Stakes in 1972;
Bayakoa, the Argentine filly, who became a double champion in the
United States by winning 16 of her 21 starts in 1989 and 1990, and
Fort Marcy, three times a champion on grass and Horse of the Year
for his exploits in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   They brought the Hall of Fame roster to 77 jockeys, 71 trainers
and 154 horses. But few have been honored as early as Bill Mott, a
veterinarian's son from South Dakota, who started cleaning out
stalls at the age of 14 for $50 a week and had become a superstar
by the time he turned 40. By the close of last year, he had
achieved these towering numbers: 10,750 races started, 2,330
winners for a 22 percent success rate and purse money of $80
million.
</P>
<P>
   He ranks on the top rung of trainers with D. Wayne Lukas, the
runaway leader on most charts, who chafes because the rules say a
trainer must be licensed for 25 years to be considered for the Hall
of Fame. Lukas contends he has been a trainer far longer. He is
supported by Mott, who says: ``Nobody deserves to be in the Hall of
Fame more than Wayne. He changed the face of racing.''
</P>
<P>
   Mott was presented for his induction by an old boss and mentor,
Jack Van Berg, a Hall of Fame trainer himself, who flew in from the
West Coast and said, ``I wouldn't have missed this if I had had to
walk from California.''
</P>
<P>
   Mott gained fame after he switched Cigar from grass to dirt and
then saw his star win 16 straight races. He also trained the
champions Theatrical, Paradise Creek and Ajina, and he saddled the
1997 Horse of the Year, Favorite Trick, here on Sunday for the Jim
Dandy Stakes, which the colt won by a nose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am honored and humbled,'' Mott said. ``I've been blessed by
the number of friends I've had and by the support of my family.
I've had assistants who have been with me for more than a decade.
I've received some year-end awards. But this one is for a career.''
</P>
<P>
   In terms of age, he surpassed the record set by Allen Jerkens,
who was elected to the Hall of Fame in 1975 when he was 46.
</P>
<P>
   But if the election of Mott marked a triumph for the present,
the recognition belatedly accorded Williamson marked a triumph for
history.
</P>
<P>
   He was born a slave around 1806 in Virginia, and his days as a
horse trainer have been traced to the 1850's. He had significant
victories in New Orleans, Charleston, Atlanta and Mobile, and then
won the Jersey Derby with Norfolk, the Travers with Tom Bowling and
the inaugural Kentucky Derby with Aristides. He died in 1881,
leaving no descendants but many major successes.
</P>
<P>
   Vasquez came to this country in 1960 from Panama and, when he
retired two years ago, stood 15th ion the career list in winners.
He won the Kentucky Derby in 1976 with Foolish Pleasure and in 1980
with the filly Genuine Risk. He elected to ride the undefeated
filly Ruffian in her ill-fated match race with Foolish Pleasure,
and his presenter was Frank Whiteley, the Hall of Fame trainer of
Ruffian, who said, ``You've been deserving of this for a long
time.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-98 2118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980810.0406 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7063 &Cx1f; tad-z
a s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWM-NATIONALS-COX     08-10 0370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWM-NATIONALS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Schumacher wants chance to double
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLOVIS, Calif. _ Brad Schumacher has the singular goal of double
dipping in the Sydney Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   After this week's U.S. Swimming National Championships, he'll
know if he's heading in the right direction or just treading water.
</P>
<P>
   Because Schumacher has all but been named to the U.S. water polo
team, ''More and more,'' he said, ''it looks like it's going to be
a matter of me making the swim team'' to reach his two-sport
objective.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Schumacher won two freestyle relay gold medals at
the 1996 Atlanta Games won't hold water when he arrives at the 2000
Trials. And if he makes the U.S. team, he wants a clear shot at his
goal.
</P>
<P>
   Schumacher had to appeal to a U.S. swimming board of review for
permission to compete in both sports at the 1999 World
Championships, where he became the first athlete to win gold in
each. Swimming national team director Dennis Pursley originally
denied the bid because he thought Schumacher would set a bad
precedent by missing a few days of training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Schumacher, 24, of Bowie, Md., will soon send a letter to U.S.
Swimming spelling out his intentions, ''because there's no reason
for them not to let me do it,'' he said. ''It doesn't make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   At the World Championships, the sports overlapped; at the
Olympics, swimming will be the first week and water polo the
second.
</P>
<P>
   Swimming championships
</P>
<P>
   _ When: Today through Saturday
</P>
<P>
   _ Where: Clovis, Calif. (a suburb of Fresno)
</P>
<P>
   _ Who: More than 1,100 of the nation's top swimmers, including
Olympians and top Georgians such as Kristy Kowal and Sabir Muhammad
</P>
<P>
   _ At stake: Berths on four teams: Pan American Games, Pan
Pacifics, World Short Course Championships and World University
Games
</P>
<P>
   _ Schedule: Today women's 800 free. Wednesday 100 free, 200
breast, 200 back, 200 fly. Thursday: 200 free, 400 IM, 400 free
relay. Friday: 100 back, 400 free, 100 fly, 800 free relay.
Saturday: 200 IM, 1,500 free, 50 free, 400 medley relay.
</P>
<P>
   _ TV: Aug. 30, 2:30-4 p.m., NBC/Channel 11
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
