<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7070 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIVENT-DRABINSKY-465&AMP;     08-10 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVENT-DRABINSKY-465&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CURTAIN DROPS ON OUTSIZED PRODUCER AND SPENDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (With CANADA-LIVENT)  
(lb) 
 By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Garth Drabinsky, the Canadian showman whose
flamboyant rise to prominence on Broadway has apparently come to a
halt, was a man who inspired both admiration and resentment from
his colleagues in the staid business of live theater.
</P>
<P>
   Drabinsky, ousted Monday as chief creative director of Livent
Inc., the theater company he helped found, was known for
outspending rival producers for actors' salaries, stage sets and
advertising. As a result, he was long the subject of suspicion
among those who could not figure out how he made the numbers add
up.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, many of his loudest critics gave him credit
for his accomplishments: the lush and lovely revival of ``Show
Boat,'' which ran for two years at the Gershwin Theater and
recouped its cost, though at $10 million it was very likely the
most expensive musical revival of all time; the construction, on
time and on budget, of the Ford Center for the Performing Arts on
West 42nd Street, a nearly universally praised building that, with
musical theater houses in short supply, Broadway and New York City
needed; and the original musical ``Ragtime,'' which won four Tony
awards and is virtually selling out at the Ford Center eight times
a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admired his passion and commitment to his goal, which was
the production of quality theater that would appeal to and reach
worldwide audiences,'' said John Breglio, an entertainment lawyer
who has had wide dealings with Drabinsky. ``But as an outside
observer, I was confounded by certain business decisions, namely
the production and advertising costs, which seemed to contradict
good economic sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Drabinsky, 48, is known as a man with expensive tastes,
considerable self-regard and no lack of confidence. The profile of
a man who would spend lavishly, perhaps recklessly, to support and
sell his artistic vision is in sync with Drabinsky's reputation for
arrogance and hubris. And he has been cut down before.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979 he founded Cineplex Odeon, the movie-theater concern,
building it over a decade from an 18-screen complex in Toronto to
an 1,800-screen chain throughout the United States and Canada. But
in his expansion plans, which included film production and
distribution and forays into live theater, he ran afoul of MCA, the
partner he had taken on in 1986 to avert bankruptcy. MCA ousted him
in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   As severance, he took with him the company's live-entertainment
division, consisting of two assets: the newly renovated Pantages
Theater in Toronto, and the right to present in it the Andrew Lloyd
Webber musical ``The Phantom of the Opera.'' That was the
foundation of Livent.
</P>
<P>
   Now that he has once again taken on partners to avert financial
disaster, history has repeated itself and he has again been
dismissed from the company he created.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Since Livent was revamped in April, Drabinsky's position has
been widely speculated to be precarious, but Monday's announcement
was nonetheless surprising.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised and I'm sad, because our experience with Livent
under Garth's direction has been excellent,'' said Cora Cahan,
president of the New 42nd Street, a nonprofit development agency,
which is effectively Livent's landlord for the Ford Center and
which signed an agreement with Livent last week to take over the
Times Square Theater, the last empty theater on 42nd Street.
(Livent has proposed to create within the current building a
500-seat house for plays and small musicals, a restaurant and
offices.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We have other men who own theaters,'' Ms. Cahan said. ``We
don't have too many with such vivid dreams. It's sad what's
happened to him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
