<HEADER>
A7073 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-GIANTS-NYT &LR;      08-10 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS MAY GAMBLE ON PLAN FOR SAFETY  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL PENNINGTON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ There is a secret plan afoot for the Giants'
rookie safety, Shaun Williams. But something this simple can't stay
a secret for long.
</P>
<P>
   The plan? Get Williams on the field as much as anyone, even if
it means some very unconventional alignments _ such as a
one-linebacker set that puts all four of the Giants' talented
safeties on the field at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   It may sound needlessly risky, and it is a concept still
confined to training camp, but the Giants' defense has been
elevated to an elite status by defying convention.
</P>
<P>
   Jessie Armstead was supposed to be too small to play weakside
linebacker. He made the Pro Bowl last year.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Scott Galyon was supposed to be too much like
Armstead to be useful. Galyon was in 350 plays from scrimmage as a
nickel linebacker last season and dominated. Jason Sehorn was
supposed to be too big for cornerback. He is now considered among
the top five at his position.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is a hybrid player _ with the size and instincts of a
safety and the skills of a cornerback. That is the kind of
combination that tantalizes coaches who spend hours in darkened
film rooms searching for ways to confuse the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Why not then create a hybrid defense suited to the skills of a
unique player?
</P>
<P>
   The blueprint has been drawn, but the implementation may take
several weeks. Williams, the team's first-round draft pick out of
UCLA, is still learning the basics of strong safety, where he is
the backup to Sam Garnes. Williams is also still learning the
one-on-one skills he will need to become the nickel defender
assigned to the slot receiver in obvious passing situations.
</P>
<P>
   Tutelage in those disciplines occupies his time for now. And
there are his special teams duties, which should get Williams on
the field for another 350 to 370 plays this season.
</P>
<P>
   But if Williams can play reliably in the nickel defense with
safeties Percy Ellsworth and Tito Wooten and cornerbacks Sehorn and
Phillippi Sparks, then maybe the Giants can sneak Garnes onto the
field, too. Garnes, powerfully built at 228 pounds and known as a
ferocious hitter, could be disguised as a linebacker. Add Armstead
to that mix and that is a mighty formidable seven behind the front
line.
</P>
<P>
   And what would opposing offenses make of a defense with four
safeties, three of whom are more than capable against the run?
Ellsworth, after all, is 225 pounds and Williams is 216 pounds and
also known as a hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Is this a defense daring you to run or daring you to pass?
</P>
<P>
   It's mostly theory for now, but it's one the Giants coaches have
tinkered with. Anything to get Williams on the field more often.
</P>
<P>
   He isn't ready for the advanced lessons yet, and the Giants
defense is playing well enough that there's no need to rush
Williams' education.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Giants' opponents become more difficult, as the games
with San Francisco, Denver and Green Bay get closer and as the
division opponents prepare to play the Giants a second time, it
will tempting for the Giants' coaching staff to unveil a new,
powerful wrinkle or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically, Shaun can do all these things,'' said the Giants'
defensive coordinator, John Fox. ``I'm not worried about that. He's
got those kind of special abilities. But normally, you wouldn't
even think of asking a rookie to learn so much. But he can handle
that, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you watch him develop and you see a confidence in him that
comes from being successful. And you dream about the other things
that might be possible. But there are other players who deserve
expanded roles, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox's problem is that Marcus Buckley, the new strongside
linebacker, is good in pass coverage. So is Galyon, who had another
strong game Saturday against Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams did not hurt his case on Saturday, either. He made
mistakes but opened eyes, too. He forced a fumble with a jarring
hit at the line of scrimmage, and he held his own when facing
receivers one on one. Most of all, he played a lot, virtually every
play of the second half that didn't involve the team's offense.
</P>
<P>
   That may have been the future on display for the Giants' defense
Saturday night. Shaun Williams played safety. Shaun Williams played
like a cornerback. Shaun Williams played on special teams.
</P>
<P>
   Some secret.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
