<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDOUGAL-TRIAL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY SELECTION BEGINS IN MCDOUGAL EMBEZZELMENT TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: clarifications in 7th paragraph, saying Bill Clinton was
governor at the time of loan, not president.)  (ll) 
 By DON TERRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After years of delays and legal wrangling, jury
selection began on Monday in Susan McDougal's embezzlement trial in
Santa Monica.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. McDougal, who spent nearly two years in jail for refusing
to answer questions from the Whitewater independent counsel,
Kenneth Starr, faces up to seven more years behind bars if
convicted in her latest battle with the law.
</P>
<P>
   In Santa Monica, she stands accused of bilking conductor Zubin
Mehta and his wife, Nancy, out of more than $150,000 when Mrs.
McDougal was their personal assistant and bookkeeper from 1989 to
1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad to start the trial but I'm hurting a little bit
today,'' she told The Associated Press, referring to the back
problems that prompted a federal judge to release her from a
California prison in June and send her to her parents' home in
Camden, Ark., as part of a 90-day home-detention sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. McDougal, 43, wore a back brace under her dress at the
courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   When she was released, Mrs. McDougal was three and a half months
into a two-year sentence for taking part in a fraudulent scheme to
obtain a $300,000 loan in 1986 that was paid to a company she
created called Master Marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the proceeds went to pay the debts of the Whitewater
Development Co., in which she and her husband, James McDougal, were
partnersin Arkansas with Gov. Bill Clinton and Hillary Rodham
Clinton. Mrs. McDougal and her husband were separated in 1984 and
divorced in 1990. He died in prison in March of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. McDougal's current legal problems have nothing to do with
her defiant role in the Whitewater investigation. Los Angeles
County Superior Court Judge Leslie Light told the dozens of
potential jurors on Monday to disregard ``anything and everything''
they may have heard about Mrs. McDougal from that case.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Monica charges were filed against her five years ago
and ``we have basically been waiting since then,'' said Sandi
Gibbons, a spokeswoman for the Los Angeles County District
Attorney's office. ``We did agree to allow her other prosecution
back East to be completed.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. McDougal is facing 12 counts of embezzlement and fraud in a
case that is built around the Mehtas' financial records.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. McDougal, who lived in one of the Mehta family's five homes
and traveled throughout the United States and abroad for Mehta's
concerts, is, among other offenses, accused of forging Mrs. Mehta's
name on a credit card application and fraudulently charging more
than $90,000 of personal items, including expensive clothes and
hotel stays.
</P>
<P>
   She is also accused of charging thousands of dollars of personal
air travel and of bilking the couple out of $65,000 in falsely
claimed expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The court has imposed an order that neither side can discuss the
evidence of the case outside the courtroom, but in a previous
interview, Mrs. McDougal's lawyer, Mark Geragos, said the Mehta
case would have been dropped long ago if the defendant were not a
prominent figure in the Whitewater investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Geragos said Starr's prosecution team had used the California
charges as a ``club'' to force Mrs. McDougal to cooperate, an
accusation Starr's team denies. The local prosecutor, Jeffrey
Semow, has also denied any connection between the two matters.
</P>
<P>
   The delays are not over yet.
</P>
<P>
   After the jury is selected, Ms. Gibbons said, the trial will
take a two-week hiatus so the defense and prosecutors can review
thousands of pages of recently released Internal Revenue Service
documents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
