</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-RIGHTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON VOWS TO VETO GOP PLAN, URGES `PATIENT BILL OF RIGHTS' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ President Clinton vowed Monday to veto
Republican legislation that would provide some protections for
patients in managed health care plans, saying it fails to offer key
safeguards.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton left the sex scandal swirl of Washington to attend a
series of fund-raising events for Democrats in Kentucky, Illinois
and California. He will return Wednesday, a day earlier than
planned so he can meet with national security advisers following
the embassy bombings in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The president later raised $400,000 for candidates in Kentucky
and flew to Chicago where he raised $1 million for the Democratic
Party. Clinton on Tuesday will raise $3 million at three events in
California for Gray Davis, the Democratic candidate for governor.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of protesters greeted Clinton at the Commonwealth
Convention Center here, holding signs aimed at the Monica Lewinsky
investigation. ``Proof is on the dress; now you must confess,''
read one, referring to Lewinsky's dress that may contain DNA
stains.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, ignoring the demonstrators, stepped up pressure on
Congress to pass a ``patient bill of rights'' in September before
members adjourn. The House recently passed its version and the
Senate is considering another alternative.
</P>
<P>
   But the president said the Republican plans would give patients
a ``false sense of security'' that they were protected from the
excesses of health maintenance organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a bill of rights, not a bill of goods. We need a law,
not another loophole. If I get that other bill of right, I will be
forced to veto it, and I will,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said a ``real patient bill of rights'' would strengthen
privacy protection for patients while the Republican version would
increase the number of people who can see patient records.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Democratic version would guarantee patients the
right to see specialists while the Republican alternative would
not. The Democratic version would guarantee patients in the middle
of major medical treatment the right to keep their doctor and would
bar incentives offered by HMOs for doctors to limit medical care.
The GOP plan would not, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic plan would guarantee patients the right to
emergency room care and allow patients to file lawsuits against
HMOs, which currently are protected from such claims.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the Democratic plan would apply to all
employer-paid health plans but the the Republican plan would exempt
the 100 million workers for small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The president said managed care plans have done some good things
in controlling costs. He noted that in the 1980s, health care costs
increased at three times the rate of inflation, a level that could
not be sustained. He noted that since 1990 the number of people in
HMOs has nearly doubled to 160 million people.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton said some plans have gone too far.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, when the bottom line is more important than patients'
lives, when families have nowhere to turn, when their loved ones
are harmed by bad decisions, when specialist care is denied, when
emergency care is not covered, we have to act,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   He noted an ``overwhelming grass-roots consensus'' has developed
about the need for a patient bill of rights.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the Republican leadership balked for nine months
before taking any action.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have listened to those with an interest in preserving the
status quo rather than the clear call of the public interest,'' he
said. Republicans, he charged, have made the patient bill of rights
a partisan issue.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
