</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ Significant contrasts are part of the
adaptation process for Summit Chase head professional Stephen
Keppler at the 80th PGA Championship this week. The road from
Snellville, Ga. to Sahalee was long and particularly winding.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Keppler, 37, the four-time Georgia PGA player of the
year, longed for a few preflight glimpses of Sahalee Country Club,
but had no time to watch the PGA preview show on CBS Sunday. It
conflicted with Summit Chase's member-guest tournament, a summer
highlight for Stephen and his staff.
</P>
<P>
   So much for research opportunities. Armed with a few details
from the weekly golf periodicals, Keppler was on site at the
tree-lined venue Monday, striking balls on the Sahalee practice
range between Colin Montgomerie and Davis Love III.
</P>
<P>
   Do not be misled, however. While Keppler might be a tad rusty,
he's more comfortable with the surroundings than many of the 25
club pros in the 150-player field. For those unfamiliar with the
English-born Keppler, he nearly won the BellSouth Classic in 1995,
finishing third and earning $88,400 after sharing the 54-hole lead.
He played in the PGA at Riviera three months later, missing the
cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Riviera was slightly different in '95 because I had gotten
some attention at the BellSouth Classic,'' Keppler said. ``It made
it a lot easier to play at Riviera. This year I'm just more like
one of the club pros.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been a turbulent year for the Keppler family. For several
months Stephen Keppler's golf game fell dramatically down the
priority list, and for good reason. Daughter Jordan, 4, in January
required removal of a kidney that had been diseased by a
grapefruit-sized tumor. Precautionary chemotherapy followed for
Jordan, bringing months of anguish for Stephen and wife Karen.
Jordan is fine now, with no evidence of the illness. She was at the
airport Monday, kissing her Daddy goodbye and wishing him good luck
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of puts everything in perspective,'' Keppler said.
</P>
<P>
   Handling whatever pressure ensues this week should not be a
problem for Keppler, considering how he got here. At the PGA's Club
Pro Championship at Pinehurst in June, he chipped in on the 72nd
hole from 30 feet to tie four other players and grab the last spots
for Sahalee.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I play decently, I'll feel comfortable this week,'' Keppler
said. ``The guys out here have always been real friendly to me. I
don't really feel any pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   That might come later. If Keppler were to make the cut at
Sahalee, he still wants to play in the Nestle Chilled Beverage
Georgia Open at Jekyll Island on next Monday through Thursday. It
would demand a red-eye flight to Atlanta Sunday night and a
connection to Brunswick, Ga., with sleep optional.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should be able to make it,'' he said calmly. ``They gave me
a late tee time.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes:
</P>
<P>
   A flood of withdrawals have given Atlanta's Billy Andrade, the
ninth alternate, a breath of hope to make the field. Among those
out of the field are Germany's Bernhard Langer (neck) and Michael
Bradley (back), Bruce Lietzke (back) and Mark McNulty (elbow).
Added to the field were Jim Carter, Clark Dennis, Robert Damron,
Neal Lancaster, Mark Wiebe and Rocco Mediate, the seventh
alternate.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
