<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT'S LAWYER WILL VIEW DEPOSITION IN PAULA JONES SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal judge in Little Rock granted permission
Monday to President Clinton's private lawyer to view the
president's videotaped deposition in the Paula Jones sexual
misconduct case, as he prepares to testify before cameras once
again, this time about his relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The decision came a day before one of the president's most
valued image-makers, Harry Thomason, is expected to appear here
before the grand jury investigating the Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, David Kendall, already had access to a printed
version of the deposition. But he asked in a sealed motion last
Thursday to view the videotape before Aug. 17. On that day, the
president is scheduled to testify at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's testimony is to be shown live on closed-circuit
television to a grand jury, and there has been speculation inside
and outside the White House about whether the manner in which it is
shot could affect jurors' views. Will Clinton be shown in close up?
Will the prosecutors also be seen? Who will control the camera?
</P>
<P>
   The Little Rock judge, Susan Webber Wright, dismissed the Jones
case on April 1. She ruled Monday that Kendall could view the
videotape under the supervision of Judge Norma Holloway Johnson,
who is overseeing the grand jury in the Lewinsky investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The Judge Wright said that Kendall could not copy the tape, and
that he was bound by the confidentiality order muzzling others who
have access to it.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Wright rejected several conditions sought by Mrs. Jones,
including that she have a lawyer present for the viewing. Under an
agreement between the two sides in the suit, the judge has custody
in her vault of at least two copies of the videotape, one of which
is considered Clinton's and one Mrs. Jones'. The judge is holding
them to prevent their use for ``any improper purpose,'' her
decision Monday said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomason, the Hollywood television producer who has staged some
of Clinton's most important appearances, will appear on Tuesday
before the grand jury, an administration official said. With his
wife, Linda Bloodworth-Thomason, Thomason rushed to the president's
side after the accusations emerged in January that Clinton had lied
about an affair with Ms. Lewinsky and tried to cover it up.
</P>
<P>
   Thomason, an Arkansan who is a close friend of the Clintons, was
quoted in the July 6 issue of The New Yorker magazine as saying
that in January he urged Clinton to issue a forceful denial of the
accusations.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did so on Jan. 26. ``I did not have sexual relations
with that woman, Miss Lewinsky,'' Clinton declared, shaking a
finger. ``I never told anybody to lie, not a single time _ never.
These allegations are false. And I need to go back to work for the
American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has avoided describing the relationship since then.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's office declined to comment Monday, and Thomason did not
return a telephone message left at his office.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has been interviewing friends and advisers of Clinton to
learn what he may have confided to them about Ms. Lewinsky.
Thomason was quoted in the magazine as saying that after he arrived
at the White House in January, ``We stayed up half the night
talking.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that he emerged from that conversation ``positive that
nothing happened between him and Monica.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
