<SLUG> BC-TV-COMEDY-STEWART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMEDY CHANNEL AND CBS TRADE TALENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Also moved in ``e'' category.) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Comedy Central, whose biggest star, Craig Kilborn, is being
lured away by CBS, is announcing Tuesday that it will replace him
with someone CBS had once coveted: Jon Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Comedy Central had announced its intention of blocking the move
by Kilborn, host of ``The Daily Show,'' to CBS as long as it could.
It is expected to disclose its decision Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who had his own late-night syndicated show in 1994, was
also for a time under contract with Worldwide Pants, the production
comedy owned by David Letterman, the host of CBS' late-night show.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart was expected to become host of whatever show CBS decided
to run after Letterman's ``Late Show'' upon the retirement of Tom
Snyder, who is host of ``The Late Late Show.'' But that contract
had already lapsed by the time Snyder announced his forthcoming
retirement late last year.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart is expected to take over ``The Daily Show'' sometime
this year. ``The Daily Show'' is a half-hour nightly comedy takeoff
on the news. It has become one of the highest-rated regular
programs on Comedy Central, which is owned by Time Warner and
Viacom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
