<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBE-BARNICLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLOBE, BARNICLE TALK AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The status of Boston Globe columnist Mike Barnicle
remained unresolved after a one-hour meeting Monday between Globe
publisher Benjamin B. Taylor, Globe editor Matthew V. Storin, and
the columnist.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released Monday evening, Taylor said, ``This is
is a decision that can not and will not be rushed. It involves the
integrity and character of the Globe and the career of an employee
who has served this paper well for 25 years. The decision we make
must be deliberate, thoughtful, and carefully considered.''
</P>
<P>
   Storin, returning from vacation Monday, added that the meeting
was held because ``I had thought it was important to hear him out
in person.'' Barnicle was not available for comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle became embroiled in controversy after an Aug. 2 column
was found to contain eight jokes that closely resembled ones in
comedian George Carlin's book ``BrainDroppings.'' Storin requested
his resignation last Wednesday night after WCVB-TV (Channel 5)
aired a video clip from a June 22 edition of ``Chronicle'' in which
Barnicle endorsed the book, which he earlier had told his editors
he had not read.
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle, 54, has maintained that he would not resign, but has
declined to comment on his status in recent days. He has also
stated that he received the Carlin jokes from two friends and that
that he did not read ``BrainDroppings'' before he recommended it on
Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   When asked Monday if Taylor's statement that the Barnicle
decision ``will not be rushed,'' represented a reconsideration of
the resignation request, Globe spokesman Richard P. Gulla said,
``Nothing has changed. We're affording Mike the confidentiality
that we would afford any other longtime employee. We're not going
into the details of what's going on.'' The Globe statement did
indicate a decision on Barnicle would be announced soon.
</P>
<P>
   Gulla also said that as of Monday at 1 p.m., 287 Globe readers
had canceled their subscriptions in displeasure with the paper's
handling of the Barnicle situation. He said that no advertisers had
threatened a Globe boycott over Barnicle since Staples chairman
Thomas G. Stemberg sent a letter to Taylor on Friday hinting at
that possibility.
</P>
<P>
   And while calls and e-mails on the controversy continued to
arrive at the Globe Monday, the pace slackened noticeably.
</P>
<P>
   As of 4 p.m., the Globe ombudsman's office had received about
100 e-mails and calls on the subject, with the responses running
about 70 percent to 30 percent in favor of Barnicle. As of Monday
evening, the Globe's city desk had received 225 telephone calls,
with readers favoring the retention of Barnicle by about a 2-1
margin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
