<SLUG> BC-MAINE-FORESTS-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANXIOUS MAINERS DEBATE FUTURE OF THEIR FORESTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A locator map and a photo are being sent to NYT
graphics/photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 212-556-4204, 1243 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By JOHN H. CUSHMAN JR.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, Maine _ Hundreds of millions of dollars' worth of
forest _ a swath that is about 5 percent of the land in Maine _ is
for sale in the northern part of the state, prompting a debate over
the future of the heavily logged yet alluring woods.
</P>
<P>
   Conservation groups have called for selling the land to the
public to restore it to its original wilderness. Many residents
here are more comfortable with the status quo of much of the
century: industrial logging of the land by timber companies that
give the public free access for hunting, fishing, boating,
snowmobiling and other sport. But people in both camps worry that
some land _ only a six-hour drive from Boston and featuring miles
of undeveloped lake shores _ will be developed, profitably but
irretrievably, for more tourism, recreation and country houses.
</P>
<P>
   As paper companies liquidate their land holdings in the
Northeast to raise money for their mills, millions of timbered
acres from northern Maine to the Adirondacks of New York are either
for sale or being considered for sale, making their availability
one of the latest conservation issues in the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``Across the northern forest region, three and a half million
acres of incredibly valuable land are for sale by willing
sellers,'' said Andrea Colnes, executive director of the Northern
Forest Alliance, a coalition of environmental groups. ``It is
historic, and it will have a defining impact on the region.''
</P>
<P>
   But the issue is most pressing in Maine, where practically all
open land is owned by industrial forestry companies. In an
unexpected move last June, Sappi Ltd., a South African paper
company, announced that it would sell 911,000 acres. And another
company, Bowater Inc., has said it would consider selling all of
its Maine holdings, more than 2 million acres, after completing a
pending $2.5 billion acquisition of Avenor Inc., a Canadian forest
products company. In all, as much as 15 percent of the state may be
for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Sappi, which gained control of the land four years ago when it
acquired S.D. Warren Co.'s forestry operations from Scott Paper
Co., is selling heavily harvested softwood tracts in wild
mountains, moose country glittering with countless lakes, streams
and bogs.
</P>
<P>
   As timberland it is worth at least $200 an acre, but some
waterfront sections are prime real estate, and the ecological worth
is inestimable.
</P>
<P>
   Quietly, state conservation groups and private bidders are
trying to put together deals for Sappi land, although details are
not known. Their ideas range from buying conservation easements or
critical tracts to more far-reaching plans.
</P>
<P>
   And while the tracts are so big that other paper companies are
the likeliest bidders _ the outcome Sappi says it prefers _ the new
owners might be tempted to carve out prime parcels for real estate
developers, a prospect that has conservationists and many local
people alarmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``East of the Mississippi, there isn't another area of
wilderness-like terrain of this magnitude left anywhere,'' said Jim
Glavine, who owns Beaver Cove Camps on Moosehead Lake, at 75,000
acres the largest lake in New England. ``If you look across the
shoreline, you don't see anything. Essentially, there is nothing.
There are no lights to see in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an opportunity for conservation-minded folks and
residents and people who live and work in the area and make a
living from everything from forestry to tourism to see to it that
what we see when we look out across this lake doesn't change.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The most ambitious plan, if not the likeliest, would convert
most of Sappi and Bowater's lands, along with other tracts, into a
huge national park including parts of the Allagash Wilderness
Waterway, surrounding Baxter State Park and Moosehead Lake and the
100-Mile Wilderness stretch of the Appalachian Trail.
</P>
<P>
   Jym St. Pierre, the Maine director for Restore the North Woods,
a conservation group that advocates creating a 3.2-million-acre
national park and preserve, said, ``From Mount Katahdin to
Moosehead Lake, the region has the collection of natural, cultural
and historic resources that qualify it for a park, and it has large
ownerships with land for sale and is virtually uninhabited.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gov. Angus King called plans for a national park misguided.
``I am dead set against the idea,'' he said in an interview. Like
many other political leaders in Maine, he views the timber industry
as too important to supplant.
</P>
<P>
   King said that though it was not feasible for the state to
acquire the whole tract, it hoped to make a bid for part of the
land for conservation soon.
</P>
<P>
   Many local residents join the governor in not embracing the
creation of a national park. People are used to the gravel scrapes
and clear-cut scabs that tally forestry's contribution to the
state's economy and its effects on the state's environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone buys the land and won't let us cut on it, we are
all going to be out of a job,'' said Charles Libby Sr., a trucker
who was about to haul a semi-trailer of chips to a pulp mill.
``Right now, the way I feel, we have enough tourists up here. We
lock the gate down on the Interstate, it wouldn't bother me a bit.
Keep them out. We've got plenty of parks.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest concern of many people who live in and near the
woods is that they would lose access to the land if the government
took it over.
</P>
<P>
   Even though forest product companies control almost all of the
woods, they let anyone fish or hunt, hike or ski, or cross their
property in canoes or snowmobiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the tourists who come up here are ecotourists,'' said
Toni Blake, executive director of the Moosehead Chamber of
Commerce, based in Greenville at the foot of the antler-shaped
lake. ``They want to do the hiking and the biking and to get out in
the woods. Snowmobiling is a big industry, and I think that would
all change. A national park is something that sets restrictions.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Candeloro, who owns a sporting camp in Kokadjo, said:
``Right now with Sappi, we have the best land-use deal in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   The park's advocates are proposing that part of it be held as a
preserve open to uses like hunting that are not allowed in parks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conundrum of the whole thing,'' said Garrett Conover, a
canoeing outfitter and guide, ``is the people of Maine are
desperately afraid of federal controls because of lack of access.''
</P>
<P>
   He supports public acquisition of the land, which despite the
relentless logging he considers the best canoeing region this side
of Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody in history ever made the mistake of putting aside too
much wilderness,'' Conover said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
