<HEADER>
A7092 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-OILERS-HNS &LR;      08-10 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-OILERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Help for McNair 
gives Oilers hope
<TEXT>
<P>
   New receivers must catch on fast
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN McCLAIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ The Tennessee Oilers have stockpiled enough
talent that they could have their best and most explosive offense
since the run-and-shoot era.
</P>
<P>
   In the team's last season as the Oilers, Tennessee is planning
to make the playoffs for the first time since winning the AFC
Central title as the Houston Oilers in 1993. Last week's 31-16
preseason victory at Atlanta showed offensive production should
increase drastically for the Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got weapons at every position, just like we did in the
run-and-shoot,'' says guard Bruce Matthews, a 10-time Pro Bowl
selection entering his 16th season. ``Our offense from that era has
a special place in my memory because it was really united. We were
close. We played together for a long time. And we were
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   The Oilers reached the playoffs an NFL-high seven consecutive
seasons from 1987-93. They consistently ranked among the NFL's top
three in scoring, total offense and passing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This offense has talent, too,'' Matthews says. ``We just don't
have as much experience playing together. We have the kind of
personalities we need to develop the kind of unity you need to win
the close games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's refreshing to see so many talented young players with
humility.''
</P>
<P>
   In Steve McNair's first full season as the No. 1 quarterback in
1997, the Oilers finished 8-8 while running the ball 57 percent of
the time _ the top figure in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie George followed his 1,368-yard rushing performance as a
rookie in 1996 with 1,399 yards, though his production dropped near
the end of the season because of an injury and the wear and tear of
facing eight-man fronts so often.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jeff Fisher says, ``Of the seven teams that ran the ball
more than they threw it, six made the playoffs.'' Fisher emphasizes
the run (the Oilers were fourth in the NFL). He wants to get more
production out of a passing game that ranked 29th.
</P>
<P>
   ``The running game set the standard last season,'' Fisher says
of the 151-yard average that was the highest by the Oilers since
1980, when Earl Campbell helped generate 165 a game. ``Our goal was
to be able to run against the eight-man front, and we did.
</P>
<P>
   ``This season, I think defenses will take the same approach.
They'll want to stop the run and force us to pass, so we need a
more efficient passing game. Steve will have to throw well enough
to get the defense out of the eight-man front.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our passing production has to increase, and that
responsibility falls on Steve. He's head and shoulders above where
he was last year. He understands the plays and reads.''
</P>
<P>
   In the offseason, Fisher, general manager Floyd Reese and
director of player personnel Rich Snead targeted the primary
weakness in an offense that averaged 307 yards and 20.7 points and
decided they had to acquire big-time receivers.
</P>
<P>
   Tight end Frank Wycheck led the team in receiving the last two
years. Willie Davis (43 receptions) and Chris Sanders (31) were the
only wideouts with more than 14 catches.
</P>
<P>
   First, Reese signed Pittsburgh's Yancey Thigpen to a five-year,
$21 million contract that, at the time, made him the highest-paid
receiver in NFL history. Thigpen, who caught 79 passes for 1,398
yards last season, has been to the Pro Bowl two of the last three
years.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the Oilers used their No. 1 draft choice on Utah's Kevin
Dyson. He and Randy Moss were rated by NFL scouts as the two best
receivers in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Thigpen (6-1, 203) and Dyson (6-1, 201) elevate the talent level
at receiver and add size _ which was one of Fisher's goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a lot of talent, especially a lot of young
talent, guys can get confused unless they know their roles,''
Thigpen says. ``You have to know what the guy next to you's going
to do, and that only comes with experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The Oilers have been unable to contain their enthusiasm for
Thigpen, who is 100 percent healthy after offseason surgery on his
foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I can contribute is to make the big play when we're down,
make an unbelievable catch when we need it the most,'' Thigpen
says. ``I think I can help this offense with my enthusiasm in the
huddle. So much of this game is mental, and my adrenalin is really
pumping during games.''
</P>
<P>
   Dyson, who is competing for the starting job opposite Thigpen,
got off to a slow start in camp but caught a 46-yard touchdown pass
in the win over Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dyson's got outstanding size and speed, and he works hard,''
McNair says. ``He's still learning the system, and once he does,
his natural ability will take over and you'll see him become a
great player.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair, who restructured his contract to free up salary-cap room
to sign other players, has worked overtime with Thigpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yancey's a go-to guy who's so dependable,'' McNair says. ``He
works hard to set an example for the younger receivers. He makes
the crucial catch. He's going to make my job a whole lot easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Wycheck had 116 catches over the last two seasons, making him
more of an H-back than a true tight end, so the Oilers signed free
agent Jackie Harris from Tampa Bay. Harris used to be one of the
top tight ends in the league but has been limited to 49 catches
over the last two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the additions, the offense is still built around McNair
and George.
</P>
<P>
   McNair has shown improvement in each of his four seasons, and
because Les Steckel is in his second season as offensive
coordinator, McNair should be more knowledgeable and comfortable
with the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Starting regularly for the first time, McNair completed 216 of
414 passes for 2,665 yards last year. He threw 14 touchdown passes
and 13 interceptions and needs to improve his 52-percent completion
percentage.
</P>
<P>
   He was more dangerous as a runner than a passer, rushing for 674
yards and scoring eight touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to become more consistent,'' McNair says. ``I'm
working hard to get on the same page with my receivers. We have to
develop consistency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so fired up about this offense. We've got so much
athleticism. And the best thing is that every player is willing to
do whatever it takes to be successful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
