<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE LEGEND NO ONE HAS HEARD OF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., France)  (mk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When he steps on the court with one of the all-time greats, with
a Connors or a Borg, he hears people say, ``Who the hell is this
guy?'' Mansour Bahrami has a story to tell, though, and it happens
to be the stuff of legend.
</P>
<P>
   There are Grand Slam champions, celebrity millionaires, who play
the stay-in-shape 35-and-over tennis circuit. Then there is this
Nuveen tour walk-on named Bahrami, who lost the heart of his career
to politics and poverty, but who has metaphorically triumphed over
a prohibitive class system, a cultural revolution and global
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   He is 42, and his first-round opponent Tuesday night in the
Citibank Champions tournament at Manhattanville College in
Purchase, N.Y., is Jose-Luis Clerc. Bahrami, a doubles specialist,
seldom gets very far in these crowd-pleasing events, but then, he
never claimed he would have been another John McEnroe, or No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really know how good I could have been,'' he said.
``Realistically, I believe I was as good as Clerc, Gene Mayer, guys
who got to No. 5 or 6. But I didn't have the chance. My best 10
years, I didn't play.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and did we mention that Bahrami, an Iranian who lives with
his wife and two sons in Paris, has never in his life had a
personal coach?
</P>
<P>
   The son of a Tehran gardener who tended the grounds of a tennis
club, Bahrami was not allowed to use the courts and was once beaten
by authorities for sneaking on with friends. He had no racquet
until long after he had taught himself to play with dustpans,
pieces of wood and, when all else failed, the palm of his hand. He
taught himself so well that he forced his way onto those courts
and, much later, the Iranian Davis Cup team.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the overthrow of the shah in 1979, the return to the
country of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini and the denouncement of
tennis as an anti-Islamic, capitalist sport. Clubs were closed, the
men's tour stop in Tehran was eliminated. While McEnroe was
imagining great line-call conspiracies against him in the late
1970s, Bahrami was looking to break free from suffocating
repression.
</P>
<P>
   He left Iran on Aug. 8, 1980, with a short-term visa to France
that expired too soon and left him homeless and broke, on the
streets of Paris, in retreat from the immigration police. He
refused to seek political asylum, ``to be so selfish and forget
about everyone, my family.'' He said he was too proud, too
stubborn, to sleep on Paris' streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would walk all night,'' Bahrami said. ``Long, long nights,
when you feel like it would never be day again. But when the day
came, I could look like anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Until he would espy an officer of any kind nearby, and then it
was time to forget tennis, become a sprinter.
</P>
<P>
   For months, Bahrami eluded the authorities, until Iranian
expatriates helped him penetrate the local tennis community. His
tale of life on the run reached the news media. ``They wrote, `We
let dictators stay, yet we want to throw out a sportsman?'''
Bahrami said. He remained in Paris, played in various French
tournaments, including the Paris and French Opens. He still had his
Iranian passport, though. When he applied for visas to play in
places as far away as Australia, or across the border in Belgium,
the answer was always, ``Three months' wait.''
</P>
<P>
   He would say, ``By then, there is no tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Bahrami had a French passport, he was, for the sake
of a successful singles career, too old. He played mostly doubles,
made the French Open final with Eric Winogradsky in 1989 and earned
himself a few hundred grand hustling around the world until he
joined the seniors tour three years ago. He is a clown prince of
sorts, a Nastase-like shotmaker who can get under the skin of his
less sanguine opponents (read: McEnroe) in the heat of a match.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read once where Rod Laver said I was one of the most
talented players to pick up a racquet, but what I've lost I've
already lost,'' Bahrami said. ``Now I play to have fun, to
entertain. I make the best of what I have.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and did we mention how Bahrami met his wife, Frederique? It
was on New Year's Eve, amid bumper-to-bumper traffic on the
Champs-Elysees. He in one lane, she in the other. He rolled down
the window and asked if it was French custom to kiss the person
next to you as the clock struck 12. Yes, she said. He got out of
his car, and, voila, out of another jam came something worth the
wait.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
