<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK ASKS OXFORD TO RAISE RESERVES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By REED ABELSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York State Insurance Department announced
Monday that it had asked Oxford Health Plans Inc., the troubled
managed-care company, to increase its reserves for its New York
plan by $152 million to ensure that it had sufficient funds to pay
medical claims over the next year.
</P>
<P>
   The request came after the department completed its long-awaited
review of Oxford's finances, which it began last year after the
company fell months behind in paying its doctors and hospitals.
This is the third time in the last year that the department has
asked Oxford, one of the New York area's largest plans, with about
1.4 million members in the state, to add to its reserves.
</P>
<P>
   The department also issued a lengthy report on Oxford's
finances.
</P>
<P>
   Oxford underwent a sweeping restructuring earlier this year. The
company, based in Norwalk, Conn., named a new management team and
raised $710 million in new capital.
</P>
<P>
   The department said it had determined that Oxford had
underestimated the reserves it needed, based on actuarial estimates
of future medical claims, according to the deputy superintendent,
Bonnie Steingart. The state requires all health plans to have a
portion of future claims in cash. Ms. Steingart said she was not
aware of any actions taken by other states where Oxford conducts
business, like New Jersey or Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Membership in the New York plan has grown, medical costs have
increased and Oxford is still making its way through piles of old
claims that had been lost or misplaced, she said. The department
calculated that Oxford's future claims and other liabilities in New
York were about $726 million, substantially higher than the
company's own estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The company also added $40 million in cash to the reserves last
month to cover the New York plan's holdings of stock in FPA Medical
Management, which filed for bankruptcy in July and is now worth
virtually nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Oxford, which said Monday night that it had cooperated fully
with the insurance department, is expected to release its quarterly
financial results Tuesday. The reserves for the New York plan are
expected to be included in what analysts are predicting will be a
substantial earnings loss. Anxiety over the financial results have
helped push Oxford's stock down to new lows. It closed Monday at
$6.5625.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance department's action should give Oxford's New York
consumers and doctors some comfort, however. The department could
have taken more dramatic action, and the higher reserves mean
Oxford has more of a cushion to pay its claims for its current
members.
</P>
<P>
   ``The enhanced combination of resources and talent should
strengthen Oxford's position in the marketplace,'' Neil Levin, the
superintendent of insurance, said in a statement.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Oxford emphasized that it had ample financial resources. ``Going
forward, the company has over $1 billion in cash and marketable
securities,'' said a spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   But whether Oxford has resolved its problems, especially in its
ability to estimate its medical claims, remains to be seen. It
continues to work on fixing large-scale computer problems, which
helped lead to its operational chaos and caused the company to
seriously underestimate the cost of delivering care.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance department sharply criticized Oxford in an earlier
report on its market conduct, fining it $3 million and ordering it
to pay an additional $500,000 in restitution to its customers and
its doctors.
</P>
<P>
   The department said it would watch closely to make sure Oxford
was working toward developing a better system of tracking and
paying claims. Oxford is now in full compliance with all state
regulatory requirements, the department said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
