<HEADLINE>
11 AMERICANS KILLED IN KENYA BOMBING RECEIVE HONORS AT U.S. AIR
BASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: AFRICA-BOMBINGS, AFRICA-TERRORISM, AFRICA-U.S.,
AFRICA-FUNERAL, AFRICA-SURVIVE) 
(JT) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMSTEIN, Germany _ In silence broken only by a drum roll, the
flag-draped coffins bearing the bodies of 11 Americans killed in
the explosion at the U.S. Embassy in Nairobi, Kenya, last Friday
were received with full military honors early on Tuesday at the
American Air Force base here.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies of the 11, all employees of the State Department, are
to be flown to the United States on Thursday after Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright arrives. She will accompany their coffins
to Andrews Air Force Base, Md., where President Clinton will
receive them.
</P>
<P>
   A 12th victim of the bombing, Jean Dalizu, was to be buried by
her family in Kenya, where the U.S. ambassador, Prudence Bushnell,
who was slightly hurt, watched as the bodies were loaded aboard an
Air Force C-141 Starlifter.
</P>
<P>
   Pallbearers in the dress uniforms of the Army, the Marine Corps
and the Air Force, eight for each of the dead, marched stiffly onto
the long, gray plane and bore the 11 coffins past a color guard to
vans that took them to the morgue of the American military hospital
in Landstuhl.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 troops watched in silence during the hour it took for
the bodies to be taken off the plane after it taxied to a stop
shortly after 1 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   American officials said that Albright was expected to arrive
here Wednesday night, and that she planned to greet some of the
American and Kenyan injured being treated at the military hospital
here.
</P>
<P>
   Military officials at the hospital said the bodies would be held
in the morgue for 48 hours to give relatives time to assemble for
the presidential ceremony on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   One of the 10 Americans flown to an American military hospital
here on Sunday, a woman who suffered severe eye injuries, was
evacuated to Walter Reed Medical Center in Washington late on
Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We became concerned about a possible loss of her vision,''
said Col. Robert Harvey, the physician who is director of the
Army's Regional Medical Center, in Landstuhl, near the base here.
He did not identify her.
</P>
<P>
   Ten Americans and five severely injured Kenyans, all embassy
employees, arrived here on Sunday on a C-141B Starlifter from
Nairobi, and Harvey said that two of the Kenyans and one of the
Americans _ a woman he did not name whose injuries included severe
damage to her lungs _ were in critical condition on Monday. The
other Americans now here, he said, would probably be flown on to
Washington on Wednesday on a regularly scheduled medical evacuation
flight.
</P>
<P>
   Those who could talk were being interviewed by Federal Bureau of
Investigation and State Department officials, hospital employees
said, and would be offered the services of a State Department
psychiatrist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long, traumatic trip for them,'' Harvey said.
``There are still a lot of them that feel quite depressed.''
</P>
<P>
   The names of all of the injured who arrived here on Sunday,
except for a critically injured Kenyan man being treated in
Homburg, in the Saar, were given by the Regional Medical Center as
follow: Americans _ Marine Sgt. Daniel Briehl, Ellen Bomer, Carol
Hawley, Clyde Hirn, Gary Lonnquist, Frank Pressley, Carolyn Riley,
David Robertson, Lydia Sparks, and Gary Spears; Kenyans _ Pauline
Abdall, Gideon Maritim, Mary Ofisi, and Carolyn Wayro.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
