u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOMBING-EMBASSIES-1ST     08-10 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMBING-EMBASSIES-1STLDWRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. OFFERS $2 MILLION REWARD IN EMBASSY BOMBINGS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Sub to correct day in 14th graf. It Should say Wednesday
sted of Tuesday.) 
 
 
By STEVE LASH 
and NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. government is offering a $2 million reward
for information leading to the capture of the ``despicable
cowards`` responsible for deadly attacks on two U.S. embassies in
East Africa, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright announced
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This nation ... will not be intimidated,'' Albright said at a
meeting of State Department employees that was part memorial, part
call to action. ``Although terror can turn buildings to rubble and
laughter to tears, it can never, will never, deter America from its
purpose or presence around the globe,'' she declared. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Twelve Americans were among the 202 people killed in Friday's
blasts in Nairobi, Kenya, and Dar es Salaam, Tanzania, that wounded
more than 5,000. More than 100 FBI agents have been sent to the two
countries to help conduct the investigation with Kenyan and
Tanzanian law enforcement personnel.
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen people were detained for questioning Monday in Dar
es Salaam, but Assistant Secretary of State Susan Rice told
reporters ``don't attach too much importance'' to what she
characterized as a ``routine roundup.'' She said those in custody
had not been formally charged, but ``we want to hear what comes out
of these suspects.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the detainees were Iraqis or Sudanese, according to wire
service reports.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq and Sudan are on the State Department's annual list of
terrorism sponsors. The Clinton administration and Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein are longtime enemies and Sudan is ruled by
fundamentalist Muslims who are fighting a civil war against
Christians. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; State Department officials praised the efforts of an embassy
guard in Nairobi who refused to open a gate into the embassy to a
truck suspected of carrying the bomb, despite having grenades
thrown at him.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman James Foley said the guard, who he would not identify,
``not only performed heroically but as horrific as the bombing was,
probably helped to minimize the damage.''
</P>
<P>
   Foley said the guard is still alive and though his story cannot
be independently verified, ``it is a seemingly plausible account.''
</P>
<P>
   As the investigators questioned suspects and witnesses, the
bodies of 11 of the 12 Americans killed by the blast were flown to
Germany to be prepared for return to the United States on
Thursday. &UR;  &LR; One of the U.S. victims was married to a Kenyan and will
be buried in that country &UR; .
</P>
<P>
   &LR; President Clinton will cut short a cross-country political trip
and return to Washington on Wednesday to meet with national
security personnel and participate in a memorial at Andrews Air
Force Base when the bodies come back. The service, set for 11 a.m.,
EDT, will include members of the victims' families.
</P>
<P>
   At an appearance in Kentucky on Monday, Clinton warned that the
United States cannot shy away from its global role and must be
resolute in confronting terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must be strong in dealing with this. We must not be
deterred by the threat of other action. There is no way out if we
start running away from this kind of conduct. We have to build a
civilized, open world for the 21st century,'' Clinton told a
Louisville audience. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Back in Washington, Albright said she plans to fly to Germany
on Wednesday and meet with wounded Americans being treated at
Landstuhl Hospital near Wiesbaden. She will then accompany the
remains of the victims on the trip home.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were honorable lives spent in service to our country and
our ideals,'' Albright said during her 15-minute address to the
State Department employees. ``Any work worth doing is done on
faith.''
</P>
<P>
   She reminded her audience that U.S. diplomats must often work
``where comforts are few and dangers are many'' as part of their
mission to help eradicate poverty and promote democracy. As a
result, Americans in overseas embassies will continue to be
inviting targets for terrorists ``because we use our strength to
resolve conflicts that some wish would go on forever.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Albright told the employees to persevere with their
dangerous jobs to show that the victims of the bombings in Africa
did not die in vain.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government's offer of a reward for helping to
capture terrorists is not unusual. The government put out a similar
bounty for information leading to the capture of Abdul Rahman
Yasin, a suspect in the 1993 bombing of the World Trade Center. Ten
terrorists have been convicted of the attack and sentenced to long
prison terms. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Suspects in the shooting of two Central Intelligence Agency
officers near Washington in 1993 were arrested in Pakistan because
of the rewards, officials say. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; In speech in Louisville, Clinton asked for a moment of silence
to honor the bombing victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hearts are heavy with the news that now 12 Americans _
brave people who are working to build a better world and represent
all of us abroad _ have lost their lives. To the nations of Kenya
and Tanzania, we thank them for their friendship to us. We grieve
for the loss of their citizens,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go forward now. You should all know that our teams are on
the ground in Africa. They're tending to the wounded; they're
providing security; they are searching and finding evidence. We
will do whatever we can to bring the murderers to justice,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The president noted that the world is rapidly moving toward
allowing the free movement of people, information, ideas and money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a global society that I am convinced will bring all
Americans our nation's best years. But there has never been a time
in human history when we have been free of the organized forces of
destruction. And, the more open the world becomes, the more
vulnerable people become to those who are organized and have
weapons, information, technology and the ability to move,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
