<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- Aug. 10, 1998 -- NY-NAZI-TRIAL, 8-10 --
Sophie Degan, who survived the Trawniki concentration camp,
testified Monday in the case of a man - Jack Reimer, 79, a retired
Brooklyn salesman and restaurateur - accused of having led SS
guards there. ``We thought something was wrong,'' Mrs. Degan, now
71, says of her arrival at the camp. ``We saw there were puddles.
They were red - red puddles. I remember they were shining.''
(Frances Roberts/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) GREENVILLE, Maine -- Aug. 10, 1998 -- MAINE-FOREST, 8-10
-- Hundreds of millions of dollars' worth of forest - a swath that
accounts for about 5 percent of the land in Maine - is for sale in
the northern part of the state, prompting a debate over the future
of the heavily logged yet alluring woods. Conservation groups have
called for selling the land to the public to restore it to its
original wilderness. (David McLain/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 10, 1998 -- AFRICA-TERRORISM, 8-10 --
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright speaking to State Department
employees Monday as journalists watch on closed-circuit television.
As the United States offered a $2 million reward for information
about the American embassy bombings, eyewitnesses told
investigators that they had seen a truck that may have carried the
bomb, possibly providing clues to the identity of the terrorists
who carried out the attack. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Aug. 10, 1998 -- CANADA-LIVENT, 8-10 --
Garth Drabinsky, chairman and chief executive of Livent Inc., the
Toronto-based theatrical production company, in his office at the
Ford Center for the Performing Arts in Manhattan. Livent, the
producer of such Broadway shows as ``Ragtime'' and ``Show Boat,''
announced Monday that an internal investigation had found serious
accounting problems involving millions of dollars. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) CHICAGO -- Aug. 10, 1998 -- BLACKS-BUSINESS, 8-10 --
Soft Sheen's Chief Executive Terri Gardner, 42, with her parents,
co-founders Edward and Betharn Gardner. Last month, the Gardners
sold their company to L'Oreal S.A. of France, the world's largest
cosmetics company, figuring that, with corporate giants chasing the
increasingly lucrative African-American market, their growth
prospects were dim without more capital. ``We knew we had to
compete with bigger players with deeper pockets,'' says Ms.
Gardner. (Steve Kagan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) BUXTON, N.C. -- Aug. 10, 1998 -- HATTERAS-LIGHTHOUSE-2,
8-10 -- Larry Hardham believes a plan to move the Cape Hatteras
Lighthouse would save it. Although it serves little navigational
purpose for today's electronically equipped mariners, the 208 foot
monolith's flashing beacon - a pair of 1,000-watt lamps that rotate
every 15 seconds - can still be detected for 24 nautical miles on a
starry night. (Todd Spencer/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) BUXTON, N.C. -- Aug. 10, 1998 -- HATTERAS-LIGHTHOUSE-1,
8-10 -- From left, Daniel Couch, Jennifer Taylor and John Hooper
oppose a plan to move the Cape Hatteras Lighthouse. ``The men who
kept this light were required to stay in the lighthouse in
hurricanes, in nor'easters, in all conditions,'' says Couch of the
208 foot monolith - the tallest and most majestic of an estimated
850 lighthouses in the United States. ``Now 100 years later we're
going to turn tail and run?'' (Todd Spencer/New York Times Photo)
*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Aug. 10, 1998 -- INDIE-FASHION-3, 8-10 -- The
independent movement spawning indie boutiques began more than a
year ago in densely packed shopping areas of Tokyo, like Shibuya
and Harajuku, where streets are lined with what the Japanese call
indies - art, music or design stores that are all about membership
in a subculture. ``The only way someone like me can compete is
doing something original and having it in one place,'' says Maria
Cornejo of Zero in Manhattan. (David Corio/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Aug. 10, 1998 -- INDIE-FASHION-2, 8-10 -- As
department stores are increasingly vapid, and as designer offerings
increasingly court the masses, fashion has sparked its own
independent movement with the indie boutique. Jane Mayle and
Christopher Jarvis, owners and designers of Phare in Manhattan.
(David Corio/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Aug. 10, 1998 -- INDIE-FASHION-1, 8-10 --
Finally, there's proof that department stores and mass-marketed
designers have reached an intolerable level of banality: fashion's
indie movement has begun. ``Our customers don't buy, pay and run
out like the Gap and those boutiques you see more and more in New
York, the cold efficient boutiques,'' says Selima Salaun of Bond 07
in Manhattan. (David Corio/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- Aug. 10, 1998 -- ELISABETH-AZR-B&AMP;W, 8-9 --
Elisabeth Kubler-Ross, author of ``On Death and Dying'' and 17
other death-related books, in 1979. After suffering a serious sixth
stroke three years ago, and despite national news stories about her
bitter attitude toward a rapidly approaching death, the 72-year-old
woman is again walking, and even dancing, in the desert around her
home. ``I am alive and well and kicking,'' she says, weakly
karate-chopping the air. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) ST. JOSEPH, Mo. -- Aug. 10, 1998 -- BARBERSHOP-QUARTETS,
8-10 -- Beanies in place, rookies test their skills at Harmony
College, a barbershop-harmony workshop in St. Joseph. The Society
for the Preservation and Encouragement of Barbershop Quartet
Singing in America (SPEBSQSA) is 60-years-old and, with more than
34,000 members in 809 chapters in this country and Canada, may well
be the largest singing organization in the world. (David Hutson/New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BOSTON -- Aug. 10, 1998 -- MA-HARSHBARGER-BOS, 8-10 --
Attorney General Scott Harshbarger and his wife Judy Stephenson at
the Boston Common. Twenty years after he first entered politics,
Harshbarger's drive has carried him by the flashier Rep. Joseph
Kennedy II, sidelined last year by family misdeeds, to a
front-runner's position for the Democratic gubernatorial
nomination, and into a near tie with Acting Gov. Paul Cellucci,
according to polls. (Bill Brett/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 10, 1998 -- SCI-OCTOPUS, 8-10 --
Carrie Reidel, a keeper at the Invertebrate House of the National
Zoo in Washington, with a 2-year-old, 30-pound male of the species
Octopus dofleini. Pet him, and he'll pet right back: he loops a
limb around your hand and explores you. ``He can pull them right
off your fingers.'' says Ms. Reidel, who warns that sometimes the
octopus suctions hard enough to leave behind a mark. ``We call that
an octopus hickey.'' (Michael Geissinger/New York Times Photo)
*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Aug. 10, 1998 -- SCI-LEMUR-WRIGHT, 8-10 --
