<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7122 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRANCE-SCANDAL-340&AMP;AD     08-10 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-SCANDAL-340&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-DEFENSE MINISTER OF FRANCE SUSPECTED OF MONEY-LAUNDERING 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ A conservative former defense minister of France and an
aide have been formally placed under investigation on suspicion of
taking part in a money-laundering scheme to finance their political
party.
</P>
<P>
   The former official, Francois Leotard, who considered running
for the French presidency three years ago, emerged from a session
with Investigating Magistrate Laurence Vichnievsky on Friday in a
furor, yelling ``a fist in the face'' to a reporter who asked him
what had happened. Under French law, being placed under
investigation is one step short of being formally charged with a
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the investigation, one of scores over the past
decade that have exposed shakedowns, phony front companies and
systematic fraud in the financing of nearly all French political
parties, was focused on 5 million francs _ $830,000 _ deposited in
small bills in a Luxembourg bank for Leotard's Republican Party in
June 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Simultaneously, lawyers familiar with the case said, the party _
later renamed Liberal Democracy _ received a loan in the same
amount from an obscure Milan bank. The money was needed to finance
the purchase of the party's Paris headquarters, Leotard's
supporters said.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, Jean Veil, said Leotard denied all the charges of
wrongdoing, as did the aide placed under investigation with him,
Renaud Donnedieu de Vabres.
</P>
<P>
   After a wave of party-financing investigations and indictments,
since 1995 French law has forbidden ``moral persons'' _
corporations and, presumably, the government _ from making
contributions. Allowances are openly provided to established
political parties from public funds.
</P>
<P>
   French press reports have said that Leotard told investigators
the cash had come from savings in special funds provided to the
party by the prime minister's office. The investigating judge is
understood to be pursuing charges that the Milan bank, Fondo
Sociale di Cooperazione Europea, agreed to be used as a front for
laundering the cash.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The French government budget this year included 48 million
francs _ $8 million _ in ``special funds'' for undisclosed purposes
and 346.7 million francs _ $57.8 million _ in ``designated special
funds'' thought to be for secret service agencies, Agence
France-Presse reported.
</P>
<P>
   Leotard, 56, was defense minister in the conservative government
of Prime Minister Edouard Balladur from 1993 to 1995. Since 1996 he
has headed the Union of French Democracy, a conservative umbrella
group that fractured earlier this year after some of its leaders
accepted support from the extreme-right National Front in order to
hold power in French regional parliaments. Leotard's own party left
the Union of French Democracy then.
</P>
<P>
   He and Philippe Seguin, the leader of the Gaullist Rally for the
Republic party of President Jacques Chirac, announced in May the
formation of a new conservative umbrella group called the Alliance,
in hopes of rebuilding the French right after it lost legislative
elections last year to a leftist coalition headed by Prime Minister
Lionel Jospin, a Socialist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-98 2203EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980810.0441 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7125 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRICA-TERRORISM-1STL     08-10 1356
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-TERRORISM-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$2 MILLION REWARD OFFERED BY U.S. IN AFRICA ATTACKS  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: changes lede to tightens, emphasize reward.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(See also: AFRICA-BOMBINGS, AFRICA-U.S., AFRICA-FUNERAL,
AFRICA-DEAD, AFRICA-SURVIVE) 
(JT) 
 By TIM WEINER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ The United States offered a $2 million reward
Monday for information about the embassy bombings, and
investigators focused on credible eyewitness reports of a truck
that may have carried the bomb that wrecked the American Embassy
here and the terrorists who carried out the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the CIA and the FBI were also evaluating other
preliminary leads. They included a terrorist manifesto delivered in
Cairo that praised Osama bin Laden, a Saudi financier whom American
officials have identified as a possible suspect, and vague warnings
picked up by a foreign intelligence agency that an Islamic
terrorist group might be planning an attack in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   The work of CIA officials took on a personal as well as
professional intensity as they mourned the death of one of their
own, an intelligence officer killed in the Nairobi explosion. The
CIA does not make public the names of its agents.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said in Washington that
the reward would be paid for information leading to the conviction
of those responsible for the attacks. The bombings killed more than
200 people and wounded nearly 5,000 others in Nairobi and Dar es
Salaam, Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   In this decade, the American government has paid more than $5
million for information critical to solving other terrorist
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   FBI officials here and in Dar es Salaam continued a grisly
search for evidence, meticulously combing through the rubble near
the ruined embassies and examining bodies in a hospital morgue for
pieces of metal.
</P>
<P>
   The CIA and FBI have sent large teams of investigators to
reconstruct the events leading to the bombings. Some 60 FBI agents
have been sent to Nairobi and another 60 to Dar es Salaam, and CIA
officers have come to the area from around the world. They are
interviewing witnesses like a Kenyan guard who told investigators
that he refused to allow a truck through the rear gate of the
embassy. The guard said that a man jumped out of the truck and
opened fire on him and may have thrown a hand grenade. Other Kenyan
witnesses provided similar accounts, including a Kenyan driver who
said he saw a man leap from the back of a yellow pick up truck and
throw something toward the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI team is larger than the one sent to investigate the 1996
bombing at the Air Force apartment complex in Saudi Arabia. FBI
officials are trying to determine what kind of explosive was used
in the attack, which will help focus their investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The Israel army radio said investigators suspect Semtex, a
powerful plastic explosive. If that was the case, the investigation
may focus on a network of known terrorist groups. In the 1970s and
1980s, Czechoslovakia sold 100 tons of Semtex to Libya, according
to the Czech president, Vaclav Havel. If the bomb was made of a
commercially available explosive, like dynamite, the investigators
may have to look in other directions.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators must check ports of entry by land, air and sea
on Kenya's porous borders. They must search commercial records like
bills of lading for suspicious shipments. The movements,
characteristics and capabilities of known terrorists must be
reviewed. The task could take years, American officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Among the facts the investigators had in hand today were a few
tantalizing leads.
</P>
<P>
   The Tanzanian police said that they had detained ``several''
suspects _ said to be Iraqis and Somalis _ but Susan Rice, the
assistant secretary of state for African affairs, cautioned that
the detentions were part of a routine roundup and should not be
taken too seriously.
</P>
<P>
   A foreign diplomat here said in an interview today that a
foreign intelligence service reported indications months ago that
an Islamic terrorist organization with bases in Afghanistan and
Pakistan might be planning an attack in Kenya. An American official
confirmed that U.S. intelligence agencies were aware of that
report.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were told to take care for flights coming from Pakistan,''
the foreign diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   But, like most such warnings, the information obtained by the
foreign intelligence service was indefinite _ too fuzzy for
effective countermeasures. The embassy here never went on alert, an
American official said.
</P>
<P>
   A senior official of a foreign intelligence service also
confirmed tonight that his service had received the reports of a
possible attack in Nairobi. But he and other intelligence officials
said such reports come in constantly, and are often understood only
in hindsight. ``Intelligence pours in all the time,'' he said.
``You can't cry wolf every time.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigators were also analyzing a statement issued by a
previously unknown Islamic group taking responsibility for the
attack. American and foreign intelligence officials said that they
were still evaluating whether the manifesto was credible, and they
cautioned that claims of responsibility were easily made and
difficult to verify.
</P>
<P>
   In the Arabic-language communique, the group said it would
``pursue United States forces and strike at United States interests
everywhere'' unless changes were made in American policy in the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   The statement included several signs pointing toward bin Laden,
who has financed and otherwise supported previous terrorist attacks
on American outposts, according to U.S. officials.
</P>
<P>
   The communique, issued to a French news agency and made public
in Cairo this morning, said the group was inspired by the
statements of bin Laden. Four Saudis beheaded for bombing an
American installation in Riyadh in November 1995 said in televised
confessions that they, too, were inspired by bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   The statement demanded the withdrawal of American forces in
Saudi Arabia and an end to U.S. support for Israel. It also called
for the release of imprisoned Islamic militants _ ``first and
foremost Sheik Omar Abdel Rahman,'' the blind cleric convicted and
imprisoned for life for his role in a plot to bomb several New York
sites, including the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden has voiced similar demands in the past. He not only
sheltered Sheik Rahman but also harbored Ramzi Yousef, the
convicted mastermind of the 1993 bombing of the World Trade Center,
in homes bin Laden owned in Peshawar, Pakistan, near the Afghan
border.
</P>
<P>
   The statement also said ``a man from Egypt who belongs to the
Abdallah Azzam battalion'' carried out Friday's attack on the
American Embassy in Tanzania. Abdallah Azzam, who died in 1989, was
a Palestinian who fought alongside the CIA-supported Afghan rebels
battling Soviet invaders in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was bin Laden's partner'' in Islamic militant politics, an
American official said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   It was also in 1989 that bin Laden, whose family made a fortune
building mosques, royal palaces and government offices for the
Saudi royal family, began to build ``a multinational organization
for jihad, to purge the world of Western corrupters and their Arab
friends,'' the American official said. Jihad is the Arabic word for
holy war.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden now funnels tens of millions of dollars a year through
Islamic charities and banks to support terrorist groups and
extremist political movements in Algeria, Egypt, Lebanon, the
Sudan, Yemen, and other nations, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The CIA revived its bomb-shattered station here today, led by
officers from the agency's headquarters in Virginia. American
intelligence officers in Germany who track developments in Iran,
Iraq and Afghanistan, where the United States has no embassies, are
also investigating.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI officials include a Rapid Start unit of FBI computer
analysts who inventory and collate evidence.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
