u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-NAZI-TRIAL-ART-NYT     08-10 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NAZI-TRIAL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLOCAUST SURVIVORS TELL OF HORRORS AT TRIAL OF ACCUSED GUARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204)  
 (af)  
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three Holocaust survivors, testifying in the federal
case against a Brooklyn man accused of hiding his wartime role in
liquidating European Jews, said on Monday that no one who worked
for the Nazis in the death camps and ghettos of Poland could have
been unaware of the daily horrors and mass murders that took place
there.
</P>
<P>
   None of the three elderly witnesses said they knew or recognized
the man, Jack Reimer, 79, a retired Brooklyn salesman and
restaurateur who is accused of participating in atrocities and
misrepresenting his duties for the German army on his application
to immigrate to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But the survivors, testifying before Judge Lawrence M. McKenna
of U.S. district court, graphically described conditions in three
of the places where Reimer is alleged to have served as a commander
of SS guards.
</P>
<P>
   Sophie Degan, for instance, spoke of her arrival, 17 years old
and alone, at the cold and eerily silent Trawniki concentration
camp in Poland in late 1943.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought something was wrong,'' Mrs. Degan, now 71,
recalled. ``We saw there were puddles. They were red _ red puddles.
I remember they were shining.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the prisoners' barracks, the new arrivals from the Warsaw
ghetto saw that the rooms had been recently occupied. There were
clothes, utensils and other personal belongings tossed onto the
floor. But she and her fellow inmates, already veterans of two Nazi
labor camps, found only corpses _ with the exception of a small boy
of about 2 who was soon taken away from the lonely women by the
Nazi guards.
</P>
<P>
   The men in their group were assigned to feed the dead bodies
onto bonfires after removing any gold teeth or jewelry they found,
Mrs. Degan added. ``You could not help but see the glow, the red
glow,'' she said. Then she added, softly: ``And the smell.''
</P>
<P>
   Trawniki was also a Nazi SS training camp. The Justice
Department says Reimer was not, as he claims, merely a German army
clerk removed from the day-to-day horrors, but a highly decorated
commander who took part in murdering 50 to 60 Jews at a pit at the
camp. It is asking McKenna to revoke his citizenship, a first step
to his deportation.
</P>
<P>
   As the survivors recounted their experiences, Reimer sat quietly
and impassively at the defense table. His lawyer, Ramsey Clark, did
not question any of them.
</P>
<P>
   But outside the courtroom after their testimony, Clark, a former
U.S. attorney general, said he considered the government's strategy
inappropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the survivors' story is of enormous human
importance,'' he said, ``but I think it's obviously unfair to
individual rights and individual justice to tell those
heartbreaking stories in the trial of a man whose precious American
citizenship is at risk, when they have no relationship to him and
they don't know him.''
</P>
<P>
   When Reimer applied for permission to immigrate to the United
States from Germany in 1952, he told investigators that he was
drafted into the Soviet army in 1940 in his native Ukraine and
later captured by the Germans. Following his release from a
prisoner of war camp, he said, he went to work for the German army.
He worked first as a guard at Trawniki, then as a trainer of
guards, an interpreter and a paymaster, according to notes on his
application that were read in court.
</P>
<P>
   The government maintains that Reimer was also a commander of SS
guard units at the liquidation of both the Warsaw and Czestochowa
ghettos.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Hilton, 68, who lived through the destruction of the
Warsaw ghetto, testified that no one could have been there and not
known what was done to the Jewish residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see destruction constantly and people getting murdered and
killed day by day,'' Hilton said. ``It's impossible to not know
what's going on. It's just virtually impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   A survivor of the Czestochowa ghetto, Carl Langner, 72, made the
same point. ``I saw yelling and screaming and people running to
escape through the roofs, jumping from the windows, screams,
gunshots,'' he said, describing the roundup of Jews by Ukrainian
guards working for the Nazis, for deportation in September 1941.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if anyone who was present in Czestochowa at the time could
not know what was happening to the Jews, Langner replied:
``Absolutely not.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Because everybody,'' he added, ``took part.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
