<SLUG> BC-PHONE-STRIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL ATLANTIC STRIKE FELT FROM MAINE TO VIRGINIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ll) 
 By TERRY PRISTIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a strike by 73,000 Bell Atlantic workers entered its second
day, the repercussions were felt on Monday by customers from Maine
to Virginia who were unable to get a telephone line installed or
repaired or reach directory assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Marcus, a spokesman for Bell Atlantic, acknowledged that
many customers had encountered delays in reaching a business or
repair offices, getting a telephone listing or placing an
operator-assisted call. Marcus asked the public to be patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to negotiate with customers on a case-by-case
basis to determine if they can wait for service,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   About 23,500 managers, many with no field experience, have been
assigned to work 12-hour shifts and 6-day weeks to fill in for
workers who went on strike early Sunday after their old contract
expired.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it had no figures on how many customers could
not get help on Monday. But Marcus said that daily the company
normally handled three and a half million directory-assistance and
two million operator-assisted calls and received 29,000 calls for
repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations continued throughout the day on Monday, with both
sides expressing hope for a swift resolution. ``We've been working
very hard to reach a settlement,'' said Jeffery M. Miller, a
spokesman for the Communications Workers of America.
</P>
<P>
   As Bell Atlantic workers set up picket lines throughout the
company's service area, 2,000 union members rallied in Brooklyn,
playing Bruce Springsteen's ``Born in the U.S.A.'' over
loudspeakers and listening to speeches by several politicians,
including Rep. Charles Schumer, who is running in the Democratic
primary for United States Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Only a small fraction of Bell Atlantic's customers have been
directly affected by the strike, since basic telephone service has
not been disrupted.
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen strike-related arrests were reported on Monday.
Three strikers were arrested at the Westchester Square Medical
Center in the Bronx, after they were seen about 1:30 p.m. cutting
telephone wires _ and then damaging cars belonging to supervisors _
at the hospital that had been just been repaired by nonunion
supervisors, said Detective. Robert Samuel, a spokesman for the New
York police.
</P>
<P>
   On picket lines, Bell Atlantic workers accused the company of
refusing to honor a commitment to offer early retirement to 14,000
eligible employees. The program was initiated at Nynex when it was
seeking to downsize and encourage workers in their mid-40's to
retire early with a full pension. Nynex merged with Bell Atlantic
last year.
</P>
<P>
   The company has acknowledged that it did not anticipate that
demand for telephone service would skyrocket because of the
Internet and cell phones. So far, 11,000 workers have been allowed
to take advantage of the early retirement plan.
</P>
<P>
   Paddy Bambrick, a service technician and shop steward for Local
1101, said that many workers had counted on the retirement offer,
even going so far as to buy homes in other states but that many had
their hopes dashed. ``Bell Atlantic said they'd honor our contract,
and they haven't,'' he said. ``They lied to us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-98 2213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
