<SLUG> BC-YEAR-2000-TEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER TEST CALLED A SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Wall Street passed last month's preliminary test of
its readiness for the year 2000 ``with flying colors,'' according
to Donald Kittell, executive vice president of the Securities
Industry Association.
</P>
<P>
   The 28 trading firms that took part executed about 40,000
carefully scripted trades of stocks, bonds and options, testing
conditions on Dec. 30 and Dec. 31, 1999, and Jan. 3 and Jan. 4,
2000. Computers at the stock exchanges and securities-processing
firms handled the date transition flawlessly, although there were
problems in the mock municipal-bond market.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of problems directly related to the inability of some
computers and programs to cope with the year 2000 popped up at the
trading companies but most were corrected during the course of the
days on which they occurred, according to industry officials.
Computers and programs with dates coded in two digits _ 99 for 1999
_ may crash or mishandle data when confronted with 00 representing
the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Expanded tests are planned for next spring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
