<DOCNO> NYT19980810.0447 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-10 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7139 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BBA-REDSOX-AVERY-BOS     08-10 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
WHEELS SPIN ON ROTATION
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-REDSOX-AVERY-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By Gordon Edes 
c.1998 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette made a deal for a
lefthanded starting pitcher last Thursday, buying Pete Schourek
from the Houston Astros, Steve Avery's place in the rotation once
again seemed to be in jeopardy. And it may yet be that Avery is
bumped by the newcomer before the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, Avery has a familiar ally, manager Jimy Williams.
And when the Red Sox, fresh from a triumphant tour of the American
League West in which they won 8 of 12, take the field at Fenway
Park Tuesday night for the first time in more than two weeks, Avery
will be on the mound to face the Kansas City Royals.
</P>
<P>
   ``In reality, Dan got Schourek as a backup for us,'' pitching
coach Joe Kerrigan said. ``If something unfortunate were to happen
to Avery or (John) Wasdin, Schourek gives us a Plan B to go to.
That's a neat luxury to have, if we do have to make a move with
regard to a starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``But most definitely, Avery deserves to be out there, he and
Wasdin both. It would be crazy to take them out.''
</P>
<P>
   Since displacing Jin Ho Cho, the Korean kid rushed to the big
leagues, Wasdin had made three good starts and appeared on his way
to an easy win Sunday, when the Red Sox gave him a 12-2 lead
against the Rangers. He couldn't get three outs in the fifth,
however, giving up five straight hits, and while it would appear
unfair if he's yanked from the rotation, Wasdin could be in trouble
if he struggles in his next turn.
</P>
<P>
   Avery, meanwhile, had failed to get past the fourth inning in
two successive starts but came up big last Tuesday in the Kingdome,
when he shut down free-swinging Seattle on two hits and a run in
six innings.
</P>
<P>
   That 2-1 win raised Avery's record to 8-4, and despite his 5.18
ERA, the Red Sox are 10-4 when he pitches. They are 2-3 in Wasdin's
starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stayed ahead of hitters and expanded the strike zone with
his changeup,'' Kerrigan said, explaining Avery's turnaround
against the Mariners. ``He didn't get into too many dangerous
counts, 2-and-0, 3-and-1.''
</P>
<P>
   Scouts who have tracked the Red Sox the last two weeks said
Avery's fastball seldom ventured above the 82-84 m.p.h. range. But
that merely serves to underscore how Avery is gradually succeeding
in his transition from a power pitcher to a sinkerball/changeup
pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he's all the way convinced in his mind that
ultimately he's got to be a Randy Jones, Frank Tanana, John Tudor
type, the crafty lefthanders,'' said Kerrigan, rattling off the
names of lefthanders who relied on finesse.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he understands the way he has to pitch now. He understands
he's a ground-ball pitcher, effective when he keeps the ball down.
He plays a game of keepaway against righthanded hitters, tries to
get them to pull that changeup away so they hit ground balls to
short.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every now and then he gets it in his head that he's still a
power pitcher and goes back to his old overhand delivery. But most
of the time, he keeps his arm in a lower slot. He reminds me a lot
of Tommy John, in the way he uses his fastball and changeup, though
Tommy John used a little lower arm slot.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams's faith in Avery was demonstrated last September, when
the manager gave him the start that triggered a $3.9 million option
for this season. And while Duquette seemed to hint last week that
Schourek would go directly into the rotation, Williams had other
ideas. ``After what he did in Seattle, Avery deserves to start,''
Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   If Duquette had succeeded in his long-shot attempt at landing
Randy Johnson, Williams would have had no choice but to jettison
Avery or Wasdin from the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   But in many respects, Schourek offers little in terms of an
upgrade from what the Sox already have. He admitted himself that he
was the least consistent and most expendable of the Astros'
starters after they acquired Johnson, and his history of elbow
problems has robbed him of the dominance he showed in 1995, when he
won 18 games for the Cincinnati Reds and finished second to
Atlanta's Greg Maddux in the Cy Young Award voting.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Schourek is in the bullpen, even though it has been
four years since he pitched in relief and it's uncertain whether
his elbow can handle the strain.
</P>
<P>
   Kerrigan said that Schourek will be given plenty of time to warm
up and won't be brought in during an inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been much more effective as a starter than a reliever,''
Kerrigan said, ``and now with his past arm history, we'll have to
see what he can do out of the bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox' problems at the bottom of their rotation, Kerrigan
said, all stem from the season-ending knee injury lefthander Butch
Henry suffered back in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought (Brian) Rose could supplant him, but that didn't
work out,'' Kerrigan said, alluding to the rookie whose season was
cut short by a bone spur in his right elbow. ``We tried (Derek)
Lowe, (Robinson) Checo, Cho, it didn't work out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember back in spring training, when it looked like we had
eight starters? You just never have enough pitching.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
