u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-FOODSTAMP-FRAUD-42     08-10 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FOODSTAMP-FRAUD-420&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOD-STAMP FRAUD RING IS BROKEN UP, U.S. SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Federal authorities said Monday that they had broken
up the largest food-stamp fraud ring ever in New York, a $60
million scheme in which individuals sold their food stamps to
Chinese takeout restaurants, which in turn sold them to Hispanic
grocers, who then redeemed the coupons from the government.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, federal prosecutors said, grocers with hundreds
of thousands of dollars in annual sales had redeemed millions of
dollars' worth of food stamps.
</P>
<P>
   The case was unusual both for its vast scope and for the fact
that the scheme cut across ethnic lines. But the mechanics of the
scheme, in which individual recipients sold their coupons for less
than face value and business owners illegally turned them in to the
government, were typical of food-stamp frauds, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason to change the plan, since it works,'' Roger
Viadero, inspector general of the U.S. Department of Agriculture,
said in a telephone interview Monday night. ``Don't reinvent the
wheel.''
</P>
<P>
   The government unsealed documents showing that it had charged 18
people with defrauding the federal food-stamp program and with
money laundering. Prosecutors said large sums of money from the
scheme ended up in bank accounts in the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   The case stemmed from a two-year investigation by the FBI and
the Agriculture Department, prosecutors said. FBI agents began to
arrest suspects on Friday and over the weekend, prosecutors said,
including owners of some of the grocery stores that are accused of
participating in the scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Nine suspects were arrested in the last few days, prosecutors
said, while the rest are at large.
</P>
<P>
   An assistant U.S. attorney, Cheryl Krause, told Magistrate Judge
Douglas Eaton in court on Monday that several of the defendants
were believed to have fled to the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Four suspects who appeared in court in Manhattan were held
without bond, including Reynaldo Cespedes and his wife, Ibaniris,
who were described in court records as managers of numerous grocery
stores. A lawyer for Cespedes could not be reached by phone Monday
night. His wife's lawyer, Martin Klotz, declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   Among the fugitives was Victor Ramirez, described in the
documents as the owner of three Hispanic grocery stores in the
Bronx and Manhattan that were used in the scheme.
</P>
<P>
   None of the owners of the Chinese restaurants were among those
charged. Prosecutors would not say why, saying only that the
investigation was continuing.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Viadero of the Agriculture Department said that the government
had tried to combat the estimated $3 billion in fraud in the $26
billion program by giving food-stamp recipients cards that transfer
benefits electronically, avoiding the use of coupons, which are
like cash and can be lost or sold.
</P>
<P>
   But the electronic cards have yet to be introduced in New York,
Viadero said.
</P>
<P>
   According to prosecutors, the defendants bought large quantities
of food stamps from Chinese take-out restaurants in New York and
other sources. The records do not explain how the Chinese
restaurants obtained the food stamps originally; food stamps cannot
be used to buy meals at restaurants, but officials said that many
individual recipients who get the coupons legally are known to sell
them on the street for a fraction of their face value.
</P>
<P>
   The coupons were then resold at a slightly higher price to the
grocery-store owners, the records show. The store owners had filed
for authorization to accept food stamps with the government
program, and were thus able to redeem them at full value.
</P>
<P>
   One telling piece of evidence, prosecutors said, was the
disparity between the annual sales volume of the grocery stores,
typically around $200,000 to $500,000 a year, and the value of the
food stamps that the same stores redeemed from the government,
which was many times more.
</P>
<P>
   In one such case cited in the complaint, a store called Stop 1
Food Market in the Bronx, in applying for registration in the
food-stamp program, estimated its annual sales to be about
$371,000. Of that, about $223,000 was from sales of fruit,
vegetables and other food eligible for purchase under the program.
</P>
<P>
   Yet over the next year, it redeemed about $3 million in food
stamps, said the complaint, signed by an agent with the Agriculture
Department.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
