<SLUG> BC-NY-CRISPO-RENEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ART DEALER REINVENTS HIMSELF, AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By LESLIE EATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Andrew Crispo has always been strangely in tune with
his times _ sometimes very strangely. He became the living symbol
of the excesses of the 1980s when he was investigated for _ but not
charged with _ a sadomasochistic murder that became known as the
``Death Mask'' case.
</P>
<P>
   An art dealer with a good eye and a bad reputation, Crispo more
recently became part of a '90s trend _ he filed for personal
bankruptcy protection at a time when such filings have been
soaring. (Of course, his case was unusual in many respects; most
debtors, for example, do not own paintings by Georgia O'Keeffe.)
</P>
<P>
   And now, he is about to begin a new chapter of his life. A plan
approved last week by the bankruptcy court will soon give Crispo
the money he needs to create a new art business. If he is
successful, he will give unknown artists a way to show their work
and, perhaps, help change the face of a small corner of Greenwich
Village.
</P>
<P>
   In a building on Little West 12th and Greenwich streets that
once housed Collier's magazine and later became a meat-packing
plant, Crispo has knocked together a series of rooms and uncovered
long-darkened skylights to create an enormous, light-filled space.
Some of the vast area will be used to display sculptures and to
stage arts-related events, he said; one section will be devoted to
a sort of flea market for artists, where they can rent small spaces
to display their works.
</P>
<P>
   It will be his vindication and his ``legacy to the art market,''
said Crispo, 53. ``I do think that I am on the road to a great
success _ and I don't think that I will let anyone be
disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   But, as his critics note, Crispo was hugely successful in the
past and threw it all away.
</P>
<P>
   He was raised in a Philadelphia orphanage, and though he never
formally studied art, by the 1970s he was a rising art dealer whose
spectacular shows attracted the world's biggest patron, Baron Hans
Heinrich Thyssen-Bornemisza. The baron's purchases were so
profitable for Crispo that the dealer came up with a scheme to hide
income from the IRS ; in November of 1985, Crispo pleaded guilty to
evading taxes of nearly $4 million, and was eventually sentenced to
five years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   By then, of course, Crispo's personal life had also become very
public. In March of that year, the body of a Norwegian fashion
student, Eigil Dag Vesti, had been found. The partially burned
body, with two bullet holes in the back of the head, was wearing
only a leather mask of the sort used in sadomasochistic rituals.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard LeGeros, who worked for Crispo, was convicted of the
killing and is still in prison. LeGeros accused his boss of
ordering the killing at the end of a sexual encounter, and claimed
that other bodies were buried at Crispo's house in Southampton
(none were found). Crispo has never been charged in the case.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of all this, another man came forward to accuse
Crispo of sexually torturing him during a drug-fueled party at the
Andrew Crispo Gallery in 1984. Crispo's lawyer argued that the sex
was consensual; a jury acquitted him in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   But the lurid details of those cases seemed to stick in many
minds, and were revived in David France's book ``Bag of Toys: Sex,
Scandal and the Death Mask Murder'' (Warner Books, 1992). The book,
a revised version of which is due out next year, contends that
Crispo was centrally involved in the killing.
</P>
<P>
   Crispo said that for legal reasons, he cannot talk about Vesti's
murder, but he said the portrait of him painted by France is untrue
and has besmirched him. ``People who don't know me, hate me,'' he
said. And he thinks he has become a sort of boogeyman about whom
people make up stories, ``the Svengali of evil.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Crispo's financial problems stem from his endless and
baroque disputes with the IRS. Practically everything Crispo ever
owned, including most of his art, was essentially frozen by the
IRS, so that while he was rich, he had almost no cash.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   But the precipitating factor in the bankruptcy was his house,
which is a tale in itself. When he was released from prison in
1989, Crispo's first act was to visit his home in Southampton,
which his companion of more than 30 years, Arthur Smith, had just
redecorated. A week later, the house _ and all the art it contained
_ blew up.
</P>
<P>
   After a trial, he recovered about $5 million from Long Island
Lighting Co., which was found to have caused the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   He used some of the money to buy a mansion in Charleston, S.C.,
called the Pineapple Gate House. The idea, according to court
documents, was that he would renovate the house and run an antiques
business there.
</P>
<P>
   But by 1995, the asset-rich Crispo was running out of cash,
according to court filings. What little money he made came from
selling $127,000 worth of antiques through Smith's shop on East
60th Street. He was behind on the maintenance of his Manhattan
co-op, on loans for art he had bought and on the mortgages on the
Charleston house. Checks were bouncing.
</P>
<P>
   The day the Pineapple Gate House was to be sold in foreclosure
proceedings _ May 13, 1996 _ Crispo filed for bankruptcy
protection. He listed assets of more than $10 million and debts of
$6 million.
</P>
<P>
   His biggest unsecured debt _ roughly $1 million _ was to the
artist Robert Courtright, who had filed a lawsuit against Crispo in
1985 that was about to go to trial. In court filings, Courtright
had accused Crispo of keeping money that the artist should have
received from the sale of his paintings.
</P>
<P>
   Crispo disputes this, though he allows that some sales may have
been left unaccounted for when the gallery collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   After the bankruptcy filing, months went by and Crispo missed
deadline after deadline for reporting to the court about his
finances.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1996, the court appointed Robert Weiner to serve as
bankruptcy trustee, a position that is uncommon in a personal
bankruptcy filing. Weiner, a corporate lawyer who is also an expert
in art law, began trying to organize Crispo's affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Despite what Weiner calls ``the folklore that Andrew owes a lot
of people a lot of money,'' he found that Crispo actually had
surprisingly few creditors.
</P>
<P>
   But he had a far deeper and sadder problem than his bankruptcy.
He was caring for Smith, who died of lymphoma last October.
</P>
<P>
   Though he was as grief-stricken as any widow or widower, Crispo
said, he did not have their legal rights. Smith had left the bulk
of his estate to his family in Georgia, which did not acknowledge
Crispo and tried to evict him from the apartment the two had
shared. So the legal wrangling began.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, two important financial events had occurred.
Weiner had sold the Charleston house for a record price of $3.1
million, a tribute, he said, to Crispo's eye for the valuable and
desirable. And the trustee had also negotiated with the IRS to
enable him to sell Crispo's art collection.
</P>
<P>
   Crispo has always been reluctant to part with any of his
paintings. ``These are my little children,'' he said. But he
decided to go along with the sale, he said, not just to raise cash,
but also in the hope that the auction would vindicate him as a
dealer and collector.
</P>
<P>
   It did. Many paintings _ by artists including O'Keeffe, Stuart
Davis, Edward Hicks and Arthur Dove _ sold for far more than their
published estimates, and very few works failed to sell at all. In
all, Crispo's collection raised about $14 million.
</P>
<P>
   With more than $10 million in cash on hand, the trustee was able
to agree to pay all of Crispo's creditors in full, with interest _
highly unusual in a bankruptcy case.
</P>
<P>
   And, even after putting aside more than $1 million to satisfy
any tax claims, and paying the lawyers' and the trustee's fees,
Crispo will end up later this year with several million dollars.
``I cannot wait to get my hands on that money and buy a wonderful
work of art,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
