<HEADLINE>
STUDENTS MAY LACK REQUIRED IMMUNIZATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Alan Hevesi, the city comptroller, criticized the
Board of Education on Monday for failing to keep accurate records
of student immunizations, saying about 30 percent of the students
in a group of high-risk districts his staff examined had not
received all the shots required by state law.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the board had not complied with a state law
requiring that students complete immunization for measles, mumps,
rubella, diphtheria, tetanus, whooping cough and polio within two
weeks of entering a school.
</P>
<P>
   In response, school officials said Hevesi had overlooked state
guidelines extending the amount of time allowed for the
immunizations, and that the student immunization rate had increased
since the period covered in his sample.
</P>
<P>
   Hevesi made it clear that he was not interested in filing a
complaint for noncompliance with the law _ which he had
co-sponsored 19 years ago as a state assemblyman _ but in
pressuring the board into acting. He also conceded that his sample
of students was too small to permit conclusions about the entire
school system.
</P>
<P>
   Hevesi's report examined 12 schools in three community school
districts _ District No. 7 in the Bronx, No. 19 in Brooklyn and No.
30 in Queens _ that had sizable outbreaks of measles during a
1990-91 epidemic that affected about 3,000 New Yorkers, according
to the Health Department.
</P>
<P>
   Hevesi's staff members checked the records of 697 children in
those districts, 550 in the 1994-95 school year and 147 more in the
1996-97 school year. They found that in each survey, about 30
percent of the students checked had not completed their
state-required inoculations. Two-thirds of them lacked the
follow-up shot for measles.
</P>
<P>
   Hevesi said his staff members also found that some schools had
poor methods of keeping records. In one case, a secretary at a
Queens school could not find the necessary paperwork to document
the immunization rate of nearly 100 percent entered in the state
database. After checking other records and questioning some
parents, the staff decided that the rate had been a simple guess.
</P>
<P>
   The need for keeping good records has been increased by the
recent surge in immigration, Hevesi said, which also increased the
number of parents who may not know of the state requirements or be
able to read health instructions easily.
</P>
<P>
   City Health Department and Board of Education officials pointed
out that much of the data in Hevesi's report was three years old
and that record-keeping methods had improved since then. As of
June, said the board's chief spokeswoman, Chiara Coletti, 89
percent of the 800,000 elementary and middle school students had
all their required inoculations.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a city Health Department random check of the records of
60,000 students in 225 schools this school year, 84 percent had
completed all their shots, said Vincent Giordano, the board's
deputy executive director of student support services.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't disagree that in 1995, 70 percent of students may not
have completed their immunization, but the rate is much higher now
_ at nearly 90 percent,'' Giordano said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Stephen Friedman, assistant commissioner of the city Health
Department's Bureau of Immunization, said the board's policy
complied with state guidelines issued after the law. Rather than
applying the two-week period to the interval after the student
enters school, he said, the guidelines allow it to apply to the
interval between vaccine doses. It takes a child on average about
eight months to complete all the doses for all the vaccines, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the board wanted to avoid forcing a child to take
too many shots too fast, and since many students start school
without their shots, following the state law blindly could endanger
a child.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Coletti said the size of the sample in Hevesi's study made
it impossible to draw conclusions about the status of the whole
system, a point Hevesi conceded at a news conference in response to
a question. ``We don't know that we can extrapolate for the whole
system,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the board could be sued by parents of a child infected
by one who should have been immunized. ``This is a serious
liability issue for the board,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
