<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-FREE-SPEECH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: FREE SPEECH AND PUBLIC SAFETY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Aug. 11:
</P>
<P>
   The ``Million Youth March'' proposed for Harlem over Labor Day
weekend presents some classic questions about the constitutional
rights of free expression for people with abhorrent views. Khalid
Abdul Muhammad, the march organizer, has a record of outrageous
anti-Semitic rhetoric. He wants to stage his event along Malcolm X
Boulevard in Harlem, an area that New York City's police have
rejected for reasons of traffic and security. Some black leaders
not aligned with Muhammad have nevertheless worried out loud about
censoring people who want to take part in what is being billed as a
march to empower minority youth.
</P>
<P>
   Self-promoting demagogues provide unique challenges to the
American political culture, and that is especially true in diverse
cities like New York. The test is to clearly think through the
situation without being driven to knee-jerk authoritarianism or, at
the other extreme, pandering to outrageous demands that jeopardize
civic harmony or public safety to an unreasonable extent.
</P>
<P>
   The first test here is not to be misled by the word ``march.''
What Muhammad has called a march is actually an extended stationary
rally, which he says will draw thousands or even millions of young
people to hear speeches and listen to music. Although it is
doubtful the organizers are capable of assembling that many people,
the city must take Muhammad at his word for planning purposes. A
busy thoroughfare in central Harlem, which might be appropriate for
a march or parade, is clearly not a suitable site for a day-long
event involving a massive crowd that would create a traffic and
safety nightmare. The Police Department's suggestions of Randalls
Island or Van Cortlandt Park in the Bronx do not seem unreasonable.
If they do not suit Muhammad, he has recourse to the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Million Man March in Washington, to which Muhammad
obviously wants to draw comparisons, the organizers of the Million
Youth March do not appear to have made serious logistic or security
plans for handling large numbers of people. Every black leader of
any standing who has endorsed a march for Labor Day weekend appears
to be sponsoring a competing event in Atlanta known as the Million
Youth Movement.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad exists on the far fringes of African-American politics,
but when he first announced his march, some of Harlem's political
leaders made attempts to negotiate with him. Given the loathsome
history of Muhammad, who was dismissed by the Rev. Louis Farrakhan
after making a speech in which he called Jews ``bloodsuckers,'' any
interaction that gave him a tinge of credibility was unwise. But
the politicians' concern for the safety of young people who might
be drawn into the event was understandable.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, it has become clear that Muhammad is less
interested in negotiating than in creating confrontation, as he has
in recent years by trafficking in anti-Catholic and homophobic
sound bites. His rhetoric seems likely to attract those so
alienated as to pose the prospect of violence. That means Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani has to be firm but not provocative in his public
statements and in guiding the police preparations for the event.
The other elected leaders who tried to work with Muhammad must make
it clear that they support neither his rhetoric nor his march. It
is also most important that they offer young black people other
opportunities to make their voices heard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
