<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAXXAM-HEADWATERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUDGET AXES THREATENING MAXXAM FOREST DEAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Calif.) 
 
By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Maxxam company's 2-year-old agreement to sell a
stand of ancient redwood trees in Northern California to the
federal and California governments is close to unraveling.
</P>
<P>
   Budget negotiators in Sacramento, Calif., have dropped from the
state's 1999 budget a $130 million appropriation needed to buy
Houston-based Maxxam's Headwaters Forest _ the largest stand of
old-growth redwood trees left in private hands.
</P>
<P>
   That $130 million represents California's share of a $380
million, three-way deal to purchase 5,600 acres of virgin redwood
timberland to serve as the core of a 7,500-acre preserve.
</P>
<P>
   Washington already has allocated the remaining $250 million to
purchase the property from Maxxam's Pacific Lumber Co. subsidiary,
but those federal dollars will disappear if California does not
cough up its share by March.
</P>
<P>
   California's inability to move forward on the Headwaters funding
is causing consternation on three coasts, as negotiators from
Houston to Sacramento to Washington watch years of effort stumble
on the final hurdle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made a lot of compromises in order to get this far,''
said Bob Irelan, a spokesman for Maxxam in Houston. ``We feel the
state has an obligation to fund its share.''
</P>
<P>
   California lawmakers this week will try to craft a new bill that
would include funds to purchase Headwaters. But such a bill would
require a two-thirds vote, and few observers believe supporters can
muster that many votes before the legislature adjourns at the end
of the month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting two-thirds is going to be extraordinarily difficult,''
said one legislative source.
</P>
<P>
   California lawmakers yanked the $130 million provision from
Republican Gov. Pete Wilson's budget proposal last week because of
opposition from conservationists and conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Many environmentalists object to the legislation because they
believe regulators didn't go far enough to protect wildlife, such
as the coho salmon, when they negotiated the logging guidelines
Pacific Lumber will have to follow for the next 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not worth taking a fatally flawed habitat conservation
plan in order to buy Headwaters Grove,'' said Paul Mason, president
of the Garberville, Calif.-based Environmental Protection
Information Center.
</P>
<P>
   Conservationists have lined up behind a bill sponsored by
California Sen. Byron Sher, the dean of California's
environmentalist bloc, that would impose greater restrictions on
Pacific Lumber's ability to log near streams.
</P>
<P>
   Maxxam officials vehemently opposed that legislation, arguing it
would double the acreage put off limits because of environmental
concerns and prevent Pacific Lumber from being economically viable.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives are opposed to the notion of the state and federal
governments' buying up privately held land.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those divergent viewpoints, lawmakers such as Mike
Thompson, chairman of the Senate budget committee and a state
senator from Pacific Lumber territory, hasn't given up hope of
finding a compromise that would, as legislative director Ruth
Coleman said, ``protect these trees in a way that allows the
company to operate.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., who was instrumental two years
ago in helping to negotiate the Headwaters deal, had her staff on
the phone all weekend with lawmakers in Sacramento, trying to
figure out a way to salvage the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still hopeful an agreement can be reached,'' said
Howard Gantman, a spokesman for Feinstein. ``We feel it would be a
loss of a tremendous resource if the deal doesn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Jill Ratner president of the Rose Foundation, an Oakland,
Calif.-based environmental group, argued ``there has to be a reason
for legislators to feel it's worth it for them to vote to spend
$130 million, which even in California's budget is a lot of
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding the money to pay its share of the Headwaters purchase
price has never been an easy issue for California.
</P>
<P>
   When the Headwaters deal was finally hammered out in September
1996 after months of painstaking negotiations, California offered
to allow Maxxam to choose from among 51 state-owned properties,
ranging from a old bus station in San Francisco to a canine
training facility in South Lake Tahoe.
</P>
<P>
   Other properties included a rock quarry, an earthquake-damaged
building and land adjacent to a state prison.
</P>
<P>
   Maxxam, however, held out for cash and timberland.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Headwaters agreement, the federal and California
governments would pay Maxxam $300 million in cash. The governments
also would purchase 9,600 acres of previously logged timberland
from another party and turn 7,700 acres of that land over to Maxxam
for logging.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining 1,900 acres would serve as a buffer zone for
Headwaters and the smaller Elk Head Springs virgin redwood grove.
</P>
<P>
   If California lawmakers cannot reach an agreement this month,
they can return to the issue next January, when a new legislature
convenes. But supporters of the agreement worry that a new
legislature, with fresh faces and new priorities, will not be able
to make the Headwaters agreement a priority.
</P>
<P>
   And they fear if California misses this window of opportunity,
all hope of obtaining federal funds again will be lost. Feinstein,
in a letter sent to Wilson last month, warned: ``The federal money
will clearly be taken away and spent elsewhere by a Republican
majority in Congress who feel that Californians cannot get their
act together.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt, in a letter to Feinstein,
warned that the federal government will not be able to protect the
Headwaters Forest without an outright purchase.
</P>
<P>
   ``The failure of the state of California to provide its share of
funds for the purchase and permanent set-aside of the Headwaters
Forest will result in an irretrievable and tragic loss,'' Babbitt
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
