<SLUG> BC-NY-PHONE-UNIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELEPHONE STRIKE TALKS ALSO FOCUS ON 1,500 SUBSIDIARIES' WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ll) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As Bell Atlantic continued to negotiate on Monday
with the union that represents the company's 73,000 striking
workers, the talks focused in part on two of the telephone giant's
small but fast-growing subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   The two units employ only about 1,500 of the company's 141,000
workers; but for both the union and the company, the small
operations represent the future of Bell Atlantic and of the
telecommunications industry.
</P>
<P>
   The subsidiaries provide advanced data communications, including
access to the Internet, to corporate customers and bundles of
services like caller ID and wireless phone service to consumers.
None of the Bell Atlantic employees at either unit are represented
by a union; the striking union, the Communications Workers of
America, wants to change that.
</P>
<P>
   ``These subsidiaries may not be that labor-intensive now, but
these are the growth areas and we are concerned whether that will
be union work,'' said Jeffrey Miller, a union spokesman in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic, based in New York, declined to discuss the units
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways the importance of the two units reflects the
evolution of the telecommunications business. Phone companies
around the nation are scrambling to keep up with far-reaching
regulatory changes and waves of multibillion-dollar mergers that
are changing the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bell Atlantic is at a difficult crossroads here because their
competitors in most cases don't have to hire union workers,'' said
Eric Strumingher, a telecommunications-industry analyst at Paine
Webber. ``They want to be in these growth sectors, but they need to
have a lean cost structure to be competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   One subsidiary, Bell Atlantic Network Integration, was formed
about five years ago with fewer than 100 employees. In 1995, the
last time Bell Atlantic and the communications workers union
negotiated a contract, the operation was still small enough to
escape serious scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the unit employs around 750 people and is growing quickly,
with contracts to maintain complex data networks for big companies,
including US Airways. Bell Atlantic calls all of the unit's workers
management employees, so they are not represented by the union.
</P>
<P>
   The union mainly wants to represent the unit's workers who
install communications wiring inside buildings, a person involved
in the talks said on Monday. That person said it was likely that
the two sides would reach an agreement that would allow the union
to represent some of those employees.
</P>
<P>
   The other unit, Bell Atlantic Plus, in Hampton, Va., sells
services to residential customers. Bell Atlantic started the unit
several years ago. Partly because of complex regulations then in
place, the company hired all of the unit's workers, mostly customer
service representatives, through a Boston company called the
Faneuil Group.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the regulations have eased, the union wants to
represent those workers. The Faneuil Group employees make about $7
an hour; comparable union jobs would pay about $15 an hour.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
