<SLUG> BC-CONN-SHOOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN SHOT TO DEATH NEAR BRIDGEPORT COURTHOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JONATHAN RABINOVITZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. _ A 21-year-old man was shot to death on
Monday in front of the state courthouse here after being attacked
by a group of young men, witnesses and the police said.
</P>
<P>
   The man, Dante Jones of Bridgeport, was pronounced dead on
arrival with a gunshot wound to the abdomen early Monday afternoon
at Bridgeport Hospital, said John Cappiello, the hospital
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. David Boston of the Bridgeport police said Jones had
dropped off someone at Superior Court in Bridgeport.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after that, a fight broke out on the steps leading to
the courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``This just erupted all of a sudden,'' Boston said. ``It got
violent _ there were blows thrown. They tumbled down the steps and
someone pulled out a gun and shot the victim.''
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said a group of four or five young men surrounded
Jones, kicking and hitting him until he fell to the ground on
Golden Hill Street in front of the courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   The beating lasted a few minutes, said Eddie Gonzalez, a state
child-support enforcement officer who watched it from a third-floor
window of the courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were ganging up on him, they were kicking and hitting
him, and then I heard five or six shots,'' added Gonzalez, who did
not see the gun or who fired it.
</P>
<P>
   It was then that sheriffs came rushing out of the building as
the young men ran away. Hector Gonzalez, 17, who is no relation to
Eddie Gonzalez, said he saw the sheriffs come back with one young
man in handcuffs.
</P>
<P>
   But Sgt. Brian Meraviglia of the state police major crime squad
said this evening that the police had no one in custody, no
suspects and no motive, though they ``had a lot of witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones worked for United Parcel Service and had turned 21 last
week, according to The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   James Vine, 32, of Bridgeport said Jones lived with his mother
in the city's East End and ``was a nice kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones was a graduate of Harding High School, said another
neighbor, Mike Horan, 23.
</P>
<P>
   E. Paul Haringa, a lawyer, said he was in the building, talking
to a client's family outside a courtroom, when he heard the shots
fired outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``People started streaming out of the courtroom, and the
sheriffs ran for the door,'' Haringa said. He said that he went to
a window to watch and that he saw the sheriffs seize one of the men
involved in the fight.
</P>
<P>
   He said he saw sheriffs bring the man inside the courthouse in
handcuffs.
</P>
<P>
   The police shut the front doors of the courthouse for about 10
minutes after the shooting and began letting people out the side
doors as they roped off the crime scene, Haringa said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
