<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Mo.)  
 METS NOTEBOOK: WAIVER DEAL PUTS QUESTION TO REST; WILSON IS NOT
LEAVING; LEAGUE REJECTS A PROTEST; McMICHAEL REJOINS THE TEAM  
(lb) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Over the weekend in Denver, Brian McRae wondered who
would spell him in center field if he needed a day off down the
stretch. Not that McRae wanted one. He just wondered who it would
be, considering that the other New York Mets outfielders were more
comfortable playing the corners.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, General Manager Steve Phillips addressed the issue in
a waiver-wire deal when he acquired 27-year-old Jermaine
Allensworth from the Kansas City Royals for a player to be
determined by Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gives us some speed in either a complementary or main
role,'' Phillips said Monday from Port St. Lucie, Fla. ``He also
gives us the depth to give Brian a blow, considering that Brian's
played every day.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time Allensworth has been traded this season.
He began the season with the Pittsburgh Pirates and batted .309
with eight stolen bases in 69 games. The Royals acquired him on
June 27 for Manuel Bernal, who was pitching for the Mexico City
Reds. With Kansas City, Allensworth batted .205 with seven stolen
bases in 30 games. But he was three for his last 26 and was playing
sparingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see him as a starter right now for this team,''
Manager Bobby Valentine said before the Mets played the Cardinals
Monday night. ``We obviously have had a situation where we need an
outfielder who can play defense ever since the All-Star break, and
we've needed them almost every day. We've put Lenny Harris out
there and that has taken away one of our best pinch-hitters and
left the team a little strapped. Someone to pinch-run late in the
game has also been a need.''
</P>
<P>
   To make room for Allensworth on their 40-man roster, the Mets
designated for assignment Benny Agbayani, who was playing outfield
and first base at Class AAA Norfolk.
</P>
<P>
   An educated guess would be that Allensworth will replace catcher
Todd Pratt, who has bounced between the Mets and Norfolk this
season, on the 25-man roster. Allensworth was not expected to join
the Mets until Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said he tried to obtain Allensworth from the Pirates
before the player was traded to Kansas City. Shortly before the
July 31 non-waiver deadline, the Mets had scouted Allensworth
heavily, but apparently did not offer Kansas City General Manager
Herk Robinson what he wanted. The Royals need pitching and a middle
infielder.
</P>
<P>
   ``The player we're getting wasn't available at an earlier
date,'' Robinson said. ``I feel like we're getting a quality player
in return.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson Is Not Leaving
</P>
<P>
   Paul Wilson is one person that two members of the Mets'
organization said would not be the remaining part of the Jermaine
Allensworth trade. Wilson, the No. 1 overall pick in the 1994
draft, has just progressed from arm troubles back to Class AAA
Norfolk.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander pitched six shutout innings last Thursday in
his Norfolk debut and is scheduled to make his next start Wednesday
in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson is progressing faster than the Mets' top hitting
prospect, Jay Payton, who is back playing the outfield and a little
first base after being troubled by hamstring injuries. Payton is
batting .244 at Norfolk with 11 stolen bases, but has not stolen a
base since an extended stay on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Allensworth figures to be with the Mets at least until Butch
Huskey (strained left hamstring) comes off the 15-day disabled
list, on which he was placed Aug. 3. Huskey took early batting
practice Monday and hopes to do so again Tuesday. But the Mets
conceivably could wait until after double-headers at Shea Stadium,
Aug. 20-21, to activate Huskey. They could either move a pitcher _
the Mets are carrying 12 _ or send Allensworth, who has options
left, to Norfolk.
</P>
<P>
   League Rejects a Protest
</P>
<P>
   National League President Leonard Coleman denied the Mets'
protest of their 4-3 loss to the Los Angeles Dodgers at Shea on
July 31.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had argued that the Dodgers submitted an inaccurate
lineup card, listing Wilton Guerrero at second base and Tripp
Cromer as a reserve.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers then activated Eric Young from the disabled list and
put Cromer on it, before announcing the trade of Guerrero during
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find that the requirements of the League Constitution were
met,'' Coleman stated in his written decision. ``The Home Plate
umpire, the on-field League Representative, was informed prior to
the commencement of the game of the changes and the Mets were
similarly informed ... as was the press box.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman also invoked an interpretation of Rule 4.01. ``As the
Rule contemplates `teams should not be trapped later by some
mistake that obviously was inadvertent and which can be corrected
before the game starts.'''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Valentine expressed disappointment with the
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trade wasn't made at game time,'' Valentine said. ``They
were not being trapped. The trade was made well after that. I think
it's an incorrect decision. Obviously the rules we're supposed to
abide by don't mean anything.''
</P>
<P>
   McMichael Rejoins the Team
</P>
<P>
   Greg McMichael returned from Atlanta, where his wife, Jennifer,
had gone into labor over the weekend but did not give birth. John
Olerud, who batted .485 with 16 hits, 25 total bases, six doubles
and seven runs scored, was named National League player of the
week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
