<SLUG> BC-NY-STRIP-RULING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE SAYS COSMETIC CHANGES MAY NOT KEEP SEX SHOPS OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ll) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In an interpretation that could bolster New York
City's move to shut down sex shops, a state Supreme Court justice
warned on Monday that efforts by shop owners to reduce their
adult-entertainment stock would not automatically exempt them from
new zoning laws.
</P>
<P>
   Since the law went into effect on July 22, sex shop owners have
been scrambling to comply with the new zoning law by reducing to 40
percent their stock of adult-entertainment wares.
</P>
<P>
   But Justice Stephen Crane said shops could be judged by the
percentage of their revenue derived from adult entertainment and by
whether the majority of their patrons were in search of adult
products. He said that the standard for judging shops could not
``just be a mechanical formula'' and that the standard ``should be
a practical and common-sensical one.''
</P>
<P>
   Crane's comments came in a hearing at which he bitterly accused
the owners of the Harmony Theater in the Chelsea section in
Manhattan of instituting merely cosmetic changes to circumvent the
law and ordered the theater padlocked. Making little effort to hide
his anger, Crane dismissed an effort by the strip club to restrict
nude dancing to an area behind a set of portable Japanese shoji
screens as a way to no longer be considered an adult establishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is transparent,'' Crane said. ``It is the rankest effort.
It offends me deeply.''
</P>
<P>
   While his ruling was directed at the Harmony Theater, Crane's
comments earlier in the day extended to the 144 sex shops affected
by the law. He indicated that expensive and extensive efforts on
their part to avoid violating the law might also prove futile.
</P>
<P>
   The justice, who carried out a personal, impromptu inspection of
the Show World sex emporium in Times Square on Friday afternoon,
said he would use a ``common sense'' standard to determine whether
a business was a sex shop.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is a vaguely worded section of the new law that is the
primary remaining hope of the stores and strip clubs.
</P>
<P>
   The 1995 measure, which prohibits sex shops in residential areas
or within 500 feet of schools, churches or each other, defines a
sex shop as a business that devotes a ``substantial portion'' of
its floor space or stock to adult products. The Giuliani
administration included the phrase in the law to avoid having it
declared an unconstitutional ban on free speech. In Federal court
in July, the city's Department of Buildings defined a ``substantial
portion'' of a business as more than 40 percent of a store's floor
space.
</P>
<P>
   Herald Price Fahringer, the lawyer representing 107 of the 144
sex shops affected, seized on the formula, apparently advising
dozens of his clients to devote 60 percent of their stock to
products like perfume, souvenirs and general-audience videos.
Fahringer, citing the city's own interpretation of the law, has
argued that sex shops that devote less than 40 percent of their
floor space to adult products could no longer be defined as adult
establishments.
</P>
<P>
   But Crane, extensively commenting on the issue for the first
time on Monday, dismissed that argument, saying that unless
Fahringer could convince him otherwise, he was not bound by the
40-60 formula.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't really capture the essence of `substantial
portion,''' the justice said. ``Substantial portion can't just be a
mechanical formula.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Connolly, the lawyer arguing the case on behalf of the
city, praised that interpretation. But Fahringer accused the city
of unfairly shifting the ground rules and warned that if Crane
closed X-rated businesses based on his broader interpretation, the
sex shops would have grounds for an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of test cases, the Giuliani administration asked
Crane to close three Manhattan strip clubs, including the Harmony,
and three Manhattan adult video stores. The order to padlock the
Harmony on Monday was the first time the new zoning law alone had
been used to padlock a Manhattan strip club.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
