<HEADLINE>
FOR DECORATORS, BUSINESS AS USUAL  
 A 2ND LEGAL FRONT IN SUIT OVER BOOK  
 BLACKOUTS, IN SYNC 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JAMES BARRON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the name in a one-name design firm dies, what
becomes of the firm?
</P>
<P>
   The question arose after the death last month of the interior
decorator Mark Hampton, who was sought after for his crisp but
comfortable traditionalism. Several New York antiques dealers had
said that the decorators who worked at the Hampton firm had been
taking on outside projects even before he died. They had his
permission, the dealers said, but the arrangement left the
impression that the firm would not continue after his death and
that the decorators would strike out on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, maybe not. Hampton's widow Duane, who said last
month that no decisions about the future of the firm had been made,
issued a statement Monday that signaled that the firm is not
closing its doors. ``In answer to the question, `Is Mark Hampton
still in business?' Duane Hampton replies: `Most emphatically yes!'
'' The statement went on to say that the decorators, draftsmen and
architects who had worked for Hampton ``are completing jobs already
under way and undertaking new business.''
</P>
<P>
   A 2nd Legal Front in Suit Over Book
</P>
<P>
   New YORK _ Hector Feliciano, who wrote a book that traced the
fate of artwork looted by the Nazis, only to be sued in France by
the family of the art dealer Alec Wildenstein, has another lawyer,
and Feliciano credits Ronald Lauder, the cosmetics executive and
collector, with the referral. Louis Begley, a partner at Debevoise
&AMP; Plimpton, said that he would advise Feliciano, even though
Feliciano already has a lawyer in France. (A lawyer for the
Wildensteins said last week that the case involved, in effect,
damage to the Wildensteins' reputation in Feliciano's book, ``The
Lost Museum: The Nazi Conspiracy to Steal the World's Greatest
Works of Art.'')
</P>
<P>
   Begley would not say who was paying his fees. ``I haven't done
anything I need to be paid for yet,'' he said. ``I know that Hector
knows Ronald Lauder, and I know Ronald Lauder. I believe that
Ronald Lauder told him it was a good idea to come to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Blackouts, in Sync
</P>
<P>
   Conspiracy theorists who love classical music can try to make
something of this: Two summer music festivals 1,853 miles apart had
power failures over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The lights went out at the Bridgehampton Chamber Music
Festival's gala at the Atlantic, a country club in Bridgehampton,
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were downstairs warming up,'' said Marya Martin, the
artistic director and flutist. ``We noticed that the
air-conditioning was off, which was no big deal. It wasn't until
everyone gathered in the performance room until we realized the
lights were off and we were ready to walk on, and it was dark. We
couldn't have read the music.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic Club members, who pay substantial entrance fees when
they join, were scrambling to find torches or candles when the
lights came on again, and the concert began.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Fe Opera in New Mexico was well into the first act of
``The Magic Flute'' by Mozart, with Raymond Very, Thomas Barrett,
Sheri Greenwald, Joseph Gayer and Anne-Marie Owens singing a
quintet, when the lights went out on the stage and in the orchestra
pit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The orchestra knows the opera so well, they just kept
playing,'' said the conductor, Robert Spano, adding that the Santa
Fe Opera had just installed a new emergency power system. ``This
was its first test, and it worked very well,'' he said. ``It's
meant to take seven seconds to turn on, and I'm told it did. It
felt like seven years to me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
