<HEADLINE>
GIANTS' RUNNER HOPES TO STICK AROUND FOR A BIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Texas)  (ll) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Gary Brown is still feeling his way around the
Giants' training camp and his third team in eight years.
</P>
<P>
   But it would be unfair to term Brown a journeyman, not after he
rushed for 1,002 yards with an American Football Conference-best
5.1 yards a carry with the Houston Oilers in 1993, and not after he
accumulated 945 yards on the ground for the San Diego Chargers last
season.
</P>
<P>
   But even Brown is unsure just how he has been unable to find a
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard, because you see guys who have had success and they
seem to stay with the same team for years,'' Brown said after a
recent morning practice. ``But that wasn't my thing, so I just have
to go out and make the best of my situation. Hopefully, I can play
well again this year. I look forward to playing well this year, and
then maybe I can play here for a couple more years and maybe even
retire here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants would be pleased to see Brown, a 29-year-old running
back out of Penn State, find a home. They signed him to a one-year,
$400,000 contract as an unrestricted free agent on April 21 after
making their way through the draft without finding a running back.
</P>
<P>
   With Rodney Hampton gone, Brown, with his strength and skill
running between the tackles, could became the primary running back.
In the Giants' exhibition opener Saturday night, Brown ran for 19
yards on 10 carries in a 24-17 victory over the Cincinnati Bengals.
Brown was operating behind the second-team offensive line, which
has had trouble opening holes for the running backs.
</P>
<P>
   There are disappointments scattered throughout Brown's story. An
eighth-round draft pick of the Oilers in 1991, he carried the ball
only 27 times in his first two seasons and had only 16 carries in
the first eight games in 1993 before an injury to a teammate
provided him with his first start. Brown responded with 166 yards
rushing. He followed that with a 194-yard performance the next week
against Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   But he slid to 648 yards rushing in 1994 and to 293 the next
year. Overweight, overconfident and undermotivated, he was waived
by the Oilers in April 1996. Brown sat home and sulked, ballooning
to nearly 40 pounds over his playing weight of 225 pounds. When the
season began, he was at home in Williamsport, Pa. He remained there
in a funk all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just sat around the house,'' Brown said. ``I took the wrong
attitude. I blamed the Oilers. I'd sit around watching TV and
eating. Finally, I was watching the AFC playoff games and I
realized I wanted to be back there.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown made it back last season, signing with the Chargers and
compiling another successful season. But in the final game of the
season, one that Brown does not enjoy talking about, he was kept on
the bench against his wishes, falling short of the 1,000-yard
plateau and a $200,000 bonus. When the Chargers re-signed Natrone
Means, Brown realized his days were numbered.
</P>
<P>
   ``The San Diego thing is something I had no control over,''
Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown put opportunity ahead of money to sign with the Giants,
believing that he can earn playing time in a backfield already
crowded with Tiki Barber, Tyrone Wheatley and Charles Way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I proved myself,'' Brown said. ``I think at this
point I wanted to be in a good situation where I can go out and
just continue to do the things I can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to learn. If I just go out and play hard and do the
things I do, that's the only thing I can control.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-98 2312EDT &QL; 
