<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TWINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS BEAT TWINS, 7-3, FOR FIFTH STRAIGHT WIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As a longtime player and coach with the Yankees,
Frank Crosetti called Babe Ruth, Joe DiMaggio and Mickey Mantle
teammates, and when Crosetti counseled Joe Torre in Oakland last
week, the Yankees' manager listened. After all, Torre said,
Crosetti has enough World Series rings for all his toes and
fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Don't let those guys relax, Crosetti told Torre, whose team is
running away from the American League and toward history. Don't let
them relax.
</P>
<P>
   Relating the story on Monday, Torre shrugged: He does not
believe it's within the nature of his team to relax. The Yankees
won their fifth consecutive game Monday night, crushing the
Minnesota Twins, 7-3, before 29,600 at Yankee Stadium. They are
85-29, and if they merely win half of their remaining 48 games,
they will match the record of the 1961 Yankees (109-53).
</P>
<P>
   Hideki Irabu (11-5) surrendered just two hits in seven innings;
in his last two starts, he has allowed four hits in 15 innings.
Irabu pitched a no-hitter for four innings Monday night, extending
the Yankees' streak of hitless innings against Minnesota to 14,
before Marty Cordova led off the fifth inning with a single. The
Twins had last played against the Yankees on May 17, when David
Wells pitched a perfect game.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are far ahead of the Boston Red Sox in the AL East,
17{ games, and they could clinch a playoff spot during their next
road trip. No one is going to catch them during the regular season,
and yet they are playing each game with a sense of desperation,
racing against what is possible, racing against themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The soonest any team has won for the 100th time is Sept. 9,
accomplished by the 1961 Yankees and the 1906 Cubs, according to
the Elias Sports Bureau. The Yankees may reach that milestone by
the end of August, if only they keep pushing hard. They may win 120
games, if only they keep pushing.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Twins Monday night, the Yankees quickly scored the
requisite number of runs to win. Martinez singled home O'Neill in
the first inning; typically, the Yankees set Minnesota's Frank
Rodriguez on the defensive immediately, forcing him to throw 25
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez would throw 26 in the second inning, when the Yankees
effectively put the game out of reach, with some help from the
Twins. Chad Curtis and Scott Brosius each hit singles with one out,
and after a forceout, Jeter laced a single to left. One run scored,
and when Minnesota's Marty Cordova over-ran the ball in left, so
did another. Yankees 3, Twins 0.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius pounded a two-run homer in the fourth, his third home
run in three days and his 13th of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The only question was when or if the Twins would get a hit
against the Yankees. They did not get a hit in the ninth inning
against the Yankees May 16, Wells pitched his perfect game the next
day _ and Irabu had no-hit stuff Monday night, against one of the
league's most benign offenses.
</P>
<P>
   As he had in his previous start, Irabu had a fastball in the
mid-90s, the sort that hitters cannot catch up to, when thrown
above the waist. To complement this, Irabu's split-fingered
fastball dove and sunk and darted. Jorge Posada, the Yankees'
catcher, often blocked pitches in the dirt that the Twins had swung
over.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu hit Otis Nixon with his first pitch of the game, but
retired the next three batters, then all three Twins in the second.
Two outs into the third inning, Irabu walked Nixon and Matt Lawton,
but struck out Paul Molitor on three pitches to get out of the
scrape. Three innings, no hits.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth inning: Three batters, three outs. The streak of hitless
innings reached 14. But Cordova slapped a clean single through the
middle in the fifth inning, and many in the crowd stood and
clapped.
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Mike Stanton relieved Irabu to open the eighth
inning, with the score 7-0. Stanton, who intermittently has had
control problems, walked two before giving up a three-run homer to
Lawton, breaking a streak of 371/3 innings of scoreless relief for
the Yanks.
</P>
</TEXT>
