<HEADLINE>
3-YEAR-OLDS ARE TIGHTLY BUNCHED FOR TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ll) 
 By JENNY KELLNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four horses, one title.
</P>
<P>
   If he were to add the Travers to his victory on Sunday in the
Haskell, would Coronado's Quest lock up the 3-year-old
championship? Or would the Belmont Stakes plus a Travers add up to
year-end honors for the Haskell runner-up, Victory Gallop?
</P>
<P>
   Did last year's Horse of the Year, Favorite Trick, sneak back
into the picture with his dramatic victory Sunday in the Jim Dandy
at Saratoga? Or has two-thirds of a Triple Crown already equaled a
championship for the sidelined Real Quiet?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think with Real Quiet out, it's sort of up to Victory Gallop
and Coronado's Quest not to give it up,'' said Shug McGaughey,
trainer of Coronado's Quest, who scored his fourth straight victory
and first Grade I victory in the Haskell at Monmouth Park. ``And I
think they'll probably have to figure it out on the race track. The
Breeders' Cup is our ultimate goal. The Travers is one big step.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Aug. 29 Travers at Saratoga is definitely step No. 2
for both Coronado's Quest and Victory Gallop, Favorite Trick is not
a serious candidate for the mile-and-a-quarter race, said his
trainer, Bill Mott.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Mott, who was inducted into racing's Hall of Fame on
Monday at Saratoga, said he had his eye on the Breeders' Cup Mile
on the turf as a possible goal for Favorite Trick, whose victory in
the Jim Dandy, at a mile and an eighth, was his first beyond a
mile.
</P>
<P>
   But Mott did not rule the Travers out, and said he would take a
week or so before deciding.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take some thought,'' Mott said, adding, ``He
proved he was a champion last year.''
</P>
<P>
   If Favorite Trick is not entered in the Travers, and with Real
Quiet out for the year with a leg injury, Coronado's Quest and
Victory Gallop would be left to face Deputy Diamond, Raffis
Majesty, Archers Bay and possibly one or two others in the $750,000
race.
</P>
<P>
   The trainer Elliott Walden firmly believes that Victory Gallop,
who won the Rebel and the Arkansas Derby before finishing second to
Real Quiet in the first two legs of the Triple Crown, can win the
title and that the Travers will bear him out.
</P>
<P>
   ``That day will be to our advantage; Coronado's Quest was the
horse to beat in the Haskell, but I don't think that will be the
case in the Travers,'' said Walden, who admitted he took a chance
in running Victory Gallop in a nine-furlong race on a
speed-favoring track.
</P>
<P>
   McGaughey, who was also in Saratoga yesterday for the Hall of
Fame induction, conceded that Victory Gallop would no doubt relish
the mile and a quarter, but said he did not think the added
distance would disturb Coronado's Quest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our ultimate goal is the Breeders' Cup Classic, and I think
this was the first step,'' he said. ``We've got a ways to go,
though, and work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting with the Travers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be tougher,'' McGaughey said of his once
fractious colt. ``Just getting him settled down, I knew he would
run a great race. We'll have to move forward off that race.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
