<HEADLINE>
BOEING LICENSE FOR SEA LAUNCH SUSPENDED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boeing Co. yesterday found itself trying to avoid the same
kind of political firestorm that recently engulfed U.S. satellite
maker Loral over the exchange of sensitive information with old
Cold War foes.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department suspended Boeing's export license for Sea
Launch, the first-ever project to launch commercial rockets from an
ocean platform, after the Seattle-based aerospace giant improperly
shared sensitive technical information with its Russian and
Ukrainian partners.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department official said the Justice Department is
reviewing the incident to determine if Boeing broke any U.S. laws.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Sea Launch is all but dead in the water for now.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 Russian and Ukrainian engineers at the Sea Launch
homeport in Long Beach, Calif., who were preparing for the first
launch early in 1999, have returned home until the company gets its
license back. And the government won't say how long that will take.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Boeing nor the State Department would reveal exactly
what information was passed along to Russian and Ukrainian
engineers. Dick Dalton, a spokesman for Boeing in Washington, D.C.,
said the information in question was not classified, though he
would not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Before the license suspension is lifted, Boeing must demonstrate
that it has adequate security safeguards in place to prevent a
recurrence of the lax procedures that got it into trouble, a State
Department official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people at Boeing are optimistic it will be a brief
suspension,'' a Congressional source said Monday. ``But because of
the Loral mess, it's not the best political environment for
something like this to come out now. The only worry Boeing has is
if politics comes into play. This is a hyper-sensitive issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The source said the conservative American Spectator magazine is
working on the story. If true, that could result in exactly the
kind of political repercussions that Boeing wants to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Boeing does not get caught up in the politics of this, it's
probably a non-event,'' said John Pike, director of space policy
for the Federation of American Scientists in Washington, D.C. ``If
it does, then it doesn't matter what they did. They are in
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   A House select committee has been investigating U.S. satellite
technology exports to China by Loral. That incident, in which Loral
apparently helped the Chinese after one of their rockets exploded,
has received widespread attention and resulted in much negative
publicity for Loral.
</P>
<P>
   But the committee's mandate is narrow and it is unlikely to
examine the Boeing case, said George Behan, press secretary for
U.S. Rep. Norm Dicks, a Washington state Democrat and minority
leader on the committee.
</P>
<P>
   That does not mean, however, that some other committee in
Congress won't investigate, Behan said.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing briefed Dicks' office Friday about the matter in advance
of a Washington Post article Saturday that first disclosed the Sea
Launch license suspension.
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional source, who is familiar with what happened,
said a State Department representative was not present, as is
required under the export license agreement, when Boeing and its
partners discussed sensitive technical information.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure it was us (the United States) and not the Russians or
Ukrainians who benefited from the flow of information, but even so
it was a violation of the license,'' the source said.
</P>
<P>
   Industry experts said the Boeing case does not appear to be
nearly as serious as that involving Loral.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese rocket technology is inferior to that of the United
States, and the concern in Congress is that any information
supplied by Loral could help China build more reliable nuclear
missiles.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Sea Launch, however, it is the Russians and
Ukrainians who are supplying the rocket, which is considered as
good if not better than rockets built by the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing is a partner in Sea Launch with the European shipbuilder
Kvaerner of Oslo, Norway; Russia's RSC-Energia in Moscow; and the
Ukrainian company Yuzhnoye/Yuzhmash.
</P>
<P>
   Energia is the company that launched the first Sputnik and
designed the Russian Mir space station. It also is building
hardware for the International Space Station, for which Boeing is
prime contractor. The Ukrainian company is best known for building
the former Soviet Union's most mighty intercontinental ballistic
missile, the SS-18, dubbed by the Pentagon as ``Satan.''
</P>
<P>
   Sea Launch will use a two-stage Zenit rocket built by the
Ukrainian company, with the third-stage built by Russia. As part of
its 40 percent stake in Sea Launch, Boeing's contribution includes
about $500 million and its expertise at integrating complex
engineering systems.
</P>
<P>
   The venture's first launch of a Hughes Space and Communications
satellite was originally scheduled for October, but was recently
postponed until early next year so Hughes could modify the
satellite. If the Sea Launch project remains shut down for any
length of time, that initial launch would be in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Sea Launch has contracted to launch 13 Hughes Space and
Communications satellites. Sea Launch also has sold five launch
slots to Loral Space &AMP; Communications.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department would not say how long it might be before
the project can resume.
</P>
</TEXT>
