<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES NOTEBOOK: DAVIS JOINING A CROWDED OUTFIELD; WAITING ON
NELSON 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Chili Davis and Darryl Strawberry stood about 15 feet
apart in the Yankees' clubhouse Monday, each surrounded by
reporters, each answering questions about the other player. They
play the same position, and if Davis returns to the lineup next
week as expected, it's quite possible that only one will be able to
play at a time.
</P>
<P>
   This is the Yankees' version of a quarterback controversy:
Strawberry leads the Yankees with 21 home runs, while Davis has
none after missing all but two games this season with ankle
trouble, and yet Manager Joe Torre intends to play Davis regularly
when he first comes back.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry has been here all year and has become a working
symbol of the club's unselfishness, quietly accepting his part-time
role. Davis has been in Tampa, Fla., and has never worn pinstripes
on the Yankee Stadium playing field.
</P>
<P>
   But this is hardly Glenn Foley vs. Neil O'Donnell. Strawberry
and Davis are friends _ for most of this season, Strawberry has
worn a T-shirt given to him by Davis _ and both indicated they
would abide by whatever decisions Torre made.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'll be an obstruction,'' said Davis, who added
that he intended to speak to Torre when he was activated. ``You
don't want to interrupt some guys who are putting up some pretty
good numbers. I'll do whatever he sees as best.''
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry said: ``What I'm going to have on my mind is when Joe
puts me on the field, I'm going after it. It's a good problem to
have.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just happy for him, happy he's able to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis is nearing the end of his 20-day minor-league
rehabilitation assignment. He began with Class A Tampa, before
moving up to Class AA Norwich, where he hit .243 with a homer and
five RBIs over 11 games. Davis took batting practice at Yankee
Stadium on Monday, and on Tuesday he will join Class AAA Columbus
for six days; unless he has a setback, the Yankees will activate
him next Monday in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees invested nearly $14 million in a three-year deal for
the 38-year-old Davis during the off season, and as Strawberry
joked over the weekend, their principal owner, George Steinbrenner,
will probably want to realize some dividend. If healthy and
productive, however, there is no question that Davis, who is coming
back from ankle surgery, will provide another element to the
offense, as a switch-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Davis hit 30 home runs and drove in 90 runs for Kansas City last
season, and it appears Torre wants to play him enough to determine
whether he can regain his swing quickly enough to lend similar
support in the final month and the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But Davis is strictly a designated hitter. Strawberry played
left field in spring training and at the season's outset, before
his weakened left knee relegated him to service as a designated
hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Once Davis comes back, it figures that Torre will at least try
to play Strawberry in left field; on Monday, Torre said he had
clearance to play Strawberry on the artificial surface in Minnesota
next week.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry's limp, however, has worsened during the season, and
he may not be able to cover as much ground in the outfield as he
did in spring training. To incorporate both Strawberry and Davis in
the lineup, it may be that Torre will eventually use them as a
left-handed and right-handed platoon, with Tim Raines and Chad
Curtis sharing time in left.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting on Nelson
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have been extremely aggressive in making waiver
claims and preventing players on other teams from being traded. But
Yankees General Manager Brian Cashman is playing offense, as well
as defense, searching for another pitcher who could be used in the
postseason in the event Jeff Nelson does not return from back
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   But Cashman said Monday that he did not think he would be able
to find a pitcher to his liking, because the good pitchers were
being claimed and therefore could not be traded.
</P>
<P>
   Cashman said the team's medical staff was confident that Nelson
would be back and ready to pitch around Sept. 1, giving the Yankees
about four weeks for the right-handed Nelson _ crucial to the
bullpen because of his ability to dominate right-handed batters _
to regain his command and for the Yankees to assess whether he is
healthy enough to be part of the postseason staff.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Holmes may also have a chance to return, but there are
those who believe Holmes' back trouble will prevent him from
pitching in the majors again this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
