u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CARDS-MCGWIRE-NYT     08-10 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CARDS-MCGWIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCGWIRE FEVER, LIKE THE BALL, GOES DEEP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo.)  (ll) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The muscular giant with red hair, red goatee, red
baseball cap and red jersey flicked the 35-inch bat around like a
toothpick as he strode to the plate, causing the hundreds of fans
who were stationed in the left-field seats at Busch Stadium to
stand up and become imaginary outfielders. It was Mark McGwire time
in batting practice, which meant it was time for baseballs to
disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Mets Manager Bobby Valentine had seen this powerful display
dozens of times, so he sat between the railings of the third-base
dugout with his back to the plate, actually looking at a bunch of
reporters instead of at McGwire. But Valentine did not need eyes to
know if McGwire had transformed another 75-mile-an-hour pitch into
a souvenir. The sounds told the story: lots of noise, lots of
souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark is the man,'' said Valentine, who never peeked over his
shoulder for a glimpse of McGwire, but did have a close-up view of
a deep fly ball that would have been a two-run homer off Al Leiter
in the first inning if it had not drifted foul by about 15 feet.
``I don't need to tell him anything.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire is obviously the man here, where fans were lined up six
deep for tickets four hours before the first pitch of the
Mets-Cardinals game on Monday night and where the scramble for
seats in left field when the gates opened resembled a scene from
Pamplona. The fervor extends beyond the confines of Busch, where
McGwire's relaxing dinner for two sometimes becomes a meal with
three or four unwanted guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I swear, going out with him is like going out with Elvis,''
said Pat Kelly, one of McGwire's teammates and close friends.
``It's unbelievable. Everywhere he goes, people follow him. I feel
sorry for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine does not. The Mets' manager is amused by how McGwire
has become a little more ornery as his homer total has increased to
46 and the attention toward his chase of Roger Maris' 37-year-old
season record of 61 has intensified.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire would not speak with reporters from New York before
Monday night's game. When a reporter from St. Louis asked Valentine
how McGwire would handle the pressure if he were pursuing the most
illustrious record in baseball in New York, Valentine reminisced
about what Mickey Mantle told him on how Maris endured.
</P>
<P>
   ``In '61, the guy who was breaking the record was breaking Babe
Ruth's record,'' said Valentine, his voice rising as he mentioned
Ruth's name. ``He was competing against not Sammy Sosa, but Mickey
Mantle. Even though it's 1998 and we have more TV's and we have
more guys with pens, I think Roger Maris had as much, if not three
times more, scrutiny with everything he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine said McGwire _ unlike Maris _ was the overwhelming
people's choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think they want McGwire to break it?'' Valentine said
with a smile that had already answered the question. ``I think most
people do. No one wants Sammy to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine thinks McGwire will topple Maris. Actually, he thinks
McGwire, Sosa and Ken Griffey Jr. will hit 62 or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought in May that three would do it,'' Valentine said.
``I'll stick to three.''
</P>
<P>
   But that does not mean Valentine wants to see McGwire rip even
one against the Mets in their three-game series. St. Louis manager
Tony La Russa groused Sunday about how the Cubs did not challenge
McGwire early in games, saying: ``I never have problems with it
late in the game. That's baseball. But the first five or six
innings? Never. It should be their best against your best.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine, who does not exchange Christmas cards with La Russa
and who even tweaked the manager recently for batting the pitcher
eighth in the lineup, is unaware of rules on strategies for facing
the most productive power hitter in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ethics?'' Valentine asked. ``First of all, I don't know if
it's important for him to break the record or not to break the
record as far as baseball is concerned. If it happens, I have
nothing to do with Mark McGwire. I don't deal with individual
players on my team. I deal with the team. And I don't deal with
individual players on their team. I deal with the team. It's us
against them. It's not a few of us against Mark or a few of them
against us. It's our team against their team, and we'll do whatever
we can to come out on top.''
</P>
<P>
   That meant Valentine did not mind when Leiter walked McGwire
with the Mets leading, 2-1, with no one out and a runner on second
in the first inning. It probably irked La Russa, who watched the
Cubs walk his first baseman six times on Saturday and Sunday and
claimed it was ``stressing'' McGwire out. That will happen over and
over.
</P>
<P>
   As McGwire's pursuit continues, Valentine will watch from afar
and will be one person who still wonders what it all means.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe if the record holds, there will be just as much
excitement about it next year,'' Valentine speculated. ``Maybe that
will be better for baseball, I don't know. If he breaks it, I don't
know if that's good for the game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
