<SLUG> BC-NY-CUNY-REMEDIAL-375&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE HALTS CUNY'S PLANS TO CUT REMEDIAL CLASSES 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A state judge on Monday ordered the City University
of New York to temporarily cease preparations to end remedial
classes at its senior colleges pending a trial on whether the
university violated the state's open meeting law.
</P>
<P>
   Although the ban on remedial classes is not set to take effect
until September 1999, the preliminary injunction issued on Monday
by Justice Elliott J. Wilk has immediate implications because CUNY
must begin to alert potential applicants to the new policy this
fall, and it has asked its colleges to submit implementation plans
by September.
</P>
<P>
   In his 20-page ruling, Wilk said he was granting a preliminary
injunction because the plaintiffs in a lawsuit against the
university had shown that CUNY's trustees had violated the state's
open meeting law. The trustees, who adopted the policy in a meeting
on May 26, ejected most of the public spectators at the meeting
rather than just those who were disruptive.
</P>
<P>
   Wilk also said in the ruling that he believed there was ``a
strong likelihood that the May 26, 1998, resolution will be
voided'' at trial.
</P>
<P>
   CUNY officials said Monday that they planned to appeal the
injunction. ``On the merits, I think the judge is absolutely
wrong,'' said Herman Badillo, vice chairman of CUNY's board of
trustees.
</P>
<P>
   If CUNY wins a stay of the injunction _ which government
agencies are usually granted _ an appeals court hearing to overturn
the injunction would probably be put off until at least October,
and a full trial until sometime later.
</P>
<P>
   CUNY officials said they believed a stay would allow them to
continue their preparations for carrying out their new policy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the ruling cast some uncertainty on the longer-term
outlook for the policy, which says that any student who cannot pass
all three of CUNY's placement exams in reading, writing and
mathematics will not be allowed to register at CUNY's senior
colleges. Under the policy, students will be directed to community
colleges or to adult education courses.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two-thirds of CUNY's entering freshmen at the four-year
colleges failed one or more of the placement tests last fall,
although some of them may have been able to pass the exams after
taking remedial courses during the summer.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's office denounced Wilk's decision on
Monday, predicting that it would be reversed ``and will not stand
in the way of CUNY's efforts to raise standards.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The opinion clearly is written by a judge who considers his
own personal political viewpoints to be more important than the
law,'' Anthony Coles, senior adviser to the mayor, said in a
statement. He said the remedial education vote ``has received more
public scrutiny than any CUNY vote in the last 30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   CUNY has begun work on programs to expand remedial courses
during the summer and to give high school students better
preparation so they will be more likely to pass the placement
tests.
</P>
<P>
   Wilk said, however, that he was not persuaded that high school
and college administrators ``will be able to provide remedial
courses sufficient in quantity and quality to satisfy the need for
remediation formerly available at the senior colleges'' by
September 1999.
</P>
<P>
   When students and faculty members initiated the lawsuit three
years ago, they charged that CUNY repeatedly violated New York
state's open meeting law.
</P>
<P>
   Working with their lawyer, Ronald Minkoff, the plaintiffs
recently amended the complaint to include the May board meeting at
which the trustees adopted the remedial policy, which has been
widely attacked as too restrictive.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs said they hoped it would prevent the
implementation of the remedial policy, as well as force CUNY to
provide more room for the public at its meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board has been put on notice that it can't show contempt
for the public, and can't show contempt for the students,'' said
William Crain, a psychology professor at City College and one of
the plaintiffs.
</P>
</TEXT>
