<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-CARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS BEAT CARDINALS, 4-2  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Inches. Fractions of inches, to be more precise.
</P>
<P>
   That is what Mets Manager Bobby Valentine estimated was the
margin by which Todd Hundley missed two home runs Sunday afternoon
in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   However little the margin, there was no doubt Hundley was
missing more often than not.
</P>
<P>
   During a three-game weekend series against the Colorado Rockies,
Hundley struck out in six consecutive at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Coming into a three-game series with the Cardinals, Hundley had
struck out in seven of his last 10 plate appearances, eight of 11
after his first at-bat at Busch Stadium Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   But when the St. Louis right-hander Matt Morris left a 1-0
fastball up in the third inning, there was no way Hundley was going
to miss again.
</P>
<P>
   He turned on the ball and hit it so hard that right fielder
Brian Jordan never looked back.
</P>
<P>
   The ball landed in the luxury suites in deep right field for a
two-run home run that helped power the Mets to a 4-2 victory over
the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   The home run, Hundley's first in the majors in nearly a year,
not only broke a 2-2 tie, but also lifted the Mets to their 15th
victory in their last 22 games.
</P>
<P>
   His last home run in the majors came Sept. 8, 1997, off the
Philadelphia right-hander Mike Grace.
</P>
<P>
   It mattered little that Hundley struck out again in his final
at-bat, and for the ninth time in his last 13 appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley might be struggling at the plate, but with one at-bat,
he reminded everyone why a lineup with Hundley batting behind Mike
Piazza might be one of the most dangerous around.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the two All-Stars drove in all the runs for the Mets
Monday night. Piazza knocked in two off Morris in first with a line
drive that found the gap in left-center field.
</P>
<P>
   But St. Louis came back to tie the score in the bottom of the
first on Ray Lankford's run-scoring double, Al Leiter's wild pitch,
and Jordan's sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   With the score still tied, Piazza reached first in the third
inning on a two-out error by rookie shortstop Luis Ordaz, who let a
tough grounder play him.
</P>
<P>
   Up stepped Hundley, who was batting .197 when the day began.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley _ who had three hits at home last Thursday and two more
in Denver on Friday night _ said he was encouraged by his two
near-misses Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, it's frustrating,'' said the switch-hitting Hundley,
who struck out four times Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the production there. I feel good at the plate. It's
just getting the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   All that frustration was gone with one left-handed swing of the
bat.
</P>
<P>
   The blast made a winner out of Leiter (11-4), snapping a string
of three consecutive no-decisions for the veteran left-hander.
Leiter allowed four runs in each of his last three starts.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, after the two-run first, Leiter pitched six
scoreless innings to leave with the 4-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Leiter allowed four hits and two runs in seven innings,
walking two and striking out seven.
</P>
<P>
   He went to a full count each time he faced McGwire, walking the
St. Louis slugger in the first, before catching him looking in the
third (with a fastball, set up by a change up) and again in the
sixth (with a slider).
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, who leads the majors with 46 home runs, came up once
more, with one out and a runner on first in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine called on the right-hander Turk Wendell to replace the
left-hander Dennis Cook.
</P>
<P>
   On a 2-2 count, McGwire took a big cut _ and struck out for the
third time.
</P>
<P>
   John Franco picked up his 24th save by pitching a scoreless
ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Mets first baseman John Olerud, who went 0 for 3 with a walk on
Monday night, had his hitting streak stopped at 23 games, one short
of Hubie Brooks' team record.
</P>
</TEXT>
